<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTHER JONES' MAKEOVER; MIAMI HERALD ENDS INTERNATIONAL EDITION;
NEW YORK'S NEW MEDIA CRITIC; CELEBRITY PREDICTIONS FOR THE
MILLENNIUM  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Fla., N.J., N.Y.)  (js) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   She's gotten a little, well, frumpy. Many of her old admirers
have moved on, and younger ones, used to a quicker tempo and a
brassier look, are not necessarily taking their place. So Mother
Jones, the counter-culture dowager, is getting a make-over this
week, hoping to rekindle old flames and light some new ones.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1976 as the house organ of the nonprofit Foundation
for National Progress, and named for labor organizer Mary Harris
Jones, Mother Jones calls itself ``a magazine of investigation and
ideas for independent thinkers.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, after early acclaim for hard-nosed investigative
reporting that many other journals wouldn't touch, the magazine, a
bimonthly based in San Francisco, lost focus in the 1980s and early
1990s as its readers aged and their political activism waned, said
Jay Harris, the publisher.
</P>
<P>
   That has changed, Harris said, crediting Jeffrey Klein, one of
the founders of the magazine, who returned as editor in 1992 to get
the magazine back to its roots. But despite a circulation increase
of about 25 percent since Klein's return, sales of Mother Jones
have stagnated at about 145,000 copies an issue since last year,
according to the Audit Bureau of Circulations.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Despite a ``very loyal band'' of readers, ``there is very
little depth of engagement left among baby boomers,'' said Vishwa
Marwah, president of Tattoo Marketing, a San Francisco consulting
firm that did research for Mother Jones.
</P>
<P>
   And though there is ``an emerging next generation that does
care, their language is not the same,'' he said. ``This generation
communicates visually as well as verbally.''
</P>
<P>
   That, Klein said, means ``more visual entry points'' _ bolder
graphics and brighter colors meant to attract readers who ``are
more likely to be channel flickers.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention more articles about technology and corporate
misfeasance, which hold more interest for younger readers than
tales of political corruption, Marwah said.
</P>
<P>
   The first issue sporting the new look will be mailed to
subscribers this week. It features a cover story on Rupert Murdoch,
the chairman of News Corp., rendered in the form of a mock tabloid
pullout. Sections have been added and revamped. Headlines are
bigger, type is darker and the use of photographs has been
increased.
</P>
<P>
   But Klein insists that ``underneath the glitz, we're
harder-edged than ever.''
</P>
<P>
   _ BERNARD STAMLER
</P>
<P>
   Miami Herald to End Its International Edition
</P>
<P>
   Citing financial reasons and a push to include more news about
Miami for foreign readers, The Miami Herald plans to stop
publishing the international edition it has sold throughout Latin
America and the Caribbean for 52 years and replace it with a
portion of the Miami edition.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of The Herald say they expect to save money on the
change, which is scheduled to take effect by the end of the month.
The international edition has never yielded a profit, said Douglas
Clifton, The Herald's executive editor.
</P>
<P>
   The decision comes on the heels of other developments that have
led to questions about The Herald's future, including the departure
of the headquarters of its parent, Knight Ridder, to California, a
decline in circulation and an unexpected change of publishers.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its modest circulation of a little more than about
19,000, the international edition is often regarded as the region's
international English language newspaper. It offers more
prominently displayed articles about Latin America and less
advertising than local papers. But Herald executives said that some
newspapers in the region, particularly in the Bahamas, which print
The Herald's international edition, had expressed more interest in
local Miami news.
</P>
<P>
   _ PAMELA MERCER
</P>
<P>
   `Burn Rate' Author Gets a Media Column
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ How does an erstwhile journalist and failed
entrepreneur become a media critic?
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Michael Wolff, whose media column has its debut
in the current issue of New York magazine, his new status as enfant
terrible of media culture old and new is a result of his recent
book, ``Burn Rate: How I Survived the Gold Rush Years on the
Internet'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster).
</P>
<P>
   The book recounts Wolff's escapades, raising and spending money
in the early days of the World Wide Web in the mid-1990s, as the
publisher of Netguide, a series of books about the Internet. Though
``Burn Rate'' has been acclaimed for its candid, behind-the-scenes
glimpse at the frenzy of the early online world, it did not endear
its author to the many people whose blunders in their race for
money and power he details.
</P>
<P>
   Since early summer, Wolff has been critiquing the online media
for the Industry Standard, an Internet trade publication. His New
York magazine column will focus on the traditional media.
</P>
<P>
   Wolff finds his sudden stature as pundit ``funny'' because he
ended up where he is because he got out of journalism in the first
place. (He had written for magazines and had two books published
before moving on to Netguide.) ``It is an irony that I giggle at
every day,'' Wolff said.
</P>
<P>
   It was not until a story about the book appeared in New York
that the notion occurred to the magazine's editors that Wolff might
be a candidate for the media critic job, which had been open since
Rich Turner left for Newsweek last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Wolff column, according to Caroline Miller, New York's
editor, will be ``written from his personal perspective, from his
experiences and considerable relationships with people.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolff described his approach to writing as ``there is no `off
the record.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Media is filled with people who are always spouting off at
each other,'' he said. ``So much of the information that moves
around in the business is information people feel they can't
report. The nice thing about a column is it's my space and I can
report that.''
</P>
<P>
   _ LISA NAPOLI
</P>
<P>
   All Walks of Celebrities Offer Their Predictions
</P>
<P>
   From two guys in a New Jersey basement comes this weighty tome:
``Predictions for the New Millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   By day, Todd Nickerson, 30, and David Kristof, 32, are
telecommunications salesmen. By night, they are neophyte authors
with worldwide headquarters in a Basking Ridge basement with a
computer data base of more than 6,000 celebrities who have received
their brief queries to write predictions or messages of hope for
the new millennium on a simple postcard.
</P>
<P>
   More than 600 messages came back _ enough material to fill a
book that will be published by Andrews &AMP; McMeel in November with
reproductions of the handwritten or typewritten musings. The
various millennium musers range from Bill Cosby and Joan Rivers _
who predicted that ``interest rates will be higher and my breasts
will be lower'' _ to Desmond Tutu and the Dalai Lama, who expressed
confidence that mankind will ``act with more maturity in the next
century and thus create better prospects for peace, harmony and
tolerance.''
</P>
<P>
   Nickerson said that he and his partner did not have a
particularly rigorous selection system; they gleaned names of the
famous and infamous from magazines and newspapers, drawing the line
at murderers. They unsuccessfully approached headliners like Monica
Lewinsky, Linda Tripp and Paula Jones, but were satisfied with
responses from Gloria Steinem, Chuck Yeager and Newt Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't quite honestly sure that it would be a success,''
Nickerson said. ``We've just been blown away by all the
responses.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he expressed some disappointment that he did not get a
postcard from President Clinton, who preferred to remain silent
about the post-millennium. On this issue, he apparently agreed with
Kenneth Starr, the independent prosecutor, who didn't return his
card, either.
</P>
<P>
   _ DOREEN CARVAJAL
</P>
</TEXT>
