<HEADLINE>
STATE'S MEDICAID ROLLS HAVE DECLINED SINCE '95 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By NINA BERNSTEIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a trend that has alarmed health care providers,
the number of poor people enrolled in Medicaid in New York state
has been declining for the last three years.
</P>
<P>
   While the strong economy may account for some of the drop, many
analysts say the decline is, in part, a side effect of the overhaul
of the nation's welfare system in late 1996, legislation that was
intended to move recipients into the work force.
</P>
<P>
   When Congress drafted the overhaul, it took pains to spell out
that people no longer entitled to welfare, particularly children,
would continue to be eligible for Medicaid, the federal and state
health benefits program created more than 30 years ago for the very
poor and the very sick. But in practice, health care analysts
contend, people who have been removed from welfare or discouraged
from applying in the first place have also been swept from the
Medicaid rolls.
</P>
<P>
   In New York state, whose efforts at reforming welfare were
taking shape before the federal overhaul began, the number of poor
people enrolled in Medicaid declined 26 percent, to 1.28 million,
between January 1995 and January 1998, according to analysts at the
United Hospital Fund, a nonprofit philanthropic and medical
research organization based in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The magnitude of the drop is a matter of debate, because of
growth in other, overlapping Medicaid categories, like disabled
adults and the ``medically needy,'' whose high medical expenses
offset their higher income. State officials, taking into account
some of those categories, put the decline in the number of poor
Medicaid recipients at closer to 17.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But whatever the figure, health care providers and analysts are
increasingly alarmed by the trend, which they say reflects an
emerging national pattern.
</P>
<P>
   ``The very group that is eligible for Medicaid and not getting
it are the kids who have the highest rates of asthma, anemia and
every imaginable health care problem,'' said Dr. Irwin Redlener,
director of community pediatrics for Montefiore Medical Center in
the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Officials estimate that 4.5 million children in New York state
are eligible for Medicaid but are not enrolled.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody can say for sure why Medicaid enrollment has fallen, but
analysts offer many reasons. The most optimistic is that in a
stronger economy, more people are finding jobs that offer private
health insurance. But Kathryn Haslanger, director of policy
analysis for United Hospital Fund, said this was unlikely to
account for much of the change, because the ranks of the uninsured
have been growing even faster in New York than in the nation as a
whole, and many low-wage jobs do not offer affordable insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Another partial explanation is that more low-income families may
be forgoing both welfare and Medicaid because new workfare rules
make it harder to combine a relief check with off-the-books
earnings, even as a better economy makes it easier to find a
part-time job.
</P>
<P>
   Also, many parents may not realize that their children probably
are still eligible for Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   Other reasons concern new barriers in the public-assistance
system, and the factor that Jim Tallon, president of the United
Hospital Fund, described as ``demand suppression _ where people are
simply not coming in the front door of the public-assistance
program because they perceive it not to be open to them.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   Historically, the vast majority of low-income Medicaid
beneficiaries were enrolled at the same time they qualified for
cash assistance in their local welfare office. This is still the
case, but fewer people have been seeking welfare, and more are
being turned away. The number of welfare recipients in the state
has shrunk since 1995 by at least 547,000, two-thirds of them
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``In welfare and Medicaid we are asking the former public
assistance system to do two opposing things,'' Tallon noted. ``One
is to divert people away from benefits, and the other is
simultaneously to maintain their eligibility for benefits. The data
suggests that there has been an enormous underestimation of the
administrative difficulty of implementing two conceptually
conflicting requirements.''
</P>
<P>
   The tension between the two public policy goals is evident in
New York. Gov. George Pataki has been in the forefront of a
national push to extend health insurance to more children, and
state lawmakers recently passed bills expanding both Medicaid and
Child Health Plus, a program aimed at insuring children of families
with somewhat higher income than the limit for Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   But in New York City, where most of the state's poor and
uninsured families live, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has been just as
outspokenly committed to redesigning welfare centers so that poor
people are discouraged from public assistance at the front door by
being directed to seek jobs or charity before they are allowed to
apply.
</P>
<P>
   Debra Sproles, a spokeswoman for the city's Human Resources
Administration, which oversees both welfare and Medicaid, said the
city is beginning an internal review of how welfare centers handle
Medicaid, ``to make sure that people are getting what they
should.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, people who still obtain Medicaid along with a
welfare grant are now at greater risk of losing both. Thousands of
recipients are cut from the rolls each month for failing to meet
strict workfare requirements, according to city data. People who
lose public assistance for any reason automatically lose Medicaid,
too, unless they appear in person at a Medicaid office for a
``redetermination'' of eligibility within 30 days _ a process that
state officials acknowledge has led to erroneous terminations.
</P>
<P>
   In Wisconsin, which pioneered the job-center model now gearing
up in New York City, a recent study by researchers at the Medical
College of Wisconsin in Milwaukee documented a 24 percent drop in
Medicaid enrollment among the state's children when they compared
the three-year period before that state's version of welfare reform
and the six-month period after full implementation in September
1997. Wisconsin recently started an aggressive Medicaid outreach
campaign, largely because state Medicaid caseloads had fallen so
much more than expected.
</P>
<P>
   Though national Medicaid enrollment figures are not yet
available for the period following the federal welfare overhaul,
during the 1995-1996 period, when similar welfare changes were
already well under way in many states, the decline already was
taking shape, said Leighton Ku, a health policy analyst at the
Urban Institute, a nonpartisan social policy research organization
based in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Few state Medicaid directors have been willing to draw attention
to the problem, Ku said. ``One, welfare reform is sacrosanct in
many states,'' he said. ``And the decline in caseload means for the
first time Medicaid is not eating the budget.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York state Coalition of Prepaid Health Services Plans
recently reported that ``involuntary disenrollments'' are running
20 percent higher this year than last year among more than 200,000
Medicaid managed-care members and now affect more than 4.17 percent
of the caseload each month, wreaking havoc with health care and
billing.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts at the Greater Hospital Association of New York said
they hoped the loss of children from Medicaid would be partly
offset and stemmed by Child Health Plus and ``enrollment-friendly''
measures recently passed by the state for children receiving both
welfare and Medicaid.
</P>
</TEXT>
