<HEADLINE>
NOTES AND QUOTES FROM THE PGA CHAMPIONSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ Despite finishing second in the PGA
Championship, Steve Stricker has much to be pleased about. He has
bounced back strong from a disappointing 1996, and he and his wife,
Nicki, are expecting a child in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Stricker broke down in tears at the post-tournament news
conference when he began talking about his wife, who often caddies
for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``No more questions about Nicki, she makes me cry,'' Stricker
said of his wife, who watched the tournament from home. ``I talked
to her last night, and she was really excited. We have a lot to
look forward to.''
</P>
<P>
   Stricker's even-par 70 Sunday was his first round in the 70s in
the tournament. He said the experience would help him in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned a lot today,'' Stricker said. ``You try to make it
feel like a regular tournament, but it's nearly impossible. This is
my first opportunity to win a major. I was fighting my swing. I
woke up early this morning, couldn't go back to sleep. I'm not
going to lie. It was difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   No Majors for Woods
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods, forced to settle for a tie for 10th place in the
tournament, was also forced to accept not winning a major
championship this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year I won one and played miserably the rest of the year,
but this year I have three top 10s'' Woods said, assessing his play
in the major championships. ``That's not too shabby.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't play too well today. I didn't hit the ball solid, and
I couldn't control my shots the way I needed to to give myself a
chance. Quite frankly, it's a mini-miracle to shoot what I shot the
last two rounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Vijay Singh's victory meant that all four majors were won by
players in their 30s or older. Mark O'Meara, who is 41, won the
Masters and the British Open; Lee Janzen, who won the U.S. Open, is
33, and Singh is 35.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Price, one of Singh's friends on tour, was glad to see him
rewarded for his effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``I''ve never seen anyone work as hard as that man does,'' Price
said of Singh. ``A couple of weeks back, I said to my caddie, `I'm
going to stay on the practice tee longer than Vijay today.' I was
there for five hours. I couldn't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Pebble Beach Revisited
</P>
<P>
   More than six months after it started, the AT&AMP;T Pebble Beach
National Pro-Am is finally scheduled to end on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   With the tournament's three courses saturated by water in
January, soaked by heavy rains in California, the tournament was
suspended Feb. 2 after only 36 holes. Faced with the prospect of
seeing the Pebble Beach event canceled for the second time in three
years because of rain, tournament and PGA Tour officials decided to
postpone the third round until March 2, and to end the event after
54 holes.
</P>
<P>
   However, several weeks after the original postponement, it
became obvious that the courses would still not be ready in early
March. At that point, it was decided to hold the third round on the
Monday after the PGA Championship, the next time the tour would be
out West.
</P>
<P>
   So Sunday night, players boarded a charter flight to Monterey,
Calif., to complete what will be remembered as a bizarre
tournament. Some of the players who are out of contention at Pebble
Beach are not expected to return for Monday's final round, but the
contenders definitely will, with a $450,000 first-place check at
stake.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Herron and Tom Watson are tied for the lead at six under
par, one stroke ahead of Jay Haas, Tom Lehman and Phil Mickelson.
Because Pebble Beach is the last West Coast event, the $100,000
bonus given by Bank of America for the year's West Coast money
leader has been put on hold until after Monday. David Duval is the
West Coast money leader with $533,663, but he will start Monday's
action 10 strokes off the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Enjoying Northwest Exposure
</P>
<P>
   The majority of players hoped that a future major would be held
at Sahalee Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great course,'' Davis Love III said. ``It proved it
could stand up to the best players in the world. We all got
frustrated at times because it's a tricky course. But we enjoyed
it. They did a great job with it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
