<SLUG> BC-NY-PARADE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELEBRATIONS IN NEW YORK DRAW WALL-TO-WALL POLITICIANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ANDY NEWMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The boys and girls in the fur-festooned blue and pink
gowns were wilting in the heat, their glittery lips going dry with
thirst. Twenty feet away, Peter Vallone, his white guayabera shirt
taking on wrinkles, tapped a rolled-up Dominican flag against his
leg impatiently. The Dominican Day Parade was more than an hour
late getting started because the mayor and the governor had not
shown up yet.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Flood, an aide to Vallone, materialized out of the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just spoke to Ramon,'' he said. ``There's no way to do this
parade and then the other parade and sneak you into the press
conference, too.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's really frustrating,'' Vallone, the City Council speaker
who is running for governor, said as he scanned the starting-line
crowd, which also included all three Democratic candidates for the
U.S. Senate. ``It's very rude to keep people waiting like this,
especially in the hot sun.''
</P>
<P>
   Vallone's annoyance was understandable. There were so many
parades, after all, and so little time.
</P>
<P>
   While New York City seldom seems emptier than on a weekend in
August, many of those who are left behind take advantage of the
opportunity to celebrate. And so it was that with at least six
festivals drawing the attention of state- and national-level
candidates, New York City spent much of Sunday in a state of
near-political gridlock.
</P>
<P>
   Office-seekers dashed from parade to street fair, changing
marshal sashes in the car as they idled in mini-traffic jams caused
by the very events they were trying to get to, and weighing the big
questions. Would the congresswoman wait for the candidate she was
endorsing to arrive? Was it possible to visit only the Indian
parade or just the Pakistani festival without alienating the other
constituency?
</P>
<P>
   Even though New York may be a media capital, the proliferation
of outlets itself makes old-fashioned politicking even more
important here than elsewhere, said Vallone's communications
director, Peter Ragone.
</P>
<P>
   ``In other places, in modern politics, you can just spend a lot
of money on TV,'' Ragone said. ``Here, it's so hard to reach a big
group of people that field organization and pressing the flesh
could make the big difference.'' And with 75 percent of the vote in
the Democratic primary expected to come from downstate, a day on
the stump becomes not just a scheduling challenge but an endurance
contest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't do my two miles on the treadmill this morning,''
Geraldine Ferraro, one of the Senate candidates, said, noting that
she had started the day at a Baptist church in Queens and planned
to hit the grand finale of the Harlem Week '98 street fair and the
Fere Agosto festival on Arthur Avenue in the Little Italy section
of the Bronx. ``I figure I'll make it up out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Even after Gov. George Pataki and Mayor Rudolph Giuliani finally
arrived _ ``coincidentally, at the same time,'' Vallone said _ and
the Dominican parade stepped off onto Avenue of the Americas at
36th Street, the logistical difficulties did not end. For one
thing, there were not enough endorsers to go around.
</P>
<P>
   Guillermo Linares, the Dominican-American Councilman from
Washington Heights who had endorsed Vallone at a pre-parade
breakfast, walked instead with Rep. Charles Schumer, the Senate
candidate, whom he had also endorsed. Linares kept breaking from
the march to hustle Schumer off to the side to shake hands, leaving
Vallone to stand in the middle and wave.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were going to switch off,'' Ragone said. ``But now it looks
like we may have to depart.'' He went off to speak to Vallone, but
the candidate simply glanced up at his watch as he waved his left
hand overhead and said he wanted to stay.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, around 43rd Street, Ragone and a colleague, barking
into their cell phones over the roars and whistles of the crowd,
got the break they needed: a call from an advance man for Nydia
Velazquez, a Democratic congresswoman from Brooklyn who was set to
march with Vallone in the Brooklyn Puerto Rican Parade in
Williamsburg _ which was just about to start.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nydia's advance guy says that she's running a little late,
too,'' Ragone said. ``He wanted to know if we could meet up and do
the endorsement after the parade.''
</P>
<P>
   Barely half an hour later, Vallone hopped out of the back of his
car in Williamsburg, shook hands with a man wearing a baseball cap
that declared ``Women want me, fish fear me'' and clutching a stack
of Vallone fliers, and marched in the last several hundred feet of
the parade before cutting across McCarren Park. With a little salsa
step, he took the stage overlooking a dusty ball field, just in
time for Ms. Velazquez's introduction.
</P>
<P>
   ``On September 15, you will see a parade of candidates'' on the
ballot, she told the crowd, and said she hoped they would vote for
Vallone, ``un Democrata de verdad.'' Vallone thanked Ms. Velazquez
profusely, gave his condensed stump speech and headed for Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a disaster that turned out to be a nice stop,'' he said,
praising his campaign team for coordinating it and noting with
pleasure that for the second day in a row, he had not run into any
of his opponents on the campaign trail. (One of them, Betsy
McCaughey Ross, spoke at a church in the Bronx, then spent much of
the afternoon in East Hampton at a benefit for a group that runs
women's shelters in Suffolk County. ``We did the unusual, we did
the unpredicted,'' said Kevin Davitt, Ms. McCaughey Ross'
spokesman.)
</P>
<P>
   In Harlem, Vallone bought a Not Just Fruit salad from a vendor,
Robert Best _the first bite he had eaten since the
pre-pre-parade-breakfast with his wife _ and bought a present for
his 8-year-old granddaughter: a tiny Cleveland Browns pillow that,
when turned inside out, became a teddy bear.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
