<SLUG> BC-NY-THEATER-FIRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRE FORCES THEATER EVACUATION 2ND DAY IN ROW 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KIT R. ROANE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A popular Upper West Side movie theater was evacuated
for the second time in as many days Sunday after a small fire broke
out in a storage room on the fourth floor, fire officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's fire at the Sony Lincoln Square and Imax Theater, which
started shortly before 2:50 p.m. as moviegoers were watching
matinees of shows like ``Saving Private Ryan'' and ``Lethal Weapon
4,'' came less than 24 hours after a pair of noxious smoke bombs
were set off in the theater, sending 4,000 people rushing outside.
Twenty-one people were treated for breathing difficulties, and two
had to be taken to local hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike that disturbance, which appeared to be the work of
pranksters, Sunday's fire was believed to be an accident, said
Assistant Chief Daniel Nigro of the New York City Fire Department.
A knapsack that firefighters had thought was suspicious, he added,
turned out to be harmless.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 61 firefighters were brought out by the fire, which
was extinguished in less than 25 minutes. Three patrons were taken
to St. Luke's-Roosevelt Hospital Center for treatment of smoke
inhalation, said Elbert Washington, a Fire Department spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   He added that a firefighter who was hit by a falling tile as he
battled the small blaze joined them later after complaining of neck
pain.
</P>
<P>
   For the others, the smoky fire spoiled an afternoon at the
movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was a bomb or something,'' said Matthew
Constantino, 25, adding that he did not wait for an explanation
before leaving his seat at the movie ``Snake Eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The movie just went off,'' he added, ``and this little guy
came to the front and said that due to circumstances beyond his
control, we would all have to be evacuated from the theater. The
guy did a good job of getting people out, but a lot of them refused
to leave unless they got fresh tickets. Not me.''
</P>
<P>
   Theater workers who spoke on condition of anonymity said that
ticketholders who missed shows Sunday would be able to exchange
them.
</P>
<P>
   A theater manager, who would not give his name, refused comment
on the fire or any possible refunds.
</P>
<P>
   The disturbance also caused trouble for drivers trying to make
their way along Broadway or crosstown on 67th and 68th Streets, as
about two dozen Fire Department vehicles clogged the roads for more
than two hours.
</P>
<P>
   Most theaters in the multiplex, which has 13 screens, had
reopened by 7 p.m. Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Josh Miller, 30, from the Lower East Side, said he would revisit
the theater quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll try again tomorrow,'' he said. ``I mean, the chance of
something like this happening two days in a row is pretty rare, so
I bet three days in a row gives me even better odds.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
