<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL NOTEBOOK: LOCAL RACE WITH A MAJOR TV BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JONATHAN P. HICKS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ While candidates for statewide office in next month's
Democratic primary have received a good deal of attention for their
spending for television advertisements, they are not alone in
buying media time. In a more local race, one candidate is planning
a television blitz in which he will spend more than any of his
opponents have raised for their entire campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   City Councilman Noach Dear, a candidate in the Democratic
primary for a congressional seat in a district that includes parts
of Brooklyn and Queens, is planning a $700,000 advertising campaign
that will run on the major network affiliate stations in the two
weeks before the Sept. 15 primary. The seat is now held by Rep.
Charles Schumer, who is seeking the Democratic nomination for U.S.
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Dear, who represents Borough Park, Brooklyn, is one of four
elected officials seeking the Democratic nomination to represent
the 9th Congressional District. The others are Anthony Weiner, a
city councilman from Sheepshead Bay, Brooklyn, and two members of
the Assembly, Daniel Feldman of Sheepshead Bay and Melinda Katz,
who represents Forest Hills, Queens.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Dear has taken on an unusual campaign tactic. His
campaign has produced a 10-minute videotape that will be mailed to
about 20,000 residents in the congressional district who are
considered likely voters.
</P>
<P>
   John Paone, a spokesman for Dear's campaign, said the tapes will
include biographical information about the Councilman, his views on
various issues and ``testimonials from people he has worked with.''
They will also include comments from constituents and at least one
elected official _ City Councilman Alfonso Stabile, a Republican
from Howard Beach, Queens.
</P>
<P>
   Although Dear's spending on television is considerable, his
opponents suggest that such heavy spending is unnecessary and that
they do not feel overwhelmed by the councilman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the race will depend on grass-roots operation and
people who really care who represents them,'' Ms. Katz said. ``I'm
counting on volunteers and people in the community. I don't think
money can buy that.''
</P>
<P>
   Weiner said, ``Most likely, he'll spend the most money, but
he'll come in last. You can't buy a district like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials in the campaigns of Dear's opponents suggested that
the councilman's strategy was to advertise on television at the
expense of appearances at forums or debates with his Democratic
rivals. Just last month, Dear declined to participate in a debate
between the candidates on New York 1, the cable news station. They
also pointed out that Dear has so far not participated in any
forums or debates with other candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Paone denied that the councilman refuses to debate, but said
that the candidate prefers responding to the questions at forums
from ordinary citizens in the district, rather than reporters. ``He
just thinks voters should have more of a voice in the process,''
Paone said.
</P>
<P>
   A Rare Primary Challenge
</P>
<P>
   For leaders of political parties in New York City, there are few
priorities higher than keeping their incumbents from facing primary
challenges. And of the Democratic Party chairmen in the five
boroughs, none is quite as passionate as Roberto Ramirez, the Bronx
Democratic chairman, whose organization works diligently through
the courts and other means to keep insurgents off the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Ramirez, an assemblyman from Kingsbridge,
successfully challenged the election petitions of an opponent, who
was thrown off the ballot. And the assemblyman has had no
challenger since he was elected in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   So this year, Ramirez must feel he is traveling in uncharted
territory. He is facing a primary challenge from Richard Soto, a
businessman.
</P>
<P>
   Soto ran unsuccessfully last year for a City Council seat. And
while he lost to Adolpho Carrion Jr., the candidate backed by the
Democratic Party organization, he won nearly 40 percent of the
vote.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez said he relished the prospect of a campaign. ``There are
a few things I do well, and campaigning is one of them,'' he said.
``I love to go out and talk to people.''
</P>
<P>
   But the activities within the Democratic organization in the
Bronx have made it clear that its chairman would prefer no
opposition. The organization spared no effort to force Soto off the
ballot by challenging his filing papers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have subpoenaed our witnesses, and 15 to 20 of the people
who signed petitions,'' said Carl Saez, Soto's campaign manager.
``They had 10 lawyers down at the Board of Elections trying to
knock us off the ballot. We feel that Ramirez is concerned with
establishing his own fiefdom instead of being concerned about the
community. He's afraid of a challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   A Battle for Independence
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, their contest at the polls turned out to be one
of the closest among the state's legislative elections. Now, it
seems that Ann Margaret Carrozza, a first-term Democratic
assemblywoman from Queens, will once again face Douglas Prescott,
the Republican and former assemblyman she defeated in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Prescott's defeat was considered a major blow to Queens
Republicans because he had represented the 26th Assembly District
in northeastern Queens for all but two years since 1980. Ms.
Carrozza, a political novice who had worked as a law secretary to a
state Supreme Court justice in Queens, won with 53 percent of the
vote.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly half her total came from voters who pulled the lever
under the Independence Party line. And so a battle between Ms.
Carrozza and Prescott has been waged this summer over which
candidate would receive the Independence Party's designation.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, Republican officials had courted the Independence
Party and thought they had a deal giving Prescott the nomination,
but the party selected Ms. Carrozza. Prescott tried to gather
enough signatures to force a primary on that ballot line, but that
effort failed last week when a state Supreme Court justice tossed
out his petitions, saying that they had been improperly collected.
Prescott did not return calls to his home.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Carrozza must still face Prescott in November. ``I feel
positive and optimistic,'' she said. ``I just hope that the race
will be one where we discuss issues and that the other side will
not be nasty.''
</P>
</TEXT>
