<HEADLINE>
CUTS STING MARINERS IN CLOSE SHAVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM STREET  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The Mariners were reminded Sunday that proper
execution often is the difference in a close game.
</P>
<P>
   A missed sacrifice bunt, a blown chance at a double play and a
couple of outfield throws that were cut off when they might have
produced outs put the M's in a what-if mood after a 5-3 loss to the
Chicago White Sox before 25,471 fans at Comiskey Park.
</P>
<P>
   Thus the nine-game road trip that began with a four-game sweep
in Detroit ended with a four-losses-in-five-games whimper.
</P>
<P>
   ``That has been the pattern all year,'' manager Lou Piniella
said. ``We've had our good streaks and our bad streaks. We just
haven't been able to get over the hump.''
</P>
<P>
   Mariner starter Jeff Fassero pitched a complete game but wasn't
particularly sharp in absorbing his ninth loss in 10 decisions.
Chicago second baseman Ray Durham led a 13-hit assault with a
two-run homer in the third inning to erase a one-run Sox deficit
and singled home the eventual game-winner in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Buhner's two-run homer in the top of the seventh pulled
Seattle even.
</P>
<P>
   But close games aren't the Mariners' forte this season _ they
are 4-19 in one-run games and 12-12 in two-run games _ and they
returned home last night for an eight-game homestand, undoubtedly
wondering when they will win another close one.
</P>
<P>
   Asked for an explanation, Mariner shortstop Alex Rodriguez said,
``Our fundamentals, as a unit, haven't been very good this
season.''
</P>
<P>
   He was involved in two of the most crucial plays, both in the
sixth inning.
</P>
<P>
   When Rodriguez didn't hear a call from third baseman Russ Davis,
he cut off a throw from center fielder Ken Griffey Jr., erasing any
chance of cutting down Albert Belle at third base.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been a close play,'' Davis said, ``but I didn't
tell Alex what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Rodriguez: ``I (cut it) on my own.''
</P>
<P>
   To magnify what might have been, Wil Cordero chopped a grounder
to Rodriguez, who got caught between hops. He said he didn't want
to be over-aggressive and mishandle the ball or force an awkward
throw to second base.
</P>
<P>
   He took the safe route and didn't have enough time to complete
what would have been an inning-ending double play, allowing Belle
to score and give Chicago a 3-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   After Buhner's 11th homer of the season produced his 28th and
29th RBIs since the All-Star break and tied the score, Davis
doubled to right-center, putting the Mariners in position to regain
the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Then came another fundamental breakdown.
</P>
<P>
   Catcher John Marzano, trying to advance Davis to third with a
sacrifice bunt, bit at reliever Keith Foulke's first pitch and
bunted the ball on one hop to the pitcher, who gunned down Davis at
third.
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, Marzano said he should have waited for a better
pitch to bunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was up and in, and although (Foulke) made a good play on
the ball, it wasn't a good bunt by any stretch of the
imagination,'' Marzano said. ``Yeah, I should have waited for a
pitch I could have gotten down better.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Mariner catcher Chad Kreuter led off the seventh inning
with a double into the left-field corner, and Durham ended his
productive game with a game-winning single to center off Fassero.
</P>
<P>
   After arguing with plate umpire Bill Miller about a called
strike, Durham calmed down and delivered a base hit that scored
pinch-runner Mike Cameron from second base.
</P>
<P>
   Fassero, who pitched out of most of the other jams he
encountered, then yielded a run-scoring single to Mag-glio Ordonez
for an eighth-inning insurance run.
</P>
<P>
   Although Mariner left fielder Raul Ibanez made a strong throw to
the plate, Davis cut it off and settled for the inning-ending out
at third base.
</P>
<P>
   ``In that situation, late in the game, I probably should have
let (the throw) go through,'' Davis said. ``But I didn't think it
was going to be in time to get (Robert Machado).''
</P>
<P>
   Fassero pitched his club-high fifth complete game of the season,
but labored most of the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``He kept us in the game, but he's been sharper,'' Piniella
said. ``The White Sox hit the ball well against us the whole
series. They even had 17 hits in the game they lost (Saturday
night).''
</P>
</TEXT>
