<HEADLINE>
HUARD'S GOAL FOR '98 GOES FAR BEYOND HELPING SELF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Brock Huard has heard from former Husky teammate
Jerome Pathon how different the NFL is from college. Maybe that's
why Huard is the happiest man in Seattle right now.
</P>
<P>
   He knows he was right to stay at the University of Washington
for his junior season.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can get caught up in the emotion of that, `I could be in
the NFL,' but then you look at it and you know you've made the
right decision,'' Huard said.
</P>
<P>
   And since Pathon made a visit to the Kingdome last week to play
against the Seahawks as a member of the Indianapolis Colts, it is
easier for Huard to smile. All the talk, all the feedback serves to
re-affirm Huard's decision.
</P>
<P>
   None of the 10 Huskies drafted last April is telling the
6-foot-5, 225-pound lefty quarterback how great it is, how easy
life gets once you've grabbed the NFL's brass ring.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies are preparing for a season in which they could be
frequently over-matched. Still, Huard is like a kid with a happy
secret.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not trade places with anybody in the world right
now,'' Huard said Sunday about a season he hopes becomes one of the
most fulfilling experiences of his life.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Huard, a Heisman Trophy candidate and top pro prospect,
is placing no pressure on himself beyond this season. The future
will take care of itself, he figures, which is why he has not taken
out an insurance policy to protect himself against a career-ending
injury _ a standard practice among top collegians, especially when
they have passed up a pro draft to stay one more year in school.
</P>
<P>
   Huard said an insurance policy to protect his financial
potential is not his style. He is ``letting that rest in greater
hands.'' He believes that if his football career came to an end in
college and not in the NFL, where many expect Huard will be a top
draft pick next April, then a different course in life was meant
for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a lot of goals and dreams. I just kind of take
this one day at a time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With that kind of mind-set, Huard does not care that 1998 will
in no way resemble last season, when the Huskies, stocked with
future NFL draft picks, were preseason favorites to win the
national championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year there was such great expectation. I think some of
the expectation outweighed some of that excitement. It was like,
`Let's get to the game and prove that we can live up to these
expectations,''' said Huard, who has all but been left behind after
the departure of 1997 Husky standouts like Pathon, Rashaan Shehee,
Jason Chorak, Cam Cleeland, Benji Olson, Olin Kreutz, Fred Coleman
and Tony Parrish.
</P>
<P>
   Now it is as if Huard is starring in ``Gulliver's Travels,'' the
way he towers in stature and ability over his (pardon the
expression) no-name Husky teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year we had some great physical talent, but the overtone
now is that we're a better team. We're a better group of guys, a
better attitude. There's a lot of positive feelings,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the fault of the guys who had talent, and not that
all the 10 draft picks last year were bad guys. I'm not saying that
at all. But what happens sometimes, guys who have been waiting
their turn, guys that have been backups, they're getting their
chance.''
</P>
<P>
   And Huard wants to lead them, even if the Husky schedule takes
them to Arizona State on opening day, and through Pac-10 favorite
UCLA and Lincoln, Neb., and even though the go-to guys Huard is
supposed to throw to, and the guys who are going to carry the ball,
have yet to emerge.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Pathon and Coleman accounted for 111 receptions,
1,968 yards and 15 touchdowns. Now all eyes will be on track star
Ja'Warren Hooker to fill some of that void, along with Gerald
Harris and Huard's former Puyallup High School teammate, Dane
Looker.
</P>
<P>
   After two seasons, Huard is only 1,819 passing yards short of
his brother Damon's school record. Yet, he is not looking for
individual stats or accomplishments to measure his success.
</P>
<P>
   He called the hug of friendship and gratitude he got from
Coleman on the field after last year's Aloha Bowl one of the best
moments in his career. It is for such moments that he is back.
</P>
<P>
   ``How much can I improve myself and just give of myself to make
everyone else better? That's what it is,'' Huard said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leaders need to serve. Great leaders do that. They serve first
and they give first, and if they can command that respect, they can
lift people.''
</P>
<P>
   Not many of us know ourselves so well, so young, but Huard is a
rare and lucky one. The light came on and the vision was clear,
which may be why The Big Man on Campus is wearing a smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys in the NFL now are saying how different it is. Things
like `Boy, it's a lot of work. I can't believe we start training
camp in mid-July. This is a business. You have to earn your
paycheck,''' Huard said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad I'm making my $670 a month right now. Actually, I'm
not making anything yet, since we're living in the dorms, but that
$670 (stipend) will be just fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Which goes to show you: All the money in the world couldn't buy
you a college quarterback with better priorities.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
