<SLUG> BC-FBC-HUSKIES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUSKIES OPEN WITH ATTITUDE CHECK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BUD WITHERS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Last year, when the University of Washington football
team gathered in fall camp for its conditioning tests _ 16 sprints
of 110 yards in a required time _ one of the guys who didn't make
it was a senior co-captain.
</P>
<P>
   Bad sign.
</P>
<P>
   Talk to the leaders of the 1998 club that had its first
two-a-day drills Sunday, and they'll say that what might have
seemed like a trifling, mid-August moment was actually symptomatic
of what went awry with the '97 Huskies, who started with national
championship aspirations and finished 8-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that he didn't make them (the 110s) didn't look good
at all,'' said tight end Reggie Davis, a '98 co-captain.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did the season, after a convincing loss to Nebraska and
three numbing November defeats.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Huskies are like a lot of other clubs, saying their
minds are right. One hundred twelve Division I-A teams, honk if
you've got a better attitude than a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year is really different,'' insisted rover Nigel Burton,
another co-captain. ``People are really looking out for each other.
Everybody seems to be buying into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis, Burton and the two other co-captains, linebacker Lester
Towns and quarterback Brock Huard, agree that they don't want to
repeat mistakes they saw made by some of last year's seniors, the
class that had a collegiate-high 10 players drafted by the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had great guys on the team,'' said Davis. ``But I think
there was too much focus on going to the next level before it was
time. I plan on going to the NFL myself, but that's not something I
focus on right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Especially now that I'm a senior, I could understand thinking
about the NFL _ thinking I've got to perform this year, that I've
got to have the ball to show people what I can do. I just think it
comes down to prioritizing.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton was asked how much ``senioritis'' played a part on the
1997 team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Huge,'' he said, as he downed a Philly cheesesteak sandwich
between practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, we had 10 or 12 guys (anticipating the NFL). (It
was) `I got to get better, I got to do this, I got to do that.' The
problem is, there were a lot of I's in that statement, and in the
long run, it hurt us as a team.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton won't forget the mess of November, when the Huskies
allowed 124 points to Oregon, UCLA and Washington State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw it on the defense,'' Burton recalls. ``The other team
would score, we'd come off the field, and it was like watching 11
dogs snapping at each other. It was like, `I didn't mess up, you
messed up.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Pointing fingers, yelling at each other, coaches trying to
calm things down on the sideline ... part of that is the heat of
battle. But it wasn't positive, it was critical, it was `You, you,
you.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody always tried to fix it, but the damage was already
done.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been few discouraging words uttered about the '97
Husky seniors. These were the freshmen who entered the UW in 1993
and were immediately bludgeoned with the Pac-10's two-year bowl
sanction.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps in the end, some of last year's seniors simply got tired
of it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't get inside their heads,'' Burton said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he sensed senioritis last year, UW coach Jim
Lambright said, ``I just think this is a different group, a
different year. You have much more dominant captain control of the
team. It's been great, the commitment by so many more players over
the summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the coaches have done some soul-searching away from
videotape and playbook. In July, they attended a retreat in
Winthrop sponsored by positive-thinking guru Lou Tice.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing that came out was, change is growth,'' said
offensive coordinator Scott Linehan. ``For us as a coaching staff,
we've been doing pretty much the same thing since I've been here.
</P>
<P>
   ``This coaching staff has worked some (long) hours, and when we
lost a game, it was worse. But maybe we can work smarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other thing is, you get to know a little more about the
people you work with. It's kind of fun to see (assistant coach) Ron
Milus on a horse. I never thought I'd see that.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton says he senses a change in the coaching approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just us (players),'' Burton said. ``The longer they
can keep their new attitude, keep things positive, the longer we're
going to be able to do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot more of our meetings have been less X's and O's, more
about goal-setting, making sure everything's right with our team.
It's just kind of snowballing. There's a good feeling about being
around here.''
</P>
<P>
   NOTES: ILB Lester Towns, still bothered by the after-effects of
April foot surgery, did little in Sunday's workouts. ... The
on-again, off-again weather caused the Huskies some uncertainty for
their afternoon practice. They wanted to work out on grass, but an
overnight irrigation and the unexpected rains drenched the natural
stuff and kept them on AstroTurf. ... Burton and RB Maurice Shaw
were limited by mild hamstring pulls. ... The three-game academic
suspension of CB Mel Miller bumps Toure Butler into a starting role
through the Nebraska game and means redshirt freshman Wondame Davis
must play early. ... Using an index of weight lifts including the
bench press, incline press, squat and power clean, the Huskies'
five strongest players are offensive linemen Chad Ward, Brad Hutt
and Ben Kadletz, plus Towns and Reggie Davis. ... Towns did a
480-pound bench press and 415 incline to set UW linebacker records,
Hutt did the same with 391 in the power clean and WR Andre
DeSaussure had a 375 bench for an all-time high at his position.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
