<HEADLINE>
DOUBLE BOGEY ENDS LOVE'S BID FOR REPEAT PGA TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANGELO BRUSCAS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ There would be no rainbow over Davis Love III
Sunday, only rain on his parade, ending his bid to become the PGA's
first back-to-back champion since Denny Shute in 1936-37.
</P>
<P>
   Love began the day at 3 under par, four strokes behind Vijay
Singh and Steve Stricker. He finished with an even-par 70 and a tie
for seventh place.
</P>
<P>
   Before he started the final round, Love alluded to the rainbow
that spread over the 18th green at Winged Foot Golf Club in New
York, where he claimed his first major victory in the 1997 PGA
Championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``A year ago, I was hoping for a rainbow before we started to
get me off to a good start,'' Love said.
</P>
<P>
   But he never saw one Sunday, and said it felt a little different
this year, having to chase the leaders rather than leading the
tournament and holding on for the victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I know what it felt like last year chasing Justin
(Leonard) and myself,'' Love said. Love and Leonard began the final
round at Winged Foot tied for first place, seven strokes ahead of
the field.
</P>
<P>
   The end came early Sunday. After running off four consecutive
pars, Love put his tee shot on the 195-yard par-3 fifth hole into a
pond and ended up with a double bogey from which he never
recovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``My round was not very good,'' Love said. `` ... It was not
what I was looking for today. Obviously, Vijay was in control and
it would have taken a lot, probably even an impossible score, to
win. It certainly wasn't the round I wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Love acknowledged that the weather has played a big role in the
last two PGA Championships. He said Sunday's rain made the greens
and fairways softer at Sahalee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it made play a little easier, but it's still the last
round of a major, so it still plays pretty hard,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The outgoing champion also had kind parting words for Sahalee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great course,'' Love said. ``It proved it can stand up
to the best players in the world. We all got frustrated at times
because it's a tricky course. You have to be very patient.
</P>
<P>
   ``We enjoyed it, it is in great shape, and they did a great job
with it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
