<SLUG> BC-PGA-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SINGH NO LONGER AN ISLAND UNTO HIMSELF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ Staying on the island will be hard now.
</P>
<P>
   Not Fiji. Vijay Singh long ago left his Polynesian homeland.
Hasn't returned in years.
</P>
<P>
   The island he's been on is mostly self-created. The solitary man
on the practice range. The reticent man who resents interviews. The
stoic man who never betrays an emotion. A colorless man of color in
a mostly white game. The man with a cheat in his past.
</P>
<P>
   Now he is PGA champion, a winner of one of pro golf's four
majors. At least a part of him now belongs to sports history, to
the golf public. And to a world that demands more of its champions
than grinding efficiency, one that won't let him emulate the other
mysterious Polynesian icons, the equally inscrutable stone faces of
Easter Island.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the PGA Championship draws him from his self-made
isolation will be one of the more intriguing stories on the golf
tour. But when he grows contemptuous of the personal stretch, he
can always return in comfort to a little patch of forest east of
Seattle, where he said he ``got the most yelling I've ever got.''
</P>
<P>
   A guy the touts didn't see coming won the little Redmond golf
festival Sunday, and in return, it won him over _ an affection that
seemed to startle a man unfamiliar with such expressions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised at how many cheers I got on every hole I went
to,'' Singh said. ``I think this is the best crowd I've ever
experienced for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were really very fair. I just wish we could have this
kind of crowd every tournament we go to.''
</P>
<P>
   Not a lot of people have cheered for Singh.
</P>
<P>
   His now-infamous episode of scorecard alteration at the 1985
Indonesian Open got him suspended from the Australian PGA Tour and
led to his temporary golf exile in Borneo. The frequency with which
the subject was reintroduced upon his appearances in Europe and the
United States has led to an alienation with the golf media.
</P>
<P>
   In Fiji, almost none of his immediate family remains, having
scattered to New Zealand, Australia and beyond. The Fijian East
Indian community of which they were a part has grown large and
influential, to the dismay of some of the native population. The
tension created racial politics, including for a time legislated
discrimination. So it wasn't so surprising the way he responded to
a question about how his victory will be greeted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope I'm a hero in Fiji,'' he said. ``It's hard to answer
that question.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1993, he and his wife and son have lived in one those
faceless golf-community suburbs near Jacksonville, Fla. They also
keep an apartment in London. The man who never misses a cut and
never makes an impression is virtually a man without a country,
even though he has played golf in many of them.
</P>
<P>
   Now a winner of six PGA Tour events and seven on the European
tour, he was probably more deserving than either Colin Montgomerie
of Phil Mickelson of the dubious sobriquet of ``best golfer never
to win a major.'' But he is so bereft of constituency that he
seemed only on the periphery of the PGA's golf consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   Not anymore.
</P>
<P>
   The expectation was that Singh and another unlikely challenger,
fellow third-round leader Steve Stricker, would fall to pressure on
a damp day that anticipated charges from Tiger Woods and Mark
O'Meara. Instead, golf's likeliest history makers fell back. It was
left to former PGA champions Nick Price and Steve Elkington to get
hot. But they began too late.
</P>
<P>
   The tournament came down to the final twosome on the 17th green.
Singh was a stroke ahead of Stricker and each had a similar putt of
12 feet for par.
</P>
<P>
   For Singh, such pressure evokes a memory from his days of exile
as a teaching pro in Borneo after his fall from grace. To keep his
wits and his competitive edge in the steaming jungle courses, he
would play high-stakes handicap games with timber and oil
executives.
</P>
<P>
   He told John Garrity of Sports Illustrated that he was down to
the last hole with $10 in his pocket and $700 on the line. The
par-5 required a shot over water to an island fairway, but he hit
his drive out of bounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The feeling I had when I stood over the next drive was the
worst feeling I've ever had in the game,'' Singh said. ``How would
I pay if I lost? Would I lose my job? What would I tell my wife?''
</P>
<P>
   Singh found the fairway with his second shot and made eagle
while his opponent double-bogeyed.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I won the hole and a lot of money,'' Singh said. ``Now
whenever I'm in contention in a tournament, I think about that.''
</P>
<P>
   At Sahalee, far from the equatorial jungle but with almost as
much at stake, Singh drained his putt. Stricker slid past to the
left, and the guy called the hardest working man in golf business
had his championship, and considerable redemption.
</P>
<P>
   Since his 1985 transgression, which Singh to this day denies was
cheating, calling it a misunderstanding, he has had no further
character challenges. Neither are there challengers to his
standards of effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of us foreigners tend to gravitate towards each other
over the years, and I've played a lot of golf with him,'' said
Price, a native of Zimbabwe who finished tied for fourth. ``I've
never seen anyone work as hard as that man does.
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple of weeks back I said to my caddie, `I'm going to stay
on the practice tee longer than Vijay today.' I was there for about
five hours. I couldn't do it, and that was just one day.
</P>
<P>
   ``You talk to anyone who lives in Jacksonville ... I mean that
guy's torn up more practice tees. I wonder how much earth he's
moved over the years.''
</P>
<P>
   He has a fresh patch of earth now. The man who left one island
for another is upon golf's mainland, whether or not he _ and golf _
are ready.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
