<HEADLINE>
COUPLES FINISHES STRONGLY IN FRONT OF HOMETOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANGELO BRUSCAS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ The standing ovation echoed through the
evergreens, and Fred Couples soaked it in like the liquid sunshine
that briefly covered Sahalee on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   After nearly bowing out after the first two rounds, the native
son rebounded with a 3-under-par 67 Saturday and a 68 Sunday to
finish at even par in his 17th PGA Championship.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't enough to put him in contention, but Couples was
pleased he made the cut and gave his hometown fans something to
cheer about in the final two rounds.
</P>
<P>
   As he left the 18th green, fans started chanting, ``Freddie,
Freddie, Freddie.''
</P>
<P>
   He only wished his entire round Sunday had ended like it began,
with back-to-back birdies. Instead, he had to scramble to save pars
on the back side.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good day. I got off to a booming start, then slowed
down a little bit and then played well the rest of the way,''
Couples said. ``To shoot 2-under (Sunday), I'm real proud of that.
... I wish I would have played well on the first day.''
</P>
<P>
   Couples also was proud of Seattle-area golf fans and the golf
course itself, which had never played host to a regular PGA Tour
event, much less a tournament the magnitude of the PGA
Championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is where I grew up so I was waiting for this a long
time,'' Couples said. ``So far, everyone has liked the place and
that's a good feeling, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though he was the heavy fan favorite, Couples said he
thought the crowd ``was behind everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   ``With everyone screaming at you, it was lot of fun, but it's a
long week,'' Couples said. ``I would never say that I didn't have a
great time, but I knew on Monday not to get too enthralled with
being from here. It's a big tournament and I just wanted to go out
and play.''
</P>
<P>
   The course held up well, according to Couples, and Sahalee
proved that the Seattle area can support one of golf's major
championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``The area deserved a big tournament. The people have come out
from everywhere to watch it,'' he said. ``That's what you go by.
And any golf course that you make this hard is going to be close to
par.''
</P>
<P>
   For Couples, the key to making Sahalee difficult enough for a
major event was shortening two par-5s (the sixth and 18th holes)
and converting them to par-4s, lowering the par for the course from
72 to 70 for the best players in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``They needed to do that. You need to have a par-70,'' Couples
said. ``I don't think any player has had a gripe about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Just because the course measures 6,906 yards doesn't necessarily
mean it's short and easy for Couples or any of the other players.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great course,'' Couples said. ``True, the first couple
of days, it played a little shorter off the tees, with people
hitting a lot of irons. But I have played at Inverness before and
Riviera, and it's a lot like those courses. It's just a lot longer
from your tee shot to the greens here.''
</P>
<P>
   Couples also liked the course conditions, calling the greens
``the best we've played on all year. The rough was deep and
tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead, Couples will play in a skins game against Ernie
Els in Whistler, B.C., then will wed Thais Bren on Sept. 12. He
will go to Paris for a European Tour event, have a honeymoon, and
return to play the Las Vegas Invitational and The Tour Championship
in October.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't plan to get back on a regular PGA Tour schedule until
next January, when he hopes to accumulate enough points to make the
Ryder Cup team. The 1999 Ryder Cup will be played at the Country
Club in Brookline, Mass., and Couples is in fourth place, behind
Mark O'Meara, David Duval and Tiger Woods, for one of the top 10
spots on the U.S. team.
</P>
<P>
   Points are awarded for top-10 finishes at PGA Tour co-sponsored
events during 1998 and 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will play a lot early on the West Coast up until (the
Masters), and see what happens,'' Couples said. ``I always get off
to a quick start, so if I do, that will put me in position to maybe
make the team. If that's the case, then I will try to play a little
more to get points to make it.''
</P>
<P>
   After he tapped in his final par putt, Couples felt the emotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I heard it up close, I felt like I would like to hear
that every week,'' Couples said. ``I'd like to play in Seattle
every week.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
