<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-ACURA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVENPORT NOT NO. 2 THIS TIME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE STEVENS  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANHATTAN BEACH, Calif. _ Lindsay Davenport is on such a roll
that not even the world's top-ranked player can slow her down.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport's scorching play continued Sunday as she beat
top-ranked Martina Hingis 4-6, 6-4, 6-3 in the final of the Acura
Classic at Manhattan Country Club. It was Davenport's third
straight tournament victory and 12th consecutive match win.
</P>
<P>
   As Davenport, the second-ranked player, inches closer to Hingis
in the rankings, she points to serenity as the key to her streak.
``I just feel so calm and in control out there on the court,''
Davenport said. ``I don't ever feel rushed. I don't feel I am not
getting upset like I used to get.''
</P>
<P>
   Service breaks were the key to the match. Hingis broke Davenport
twice in the first set to win, recovering from a 4-2 deficit.
Davenport won the final two sets because she broke Hingis' serve
early and did not allow Hingis to break her.
</P>
<P>
   The sore point for the 17-year-old Swiss miss was her first
serve. She put in 84 percent of her first serves in the first set.
In the following two sets, she made just 45 percent of her first
serves. Hingis also was hurt by seven double faults to Davenport's
three. Yet Davenport did not see Hingis' serve as a major factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``She served well,'' Davenport said. ``I think people always
underestimate her serve. She might not hit it 110 (mph), but she
places it where she wants it to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Davenport's hard returns affected Hingis' serve. ``She put on a
lot of pressure from her side,'' Hingis said. ``Because of that, in
the third set, you get a little tired and you can't concentrate
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Though women's tennis has become more of a serving game _ like
the men's _ not all of the players have become accustomed to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``In women's tennis now, you have to keep holding serve,''
Hingis said. ``It's like men's tennis, and I just don't feel at
home with that strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Davenport's win, Hingis has a strong grip on the No.1
ranking. With the victory, Davenport made up 54 points in the
rankings and now trails Hingis by 444 points. Davenport might have
the latest bragging rights, but she does not put heavy stock into
them or the rankings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Number one is 52 weeks of a player's results,'' she said. ``I
have had three great weeks, but Martina has had about 40 greater
weeks than I have had.''
</P>
<P>
   Davenport, a resident of Newport Beach, took home $79,000 with
the win plus an Acura, the first car she has won in her career.
Hingis made $36,000.
</P>
<P>
   The match lasted 1 hour, 26 minutes. It ended on a marathon
point, in which Hingis twice hit drop shots to force Davenport to
charge the net. Hingis also hit a lob that forced Davenport to the
baseline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everyone thought I had won that point before I won
it,'' Davenport said.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport's goal is not to become No.1. Rather, she wants to win
a Grand Slam tournament. She will have a chance at the U.S. Open,
which starts August 31. Davenport is hoping her streak will
continue until the Open. Hingis joked that she is hoping for
something else.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has to take a break now and let somebody else win a
tournament,'' Hingis said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
