<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PGA-FINAL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SINGH CAPTURES PGA CHAMPIONSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ Vijay Singh often strayed from the fairway,
visiting places that resembled his native Fiji and adopted
Malaysia. But the world traveler pushed aside the branches and
plowed his way through the tall grass to complete the golfing
journey of a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   Singh calmly shot his way to a two-stroke victory Sunday in the
80th PGA Championship at Sahalee Country Club, holding off both
Steve Stricker and a Pacific Northwest monsoon.
</P>
<P>
   Flashing an easy smile and a confident swing, Singh collected
his first victory in a major championship, a check for $540,000 and
a considerable boost to his golf reputation. He shot a 2-under-par
68 Sunday, giving him a 9-under 271 total.
</P>
<P>
   Of East Indian heritage with a first name that means ``victory''
in Hindi, Singh had been better known as a player who practiced
incessantly and won too infrequently. No more.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something I thought was never going to happen,'' said
Singh, as a heavy, post-tournament rain beat down on the media
tent. ``I never expected it to happen like this. I've practiced so
hard for this. It's a dream come true.''
</P>
<P>
   Geography prevailed while history took a beating in Sahalee's
tree-lined classroom. Mark O'Meara, pursuing a rare third major
victory in one season, finished tied for fourth, five strokes back.
Davis Love III, bidding to become the PGA's first repeat champion
in 61 years, wound up tied for seventh, six strokes behind.
</P>
<P>
   The people's choices also took a backseat. Tournament favorite
and first-round leader Tiger Woods finished tied for 10th, eight
strokes back, and Seattle native Fred Couples closed strongly to
finish tied for 13th, nine back.
</P>
<P>
   Singh gave only Stricker a chance to beat him, and it was a
fleeting opportunity. The two golfers entered the final round tied,
then Stricker grabbed a one-shot lead through four holes, gave it
back a hole later and fell behind for good with a bogey at No. 6.
If this was match play, it was over by the 17th hole, when Stricker
bogeyed one last time.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of South Seattle might not know Singh well, but
everyone from the South Pacific to Southern Asia was ready to claim
him Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Ani Gulati, an Indian-American attorney, flew from Minneapolis
solely to watch Singh play. He couldn't believe his good fortune _
witnessing Singh score his career breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   On the 10th tee, a bearded man in a red turban, Gurpreet Singh
Pall, stood fixated on the golfer, close enough to touch him. The
Microsoft employee, who let out a loud squeal when Singh nearly
holed a shot on the 15th, was accompanied by two other
Indian-Americans, Sesh Velamoor and Sunny Singh, both involved in
the computer industry. The trio came away captivated by the
outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``India is only known for scientists and engineers,'' Velamoor
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And camels,'' said Gurpreet Singh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it will be for golf,'' Velamoor concluded.
</P>
<P>
   In winning for the sixth time on the PGA Tour and 24th time
worldwide, Singh simply would not go away, as he had so many times
before. He grabbed the lead from Woods in the second round and
shared it with Stricker after the third.
</P>
<P>
   Burning in his memory were recent failed attempts in the PGA
Championship _ he finished 13th, fifth and fourth in three of the
previous five events. He even asked Nick Price, a three-time major
winner, for some early morning advice regarding the task at hand.
Price's words were more of a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Go out there and play your own game. You know what
to do. You've played it enough,''' Singh said. ``And that's what I
did.''
</P>
<P>
   Singh had won in such far-flung places as Nigeria, Morocco,
Zimbabwe, Sweden and the Ivory Coast. He had worked as a club pro
in Malaysia and Borneo. Sahalee couldn't show him much he hadn't
seen before.
</P>
<P>
   After parring the first four holes, Singh scored one of his two
final-round birdies. On the par-3 fifth hole, he hit a 6-iron
within 5 feet and coaxed in the putt. He parred the next five
holes.
</P>
<P>
   Stricker fell behind for good with his bogey at the 480-yard
sixth hole, hitting his tee shot into the trees. He dropped another
stroke at the ninth, splashing his tee shot into the lake for a
bogey 4.
</P>
<P>
   Singh and Stricker matched birdies at the par-5 11th hole, with
the leader hitting the top of a tree with his second shot but
somehow putting the ball on the green. Basking in his good fortune,
Singh leaned on his club for several seconds and beamed.
</P>
<P>
   He made his only serious mistake on the par-4 12th, bogeying
after he landed his tee shot in a fairway bunker and his second
shot in greenside rough.
</P>
<P>
   On the par-4 14th hole, Singh pulled one deep into the woods.
But he handled the predicament like a champion, hooking one through
the trees and the people, and stopping it on the front of the
green.
</P>
<P>
   Singh matched birdies with Stricker on the par-4 15th, both
dropping medium-range putts.
</P>
<P>
   Heading into the final three holes, Singh had absorbed
Stricker's best shot and still held a one-stroke lead.
</P>
<P>
   On the par-3 17th, both golfers hit tee shots into the trap left
of the green, and each left his bunker shot well short. Singh,
however, dropped the longer of the two putts from about 15 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Stricker slid his putt past the cup, making bogey and giving
Singh a two-stroke lead going to the final hole.
</P>
<P>
   The Wanamaker Cup now had a Fiji address on it.
</P>
<P>
   Walking off the 18th green after making par, Singh was greeted
with hugs from his wife, Ardena, his son, Qass, and Australian
golfer Steve Elkington, winner of the 1995 PGA Championship and the
third-place finisher Sunday. Singh had three-putted once in four
days. He had come a long way. And he still wasn't sure where he had
landed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing all those places,'' he said, ``I never thought I'd be
doing this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
