<HEADLINE>
PGA PLAYERS ENJOY SAHALEE BUT MISS THE PAR-FIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SCOTT SUNDE AND ELLIS E. CONKLIN  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ Players left Sahalee Country Club with good
things to say, yet they also departed Sunday wondering how the PGA
Championship course might have played in its normal setup _ as a
par-72.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really a nice golf course, but I personally wish they
would leave the par 5's as 5's,'' said Joey Sindelar, who finished
at 7-over-par. ``The 18th would have been a cool par-5.''
</P>
<P>
   Compared to his U.S. Open experience in San Francisco last June
_ where he finished tied for 43rd _ Sindelar was ecstatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``This course was fun,'' he said. ``The Olympic Club was a
headache, from the time you teed off until the time you were done.
This was the way I would have set up a golf course, where it's
slightly easier when the ball goes in the rough and slightly easier
when it goes in the fairway.''
</P>
<P>
   Phil Mickelson's only complaint with his week in the Pacific
Northwest was the lack of par-5s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a fan of what the PGA and USGA does with par-5s, but
other than that, I think they did an excellent job of setting up
this golf course,'' the lefty said. ``Yes, I would return. Even
though this city doesn't have a regular golf event, we all felt
welcome here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
