<SLUG> BC-PGA-WINNER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PGA CONTENDERS, PREDENDERS FALL BY WAYSIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM MOORE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ Big names, small names, no-names _ they all
wanted to break up the match-play battle between Vijay Singh and
Steve Stricker and turn it into a rollicking party.
</P>
<P>
   Persistently, they fired, shooting for the leaders and the pins.
The golf course was supposedly exposed, softened by the rain,
vulnerable to the greatness-seekers.
</P>
<P>
   The brash youngster, Tiger Woods, figured to challenge. He began
Sunday's final round five shots behind. Given the conditions and
his capabilities, a 62 or 63 seemed possible. It could have
produced a dramatic finish, a playoff with Singh, heroic headlines,
added footage to the legacy.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Tiger ``In The'' Woods was basically beauty bark in the
PGA Championship, enhancing Sahalee's landscape by his presence
only. As far as his game at tight layouts, it needs work.
</P>
<P>
   Woods tied for 10th with Skip Kendall and Kenny Perry at
1-under-par after shooting a final-round 71. Consecutive bogeys at
six and seven followed by another at nine yanked Woods from
Sunday's storyline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't play very well,'' said Woods, who finished with three
top-10s in the major championships this year. ``I didn't hit the
ball solid and I couldn't control my shots the way I needed to to
give myself a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   After leading the tournament with a 66 on Thursday, Woods never
broke par again. Blame it on wayward drives, not mental mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite frankly, it's a mini-miracle to shoot what I shot the
last two rounds,'' he said. ``(On Saturday), I only hit seven
fairways and today was about the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thursday was the only day I hit the ball well. I never made a
bad mental decision in the tournament. I made some physical errors,
but I can say I played 18 holes, four days in a row, without one
mental error. That's amazing considering where I have come from.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the rest of the contenders, Steve Elkington was the one
who appeared on the doorstep with the loudest knock.
</P>
<P>
   The former PGA champion shot a 67 and moved within two strokes
of Singh after a birdie at 17.
</P>
<P>
   The fluid swinger from Australia hoped to birdie 18 and apply
continued pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would have forced Vijay to make par to win,'' said
Elkington, who instead bogeyed after missing a 3-footer for par.
</P>
<P>
   Elkington gambled by using his driver, attempting to get
increased distance to make for a shorter approach. That backfired
when his tee shot found the rough.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Elkington was rejected. He won his first and only
major in 1995 at Riviera, sinking a birdie putt at 18 to force a
playoff with Colin Montgomerie.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Price is the only man to interrupt the PGA's current string
of first-time winners. He won in '92 and '94 and had a chance
Sunday to add '98 to the list.
</P>
<P>
   After an eagle at the par-5 11th, Price moved to 4-under for the
tournament and 5-under for the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had visions of having a good shot at it, even winning it,''
Price said.
</P>
<P>
   But he parred in, missing opportunities at the 16th and 17th
holes, the latter with his ball hanging on the lip, defying
gravity, denying Price.
</P>
<P>
   Others tried for starring roles only to end up like a potted
plant on the set, there for effect.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Lickliter got it to 5-under before finishing in a tie for
fourth with Price and Mark O'Meara.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Mayfair, last week's Buick Open champ, used his unorthodox
putting stroke to move to 5-under after a birdie at No. 11. He
ended up at 3-under in a tie for seventh with defending champ Davis
Love III.
</P>
<P>
   Even a bogey at 18 could not spoil the afternoon or the memories
for Mayfair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sahalee was great,'' he said. ``The fans coming up the last
few holes were thanking us for coming here. We have never heard
that before.''
</P>
</TEXT>
