<SLUG> BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: THE CIRCLE COMES ROUND AT COLUMBUS CIRCLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STEVEN R. WEISMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When it comes to civic amenities, New York City has
long known how to squander an opportunity. Take Columbus Circle,
the repellent open space at the southwest corner of Central Park.
In the 1950s, Robert Moses secured federal slum clearance funds to
raze the rundown theaters, shops and apartments to the west of the
circle, only to put up the windowless New York Coliseum, of which
Frank Lloyd Wright once observed, ``It's a great utilitarian
achievement, but architecture is something else again.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Huntington Hartford enlisted the architect Edward Durell
Stone to create yet another windowless building to the south of
Columbus Circle for a museum devoted to representational art. With
its pseudoclassical design, the building was supposed to serve as a
rebuke to modernism. But its white marble facade, perforated
corners and spindly columns inspired Ada Louise Huxtable, The
Times' architecture critic, to dismiss it as a ``die-cut Venetian
palazzo on lollypops.'' Others compared it to a giant shower stall.
The museum closed in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Today Columbus Circle remains a bleak place of traffic jams,
soulless architecture and unrealized potential. But now that Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani and the Metropolitan Transportation Authority have
ended 15 years of squabbling and chosen a promising developer for
the Coliseum site, there is a chance to transform the circle into
the splendid gateway it was meant to be.
</P>
<P>
   The new building at the Coliseum site will help tremendously.
The developers, Time Warner and the Related Cos., have commissioned
an immense complex that will include a hotel, stores and
apartments, as well as a 1,000-seat performance hall for a new home
for Jazz at Lincoln Center. The scheme by David Childs has twin
towers designed to echo the great apartment buildings on Central
Park West. Its curved facade and a circular rotunda at the entrance
work together to evoke the circle on which it sits.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, the Giuliani administration reconfigured the traffic
at Columbus Circle to make it into a true roundabout. But the mayor
will not say what he would prefer to do with the old Huntington
Hartford building, now owned by the city, though it is obvious he
would be happy for it to be torn down. Many an architecture buff
has recoiled at its sight.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the building has also become a kind of beloved eyesore, an
icon of its time. For all its classical pretensions, it reflects an
attempt by a serious architect of another era to evoke tradition
and modernity as they were then viewed. The architect Robert Stern
has led an unsuccessful campaign to get it designated as a
landmark, which would keep it preserved in the face of what he
calls the ``ever-present tendency to dismiss, or even revile, the
recent past.'' Other architects have begun standing up for a
building they admit privately they were trained to dislike, in part
because of its original reactionary purpose.
</P>
<P>
   When Giuliani announced the new Time Warner complex last month,
I felt eager myself to see that dowdy marble shower stall torn
down. Now I am not so sure. The essence of urbanism, articulated by
the architectural historian Vincent Scully, is a kind of dialogue
across time by buildings that respect each other. When I studied
under Scully at Yale, he reviled that building. Recently, he told
me he sympathized with the views of his former student, Stern.
``It's strikingly awful, a pungent anachronism, a folly,'' Scully
said. ``But if we acted only on current preferences, we would be
tearing everything down.''
</P>
<P>
   With so many new visitors to Columbus Circle, the Stone
structure may yet find new life as a museum for art or music. But
no dialogue across time will be possible unless it is better
facilitated by the circle itself.
</P>
<P>
   That is why the urgent priority of the mayor should be to
generate discussion on transforming the whole area. The Municipal
Art Society sponsored a competition in which several architects
proposed building fanciful hemispheres or circles of light
overhead. More realistic, perhaps, would be an elaborate new
circular pattern of trees, paving stones, benches and fountains
restoring life to the circle.
</P>
<P>
   Any surface improvements could be enhanced by a rethinking of
transportation patterns below ground. The Columbus Circle subway
station is a subterranean nightmare, in which riders scuttle
through dark decrepit tunnels to make connections or get to the
surface. Childs, the architect of the Time Warner complex, suggests
a set of raised skylights bringing light and clarity to the
underworld. The American Institute of Architects has called for a
thorough rehabilitation of the subway to reflect its coming
importance as a hub.
</P>
<P>
   With Times Square, Grand Central Terminal and possibly the old
Post Office at 34th Street transforming themselves before our eyes,
there is ample evidence that New York City can reinvent itself. Ten
years from now, Columbus Circle, like Rockefeller Center and
Lincoln Center before it, could become a place that seems like it
was always meant to be instead of a squandered opportunity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-98 0104EDT &QL; 
