<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DREIFORT SETS TONE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Darren Dreifort knew the score Sunday even if
there wasn't one in the top of the second inning.
</P>
<P>
   At the plate was Andres Galarraga, who had beaten the Los
Angeles Dodgers with home runs the past two days, shaken further
their confidence and sent a message that somebody's season was just
about over.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort hit him in the left side with a fastball. And when
Galarraga took a couple of steps toward the mound, Dreifort came
down to get in his face.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing happened. Or did it?
</P>
<P>
   Although Dreifort wasn't around when Eric Young homered in the
eighth inning to give the Dodgers a 1-0 victory over the Atlanta
Braves at Dodger Stadium, that showdown with Galarraga might have
been the Kodak moment of this season.
</P>
<P>
   Does it mean the Dodgers' dreary season finally has turned
around with a victory over the best team in the National League?
Baseball rarely paints with such broad strokes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't really matter if the pitch was intentional or
not,'' said closer Jeff Shaw, who pitched the ninth for his 36th
save. ``Galarraga had been diving out over the plate all series
driving balls to right center and killing us. After Darren went
inside he never swung like that again.''
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort wouldn't say if he meant what he threw. Galarraga was
in the trainers room after the game and did not comment.
</P>
<P>
   But as the Dodgers head out on the road after a disappointing
4-5 homestand, they hopefully take a little of Dreifort's grit with
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Momentum is too strong a word, especially when you played the
way we have,'' shortstop Mark Grudzielanek said. ``But this thing
is almost over. We need to have a great trip, one week where we
play like we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort pitched seven innings and allowed just one hit, a
second-inning single by Javy Lopez. He also walked six and always
seemed to be pitching out of the stretch. Scott Radinsky (5-5)
pitched the eighth to get the victory, which moved the Dodgers
within six games in the wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Darren's effort was such a boost for us,'' said manager Glenn
Hoffman, whose team has not been swept at home all season. ``It
would have been very difficult to leave here on a down note.''
</P>
<P>
   There were plenty in the past week, including a .197 (13 for 66)
average with runners in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   One bright spot was Young, who had 14 hits on the homestand. But
he was 0 for 3 Sunday before hitting a 1-1 fastball from Denny
Neagle (11-11) into the left-field stands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did I think it was gone? I never think it's gone,'' said
Young, who has 37 homers in his six-year career but two in the last
two games. ``I was running like it was triple.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Dodgers scored just five runs in the first two games
of the series, it was clear they weren't going to break out against
Neagle, who is having a tough season after winning 20 games in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Tom) Glavine was the hard-luck guy last year,'' Neagle said.
``He had 12 no decisions with a 2.50 ERA in those games. I was
getting seven, eight runs a game every time I pitched. Now, it's my
turn.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers got the leadoff hitter on in the third, fourth and
fifth innings, but Neagle wiggled out of trouble each time.
</P>
<P>
   Their best chance came in the fourth, when Trenidad Hubbard
opened with a double to right-center. But Raul Mondesi's impatience
at the plate was glaring when he struck out on pitches out of the
strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Sheffield, back in the starting lineup after missing two
games with a sore right thumb, flied deep to center, but Andruw
Jones glided to the wall and made the catch look easy. Eric Karros
grounded to third to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort was through after seven but had a chance to win in the
bottom of the inning when Grudzielanek singled with one out. With
Charles Johnson at the plate, Grudzielanek took off for second but
stopped halfway.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez threw to second, but Grudzielanek raced back to first and
beat the return throw. It was the kind of break the Dodgers hadn't
seen all series. But Roger Cedeno batted for Dreifort and grounded
into an inning-ending double play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a hit-and-run play and I like that,'' Grudzielanek
said. ``That's what we need to do, set a tone, put pressure on the
other team. It didn't mean a run tonight, but it will.''
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort struggled in his previous four starts, allowing 16
earned runs in 24 innings over four starts. Before that, he limited
the Cincinnati Reds to one hit in eight innings July 20, his only
victory in six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I threw a lot of pitches,'' said Dreifort, who had 118. ``But
I felt good out there. I got some great defense. This was a good
win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
