<SLUG> BC-BBN-LOPEZCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Happy homestand warms the heart
<TEXT>
<P>
   BY JOHN P. LOPEZ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   Three things we realized on an entertaining, star-studded, nip
and not to mention tuck afternoon of baseball at the Astrodome:
</P>
<P>
   Kerry Wood's arm is not dead. Neither, technically, are the
Chicago Cubs. And there are at least 128 people in this town who
prefer Beanie Babies over watching Randy Johnson pitch.
</P>
<P>
   You know who you are.
</P>
<P>
   When Johnson wowed us to begin the 10-game homestand Aug. 7, a
record 52,071 fans saw the start of what had to be considered a
critical stretch for the Astros, in the standings and at the gate.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, 128 more people came to the Dome, boosting the
regular-season attendance record to 52,199 and hoping their kids
would be among the first 20,000 to click the turnstiles, thereby
scooping up Derby the Horse.
</P>
<P>
   Beanie Baby craziness was a part of this day _ from the
overnight camping at the gate after Saturday night's win, to the
long line of fans circling the stadium before the doors opened, to
the vendors who barked out, ``Get your ice cold Beanie beer!''
</P>
<P>
   This highly successful ploy _ some 20 big-league teams have
cashed in on the Beanie giveaways _ was designed for kids
14-and-under. But from the looks of the Astrodome parking lot
Sunday, it just as well could have been for moms 30-and-over who
drive minivans, have school-age children, and couldn't tell you
what it means to protect the plate but sure know about telling
their kids to protect the Ty tags.
</P>
<P>
   Beanies take back seat
</P>
<P>
   Even the Astros caught the craze, some of them talking in the
clubhouse before the game about which Beanies their kids did and
didn't have, then carefully stowing Derby the Horse in their
lockers.
</P>
<P>
   But beyond the craze was the game. And yet again, there was
reason to believe ticketing gimmicks should be saved for weekday
games.
</P>
<P>
   This also, after all, was a day for big-time baseball stars, a
division race and a tense, emotional game between contenders.
</P>
<P>
   There was Kerry the Ace, Sammy the Slugger, Moises the Stud and
Biggio the Ballplayer. They put on a quality show that might have
ended with the Astros finishing the homestand on a down note but
not exactly singing the blues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too bad it had to end that way,'' Astros manager Larry Dierker
said after the 11-inning 2-1 loss that came only after pinch hitter
Manny Alexander skipped a two-out grounder between Biggio and Jeff
Bagwell. A little to the left or a little to the right, and the
Astros would have been out of that jam and perhaps ultimately back
in the winner's circle.
</P>
<P>
   The seeing-eye grounder was a bad break for the Astros for sure,
but Dierker had no reason to cry in his beer, or even over his
Derby the Horse.
</P>
<P>
   In taking eight of 10 games in the homestand, the Astros managed
to turn what was a 4{-game edge over the Cubs in the National
League Central into an eight-game lead as they head off on a road
stretch at Philly, Milwaukee and Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros remain in control of the division, and unless things
fall apart over the next 10 days, they should take the title with
relative ease.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking at (the homestand) ahead of time, it figured to be
important, and it was,'' Dierker said. ``We hoped for more, but we
can't argue with extending the lead.''
</P>
<P>
   Astros hang in there
</P>
<P>
   If anything, Sunday's game only should have given the Astros
confidence about how the remainder of the season will go. Starter
Sean Bergman (eight innings, nine strikeouts) was superb. The
bullpen arms _ Mike Magnante, Doug Henry, Jay Powell and Trever
Miller _ did their jobs, save for Alexander's well-placed grounder
off Miller that won the game.
</P>
<P>
   And despite facing Wood, the kid who sat them down a
record-tying 20 times the last time he faced them and had 11 K's on
Sunday, the Astros scratched out a game-tying run in the fifth
inning. Eventually, the Astros made it to the Cubs' bullpen and _
what else on Beanie Baby day _ were Ty-ed after nine innings.
</P>
<P>
   Before Sunday, Wood was said to have been inflicted with
baseball's ``tired arm'' syndrome, which often gets to 21-year-olds
thrown into big-league schedules. But if he was, he's feeling much
better now.
</P>
<P>
   Wood regularly hit 98 mph on the radar gun and held Derek Bell,
Bagwell and Moises Alou without a hit. Still, there was a chance
for victory for the Astros, and how many times does that happen on
days when the Cubs have Wood on the hill and in the same game
slugger Sammy Sosa adds to his remarkable home-run count? (No. 47
came in the fourth.)
</P>
<P>
   ``When you go 8-2 (on the homestand), you take it,'' Biggio
said. ``You have to be happy with 8-2.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless you weren't among the 20,000 who got a Beanie Baby.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-98 0109EDT &QL; 
