<HEADER>
A6611 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-PGA-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-17 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Latest champ pays dues with hard work
<TEXT>
<P>
   By DALE ROBERTSON &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ In recent years, for reasons that defy a simple
explanation, the PGA Championship has evolved into the
proletariat's major. It's the one Slam where the everyman can
dance, too, and the 80th edition provided perhaps the best example
yet of how level its fairways have become.
</P>
<P>
   Since Jeff Sluman won in 1988, the Wanamaker Trophy has been the
Holy Grail for the PGA Tour wannabes. Let the established masters
win the Masters. At the PGA, the less accomplished or heralded you
are, it seems, the greater your chances of leaving with a smile and
first-place jingle in your pocket.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with Vijay Singh having become the latest member of the
Wanamaker club, 10 of the past 11 PGA winners are first-time guests
in the majors' winner's circles. The lone exception has been Nick
Price, who announced himself at the 1992 PGA but broke with fashion
by prevailing again in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vijay'' means victory in Hindi. But Vijay Singh was hardly
unto the golfing manor born. If ever there has been a self-made
champion, a byproduct of ridiculously long hours spent smacking
balls on the driving range or tapping them into cups on a putting
green, it's Singh. Golf isn't merely a livelihood. It's his
passion, his compulsion.
</P>
<P>
   His all-consuming obsession.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've practiced so hard for this,'' Singh said Sunday, and he
wasn't exaggerating.
</P>
<P>
   At dusk Thursday night, after the first round of the PGA at
Sahalee Country Club, I shared a hotel elevator with Singh, his
wife, his son and his golf bag. Only the latter, by all accounts,
is always at his side. Singh had, of course, just returned from his
second home on the range after scoring an even-par 70, four strokes
off Tiger Woods' then tournament-leading, course-record pace.
</P>
<P>
   Vijay was going to order room service, probably poke a few more
putts across the carpet, then turn in for the evening and dream
about his next round of golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go to sleep thinking about golf,'' he once told a reporter.
``I wake up thinking about it. I have a family, but my mind is
consumed by golf. I like to practice _ and there is always
something to practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, it made perfect. Singh took the PGA by two shots over
Steve Stricker, who, come to think of it, would have made a perfect
PGA title-holder in his own right, considering his conspicuous lack
of credentials.
</P>
<P>
   Vijay committed myriad mistakes across the back nine, plunking
shots off the tree limbs, planting them in the rough and burying
them in bunkers. But he recovered magnificently on every occasion
save for his bogey on No. 12. His steady hand _ well, crossed hands
_ on the greens proved particularly rewarding.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best putting tournament I ever had,'' he proclaimed it
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Although Stricker passed him briefly with a birdie on the fourth
hole, once Singh regained the lead on No. 6 there was no stopping,
or catching, him. Sunday was Vijay Day. He ended it singin' in the
rain.
</P>
<P>
   But missing from the suddenly turbulent skies over this heavily
forested plateau east of Seattle was any trace of a rainbow. There
was nothing magical about Singh's triumph, as there had been when
Davis Love III got the monkey off his back a year ago at Winged
Foot. Love, the son of a beloved PGA teaching pro who had died in a
plane crash, was reared to win a major. He just hadn't done it yet.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Love might be the most popular player on the tour. Singh
is something of a loner with just a few close friends among his
peers. If you want to know Vijay, you better bring your clubs. He
doesn't waste time chit-chatting when there are buckets of balls to
hit.
</P>
<P>
   Much of his past is shrouded in mystery and, according to him,
gross misunderstanding. In 1985, he was charged with doctoring a
scorecard at the Indonesian Open in order to make the cut. He says
it was the official scorer who messed up, but he was banned from
the Asian Tour because of the incident and wound up take a teaching
pro's job in Borneo _ for $160 a month.
</P>
<P>
   He returned to competition a couple of years later on the
African Safari Tour. He played in a dozen countries before he
earned a PGA Tour exemption in 1993, after which he moved to
Florida and pretty much turned his back on his native Fiji.
</P>
<P>
   Why? It's complicated stuff, relating in part to the poor
treatment of Indian immigrants by ethnic Fijians on the South
Pacific island, and he's disinclined to explain his feelings
through the media, which he distrusts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's gotten a lot of bad press,'' says his caddie, Scotsman
David Renwick. ``If I were him, I wouldn't want to talk to you
guys, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Renwick's role probably can't be overstated. He carried Steve
Elkington's clubs at Riviera in the 1995 PGA _ yes, Elk won _ and
was in the employ of Jose Maria Olazabal for his Masters victory in
1994. He gave Singh an edge he couldn't have had on his own, save
for the obvious one.
</P>
<P>
   Vijay was made for the PGA, wasn't he? As a good golfer who
never had won a major, he was the right man in the right place at
the right time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-98 0111EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
