<HEADLINE>
`PRIVATE RYAN' HOLDS OFF RIVALS TO BOX OFFICE POSITION
</HEADLINE>
 
(fixing byline   and name Fiennes) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Also moving in the ``a'' national news file.)  
 
  
By DAVE MCNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Steven Spielberg's ``Saving Private Ryan''
remained victorious for the fourth straight weekend at the box
office with an estimated $12.9 &UR;  &LR; million at 2,654 theaters
nationwide during the Friday-Sunday period, studio sources said
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The performance gave DreamWorks' D-Day epic an impressive
$125.8 &UR;  &LR; million in its first 24 days as the weekend-to-weekend
decline registered a mere 24 &UR;  &LR; percent, indicating that ``Saving
Private Ryan'' has an excellent shot at becoming the 24th movie to
top the $200 &UR;  &LR; million mark in U.S. grosses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we'll continue to see the movie play well into the
fall,'' said distribution chief James Tharp. ``It won't be as
affected as other films by the start of school.''
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Arthur Rockwell of Drake &AMP; Co. agreed, noting that
``Saving Private Ryan'' will receive an additional boost near the
end of the year as Hollywood's awards season heats up. ``I think
$200 &UR;  &LR; million is in the bag already,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Finishing a solid second was 20th Century Fox's opening of ``How
Stella Got Her Groove Back'' with $11.8 &UR;  &LR; million at 1,339 theaters.
The romance, with Angela Bassett involved with a man half her age,
overcame mixed reviews with a strong marketing effort, Rockwell
said.
</P>
<P>
   Box office tracker Robert Bucksbaum, president of Reel Source,
said ``Stella'' will continue to draw well for several weeks but
noted its results could be held down by two openings starring
African-Americans next weekend _ New Line's ``Blade'' with Wesley
Snipes as a vampire fighter and Sony's ``Dance With Me'' with
Vanessa Williams as a salsa dancer. ``It's strange that these have
been bunched together,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Warner Bros.' debut of ``The Avengers'' came in third with
$10.5 &UR;  &LR; million at 2,466 theaters after the studio took the rare
step of not screening the action-fantasy for critics prior to the
opening. Reviews this weekend were brutal and the returns for the
$60 &UR;  &LR; million project, starring Sean Connery, Uma Thurman and Ralph
Fiennes, were disappointing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reviews don't matter much on a movie like this, but it's a
tough sell since the TV series was only on for a few years,'' said
Bucksbaum, who had been expecting a $15 &UR;  &LR; million opening.
</P>
<P>
   20th Century Fox's fifth weekend of ``There's Something About
Mary'' was an impressive fourth with $8.8 &UR;  &LR; million at 2,201 sites
to go past $91 &UR;  &LR; million. It lost only 8 &UR;  &LR; percent from the previous
weekend and will soon become the 175th film to top the
$100 &UR;  &LR; million mark in U.S. grosses, although it will be one of the
few to do so without ever leading the weekend box office.
</P>
<P>
   `` &UR;  &LR; `There's Something About Mary' is a low comedy that's really
worked well,'' Rockwell said.
</P>
<P>
   The eight 1998 titles to hit the $100 &UR;  &LR; million milestone are
``Deep Impact,'' ``Godzilla,'' ``The Truman Show,'' ``Mulan,''
``Dr. Dolittle,'' ``Armageddon,'' ``Lethal Weapon 4'' and ``Saving
Private Ryan.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mary'' edged a pair of entries in their second weekends _
Paramount's ``Snake Eyes'' with $8.7 &UR;  &LR; million at 2,718 sites and
Miramax's ``Halloween: H20'' with $8.4 &UR;  &LR; million at 2,669 sites. The
latter, with a slight $17 &UR;  &LR; million budget, is churning out profits
for parent Walt Disney Co. with $39.8 &UR;  &LR; million in its first 12
days.
</P>
<P>
   The slasher sequel was followed by a pair of family comedies
with solid returns in their third weekends _ Fox's ``Ever After''
with $5.8 &UR;  &LR; million at 2,058 locations and Disney's ``The Parent
Trap'' with $5.5 &UR;  &LR; million at 2,407 sites.
</P>
<P>
   Rounding out the top 10 were Disney's seventh weekend of
``Armageddon'' with $4 &UR;  &LR; million at 1,786 theaters and Warner Bros.'
second weekend of ``The Negotiator'' with $3.98 &UR;  &LR; million at 2,032
screens.
</P>
<P>
   Sony's fifth weekend of ``The Mask of Zorro'' came in 11th with
$3.88 &UR;  &LR; million at 2,123 sites, followed by Warner's sixth weekend
of ``Lethal Weapon 4'' with $3.2 &UR;  &LR; million at 1928 theaters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Armageddon'' has reached $179.9 &UR;  &LR; million in 47 days and ranks
34th on the all-time domestic list behind ``Mission: Impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   Two other new entries posted unimpressive results _ Miramax's
comedy sequel ``Air Bud: Golden Receiver'' fetched $2.7 &UR;  &LR; million at
1,669 theaters and PolyGram's Malaysian drama ``Return to
Paradise'' with $2.4 &UR;  &LR; million at 969 screens as the latter failed
to capitalize on generally positive reviews. Bucksbaum said
PolyGram may have been distracted by the pending sale of its film
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Fox Searchlight's limited opening of offbeat comedy ``The Slums
of Beverly Hills'' generated strong returns with $135,000 at seven
screens.
</P>
<P>
   Year-to-date business has reached $4.2 &UR;  &LR; billion and is
8 &UR;  &LR; percent ahead of the same period last year. Summer business,
starting with the Memorial Day weekend, is at about $2 &UR;  &LR; billion, or
about 11 &UR;  &LR; percent up from the same period last year. The 1997
summer set a record of $2.22 &UR;  &LR; billion when it closed out on Labor
Day, while this summer will finish around $2.5 &UR;  &LR; billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall business is pretty good right now, considering that
it's the soft end of summer with the last hurrah for vacations,''
Rockwell said.
</P>
<P>
   Paramount's ``Titanic'' drew $715,000 at 594 theaters in its
35th weekend to push its overall domestic total to $598.9 &UR;  &LR; million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saving Private Ryan'' will face competition next weekend from
``Dance With Me,'' ``Blade'' and two new comedies _ Warner's
``Wrongfully Accused'' with Leslie Nielsen in a spoof of ``The
Fugitive'' and Paramount's ``Dead Man on Campus.''
</P>
</TEXT>
