<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIJAY DAY: A MAJOR VICTORY FOR SINGH 
</HEADLINE>
 CHAMPIONSHIP-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ As a light mist fell over the Sahalee CC in
Sunday's final round of the 80th PGA Championship amid the towering
pine trees, Vijay Singh of the Fiji Islands realized his finest
moment of a long and dedicated career when he resolutely carved out
a 68 for a 9-under 271 to win his first major title out here in the
suburbs of Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   This was a triumph for hard work, because nobody has spent more
time on a practice tee or rearranging furniture in a motel room to
practice putting than Singh. He has been seen on practice tees as
darkness settled in, a solitary presence. He has won five times on
the US PGA Tour, but victories also have came in South Africa,
Germany, Nigeria, Sweden, Zimbabwe, Morocco, and Malaysia. Now he
has joined the list of golf's major champions.
</P>
<P>
   Executing a marvelous shot out of the woods on the 14th hole
that drew its way onto the green to save par, Singh took it from
there to beat Steve Stricker (70_273) by two shots in the first PGA
Championship in this region since Ben Hogan won in 1946 at Portland
GC in Oregon. Steve Elkington, who has struggled because of sinus
problems and injuries, made a bold bid to stay in the hunt but a
bogey 5 on the final hole brought him in third on 67_274 totals.
</P>
<P>
   There was an early burst by Mark O'Meara to write history when
he started off par, eagle, par, par, birdie. He'd won the Masters
and the British Open to become the oldest (41) to win two majors in
the same year, and just Hogan in 1953 had won three. Reality set in
when he bogeyed the sixth, seventh, and eighth holes. O'Meara's
eagle putt was 50 feet, and a closing birdie putt on the 17th was
the same distance. ``It's a little disappointing,'' he said, ``but
that's the way it goes.''
</P>
<P>
   Singh, who was taught the game by his airplane technician father
and took his first job as a professional in Borneo, rarely faltered
as he marched to his first major, with wife Ardena and 8-year-old
son Qass in the gallery. He and Stricker, whose wife and former
caddie Nicki is expecting their first child at home in Edgerton,
Wis., engaged in an enthralling duel that was entered by Elkington
before he finished with the bogey on 18.
</P>
<P>
   Singh staked his ground with a birdie on the par-3 fifth when he
hit a 6-iron to 4 feet to pull even with Stricker. Singh took the
lead on the sixth when Stricker missed an 8-foot par-saving putt.
The lead became two when Stricker pulled a 4-iron on the par-3
ninth and bogeyed. After they each birdied the 11th, Singh bogeyed
out of the left trap on the 12th to let Stricker back in.
</P>
<P>
   Then it became match play, with Singh's marvelous save on the
14th preserving his 1-up advantage. After they both birdied the
15th and penciled in pars on the 16th, Stricker did himself in when
he couldn't get up and down out of a sand trap on the 17th, where
he'd taken a double bogey Friday. ``I had an opportunity to put a
little bit of pressure on 17, because I had the tee there first,''
he said. ``I didn't hit a very good shot, and that was the turning
point when he made the up-and-down and I missed my par.''
</P>
<P>
   Singh played the treacherous 18th with a two-putt par, and he
finally broke into a smile as he approached the green. ``This is a
dream come true,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a little bit of a struggle at times,'' said Stricker.
``I thought I hung in there pretty well and I gave myself a chance
down to the end. That's really what I set out to do. Just to have a
chance. I fought hard. I didn't give up.''
</P>
<P>
   It was simply a case of Singh finally realizing all the promise
of a career that has spanned the globe, evoking memories of seeing
him on a practice tee when everybody else had left the course
except the media. He started to putt cross-handed at the Western
Open, and he estimated he's tried between six and eight putters
this year. ``I think I'll stay with the one I have now,'' he said.
The putter was his magic wand with the PGA Championship on the
line.
</P>
<P>
   The shot of the tournament was the one out of the trees that
Singh hit on the 14th. ``I got away with one on 11 when I pushed my
second shot to the right,'' said Singh. ``Then I hit a bad shot on
12 and another on 13. When I hit that tee shot on 14, my caddie
(David Renwick) said, `Hey come on. You can do better than this.
You're going to lose if you keep doing what you're doing.' So it
wasn't a difficult shot out of the trees. I just had to hook it
about 50 yards.''
</P>
<P>
   Elkington was knocking on the door, but the finishing bogey
ended his chances. ``I think if I had made birdie at 18 that would
have forced Vijay to make par to win,'' said Elkington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I needed to hit a good drive. It's just a very hard tee shot
for me, because I fade the ball.'' He yanked a short putt to the
left for bogey. ``I wouldn't say I'm satisfied,'' said Elkington,
``but I think I'm over the hump.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-98 0136EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
