<DOCNO> NYT19980817.0035 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-17 01:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6632 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-BOSTONCUP-BOS &LR;      08-17 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-BOSTON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DE SWARDT CAPTURES CUP 
</HEADLINE>
 CUP-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WELLESLEY, Mass. _ For much of the week, the concession stands
and sponsor tents seemed to outnumber the fans at the Corel Boston
Cup. But interest never should be equated with interesting, because
Mariaan de Swardt and Barbara Schett for the rest of their lives
will recall with fascination _ or dread _ what happened Sunday at
Babson College.
</P>
<P>
   For de Swardt, it will be a dream because she was down, 1-5, in
the third set, with her opponent serving, and somehow won. For
Schett it will be a nightmare _ although she denied as much _
because she gave away her first WTA title as that 5-1 lead melted
with her game and her psyche.
</P>
<P>
   ``At 5-1, I thought I was going to be in the showers soon,''
said de Swardt, the South African who suddenly was reborn, revived,
and resurgent as her opponent went soft. ``But when I was down,
5-1, I said, `I'm going to make her earn it.'''
</P>
<P>
   And when Schett's collapse was done, losing the match and the
title, 3-6, 7-6 (7-4), 7-5, the Austrian had one more unfortunate
site and score to add to her litany of collapses. ``I was once up,
5-1, in Boston with my serve in the third set ...'' she now can add
to her blowing third-set leads to Jana Novotna and Arantxa Sanchez
Vicario in Berlin, and how she once had six match points against
Monica Seles in Madrid. Losing all.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are leading, 5-1, with your serve in the third set of
the final in a tournament, yes, you are mad at yourself,'' said
Schett, a 22-year-old from Innsbruck. ``You are losing the match
that way and it is truly disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   Comebacks from 5-1 in the third set of a title match are as rare
as a one-handed backhand on the women's tour, but given the
circumstances of what happened just before Schett took that 5-1
lead, such a comeback _ or collapse _ seemed well nigh impossible.
</P>
<P>
   In the second game of the final set, Schett broke de Swardt's
serve when de Swardt double-faulted at 30-40, a line judge calling
the serve long. The South African was irate, hollered out to the
chair, threw her racket, and then fumed for the next several games
as Schett's lead grew to 5-1. De Swardt not only seemed physically
wiped out from the 90-degree heat, but emotionally spent. Schett
seemed in full control.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was most upset,'' said de Swardt. ``It was a really big
point and I felt it could have been in. It could have touched the
line. I was really upset and it took me a game or two to get over
it. I was really fuming.''
</P>
<P>
   But Schett squandered her opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of attacking at 5-1, Schett ``became more tentative and
tried going for shots she hadn't been trying,'' said de Swardt. She
never had played against Schett _ ``I'd never even seen her play''
_ but had heard that Schett had trouble finishing off foes in the
third set. So it was de Swardt who became the aggressor.
</P>
<P>
   When she began her serve at 5-1, Schett recalled, ``I felt I was
concentrated still and I felt I was going to win this. No, I
wouldn't say it was nerves. No, I wouldn't say it was
overconfidence. I wasn't aggressive enough; that was the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   At 5-1, Schett went on, ``I was thinking, `I am going to serve
next and I am going to win this game.' That's because one game
before I had won my serve pretty easily. `It's going to be my
title,' that's what I thought. I was pretty confident.''
</P>
<P>
   But Schett had no killer instinct, even though her coach, Tom
Prerovsky, kept hollering out to her in German to be more
aggressive. Instead, Schett was the opposite, visibly wilting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't aggressive enough with my serve ... I was just
putting the ball into the court and she was aggressive,'' said
Schett. ``And that was the mistake. I would say she was more
aggressive then because she had nothing to lose then and playing
very powerful, especially her serve.''
</P>
<P>
   Schett gave away her serve, then could not break de Swardt and
next gave away another serve game to bring the score to 5-4. ``At
5-2, I still was confident,'' said Schett, ``and then she was
starting to serve better again and I had no chances when she was
serving. That's why she was able to put pressure on me again.''
</P>
<P>
   Schett's last chance came on de Swardt's serve at 5-4 when she
had a match point and de Swardt was down to her second serve. But a
hint of how much an emotional roller-coaster this match was for
both women came later when de Swardt could not remember that Schett
ever had a match point. ``I don't remember a match point for her,''
said de Swardt.
</P>
<P>
   Schett remembered the game well, ``because it was 5-4, 40-love
for her on her serve and I came back to have match point,'' she
said. ``But the match point I could not do anything ... she hit a
forehand winner and I had no chance.''
</P>
<P>
   At 5-5, Schett was down to a shell of herself and de Swardt
broke serve and won the game with a cross-court forehand winner.
Serving at 6-5, de Swardt blasted three aces and the agony _
mercifully _ was over for Schett and the ecstasy began for de
Swardt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was not thinking of past times,'' Schett said, when asked if
her past failures in similar situations were on her mind during
Sunday's slide. And she said she would not torture herself by
thinking about Sunday ``because there is another tournament
(Monday) where ... where? ... in Montreal, and I will think of
that.''
</P>
<P>
   And the lesson from Boston, a hurt that even a $13,500 runner-up
check could not salve, is this, said the young Austrian.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well ... yes, next time I am leading, 5-1, in the third set, I
am just trying to keep on playing aggressive. And be concentrated
until the last point is made.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
