<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-FALMOUTH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KHANNOUCHI LEAVES GRIEF, FIELD BEHIND 
</HEADLINE>
 RACE-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FALMOUTH, Mass. _ One week ago, Khalid Khannouchi wasn't much in
a running mood. He had just gotten word that his older brother,
Said, had died of a heart attack at his home in Morocco.
</P>
<P>
   But his wife said, ``Go to Falmouth,'' and his family said, ``Do
it for him.'' So Khannouchi, the Moroccan native who now lives in
Ossining, N.Y., took a deep breath, drove to the Cape, and Sunday
successfully defended his title in the 26th annual Harvard Pilgrim
Health Care Falmouth Road Race. His time of 31 minutes 48 seconds
was 10 seconds better than last year's and third best in race
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had two goals here,'' Khannouchi said. ``To win Falmouth and
to win it for him.''
</P>
<P>
   As the 9,000 runners set out in front of Captain Kidd's bar in
Woods Hole at 10 in the morning, Khannouchi was just a face among
the pack of lead runners. The men ran a 4:37 first mile, and as the
7.1-mile course wound its way past the boats in the harbor and
along the beach, the elite runners pulled away from the pack.
</P>
<P>
   But even though the sun wasn't blazing, the 82-degree heat and
humidity took its toll. The lead pack of 24 dwindled to 20, then to
a dozen, and by the time the runners had hit the 6-mile mark only
seven were leading the way. And nobody seemed willing to break away
until Khannouchi decided to make his trademark kick.
</P>
<P>
   Then, as the runners headed uphill, Khannouchi pulled away,
virtually leaving the others in the dust. Pumping his arms and
pushing his legs as fast and rhythmically as he had the entire
race, Khannouchi kept going until he saw the giant American flag
hanging over the road in Falmouth Heights. By then it was sealed _
the No. 1 he wore as last year's winner was his again.
</P>
<P>
   Five seconds behind was Kenyan John Korir, and two seconds
behind Korir was Kenyan Luka Cherono.
</P>
<P>
   Khannouchi said that even though the $10,000 prize was sweet, it
was a hard race to run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was emotionally upset, because Said was the oldest and
smartest of the family,'' said Khannouchi, one of his family's six
children. ``I was almost going to cancel, but my wife and family
told me, `You've got to keep running normal and to keep up your
training.' They said, `Said wants to see you as a great runner, you
have to do it for him.' So I was running and his spirit was with
me.''
</P>
<P>
   It was that spirit, not to mention Khannouchi's incredible surge
at the end, that pulled him through.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was confident in my kick, and this year I've won several
races using that kick,'' Khannouchi said, noting that he sprinted
out Sunday sooner than he usually does. ``But I made the move early
to make sure I was going to win. I made a move then to secure the
victory.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the race has a decidedly hometown flavor, from the
impromptu bands set up on the side of the road to the spectators
ringing cowbells or spraying hoses on the runners, the
international field is making its mark. The top 14 finishers were
from Africa, 11 from Kenya.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Jacobs, of Rockford, Ill., was the first American to cross
the line, which earned him $4,000. It was a move up the ladder for
Jacobs, 34, who was the third American in 1996, and the second last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs said he looks forward to the speedy Kenyan influence
``because I go to these races to push myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Khannouchi seemed to emerge from the shadows of the pack
Sunday, but the spotlight has been shining on him since last
October, when he ran his first marathon in Chicago. Not only did he
win with a time of 2 hours 7 minutes 10 seconds, but it was the
fastest marathon ever run in the United States, and just 20 seconds
off the world record.
</P>
<P>
   So it shoudn't have surprised him to hear chants of ``Go
Khalid'' from the thousands of fans lining the course.
</P>
<P>
   And he had his personal rooting section, his wife, Sandra.
</P>
<P>
   She said that even though she's run Falmouth before, a bout of
Achilles' tendinitis has sidelined her _ to a point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to start the race, because I bring him good luck,'' she
said, standing behind her husband and rubbing his neck after the
race. ``So I ran about 400 meters, then got on a bike and rode to
the finish and got here three minutes before he did.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, the good luck charm worked.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
