</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AVERY WEARING THIN IN ROTATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BOSTON _ Today's quiz: What Red Sox manager said the
following? ``I don't make decisions about the pitchers on my staff,
they make them for me.''
</P>
<P>
   If your first guess was current Boston skipper Jimy Williams,
you're wrong. One might have thought that after watching Steve
Avery suffer on the mound again Sunday at Fenway Park. But the man
who said it was Ralph Houk, who used the line almost daily when
evaluating his staff.
</P>
<P>
   Houk's thinking was that if a pitcher looked horrible, he might
just be horrible. If he showed flawed mechanics, and had more walks
than strikeouts, he just might not be very good. Houk was right
about a lot of things, and Williams may be wise to consider his
words of wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   Try as he may, Avery can't seem to get off that roller-coaster
ride that is spoiling his bid to return to the successful form he
showed for years with Atlanta. Meanwhile, Pete Schourek, newly
acquired from Houston, is ready and waiting. He may get his chance
soon.
</P>
<P>
   The sooner the better after seeing Avery give up six more earned
runs Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ```We'll decide that later,'' said Williams after Boston's 6-3
loss to Minnesota. ``Whatever we decide is best for our staff is
what we'll do. If there is a change, we'll let you know in good
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, the time is now, and not just because of what happened
Sunday. Yes, the Red Sox are 11-5 this season when Avery starts.
And yes, he had a nice streak after overhauling his mechanics,
which earned him the praise of teammates and fans. But recently
he's struggled, and how can a team fighting for a playoff spot
continue to go with a pitcher who after a year and a half in Boston
still is lacking the killer instinct that was part of his
personality in Atlanta. Sunday he had only 11 of 22 first-pitch
strikes in a 77-pitch outing. He fell behind hitters repeatedly,
walking three and striking out just one.
</P>
<P>
   That's no way to stay ahead of the pack in the American League
wild-card race. With 41 games left, the Sox need to be able to
count on their Nos. 4 and 5 starters as well as the big three of
Pedro Martinez, Bret Saberhagen, and Tim Wakefield. If they should
come up short, as was the case in the four-game split with the
lowly Twins, it puts tremendous pressure on the Red Sox' bullpen.
Boston's 6 1/2-game lead in the wild-card race is hardly
comfortable. The Rangers come to town for two games starting Monday
night. Anaheim, Seattle, Toronto, New York, and Baltimore remain on
the schedule. Should one be worried? Damn right.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we're trying to do is go out and play for today,'' said
Williams before Sunday's loss. He was looking for innings from
Avery and didn't get them. ``You can't look back. You look for
today. You can't panic. Fans can look ahead. For us, it doesn't
matter. We just go out and play the schedule. At the end of the
season, you look around and see where we are. Our goals remain
small. You can't play 162 games in one day. You can only play
one.''
</P>
<P>
   Avery didn't stick around long enough to discuss his poor
outing, opting instead for a postgame party. Pitching coach Joe
Kerrigan didn't have the luxury of ducking the media. He merely
confirmed what they had all seen, calling it a bad outing by a
veteran lefthander who should be doing better. After all, the Twins
are not the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The previous three times, he pitched OK,'' said Kerrigan.
``But today he regressed. He went back to his old overhand
delivery. He couldn't find the slot from which to throw the ball,
and started wrapping it around his head. Instead of that good
sinking action, there was a cut to his pitches and they went into a
righthanded hitter. In his slot, the balls go away, usually.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams was kinder. He put his neck on the line this year by
sticking with Avery. But two steps backward is hardly progress, and
he has to know this.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you compete,'' he said, ``sometimes you revert back and
you don't realize you're in the same old slots. If he stays with
that new slot, he can be very consistent with his location and he
can stay ahead of the hitter. His pitches are located a little
better. His command is better.''
</P>
<P>
   Schourek says he's ready if the call comes.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as I can continue to throw and stay sharp, I'll be all
right,'' said Schourek. ``I was throwing decent in Houston. With
Randy Johnson, we had too many guys in the same slot. I'm working
out of the bullpen, and if that's where they want me, fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Using Schourek as anything but a starter probably won't last
much longer, anyway, says Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will take care of it the best way we know how,'' he said.
``If you use him out of the bullpen too much, you have to rest him.
We'll try to do what we think is the best way for us to use him and
win as many games as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   But don't be too surprised if nothing is done right away. Avery
still has a lot of respect and support.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really hard,'' said Martinez. ``We as pitchers understand
all the things he's going through, especially the mind game. At
this level, it's particularly hard. I think he deserves some credit
for the things he's done for himself and/or the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Saberhagen: ``I was very surprised he adapted so quickly.
He had to go from throwing all your career one way to trying to
change it to another. The thing that is hurting him now is pitching
from behind and the bases on balls and being a little wild. That's
all a part of mechanics, and the mechanics are what he's trying to
adjust to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
