<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-TWINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILTON THROWS RED SOX FOR LOOP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ OK, so setting the '27 and '98 Yankees aside for a
moment, every team hits one of these stretches, maybe even two or
three of them, over the mind-altering, body-beating course of the
162-game season.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox were rubbed out by the Twins, 6-3, Sunday at the
Fens, done in by the sharp pitching of Minnesota starter Eric
Milton and the el-foldo show of their own Steve Avery (3 IP, 9 H, 6
ER, every pitch a battle).
</P>
<P>
   In and of itself, no big deal. But matched up with Saturday's
3-2 loss to the Twins, and considering how no one in the Sox'
rotation right now appears capable of turning off the shower (never
mind being sent there early), there's the doomsday inclination to
hang one giant ``Uh-oh'' over the Back Bay with six weeks still
left in the season.
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't be summer in this city without at least reaching for
the alarm. The Townies still own a 6 1/2-game lead over Texas in
their bid for a wild-card spot, which means they should clinch a
berth in the AL postseason if they play somewhere around .550 ball
the rest of the way. Lapse into .500 or less, keep breaking even as
they did in their four-game set with the Twins, and they'll just
disappear with the rest of their failed forefathers of the last 80
years. Oh, and Babe Ruth died 50 years ago Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   It's time now for the Sox to separate themselves from the rest
of the pack, or risk seeing the ghost of Bucky Dent tiptoe his way
down Ted Williams Way and stick his nose over the Wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to stay strong mentally,'' said Sox slugger Mo Vaughn,
stymied, like all his teammates, by Milton's no-hit pitching into
the sixth inning. ``We have to have a strong attitude, and we'll
break this thing (Monday night).''
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of 30,893 watched Avery retire leadoff hitter Otis Nixon
on a routine pop to start the afternoon, but it quickly turned into
three-plus innings of intense labor for the lefthander. Eight
hitters came to the plate in the first and two runs came across,
Marty Cordova trotting in with the 2-0 lead when Avery walked Alex
Ochoa with the bases loaded.
</P>
<P>
   In the second, another pair came across, after it briefly
appeared a Matt Lawton double-play grounder would short-circuit the
inning for the Twins. No such luck. Pat Meares scored on the DP,
and the next hitter, Cordova, knocked in Nixon for the 4-0 lead
with a double past first base. The Twins weren't exactly hammering
Avery (8-5), but their squib hits and his lack of control proved a
lethal combination _ so deadly that the Sox brass soon might have
to bump Avery to the bullpen and give Pete Schourek a start.
</P>
<P>
   After some technical talk from pitching coach Joe Kerrigan after
the second inning _ a chat in the tunnel about release point in his
delivery _ Avery made short work of the third inning, allowing only
a Terry Steinbach single. But the Twins' fourth started this way:
Nixon single, Brent Gates double, wild pitch (scoring Nixon),
Lawton double. The Twins had a half-dozen runs in the bank and
Avery was cashiered for Carlos Reyes. Day done.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the masterful Milton, only 23 years old, wouldn't let
the Sox near a base after allowing a Darren Lewis leadoff walk in
the first. In fact, he set down the next 15 straight hitters,
mostly on strikeouts and fly balls, until Jason Varitek knocked him
for a leadoff single in the sixth. He made it into the seventh, at
which point the Twins' own parade of bullpen backups _ Mike
Trombley, Eddie Guardado, Hector Carrasco, and Rick Aguilera (think
'86 Mets, Bill Buckner, ... help!) _ carried it to the win column.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll get back here (Monday night) with (Bret Saberhagen),''
said Vaughn, the Sox now 71-50 with about 25 percent (41 games) of
the season to go. ``We'll be all right ... everyone's going to have
their lapses.''
</P>
<P>
   They say that everywhere. Except New York. The question now is,
who'll stop the rain?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
