<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS HOPE TO FIND THEIR WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Amid the chaos of this city of nearly 17 million,
the Patriots are trying to find some peace of mind.
</P>
<P>
   Winless in two exhibition games, the Patriots not only are
trying to beat the Dallas Cowboys (also 0-2), but are trying to
look good before national television and international audiences.
</P>
<P>
   They will be trying to reaffirm to themselves, their fans, and
the pundits that they are one of the elite teams in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going there to get better,'' said free safety Willie
Clay. ``We're going to make progress. We want a situation where
every game we make some progress and then peak in time for the
start of the season. That's the goal of the preseason. We haven't
looked that good so far, but we've been practicing well and I think
we're ready to show it.''
</P>
<P>
   Special teams captain Larry Whigham said, ``I try to win every
game, preseason or regular season. We'd like something to show for
all the work we've been doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Training camp ended Saturday in Smithfield, R.I., with the
Patriots still not making noticeable progress on their two biggest
issues: the offense, especially the new timed passing game, and the
right cornerback spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to emphasize the run in this game,'' said coach
Pete Carroll. ``We're seeing things that we're very encouraged
about, but so far we haven't seen those things in the games. This
is a good opportunity for us to have success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our team needs to get something out of this. It's not so much
winning, it's about getting our first unit some valuable experience
out there against the type of defense we haven't seen the past
couple of weeks. Dallas poses new problems for us. They're similar
to Miami, so this will be a big test for us.''
</P>
<P>
   In more ways than one.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots will be playing at an elevation in Azteca Stadium
that will provide excellent practice for the season opener at
Denver in three weeks. Mexico City's elevation is 7,350 feet,
Denver's is 5,280. There's also a lot of smog in Mexico City, and
it's hot and muggy, so the conditions should be taxing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not using the conditions as an excuse,'' said Carroll.
``It's the same for both teams. We're hoping our players adapt to
the conditions quickly and then forget about it and go out and
accomplish the things we're trying to get done this week. The crowd
(expected to be about 108,000) should be more of a Dallas crowd, so
we'll be in a hostile environment. We'll have to contend with all
of those things, so I think this is a great situation for us to
have to overcome some adversity.''
</P>
<P>
   The game will also be an experimental one for instant replay.
When there's a call being questioned by the officials, play will
stop, the replay will be viewed, and the decision made by the
referee after consulting with the other officials. This should
prolong what could be a long night.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll said he will use his starting units on offense and
defense for at least the first half.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots spent many more hours last week working on the
passing game. During Saturday's walk-through, Drew Bledsoe threw
the ball very well and the timing seemed OK. The Patriots hope
Bledsoe can get the ball into the hands of Terry Glenn and Ben
Coates often in the first half, while also giving a lot of carries
to running backs Sedrick and Harold Shaw and Derrick Cullors.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll said there will be some substitutions on the first-team
offense and defense as he would like to see how some of the backups
perform with the first unit.
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver Troy Brown, who will do the bulk of the punt
returning, will be on the field on third down, as will Vincent
Brisby. The Patriots also hope to get rookie Tony Simmons some reps
with the first team.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots are expected to continue to use their regular
defense and save their blitz packages for the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   On the defensive line, Mark Wheeler and Chad Eaton will start
inside in the absence of Henry Thomas, who still is recovering from
a root canal that required nine stitches. Willie McGinest and
Ferric Collons will start at the ends, but former Boston College
star Chris Sullivan and rookie Greg Spires (if his ankle is better)
will also see time at end. Spires is expected to see some
third-down action with the first unit to test his pass rushing
skills.
</P>
<P>
   The key position, right corner, will be manned by Chris Canty,
the team's 1997 first-round draft pick. Canty needs to show
improvement. It doesn't appear that this year's No. 1 pick, Tebucky
Jones, will play the position because of turf toe. That will give
Steve Lofton, Mark Tate, Kato Serwanga, and Terry Billups plenty of
opportunity to earn backup spots.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a big night for players on the fringe.
</P>
<P>
   Receiver Anthony Ladd, one of the stars of training camp and a
favorite of the coaching staff, could do wonders for his situation
with a good game. It's also prime time for Tony Gaiter, last year's
sixth-round pick out of Miami, who needs to show his moves and
speed on kickoffs, punts, and as a receiver quickly. Veteran
defensive lineman Mike Jones also appears to be on the bubble and
could help his cause with a big game.
</P>
<P>
   There's still a battle for the starting receiver job between
Brisby and Shawn Jefferson; on special teams between linebackers
Vernon Crawford and Bernard Russ; and at right guard between Todd
Rucci and Heath Irwin.
</P>
<P>
   The game also will pit Dallas coach Chan Gailey's new offense
against that of Ernie Zampese, who is now running the old Cowboys
offense in New England. Despite his public words, Zampese, who came
under fire in Dallas last year and was dismissed after coach Barry
Switzer was fired, undoubtedly would like a strong effort by his
offense to stick it to his old team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want our offense to do well because we need to start doing
well. For no other reason,'' said Zampese.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-98 0157EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
