</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-BOSTON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINNER SERVES UP MEMORABLE FINAL 
</HEADLINE>
 CUP-DE SWARDT-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WELLESLEY, Mass. _ She was trailing, 5-1, in the third set, one
game from losing the Boston Cup championship Sunday, and Mariaan de
Swardt wanted to make seventh seed Barbara Schett earn the title.
She didn't want to give up any free points.
</P>
<P>
   There was one match point for Schett, in the 10th game on de
Swardt's serve, but the unseeded de Swardt hit a forehand winner up
the line. Then came another forehand winner, followed by a service
winner to the forehand.
</P>
<P>
   Schett, with two service games for the match, never was able to
finish it off. In the 12th game, de Swardt hit three aces to the
backhand on the deuce side, capturing the match, 3-6, 7-6 (7-4),
7-5, before 1,700 at Babson College.
</P>
<P>
   In the final game, de Swardt put everything into her first
serves. ``I was going for it,'' she said. ``I think she was leaning
to the left. If she was going to break me, she was going to have to
come and get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Schett was nervous, something de Swardt could tell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she got a little tentative, a little nervous, and I
said, `Well, I'm going to see if I can try and hold my serve one
more time and go from there,''' said de Swardt, ranked No. 50 in
the world. ``I actually wanted to make her serve it out one more
time and she started going for shots that she didn't go for before.
When she was up, 5-1, she started going for too much and she made a
few errors and gave me a few free points. I just took my chances
from there on.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was going for a lot of shots and before she didn't. She
was going for a lot of lines and she made a few bad errors. I kind
of sensed she was a little anxious so I just tried to make her hit
the winners. I hung in there, just making her play.''
</P>
<P>
   At one point, de Swardt held on to the fence to catch a
breather. That was in the 11th game of the third set, after she hit
a drop shot to go up, 6-5, on Schett's serve. It was 87 degrees,
with high humidity, and that played a factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was running me all over the court, and I was so tired and
I was making some unforced errors,'' said de Swardt. ``I don't
think it was as much the heat as it was me being tired. I've played
a lot of tennis the last two or three days. I knew I'd do a lot of
running. I've played a lot of three-set (matches), but I dug it out
somehow.''
</P>
<P>
   Most everyone plays to de Swardt's backhand, on which she
usually slices, and that's what Schett did. De Swardt wasn't able
to get to the net, Schett keeping her deep near or behind the
baseline. Especially in the first set and a half.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that I gave her too many free points on my
backhand,'' de Swardt said. ``I didn't make her work as much as I
would have liked her to. She made me work. I wasn't moving as well
as I have been the last two days. I wasn't hitting my backhand that
well.''
</P>
<P>
   But she recovered, and now has $27,000 to spend for taking the
title.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
