<SLUG> BC-RAC-WONDERLAND </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCKING-CHAIR WIN FOR GRANNY 
</HEADLINE>
 DERBY-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   REVERE, Mass. _ It was the perfect match, a rail-runner and the
No. 1 box, and it led to a rapidly run victory by Granny in the
$100,000 Wonderland Derby Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   A talented invader from Mile High in Colorado, Granny loves the
inside and the rest of the field was in trouble as early as
Thursday afternoon when trainer Rebecca Chamberlain, representing
the Pat Collins Kennel, pulled the No. 1 pill for Granny at the box
draw.
</P>
<P>
   Backed down to 8-5 ($5.20 to win), the favorite did not
disappoint, outdueling Greys Freckles, an 8-1 shot from box No. 5,
for the early lead, and drawing away along the fence to tally by 3
1/2 lengths. Greys Betsy Ross, an outstanding dog from St.
Petersburg, Fla., who had been the top Derby qualifier, broke last
from box No. 8 as the 5-2 second choice and fought her way clear to
nip Greys Freckles for second at the wire.
</P>
<P>
   The 1-8 quiniela paid $8.60, the 1-8-5 trifecta was worth
$72.80, and the 1-8-5-6 superfecta, with 38-1 Dornsife finishing a
distant fourth, returned $284. Rounding out the field, in order of
finish, were Jauss, Florida Sharp, Jimbo's Chelsie, and Glowing
Gem. The time of 38.10 over the 2,045 feet of the Revere Course was
the second-fastest in 64 runnings of the Derby, behind Bartie's
38.04 in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get in a race this size, when you're facing dogs of
this caliber, the No. 1 box is the box to have,'' said Larry
Chamberlain, who assists wife Rebecca. ``I don't care if the dog is
an inside runner or a wide runner, the one hole is the best hole.
That's just my opinion. If you've got the one hole, you've got the
lane if you can beat the box. And Granny's got good speed.''
</P>
<P>
   Granny is owned by Floyd Gibson of Denver, who flew in for the
occasion. When asked what he did for a living, Gibson said
something about ``a concrete mixer.'' A couple of writers initially
thought he owned a construction company, but further questioning
revealed he drives a concrete mixer and is a regular guy who grew
to love dog racing as a fan. Granny is Gibson's only active
greyhound, though he now owns eight puppies sired by Trojan
Episode, Granny's father.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson, who began attending races in 1978 and slowly developed a
desire to be an owner, was quietly emotional after accepting the
$60,000 winner's share. His eyes teared as he recalled how he had
named Granny, whom he personally picked out from her litter, for
his late mother, Della, because that's what the kids had called
her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to fly, but I did it for Granny. This one is for
my mother,'' said Gibson. ``The only time I ever flew before was
when I went to Germany when I was in the army. I thought that was
enough. I'm not even going to get on the plane to go back if it's
raining.''
</P>
<P>
   When Gibson does get on the plane, his pockets will be a lot
heavier thanks to his very professional, and aggressive, greyhound.
``She's a great dog in the kennel,'' said Larry Chamberlain. ``She
does everything she's supposed to do. She doesn't cause any
trouble, she fits right in. There's one thing, though. We have to
feed her first.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Derby drew 1,892. The modest crowd was enthusiastic,
however, and there was a discernible buzz in the plant. The total
handle on the 19-race card was $466,735, the largest of the year,
with $228,314 bet on-track.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Derby is more a race now for people who follow the
greyhounds,'' said Wonderland assistant general manger Ron Wohlen.
``One thing you get with a big race is they yell. They cheer on
their dogs. This race has an identity and the dogs in it have an
identity. The fans actually call the dogs by name instead of
yelling: `Come on, 1-8.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
