<SLUG> BC-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIVATE RYAN LESSONS HELPED SAVE JOHNSON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now that Randy Johnson has become a temporary Texan, there is a
prevailing theory that the Big Ugly will soon be a permanent
resident of The Big State.
</P>
<P>
   As a free-agent-to-be, Johnson could stay in Houston, where he's
the hottest thing with the populace since mosquito repellent. Or
...
</P>
<P>
   How about Randy in Arlington? Even as we speak, Tom Hicks might
have some hip pocket plans for Johnson, come winter.
</P>
<P>
   There are many ways to describe Johnson _ best pitcher in ball;
miserable human being; head case; quitter in Seattle this season
while being paid $6 million. There is some truth in all of those.
Plus, Johnson will be 36 next season, and has a history of back
ailments.
</P>
<P>
   Considering everything, would you want him on your team?
</P>
<P>
   ``Depends,'' answered Nolan Ryan. ``Depends on if you are
serious about wanting to win the World Series.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan, of course, is the Rangers' part-time goodwill ambassador
and a full-time banker, rancher, and whatever-he-wants-to-be. But
ironically, Ryan is also the best thing to ever happen to Randy
Johnson, or so says Randy Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Nolan denies it, and tries to low-key the idea, partly because
he knows it's sort of a sore subject for past and present Rangers'
baseball people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just trying to help a fellow pitcher, but my role wasn't
that large,'' said Ryan, laughing. This was late last week after
Nolan had paid a visit to the Astrodome to watch Johnson pitch.
Following that Thursday game, Randy spent more time with the media
talking about Nolan than himself.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, Johnson's career has been resurrected in Houston.
Which is a nice tie-in to the fact that six years ago his career
was saved in Alvin, some 30 miles down the road from the Dome.
</P>
<P>
   But it was under another baseball big top when the connection
between Randy Johnson and Nolan Ryan actually started. Ryan and the
Rangers were at the Kingdome in Seattle in 1992 when word came to
the visiting clubhouse that a Mariners' pitcher needed Ryan's
advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``That happened a lot, and I always agreed to do it,'' said
Nolan, who would retire after the '93 season. ``I told Randy to
meet me in the outfield early in batting practice.''
</P>
<P>
   And they talked, and talked, and talked. Finally, it was time
for pregame infield. So they went into the clubhouse tunnel and
continued talking. Ryan even suggested Johnson also seek advice
from Tom House, the Rangers pitching coach.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Johnson's career was going nowhere. He was in the
midst of an eight-game losing streak and after five years, wasn't
even a .500 pitcher in the majors. Immense talent has been
swallowed up by inconsistency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mostly when I'm asked to talk to other pitchers, it's like a
five-minute conversation,'' Ryan said. ``They come with questions,
but they have their own answers. They hear me, but they aren't
listening. Randy was totally different. He truly wanted a different
point of view.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan gave pitching pointers. So did House. ``Seattle had a bad
team and Randy was going bad ... I didn't think a thing about it,''
Ryan said.
</P>
<P>
   Two months later, Johnson came into old Arlington Stadium and
struck out 18 Rangers. ``I'm catching hell from the hitters in the
dugout,'' remembered a grinning Ryan. `` `Way to go, Nolan,' ''
they kept telling me. And House stayed hidden down at the end of
the dugout. I got no support from him.''
</P>
<P>
   During that off-season, Ryan and House invited Johnson to Alvin
to participate in the filming of a how-to-pitch video for
youngsters. On the high school diamond (Nolan Ryan Field), Johnson
received a couple of days of private tutoring from Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   In the '93 season, Randy went 19-8 and his career began a
skyrocket ride. Only this season did it bottom out again in Seattle
as Johnson seemed to mentally fold due to unpleasant contract
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's ``bad guy'' reputation also grew.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe that at all,'' Ryan said. ``People look at
Randy on the mound and see a dominator and an intimidator. They
think that's also the real-life Randy Johnson. But I see him as a
sensitive person, who can have his feelings hurt, and he takes a
lot of things personally. There are times when things boil over
inside, and he reacts. To me, however, Randy is a good guy, and one
of the true great pitchers.''
</P>
<P>
   Remember this _ Doug Melvin and Tom Hicks will be asking Ryan
for his opinion on free-agent Randy Johnson. Plus, Johnson might be
asking Ryan for more career advice. Such as living conditions in
Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   If the Rangers are interested this winter _ and they will be _
then Nolan could give them a quick inside track to Johnson's
signature.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
