<SLUG> BC-LeBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNTIL TYSON RETURNS TO RING, JOKES ARE ON BOXING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The satellite dish is out, so I can't get Comedy Central.
</P>
<P>
   But good news _ there's always boxing.
</P>
<P>
   Boxing is the comic relief of the sports scene. It is the
sporting world's peep show. Its 10-car collision. Its cousin Bluto.
It is the No. 1 reason why the civilized British believe this whole
New World thing was a big mistake.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't all about Mike Tyson, though it could be. Tyson made
news last week by withdrawing his application for a New Jersey
boxing license, opting instead for reapplying in Nevada, where his
permit was revoked 14 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Shelley Finkel, serving as Tyson's spokesman, had told reporters
that his man was ``hungry to fight again.''
</P>
<P>
   Our ears immediately perked, so to speak. And I promise not to
tell any more bad biting jokes.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson, however, prompted more than curious speculation when he
suddenly withdrew his New Jersey application. Published reports
there suggest that Tyson felt his request was going to be denied
and didn't want to deal with the tidal wave of ``Tyson Rejected''
headlines. Or, then again, maybe he was afraid that if he got
reinstated, he'd be asked to appear on that Magic Johnson show.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't bode well when a Jersey state senator, William
Gormley, who happens to be the brother of one of the board members
considering the fighter's reinstatement, came out and publicly said
Tyson shouldn't be licensed.
</P>
<P>
   But this was supposed to be Atlantic City, N.J., which is sort
of like Vegas on Prozac. Boardwalk moneybags Donald Trump
reportedly was ready to roll out the red carpet for Tyson. Trump's
millions could have staged the next Tyson-Evander Holyfield fight.
</P>
<P>
   But don't try to understand Mike Tyson. He is boxing's poster
child. He has been a childhood thug, nearly an Olympian (Fort
Worth, 1984), a car-crasher, head-basher, topless dancer fondler,
beauty contestant rapist, ex-convict and ex-champion.
</P>
<P>
   Yet _ and here's the scary part _ outside of Muhammad Ali, Tyson
owns the most recognized name and face in boxing on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   The sport needs him. The current champ, Holyfield, had to cancel
a summer title defense against Henry Akinwande. The reason given
was that Akinwande contracted the hepatitis-B virus. Curiously,
that diagnosis came one day after reports said that pay-per-view
sales for the fight were pitifully lagging and that the fight
loomed as a financial bust.
</P>
<P>
   This is the same sport, of course, where Roberto Duran _ the
real one, not his grandson _ has signed on to fight William Joppy,
who was born in 1970, three years after Duran started boxing.
</P>
<P>
   This is the same sport where George Foreman and Larry Holmes are
scheduled to fight in January. (Supply own joke here).
</P>
<P>
   And this is also the sport where Bonecrusher Smith, age 45,
squared off against Joe Bugner, age withheld pending carbon-dating,
last month in Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Missed that one? Well, it didn't last long. On Bonecrusher's
first attempted punch of the night, he dislocated his shoulder and
the bout had to be stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, boxing.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week came word that Irish promoters had put up a purse
of one million British pounds ($1.65 million) for that ``Lord of
the Dance'' guy to fight. It seems that Michael Flatley claims to
have boxed when he was growing up in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, right.
</P>
<P>
   But the Irish matchmakers are serious. They think it would be
``good fun.'' And I'm not so sure I myself wouldn't pay to watch
Flatley get clogged and flogged around the ring. At least make him
button his shirt.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, boxing.
</P>
<P>
   It needs Tyson, because without him, there is only an abyss of
Andrew Gulotas, Michael Moorers, Bonecrusher Smiths and Vaughn
Beans to look forward to. Bean has been announced as the latest
opponent for Holyfield, with the bout set for Sept. 19 in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Bean _ Butterbean? Mr. Bean? _ showed up for the press
conference wearing a red turban. At the same event in Atlanta, an
executive from the Showtime network, Jay Larkin, took the
microphone and tried to make funny business of the imminent arrival
of the Holyfield family's next baby. Noting that the champ and his
wife were fond of names beginning in ``E,'' the Showtime exec
suggested they name the kid ``E-coli.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta is where more than 20 children were stricken recently
with E-coli bacteria, leading to one death.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, boxing.
</P>
<P>
   When boxing is in the news, I'm all ears.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry. Couldn't resist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-98 0213EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
