impresario of the New York new-media scene, is either an
entrepreneurial wunderkind or a sophomoric pain in the neck. Which
makes him the perfect embodiment of Silicon Alley itself, as it
reaches a new state of maturation. By Amy Harmon. (With graphics
and photo.)
</P>
<P>
   BELLS-ASSESS (Undated) _ The stock of Bell Atlantic Corp. has
lost 11.8 percent of its value since Aug. 3, when the 73,000 of its
employees who are represented by the Communications Workers of
America authorized the union to call the strike that began the next
weekend. Over the same period, shares of the other four local Bell
telephone companies _ each with their own big union contingents _
have declined by an average of 3.8 percent. While three of them
have signed new labor contracts since last spring, about 34,000
union workers at US West walked off the job early Sunday. By Seth
Scheisel.
</P>
<P>
   TV-WRESTLING-MEDIA (Undated) _ Wrestling shows on three cable TV
channels have become the dominant hits of cable television. The
cable channels with wrestling shows, TNT, TBS and USA, are
increasingly using this fact to try to pry more revenue from
advertisers. Network executives, meanwhile, are trying, with some
forced subtlety, to reference the stereotype of the wrestling
audience _ lower-income, under-educated _ as a reason why cable is
not a place premium advertisers ought to want to be. By Bill
Carter. (With graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T-TCI-GREENTHAL (Undated) _ It is only reluctantly, and a
little brusquely, that Jill Greenthal, a media banker for the
investment banking firm of Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette, speaks
about the thing that makes her stand out from her colleagues, her
competitors and most of her clients. That is, that she is a woman.
By Joseph Kahn. (With graphic and photo.)
</P>
<P>
   EDS-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ As hard as Electronic Data Systems
has tried to define itself as something other than the company that
Ross Perot founded, it has never quite escaped his legacy. Fourteen
years after Perot sold the company to General Motors, it is still
run by his former lieutenants. But all that is about to change. By
Allen R. Myerson. (With graphic.)
</P>
