A6657 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPORTSMANSHIP-TEX     08-17 1153
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPORTSMANSHIP-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUTH SPORTS ARE NO LONGER CHILD'S PLAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHARD TIJERINA AND ANDY FRIEDLANDER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
Second in a series 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A 16-year-old is piled in the locker room by his junior varsity
teammates for committing errors in a baseball game. A parent is
banned from watching his daughters at the state tennis tournament
for throwing orange peels at an opposing school's player. A
sixth-grade football game erupts into violence involving players,
coaches and parents.
</P>
<P>
   More and more, poor sportsmanship at the youth level appears to
be the rule, not the exception.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches at the high-school level are expected to teach proper
conduct. But the seeds of sportsmanship, both good and bad, are
sown early, long before athletes get to high school.
</P>
<P>
   Little League fields, recreation gymnasiums and driveways are
often the learning grounds for young athletes. Combine that
training ground with what they learn from television highlights and
sound bites, and the message is often mixed as to the importance of
taunting, showmanship and sportsmanship vs. winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to get a handle on what youth sports is all about,''
says Dr. David Cook, a sports psychologist in Fort Worth, Texas.
``Yes, it's about learning how to compete, but under the guidelines
of sportsmanship and competing within the rules. Any time sports
become nothing more than a pursuit of championships, everything
else gets lost.''
</P>
<P>
   That message is being lost, according to the National Alliance
for Youth Sports, a Florida-based nonprofit organization that
claims to focus on providing youngsters with safe, fun and positive
experiences in organized sports programs.
</P>
<P>
   Its research says that 70 percent of children quit sports by age
13 because it isn't fun, 45 percent of children have been called
names and insulted while playing sports, 8 percent have been called
names with sexual connotations and 21.5 percent have been pressured
to play with an injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 43 and I can remember my days of playing ball and it
wasn't like this,'' says Jerry Johnson, a parent and coach of the
Devil Rays, a Fort Worth University Little League team of 11- and
12-year olds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just seems like winning is overemphasized, and it starts
with TV and moves on down the line from there. If you listen to the
boys talking about what's important, more and more you find that
winning is everything, more important than being good sports.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a bigger picture, coaches say. Once, Irving Nimitz
football coach Mike Farda says he was consumed with winning more
high school football games than the legendary Gordon Wood. That was
25 years ago. He knows more now, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of us realize we are teaching,'' says Mike Fielder, the
former Haltom (Texas) softball coach. ``Whether we win or lose,
athletics is a microcosm of life. In a ballgame or a season, you're
having to deal with the roller-coaster that life provides: how to
deal with the downs and how not to get too up when things are
good.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all is lost, says Lance Van Auken, a spokesman for Little
League Baseball International in Williamsport, Pa. For every
alarming story you hear about bad conduct, he says there are
countless good ones that gone unnoticed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you stop to think about it, last night _ or on any given
night _ there were 10,000 Little League games in the United
States,'' Van Auken says. ``That happens day in and day out. And
with all those games, we'll have an incident reported to us maybe
once every three or four weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, while no tangible statistics or figures can back them up,
many coaches, parents and administrators say youths are arguing
more with umpires and referees than in the past, and are
confronting or taunting or even trying to injure each other with
increasing frequency.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent eight-week period, one area youth sports program
endured fights between a coach and the grandfather of a player, a
coach and a parent, two opposing coaches and two opposing players,
according to a league official.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that's not just us,'' the official said. ``It's going on
nationwide.''
</P>
<P>
   The culprits?
</P>
<P>
   Television bears the brunt of the criticism. Youths are eager to
emulate the professionals they admire and begin to act like little
John McEnroes on the tennis court, little Dennis Rodmans on the
basketball court and little Bryan Coxes on the football field.
</P>
<P>
   ``My son is 5, and he already talks trash,'' says Rick Branum,
27, the coach of a 9- and 10-year old basketball team in the
Arlington Parks and Recreation league. ``I try to keep him from
that, but you see it everywhere and he copies it. You see that a
lot.''
</P>
<P>
   A recent survey of Division I basketball coaches asked who they
consider to be coaching role models. Cook says that while most
named coaches like Roy Williams, Dean Smith or John Wooden, not a
single vote was cast for Indiana's Bobby Knight, who is known for
yelling at officials.
</P>
<P>
   But when those same coaches were asked whom they would like to
deliver a clinic teaching basketball theory and techniques, Knight
was the choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you have is people saying `We love Bobby Knight and
admire him as one of the greatest basketball minds ever, but we
can't support his actions,' '' Cook says. ``The coaches can make
that distinction. But people just watching on TV, including kids,
just see the actions. And then they hear the announcers telling
them how great a coach he is.''
</P>
<P>
   But it doesn't end with TV.
</P>
<P>
   There is a perception among many youth sports officials that
parents are pushing their kids at younger ages harder now, trying
to groom their sons and daughters to earn athletic scholarships and
professional careers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to assess the blame to everyone, including parents,''
says Roger Hancock, the president of the Grand Prairie Youth
Football Association. ``You get a parent in the stands yelling, `Go
kill them, Jimmy!' Well, wait a minute. We're not out there to kill
them. We're here to teach the fundamentals of football, and one of
them is teamwork. Scoring touchdowns is a side benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   Youth leagues, however, have begun to fight back.
</P>
<P>
   Many leagues now have rules to enforce sportsmanship, including
mandatory suspensions if a player, coach or parent is thrown out of
a game. Some try to remove the pressure from the youngest players
by not keeping score in T-ball, which generally includes 5- and
6-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, though, youth leagues pin their hopes on parents,
specifically on getting parents to not challenge referees and
direct their children toward fair play and having fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``The average fan is very interested in wins and losses,'' Farda
says. ``The parents are the fans who are in there who really
understand what athletics is about. They're more concerned. But
even those are diminishing every year, in my opinion.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
