<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPORTSMANSHIP-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH SPORTSMANSHIP PACKAGE 
ATHLETES PUSH LIMITS TO GAIN EDGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of all the unsportsmanlike acts exhibited on playing fields and
in arenas, probably none is more reviled than cheating.
</P>
<P>
   Call a Bryan Cox or an Albert Belle a dirty player or a bad
actor, and they're more likely to wear the criticism as a badge of
honor than to confess and repent. But call an athlete a cheater,
and it's clear they regard it as the greatest of sins, something
they can't bring themselves to admit doing.
</P>
<P>
   Belle, for instance, didn't back off his basepath bulldozing of
Milwaukee's Fernando Vina a couple years ago, but he never copped
to corking his bat, even when caught.
</P>
<P>
   Irish Olympic gold medal swimmer Michelle Smith proclaims her
innocence despite her recent four-year ban from international
competition for tampering with her drug tests.
</P>
<P>
   The shame of being caught cheating doesn't stop athletes from
trying to get an edge, though. And that has resulted in an
increased policing of the games athletes play, amateur and
professional.
</P>
<P>
   Bass tournament officials now administer polygraph tests to
competitors because suspected cheaters would never admit to having
weighted down a bass or imported a bigger catch to the lake.
</P>
<P>
   Motorsports officials are forced to check under the hoods of
race cars at every competition to make sure nobody's trying to get
a tiny technical advantage.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA has long fought a losing battle trying to compel
schools, and their boosters, to obey the rules.
</P>
<P>
   So ingrained is cheating that it is even being taught as an
accepted way to win a game, says John Mackovic, former football
coach at the University of Texas and chairman of the American
Football Coaches Association's ethics committee. Mackovic recalls
being incensed when, while watching a college bowl game last
December, he saw a team run a ``pick'' play. In that play, an
offensive player screened a defender trying to get across the field
to cover an offensive teammate who was supposed to get the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an illegal play. It's against the rules. It's not
supposed to be taught,'' Mackovic said. ``And what has the player
learned from this? That it's OK to break the rules?
</P>
<P>
   ``That coach (who taught the play) should be run out of this
business.''
</P>
<P>
   A coach's sanction of cheating, either through tacit acceptance
or overt encouragement, is a powerful influence on young athletes
when combined with the societal pressure to win and the minimal
risk of being caught.
</P>
<P>
   Sports psychologists and sports ethicists say that more than
ever, winning is everything to competitors today, and that has a
profound impact on the likelihood of cheating. That's especially
true if money is involved, as in the case of professional athletes
and coaches, but it's also true when nothing but bragging rights
are at stake.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pressure to win today is almost insurmountable,'' said
William E. Shelton, president of Eastern Michigan University and
former chairman of the NCAA Committee on Sportsmanship and Ethical
Conduct in Intercollegiate Athletics.
</P>
<P>
   Added Mackovic, ``We've canonized those who've won, regardless
of their means.''
</P>
<P>
   Mackovic knows firsthand the importance of winning. He was
reassigned at the University of Texas last fall after his team's
poor season _ only a year after his team's stunning upset of
Nebraska in the Big 12 Conference championship game. Coaches at all
levels are dismissed when they don't win at the rate expected by
administrators, owners, alumni or fans.
</P>
<P>
   Is it any wonder, sports ethicists ask, there is such pressure
to win _ pressure sufficient to provoke cheating?
</P>
<P>
   Cheating comes in many forms in sports, some modern and
technology-driven. Performance-enhancing drugs are the most common
abuse of the rules in major international competition today.
</P>
<P>
   While most instances of cheating are clear to all, some are less
obvious. Often, the intentions of the perpetrator can be debated:
Did the athlete or official or administrator intend to cheat, or
was the act unwitting or unintentional?
</P>
<P>
   Last winter, the Ambassadors of Christ Academy in Fort Worth was
not allowed to compete in Texas' private school boys basketball
tournament because it improperly enrolled two players on its team.
The players were enrolled at another school at the same time and
also played before the completion of a mandatory 21-day waiting
period for transfers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a breakdown in communication and a failure to
understand the rules,'' said Edd Burleson, director of the Texas
Association of Private and Parochial Schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't believe they came out and were trying to be deceitful
or underhanded,'' board member Mark Bowles said.
</P>
<P>
   Questionable acts can be illegal according to the rules, or
legal simply because no rule has been written to cover it.
</P>
<P>
   Hockey players use sticks that are legally too long. Goalies use
pads determined to be too large. Wide receivers use sticky
substances on their hands and fingers and arms, hoping the ball
will better adhere to them. Offensive linemen use slippery
substances on their uniforms to prevent defensive linemen from
grabbing hold.
</P>
<P>
   Besides bat-corking and spitball-loading, baseball teams are
routinely accused of stealing signs _ from outposts behind the
outfield fence _ and relaying them.
</P>
<P>
   The definition of cheating often depends on the traditions of
the game, the precision of the ground rules and the observer's
philosophies of sport.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever form it takes, cheating has always been around in
sports, and some observers think it's a part of society that always
will be in sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care where you go, you're going to find bad people,''
said Debra Dean, who, with her husband, Jerry, operates bass
fishing tournaments in Texas. ``The polygraph tests have changed
the face of our tournaments. They've curbed some of the cheating.
But you're always going to have it because some people look at it
as a way to make money.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they could cheat at the Lotto, they'd do it, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
