</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPORTSMANSHIP-LOMBARDI-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH SPORTSMANSHIP PACKAGE 
LOMBARDI-SPEAK PROVES PROPHETIC IN WORLD OF SPORTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM PEDLEY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Saint Vincent, old man, what hath thou wrought?
</P>
<P>
   Some say nothing less than the institutionalization of poor
sportsmanship in America.
</P>
<P>
   Whoa. A rather significant accusation.
</P>
<P>
   And all because of one rather closed-ended statement.
</P>
<P>
   It was a simple statement you uttered some 30 years ago _ or,
supposedly uttered (as history is a tad muddy on origin and exact
wording of the statement).
</P>
<P>
   Yes, slick and catchy, but simple:
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning isn't the most important thing. It's the only thing.''
</P>
<P>
   It's lyrical, rhythmic and has just enough punch as to
incorporate a bit of 1960s shock value.
</P>
<P>
   It probably was not meant to be taken literally. And it
certainly wasn't offered up as a mantra. But it stuck. And how.
</P>
<P>
   Not just with those legendary Green Bay Packers teams of yours _
though probably, at least in part, because of them _ but with just
about every athlete who suits it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning isn't the most important thing. It's the only thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Though you still hear it used on Sundays in 1998, you also hear
it on Saturday afternoons. And even on Friday nights.
</P>
<P>
   You hear it on national television and you hear it in city
parks.
</P>
<P>
   There are coaches and players and fans out there who don't
remember the Packers sweep or Fuzzy Thurston or who won the first
Super Bowl. But they know that winning isn't the most important
thing. They know it's the only thing.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, winning. The only thing. Cool.
</P>
<P>
   Poor sportsmanship wasn't invented the day you expressed those
sentiments. But on that day, suddenly, poor sportsmanship could be
rationalized, legitimatized.
</P>
<P>
   And, brother, has it become popularized.
</P>
<P>
   I think about Lombardi and those words:
</P>
<P>
   When I remember the scene of Pete Rose leveling Ray Fosse _ and,
in effect, ending the catcher's career _ in a play at the plate.
(In an All-Star Game, for God's sake.)
</P>
<P>
   When I think of Ohio State coach Woody Hayes punching an
opposing player on a college sideline.
</P>
<P>
   When I hear local players talk of what goes on under piles of
tacklers when playing against a certain Northeast Tarrant
high-school football team.
</P>
<P>
   When I hear of good, solid human beings driven out of
high-school coaching jobs because they spent more time instituting
a mentoring program than a win-at-all-costs mentality in their
football players.
</P>
<P>
   When I hear a mom yell ``kill him'' to her son during a youth
soccer game.
</P>
<P>
   When I answer my phone and am told that I should not be covering
this, that or the other team because ``they are a bunch of
losers.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, loser. It used to be a word.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Saint Vincent, it has become a stigma, a persona.
</P>
<P>
   It has become a label to avoid at all costs.
</P>
<P>
   Loser? Better to be called a racist or a thief or lazy or a liar
or a cheat.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, a cheat. Especially a cheat.
</P>
<P>
   Diving at a quarterback's knees will cost you 15 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Sticking a hockey stick between an opponent's legs will cost you
five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Using a performance-enhancing drug will cost you a year.
</P>
<P>
   An illegal carburetor will cost you a race.
</P>
<P>
   Not conforming to the NCAA's voluminous rule book will cost you
scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   But doing all of that, and risking the consequences, is OK. It's
acceptable because losing can cost you everything: job, happiness,
self esteem, dreams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning isn't the most important thing. It's the only thing.''
</P>
<P>
   I worked with a sports columnist a couple of jobs ago who let
Saint Vince's words get to him. After several years of sports
reporting at the local and college levels, he had had enough.
</P>
<P>
   He stomped off the sports beat one day in favor of working in
the more straightforward and less hypocritical area of crime
reporting.
</P>
<P>
   His parting words to his readers could be construed as an
exasperated attempt at combating The Only Thingism: ``And
remember,'' he said in the column's final paragraph, ``it's only a
damn game.''
</P>
<P>
   Vince, I love ya. Love what those Packers of yours did and for
what you did for a great game.
</P>
<P>
   But Vince, gotta tell you; that advice has proved less than
saintly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
