<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RANGERS-YANKEES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS' BLAST DROPS RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Rangers right-hander Xavier Hernandez threw his
second-best pitch to the American League's No. 1 hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees center fielder Bernie Williams then hit home run No. 18.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' one-out, ninth-inning solo home run propelled New York
to a 6-5 victory Sunday at Yankee Stadium, yet the Rangers remain
only one-half game behind in the AL West after the Angels' 6-5 loss
to the Blue Jays Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers departed New York with their third loss in this
four-game series, despite two home runs and three runs batted in
from center fielder Roberto Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees joined the 1944 Cardinals as the only 90-game
winners through 120 games, and Williams made it possible by
depositing an 0-1 fastball from Hernandez (5-2) into the upper deck
of the right-field seats for a 401-foot exclamation point.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, who retired right fielder Paul O'Neill on strikes for
the inning's first out, entered the final at-bat limiting
left-handed hitters to a .186 batting average.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez threw his best pitch _ a split-fingered fastball _ to
get ahead of the switch-hitting Williams in the count before
delivering a fastball on the game's final delivery.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two schools of thought there,'' Hernandez said.
``One says stick with your best pitch and get beat with your best
pitch if you're going to get beat. The other school of thought says
think while you're out there. I thought it was a good idea, but it
was poor execution.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez blamed the result on not getting the pitch high enough
in the strike zone. Hernandez often buries hitters by getting ahead
in the count and afterward pounds his opponents with a steady diet
of split-fingered fastballs.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez altered the pattern for Williams, whose .355 batting
average leads the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got to be looking down and in there,'' Hernandez said,
``but he whacked it.''
</P>
<P>
   Happy birthday, Xavier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had a lot of success this year throwing my fastball in
\Rsplit-fingered fastball\S counts,'' said Hernandez, who Sunday
celebrated his 33rd birthday. ``Guys are telling themselves, `Stay
back for the split,' and _ whoom! _ the fastball blows by them ...
well, except for today.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly provided the Rangers' 5-4 lead with his fifth-inning solo
home run and second off left-hander David Wells. The Yankees,
though, tied the game in the bottom half of the inning when O'Neill
scored from third on a double-play ground ball off the bat of first
baseman Tino Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers wasted their golden opportunity in the ninth inning
against closer Mariano Rivera (2-0). Second baseman Mark McLemore
collected a one-out single and advanced to second on the ensuing
walk to Tom Goodwin, who replaced Kelly as a pinch hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera retired left fielder Rusty Greer on strikes, but the
right-hander then issued a walk to designated hitter Juan Gonzalez.
That brought first baseman Will Clark to the plate with the bases
loaded and two outs, but Rivera induced an inning-ending ground
ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was two good ballclubs going after each other,'' Rangers
manager Johnny Oates said, ``until the final pitch of the game
decided it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-98 0227EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
