 NEWS AND FEATURE SUMMARY No 2472- August 17, 1998   We are offering
the following articles for sale. Please contact us for availability
your country. Best regards, Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. PERMISSION GRANTED TO KILL A WHALE. NOW WHAT? For the Native
American Makah tribe, getting the green light for their first whale
hunt in two generations was the easy part. The environmentalists
protested; the tribal elders squabbled. And none of the living
Makah have ever hunted a whale before. By Robert Sullivan. From The
New York Times Magazine. 2,500 words. 2. RUSSIA NEEDS LEADERSHIP,
NOT IMF BAILOUTS Will the new IMF bailout affect the Russian
situation in a positive way? How can IMF money influence the course
of events in Russia? Mikhail Gorbachev writes that the new economic
policy is no more than a mirage. ``If Russia and its partners are
facing a dead end, this has strong implications for the West, for
Asia and for the rest of the world.'' 1,000 words. 3. FOR THE 21ST
CENTURY, A BEIGE AND BLACK AMERICA By the end of the next century,
experts predict, racial intermarriage will break down the colour
divide in America. The truth is a bit less black-and-white. By
Michael Lind. From The New York Times Magazine. 2,000 words.
________________________________________________________ 4. BALKAN
KILLING FIELDS The horrors of the Bosnian war can be told through
the experiences of several generations of one family. Review of
Chuck Sudetic's book 'Blood and Vengeance' By Tom Gjelten. From The
New York Times Book Review. 1,800 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 5.
STILL LIVING WITH '68 The worldwide youth revolutions of 30 years
ago are history - except in America. That's because communism never
really mattered there, and democracy mattered too much. By Mark
Lilla. From The New York Times Magazine. 3,000 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 6.
FANTASY ISLAND : THE SEARCH FOR ATLANTIS Invented by Plato to
further an argument, the story of Atlantis has attracted true
believers down the ages. Review of Richard Ellis' book 'Imagining
Atlantis.' By Robert Eisner. From The New York Times Book Review.
1,500 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 7.
MEDICAL ID FOR VIAGRA USERS RECOMMENDED Viagra may be a wonder drug
for men suffering from impotence, but it may also produce
undesirable consequences, especially for men who take heart
medication. By Dr. Charlotte Yeh. Medical Tribune News Service. 500
words. 8. From NATURE NEWS SERVICE (N/A France and Spain. Embargo :
1800 GMT Wednesday August 19)
</P>
<P>
   A. Climate : A Quest for Fire The memories of the pall of smoke
that hung over southeast Asia last year, caused by forest fires in
Indonesia, will be slow to fade. But forest fires happen all the
time through natural causes, so just how important are human-caused
forest fires to the global climate? By Henry Gee. 600 words. B.
Stretching the Limits of Hearing The discovery of an ancient
'earless' grasshopper shows how 'stretch' detectors on the body
formed the starting point for the evolution of hearing in insects.
Surprisingly, the hearing sensitivity of these primitive sound
sensors is better than almost any other insect living today. By
Helen Phillips. 600 words. 9. IS ETHNIC MARKETING ANOTHER KIND OF
BIAS? American Frank Wu was astonished to receive an early morning
phone call promoting a telephone long distance service - in
Chinese. Curious, he discovered that the company had 10 different
ethnic marketing campaigns. ``Ethnic marketing suffers the same
problems as any racial stereotyping, and it also compounds them,''
he writes. From New America News Service. 1,000 words. 10. From NEW
SCIENTIST magazine (N/A Australia, New Zealand, Brazil) A. HOW NOT
TO SAVE THE TIGER : Only 6,000 tigers survive in the world. The
battle to save them will be lost unless conservationists change
their tactics, warns a leading expert. By Oliver Tickell. 800
words. B. BUGS IN THE BRAIN : Could a simple course of antibiotics
protect you from Alzheimer's disease? By Phyllida Brown. 800 words.
C. LIFE SUPPORT : Why bother to save every last species on the
planet? Because they are the Earth's insurance policy, says Bob
Holmes. 3,500 words.
