<SLUG> BC-R-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
15.)
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing. Originally filed on Saturday, August (The Week in Review)  
 (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the Dow Trembles, Small Investors Stand Firm
</P>
<P>
   It's been a disconcerting summer for investors. Wild swings in
share prices sent the Dow Jones industrial average to 9,337.97 in
mid-July, but since then stocks have been plummeting on fears about
the worsening economic crisis in Asia and evidence that U.S.
corporate profits are on the wane.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Dow sank another 173 points, to 8,425 _ its
lowest level since February.
</P>
<P>
   Few investors can make sense of the recent whipsawing stock
prices, but a survey of market watchers suggests that large
institutional investors, like hedge funds, are behind most of the
summer's anxious selling, which has pushed volume up to record
levels in July and August.
</P>
<P>
   Individual investors have been a nervous group, but also a quiet
one. They have not flooded telephone lines at mutual fund
companies, and their silence seems to suggest that they have not
yet called it quits.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID BARBOZA
</P>
<P>
   Swiss Banks Reach Accord
</P>
<P>
   After years of bitter dispute, Switzerland's leading banks
settled a lawsuit with victims of the Nazi era who had accused them
of improperly retaining their assets. The banks agreed to pay $1.25
billion to claimants in the class-action suit _ people who survived
the Holocaust and the heirs of those who did not.
</P>
<P>
   The case, which began as three separate lawsuits in U.S.
District Court in Brooklyn, involved assets that the plaintiffs
said had either been deposited in the banks by victims of Nazi
persecution or had been looted by the Nazis and stored in the
banks.
</P>
<P>
   Many details remain to be worked out, including who is eligible
for the money _ estimates ranged last week from tens of thousands
to hundreds of thousands of people.
</P>
<P>
   The banks are UBS, recently formed by the merger of Union Bank
of Switzerland and Swiss Bank, and Credit Suisse.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JOSEPH P. FRIED
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic Workers Return
</P>
<P>
   Two days after walking off the job, 73,000 Bell Atlantic
employees returned to work on Tuesday after reaching a tentative
two-year agreement with management that guarantees that union
members will install and maintain the high-technology
communications systems now being developed.
</P>
<P>
   Facing intense competition from nonunionized telecommunications
companies, Bell Atlantic was under pressure to settle the strike,
which was already inconveniencing customers. The company also
agreed to phase out hundreds of customer service jobs now being
performed by nonunion personnel in Hampton, Va., and return them to
union workers.
</P>
<P>
   _ By TERRY PRISTIN
</P>
<P>
   Internet Privacy Deal
</P>
<P>
   When new members fill out an online application form for the
popular World Wide Web site Geocities, they are asked to reveal
personal information about education, income, occupation and
personal interests.
</P>
<P>
   Not to worry, Geocities promised on the site's registration
page: ``We will not share this information with anyone without your
permission.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Federal Trade Commission found that Geocities had misled
more than two million subscribers by passing the information to
advertisers and others. In the federal government's first
Internet-privacy enforcement action, the FTC approved a settlement
with Geocities under which the site has to disclose how it intends
to use the personal information it collects.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JOEL BRINKLEY &QR;
</P>
<P>
   No Caribbean Secession
</P>
<P>
   The principle of self-determination was tested on a tiny scale
when the 10,000 people who live on the Caribbean island of Nevis
voted on a proposal to secede from federation with their 36,000
neighbors on nearby St. Kitts.
</P>
<P>
   Although 62 percent voted to split from what is already the
smallest country in the Western Hemisphere, a two-thirds majority
was required to achieve independence. That means Nevisians will not
join the likes of Tuvalu and Nauru in the United Nations _ at least
not for the moment, since the country's constitution permits Nevis
to try again any time it wishes.
</P>
<P>
   _ By LARRY ROHTER
</P>
<P>
   Air Force Rocket Explodes
</P>
<P>
   The fireworks over Florida on Wednesday were spectacular but not
free. The fireball near Cape Canaveral that signaled the death of
an Air Force Titan 4A rocket and its spy satellite  &QL; 
cargo meant a loss of $1 billion or more and a setback for the
country's space-reconnaissance program.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon said it could still do its job with the satellites
already inorbit. But a crestfallen Air Force general captured the
mood best. ``We're hurt,'' he said. An inquiry has begun.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID STOUT
</P>
<P>
   New Help for Clinton
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton is running the meter on his lawyers' clocks
this weekend by preparing for his grand jury testimony Monday. But
he can take comfort in knowing that his new legal defense fund has
raised more than $2 million in just six months.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton Legal Expense Trust has far exceeded expectations,
enriched mostly by an increase in the annual limit from $1,000 to
$10,000 and anger among the president's supporters at Independent
Counsel Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and his wife, Hillary, owe an estimated $6 million to
their private lawyers, and could owe as much as $10 million by
2001. ``There is a well-financed group of zealots who want to bring
down the president,'' said entertainment mogul David Geffen. ``And
this guy has no money. He's broke.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By DON VAN NATTA Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Young Killers Are Punished
</P>
<P>
   In the photographs, the two boys looked alarmingly normal _
except for the chains and handcuffs. But as an Arkansas judge
ordered Mitchell Johnson, 14, and Andrew Golden, 12, to a juvenile
detention center for killing four students and a teacher in a
school shooting spree in Jonesboro last March, a single question
seemed to scream out from those photos: Why?
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we were going to shoot over their heads,'' Mitchell
said, while Andrew pleaded temporary insanity. Mitchell's father
said his son ``doesn't have an answer.'' The slain teacher's
husband will wait: he asked the boys to ``tell us why'' someday.
</P>
<P>
   _ By HUBERT B. HERRING
</P>
<P>
   Reprieve for Globe Columnist
</P>
<P>
   The columnist Mike Barnicle was granted a reprieve by the
management of The Boston Globe. Barnicle's original offense _ an
Aug. 2 column with jokes that paralleled those in a book by
comedian George Carlin _ was compounded when the columnist, who
told his editors that he had never read the book, was shown in a
videotape recommending it to television viewers.
</P>
<P>
   The first offense drew a one-month suspension; after the
videotape surfaced, Globe editor Matthew Storin asked for
Barnicle's resignation.
</P>
<P>
   That decision prompted criticism from Barnicle's supporters,
including advertisers and subscribers. After meeting with the
columnist, Storin and publisher Benjamin Taylor decided instead on
a two-month suspension without pay.
</P>
<P>
   The decision was greeted with jubilation by some, but 50
employees in the newsroom of The Globe, which is owned by The New
York Times Co., sent a petition saying, ``Barnicle's reprieve gives
the appearance of a double standard that allows one individual to
ignore journalistic principles other reporters must follow.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By FELICITY BARRINGER
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
