<HEADLINE>
15.) 
 UNDATED: FELICITY BARRINGER 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing. Originally filed on Saturday, August
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jagger &AMP; Co. Play Moscow, Finally
</P>
<P>
   Better late than never.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Russian rock-and-roll fans were saying last week as
they watched with awe and nostalgia as a middle-aged Mick Jagger
pranced and pirouetted across the stage of a Moscow sports arena,
playing the songs of their youth.
</P>
<P>
   It has been 30 years since Russians first heard hits by the
``Rollingi,'' as the Rolling Stones are known here.
</P>
<P>
   In those dys, back in the now-collapsed U.S.S.R, hits like
``Satisfaction'' and ``Jumping Jack Flash'' were furtive thrills
for Soviet teen-agers who had to engage in illegal ``speculation''
just to buy a smuggled LP. More likely, they listened to bad copies
made on reel-to-reel tapes, or on used X-ray film ingeniously
transformed into disposable records.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't matter that Jagger's face is creased with wrinkles, or
that Charlie Watts' hair has gone white. After all, their loyal
fans didn't look like spring chickens either.
</P>
<P>
   It was enough just to see the group perform with all the gusto
those old records had conveyed, to watch them put on a world-class
show, full of colored lights, glitter and puffs of smoke. That was
all it took to make Russia's 30- and 40-somethings feel they had at
long last shared an experience that their generation the world over
has taken for granted: a chance to see the Stones, live and in
concert.
</P>
<P>
   So what's 30 years? Nothing if in the end you can get what you
want.
</P>
<P>
   _ By CELESTINE BOHLEN &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Popcorn, Peanuts and Valentino
</P>
<P>
   Baseball traditionalists will tell you that fans come to ball
parks for the pastoral experience, the clout of a mighty home run,
an intense face-off between a flame-throwing righthander and a
Bunyanesque hitter or the work ethic of a player who never sits out
a game.
</P>
<P>
   But baseball owners have discovered yet another lure: Beanie
Babies. Teams that give away the cuddly bean-bag animals with names
like Peanut, Glory and Valentino have found that these little toys
possess the awesome power to produce sellouts nearly every time
they're offered.
</P>
<P>
   Ty Inc., the Beanies' manufacturer, never planned for its
animals, which are sold at specialty retailers, to become baseball
giveaways. A Chicago Cubs marketing executive, curious about one of
his daughter's Beanies, Cubbie the bear, persuaded Ty to plunge
into baseball.
</P>
<P>
   When 23,000 Valentinos (he's a bear) were given away at Yankee
Stadium in May, 49,820 people showed up. The Beanies, and their new
owners, watched the Yankees' David Wells pitch a perfect game. And
when Stretch the ostrich was given away last Sunday, the House that
Ruth Built drew 55,911.
</P>
<P>
   The Beanies have become so valuable _ collectors have priced
Peanut the blue elephant, now discontinued, as high as $5,200 _
that teams need extra security to guard them. Not even Mark
McGwire, who may break Roger Maris' single season home run record
of 61, is guarded as such precious cargo.
</P>
<P>
   By RICHARD SANDOMIR &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
