<HEADLINE>
BESTSELLERS: PAPERBACK BOOKS
</HEADLINE>
  (For release on Sunday, Aug. 23.) 
(Eds: This file is the abbreviated bestseller list for paperback
books. Please see BESTSELLERS-PAPER-L-NYT for the full version that
includes how many weeks each book has been on the list and where
the book stood the previous week.) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rankings reflect sales figures for the week ending Aug. 8, 1998,
at almost 4,000 bookstores plus wholesalers serving 60,000 other
retailers, statistically weighted to represent sales in all such
outlets nationwide. The number of titles within the two
subdivisions of non-fiction can change from week to week,
reflecting changes in book buying.
</P>
<P>
   An (x) following a book's ranking indicates that a book's sales
are barely distinguishable from those of the book above. A (b)
indicates that some bookstores report receiving bulk orders for a
book.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. DIVINE SECRETS OF THE YA-YA SISTERHOOD, by Rebecca Wells.
</P>
<P>
   (Harper Perennial, $13.50.) Three generations of
</P>
<P>
   Southern women.
</P>
<P>
   2. RISING TIDES, by Nora Roberts. (Jove, $7.50.) Returning
</P>
<P>
   to his home on the Maryland shore, a man finds a new love
</P>
<P>
   and hope for the future.
</P>
<P>
   3. THE BEST LAID PLANS, by Sidney Sheldon. (Warner, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   The relationship between a power-hungry governor and a beautiful
</P>
<P>
   woman determined to wreak revenge.
</P>
<P>
   4. THE NOTEBOOK, by Nicholas Sparks. (Warner Vision, $5.99.)
</P>
<P>
   A World War II veteran meets an old flame who is
</P>
<P>
   about to be married.
</P>
<P>
   5. PETALS ON THE RIVER, Kathleen E. Woodiwiss. (Avon, $6.99
</P>
<P>
   An Englishwoman finds love with a widower in 18th-century
Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   6. SHE'S COME UNDONE, by Wall Lamb. (Pocket, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   A woman's harrowing progress from youth to middle age.
</P>
<P>
   7.(x) UNNATURAL EXPOSURE, by Patricia Cornwell. (Berkley,
$7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Kay Scarpetta contends with a killer who uses smallpox-like
</P>
<P>
   virus and cyberspace tricks.
</P>
<P>
   8.THE GOD OF SMALL THINGS, by Arundhati Roy. (Harper
</P>
<P>
   Perennial, $13.) Death and secrets haunt a once-prosperous
</P>
<P>
   family in India.
</P>
<P>
   9. DETECTIVE, by Arthur Hailey. (Berkley, $7.99.) A serial
</P>
<P>
   killer's confession leads a Miami cop into an investigation
</P>
<P>
   of powerful political figures.
</P>
<P>
   10. THE MATARESE CONNECTION, by Robert Ludlum. (Bantam,
</P>
<P>
   $7.99.) A CIA officer struggles to thwart the return
</P>
<P>
   of an international cabal.
</P>
<P>
   11. LITTLE ALTARS EVERYWHERE, by Rebecca Wells. (Harper
</P>
<P>
   Perennial, $13.) An account of earlier experiences of
</P>
<P>
   members of the Ya-Ya sisterhood, first published in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   12. POWER OF A WOMAN, by Barbara Taylor Bradford. (Harper
</P>
<P>
   Paperbacks, $7.50.) A businesswoman struggles with her
</P>
<P>
   past after her daughter is the victim of violence.
</P>
<P>
   13. ORPHANS: BUTTERFLY and CRYSTAL, by V.C. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   (Pocket, $3.99.) A troubled orphan is adopted by
</P>
<P>
   a couple who hope she will become a ballerina.
</P>
<P>
   14.(x) THE HORSE WHISPERER, by Nicholas Evans. (Dell, $7.50.)
</P>
<P>
   A woman seeks solace for her daughter and their horse from
</P>
<P>
   a wrangler.
</P>
<P>
   15. UP ISLAND, by Anne Rivers Siddons. (Harper Paperbacks,
</P>
<P>
   $6.99.) An Atlanta woman, after a bad marriage and the death
</P>
<P>
   of her mother, seeks a new life in Martha's Vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NON-FICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. THE PERFECT STORM, by Sebastian Junger. (Harper Paperbacks,
</P>
<P>
   $6.99.) The story of the nor'easter of 1991, focusing on a
</P>
<P>
   crew of fishermen from Gloucester, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   2. INTO THIN AIR, by Jon Krakauer. (Anchor/Doubleday, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   A journalist's account of his ascent on Mount Everest
</P>
<P>
   in 1996, the deadliest season in history.
</P>
<P>
   3. UNDER THE TUSCAN SUN, by Frances Mayes.
</P>
<P>
   (Broadway, $13.) A celebration of life in the
</P>
<P>
   Italian countryside by an American poet.
</P>
<P>
   4. INTO THE WILD, by Jon Krakauer. (Anchor/Doubleday, $12.95.)
</P>
<P>
   The story of a young man whose obsession
</P>
<P>
   with the wilderness had a tragic end in Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   5. THE CLIMB, by Anatoli Boukreev and G. Weston DeWalt.
</P>
<P>
   (St. Martin's, $6.99.) Another account of the 1996
</P>
<P>
   Mount Everest disaster.
</P>
<P>
   6. THE COLOR OF WATER, by James McBride. (Riverhead, $12.)
</P>
<P>
   A black writer and musician recalls his experiences growing
</P>
<P>
   up with his white mother in a Brooklyn, N.Y., housing project.
</P>
<P>
   7. A CHILD CALLED ``IT,'' by Dave Pelzer.
</P>
<P>
   (Health Communications, $9.95.) The autobiography
</P>
<P>
   of a man who survived his mother's abuse.
</P>
<P>
   8. BRAIN DROPPINGS, by George Carlin. (Hyperion, $10.95.)
</P>
<P>
   Comments on life and the ways of the world by the stand-up
</P>
<P>
   comedian.
</P>
<P>
   9.(x) PERSONAL HISTORY, by Katharine Graham. (Vintage, $15.)
</P>
<P>
   The autobiography of the former publisher of The Washington
</P>
<P>
   Post and capital grande dame.
</P>
<P>
   10. A CIVIL ACTION, by Jonathan Harr. (Vintage, $13.)
</P>
<P>
   A lawsuit against industrial polluters. (b)
</P>
<P>
   11. WAIT TILL NEXT YEAR, by Doris Kearns Goodwin. (Touchstone/
</P>
<P>
   S&AMP;S, $13.) Recollections of a '50s girlhood on Long Island, in
</P>
<P>
   the orbit of the Brooklyn Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   12. UNDAUNTED COURAGE, by Stephen E. Ambrose. (Touchstone/
</P>
<P>
   S&AMP;S, $16.) Lewis and Clark's exploration of the West.
</P>
<P>
   13. THE LOST BOY, by Dave Pelzer. (Health Communications,
</P>
<P>
   $10.95.) The author of ``A Child Called `It' '' recalls
</P>
<P>
   life at a series of foster homes.
</P>
<P>
   14. FEAR AND LOATHING IN LAS VEGAS, by Hunter S. Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   (Vintage, $11.) The gonzo journalist's 1971 account of a
</P>
<P>
   drug-addled road trip.
</P>
<P>
   15.(x) NAKED, by David Sedaris. (Back Bay/Little Brown, $12.95.)
</P>
<P>
   Autobiographical comic essays whose subjects include the
</P>
<P>
   author's family and a nudist trailer park.
</P>
<P>
   16. (x) D-DAY, June 6, 1944, by Stephen E. Ambrose.
</P>
<P>
   (Touchstone/S&AMP;S, $16.) An account of the Allied invasion
</P>
<P>
   of Normandy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ADVICE, HOW-TO, AND MISCELLANEOUS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. DR. ATKINS' NEW DIET REVOLUTION, by Robert C. Atkins.
</P>
<P>
   (Avon, $6.50.) Ways to lose weight and achieve a healthy body.
(b)
</P>
<P>
   2. DON'T SWEAT THE SMALL STUFF ... AND IT'S ALL SMALL STUFF,
</P>
<P>
   by Richard Carlson. (Hyperion, $8.95.) How to enjoy life
</P>
<P>
   more and contribute to the world we live in. (b)
</P>
<P>
   3. PROTEIN POWER, by Michael R. Eades and Mary Dan Eades.
</P>
<P>
   (Bantam, $6.50.) Two physicians offer a protein-rich, low-
</P>
<P>
   carbohydrate plan for losing weight.
</P>
<P>
   4. DON'T SWEAT THE SMALL STUFF WITH YOUR FAMILY, by Richard
</P>
<P>
   Carlson. (Hyperion, $11.95.) How to improve one's family life.
(b)
</P>
