<HEADER>
A6972 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-SEAFARING-BOOKS-REV     08-17 1129
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-SEAFARING-BOOKS-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
15.) 
 BOOKS ABOUT SEAFARING GAIN IN POPULARITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing. Originally filed on Saturday, August (The Week in Review)  
 (ART ADV: Graphic decribing various types of sailing vessels, past
and present, is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By DOREEN CARVAJAL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like an armada of tall ships, tales of the sea are sailing onto
bookshelves.
</P>
<P>
   There are salty soap operas featuring sensitive mariners drawn
to the high seas to heal marital heartbreak or cope with terminal
disease. There are manly memoirs and survival books by Alaskan crab
fishermen and Antarctic explorers. For hard-core nautical buffs
there are handsome books on maritime arcana and history, like the
recent ``Safeguard of the Sea: A Naval History of Britain,
660-1649,'' by N.A.M. Rodger (W.W. Norton, 1998).
</P>
<P>
   And then there are recycled classics like C.S. Forester's
swashbuckling Horatio Hornblower adventures and more obscure novels
like ``The Black Ship,'' a 1963 work by Dudley Pope about a bloody
mutiny aboard the HMS Hermione in 1797.
</P>
<P>
   What is it about the siren call of the sea that makes readers
want to thumb through a ``cookery book'' like ``Lobscouse &AMP; Spotted
Dog'' (Norton, 1998) for recipes for sweetbreads in malmsey,
spotted dog (an eggy custard tinged with rosewater) and other
18th-century galley fare?
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the answer, there is enough money in seafaring
literature these days to prompt a host of trade publishers to cash
in. The boom has been driven mainly by Norton's success with
Patrick O'Brian's series of historical seafaring novels following
the exploits of Jack Aubrey and Stephen Maturin, and ``The Perfect
Storm,'' Sebastian Junger's 1997 nonfiction best-seller about the
destruction of a swordfishing boat by a violent Atlantic
nor'easter.
</P>
<P>
   Such imitation in publishing is as basic as paper. Publishing
houses are simply observing a cherished and fundamental ritual of
the trade: Follow the wake of popular books with titles in every
possible permutation till the boom goes bust. Sometimes the
publishing pack is hungry for memoirs of dysfunction and anorexia;
in other cases it's mystery books mixed with cooking recipes or
titles by new-age authors with direct lines to God.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're playing follow the leader here,'' said Starling
Lawrence, editor in chief of Norton. There are more than 3 million
copies of the 18 Aubrey-Maturin books in print, Lawrence noted,
with the next installment, ``The Hundred Days,'' to be published in
October.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence sees little evidence that the public hunger for naval
literature has been sated. He said several publishers were prepared
to pay a seven-figure advance this summer for a manuscript about
the 1820 wreck of a whaling ship by a whale. But before the auction
could take place, Penguin Putnam placed a preemptive bid of more
than $1 million for the book, ``In the Heart of the Sea,'' a
true-life adventure that inspired ``Moby Dick.'' (Penguin has also
found modest success with a more contemporary adventure, ``Sea
Change,'' which mixes memoir, wounded heart and Atlantic
adventure.)
</P>
<P>
   ``You had several publishers willing to take a huge bet,''
Lawrence said. ``This may represent some kind of high-water folly _
I don't know _ or it may just be the smart money chasing the next
boom.''
</P>
<P>
   Other publishing houses are trolling for titles in used
bookstores. Merritt Communications _ a Connecticut company best
known for magazines like Tomorrow's Pharmacist _ has rolled out a
new imprint called Capstan Press, which will publish golden oldies
like Jack London's ``Cruise of the Snark'' and ``Northern Lights,''
a 1927 nonfiction account of a potato lugger that sailed into a
raging Atlantic storm.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Holt &AMP; Co., with its new Heart of Oaks Sea Classics
series, recently reissued ``Peter Simple,'' an 1832 novel by
Frederick Marryat, a former Royal Navy captain, and ``Dr. Dogbody's
Leg,'' a 1940 collection of short stories by James Norman Hall
featuring a peg-legged narrator.
</P>
<P>
   Dean King, editor of Heart of Oaks Sea Classics, said he got the
idea for the series when he found ``Dr. Dogbody's Leg'' at the
bottom of a pile of books in the Argosy bookstore in New York. He
had already written two successful companion guides for O'Brian's
series that together have sold more than 125,000 copies for Holt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's face it, life is lived more vicariously these days,''
King said. ``We spend our time on computers and phone lines. We
have very specialized and narrowly focused skills that are often
far removed from our physical lives.''
</P>
<P>
   The attraction of sea literature is the conflict of ``man versus
nature,'' he added. ``I think we long for that interaction with our
natural world.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the popularity of nautical literature has yet to lead
to full-scale sea battle reenactments, it has inspired readers to
develop some exotic pursuits. King, for example, took a voyage to
Bermuda in June with a group of other O'Brian fans aboard the HMS
Rose, a 30-gun frigate that is a replica of a 1750s British ship
that was stationed in North America. The same frigate had been used
earlier this summer to stage a sumptuous meal for sea literature
aficionados like William F. Buckley Jr. and Walter Cronkite.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brian's devoted following includes Paul LeClerc, president of
the New York Public Library, and U.S. Supreme Court Justice Anthony
M. Kennedy. LeClerc said O'Brian ``succeeds in creating a whole
world out of language that is exotic, mystifying and enthralling
and addictive.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, like LeClerc, is not a sailor, but his reading material
has ranged from O'Brian's books to ``The Perfect Storm'' to ``The
Ordinary Seaman,'' a recent novel by Francisco Goldman about
Central American sailors stranded aboard a rat-infested cargo ship
docked outside New York. The appeal of such books, Kennedy said,
has to do with the ocean as a ``metaphor for our own existence.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have our liberty to succeed or fail, but in another sense
our fate is controlled by unseen sources,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Sir Edmund Hillary, who conquered Mount Everest in 1953,
best understood the enduring fascination of sea literature.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1976 forward to ``Shackleton's Boat Journey,'' the memoir
of a frostbitten 1914-1916 Antarctica expedition that has just been
reissued by Norton, Hillary wondered how the ``hard men of today
with their fancy equipment and `instant rescue' by radio and
helicopter would have survived under such conditions?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Danger is one thing,'' he wrote, ``but danger plus extreme
discomfort for long periods is quite another.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
