<DOCNO> NYT19980817.0090 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-17 10:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7013 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT     08-17 1083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS TRY TO PASS AS GREEN _ FOR VOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: Charles Levendosky, editorial page editor of the
Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune, has a national reputation for First
Amendment commentary. His e-mail address is
levendos(AT-sign)trib.com.)  
(gm) 
 By CHARLES LEVENDOSKY   
 c. 1998 Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Republicans and Democrats in the U.S. House are sparring about
who is more environmentally friendly. It's a paper tussle _ carried
out with feuding reports during an election season. Their words are
really aimed at voters.
</P>
<P>
   Public opinion polls consistently show that approximately 70
percent of Americans want the environment and wilderness areas
protected.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans began the public relations duel. On July 15, the
House Policy Committee, chaired by Rep. Christopher Cox, R-Calif.,
issued a report claiming that Republicans deserve recognition for
an ``historic record of environmental accomplishment.''
</P>
<P>
   The report gives the GOP credit for passing what it calls two
major environmental bills: the Tropical Forest Conservation Act
(H.R. 2870) and the Sonny Bono Memorial Salton Sea Reclamation Act
(H.R. 3267). The report states they are ``two new wins for the
environment.''
</P>
<P>
   More spin than win. The self-congratulatory GOP report fudges on
both of its key boasts.
</P>
<P>
   The Tropical Forest Conservation Act allows developing countries
to swap portions of their debts to the United States in exchange
for tropical forest conservation. The bill won the endorsement of
the World Wildlife Fund and the Sierra Club and passed both houses
of Congress. On July 29, President Clinton signed the bill into
law.
</P>
<P>
   It is a good piece of environmental legislation _ trouble is,
the GOP can't really accept applause for its passage. Only 161
House Republicans voted for the bill with 60 against, while 194
House Democrats voted for passage with only one nay.
</P>
<P>
   The Salton Sea Reclamation Act, introduced by Duncan Hunter,
R-Calif., passed the House by a mere 21 votes and is stalled in the
Senate. For good reason. No major environmental group supported the
House version of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   It's a hasty bill that short-cuts scientific research, the Clean
Water Act, and judicial review.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate has its own version of the bill (S. 1716), introduced
by the two Democratic senators from California, Barbara Boxer and
Dianne Feinstein. Their bill is scientifically sensitive and gained
the endorsement of the National Audubon Society and other
environmental groups.
</P>
<P>
   The bills were designed to reclaim the Salton Sea which formed
in 1905 when a levee broke and the Colorado River flowed in the
Salton trough about 130 miles east of San Diego. It's a landlocked
body of water that is now threatened by gradually increasing
salinity and industrial pollutants. The briny sea is beginning to
take its toll of fish, birds and other wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   Legislation is needed, but not the House bill.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a month after the GOP issued its report, Democrats
fired back.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 6, Rep. George Miller, D-Calif., and the Democratic
staff of the House Committee on Resources issued a response
entitled ``The Great Republican Environmental P.R. Campaign'' which
calls the report a publicity stunt ``designed to `greenwash' the
press and the public.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller condemns the GOP report as a ``decoy for
anti-environmental riders'' that have been attached to recent
appropriations bills: ``Hidden in the VA-HUD, Interior, and
Commerce appropriations bills pending before Congress are riders
that will gut public health and environmental protections _ just
like the highly controversial Republican riders of the 104th
Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic parry and thrust has its own false footing. The
Miller report criticizes the GOP for undercutting the National
Parks, but completely ignores ``Vision 2020 National Parks
Restoration Act'' authored by Sen. Craig Thomas, R-Wyo. The
national parks bill passed the Senate by unanimous consent and is
now being considered in the House Resources Committee.
</P>
<P>
   This bill would strengthen National Parks and provide means for
protecting these beloved natural resources.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Miller report is deadly accurate when it points to
the numerous anti-environmental riders attached to appropriations
bills by Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Riders to both the House and the Senate version of the
Departments of Veterans Affairs and Housing and Urban Development
Appropriations Act (VA-HUD) severely limit the number of
toxicological profiles that can be taken at hazardous substance
Superfund sites. These profiles are used to gauge acceptable levels
of exposure to pollutants found at these sites.
</P>
<P>
   The VA-HUD appropriations bills delay cleanup of PCBs in the
Hudson River and other rivers around the nation and cut funding for
cleaning up old, vacated industrial urban areas.
</P>
<P>
   GOP riders to the Department of the Interior Appropriations Act
cut funding to the National Park Service, the Bureau of Land
Management, and the Fish and Wildlife Service. They subsidize more
logging and logging roads. They end the Interior Columbia Basin
Ecosystem Management Plan that was designed to improve the
management of 72 million acres of BLM and Forest Service lands and
allows projects that could jeopardize the ecosystem to go forward.
</P>
<P>
   The House version of the Interior appropriations bill mandates a
road to be built through Alaska's Chugach National Forest and
across the Copper River Delta, one of the nation's largest wetlands
and waterfowl feeding areas. The GOP rider waives all environmental
review and public hearings.
</P>
<P>
   A GOP rider to the House version also opens 75 acres of
Florida's coastline to development and removes them from the
Coastal Barrier Resources System. These coastal barriers are
nesting areas for sea turtles and other threatened and endangered
species. The area is also prone to hurricane destruction.
Development in these 75 acres would now be eligible for federal
subsidies and taxpayer dollars when buildings and settlements are
destroyed by wind and sea.
</P>
<P>
   When amendments were offered to soften the worst
anti-environmental riders, the tally of votes told a sad tale.
According to the Miller report, of seven key pro-environmental
amendments, on average, only 17 percent of the Republicans in the
House voted for their passage.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Party should blush red for pretending to be
green.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
