A7058 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN19-CO     08-17 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: You gotta believe _ not!
 &HT;    (For release Aug. 19, 1998)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ever so slowly, at a steady but glacier-like pace, everything
seemingly believable becomes unbelievable. Even the stories that
render other stories implausible become implausible themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, a psychologist in San Francisco made it known
that tape recordings that he stuffed into his desk 25 years ago and
forgot about show that the incredible 1973 book about the
multi-personality Sybil (she led 16 different existences at the
same time) was a sham.
</P>
<P>
   A susceptible Sybil was responding to suggestions by her
psychiatrist rather than inquiries, says Dr. Robin Rieber of the
John Jay College of Criminal Justice in New York. Both the
psychiatrist and the author of the book are dead, so we can't hear
from them.
</P>
<P>
   Or can we?
</P>
<P>
   Anything is believable _ and unbelievable.
</P>
<P>
   How many Americans will swear to you that Elvis is alive? Did
Shirley McLaine have anything to do with the French Revolution? And
was it really a hired actor, imitating Winston Churchill's voice,
who spoke the words over radio that stirred the British people
against overwhelming odds in the early days of WWII?
</P>
<P>
   And let's not forget that despite the eyewitness accounts of
conquering armies, the surviving victims, and miles of newsreel
film and paperwork, there are some who don't believe there was a
Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   Another revision: Many years after the publication of Merle
Miller's ``Plain Speaking,'' the highly-regarded oral biography of
Harry Truman, it was termed a fraud by two Truman scholars. Truman
never said much of what Miller said he said, they contended. Of
course, this did not come out until after both Truman and Miller
were dead.
</P>
<P>
   So, there's no qualified debate, just as there can not be any on
the Sybil issue; that is, unless Ms. McLaine once was one of
Sybil's 16 personalities and can help us out.
</P>
<P>
   While Dr. Rieber would have us accept that the tapes he
possesses document that Sybil's story was infused with suggestions
by her psychiatrist _ thus creating the multiple personalities _
what are we to think of Dr. Rieber himself?
</P>
<P>
   Could he have been the inspiration for the Disney flick ``The
Absent-Minded Professor''? Do we accept at face value Dr. Rieber's
story that he had these tapes in his drawer for 25 years and simply
forgot about them?
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Rieber, who says he got the tapes from ``Sybil'' author
Flora Rheta Schreiber, contends there was no malice intended by
either Schreiber or the attending psychiatrist, Dr. Cornelia
Wilbur. They were not totally aware that the story they were
telling was wrong, Dr. Rieber said. ``Yet, at the same time, they
wished to believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the way Aesop did things; also the columnist from the
Boston Globe. (No, not the George Carlin plagiarizer, the other
one.)
</P>
<P>
   Unearthing the Sybil tapes, and Dr. Rieber's interpretation of
them, also will renew skepticism about the 1950s reincarnation
story of Bridey Murphy. Unlike Sybil, who was living 16 lives
concurrently, Virginia Tighe _ under hypnosis _ conjured past
lives, including a 19th century Bridey Murphy of Cork, Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   I say it can renew skepticism because ``The Skeptic's
Dictionary,'' by Robert Todd Carroll, a professor of philosophy at
Sacramento City College, already tagged it as a phony. Carroll says
the Chicago American (now deceased, but you never can be sure of
these things) found a Bridey Murphy Corkell lived in a house in
Chicago across from where Virginia Tighe lived as a child _ no past
life, just a confused childhood.
</P>
<P>
   Everything, everyone is under the spotlight of revisionism and
rediscovery.
</P>
<P>
   One only can imagine what will be the prevailing thoughts about
Clinton/Lewinsky 50 or so years from now.
</P>
<P>
   Someone probably will claim Monica was a Hammas operative, or
some vague medical evidence will appear that Clinton was impotent,
both inside and outside the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing should surprise us any more, or make us believe.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
