<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Monday, Aug. 17, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Tuesday. If you have questions, call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   O'HAIR-MISSING (San Antonio) _ Atheist Madalyn Murray O'Hair was
an American cultural icon when she disappeared in 1995 along with
her two adult children and a half-million dollars in gold coins.
Danny Fry vanished at the same time. One case became a Great
American Mystery, the other a forensic footnote. By JOHN
MacCORMACK.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   YIP-COLUMN (Undated) _ In these times of stock market turmoil,
the inclination is to go for what is the greatest, hottest stock _
a brand-name stock with a kick-butt track record. Resist the urge,
particularly now that the market is in a bad mood. By PAMELA YIP
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ A reader wants to know how to help her
blue butterfly bush (Clerodendrum ugandense), which is kept in a
container. Q&AMP;A. By KATHY HUBER
</P>
<P>
   UKRAINIAN-ART (San Antonio) _ Golden treasures of the ancient
Scythians, rarely seen outside Ukraine, will make their U.S. debut
at the San Antonio Museum of Art in a major national touring
exhibit scheduled for November 1999. ``Scythian Gold: Treasures
from Ancient Ukraine'' will feature 165 objects dating from the
fifth to third centuries B.C. By DAN R. GODDARD.
</P>
<P>
   DI-ANNIVERSARY (San Francisco) _ Many media outlets are planning
fresh tributes to Princess Diana as the Aug. 31 anniversary of her
death approaches. By DAVID ARMSTRONG.
</P>
<P>
   ANTI-GAY-AD (San Francisco) _ San Francisco's gay community
criticizes a newspaper ad sponsored by a group that claims it can
cure gays and lesbians of homosexuality. That ad features a
photograph of about 100 smiling men and women described as
``ex-gays'' and offers to help homosexuals change their orientation
through faith. By JIM HERRON ZAMORA.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-PROFILE-MACBETH (New York) _ Joe Gagen, 58, has done
industrial and corporate videos before, and as a lifelong film buff
he has long dreamed of producing ``something tangible ... something
that maybe people could enjoy and get sustenance from.'' What he is
producing in the urban jungle of New York is the independent film
``Macbeth in Manhattan.'' By AMY BIANCOLLI.
</P>
<P>
   ELVIS-ANNIVERSARY (San Francisco) _ If Elvis Presley had lived,
he would be 63. But if he had lived, hundreds of would-be authors
would find no buyer for their books, thousands of Elvis
impersonators would find no outlet for their pain, there would be
no ``I Brake for Elvis'' bumper stickers and no arguments over
whether the King was reading ``Sex and Psychic Energy'' or ``The
Scientific Search for the Face of Jesus'' at the time of his death.
By EDVINS BEITIKS.
</P>
<P>
   NOT-WOODSTOCK (Bethel, N.Y.) _ A Day in the Garden _ actually
three days of rock music _ on the site of the original 1969
Woodstock festival, has generated a cultural critical mass of its
own. Though it has drawn a fraction of the 400,000 people who
flooded Max Yasgur's farm for the concert 29 years ago and fewer
than the 30,000 promoters had hoped for on Saturday, a sense of
optimism and accomplishment abounded in the countryside. By
ELIZABETH BENJAMIN.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-TREMAIN-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``The way I found her'' by Rose
Tremain is a stylish, entertaining novel about a 13-year-old boy
who is smitten by an ``older woman'' and must turn sleuth when
she's kidnapped. By BARBARA LISS.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLUMN (Undated) _ Fitness Magazine's newly released
survey of ``diet-damaging regional delicacies'' really _ ahem _
takes the cake. What's the point of traveling if we can't fully
immerse ourselves in a destination's culture? Cuisine included. By
HARRY SHATTUCK
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-LOS-ANGELES (Undated) _ Bill Walsh is still intrigued by the
gaping maw of the Los Angeles market, celebrating its fourth year
of NFL-free living and showing no signs of moral, economic or
vitamin deficiency. He still sees the possibilities of unlimited
wealth for the lucky swine who gets in first with a team, a
building and a plan to un-jade the most encrusted sports fans in
America. By RAY RATTO.
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOORS-COLUMN (Castle Rock, Wash.) _ After climbing 4,500 feet
through forest, over and around boulders and finally across a steep
snowfield, your last steps take you to the rim of the Mount St.
Helens volcano. The view is electrifying. By TOM STIENSTRA.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ President Clinton's troubles are
private stuff, right? Sure. If, that is, you want to kiss goodbye
to enforcing sexual harassment laws, if you want bosses to lie with
impunity in these cases, regardless of the evidence. That's the
price of privacy in matters like this. By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
<P>
   FILIPINO-VETS (San Francisco) _ Everyone wants to save Private
Ryan. No one wants to save Private Felizardo Ticao. He's Filipino.
He's one of those heroes no one seems to give a damn about. In a
few short years, he's likely to die, our debt to him unsettled. By
EMIL GUILLERMO.
</P>
<P>
   PETE-WILSON (Sacramento, Calif.) _ The record on Pete Wilson's
eight years as governor and California policy-maker is now all but
closed. Unless something totally unexpected occurs in the next few
months, it's a record in which negative strokes of politics, though
often successful, are likely to be more memorable than the positive
acts of policy. By PETER SCHRAG.
</P>
<P>
   ROSENFELD-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ The flap at The Boston Globe
over different punishments meted out to two transgressing
columnists, one a black female, the other a white male, illustrates
how race impacts what otherwise might have been just another
dispute over journalistic standards. By HARRY ROSENFELD.
</P>
<P>
   ROBISON-COLUMN (Austin, Texas) _ Summer may have another month
to run _ according to the calendar and the thermometer _ but it has
effectively ended for millions of Texas children and their parents
because school bells already are ringing. Believe it or not,
classes even began Aug. 3 in San Antonio. What's going on here? By
CLAY ROBISON
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
