<HEADER>
A7140 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAMES-DOOHAN-LOOKS-BA     08-17 1471
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAMES-DOOHAN-LOOKS-BACK-ON-HIS-D-DAY-EXPERIENCES-STARBEAT-ART-NY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TSF 
 `SCOTTY' PRAISES SPIELBERG FOR `SAVING PRIVATE RYAN' 
</HEADLINE>
 (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of James Doohan as Scotty in ``Star Trek.'' 
 By JERRY TALLMER  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    James Doohan can sympathize with the mother in ``Saving Private
Ryan,'' who collapses upon seeing a military car approaching her
house with apparent news of death.
 &HT;    Doohan, best known as ``Scotty'' in ``Star Trek,'' served in
D-Day with the Canadian forces and was injured so badly he was
shipped to England to recover. Watching the scene where the mother
learns the news, Doohan couldn't help but think of his own mother.
 &HT;    He was so moved he dropped a note to director Steven Spielberg
that began: ``Dear Mr. Spielberg, You know me as Scotty ... '' and
went on from there with a few words of praise and thanks for that
stunning motion picture. (Doohan is not alone. In its first 17
days, the film topped the $100 million mark.)
 &HT;    ``To tell the honest truth,'' Doohan says of the note some weeks
later, ``I suffered through the first 25 minutes of the movie'' _ a
ferocious re-enactment of the American landing on Omaha Beach, on
D-Day, June 6, 1944.
 &HT;    ``When I wrote Spielberg I told him I'd landed on Juno on
D-Day'' _ Juno Beach, the Canadian landing site _ ``which was
nothing as horrid as the Omaha disaster.'' Not horrid, perhaps, but
bad enough.
 &HT;    He and his men landed unscathed on Juno, and fought their way
successfully into the Normandy peninsula as far as the town of
Courseulles that first day. But Artillery Lt. James Doohan of D
Company, Winnipeg Rifles, 13th Field Regiment, Royal Canadian Army,
ended up just before midnight plugged by eight German bullets.
 &HT;    Four hit his left knee, three took out the middle finger of his
right hand and one was deflected from killing him by the
Sterling-silver cigarette case in the breast pocket of his jacket.
``I still have that cigarette case today,'' the husky 78-year-old
Doohan says through his walrus moustache, shooting his eyebrows.
 &HT;    You know him as Scotty _ Chief Engineer Montgomery Scott of the
Federation starship ``U.S.S. Enterprise'' _ as does everybody who
went around saying: ``Beam me up, Scotty.'' Doohan portrayed the
character in the 79 episodes of tv's ``Star Trek'' from 1966 to
1969, and reprised the role in seven ``Star Trek'' movies.
 &HT;    Actually, he insists, the exact line was ```Beam me up, Mr.
Scott.' The fans made it `Beam me up, Scotty.'''
 &HT;    And the line that Scotty kept having to repeat to Capt. Kirk
(William Shatner) was: ``Captain, my engines just can't take it.''
 &HT;    Doohan is not a Scot. He was ``conceived in Northern Ireland,
born in Vancouver, British Columbia, grew up in Ioco, B.C., a town
named for the Imperial Oil Company,'' and his blood is mostly or
entirely Irish.
 &HT;    It was when, as an actor with 20 years' experience, he was
auditioning for ``Star Trek'' in 1965 _ ``reading a girl's part in
eight different accents, because I could do any accent'' _ that he
was asked by ``Star Trek'' creator Gene Roddenberry which of those
accents he preferred.
 &HT;    ```Well,' I said, `if I'm to be an engineer, it had better be as
a Scotsman, because they make the best engineers,'' Doohan says.
``And then I named him Montgomery Scott, right off the top of my
head, in honor of my grandfather, my mother's father, James
Montgomery.''
 &HT;    On D-Day, the grandson of James Montgomery was in charge of an
LCA (Landing Craft, Assault) carrying 33 beach commandos, engineers
and signalmen.
 &HT;    ``We were supposed to hit the beach at 7 a.m.,'' Doohan says,
``but a torpedo boat cut across our bow saying by loudspeaker:
`H-Hour postponed 30 minutes,' because _ we didn't know it then _
the bombers were supposed to have decimated the shore, but the
clouds were too low for the bombers. So that didn't happen.
 &HT;    ``We landed safely, thank God, through those Y-shaped steel
barriers you see in the film, tracer bullets, all that, none of our
men hurt, and dashed 75 yards to the 7-foot-tall dunes,'' Doohan
says.
 &HT;    ``Crossed a minefield, found out about it later, it was meant to
blow up tanks and we weren't heavy enough. Moved up through a town
_ hardly a town, just a village _ called Graye sur mer, saw a
church tower that was a machine gun post, firing off to our left.''
 &HT;    Doohan took out the machine gun post with a couple of shots. ``I
don't know if they were killed or wounded, but it shut them up,''
he says. His unit brought up its artillery pieces, 24 American
105mm guns, and by then it was nightfall.
 &HT;    Early in ``Saving Private Ryan,'' the scene that moved Doohan
was of the car approaching the house in which the four Ryan
brothers _ three of them already dead _ grew up.
 &HT;    We see the scene from behind the mother _ see it as she sees it
from her porch, knowing, as she knows, without having to be told,
that the car is carrying official news of death.
 &HT;    As an Army officer and a chaplain get out, she sinks to a squat
of misery on the porch. ``When my wife Wende and I saw the movie at
a theater in Redmond, Washington _ a Microsoft town _ near where we
live, that was the thing that brought tears to my eyes, a couple of
them,'' Doohan says.
 &HT;    ``That car coming toward the mother of those Ryan boys, and her
knees giving way. All I could think of was my own mother.''
 &HT;    His mother was told that German bullets had hit him at 11:30
p.m. on D-Day as he was returning from a forward gun position. He
walked a quarter-mile _ ``the adrenaline lets you do it'' _ to the
regimental aid post, Doohan says.
 &HT;    He knew about his right hand and the whack on his chest against
that cigarette case, but that was all. ``The medic said: `You also
have four bullets in your left knee.' I said: `Well, I walked
here.'''
 &HT;    He didn't walk much more. They shot him full of morphine,
transported him to an landing ship tank that took him to a ship
``with 15 layers of bunks, and medics acting like Tarzan, swinging
from one layer to another.''
 &HT;    Patched back together in Britain at a Canadian wartime hospital,
he ended the war as a budding air-observation officer with 93 hours
flight training in a tiny Tiger Moth.
 &HT;    You might even call it sort of a rough preparation for ``Star
Trek,'' in as much as ``at a little aerdrome in Holland I got the
reputation as the craziest pilot in the Canadian Air Force,
slaloming an Auster monoplane under telephone wires at 55 miles an
hour _ I'm talking about dipping my wings into wheat!'' Doohan
says.
 &HT;    He got into acting in 1946 by way of listening to ``the worst
radio drama I had ever heard,'' on station CFPL, London, Ontario.
``So I got some Shakespeare and other stuff and went down to CFPL
to make a recording,'' Doohan says. ``When I played it back, I
thought it was awful, but the guy there said: `No, that was
good.'''
 &HT;    Doohan's first professional performance was Jan. 12, 1946, ``a
50-minute show between me and a taxi driver, for which we each got
$12.'' Two years of acting school followed at New York City's
Neighborhood Playhouse _ in classes with such actors as Tony
Randall and Richard Boone.
 &HT;    The break into tv was as a detective on William Gargan's
``Martin Kane, Private Eye.'' Doohan, considered ``Canada's busiest
actor'' by the time he auditioned for ``Star Trek,'' has done a lot
of acting since.
 &HT;    His next role is in Canada starring as an English butler in a
movie called ``Duke.'' But before that, he's been touring the
United States this summer in a promotional role ``Scotty'' would no
doubt find suited for the next generation.
 &HT;    He's been spokesperson for Philips Electronics in its
sponsorship of a Harris Corp./PBS road show touting the future of
High Definition Television.
 &HT;    Beam me up, Scotty ... I mean, Mr. Scott.
 c.1998 Jerry Tallmer  
