<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KATIE-HOLMES-IN-DAWSON'S-CREEK-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BUSY KATIE HOLMES GEARS UP FOR SECOND SEASON IN `DAWSON'S
CREEK' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Katie Holmes in a scene from ``Disturbing
Behavior.'' 
 By DAVID KRONKE  
 c.1998 TV Guide (Canada)  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Katie Holmes and Kevin Williamson apparently just can't get
enough of one another.
</P>
<P>
   They're gearing up for a second season as star and creator,
respectively, of ``Dawson's Creek,'' the much-discussed WB Network
hit teen drama in which Holmes plays precocious tomboy Joey, the
lifelong chum to young heart throb Dawson (James Van Der Beek), but
wishes she was something more.
</P>
<P>
   The two also spent the summer working on ``Killing Mrs.
Tingle,'' a comedy-thriller which marks Williamson's directing
debut. They're even competing against one another in movie theaters
this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Holmes stars in ``Disturbing Behavior,'' directed by ``X-Files''
veteran David Nutter, about outcast teens who find themselves in a
sinister town filled with Stepford kids. Meanwhile, Williamson,
Hollywood's hottest screenwriter, has left his fingerprints
(although sans credit) all over the highly anticipated ``Halloween:
H20.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Scream'' king developed the story line with its star, once
and future scream queen Jamie Lee Curtis, then polished the script
four days before shooting began.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a favor, do you know what I mean? I wanted to be a part
of it,'' Williamson explains as to why he worked on the film
without getting his name in the credits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm gonna be kicking myself when I don't get residuals, but
currently, I'm very happy with the fact that it turned out
awesome,'' he says. ``It's a great movie.''
</P>
<P>
   So great, in fact, that when it was announced the film would
open July 24 _ the same week ``Disturbing Behavior'' was to debut _
Holmes' film's studio moved up its release date so as not to become
another victim of psycho slasher Michael Myers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're actually not speaking right now,'' Holmes says of
Williamson and the scheduling fracas. ``He's got issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, they're getting along fine on the set of ``Killing
Mrs. Tingle,'' in which Holmes stars as a good student with bad
luck who tries to alleviate a contentious relationship with a
difficult teacher by kidnapping her.
</P>
<P>
   This, of course, does not work out as planned. ``I did the pilot
for Dawson, and he was talking about all the movies that he had in
mind and he always said, `I wanna have you in all my movies,'''
Holmes recalls.
</P>
<P>
   ``And my manager sent me this script in the fall, and I wanted
to be as professional as I could be and not go, `Oh, Kevin, I just
read the script,''' she says. ``Because we have such a nice
relationship and I didn't want to be, (imitating a whiny kid,) `Can
I be in your movie?'''
</P>
<P>
   By the time ``Dawson's Creek'' hit the air _ and hit big _
earlier this year, the first season had already finished shooting.
Holmes appreciated working without the hoopla hanging over her
head.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were all definitely new to television and so it was nice to
just concentrate on working and not be distracted with reviews and
all that pressure,'' says Holmes, whose prior acting experience was
a small role in ``The Ice Storm'' and productions in her prep
school in Toledo, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were doing all the publicity in the fall,'' Holmes says,
``but it never really registered that, `We'll be in all the
magazines.' And it just hit and it's crazy,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that we have one season under our belts, we'll be able to
accept the distractions ... I think we'll do OK.''
</P>
<P>
   When the show debuted in America, she was shooting ``Disturbing
Behavior'' in Vancouver, where the show had yet to premiere. ``My
parents had this huge party in Ohio, and invited 100 people. So I
listened to it on the phone and talked to everybody there.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first season, Dawson emerged as the dimmest guy along the
Eastern seaboard, seemingly oblivious to Joey's yearnings. ``I
spent 13 episodes just longing. I hope I don't have to do it
again,'' Holmes says. ``Fortunately, Joey is going to become a
stronger girl.''
</P>
<P>
   Williamson, for his part, has become a one-man industry. In
addition to season two of ``Dawson's Creek,'' ``Halloween ''and
``Tingle,'' he is working on ``Wasteland,'' a pilot he's developing
for ABC; an animated half-hour series he'll executive-produce;
``The Faculty,'' a film shot this summer by director Robert
Rodriguez (``Desperado''); another film he's producing, ``Her
Leading Man,'' which begins production this fall; and _ oh, yes, a
little thing called ``Scream 3.''
</P>
<P>
   About the only thing he doesn't have on his plate is the sequel
to ``I Know What You Did Last Summer,'' made without his
participation (he wrote the first one). And yet, he opines, only
half-joking after some frustrating times on the set, ``My writing
sucks.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the director in him talking _ he's not sure the story's
coming together the way he'd like. ``It just drives me nuts.''
</P>
<P>
   Holmes is just one of the many who would disagree. ``He's very
in tune, he just knows,'' she says, explaining why young audiences
relate so strongly to his work.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a real person, and he knows what's going on inside kids'
minds and he remembers that,'' Holmes says, ``along with describing
those feelings, he incorporates the whole pop culture and
everything in the world today.''
</P>
<P>
   ``His use of references and dialogue is unique. He's very aware
of kids today, and I don't know how or where that came from, but
he's just very gifted.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Williamson cuts himself some slack when it comes to the
upcoming year of ``Dawson's Creek.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really excited about the second season,'' he says. ``I
think we've all jelled. The characters are all flourishing,
evolving and the writers have gotten it together.'
</P>
<P>
   In the first season, he says, his biggest achievement was simply
figuring out ``just what the hell I was doing. The first six
(episodes) were sort of well-plotted out, but you know, there was
probably some unevenness, some inconsistencies .... Probably little
things, which people don't notice, but I did, and a lot of it is
attributable to me just getting my feet wet.
</P>
<P>
   ``For instance, the second half of the season I think we lost
Pacey _ the character played by Vancouver native Joshua Jackson _
what happened to Pacey's story line?'' Williamson says. ``We were
so centralized on Dawson and Joey. Now, Pacey has a huge story this
coming season.''
</P>
<P>
   And Williamson has his 101 projects. ``He just doesn't stop,''
Holmes says of her boss. ``He's so focused and in tune to what he's
doing that he's just amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone always asks me, `How do you do it?' and I don't
know,'' Williamson says. ``The bottom line is I'm spread a little
too thin, but that's just the reality and I'm changing all that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This fall I have to commit myself to editing this movie,
getting it ready and getting it perfect.'' He pauses. ``And work on
`Wasteland' and `Her Leading Man.' That's the rest of my year.''
</P>
<P>
   He pauses again. ``And `Dawson's Creek,' of course.'' He sighs,
and draws a bold line in the sand. ``And I'm not bringing anything
else to my plate.''
 &UR; c.TV Guide (Canada) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (David Kronke is a staff writer for TV Guide Canada)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
