<DOCNO> NYT19980817.0097 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-17 11:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7142 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WESLEY-SNIPES-IN-BLAD     08-17 1283
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WESLEY-SNIPES-IN-BLADE-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WESLEY SNIPES HOPES TO `GET THEM' NEXT TIME 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Wesley Snipes in a scene from ``Blade.'' 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Look in the Hollywood dictionary next to up-and-down careers and
there's a head shot of Wesley Snipes.
 &HT;    It's hard to fathom that the same guy who scored with ``New Jack
City'' (1991), ``Jungle Fever'' (1991), ``White Men Can't Jump''
(1992) and ``To Wong Foo, Thanks For Everything, Julie Newmar''
(1995), crashed and burned in ``Drop Zone'' (1994), ``Money Train''
(1995), ``The Fan'' (1996) and ``U.S. Marshals'' (1998).
 &HT;    ``Some of the earlier films were surprises to people,'' Snipes
says. ``They were smaller-budget films, and I wasn't as well known
then, so there wasn't as much riding on them.
 &HT;    ``The later films had lots of other things going on that were
beyond my control. (Columbia) thought `Money Train' would be a
blockbuster, and everyone was so concerned with the fluff and puff
that nobody realized it was missing the substance that might
interest the audience,'' he says. ``That showed up in the sales.
 &HT;    ``I liked `U.S. Marshals,' and the other ones missed for a whole
lot of reasons. So many things have to go right for a film to be
good, so many things have to go right for a film to make money, and
what's scary is that you can have one without the other.
 &HT;    ``You just never know until you make the movie and put it out
exactly what you've got and what will happen,'' the 36-year-old
actor adds. ``My attitude is if you don't get them this time, get
them next time.''
 &HT;    Next time is Aug. 21 with ``Blade,'' a thriller based on the
adventures of the title character, a low-profile Marvel Comics
creation who's half-human/half-vampire. Taking no chances, Snipes
not only stars as Blade, but produced the film via his production
company, Amen Ra Films.
 &HT;    ``I don't produce for the art of it or the love of it,'' Snipes
says during a phone conversation. ``It's really about control, the
ability to put your ideas into action.
 &HT;    ``That makes all the difference in the world. In the past, I
didn't have the juice or clout to effect the script, the story's
flow, the editing or what the final product turned out to be.
 &HT;    ``When people say some of my films were not so good, I agree,
man,'' he says. ``A couple of them were not the movies I thought I
was making.
 &HT;    ``I'm trying to change that with Amen Ra. If I'm making the
film, if I'm active in everything about a film, I can't blame
anyone else if people say, `That film wasn't so good.'''
 &HT;    Snipes chose ``Blade'' for a variety of reasons. He gets a kick
out of comic books and horror films, plus he could show off his
well-honed body and martial arts expertise.
 &HT;    ``I'm not pulling a whole lot of that Jackie Chan stuff where,
in real-life, I'm jumping off buildings and dodging knives, but I
am giving it that uptown New York, raw attitude feeling,'' Snipes
says. (Though born in Florida, he was reared on the tough streets
of the Bronx, N.Y.)
 &HT;    ``We've got a great story that got better and better as we went
along,'' he says. ``It starts with a woman who's pregnant. A
vampire comes along, takes a bite out of her neck, and that
genetically alters the unborn child.
 &HT;    ``The mother goes into premature labor and is dead by the time
the baby, me, comes out. I eventually hook up with Abraham Whistler
(Kris Kristofferson), who becomes my sage-
counselor-guide-friend-father figure, and helps me take on the
quest of ridding the world of bloodsuckers,'' Snipes says.
 &HT;    ``Part of that is to help humanity and part of it is for
personal reasons, to avenge my mother's death,'' Snipes says. ``It
gets complicated on the personal level, because I'm a tormented
soul whose human and vampire halves are fighting an internal
battle.
 &HT;    ``None of that is too far removed from the basic premise of the
comic.''
 &HT;    Co-starring in the film are Steven Dorff as Deacon Frost, who
seeks to summon ``The Blood Tide,'' a sort of vampire doomsday, and
N'bushe Wright as Dr. Karen Jansen, who races against time to save
herself and Blade from the lethal effects of a vampire virus.
 &HT;    Snipes promises that audiences are in for a bloody good treat.
 &HT;    ``There's a whole lot of humor in it, situational humor as
opposed to straight-up slapstick,'' he says. ``We've definitely got
some scary elements and an adventure side, and on top of all that,
there are elements of drama that'll make you say, `Wow, this is
heavy.'
 &HT;    ``I'd call `Blade' a suspense-action-comedy-drama. It's my kind
of movie, man.''
 &HT;    Following ``Blade,'' the workaholic Snipes dived right into a
batch of other projects. He produced and co-starred with Dean Cain
and Vanessa Williams in ``Futuresport,'' a sci-fi TV movie intended
as a series pilot for ABC. The network nixed the notion of going to
series and has yet to schedule an airdate for the movie.
 &HT;    Also completed is ``Down in the Delta,'' a low-budget feature
film produced by Snipes, directed by poet Maya Angelou and due for
release at Christmas.
 &HT;    ``I play the son of a man (Al Freeman) who runs an old chicken
farm where they make chicken sausage,'' Snipes says. ``It's a film
about family, about relationships, about the clash of traditional
and modern values and ideas.
 &HT;    ``It's a heartfelt, loving movie and, in a different way, it's
got as much of my kind of energy and voice in it as ``The Big Hit'
(also produced by Amen Ra) and `Blade.'''
 &HT;    Yet another project on the Amen Ra agenda is ``African
Scholars,'' a series of documentaries that Snipes financed and
narrates. ``Scholars'' realizes Snipes' dream of building an easily
accessible video and CD-ROM archive of information about esteemed,
modern-day African artists, scholars and thinkers.
 &HT;    ``There are a number of great African minds who are never
mentioned in the mainstream, and some of them are working in the
mainstream, '' Snipes says, referring to the likes of Dr. John
Henrik Clarke and Dr. Yosef ben-Jochannan. ``I want everyone to
know these people exist because the voices of these people should
be heard when we're looking for alternative ideas for some of our
social, political, economic, philosophical and spiritual problems
and differences.
 &HT;    ``For me, part of doing this is a matter of giving back and part
of it is a matter of necessity. It's long, long overdue.''
 &HT;    Overdue, too, is some rest for the weary multi-talented Snipes.
 &HT;    ``Between the acting and producing, I've been working non stop
for two years,'' he says. ``I've got to slow down a little after
`Blade' is out and enjoy life.
 &HT;    ``I'm into the club scene, computers, the motorcycle and my
martial arts,'' says Snipes, who also just opened China One, a
Chinese restaurant in Los Angeles, with girlfriend Donna Wong.
 &HT;    ``What's funny is we've got so many things going on at Amen Ra
that I'm not sure I'll be able to take a real break.
 &HT;    ``I haven't shot a film since February, but it's almost like I'm
working anyway.''
 c.1998 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
