<DOCNO> NYT19980817.0098 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-17 11:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7143 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JASON-PATRIC-IN-YOUR-     08-17 1526
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JASON-PATRIC-IN-YOUR-FRIENDS-AND-NEIGHBORS-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JASON PATRIC, THE ANTI-STAR, REBOUNDS FROM `SPEED 2: CRUISE
CONTROL' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Jason Patric with Nastassja Kinski in a
scene from ``Your Friends and Neighbors.'' 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Jason Patric is not ready for his close-up. He is never ready
for star treatment, even though he is Jackie Gleason's grandson.
 &HT;    Being a star bothers him. Actually, he would much rather see
someone else's name in lights.
 &HT;    ``I've always respected the ballplayer who threw the touchdown
and then walked to the sidelines instead of doing the dance,'' the
actor says.
 &HT;    Right now, doing an interview makes him nervous. Patric isn't a
typical young actor who carries a banner proclaiming, ``Look at
me.'' On an early Saturday morning, he slips into the Four Seasons
Hotel in Los Angeles virtually unnoticed.
 &HT;    That's how he likes it.
 &HT;    ``I think a lot of people in this business use glamour and lust
for attention to fill the other holes in their lives,'' Patric
says.
 &HT;    ``I know from growing up with my parents that the bright lights
aren't the answer,'' says the son of Linda Miller, the daughter of
Gleason. His father is Jason Miller, a Pulitzer Prize winning
playwright who penned ``That Championship Season'' (1982) and acted
in ``The Exorcist'' (1973) as the priest.
 &HT;    Patric admits, ``I was never some Okie thinking, `Wow, everybody
loves me because my movie made $30 million its opening weekend.'''
 &HT;    For Patric the wows have mostly been about romance. We've heard,
``Wow, he's dating Robin Wright (pre-Sean Penn).'' There was also,
``Wow, he's snuggling with Julia Roberts (post-Kiefer
Sutherland).'' Now it's supermodel Christy Turlington, with whom
Patric has been for two years.
 &HT;    He doesn't get angry when asked about his personal life. He just
won't use it to push his career.
 &HT;    ``I always thought acting was about surprising people, so I
decided a long time ago to save those bits of myself for the screen
instead of for People magazine,'' he says.
 &HT;    Finally, it might be about the work.
 &HT;    Patric turns in some of his best work in ``Your Friends and
Neighbors,'' the most sexually provocative film of 1998, which also
stars Catherine Kenner, Nastassja Kinski, Ben Stiller, Amy
Brennerman and Aaron Eckhart. It opens Aug. 28.
 &HT;    It's a modern immorality tale about three couples who examine
the intimacy between husband and wives and friends and neighbors.
In the film, an afternoon brunch with friends is the perfect time
to put the make on your pal's wife.
 &HT;    Vigorous sex with your lover? It's the time to voice your
contempt of the opposite sex. Patric, who also serves as producer,
says there is a moral to this story.
 &HT;    ``On one hand, these six characters just want to be fulfilled.
But, in the movie, we see the downfall of that kind of selfishness
when its at the expense of something or someone else.'' The lesson?
``It's about how we all want to be loved or at least feel
self-love, which is so hard in the '90s.''
 &HT;    Patric plays Cary, a man who tapes himself during solo sex to
study and improve his performance. He is matter of fact in contempt
of both sexes. ``I've played a lot of characters with dark edges
before,'' Patric says, ``but nothing compares to this guy.''
 &HT;    Patric teamed up with director-writer Neil LaBute after admiring
his work in the independent hit ``In the Company of Men'' (1997).
 &HT;    ``I guess I wanted to work with Neil the same way that a young
DeNiro wanted to work with a young Scorsese,'' Patric says. ``I
also wanted to act with Aaron Eckhart whose performance in `In the
Company of Men' was the best performance of last year.''
 &HT;    LaBute returns the compliment. ``I knew I needed a really good
actor because I wanted to work in really long takes,'' he says. ``I
was glad that Jason was on board as a producer, too. He was able to
create a safe space for the rest of the actors.''
 &HT;    Patric was cast for other reasons.
 &HT;    ``I really wanted a good looking guy to play Cary,'' LaBute
says. ``We have this tendency to allow beautiful people to get away
with murder. I like the idea of having a really good looking guy
like Jason saying terrible things.''
 &HT;    What appealed to Patric is that Cary has a method to his
madness, including a rape in high school. Patric says that his
character ``has created his own morality. He's vicious, but he's
specific.''
 &HT;    Patric laughs when asked about his redeeming qualities. ``He's
not some macho, God's-gift-to-women type. He never brags about his
conquests. He's the only character in the movie who never lies.''
 &HT;    Some have wondered if Cary is a closeted homosexual who brings
his hatred of women to bed with him. ``It's possible,'' Patric
says. ``He's definitely not happy with women ... He's just
chillingly scary.''
 &HT;    Patric admits that the role left him with some trepidation.
``It's chilling to think, `Can I play this guy realistically?' You
know to do that you have to draw on yourself.'' Patric isn't about
to list his best and worst dates but admits that he drew on others
to shape Cary.
 &HT;    Patric is more upfront about Hollywood, recently telling Vogue
you couldn't pay him enough to see ``Titanic.'' He also vowed that
he would never attend the Academy Awards.
 &HT;    He regularly turns down huge paychecks. ``Look, I've been
offered big money before and turned it down,'' he says. ``I was
making movies long before the Brad Pitts and the Matthew
McConaugheys. And if a big paycheck doesn't affect you at 21 when
you're trying to get girls and a cool car, it's not going to affect
you at 30.''
 &HT;    His choices have left Hollywood perplexed. With his looks,
Patric could have easily gone the hunk route.
 &HT;    ``I don't make movies, so I can wind up on magazine covers. I
don't choose scripts so I'll end up at the Oscars,'' he says.
 &HT;    ``That just epitomizes what's wrong with movies today. Everybody
does a role thinking of their next step, whether it's to win an
Oscar or get a bigger, more expensive movie.''
 &HT;    Of course, Patric has strayed a bit. Last summer's dud ``Speed
2: Cruise Control'' comes to mind. He was literally like a fish out
of water playing a by-the-books cop stuck on a speeding boat.
 &HT;    ``It was unsuccessful and rightly so,'' Patric says. ``Of
course, there were other movies last year which were successful
that were much worse than `Speed 2.'''
 &HT;    Patric says that he signed for ``Speed 2'' as a way ``to enter
into the global marketplace. It helped me make something harder
edged like this movie.''
 &HT;    He also got on board for more practical reasons. ``I wanted to
show that I am a physical guy. I thought if I did `Speed 2,' it
would allow me to show that side of myself.''
 &HT;    Perhaps Patric also wanted to lighten up.
 &HT;    Critics have said his work is usually so dark. ``The funny thing
is that I've never made movies that were darker than the movies
Pacino and DeNiro made in the '70s,'' he says. ``And those were the
movies that made these guys kings.''
 &HT;    Patric could be in their position. With his family ties he could
have had an easier ride as a young actor.
 &HT;    Even as a kid, fame didn't interest Patric. ``Somebody once said
to me, `Oh, you don't want to be a movie star?' I never said that.
I said, `I'll never pick roles to become a movie star.'''
 &HT;    His choices _ nothing if not eclectic _ include ``Sleepers''
(1996), ``The Beast'' (1988), ``After Dark, My Sweet'' (1990),
``Rush'' (1991) and ``The Journey of August King'' (1995).
 &HT;    When asked about his best work, he cites the early 1990s.
``Stuff like `After Dark, My Sweet' and `Rush,' when all I cared
about was the material,'' Patric says. ``I think I was ahead of the
dark curve that all of a sudden happened with Quentin Tarantino and
all these edgy Miramax movies.
 &HT;    ``At 32, it's nice to get back to doing this kind of stuff
again,'' he says.
 &HT;    ``I remember reading `Your Friends and Neighbors' and just
thinking, `Wow! No punches were pulled, but it wasn't extreme for
extreme's sake. I was affected by all six of the characters.''
 &HT;    For his part, Patric just examines his characters. ``You can't
make judgments about the characters you play. You can make
assessments. But I have to believe what Cary believes. I have to
find Cary in me. He is created his own world. I have to live in it.
 &HT;    ``But only for a couple of months,'' he says and smiles.
 &HT;     c.1998 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR;
</P>
