<SLUG> BC-GEEWAX-COLUMN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Commentary: Cost of preventing crime far less than price paid
for punishment
 &HT;    By Marilyn Geewax
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ How much does a handgun cost?
</P>
<P>
   The price tag in the store might say $250. But the true cost can
run well into the millions. This month, two multimillion-dollar
guns were fired in metro Atlanta. Taxpayers, retailers and property
owners will be paying for those guns for years.
</P>
<P>
   One of the weapons was used to kill a young man in the food
court at Greenbriar Mall in southwest Atlanta. The ultimate cost of
that single crime could be staggering.
</P>
<P>
   Greenbriar is a 33-year-old mall struggling to compete with much
newer shopping centers. Two years ago, basketball hero Magic
Johnson gave Greenbriar a boost by opening a 12-screen movie
theater there. That addition spurred a $1.5 million renovation of
the mall's exterior.
</P>
<P>
   The improvements have led to higher retail sales and better
property values. Homeowners become wealthier when their
neighborhood is perceived as having access to a lively, safe
shopping mecca.
</P>
<P>
   But this month, mall customers saw a man slam to the floor of
the food court and die from a bullet wound. The next sound after
the gunshot was the roar of car engines as patrons fled.
</P>
<P>
   Greenbriar is not a dangerous place. Still, its image has
suffered from the murder. If the shooting leaves some customers
leery about the mall, sales and property values could decline.
</P>
<P>
   And that's to say nothing of the cost of capturing, convicting
and jailing the shooter. In Georgia, taxpayers spend about $54 per
day to maintain each state inmate. Assuming the murderer spends 20
years in jail, taxpayers will have to pay nearly $400,000 for his
incarceration.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the loss of life. The 25-year-old victim could
have spent another 40 years in the work force. Now, his family has
lost a loved one and society has lost a man just entering his
prime.
</P>
<P>
   The other gun that carried an enormous price tag was fired in a
suburban Atlanta subdivision. Levi Simon III, 17, was shot as he
was leaving a friend's birthday party. Simon was just a week away
from moving to college when he caught a bullet fired by a
party-crasher. Police have arrested three suspects.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows how much Simon, a trumpet player with a music
scholarship, might have earned in his lifetime. But the
college-bound young man with an excellent reputation almost
certainly would have become a taxpaying contributor to society.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, his talents are lost to us. Meanwhile, we'll pay
heavily to jail his murderers. Property values in the DeKalb County
subdivision can't be helped by this.
</P>
<P>
   For years, many people believed that poverty caused crime. But
the reality is the opposite: Crime causes poverty. Crime squanders
tax dollars, drives down real estate values, discourages commerce
and prompts property owners to spend vast sums on alarm systems,
security guards and door locks.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department says that in 1997, the nation's prison
population grew by 5.2 percent, up to 1.73 million. At $54 per
prisoner per day, the annual direct cost to taxpayers just for
operating jail cells would exceed $34 billion.
</P>
<P>
   It's astonishing that Americans tolerate such waste. Even if we
spent $100 billion on programs to prevent young people from
becoming criminals, we would still come out ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Yet this year's election season will surely bring us more ads
from politicians assuring us they'll be spitting razor wire and
firing up the electric chairs. But few will discuss the fantastic
savings that could come from improving education, upgrading foster
care, funding drug treatment programs, preventing teen pregnancy,
expanding job training and improving the juvenile court system. The
U.S. economy would surge if we ever got serious about preventing
crime.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
