<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Riding down Memory Lane with Hot Rod Hairy
 &HT;    (EDS: Hairy is cq)
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ ``Don't turn around,'' I tell my companion,
``but there's a man standing behind you with a huge sign pinned to
his hat that reads: `Need outside sun visor for '39 Chevy.' '' My
friend chuckles and aims me toward the nearest lemonade stand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you see it?'' I ask. ``The sign?'' Guess I'm looking for
reassurance that my brains haven't fried in the relentless heat
cooking up from the acres of pavement here at the Kentucky
Fairgrounds. Got to be 110 degrees in the shade _ only there isn't
any.
</P>
<P>
   It's the 29th Annual Street Rod Nationals and there are 15,000
vehicles from all over the country here, cruising the parking lots
and strutting their shiny stuff. I had no idea there were this many
old cars left in the whole world, much less in mint condition and
driveable.
</P>
<P>
   Street rods, I learned, have been messed with. Unlike the
antique auto folks who go in for faithful restoration, ``rodders''
don't mind chopping a top or dropping a Corvette engine into a '40
Ford coupe. And tell me, when was the last time you took a spin in
a '37 Chevy with air-conditioning and cruise control?
</P>
<P>
   My friend hands me a sweaty cup of lemonade, my third in less
than an hour, and we set out to do some cruising of our own, on
foot, through the endless rows of iron. He's checking out engines.
I focus on interiors and memories.
</P>
<P>
   A boxy '37 Chevy sedan catches my eye. My folks had one of those
when I was a little girl. I remember riding out into the country
with my mother at the wheel and wishing I were grown up enough to
see out the window. I was tiring of treetops. And I remember being
carsick in the
</P>
<P>
   back seat _ often. So often in fact, that my father used to
wonder about the next owner. Said it'd have to be someone with a
chronic head cold.
</P>
<P>
   A few rows down, right across from the bratwurst stand, is a '40
Super Deluxe Chevy sedan, just like the one my father gave my
mother for Christmas that year before Pearl Harbor. I recognize the
body shape and the grille, but that's about all.
</P>
<P>
   Mother's Bessie (the name she gave all of her cars as a payback
to her mother-in-law of the same name) was a dignified two-tone
gray and dark blue. This buggy is dandelion yellow with candy-blue
flames licking over the hood.
</P>
<P>
   As I peek through the windows, careful not to touch or lean on
anything (the biggest social blunder in the rodder's book of
etiquette), I can't help wondering; could this possibly be the same
car that saw our family through the war with a ``B'' sticker on the
windshield that limited the gallons of gas the man at the Gulf
station was allowed to pump into our tank? Is there a chance it's
the same flivver that dropped a rusted-through fender in downtown
Cleveland's rush hour traffic back in the winter of '44?
</P>
<P>
   My friend leans over for a better look and chuckles. ``Remember
those things?'' he asks, pointing to a glassy knob clamped onto the
steering wheel. ``We called them `hairy knobs' because we thought
they made us look like real hotrods. Man,'' he sighs with a
nostalgic grin, ``we could whip around corners with our left hand
and never have to move our right arm, which, of course, was around
our date.''
</P>
<P>
   Is he kidding? Do I remember? Harry, my first boyfriend, had one
of those on his old Chevy. We put in plenty of driving time under
just such conditions. That was in the good old days before bucket
seats, when a date could scootch up under her boyfriend's arm and
stay there all the way to the drive-in. It was one of the ways
girls measured a guy's affection. ``We drove all the way to Crandon
Park and he never took his arm down,'' was a familiar gloat at
Saturday night slumber parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hot Rod Hairy'' was what we called a guy who drove fast, dug
out and squealed corners. Girls thought it was kind of dumb, but we
giggled and ogled all the same. ``Big hairy deal,'' we'd yell in
unison.
</P>
<P>
   Truth is, we used that expression a lot. It was the label we
pinned on anything we felt was not all it was cracked up to be.
Like the night a bunch of us rumbled into the Big Wheel Drive-In
for burgers after seeing the sci-fi thriller ``The Thing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Big hairy deal!'' Burton Craig groaned as he leaned up against
the side of his coupe. ``I can't believe I paid 75 cents to watch a
giant carrot eat its way through the North Pole.''
</P>
<P>
   And I can't believe those days are gone forever. But ``Hot Rod
Hairy'' is still around. He hands me another lemonade and steers me
toward a '34 Packard. A real beauty.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett is a teacher and writer in Gibsonburg, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
