<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE TUESDAY FEATURES BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These stories for release Tuesday, August 18, 1998, are moving
today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports, business and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. All stories have moved
except those with an ETA.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   OLD-YOUNG _ Pegged to ``Stella,'' older woman-younger man
relationships. A look at Terry McMillan's relationship, peppered
with comments from relationship experts on why society has been
more accepting of older men w/young girls and why the tide is
slowly changing. (Hill, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   OLD-YOUNG-LIST _ High-profile celebrity women who have
husbands/boyfriends at least 10 years their junior i.e., Mary Tyler
Moore, Olivia Newton-John, Cher, Rene Russo, Madonna.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   BROWN-COMEBACK _ ATLANTA _ Throughout the 1980s, Georgia's own
T. Graham Brown was a rising star in Nashville, churning out Top-10
country hits and recording duets with the likes of Tanya Tucker. It
was a long way from his frat party days in Athens, where he got his
start as half of the popular house band Dirk and Tony. But by the
mid-'90s, Brown's world crumbled as he fought declining record
sales and escalating alcoholism. Now Brown's back with a new album
and a new, sober lifestyle. His new single debuts Tuesday.
(Longino, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TV-SURFER _ Lifetime is debuting three series. As you'd expect,
they're strong on women: ``Maggie,'' ``Oh, Baby'' and ``Any Day
Now.'' At the heart, they tackle subjects you don't find much on
the big networks _ ``Oh, Baby'' is about a career woman who decides
artificial insemination is the way to go to be a mom. Men aren't
central to these women's lives _ and when it comes ``Oh, Baby,''
men are hardly essential. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
