<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tech Report: With help from computer, Lego robots leap to life
 &HT;    By John Ghirardini
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Many products that had their beginnings in the
low-tech days when vacuum tubes ruled have withstood the test of
time.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most successful have been Lego plastic building
bricks. They've been around in their present form since 1958, and
kids have spent hours having fun with them without realizing they
were learning at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   The Lego Group began dabbling with computer-controlled products
in 1986 in collaboration with Massachusetts Institute of
Technology, and the latest creation to spring from that fertile
alliance blends old and new into a cutting-edge toy that will usher
children _ and a lot of adults _ into the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   The Lego Mindstorms Robotics Invention System, which should hit
store shelves in the fall and retail for about $200, lets kids 11
and up design and program real robots that can move, think and act
on their own. Gort, the blank-faced metal man in the 1950s sci-fi
classic ``The Day the Earth Stood Still,'' would approve.
</P>
<P>
   The brain is the RCX, a microcomputer that can be programmed
with a PC. The RCX's sensors gather input from its environment,
processes it and signals small motors to turn on and off.
</P>
<P>
   Users build their robot with the RCX, Constructopedia guide and
700 Lego pieces included. Next, they create a program using RCX
code, a simple but powerful programming language. The program is
downloaded to the RCX with a special infrared transmitter that
comes with the kit. The robot then can interact with the
environment, independent from the PC.
</P>
<P>
   Children can build a working robot in under an hour, the company
says.
</P>
<P>
   Also coming out in the fall are three expansion sets for the
RCX. The Extreme Creatures set lets kids build virtually any
animal, real or fantasized. Included are fiber-optic strands, a
snapping claw, a working pincer and a tail-wagging mechanism.
</P>
<P>
   With the Robo-Sports set, the robots can shoot hoops, flick
pucks or negotiate an obstacle course. The Exploration Mars set
lets young explorers build a Mars rover and control it from their
own PC.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion sets will retail for $50. Each has its own
Constructopedia building guide and a CD-ROM with 12 challenges.
More challenges can be found at the Mindstorms Web site,
http://www.legomindstorms.com. The CDs are for Windows 3.1 or
Windows 95.
</P>
<P>
   A little something for your pocket
</P>
<P>
   Sharp Electronics Corp. has come out with a new personal
organizer that will store a megabyte of data in a 5-ounce package
small enough to fit in a shirt pocket.
</P>
<P>
   The palm-sized SE-300 includes software and a docking station
that allows for two-way transfer of information from a desktop
computer. The software is set up to work with Microsoft's Outlook
97, ACT 3.07 and Lotus Organizer.
</P>
<P>
   The device has a backlit LCD display screen and an infrared port
to exchange data with other Sharp products or the infrared port on
a notebook computer.
</P>
<P>
   The unit runs for 60 hours on one AA battery. Retail price is
$180.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine that!
</P>
<P>
   Compaq Computer Corp. has joined forces with the magicians at
Walt Disney World in Orlando, providing hardware for DisneyQuest,
an interactive entertainment experience that opened in June.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the computing power is concentrated in the ``Create
Zone,'' where kids of any age can combine their own imaginations
with Disney characters to create unique images and animation and
even become a part of the story.
</P>
<P>
   While in the ``Create Zone,'' visitors can learn the secrets of
animation, create a toy to take home, get a virtual makeover in the
Magic Mirror or create a painting on a Living Easel.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq provided workstations, PCs, servers and flat-panel
monitors to help fun seekers turn fantasy into reality.
</P>
<P>
   Seek and ye shall find
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is a treasure trove of useful and useless
information, but finding the nugget you want in a pile of fool's
gold can be daunting.
</P>
<P>
   A search string that isn't specific enough can turn up hundreds
of categories and thousands of Web sites that have irrelevancy in
common.
</P>
<P>
   A new search engine, GoTo.com, aims to streamline the process by
getting back to basics. There are no ad banners on the home page,
letting the page build quicker. Or a user can add the search string
right after the ``www'' in the engine's address and go immediately
on the search results page.
</P>
<P>
   Give the engine a try at http://www.goto.com. Maybe you'll
strike it rich.
</P>
<P>
   John Ghirardini writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
