<HEADER>
A7164 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ECONOMY18-COX     08-17 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECONOMY18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Market testing investor staying power
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Alan Greenspan warned us about the bull market,
fretting at one point about the ``irrational exuberance'' he
thought was pushing stock prices to extremes.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that the chairman of the Federal Reserve is worried
about the money investors might lose in a bear market. That's a
risk every investor takes.
</P>
<P>
   But he is concerned about what might happen to the economy if a
sharp and sustained drop in the market robs consumers of a
substantial part of the enormous wealth they have accumulated
during the bull run.
</P>
<P>
   The rise in stock prices has added about $12.5 trillion to the
value of household assets just since the end of 1994, according to
the Federal Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   To the extent consumer spending is driving the economy, anything
that threatens that threatens the economy, the thinking is.
</P>
<P>
   What happens depends on how serious and lengthy the current
stock market sell-off becomes. Analysts are deeply divided on both
questions.
</P>
<P>
   Is this a routine correction, in which stock indexes drop 10
percent or 15 percent from their highs, or is it the beginning of a
bear market with losses of 20 percent or more?
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average already is down 9.8 percent
from its July 17 record, and broader and secondary stock indexes
are down even more.
</P>
<P>
   Bearish analysts contend a major stock market sell-off is not
only long overdue but that this year's slowdown in corporate profit
growth makes the prospect even more likely.
</P>
<P>
   A prolonged sell-off would be especially damaging to the
economy, given the amount of household wealth Americans have
accumulated in the 1990s. The stock market ``wealth effect'' has
given middle-class Americans enough confidence _ and money _ to go
on an almost decadelong spending spree.
</P>
<P>
   That in turn has produced more than seven years of uninterrupted
economic growth since the end of the 1990-91 recession, propelled
by feel-good consumers.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Consumer Confidence Index rose from 59.40 in
February 1991, at the bottom of the recession, to 135.40 in July, a
rise of 128 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Disposable personal income _ the money available for consumers
to spend on whims as well as necessities _ rose over the same
period from $4.3 trillion to $6 trillion, a gain of almost 40
percent.
</P>
<P>
   And during that period, consumers have showed little inclination
to save for a rainy day while new cars, houses, wardrobes and other
products beckoned. Home sales, for instance, which are a major
driver of the economy, averaged about 4 million dwellings per year
from 1991 through 1997, and a combination of lower mortgage rates
and upbeat consumers kicked the 1998 annual rate to 4.8 million
units.
</P>
<P>
   The savings rate, meanwhile, has dropped from 5.5 percent of
gross domestic product in 1991 to only 0.2 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Dow advanced from 2,882.18 in February 1991 to an
all-time high of 9,337.97 on July 17, 1998 _ a rise of 224 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The climb was propelled in part by the flood of money from whole
new classes of investors: individuals forced by employers to manage
their own pension funds via 401(k) plans, baby boomers reaching
middle age and investing for retirement, and the proliferation of
mutual funds beating the drums for new clients.
</P>
<P>
   Just since 1990, total assets in mutual funds rose from $245.8
billion to $2.4 trillion last year _ an increase of 876 percent,
the Investment Company Institute reports.
</P>
<P>
   And the percentage of households owning stocks has risen from
about 25 percent in 1982 to 45 percent last year, government
figures show.
</P>
<P>
   The wealth thus accumulated in the market has translated into
economic growth that, while fluctuating, has trended steadily
higher.
</P>
<P>
   Annualized gross domestic product growth was a robust 5.5
percent in the first quarter of 1998. While it dropped to 1.4
percent in the second quarter, it was still better than most
analysts anticipated, given the impact of Asia's economic crisis
and the early round of the General Motors strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``Evidently, optimism about jobs, incomes and profits, rising
wealth-to-income ratios, low financing costs and falling prices for
high-tech goods fed the appetites of households and businesses for
consumer durables and capital equipment,'' Greenspan told Congress
recently.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan's worries about stock prices aside, investors have
shown no inclination so far to stop investing.
</P>
<P>
   In the three weeks since the latest market decline began, small
investors trading fewer than 10,000 shares added about $731 million
to the market, according to Birinyi Associates.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street professionals, meanwhile, making block trades of
more than 10,000 shares, accounted for $3.47 billion in selling,
The New York Times said in reporting the Birinyi Associates
results.
</P>
<P>
   That's not a sign of small investor panic, and if it continues,
bullish analysts say it would put a floor under the latest
correction and recharge the bull market.
</P>
<P>
   And presumably, this would also settle the question of whether
consumers will continue to fuel the economy with their spending _
which is a big unknown at the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't predict how people will spend money in the future,''
said Alan Skrainka, chief market strategist for Edward Jones in St.
Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``The safest thing to forecast is that the economy is going to
experience slower growth in the second half, not only due to the
stock market but because manufacturers are being hit hard by
Asia,'' said Skrainka.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer confidence, while down slightly in July, is still
upbeat for the year, which bodes well for continued spending.
</P>
<P>
   Economists say this is due in part to an unemployment rate that
seems to have leveled off at 4.5 percent, accompanied by benign
inflation and interest rates that are trending lower _ conditions
that helped to produce the bull market.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
