A7165 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELECTRONIC-BAT18-COX     08-17 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELECTRONIC-BAT18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hate those fastballs on the fists? Swing away with an `electric'
bat
 &HT;    By John Ghirardini
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Technology is putting a charge into the grand old game
of baseball.
</P>
<P>
   The world's first ``electric bat,'' the aluminum Copperhead ACX
by Worth Inc., hit store shelves Aug. 1, billed as having a nearly
unlimited sweet spot and promising to reduce or eliminate the sting
that results from hitting the ball near the handle or close to the
end.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the Copperhead ACX's competitors are at the cutting
edge, too. The Easton Z-Core SC500 alloys aluminum with scandium _
used in the former Soviet Union for MiG fighters _ to make a thin,
super-hard shell around a ``high-strain inner core.'' The
pressurized Louisville Slugger Air Attack 2 has a nitrogen-filled
bladder running the length of the inside of the thin-walled bat.
All range from $275 to $300 in price.
</P>
<P>
   But these advances have caused some to worry that bats have
become too dangerous, and that it's just a matter of time before a
screaming line drive seriously injures or even kills a pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   What increases the potential danger, most experts agree, is that
aluminum bats are much lighter for a given length than their wooden
counterparts. The lighter the bat, the greater a hitter's bat speed
and the speed at which the ball rebounds off the bat.
</P>
<P>
   For high school and college play, a minus-5 _ 5 ounces less than
the length in inches _ is the lowest weight allowable, said Jess
Heald, chairman of Worth Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``A ball comes off a wooden bat at 93 to 95 mph,'' Bill
Thurston, the baseball coach at Amherst College in Massachusetts,
told Newhouse News Service. ``With aluminum, it goes up to 110 to
115 mph, sometimes as high as 120 mph.''
</P>
<P>
   In response to the concerns, the NCAA announced last week that
the baseball rules committee will recommend a maximum batted-ball
exit velocity of 93 mph and a change in the size and weight specs
of non-wood bats beginning with the 1999 season. The lower limit
may be changed to minus-3, which should slow bat speed.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Sansing, baseball coach at Kennesaw State University,
favors the move. ``If we go to a minus-2 or minus-3 bat, it'll
bring back more of the traditional game,'' he said. Right now,
Sansing said, ``Every guy who goes up to the plate has the
potential of knocking it out.''
</P>
<P>
   The risks don't seem to be as great in lower levels of ball. A
Little League study of injury data in all its baseball and softball
divisions showed a decrease in injuries to pitchers from batted
balls between 1992 and 1997. In 1992, 145 pitchers were injured by
batted balls; in 1997, only 53 got hurt. Annually, only a fraction
of 1 percent of U.S. Little Leaguers are injured to the point of
requiring medical treatment, the study showed.
</P>
<P>
   The Easton Z-Core and Louisville Slugger Air Attack bats are
available in Little League models. A Little League version of the
Copperhead ACX may be available next season, Heald said.
</P>
<P>
   BOX: Device takes away the sting by neutralizing the vibration
</P>
<P>
   Made by 88-year-old Worth Inc., of Tullahoma, Tenn., the
Copperhead ACX aluminum bat uses the same ``piezoelectric''
vibration control technology used in the twin tails of F-18 Hornet
fighter jets.
</P>
<P>
   Worth combined with Active Control experts of Cambridge, Mass.,
to develop this latest wrinkle in the national pastime. The ACX
technology previously had been used in snowboards, skis and
mountain bikes.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what happens when a ball is hit:
</P>
<P>
   Inside the bat is a piezoceramic damper that takes the
vibrations created by off-center hits and turns them into
electrical energy. That energy is applied across a ``shunt''
circuit, which dissipates it as heat, removing the energy from the
bat and reducing vibration. An LED in the knob of the bat lights
when the bat is vibrating, so a batter knows the damper is working.
</P>
<P>
   It works, says Wayne Vickery, baseball coach of the Gainesville
Red Elephants, the state Class AA champions in 1995, '96 and '97.
Vickery saw the bat in action at the Sun Belt Classic tournament in
Shawnee, Okla., this summer. Worth, one of the sponsors, furnished
bats to all competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It lights up when you hit the sweet spot,'' Vickery said.
``All the players just love it.''
</P>
<P>
   John Ghirardini writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
