A7166 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELECTRONIC-GADGETS18-     08-17 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELECTRONIC-GADGETS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Anglers and athletes are getting hooked on electronic gadgets
 &HT;    By John Ghirardini
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Americans are taking their microchips out to play with
increasing frequency.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you're a golfer, hiker, angler, ballplayer or
participant in any of a dozen other sports, there's a device to
help you get closer, walk smarter, find fish deeper or hit harder.
</P>
<P>
   Take golf. Perhaps no other sport offers as many gizmos to buy.
The nation's 25 million golfers spend nearly $4 billion annually on
equipment and training aids alone, according to the National Golf
Foundation. Close to $2 billion more is spent on apparel and shoes.
</P>
<P>
   During most of the royal and ancient pastime's history,
distances to the flag were measured by shoe-leather express: The
golfer or caddy paced it off. Many courses have distance markers,
but they aren't always reliable.
</P>
<P>
   That just won't do in the computer age.
</P>
<P>
   Now the nation's duffers and hackers with disposable income have
access to binocular-like laser range finders _ hand-me-down
military technology that was beyond the dreams of grizzled
artillerymen just a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   A quality device provides a distance reading to a target _ the
flagstick, a house just off the green, or just about anything that
will reflect the laser beam _ accurate to within a yard. The lasers
are illegal for tournaments, but pros find them a great help for
practice rounds on unfamiliar courses, said Rick McCall, a pro at
the private TPC at Sugarloaf golf course in suburban Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Bushnell, a longtime maker of optical devices based in Overland
Park, Kan., offers a line of range finders optimized for a variety
of distances. All run on a 9-volt battery. The Yardage Pro 400
($300) ranges 400 yards; others cover 600 and 800 yards. The
Compact 600 runs about $400 at The Sports Authority. The 800's
suggested retail price is $449. A compact range finder from DME in
a bright yellow, high-impact case is available at Golf Warehouse
stores for $300.
</P>
<P>
   If you have an incredibly bad hook or slice that sends your ball
to faraway places, and money is no object, for $3,000 you can get
Leica's Geovid, which gives an accurate reading to 1,000 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Golfers aren't the only ones who lay out big bucks for the
latest technology. There are 83 million hikers, campers and hunters
in the nation, according to the National Sporting Goods
Association. For those who want to get away from it all while
knowing exactly where they are, or for the directionally
challenged, another legacy has filtered down from the military:
hand-held Global Positioning System receivers.
</P>
<P>
   The receivers range from about $100 to $600, and tap into a ring
of 24 U.S. government satellites encircling the Earth. After
calculating its relative position to at least three of the
satellites and the travel time of the radio signal from the
satellite, the GPS receiver uses triangulation to figure out where
on Earth it is.
</P>
<P>
   The accuracy for civilian GPS receivers is to within about 150
to 300 feet. Military versions get a lot closer, but for security
reasons, the Department of Defense restricts the civilian results.
</P>
<P>
   The brands most readily available at sporting goods and outdoors
stores are from Magellan, Garmin and Eagle. Some, such as Garmin's
GPS 48 ($417), will track up to 12 satellites at a time. Others,
such as Eagle's Explorer ($180), also handle 12, but trade the
number of functions for a lower price. Many of the receivers
feature moving maps for navigation in a car; most can be connected
to a laptop and used with mapping software for real-time
navigation. Some even include e-mail capability, though at a steep
price. Figure to spend $300 to $400 for a full-featured, backlit
unit.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's 44 million anglers spend more than $106 billion on
their sport each year, according to Field &AMP; Stream magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Fishing electronics have evolved in a few years from relatively
crude sonar depth finders to combination GPS receivers that include
split screens with zoom, speed, distance and water temperature
readings, fish-finding sonar, and bottom composition and contour
readouts. Some models include sensors that can be dropped into the
water to determine the amount of light available at a certain depth
and where the temperature changes.
</P>
<P>
   Prices range from $100 for a basic Humminbird depth finder to
$1,000 or more for a Lowrance Global Map 2000 that does it all and
includes a map of the entire world. Also included is a MapLink
reader that scans postage-stamp-sized cartridges containing
detailed information on regions in both hemispheres. For most
anglers, spending about $400 to $500 will bring a solid mix of
useful functions. Garmin, Magellan and Eagle all offer lines of
fishing electronics. Most are available in combination form or as
separate devices.
</P>
<P>
   Feeling left out if you're a baseball or softball player? Don't.
The latest king of swing is the Copperhead ACX from Tullahoma,
Tenn.-based Worth Inc. _ the world's first ``electric'' bat (see
related story, Page P3). The bat uses ``piezoelectric'' dampers to
lessen vibrations. The net result is less sting in the hands from
mis-hit balls and a larger sweet spot. An LED in the knob of the
bat blinks to let you know the dampers are working correctly.
</P>
<P>
   The bat doesn't guarantee that every hit will be a frozen-rope
liner, but should help a player make the most of even an off-center
hit.
</P>
<P>
   The Copperhead ACX reached store shelves Aug. 1, and retails for
$299.
</P>
<P>
   John Ghirardini writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
