u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PAYOFF-DEBT18-COX     08-17 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAYOFF-DEBT18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Paying off high debt a good investment
 &HT;    By Gene Tharpe
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ What are consumers learning from the stock market
correction? Or what should they be learning? What dangers lie
ahead?
</P>
<P>
   It is dangerous to carry too much debt at any time. An
unexpected problem, such as divorce or a major medical expense, can
quickly lead to calls from debt collectors and even result in
personal bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   It is especially dangerous to carry too much debt when the
economy is uncertain. And U.S. consumers are carrying the highest
debt level in history.
</P>
<P>
   In May, it appeared that consumers might have had a sixth sense
about this. Total consumer debt outstanding declined two-tenths of
1 percent and revolving credit, which is mainly credit cards,
declined 5.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Also this spring, the American Bankers Association said that
delinquent payments on consumer credit accounts _ including credit
cards, auto loans and home equity loans _ had fallen slightly in
the first quarter of 1998, after rising steadily during the past
two years. It appeared that consumers were catching up on their
debts.
</P>
<P>
   But last month brought bad news.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve said total consumer credit had risen 6.4
percent in June to $1.256 trillion, and revolving credit had risen
5.5 percent to $542.4 billion. The Consumer Federation of America
reported that about 60 percent of all U.S. households carry credit
card debt, with an average balance of $7,000. And last week, the
U.S. Bankruptcy Court said 1.42 million bankruptcies had been filed
in the year ended June 30, a record high for a 12-month period,
spurred by a 9.2 percent jump in personal bankruptcies.
</P>
<P>
   All this, added to the stock market uncertainty, might suggest a
need for concern for consumers and the economy. But Jeffrey
Humphreys, a University of Georgia economist who specializes in
economic forecasting, doesn't think so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most household balance sheets are not in disarray,'' he said.
``Debt levels are up but also are households' net worth,'' thanks
in major part to the bull market of recent years _ a bull market he
expects to continue for several more years despite the current
correction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Households are generally thrilled with the market, because
they have made more in the market than they ever expected,'' he
said. ``They currently are probably ahead of the market for the
year, and surely well ahead for the last five years.''
</P>
<P>
   Because so many baby boomers have begun preparing for
retirement, they are ``socking away thousands of dollars in the
market and I expect that to continue for several years to come,''
said Humphreys. He predicted that consumers will not cut back on
spending because of the current situation.
</P>
<P>
   However, consumer spending amounts to about two-thirds of the
economy, ``and if the correction doesn't recover reasonably quickly
and consumer confidence falters, then we could have some
problems,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A tentative sign of a consumer confidence slowdown came last
week when the Conference Board reported that its Consumer
Confidence Index fell to 135.4 in July, down from its record high
of 138.2 in June, before the market correction began.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Suzanne Boas, president of the Consumer Credit
Counseling Service of Metropolitan Atlanta, said there's a better
investment right now than the stock market: paying down credit card
debt. ``You get a great return getting rid of that double-digit
interest,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Gerri Detweiler, author of ``The Ultimate Credit Handbook'' and
an adviser to Debt Counselors of America, agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers should do what they always should have been doing _
pay off high-interest debt, save three to six months' salary for
emergencies, and live below your means to avoid future debt,''
Detweiler said.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Brobeck, executive director of the Consumer Federation
of America, said the irony of the ups and downs of the stock market
is that they have little direct effect on many people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only a small percentage of people with heavy debt has any
substantial investment in the stock market,'' he said. ``They live
close to the financial edge, and what they have to worry about is a
correction leading to an economic slowdown that might cost them
their jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Gene Tharpe writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
