</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEORGE-COLUMN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tyson to keep his license in a money belt
 &HT;    By Dave George
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ New Jersey doesn't seem to want him.
Nevada's opinion will be the result of a rematch with state boxing
commissioners who already have expressed their distaste for one
athlete tasting another in the course of a championship bout.
</P>
<P>
   If Mike Tyson studied geography in addition to the teachings of
ancient Chinese philosophers during his incarceration for rape, he
knows that no matter what happens in Las Vegas, 48 states and a
handful of U.S. protectorates remain to be petitioned for a boxing
license.
</P>
<P>
   There's South Dakota, for instance, where Jay Leno recently won
a professional wrestling match against Hulk Hogan before an
enormous outdoor crowd. If suspension of belief is a necessity for
putting on a Tyson fight, the good and gentle citizens of that
state appear receptive. They might even accept the notion that Iron
Mike is regretful for anything other than his loss of earning
power.
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana might work, too, particularly if a bout were put
together in a remote bayou village on a moonshine-soaked Saturday
night. Cockfighting and alligator wrestling would make a great
undercard, followed by the main event of Tyson roughing up some
palooka as the local sheriff holds everybody's bets. By the end of
that evening, the matter of the world's most dangerous individual,
pound for pound and bite for bite, should be settled to everyone's
satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Indiana wants him, but Lord he can't go back there. Rhode
Island? Too small to accommodate Mike's entourage.
</P>
<P>
   Fairness dictates that New Hampshire be left out of this boxing
business, too. After, all, they've got the opening presidential
primary up there. Isn't one mass invasion of crooks and clowns
every four years enough?
</P>
<P>
   Tyson's infatuation with automobiles _ he reportedly has bought
110 over the years either for himself or as gifts _ would seem to
suggest Michigan. Come to think of it, though, Mike's always had a
thing for Mercedes and Lamborghini and Rolls Royce and BMW. That
might not go over too big in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   New Mexico is still up and running after absorbing enough
underground nuclear tests to turn the toilet water eternally blue.
Can't say that a Tyson comeback fight would necessarily contaminate
the atmosphere there.
</P>
<P>
   And if all else fails, there's always Montana. When folks there
don't like the rules of their state or the federal government or
even the basic guidelines of civilized society, they simply build a
fence around their property and declare it a distinct and inviable
political entity. Tyson could buy 100 acres of ranchland somewhere
out there, name the place Ironland and elect himself as boxing
commissioner, promoter, exclusive parking vendor and, why not, Earl
of Ears, too. Goodbye, licensing problems.
</P>
<P>
   Never wonder if all these logistical problems are worth it for
boxing to sort out. After you get past Evander Holyfield's upcoming
WBA and IBF title fight with Vaughn (or is it Orson?) Bean, the
only things left on the heavyweight landscape are Lennox Lewis
defending the WBC title against some unknown Croatian and, sadly,
George Foreman fighting Larry Holmes for the WXL (World's Extra
Largest) belt.
</P>
<P>
   There is money to be made here. For this purpose the
all-consuming machine known as Mike Tyson was created. For this
purpose he will be licensed to fight again. Somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Dave George writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
