<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHTOOLS-COLUMN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Honoring the geniuses that got it all started
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Let us now remember famous men, those stalwarts of old
who made computers what they are, or perhaps what they are not,
today.
</P>
<P>
   My favorite is George Morrow. Chairman George, as he was known,
was once the Bill Gates of the computer industry back in the days
when Bill Gates was still filing his teeth into points and getting
MS-DOS ready to take over the world.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, Bill didn't have to push Chairman George off
the top of the mountain; George fell off by himself.
</P>
<P>
   I suppose George Morrow is my favorite because I owned one of
his computers, a Morrow Micro Decision. Morrow computers were based
on the CP/M operating system. CP/M stood for Control
Program/Monitor, but it might better have been called Control
Program/From Hell. It made MS-DOS look like Ned in the First
Reader.
</P>
<P>
   Hard drives were in their infancy in those days; almost no one
had one. If I remember right, adding a 10-megabyte hard drive to a
system would kick the cost up by several thousand dollars. Instead,
you had a floppy drive into which you inserted a 200k disk, and
held onto your hat as the 4 (that's right, four) MHz microprocessor
screamed up to full speed. CP/M allowed no graphics, and would look
at no more than 64k of memory.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he cast his fortune with this obviously doomed
operating system, Morrow was considered a great leader and man of
deep insight. If his choice of operating systems is not enough to
give you an idea of his insight, perhaps his final word on Local
Area Networks will be an indication.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best LAN,'' Chairman George decided, ``is a guy walking
down the hall with a floppy disk in his hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though a little red book called ``The Sayings of Chairman
George'' became a fairly hot item in the fledgling industry, Morrow
and his computer company faded rapidly from view. The last move I
can recall Morrow making was the dismantling of his customer
support operation on the simple, and probably accurate, theory that
his customers were too expensive to support.
</P>
<P>
   Other great names in computing actually predated the industry,
which may be why they remain great names.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, George Boole. Boole was an English mathematician
150 years ago who invented a kind of algebra that deals in logic
rather than in mathematics, which of course puts him right in the
philosophical lineage of George Morrow _ mathless math.
</P>
<P>
   Boole's concept was based on the simple idea that propositions
are either true or false _ no maybes _ and relationships between
these two variables can be expressed with ``operators'' such as
AND, OR and NOT.
</P>
<P>
   So you can see how Boole was really a programmer in search of a
computer, and his entire system fit perfectly into the demands of
digital computing, which deals in ones and zeroes.
</P>
<P>
   And finally we have another Briton, Alan Turing, inventor of the
Turing machine and the Turing test. The Turing machine, which he
proposed in 1936 (I am unsure whether one was actually made) was a
logical device that would scan a tape, one square at a time. The
square could contain a symbol, or it could be blank, and based on
the contents of each square the machine would make some limited
response.
</P>
<P>
   Turing's test is much more interesting, since we have yet to put
it to practical use. It is intended to reveal the point at which we
have invented an intelligent machine, and it is quite simple. It
involves one person asking a series of questions of two entities
he/she cannot see _ another person and a computer. When the time
comes that the interrogator can no longer tell which is which, we
have an intelligent machine.
</P>
<P>
   I have just one reservation about the Turing test. Who picks the
human respondent?
</P>
<P>
   Jack Warner writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
