<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-17 12:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7302 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-HANCOCK-2TAKES-BO     08-17 1190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-HANCOCK-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SCULPTOR FOR LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE TEMIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLOUCESTER, Mass. _ At 97, just one year younger than the 20th
century, Walker Hancock is pale, slim, and incandescent _ a bit
like the flames he has occasionally used in his sculptures, flames
from which noble warriors rise.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock has spent his life ennobling the human figure. He has
sculpted the great and the good, Robert Frost to Thomas Jefferson,
along with the kids in his neighborhood and the gods of ancient
myth. He gave equal dignity to all. He has spent most of his career
in the Boston area. Yet his work is not as well-known here as in
some other American cities, whose fortunate citizens see his
majestic monuments _ in a train station or a city hall, a post
office or a school _ on a daily basis. Alas, Boston has no
large-scale public work by Hancock.
</P>
<P>
   However, a plaster model for the 1990 ``Flight Memorial''
Hancock made for the US Military Academy at West Point is one of
the highlights of ``Art of the Spirit,'' a temporary exhibition at
the Forest Hills Cemetery in Jamaica Plain.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing this small work of exceptional merit made me want to see
Hancock. Meeting him was magical from the moment I started down the
long dirt road to his house and studio, a storybook complex of
slate, stone, and shingles, built beside the quarry Hancock bought
in 1930 for $1,800 _ precisely the sum he was being paid for the
``Dancing Naiads'' fountain he was making for a Long Island garden.
</P>
<P>
   The quarry waters are as still as the seas in the paintings of
an earlier Gloucester artist _ Fitz Hugh Lane. Lane's pictures are
rooted in reality yet transcend it: An almost mystical calm
pervades the best of them. The best of Hancock's figurative
sculptures also transcend the ordinary, and, like Lane's paintings,
some of them create a quiet that rivets you when you stand before
them. But in other works, Hancock creates a sense of movement so
true yet so inventive that I suspect he could have been a fine
choreographer.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock himself seems as serene as the most hushed of his
sculptures. Sitting in his parlor, an enchanting room with window
seats and a commanding stone fireplace, we pass a pleasant hour
talking about the course of his career.
</P>
<P>
   No, he says, he never wanted to be anything other than a
sculptor. Growing up in St. Louis, he started modeling clay while
still a small child. At age 9, he constructed a cardboard Parthenon
and made clay figures for its pediment. This, writes Louise Todd
Ambler in the catalog of a 1989 Hancock show at the Cape Ann
Historical Museum, was indication not only of Hancock's early
interest in sculpture, but also in sculpture in the context of
architecture.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock studied art at Central High School in St. Louis and at
Washington University there. He was something of a prodigy,
receiving his first commission at 18 _ for a World War I memorial
for Central High, in the form of a bronze tablet. In the summer of
1920, the 19-year-old made a pilgrimage to Gloucester to meet his
idol, portrait sculptor Charles Grafly. He lost his nerve on
Grafly's doorstep, an attack of shyness causing him to bolt. In the
fall, though, he went to Philadelphia to enroll in Grafly's classes
at the Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts, and the next summer,
Grafly invited Hancock to share his Gloucester studio. After
Grafly's untimely death in 1929, Hancock took over his mentor's
teaching duties.
</P>
<P>
   He fell so in love with Gloucester that he commuted from Cape
Ann to Philadelphia by bus, train, and boat. The long dirt road to
his home wasn't always plowed. ``There were times,'' he recalls,
``when I had to get out of here on skis, which I'd leave at the
drugstore.''
</P>
<P>
   About the drugstore. It was in Lanesville, Hancock emphasizes.
Technically, Lanesville is part of Gloucester. To its residents, it
is a separate town _ possibly even a separate country. ``It used to
be completely self-sufficient,'' Hancock recalls, ticking off its
amenities: barbers, grocery stores, pharmacy. ``It was also almost
a Finnish colony,'' he adds. ``The Finns had come to work in the
quarries.'' Hancock married the daughter of a local Finnish family,
Saima Natti, whose brothers were among the boys who regularly went
skinny-dipping in Hancock's quarry. (Saima Hancock died in 1984;
she and her husband had one daughter, Deane, who lives in western
Massachusetts.) The muscular youths also served as models for the
sculptor's warriors and mythical creatures, who tend to have the
high cheekbones of Finns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned to sing in Finnish,'' Hancock says, ``and to
pronounce it, but not to speak it.'' The foreign languages he does
speak are French and Italian, the latter learned from listening to
opera recordings. Both languages stood him in good stead in his
travels, which included a three-year stint in Italy after winning
the Prix de Rome in 1925 for his head of a boy named Toivo Helberg,
an orphaned Finnish refugee. The boy's expression is as delicate as
the traditional embroidery on the shirt he wears. He is grave and
composed, his stillness more telling than any histrionic gesture
would be.
</P>
<P>
   Both in intimately scaled works like the head of Helberg and in
his large-scale monuments, Hancock is heir to a tradition of
academic, realist sculpture, the tradition of Augustus
Saint-Gaudens and Daniel Chester French. Hancock was friends with
French, who died in 1931. ``He always said how much he hated
trousers,'' Hancock recalls _ not wearing them, but sculpting them.
</P>
<P>
   Of course a sculptor of nonrepresentational subjects needn't
grapple with the drape of a pant leg. Hancock came of age along
with abstraction, but the style was not for him. ``I had good
friends among abstract sculptors,'' he says, ``and found myself in
agreement with them intellectually. But my heart wasn't in it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Heart'' is what his sculpture has that much other contemporary
realist work lacks. Figurative sculpture is currently at a low
point. And Cape Ann has become as much a magnet for second-rate
derivative sculpture as Monet's Giverny was _ and still is _ for
second-rate derivative painting. Lane himself is the subject of an
appalling sculpture recently installed in Gloucester, a clumsy,
smarmy bronze portrait parked right beside Lane's hilltop house.
The bronzed Birkenstocks of the statue's maker, the late Alfred
Duca, are placed nearby, along with the inscribed suggestion that
you ``Step into my shoes and become inspired.''
</P>
<P>
   At the other extreme, in both modesty and grace, is Hancock's
own ``Triton,'' in the corner of Glouces-ter's Stage Fort Park that
is dedicated to the late Elizabeth Gordon Smith, the much-loved
founder of the Gloucester Civic and Garden Council. The whole
sculpture is one smooth arc, from the triton's upturned flippers to
the conch shell he blows to make sounds that, according to myth,
can control the wild movements of the sea. ``Triton'' is hardly
radical _ Hancock's work has never been about aesthetic revolution
_ but it's beautiful and believable.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
