<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOFTWARE LACKS ABILITY TO TRACK SMALL PORTFOLIOS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Can you write something about software available to small
investors? I would like to have a better understanding of the math
involved when you discuss returns on investments. What spreadsheets
do you use to keep track of your investments?
</P>
<P>
   L.S., Colton, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. You have touched on one of my great frustrations _ the
inability to find computer software that suits me to track small
portfolios. I now use Quicken Version 4.0 for Windows _ and I am
underwhelmed. Some of my complaints are minor _ for example, the
process of deleting old market price figures is clumsy and
time-consuming. But, more important, Quicken wants its program to
monitor my entire financial life, not just a few portfolios, and I
am continually required to compensate for its desires to balance a
stock portfolio with other accounts and functions I am not using.
</P>
<P>
   I have tried a number of other portfolio-tracking software
packages, but they have all been tied to market quote services that
I would have to buy; to assure that cheapskates like me don't
ignore the service, the only way to enter market prices is through
the automatic download over the Internet. No thanks.
</P>
<P>
   For a time some years back, I subscribed to America Online,
which offered an easy, albeit superficial, portfolio tracking
system. To me, that one strong feature was insufficient to
compensate for other frustrations I encountered with AOL, so I
moved on.
</P>
<P>
   I would be delighted to hear if some reader knows of an elegant
software package that allows you to track an investment portfolio
without paying for an on-line quote service or being a part of a
more complex package.
</P>
<P>
   My most indispensable tool for financial projections is a
program called Interest Vision from Parsons Technology (available
for $24.95 at www.parsonstech.com). I usually use an old edition
called Interest Vision Special Edition, which came free with an
income tax software package years ago. Last year I bought Interest
Vision 2.0, which is the one they're now selling, and the
improvements seem to be minimal. The program does save me hours
over the time I once spent with a hand-held financial analysis
calculator.
</P>
<P>
   For calculations involving effects of projected inflation, I go
on line to a site at www.hetherman.com/tools/
</P>
<P>
   inflatnc.html. Another site provides a record of historical
inflation and its effects on money during historical periods:
www.westegg.com/inflation.
</P>
<P>
   For market quotes, trading histories, and general information on
individual stocks, I use the Infoseek Financial Channel, but almost
any search engine will have a prominent source for such market
information.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, for spreadsheets, I use the spreadsheet function that
came with Microsoft Works of many years ago. I know it's probably
similar to a quill pen when compared to more modern programs, but
it works.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My husband and I are both 43, and our combined yearly income
is $160,000. We have no children and have not focused on our
retirement until recently. I have a 403(b) account through my
employer, which provides a menu of Fidelity funds for investment. I
have $22,000 in Fidelity Contrafund, $12,000 in Fidelity Growth and
Income, $5,000 in Fidelity Low-Priced Stock, and $5,000 in Fidelity
Select Health Care. My husband is self-employed and has just opened
a SEP account, putting $4,000 in Oakmark fund. In addition, we have
IRAs of $13,000 in Fidelity Contrafund, $18,000 in Fidelity Growth
and Income, and $4,000 in the Schwab 1000 fund.
</P>
<P>
   Could you comment on our assortment of funds. My employer adds
$90 a week to my 403(b) account, and we can add a further $100 a
week to these investments. We expect to retire in 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   B.N., Lexington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. There's no major problem with your fund selections, but there
is a different problem _ you're not putting enough in them. It's
not clear from your letter whether you expect to add a total of
$100 a week to your savings and whether you plan to maintain annual
contributions of $4,000 to your husband's SEP account.
</P>
<P>
   Using the best case, I combined $100 weekly from you, $90 a week
from your employer, and $4,000 annually for your husband's SEP
account _ for a total of $1,156.66 a month. Over the course of 25
years, an investment program starting at $83,000 with these
contributions would grow to $2,326,821, presuming 10 percent
average annual growth.
</P>
<P>
   That may sound OK _ although not terrific for people whose
living standard is based on $160,000 annual income. But it gets
worse. During each of those 25 years you can count on inflation
gnawing away at the buying power of your nest egg. If we presume 3
percent average annual inflation for that period, your buying power
shrinks to $1,111,302 in today's money; if we presume 4 percent
inflation, the figure falls to $872,829. You might expect that
latter number to produce an income stream of about $60,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   The upshot of all this is simply that you need to save more _ at
least twice as much.
</P>
<P>
   Now, getting back to your fund choices, they're all good funds.
But like many current investors, you have a portfolio heavily
dominated by the large caps _ Fidelity's Contrafund, Growth and
Income, Oakmark, and Schwab 1000 fund all concentrate their
investments in the large-cap area. Fidelity Low-Priced Stock and
Health Care represent a good start at diversification, but you need
to go further, building each of those holdings to 10 percent of the
portfolio and adding funds such as Fidelity Mid-Cap Stock and
Fidelity Overseas.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My husband and I have approximately $34,000 in Franklin US
Government Securities fund. We also have a $7,500 CD, which earns
6.1 percent interest and which matures in December of 2000. Would
it be better to cash out the CD now, adding the amount to the
Franklin account, or just leave it alone? The early withdrawal
penalty is 90 days' interest, which doesn't seem like much compared
to the increased yield.
</P>
<P>
   K.D., Poway, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. There's not much to gain. Ignoring sales changes for the
mutual fund, let's just do the math. Morningstar Mutual Funds lists
the yield on Franklin US Government Securities fund at 6.9 percent.
If you left your $7,500 in the CD for 28 months, it would grow to
$8,615.03. If you cashed out, paying $114.38 in penalties, you
would have $7,385.62 to put in the Franklin fund. At 6.9 percent
interest, that would grow to $8,634.63 over the course of 28
months, giving you a theoretical gain of $19.60.
</P>
<P>
   Now, even if there were no issue of a sales charge, it seems to
me that when you compare the federal deposit insurance that stands
behind the CD with the market uncertainty that applies to a mutual
fund, the loss of $19.60 is immaterial.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, of course, there is the sales load. Franklin tells me
that the effective yield on a new purchase _ which means that the
yield adjusted for the 4.5 percent sales charge _ is 6.17 percent.
If you invested $7,385.62 for 28 months at 6.17 percent, you would
end up with $8,496.79 _ $118.24 less than you'd have by holding the
CD.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass.
02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
