<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CHILD-SERVICES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUIT TARGETS NYC CHILD WELFARE AGENCY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two-and-a-half years ago, at age 63, Nicholas
Scoppetta quit his $400,000-a-year law practice to take one of the
most harrowing jobs in New York City government _ head of the
child-welfare agency, a bureaucratic maze responsible for
protecting 42,000 children in foster care and an additional 53,000
allegedly neglected or abused.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have lots of friends who say, `Why are you taking this
on?''' Scoppetta acknowledged, sitting at his desk in an aptly
ramshackle building in lower Manhattan. ``I'm not saying it's not
wearing, but it feels so right doing this. It does feel right.''
</P>
<P>
   The key to these feelings is a 5- by 8-inch file card, framed
and tucked away in a corner of his office. Dated March 18, 1938,
and marked ``Case No. 1,145,155,'' it's the Rosebud sled of
Nicholas Scoppetta's life _ the official documentation of his own
time as a foster child.
</P>
<P>
   From age 4 1/2 to 12, the entirety of his formative years,
Scoppetta lived with 120 other boys in an orphanage-like foster
home in the Bronx called Woodycrest. Clearly, his taking this job
now, and the passion with which he pursues it, stem from that
experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``As my wife the therapist often says,'' Scoppetta remarked with
a smile, ``what I'm feeling is _ I'm feeling very sorry for that
little 5-year-old who went into Woodycrest. Obviously, there's some
personal identification.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the next month, his mission of self-redemption could be
derailed. Marcia Robinson Lowry, executive director of Children's
Rights Inc., is suing Scoppetta's agency _ charging it with
incurable mismanagement _ and demanding that its work be turned
over to a new director appointed and monitored by the courts.
</P>
<P>
   A trial is scheduled for Sept. 16, though the two sides are
discussing a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Both Scoppetta's appointment and Lowry's lawsuit were brought on
by the same little girl _ 6-year-old Elisa Izquierdo, who in
November 1995 was murdered by her mother.
</P>
<P>
   Elisa's death shocked the city. A bright, charming girl who had
just won a scholarship to a private school, she was repeatedly
brutalized by her mother. The city's child-welfare inspector, who
visited her home regularly because of past complaints, did not
notice the warning signs.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani dealt with the shock by removing child
welfare from the city's labyrinthine Human Resources Department,
and creating an independent agency to be headed by Scoppetta _ whom
he knew from their years as prosecutors in the US attorney's
office.
</P>
<P>
   Lowry dealt with the Izquierdo case by suing the city, as she
had sued several other cities for poor child-welfare practices.
</P>
<P>
   Like Scoppetta, Lowry has been involved in New York's
foster-care system, but from the other side of the table, working
as special assistant to Barbara Blum, the child-welfare
commissioner in the early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was called a `reform commissioner,' too,'' Lowry recalled.
``I got quite an eyeful. Very depressing but extremely educational.
... There was very little I could really do _ anyone can really do
_ on the inside, so I moved to a position where I could exert
pressure from the outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a '60s liberal,'' she said with a smile. ``I went to law
school to help people. I believe courts are the last refuge of the
powerless.''
</P>
<P>
   Scoppetta wants the lawsuit dismissed, arguing that his new
agency has just initiated a package of reforms. He has hired 1,200
new caseworkers, improved training, computerized the filing system,
and will soon decentralize the system so foster children are kept
in the same neighborhoods as their parents' homes, to minimize the
trauma of disruption.
</P>
<P>
   Lowry waves aside his reform plan, saying it has no provisions
for measuring success or failure. She also cites official
documents, complaining that the new computer system is a disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, he's a good person,'' Lowry said of Scoppetta. ``But
I don't think that matters. It may even be a problem _ because he
can lull people into thinking, `Well, he's a good person, so things
must be getting better.'''
</P>
<P>
   According to the city's own records, deaths of children being
monitored by the agency went up last year _ from 26 to 33 _ and, to
Lowry, that's what matters.
</P>
<P>
   However, some other children's advocates hesitate to put the
blame entirely on the city agency.
</P>
<P>
   Bernice Manshel of the New Jersey Juvenile Justice Commission,
and a former director of that state's child-welfare agency, said:
``Social problems aren't going to be solved by a child-welfare
agency. All a child-welfare agency can try to do is pick up the
pieces.''
</P>
<P>
   By his own admission, Scoppetta was a foster child in a very
different time. Woodycrest, he recalled in a wistful, even
nostalgic tone, ``was a big Gothic structure with a big courtyard.
We had a gym, a swimming pool, lived in dorms. It was an immaculate
facility. Every Saturday, the older kids did this housekeeping that
you wouldn't believe _ waxed and buffed, scrubbed down the
bathrooms. I went to school in Woodycrest, played in the courtyard.
Yankee Stadium was right across the street and you could hear the
sounds of the ball game.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he often wonders if such institutions _ which have been
abandoned, in favor of placing foster children into families _
might work today. ``It might be easier to have 15 to 20 excellent
staff to take care of 120 kids,'' he said, ``than to find 120
excellent foster homes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' he quickly added, ``my advisers shoot me down on this.
There's absolutely no support for large institutions as an
approach, philosophically.''
</P>
<P>
   The big difference between now and then, as he sees it, is
social. ``We were kids of the Depression,'' he said of his
generation of foster children. ``We were kids who, for economic
reasons, needed someone to feed them and take care of them. Today,
75 percent of our foster kids come from families with substance
abuse. That complicates matters enormously. These kids come from
much more troubled backgrounds.''
</P>
<P>
   The population of foster children in New York City nearly
tripled in the late 1980s, the era of the crack epidemic, and
agencies shuffled them into homes with more speed than care.
</P>
<P>
   Still, though many children's advocates agree with Lowry's
critique of Scoppetta's agency, they question her solution of
turning everything over to a court-appointed receiver.
</P>
<P>
   ``The notion of a receiver,'' said Carolyn Kubitschek, president
of the National Coalition for Child Protection Reform, ``is that
the boss is doing a bad job and there's somebody you can put there
who can do a better job. The problem is, it's just a terrible
agency, they do a terrible job. Nobody who's put there does a
particularly good job.''
</P>
<P>
   Kubitschek noted that in Washington, D.C., where Lowry won a
similar lawsuit, ``the child-welfare system hasn't improved by
being put under a receiver.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover some of Scoppetta's new ideas have won the concurrence
even of pessimistic reformers.
</P>
<P>
   Manshel recently attended a workshop where a private company,
hired by Scoppetta, demonstrated new techniques they are using to
train New York City child-welfare case workers. ``The training
sounded great,'' Manshel said. ``They were dealing with very
concrete, insightful ways of how to see danger signs in the homes
they're inspecting.
</P>
<P>
   ``But then,'' she added, ``someone asked when they'd be training
the foster-care staff _ the people who make the decisions on when
kids go back to their parents. And they said, `Oh, we're not
getting to that level for three years.'''
</P>
<P>
   Manshel let out something between a laugh and a sigh. ``They're
trying real hard,'' she said. ``Meanwhile, terrible things are
happening. It takes a long time to do anything right in this
field.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-98 1257EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
