<HEADLINE>
WHAT KEEPS HEARTS BEATING? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ROPEIK  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. How do hearts beat?
</P>
<P>
   B.D., Dublin, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. That simple question requires a detailed answer.
</P>
<P>
   Let's let Dr. Peter Friedman, electrophysiologist in the cardiac
department of Brigham and Women's Hospital in Boston, give us a
tour of the heart and explain its vital mechanism:
</P>
<P>
   The heart beat starts in a clump of special cells called the
sinoatrial (SA) node in the top right corner of your heart.
</P>
<P>
   These pacemaker cells are special because they leak. One leak in
the cell membrane lets positively-charged sodium ions (atoms of
sodium that have lost one or more of their electrons) flow in. Just
down the cell wall, another lets positively-charged potassium ions
flow out.
</P>
<P>
   The outer membranes of most of the cells in your body, including
these pacemaker cells, are like whiffle balls, perforated with
passageways specialized to let certain things in and out. But those
passageways are usually closed. They open only when triggered to do
so by some chemical signal.
</P>
<P>
   Pacemaker cells are different. Their passageways for sodium and
potassium open on their own, with no `external' commands. And they
do it all the time; they're built to leak. That's the key.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the pacemaker cell, where the positively-charged sodium
ions leak in, the electrical charge gets more positive. Think of it
as a group of little plus signs, with more and more plus signs
joining in. Right next to that, where the potassium is leaking out,
plus signs are leaving and the charge gets less positive.
Eventually the difference between the more positively-charged spot
with extra plus signs, and the less positively-charged spot with
fewer plus signs, gets big enough that, in essence, it creates a
spark. That's called an action potential. And then things are off
to the races.
</P>
<P>
   The action potential spreads throughout rest of the cell. All
over the cell wall, more sodium and potassium channels rapidly
open. That causes the whole cell to put out an even bigger
``spark,'' triggering neighboring pacemaker cells to do the same
thing. Almost instantaneously, the whole SA node is sending out a
strong electrical charge.
</P>
<P>
   The charge travels in milliseconds to the heart's muscle cells,
where it tell proteins to make the muscle contract. Special tight
connections between all heart muscle cells let the electrical
charge flow through at pretty much at the same instant. Which is
why they all contract in unison.
</P>
<P>
   But why, if everything happens at once, is the heart beat a
``lub-dub?'' Why not just a ``lub'' or a ``dub?''
</P>
<P>
   The heart has two chambers on the top, a right and left atrium,
and two larger ones below, a right and left ventricle. The
electrical charge racing down from the SA node hits the atria
first, and they contract, squeezing the oxygen-depleted blood
entering the right atrium from elsewhere in the body, and the
freshly-oxygenated blood entering the left atrium from the lungs.
</P>
<P>
   But the signal runs into a little roadblock on its way down to
trigger the ventricles. It has to go through some special relay
cells that are designed to hold things up. They take a tiny
fraction of a second longer to reach their action potential, fire,
and send the signal down to the lower half of the heart. That delay
gives the muscles up in the atrium a moment to squeeze the blood
that's come in and build up pressure. Finally that pressure forces
valves open and the blood rushes down into the ventricles. The
``lub'' is the sound of those valves closing.
</P>
<P>
   At almost the same time, the electrical charge, having triggered
those relay cells, gets sent along to the ventricles. But though
the charge comes in at the top, it doesn't hit any muscle cells in
the upper part of the ventricles. Instead, special nerves carry it
straight to the bottom. The charge then starts spreading up, and
the muscles of the large ventricles contract, bottom-to-top, like
rolling up a tube of toothpaste starting at the end.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;   &UR;  &LR; That squeezes the oxygenated blood from the top of the left
ventricle out to the body, and the oxygen-depleted blood from the
top of the right ventricle on toward the lungs to freshen up. When
the blood's gone and the ventricular valves close, that's ``dub.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on an average adult heart beat of 72 per minute, that
whole incredible process happened about 200 times while you were
reading this!
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
