<SLUG> BC-SCI-FLOOD-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN EARLIER FIX ON FLOOD THREATS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although they pack little of the fast-moving drama of tornadoes,
blizzards or hurricanes, floods are America's deadliest weather
disasters, killing on average 141 people a year _ more than all the
violent windstorms combined.
</P>
<P>
   And though inundations can usually be predicted many hours or
even days ahead of time, unlike tornadoes and some other freak
weather events, flooding forecasts have sometimes fallen short _
most spectacularly in last year's deluge that wiped out Grand
Forks, N.D. Better warnings, experts agree, would offer enormous
benefits to residents, farmers and business owners in low-lying
riverfront lands.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, an elaborate new model for forecasting river floods
developed by a Massachusetts Institute of Technology professor has
drawn considerable interest from federal officials, who think it
could yield much timelier, more accurate flood alerts.
</P>
<P>
   Rafael L. Bras, chairman of MIT's civil and environmental
engineering department, will receive a substantial NASA grant next
month to test and perfect his model, which crunches hundreds of
times more data than standard models and also factors in hilliness
and local soil composition to determine when and where river basins
might flood.
</P>
<P>
   The National Weather Service is also planning to compare it to
current models and see what aspects could be incorporated in them.
</P>
<P>
   Driven in part by wild El Nino-related weather, 1998 has proven
a devastating year for floods in the US. Two Wisconsin boys were
swept into a creek and drowned this month. Flooding in June storms
left 23 dead or missing around the country, including a
four-month-old and a blind man in a wheelchair swept away in West
Virginia. March storms claimed five lives in Alabama, and floods
after torrential February rains in California were blamed for seven
deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Flood deaths are much less frequent in New England than the
South or Midwest, but in the last two years, Massachusetts has been
hit by two major inundations that sent raw sewage pouring into the
Charles and other rivers, including this past June's storms.
</P>
<P>
   Around the country, the Weather Service operates 13 river
forecast centers that monitor river levels at about 4,000 places,
including about 30 in southern New England.
</P>
<P>
   Generally speaking, the predictions treat river basins as the
equivalent of one big sponge whose water content depends on the
last 10 days of rain. New rainfall is measured in six-hour chunks
to evaluate when and if rivers might start to flood.
</P>
<P>
   There are obvious drawbacks, Weather Service officials
acknowledge. Their standard model does not differentiate, for
example, between six hours of steady drizzle or a sudden downpour,
which might be much more likely to trigger a flood.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does it consider where the rain is falling _ on a steep
hillside, a heavily developed urban area with non-porous streets
and parking lots, or sandy fields that drain quickly.
</P>
<P>
   All of those shortcomings can be addressed, however, in Bras's
model, which he has tested in Italy's Sieve River basin near
Florence. He hopes to evaluate it in several US river basins over
the next year.
</P>
<P>
   Bras's model can get into much finer detail by taking readings
from the Weather Service's new NEXRAD high-resolution radar to
estimate rainfall in each 1.5-square-mile region within a river
basin every 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Then it correlates that rain data to digital maps showing the
prevailing topography, soil types, and soil saturation within each
region. High-powered computers crunch all the numbers to determine
how much rain is likely to be running off those regions into the
river, and even forecast where within a basin flooding is
likeliest.
</P>
<P>
   In technical terms, Bras's approach is known as a ``distributed
model,'' taking lots of observations in space and time, as opposed
to the ``lumped parameter'' models the Weather Service uses that
treat a river basin as one big spot getting one big splash of rain
every six hours. The government of Italy, the Weather Service, and
the US Army have all provided research grants over the last six
years to help him develop it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an exciting project that will help guide the types of
models we do in the future,'' said Michael Smith, a research
hydrologist at the US Weather Service's Silver Spring, Md., office,
who has collaborated with Bras. ``It runs all the equations on a
much finer scale than we are able to do now.''
</P>
<P>
   A major open question, as Bras agrees, is whether the Weather
Service could run the enormously complicated calculations quickly
enough to warn residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a computational cost, and the potential for
overwhelming a computer system or slowing it down,'' Smith said.
Agreed Robert Shedd of the Northeast River Forecast Center &UR;  &LR; in
Taunton, Mass.: ``Being able to implement it in an operational
setting becomes a much bigger issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Weather Service does not get a lot of criticism for
bad flood forecasting _ though it understandably becomes a whipping
boy after dramatic, once-in-a-lifetime disaster such as the North
Dakota floods of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   As early as February, two full months before the flooding Red
River of the North wiped out Grand Forks, N.D., and sister city
East Grand Forks, Minn., sending 59,000 residents fleeing, the
Weather Service was warning of record floods as the snow melted.
</P>
<P>
   North Dakota governor Ed Schafer promptly declared a statewide
emergency and urged residents of low-lying areas to buy flood
insurance. Through March and April, Minneapolis-based hydrologists
predicted the river would crest at 49 feet and spread far out into
the cookie-sheet flat terrain.
</P>
<P>
   By April 14, after a blizzard dumped major rain and snow on the
region, the Weather Service began ramping its predictions upward.
By April 18, it was predicting a 54-foot flood crest, which indeed
came three days later, but contradicted the 49-foot prediction
local officials had been counting on for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The angry mayor of East Grand Forks, Lynn Stauss, told a crowd
of evacuees: ``They missed it, and they not only missed it, they
blew it big.'' Stauss later backed off those harsh charges.
</P>
<P>
   What Weather Service forecasters learned from the Red River
disaster was that submerged bridges will act as dams, aggravating
flooding, and the piling of sandbags on levees actually made the
river rise higher still and flow faster.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the computer could not calculate was the impact of
sandbags and bridges on the flow,'' Minnesota-based Weather Service
hydrologist Dean Braatz said. ``Neither had ever been factors
before (because) we've never had water that high before.''
</P>
<P>
   Similar complaints followed unexpectedly bad floods near
Pittsburgh in January 1996 and Los Angeles's Sepulveda Basin in
February 1992. And, of course, the Weather Service gets blasted for
forecasts that later prove too dire as well.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in February 1997, Van Buren, Ark., port officials
complained that a forecast led them to scramble to bring in crews
to spend four feverish hours raising levees along the Arkansas
River before forecasters dropped their predictions of the flood
crest by 3 1/2 feet. Two soybean farmers complained that they had
ruined a combine harvester they tried to drive through flooded
roads to escape a flood that never came.
</P>
<P>
   Without more testing, it is not clear whether Bras's model would
avoid failings such as those, but Weather Service and other
officials think it has major promise.
</P>
<P>
   In this area, flood forecast complaints have been rare. ``At
least here in southern New England, we've got a great track record,
an excellent model,'' said David R. Vallee, a senior hydrologist at
the Weather Service's Taunton office, which includes a forecast
center covering New England and New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``The times we get behind the 8-ball are when we have very
heavy, very hard hitting, and very long-lasting rains, or heavy
snow melt. That's very hard to predict,'' Vallee said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Weather Service can offer only limited predictions along
Massachusetts rivers. For example, flood warnings for the Assabet,
Concord, Charles, and Neponset are based on readings from single
flood gauges in Maynard, Lowell, Dover, and Norwood, which may not
reflect the possibility of localized floods in other communities.
</P>
<P>
   Bras, who won a $50,000 National Water Research Institute prize
earlier this year for his work in hydrology and has published two
textbooks and more than 100 journal articles, said as interested as
he is in improving forecasts, he hopes he can also get better media
publicity for existing flood warnings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Weather service river flood warnings for southern New England,
updated several times daily, can be found on the World Wide Web at:
http://www.nws.noaa.gov/er/box/)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-98 1259EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
