<HEADLINE>
PLEASE NOTE, PARK'S THEME IS POLITENESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA CLAUS, Ind. _ Even in howdy Hoosier land, the Koch family
does not take good manners for granted.
</P>
<P>
   At orientation sessions each spring, the Koches' employees spend
an hour on politeness. They practice saying please and thank you,
hello and goodbye. They work on their smiles. By midsummer, the
``bless you'' offered sneezing customers is automatic.
</P>
<P>
   The Koch family prides itself on owning the friendliest
amusement park in the nation. Now it's official. The latest issue
of Amusement Today, a trade publication, awarded Holiday World and
Splashin' Safari a ``Golden Ticket'' for having a staff even
friendlier than the Disney folks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a rural area, so I think people are naturally more
relaxed, less jaded,'' said Will Koch, Holiday World president,
whose family has owned and operated the park for three generations.
``Plus we work at it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Koch, who has 850 employees, most of them 14 to 19 years old,
said the honor is especially gratifying. Teenagers will be
teenagers, even in rural southern Indiana. They can be moody or
unintentionally mean. The other day one insisted on counting a
little girl's dropped ball as an official toss at one of the park's
games. Her father complained. Koch refunded his money with a smile
and made a mental note to talk to the teenager.
</P>
<P>
   Strolling through the park, Koch pointed to an older woman as an
example of the kind of employee who makes the park hum.
</P>
<P>
   Carrying a broom with a dustpan, and laden with cleaning
supplies, the woman was sweeping trash with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hi, mom,'' Koch said to her.
</P>
<P>
   Six days a week, sometimes seven, Pat Koch is at Holiday World.
She figures that her young employees will be more willing to work
for their money, about $5.50 an hour, when they see that menial
chores are not beneath the boss.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're fortunate to be in the Midwest, where people still wave
at each other and say `hi' to strangers,'' said Pat Koch. ``But
even we, well ... this is the end of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   At that she laughed warmly, implying that her patience can be
worn thin by crying children and complaining parents. Not that she
would ever show it in the park. As her son explained, ``When you
deal with the public, you have to make a decision that whatever
they dish out, you'll take it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Koch family has been dealing with the public since 1946,
when it opened the nation's first theme park and called it Santa
Claus Land, after the rides celebrating Christmas and the town
where children still send their postcards filled with wishes every
December. In 1984, they added Halloween and the Fourth of July,
with rides to match, and renamed the place Holiday World. Six years
ago, Surfin' Safari, a water park packed with slides and
interactive adventures, went up beside it.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion has paid off in customers. More than 500,000
people a year visit the 100-acre park, which is surrounded by
forest and farmland and not visible from any major highway. Will
Koch said five times more people visit the park now than in 1975.
Most of them come by car, from within a three-hour radius. The
season runs from May to October.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the park has added more restaurants, concert
dates, and rides to help keep the waiting times short, usually
under 15 minutes. One of the new rides is a $2 million roller
coaster that Amusement Today named the second-best in the world.
Monsoon Lagoon, a tree house of sorts that offers 60 ways to get
wet, was added this year.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Inside Track, a newspaper for roller coaster
enthusiasts, named Holiday World's staff second friendliest in its
annual poll. Now Amusement Today has made them No. 1 for the first
time. The Koch family, which has resisted selling their business to
a corporation, takes the kudos personally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who hires teenagers knows how tough it can be to find
the right ones,'' said Will Koch. ``But kids like it here because
it's a real social environment. It's better than sitting on a
lawnmower all day. Hopefully, that shows in their attitude.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
