<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDEPENDENT VOTE IS NOT THE ONLY PROBLEM FOR CELLUCCI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT JORDAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Instead of looking ahead toward his November election
battle with Democratic gubernatorial front-runner Scott
Harshbarger, it might be more prudent for Acting Governor Paul
Cellucci to look back over his shoulder at GOP primary rival Joseph
Malone.
</P>
<P>
   One reason Cellucci is having a harder-than-expected time
against Malone is Cellucci's recent budget cuts. They may be
appealing to some conservative GOP voters, but they have alienated
those voters who, while often voting Democratic in the past, this
year were considing backing the GOP candidate. Anger over the
budget cuts has sent them scurrying back to the Democratic fold.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason is the likelihood that independent voters _ upon
whom Cellucci depends _ are going elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   These are the voters who are largely responsible for former
governor William Weld's election victories over the years, and
Cellucci needs them in his corner.
</P>
<P>
   But many independent voters this year are attracted to other hot
primary contests _ sucn as the 8th Congressional District seat that
is being vacated this year by US Representative Joseph P. Kennedy
II.
</P>
<P>
   The winner among the 10 Democrats in the primary is likely to be
victorious in November.
</P>
<P>
   Voters who decide to cast ballots in the Democratic primary will
not be able to vote for any GOP candidate in the primary, be it in
the gubernatorial or congressional contests.
</P>
<P>
   Another race that could pull Cellucci's potential independent
vote away from the GOP side of the primary ballot is the bitter
battle for state attorney general between District Attorney Thomas
Reilly and State Senator Lois Pines. Many independent voters have
strong feelings toward each candidate, and they may decide to vote
in the Democratic primary for their choice, leaving them out of the
GOP gubernatorial primary.
</P>
<P>
   Even the hotly contested Democratic primary for Middlesex County
district attorney is attracting the interest of independent voters,
further enhancing the possibility that Cellucci's potential base of
support will instead vote in the Democratic primary.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not just hot Democratic primary contests that are
responsible for Cellucci's apparent voter emigration problems.
</P>
<P>
   If, for example, sentiment in Lynn is any indication, Cellucci's
budget cuts have created more for himself than he realizes.
</P>
<P>
   The reading of political tea leaves in Lynn goes like this:
Several elected officials in Lynn openly supported Democratic
gubernatorial candidate Patricia McGovern at the party's June
convention. Presuming she loses to Harshbarger in the Democratic
gubernatorial primary, at least some of those voters would have
likely gone over to Cellucci in November, rather than align
themselves with Harshbarger, McGovern's primary foe.
</P>
<P>
   But that scenario is now less likely because Lynn residents are
irritated at Cellucci over his budget cuts. Those cuts cost the
city $400,000 to repair a popular ball field in Lynn and $1.5
million to fix a seawall in the city. The cuts also robbed Lynn
lawmakers of the ability to get political mileage out of the money
they brought home to the city. In short, Cellucci's cuts alienated
both Democratic officials and independent voters in the city.
</P>
<P>
   All Harshbarger has to do, noted one political strategist, is go
into cities such as Lynn and remind voters that Cellucci took away
their field, their seawall, and other important amenities simply
for his own political self-interest.
</P>
<P>
   As for Malone, he has continued to blast Cellucci in recent
advertisements, suggesting that Cellucci's appointments are
evidence that he is more Democratic than Republican. Malone is
hoping that these ads resonate with the hard-core GOP electorate
that may be a decisive factor in the Republican primary.
</P>
<P>
   While he would be wise to focus on his battle with Malone for
the GOP nomination, Cellucci cannot afford to totally ignore
Harshbarger's candidacy. In a recent poll that included, among
other issues, questions of voter preference toward Harshbarger and
Cellucci, Harshbarger had 37 percent and Cellucci 35, a virtual
dead heat.
</P>
<P>
   For an incumbent governor to be in a tie with a challenger at
this stage of the election does not bode well for Cellucci. Worse,
any time an incumbent is below 50 percent in voter support in the
polls, he is at least politically vulnerable. If the polls have
Cellucci under 40 percent, as does this one, he has real problems
to solve before November.
</P>
<P>
   But for the next four weeks, Cellucci had better focus on
defeating his GOP challenger running hard behind him, or he may be
seeing Malone's back as they sprint to the finish line in the
Republican primary.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Robert A. Jordan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
