<DOCNO> NYT19980817.0162 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-17 13:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7338 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-SAVING-2ND &LR;  &UR; TA     08-17 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-SAVING-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... of my own.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What a punk I must have seemed to him, with my moral indignation
and my college allowance! I knew young men who fled to Canada; from
the antiwar hotbed of Austin, Texas, I counseled others on how to
avoid the draft, then flew home for the holidays to embarrass my
father by bringing up Vietnam in front of guests. While my own
position about US involvement in Vietnam was flushed with both
dovish sentiment and youthful political analysis, my father's
defense of our presence there was simple old-school patriotism and
old-style manliness. You went where you were told; you fought the
good fight (it was good because it was American); then you came
home and never mentioned it again.
</P>
<P>
   Some three decades later, I doubt either of our stances has
softened much. I only partly regret my naivete and incendiary
anger, not at all my idealism; he, less introspective than I, is
content if the stock market holds and his tax bill stays the same.
Nowadays the phone calls and visits are sweet with memories and an
old love unshaken by any war. We are the retired master sergeant
and his pacifist daughter, remembering not the fury between us, but
the spelling bees and sixth-grade pageants that preceded them.
</P>
<P>
   That is the twilight blessing of parental aging, and so now my
heart can swell at the photos of my father in uniform, going off to
a war where _ I have only just learned _ he slept with a knife
under his pillow every night, where every night he said the same
simple prayer before he went to sleep: ``Dear Lord, thank thee for
letting me be alive today.'' Three years ago, he told me that
sometimes the helmets of dead soldiers wound up at the supply depot
in Blackpool, where it was his unit's job to clean them up; to
clean off the blood and sometimes brains and send them out again.
That same night, he said he had opted for a slow boat home at the
end of the war, even though the choice kept him in England for an
extra month. He had become afraid to fly: ``That'll happen to you,
after you've seen a test pilot jump from a burning plane with his
arm on fire.''
</P>
<P>
   My imagination's passion about war has grown out of a more
sheltered existence, cemented in the past two decades by the
cultural iconography that followed Vietnam: books by Robert Stone
and Michael Herr and Tim O'Brien, movies like ``Apocalypse Now''
and ``Full Metal Jacket,'' like ``Platoon'' and ``Casualties of
War.'' And though I've seen and read what must be hundreds of
depictions of World War II, never have those dual sensibilities so
emotionally merged for me as they did that afternoon in ``Saving
Private Ryan.'' If Spielberg has created in many ways an
old-fashioned, sentimental war movie, he's nonetheless done so with
his signature stamp of the immensity of history. Thanks to those
first 28 minutes alone, the nobility of the film is far greater
than the sum of its cliches.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the power of cinema is that it does our creative work
for us: Unlike the case in prose, where the journey realized is one
of intensely personal interpretation, we're bombarded in the movies
with visual fanfare that often overwhelms the imagination. At its
best, the medium has the magnitude to deliver myth from 3 feet
away. That's the way I felt during the opening minutes of
Spielberg's reenactment of Omaha Beach, when the men in the landing
craft are simply trying to outlive their fear. The dread I felt
(``I wanted the audience to be fairly uneasy,'' Spielberg has said
about this sequence, in grand understatement) is endemic to all
war; even as I was overcome with that knowledge, I was glimpsing my
younger self's limited comprehension of it _ a girl-woman's
presumption that walking point in an unjust war in Vietnam was
somehow worse than gaining 50 feet of ground on a beach swimming in
seawater and blood.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, youth is stunning in its solipsistic sense of
originality: Strutting around 30 years ago in an old flight jacket
that alarmingly resembled the one Tom Hanks wears in the movie, I
must have believed my generation was the first to discover
individual terror and unfair sacrifice. Perhaps I am being too hard
on myself: These are, after all, the insights that come with having
outlived your earlier, coltish self. But if ``Saving Private Ryan''
forced such fleeting wisdom from me that afternoon, it's partly
because Spielberg (who is roughly my age) has made a World War II
movie with a post-Vietnam sensibility. Not the ironic, death-knell
cynicism that accompanied that war, but instead the somber, graphic
instruction that the cost of war cannot be allayed by principle or
heroic oratory. That, as George C. Marshall and Abraham Lincoln
knew so well, no words of consolation are possible for a torso
lying on a beach in the rain.
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg could not have known this, or at least filmed it, at
any earlier point in American history. And while it's true that the
rest of ``Saving Private Ryan'' can't live up to its first
half-hour, that round-trip ticket to Normandy, for much of its
audience, may have given us access to a world of courage and
suffering we would otherwise never have _ one our fathers couldn't
really talk about, cannot but would just as soon forget. That
night, after seeing the movie and calling my father in Texas, I
remembered a letter I'd received years ago, in response to a piece
I'd written about Vietnam movies. It was from a retired Air Force
captain who had served in both the Second World War and Korea, and
he admonished me for mourning the comparatively slight losses of
Vietnam. He went on at some length, told me I didn't know what I
was talking about, and called me, among other things, a Young Turk.
I didn't agree with him, but I wrote him back. And I kept the
letter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
