<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-17 13:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7341 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANADA-DIVERSITY-BOS &LR;      08-17 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-DIVERSITY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CRUCIAL CHALLENGE OF DIVERSITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID M. SHRIBMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OTTAWA _ The new Canadian census shows that minorities now make
up about a third of the population of Toronto and Vancouver. French
speakers in Quebec continue to argue about whether they have a
place in Canada. The grand chief of the Crees is arguing that the
Indian band has a right to secede from Quebec if the province
leaves Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The diversity debate is raging in Canada. But not only there.
Turkish students are protesting the ban against head scarfs at
secular Istanbul University. President Clinton has spent much of
his second term trying to cultivate a conversation on race.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge of the last years of the century _ and,
undoubtedly, the early years of the next century _ may be simple to
express but difficult to achieve: how to manage diversity.
</P>
<P>
   It is a challenge in Israel, which at age 50 is struggling to
integrate black Jews, Jews of different philosophies, and Arabs
into a nation that was founded as something of a utopian society.
It is a challenge in Great Britain and France, which for centuries
had colonies abroad but only now are struggling to make a home for
large numbers of nonwhites. It is a challenge in Asia, where Cold
War tensions have given way to ethnic tensions.
</P>
<P>
   These challenges are especially vivid in North America, which
only two centuries ago was colonized by Europeans, who pushed the
native people to the far fringes and who seeded the fertile land of
the continent with thousands of settlers, most of them white but
some of them, portentiously, slaves.
</P>
<P>
   And so Americans have wrestled with questions of diversity _
though often described by a different name _ for centuries. It is
one of the signature struggles of the American story. Even the
founders grappled with this problem. ``Perhaps I am partial to the
complexion of my country,'' Benjamin Franklin said, ``for such kind
of partiality is natural to mankind.'' Today, of course, there is
no one complexion to Benjamin Franklin's country.
</P>
<P>
   But now the United States' northern neighbor _ beset with
centuries-old language tensions rooted in European rivalries and
with a flood of new immigrants, more than half of whom come from
Asia and the Pacific islands _ is wrangling with the problem.
Indeed, the debate here over diversity reveals as much about the
United States as it does about Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian debate is being conducted in a nation whose
boundaries are so uncertain that executives' contracts sometimes
include a clause setting out how their jobs and compensation would
change if Canada split up. The American debate is being conducted
in a nation whose boundaries are more or less fixed, though the
admission of Puerto Rico as the 51st state is a topic that is far
from settled.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian debate is being conducted primarily on language
lines, with race as a subtheme. The American debate is being
conducted primarily on racial lines, with language as a subtheme.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian debate is being conducted in a nation that reveres
its sense of civility and whose cities are filled with ethnic
neighborhoods. The American debate is being conducted in a nation
that is pockmarked with violence and punctuated with ghettos.
</P>
<P>
   Canadians talk about a mosaic. Americans talk about a melting
pot.
</P>
<P>
   These discussions define the two nations. They may also define
the future of politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``You must understand that in the next century we will have to
learn to live in peace within states,'' says Stephane Dion, a
Montreal intellectual who has become the governing Liberal Party's
point man on the Quebec question. ``Different populations are
worrying about their own identities. That's an American challenge,
too _ and with the responsibilities you have, you cannot afford for
there to be too many Yugo-slavias. This is a big universal
challenge. It is not a Canadian matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the American struggle on race lies beneath many other
political and cultural conflicts, it does not threaten to break up
the nation geographically, as it does in Canada. Sometime in the
next several years, Quebec will hold another referendum on
independence. The campaign to separate from Canada lost the last
referendum by the narrowest of margins, and the Parti Quebecois,
with its slogans ready, hopes that the province will vote for a new
country for a new century.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberal government of Jean Chretien has been arguing that
Quebeckers benefit from being in Canada, and, with an eye toward
pointing out the crisis that would be prompted by a declaration of
independence, has sought a Supreme Court ruling on the legality of
separation. Its opposition rivals, the western-based Reform Party,
argues that mere reason is not enough to save the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are fighting a guy with a dream, you've got to have a
better dream,'' Reform leader Preston Manning said in an interview.
``Quebeckers want heart and emotionalism, not a cold calculation of
how things are going well.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, when census takers asked Canadians their ethnic
backgrounds, nearly 38 percent of Quebeckers responded by saying
that they were of ``Canadian'' origin. That's double the national
average, and more Quebeckers responded that way than did any other
group.
</P>
<P>
   And in the United States, a survey released early this spring
showed that the children of immigrants overwhelmingly prefer
English to their parents' language. The Children of Immigrants
Longitudinal Study also showed that these new Americans have higher
grades and lower dropout rates than other children.
</P>
<P>
   More than anything, the diversity debate is prompting Canadians
and Americans to learn more about each other, and to learn more
about what it is to be a nation.
</P>
<P>
   John Whyte, Saskatechewan's deputy minister of justice and a
constitutional scholar, made a plea this year for a multiracial,
multiethnic, multicultural society. ``The threads of a thousand
acts of accommodation,'' said Whyte, who might have been talking to
Americans as well as Canadians, ``are the fabric of a nation.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David M. Shribman is chief of the Globe's Washington bureau.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
