<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980817.0165 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-17 13:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7346 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-HANCOCK-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE     08-17 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-HANCOCK-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 GLOUCESTER, Mass.: ... and believable.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``There's a tremendous revival of interest in figurative
sculpture,'' Hancock says, ``so tremendous that there is a lot of
extremely poor work being produced by people who don't know how to
do anything but copy what they see. But you have to design
sculpture, compose it. And you have to avoid mawkishness.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my day,'' he says, ``sculptors were taught to solve
problems, to make a thing fit a situation.'' A fine example is the
heroic ``Pegasus and Warrior'' Hancock expressly designed to suit
its setting outside an Art Deco structure in St. Louis. (There's a
maquette for ``Pegasus'' in the Cape Ann museum.) He's called this
work ``almost Assyrian in its formality,'' and it does indeed have
the blunt rhythms of Assyrian reliefs. Hancock made the horse's
wings a series of jazzy horizontals finished with a scalloped edge:
On a less majestic scale, these stylized wings could be a hood
ornament for a streamlined 1930s car.
</P>
<P>
   One of his biggest design challenges was the epic ``Pennsylvania
Railroad War Memorial'' for Philadelphia's 30th Street Station, a
36-foot vertical sculpture that echoes the giant columns nearby. An
angel tenderly lifts a fallen soldier out of the flames of battle;
the angel's wings aim straight up, their lines repeating those of
the columns' fluting. ``I tried to make the angel's face represent
all of humanity, not just one race,'' Hancock says, adding that the
angel is neither male nor female.
</P>
<P>
   In the early stages of the design, ``the angel was lifting the
soldier without any real feeling,'' Hancock says. ``What you have
to do in a case like that, to get the emotion, is act the thing out
in your own imagination, putting your own feelings into the
action.'' The angel's hands are an illustration. In their first
incarnation, they were straight, flat, and formal; by the final
version, they'd become eloquent, gently pressing the soldier's
flesh so you can feel his weight.
</P>
<P>
   Gentleness, not an attribute usually associated with war, is
nonetheless a hallmark of the war memorials that occupied a good
chunk of Hancock's career. (The president of the Pennsylvania
Railroad had requested grenades hanging from the soldier's belt,
which Hancock managed to avoid.) Gentleness also seems a hallmark
of Hancock himself.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent of his military memorials is the one for West
Point, and it, too, is poignant rather than bellicose. The generals
in charge of it were ``leery of the idea of nudity at first. But
I've never worked with any committee as receptive and
appreciative,'' Hancock says, describing ``a convoy of stretch
limousines filled with generals and colonels,'' driving down his
dirt road to check on the memorial's progress. Hancock himself
served as an army captain in World War II, his talents put to use
as a member of a team who rescued art the Nazis had looted and
hidden, often in places where dampness threatened the works'
existence.
</P>
<P>
   While best known for public monuments, Hancock also made
delightful little bronzes of wrestlers, swimmers, and basketball
players, as ``a relief from the big commissions,'' he says. He
lured local youngsters with a basketball court on his property.
When he was struck by a particular gesture, he'd have them repeat
it. And repeat it. Dozens of the nimble little figures that
resulted are in the Cape Ann museum, their fleeting movements _
reaching, jumping, lunging, colliding, falling over backward _
forever frozen. They remind me of Degas's little bronzes of
ballerinas. Hancock says he was urged to sculpt dancers by none
other than Lincoln Kirstein, co-founder of the New York City
Ballet, who took him to watch George Balanchine rehearse. ``But I
resisted doing dancers,'' Hancock says, ``because I felt an art out
of an art wasn't as interesting as art out of life, with all its
accidents. That's why I enjoyed those high school basketball
players. They made so many fouls.''
</P>
<P>
   Hancock invites me to visit his studio, just up the steps from
his parlor. ``I have to go with you to defend myself,'' he says,
smiling. The studio is a gathering of sculptural friends and
family: heads of Booth Tarkington, Robert Frost, and Hancock's
daughter among them. There's also a model for ``Air,'' a 1979
commission for Philadelphia's Civic Center. How to turn bronze into
ether? ``At first I thought it should be something wispy,'' Hancock
says. ``But air can be anything from a breeze to a hurricane.
Eventually, I found the answer in Shakespeare, in a line from
`Hamlet' _ `This most excellent canopy, the air ... this brave
o'erhanging firmament.' I thought I'd make the sculpture as much a
canopy as possible.'' So Hancock's ``Air'' is a male figure who
hovers horizontally over a globe, his arms and legs swimming
through the sky.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock's view of public sculpture as problem solving met its
biggest test in the gigantic Stone Mountain Memorial, a
69-foot-high granite bas-relief depicting Confederate heroes,
carved into a rocky hill outside Atlanta. The project had dragged
on since 1915; two other sculptors had tackled it and ultimately
given up. (The first, Gutzon Borglum, went on to sculpt Mount
Rushmore.) Hancock saw the troublesome saga through to its 1970
completion, though the two great bronze towers he'd designed to
complement the figures were never cast; models of these cylinders
of flames sit in a corner of his studio.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock's public sculpture seems more a public service than an
excuse to flaunt a personal style, and though he's won all manner
of awards and even a presidential medal, he remains a reticent man.
While he didn't want to sculpt Balanchine's dancers, he probably
would agree with the choreographer's famous comment on
``creativity'': ``Creation happened once.'' Hancock, too, has a
workmanlike attitude toward art. On the matter of his aesthetic
signature, Walker Hancock notes simply that ``if you work
sincerely, the result shows whose work it is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
