<DOCNO> NYT19980817.0166 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-17 13:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7348 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-SAVING-2TAKES-     08-17 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-SAVING-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WAR IN THE FAMILY 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On my desk is an old photograph of him from 1943, taken a few
weeks before he shipped out to England for the next three years.
He's in dress uniform, standing on a downtown street in Amarillo,
Texas, holding the eternal unfiltered cigarette between his
fingers, wearing what my mother still calls ``that devil-may-care
look'' in his eyes. My father was a master sergeant in the Eighth
Air Force in the Second World War, stationed in a supply-command
base in Blackpool, England. In April or May of 1944, he wrote to my
mother _ by then, his wife of barely a year _ and told her he
believed it would all be over soon, sometime around his birthday.
His birthday was June 3, three days before D-Day, and the letter,
for obvious reasons, never made it past the censors. Not that it
needed to: Its content (magical prophecy, to a child) has lived on
in the family narrative, legend replacing what mere paper and ink
could only suggest.
</P>
<P>
   For 50 years my father, when he would even address the subject,
has insisted that he had it easy during the war, that he never saw
combat, that the worst casualties his 110 men suffered could be
treated with a healthy dose of penicillin. He is 84 now, and the
arthritis he brought home from England (it kept him out of Korea)
keeps him close to his old leather chair. For reasons that have as
much to do with time as with love, he has told me more about the
war in the last three years than he ever told anyone, including my
mother, in the five previous decades. And as with so many veterans
of his age, the memories of Blackpool are far more crystalline than
his ordinary recollections about the past year. This week, when I
came home from seeing ``Saving Private Ryan,'' I called him to talk
about the war. We played the game of bluff and bluster that has
always symbolized the intimacy between us; then I asked if he
remembered D-Day. ``Oh, yes,'' he said instantly, and there was a
long pause, and I thought, My God, he's finally going to start
talking.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, honey,'' he said, ``I was a hell of a poker player
in those days.''
</P>
<P>
   The answer may seem incongruous and, to the uninitiated,
frustrating. But those of us who came of age in the years after
World War II _ the sons and daughters who grew up playing war games
in our backyards, before the fences went up _ have long known that
this was the way our fathers spoke about the war. They bantered and
joked and told tall tales and buddy stories; if they were lucky
enough to return without wounds you could see, they came side-angle
at their pain, when they came near it at all.
</P>
<P>
   Why, then, was I weeping within 30 seconds of the opening shots
of ``Saving Private Ryan,'' wherein a white-haired American my
father's age is making his way toward a grave in a French cemetery?
Some of it was the wrenching ordinariness of the man: Harrison
Young's old soldier, wearing sport shirt and trousers, his eyes
misting with the private heartbreak of a million other vets.
Certainly I had been forewarned about the 28 minutes of Omaha Beach
I was about to witness _ Spielberg's virtuoso homage to war-is-hell
realism, intent upon showing the spilled intestines along with the
desperate valor. But an older gentleman on the long flight of
stairs into the theater had already rattled me: When I made a
friendly comment about the climb, he looked distressed, as though I
had interrupted him at a funeral. By the time the lights had dimmed
and that silent cemetery walk had begun, I had dissolved. This was
my father's war, and though I believed I had steeped myself in it
for most of my life, I was staggered in the next few hours and days
by what I hadn't understood.
</P>
<P>
   The carnage and heroism that was the Second World War came home
to us in in its aftermath in sweet waves of diffused history:
corrective myth and bearable memories and ticker-tape parades that
allowed us, as a country, to go on. The War Department's propaganda
division, which for years had employed the likes of Frank Capra and
Walt Disney to crank out GI boosterism, was no longer needed: We
had taken over the job of producing our own necessary fictions,
invented in the toy bombers and suburban fantasies of a victory
that always went to the better man. If ``The Best Years of Our
Lives'' or ``The Naked and the Dead'' told a particular truth about
the war, a less melancholy version was there to be had in the ethos
of the postwar Westerns, or on the baseball fields where fathers
showed their Little League teams how to fight and how to win. Our
dads were heroes _ all of them were heroes, it seemed _ and it was
our tender burden to be the little soldiers they'd come home to
raise.
</P>
<P>
   For me, that duty took the form of reading. My barracks was in
the basement of the public library, where I crouched on the floor
of the adult reading section, a place I wasn't yet allowed. I
remember camping out there for most of a summer when I was 10 or
11, immersed in my field manuals of Leon Uris's ``Battle Cry'' and
``Mila 18,'' thrilled and aghast at the horrors of war, trying to
steel myself for even tougher stuff. In the next several years, as
the 1960s broke out, I would graduate from that child's Valhalla,
of course, somehow finding my way to Dalton Trumbo's underground
anti-war classic, ``Johnny Get Your Gun.'' And by then, the Office
of Propaganda would have loved to get ahold of me and a million
others like me. My generation had been handed a different kind of
war, and I rejected the master sergeant who headed my family (he
was known by the neighborhood boys as ``Wild Bill Caldwell'') for a
cast-off Army jacket of my own.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
