<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-REALITY-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOYRIDING ECONOMY HITS A FEW BUMPS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER G. GOSSELIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Since the mid-1990s, analysts have been peering into
the humming engine of the American economy and looking up agog: It
was all running so perfectly. Barely a knock or a ping to be found.
</P>
<P>
   Even when Asia's economies careened off the road last year and
some analysts warned they could drag the United States with them,
events seemed to turn out happily: Foreigners pumped money into the
safe haven of US markets, which drove interest rates down and sent
stocks and the economy flying.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent months, especially in recent weeks, economists and
investors have begun to identify the first tentative signs of
trouble at home. Corporate profits no longer climb the way they
once did; consumer spending seems likely to run out of steam
because of exhausted savings; and the investigation of President
Clinton could have significant and unpredictable effects on the
administration and the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts have begun to wonder anew how long the nation's economy
can continue unscathed as countries all around flounder.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's dawning on us that we're just about the only ones left
standing, and that makes people nervous,'' said Robert E. Litan,
the economic studies director at the Brookings Institution in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In one sense, the new worries are no surprise. Everybody knew
that economic conditions here were too good to last forever.
Forecasters and policy makers have been predicting _ in fact,
hoping for _ some letup in growth to help ease pressures like the
tight labor market's upward push on wages. Even if that easing
occurs, almost no one is predicting a recession.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, by measures like inflation, interest rates, and consumer
confidence, the economy is still purring. Most economists dismiss
such warning signs as the recent slumps in industrial production
and retail sales as flukes _ statistical aberrations attributed to
the General Motors strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is still a heck of a good economy,'' said David Wyss,
research director for Standard &AMP; Poor's DRI in Lexington.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, there is a rawness to analysts' worries that has
been almost entirely absent in recent years _ a nagging sense that
the number of economic trouble spots around the world has risen too
high and too fast for comfort, an uneasy concern that the nation's
economic machinery may have become so finely tuned that if anything
goes seriously wrong, it could begin to throw rods.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are four or five miserable scenarios out there that may
only have odds of 5 or 10 or 15 percent, but are ones that a year
ago we wouldn't even have been thinking about,'' said Allen Sinai,
chief global economist with Primark Decision Economics in Boston
and, until recently, one of the country's most upbeat forecasters.
</P>
<P>
   Domestically, the big worry is Wall Street. That, according to
analysts, is because how the economy fares depends largely on
whether Americans keep spending, and whether they keep spending
depends to a remarkable degree on how their investments do. And the
last few months have not been kind to investments.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average on Friday fell 35 points to
8425, down almost 10 percent from its highs of mid-July and up a
mere 6.5 percent for the year. Other market measures, like the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 and the computer-heavy Nasdaq Composite, are
also well below their peaks. And even these declines may not
properly represent the extent of the market's slide because the
averages have been held up in recent months by the strong
performance of a few large stocks, which has masked the deeper
dives of many other companies' shares.
</P>
<P>
   To most people, the idea of bad investment news affecting
economic performance seems obvious because they assume that the
stock market and the economy have always been linked. But analysts
believe that, for better or worse, the two have never been as wired
to each other as they are today because so many more Americans are
investing.
</P>
<P>
   For the last three years, the wiring has carried a strikingly
clear message: Stocks are up. Times are flush. The chance to
consume is now. The extent to which Americans have responded is
only beginning to become clear, most recently in the government's
new household savings statistics.
</P>
<P>
   The figures show that millions of American families have
apparently decided that their expanding stock portfolios will cover
such big costs as college education and retirement, so they have
all but given up on the idea of saving money. As a result, the
nation's already paltry savings rate of about 4 percent of
after-tax income has fallen to just 0.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The average person is feeling pretty flush so he's spending
every dollar he makes,'' said Litan.
</P>
<P>
   All that spending has been great for economic growth. But
analysts wonder whether with so little in reserve beyond the paper
profits of the stock market, Americans can continue buying at their
current pace. And even more important, many worry how Americans
will respond if the markets take a prolonged dive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know what life would be like in the slow lane,'' said
Nicholas S. Perna, chief economist with Fleet Financial Group in
Boston. ``We know that when &UR;  &LR; the market is up, consumers are
exuberant. But what happens when it's down, maybe way down? Do they
get morose'' and stop buying?
</P>
<P>
   Internationally, the big worry is Japan. That, according to
analysts, is because as the world's second-largest economy and by
far the largest in the Pacific Rim, Japan is the only country with
the resources to help pull its Asian neighbors out of their crises.
But so far, it has only succeeded in making its own problems, and
those of its neighbors, worse.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard for many Americans to view the Asian crisis as a
serious threat, since virtually all its early effects seemed
positive. But analysts said that the crisis has finally begun to
catch up with US economy in two ways: through a slow, uneven, and
hard-to-track squeeze on corporate profits _ a key engine of the
stock market _ and through abrupt, across-the-board stock routs.
</P>
<P>
   Citing an Asia-related falloff in US exports and an increase in
the value of the dollar in international currency markets, which
shrinks the value of overseas earnings, analysts now say that
corporate America will be able to boost profits only slightly this
year.
</P>
<P>
   While that means companies will still make money, and in many
cases more than they made last year, the profit growth will pale
beside the double-digit growth rates that investors have become
accustomed to. And some observers say the profit damage is far from
over.
</P>
<P>
   Charles L. Hill, research director for First Call Corp., a
Boston firm that follows earnings projections, said analysts will
have to ``bring their forecast down a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, investors are having to learn to cope with the
stomach-churning experience of sudden market tumbles like the
round-the-world rout on Aug. 4 that trimmed nearly 300 points from
the Dow.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got the potential for a global financial meltdown,''
said Perna. ``I don't think it will happen, but it's a lot more
likely than six months ago.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
