<HEADLINE>
`KUNDUM' IS MAGNIFICENT; `THE APOSTLE' OFF KILTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW RELEASES:  &UR; ``Kundun''  &LR; _ Martin Scorsese's elegiac tribute
to Tibet and the boy Dalai Lama, featuring an all-Tibetan cast, is
a remarkable departure for one of the only filmmakers worthy of the
name. Beautiful cinematography reinforces the film's idyllic view;
it's pacifist theme made all the stronger by Scorsese's previous
meditations on violence. The sheer exhilaration of this magnificent
film should be seen on the DVD format, which is letterboxed.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``The Apostle'' &LR;  _ &UR;  &LR; For more than a decade, Robert Duvall
tirelessly worked to get this film about a Southern evangelist
made. As writer, director, and star, he's created a magnificently
complex character, but the star's brilliance throws the rest of his
movie off kilter. Great performance, middling movie.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``An Alan Smithee Film: Burn Hollywood Burn''  &LR; _ By the time
they got through with this one, no one wanted their name on it. A
parody turned self-parody that isn't very funny. And who designated
Joe Ezsterhaus the greatest screenwriter of the 20th century? He
stinks.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``The Man in the Iron Mask''  &LR; _ Leonardo DiCaprio couldn't
transfer his star power from the hull of the Titanic to this
hulking period piece even though he gives a fine performance. The
plot wanders, and the rest of the cast overacts. (After all those
years in an iron mask in a dungeon, how does Leonardo come out with
such a fabulous complexion?)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Senseless''  &LR; _ Remember a few months ago when everyone was
saying that comedian David Spade couldn't miss? He was hot, hot,
hot. But then this stupid movie came out and died at the box
office. Cold, cold, cold. A few funny slapstick moments do not a
movie make.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COMING ATTRACTIONS:  &UR; Aug. 25:  &LR; ``The Leading Man,'' ``Men With
Guns,'' ``The Last Way Out,'' ``Sub Down,'' ``North Shore Fish,''
``Pocahontas: Journey to a New World,'' ``Naked Lies.''  &UR; Sept. 1:
 &LR; ``Titanic,'' ``Dream for an Insomniac,'' ``Absolutely Fabulous
Moments,'' ``Barney's Great Adventure: The Movie,'' ``Star Trek:
The Next Generation,'' ``The Spooktacular New Adventures of
Casper,'' ``Leviathan,'' ``Child's Play,'' ``Breeders,'' ``The
Vicar of Dibley,'' ``Phantasm.'' &UR; Sept. 8:  &LR; ``Primary Colors,'' ``A
Call to Remember,'' ``Children of the Noisy Village,'' ``The
Spree,'' ``I Love You ... Don't Touch Me.''  &UR; Sept. 15:  &LR; ``Lady and
the Tramp,'' ``He Got Game,'' ``Deep Rising,'' ``Hush,'' ``Rhapsody
in August,'' ``Eat, Drink, Man, Woman,'' ``Buffy, the Vampire
Slayer,'' ``Suicide Kings,'' ``Man With the Gun,'' ``To Live.''
 &UR; Sept. 22:  &LR; ``Addams Family Reunion,'' ``Happy Together,''
``Nightwatch,'' ``Fallen Angels.''  &UR; Sept. 29:  &LR; ``The Object of My
Affection,'' ``The Song of Songs,'' ``The Trial,'' ``Milo,'' ``Two
Girls and a Guy,'' ``The Devil Is a Woman,'' ``Chinese Box,'' ``The
Flame of New Orleans,'' ``Paulie.''  &UR; Oct. 6 &LR; : ``Lost in Space.''
 &UR; Oct. 13: &LR;  ``The Big One,'' ``Black Dog,'' ``I Got the Hook Up.''
 &UR; Oct. 20 &LR; : ``Chitty Chitty Bang Bang,'' ``Red Corner.''
</P>
