<HEADLINE>
GLOBE CRITICS RATE FILMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
 ! poor, !! fair, !!! good, !!!! excellent  
 
 !! 1/2 ``Air Bud: Golden Receiver''  Canine Buddy plays football,
and a bit of matchmaker, in the second of what could be a series of
sports-minded-dog-saves-the-day movies. Romance is an added
ingredient as Gregory Harrison portrays a vet and potential dad to
Josh, now a junior high school quarterback. Despite its
less-interesting supporting characters and too predictable plot,
this installment remains decent but bland family fare. (G) (Scott
Powers)
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; !! ``First Love, Last Rites'' &LR;  Adapted from a 1975 Ian McEwan short
story, this sleepy tale of young romance in a steamy Louisiana
backwater never really finds dramatic momentum, despite intriguing
performances by its leads, Natasha Gregson Wagner, and Giovanni
Ribisi. (Unrated)  &UR; cf150 &LR; (R &UR; gfspanish &LR; enee Graham)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ! 1/2 ``Homegrown'' &LR;  Billy Bob Thornton, Hank Azaria, and Ryan
Phillippe play marijuana growers in northern California who try to
grab their share of the action when their kingpin boss (John
Lithgow) is murdered. In this would-be comic thriller, the hapless
trio aren't even interesting enough to be called bozos. The movie's
thriller elements are as clueless as its comedy. Kelly Lynch is a
bright spot as a player in the weed operation. (R) (Betsy Sherman)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; !! ``Return to Paradise''  &LR; Two Americans are asked to return to
Malaysia and take part of the blame for heedless drug use while
vacationing there so that a third, who stayed and got caught, won't
be executed. Vince Vaughn agonizes the most; Anne Heche works hard
as the lawyer trying to convince him to go back; and Joaquin
Phoenix sweats convincingly as the condemned man. But the film
never catches us up in its issues or passions. (R)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (FL)! 1/2 ``How Stella Got Her Groove Back''  &LR; Gorgeous-looking and
seductive, if not quite altogether soulful, romantic fantasy. A
vacationing 40-year-old San Francisco architect played by Angela
Bassett wonders if the chemistry with a Jamaican local half her age
is the real thing. Bassett's warmth and dignity, newcomer Taye
Diggs' sensitivity and dazzling smile, and Whoopi Goldberg's sassy
one-liners are the selling points here. (R)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
