<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-DELINSKY-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARBARA DELINSKY FINALLY MAKES HER MARK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEEDHAM, Mass. _ Over the past 18 years, Barbara Delinsky has
written 66 books, with 25 million copies published in two dozen
languages.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know those numbers are mind-boggling,'' Delinsky said. ``And
when I go through an airport or a hotel lobby and see someone with
one of my books, I'm stunned.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was only two Sundays ago that a Barbara Delinsky novel,
``Coast Road,'' finally crashed the New York Times bestseller list.
</P>
<P>
   The problem was that most of the 66 were romance novels. And
while copies of ``genre books,'' as they are called, sell in the
millions, they aren't considered for the prestigious bestseller
lists. Recent novels by her that have sold well in paperback made
separate lists.
</P>
<P>
   But over the past half-dozen years, as she has become more
confident in her ability to tell more complex stories, Delinsky has
been edging across the line into what the trade regards as
mainstream women's fiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coast Road'' involves a divorced couple on the California
coast. When the woman is critically injured in an autombile
accident, lying in a coma, her ex-husband returns to take care of
their two young daughters _ and answer the question of whether he
can recapture his marriage and his family.
</P>
<P>
   For ``Coast Road,'' Delinsky has a new publisher, Simon &AMP;
Schuster, ``not so much because I needed to change my image,'' she
said, ``but because I wanted my numbers to grow in hardcover.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do I want to get the numbers up?'' Delinsky asks, a bit
defensively. ``Because I've always wanted to reach as many people
as I can. I think my books are good, intelligent entertainment. I
think they touch chords in people.''
</P>
<P>
   But if ``getting the numbers up'' also makes Delinsky sound more
like business than literature, she would be the first to agree _
softly, as is her way of speaking.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps nothing better illustrates the difference between
Delinsky from the women writers of ``literary fiction'' who are
familiar figures on the Boston literary scene. She's a
genre-turned-mainstream writer, and they read each other's work as
members of editor Sally Brady's writers' group meetings, have
animated conversations at PEN/New England gatherings, and meet over
lunch at each other's houses.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're literary writers,'' said Delinsky without the
slightest bit of animosity _ or jealousy. ``They'll write a book
every three years, while a genre writer has to have three new books
in the stores every year.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh yes, she said, ``I know some writers, but there's no close
circle of friends. It helps me remember that this is a business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a working stiff,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Delinsky, 53, went into the business of writing 18 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   She grew up in Newton and went to Tufts University, where she
met her future husband, Stephen Delinsky, the former chief of staff
for Attorney General Francis X. Bellotti and now in private
practice. They live in a rambling Cape house surrounded by woods
and fields, which they built 11 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   While Delinsky speaks of the town with affection, she has kept
involvement in local activities to a minimum. One of the few
outside commitments is to the breast cancer advisory committee at
Massachusetts General Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Delinsky's mother died there, of breast cancer, at the age of 45
when Delinsky was 8 years old. ``I feel very strongly about this,''
she said. Strongly enough to use one character in ``Coast Road,''
the injured ex-wife's closest friend, to stress the importance of
early detection and treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``If one reader takes away from this book the importance of a
yearly mammogram,'' she said, ``I'll have been successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Delinsky has a large office-sitting room over the garage,
separated enough from the rest of the house, she said, ``so that I
feel that I'm going to work.'' The computer, she said, ``is always
on, and sometimes I'll come in at 9:30 at night when I have an
idea.''
</P>
<P>
   After earning a master's degree in sociology from Boston
University, Delinsky worked as a researcher with the Massachusetts
Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Children. She never took a
writing course _ was even asked to drop out of a sixth-grade
advanced placement English class ``because I couldn't keep up with
the work,'' she said _ though she wrote a bit as a reporter and
photographer for the Belmont Herald.
</P>
<P>
   After taking several years off after the birth of her son, Eric,
who is now 28, and her twin sons five years younger, Delinsky
started looking around to return to work, but found nothing
particularly appealing.
</P>
<P>
   It was a story in the Boston Globe about women genre writers
that turned Delinsky to what became her business. She wrote the
first book, ``Hills of Eden,'' in 3 1/2 weeks. ``The glove fit,''
she said. ``And by the time it sold,'' she added, ``I was in the
middle of the next book.''
</P>
<P>
   From there, she said, ``it's been a very steady progression.
There's been no miraculous breakthrough in my career.''
</P>
<P>
   Early on, Delinsky said, there were years when she wrote six
books. ``There were even a couple of times I'd spend a month
writing, then take a week off to cleanse the palate, then start in
on another one.''
</P>
<P>
   There was indeed a ``formula'' at first _ although Delinsky
perfers to use the word ``structure'' _ 10 chapters of 20 pages
each, the first one to introduce the characters, the last one to
bring resolution. ``And in between, various thing happen.''
</P>
<P>
   And as the arithmetic of 66 books in 18 years makes clear, she
said, ``that's a lot of books and a lot of hours.''
</P>
<P>
   And not a lot of vacations.
</P>
<P>
   Delinsky and her husband took their customary week this summer
in Big Sur on the California coast _ the setting for ``Coast Road''
_ hiking every day into the mountains and out to the ocean. They
will take their customary winter week ``somewhere warm,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The next book will take place in a setting similar to New
Hampshire's Squam Lake. There is a map of the lake and photographs
of the surrounding countryside tacked on a bulletin board facing
Delinsky's computer.
</P>
<P>
   In time, she said, ``we'd like to get a place in New Hampshire,
even though that means we'd have to start taking long weekends. No
more five-day work weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, however, there is spending time with friends, working
out _ ``at our age we have to be into physical fitness,'' she said
_ and relaxing with crossword puzzles. ``An enjoyable weekend for
us,'' she said, ``is spending time together.''
</P>
<P>
   Delinsky belongs to a reading group _ but there are writers in
it, she said. ``It's where I rub elbows with people and hear what's
on their minds.''
</P>
<P>
   Her own reading runs to ``what's on the bestseller list _ to see
what the competition is.'' She took Wally Lamb's 900-page chart
topper ``I Know This Much Is True'' _ an Oprah television book club
selection _ on the Big Sur trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm as competitive as any man,'' Delinsky said. ``But
this is a business I'm in. Make no mistake about it.''
</P>
<P>
   And noting that she broke onto the New York Times bestseller
list at No.14 and would be moving up a notch the second week,
Delinsky said bluntly: ``I'd like to be No.1 on that list.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
