<HEADER>
A7365 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-ANDERSON-BOS &LR;      08-17 1268
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-ANDERSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEXT STOP, BOSTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Brad Anderson was raised in Connecticut, and now lives in New
York, but he considers himself a Boston filmmaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``These days a lot of people are calling themselves Boston
filmmakers, but we're the real thing,'' said Anderson, referring to
himself and Lyn Vaus, co-writers of ``Next Stop, Wonderland,''
which Anderson also directed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only did we make a film imbued with the spirit of Boston,
but we know this town inside and out,'' Anderson said. ``I've
probably shot on every street in this city, so I really do feel
like a Boston filmmaker.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Next Stop, Wonderland'' arrives in theaters Friday still
riding the wave of buzz it generated at this year's Sundance Film
Festival. The charming comedy about the eternal search for true
love was snapped up by Hollywood heavyweight Miramax for a whopping
$6 million at the prestigious filmfest in January.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Shot entirely in the Boston area, ``Next Stop, Wonderland''
serves as yet another harbinger of Massachusetts's flourishing film
industry. A state once best known for its clam chowder, eccentric
drivers, and lovably accursed Red Sox is now garnering attention
for its ability to attract Hollywood and independent filmmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very exciting time to be working with the film industry
here,'' said Robin Dawson, director of the Massachusetts Film
Office. ``What's really exciting is in addition to the large
features, independent filmmakers have really embraced this
region.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Massachusetts pulled in a record $101.2 million in
revenue from film and television productions, Dawson said. That's a
huge increase from the second most lucrative year, $73 million in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Recently, the state has supplied locations for such movies as
``The Matchmaker'' starring Janeane Garofalo and Denis Leary, David
Mamet's ``The Spanish Prisoner,'' Steven Spielberg's ``Amistad,''
and Tom Keenan's memorable comedy ``Enough Already,'' which was
released earlier this year. Upcoming films with Massachusetts
locales include ``A Civil Action,'' starring John Travolta, Robert
Duvall, and Kathleen Quinlan; ``In Dreams,'' with Annette Bening,
Aidan Quinn, and Robert Downey Jr.; and ``The Love Letter,'' now
shooting in Rockport with Kate Capshaw, Tom Selleck, and Ellen
Degeneres.
</P>
<P>
   Other films have been swept up in the momentum like the quirky
thriller, ``pi.'' It was not filmed in Boston, but writer-director
Darren Aronofsky is a Harvard University graduate and star Sean
Gullette is from Newton, Mass. These days, that's enough of a
connection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boston's kind of funny that way,'' said Vaus, who once worked
as a security guard at Massachusetts General Hospital before
success as a screenwriter led him to New York. ``They will embrace
people and things with even a slight connection, but I think that's
really kind of touching actually.''
</P>
<P>
   In June, when acting Gov. Paul Cellucci announced that three
North Shore communities _ Rockport, Gloucester, and
Manchester-by-the-Sea _ had been selected as sites for the upcoming
DreamWorks film ``The Love Letter,'' he recognized ``the enormous
economic benefits that the big screen brings to our towns and
cities. Movies and TV shows filmed here in the Bay State have had
blockbuster success in bringing dollars, jobs, and tourists into
the Commonwealth.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, these days the best-known film with its heart in
Boston is ``Good Will Hunting,'' the 1997 film that turned
Cambridge natives Matt Damon and Ben Affleck into stars and Academy
Award winners for best original screenplay (Miramax also financed
that film, which went on the become the highest-grossing movie in
the studio's history.) But the state's film fortunes were on the
rise before Damon's character, Will Hunting, hoisted a cold one in
South Boston's L Street Tavern, Dawson said.
</P>
<P>
   ```Good Will Hunting' definitely brought prominence to the
Boston area, but we had already been creating incentives to attract
filmmakers,'' she said. One of those incentives is the ``fee-free
locations'' that allow filmmakers access to state-owned facilities
at no cost. Studios are also offered cut rates at hotels and
restaurants. So far, the program has paid off, and the budget for
the film office has increased from $450,000 to $650,000. The larger
allocation allows Massachusetts to compete better with about 300
worldwide film commissions, Dawson said.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, some filmmakers have long been convinced of the
state's virtues a backdrop. Shortly before ``Good Will Hunting''
opened last year, Damon said he and Affleck always knew that if
they wrote a film it would have to be set in their hometown.
</P>
<P>
   Boston isn't Brad Anderson's hometown, but both his
feature-length films (the first was ``The Darien Gap'' in 1996)
were set in the city where he lived for eight years. He also taught
filmmaking at Tufts University, Emerson College, Boston University,
and the Boston Film/Video Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We definitely wanted to make another movie in Boston,'' said
Anderson during a recent visit to his former home. ``We wanted to
weave together a story where we could capitalize on Boston _ not
only as a location, but also as a character in the movie. There's a
melancholy tone to the movie and I think Boston has a bit of that.
It's a sweet, charming city, but there's a sort of pensiveness,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Next Stop, Wonderland'' _ as in the Blue Line stop adjacent to
Revere's dog track _ is a fanciful story about modern love and
romance. Hope Davis plays Erin, a nurse living in Boston's South
End who has been jilted by her longtime boyfriend, Nathan (Paul
Wagner). Her sudden singlehood leaves her cynical and mistrustful
of men in general and of relationships in particular. Her pushy but
well-meaning mother (Holland Taylor) places a personal ad for Erin
in a local newspaper, and though Erin is at first offended, her
curiosity leads her to listen to some of the voice responses,
mostly from a string of losers and poseurs.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of town, in East Boston, there's Alan (Alan
Gelfant), a sweet, decent guy who also emerged bloodied and bruised
from his last relationship. Believing he's destined to be alone, he
pours all his time and energy into becoming a marine biologist at
the Boston (read New England) Aquarium.
</P>
<P>
   The film, which features such local celebrities as comedian
Jimmy Tingle and radio personality Charles Laquidara in small
roles, becomes a series of near-misses between Erin and Alan, who
are perfect for one another. The tension hinges on whether the two
will ever actually meet, though their paths almost cross several
times. Such a device might seem contrived if the film were set in
New York or Los Angeles, but not in a city with Boston's intimacy,
Vaus said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We even had a line in the movie where a character said, `In
Boston's it's nothing to bump into the same person eight or nine
times in a month.' That's conceivable here, and that was something
we could capitalize on for dramatic purposes.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's next film is a horror-mystery project that will take
him away from romantic comedy and from Boston. But he would never
rule out a return to the state where he first made his name as a
filmmaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's great that Boston is being heralded as a new
venue for film,'' he said. ``Even though I don't live here anymore,
I love Boston. It has a look, a tone, and a feel unlike any other
city. In a way, with this film, we wanted to make a valentine to
Boston.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
