<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET'S HAVE DEBATE ON WHEN TO START SCHOOLS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Ever wonder what became of the Grinch who stole
Christmas?
</P>
<P>
   Although that question probably hasn't been weighing heavily on
your mind, it has become obvious in recent days that the Grinch and
some of his offspring have been elected to a number of school
boards around Texas.
</P>
<P>
   And, now, they've stolen a large chunk of summer.
</P>
<P>
   Summer may have another month to run _ according to the calendar
and the thermometer _ but it has effectively ended for millions of
Texas children and their parents because school bells already are
ringing.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston Independent School District, the state's largest,
begins classes this week. They began last week in Austin and kicked
off _ believe it or not _ on Aug. 3 in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 3! The dog days of summer, which many Texas families used
to think of as prime vacation time, had barely begun.
</P>
<P>
   For several years now, the school year has been creeping earlier
and earlier into summer, and some people are beginning to think
that there ought to be a law.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature punted on the issue last year but will be asked
to take another look when it convenes in January.
</P>
<P>
   My own feelings are mixed.
</P>
<P>
   As a parent, I think it is ridiculous to start the school year
on Aug. 12, as the Austin Independent School District did. I
question whether finishing the first semester before the Christmas
break _ the purported reason for the early start _ is worth the
sacrifice of family recreational time and putting children on
un-air conditioned school buses during the hottest time of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   As a taxpayer, I wonder how much of my money AISD will have to
spend on the huge electricity bill that it will receive for
cranking up the air conditioners in its schools at the peak of
summer. Unlike most school buses, most Texas classrooms _
fortunately for students and teachers _ are air conditioned.
</P>
<P>
   But, also as a taxpayer and a parent, I would like to hear more
debate.
</P>
<P>
   What kind of effect, if any, does the school year's schedule
have on a child's ability to learn? Is a youngster more distracted
in the middle of August? Is it unfair _ and shortsighted _ to
shorten the summer work season for teen-agers who need summer jobs
to earn money for college and family expenses?
</P>
<P>
   Are the Christmas holidays too long? AISD classes will be shut
down for almost two and one-half weeks. The teachers and students
will certainly welcome the long respite, and I don't want to be
labeled a Grinch myself. But most working parents have to save
vacation days to take that much time off, or, if they have
grade-school children, have to scramble to find day care, which can
be an expensive proposition.
</P>
<P>
   Do school districts really need a weeklong spring break? This
has become a tradition in the public schools but was virtually
unheard of not too many years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Does state government have any business telling local school
districts when they can begin classes, or should parents who don't
like to hear school bells in August simply run for their school
board? Maybe the issue could even generate some voter interest in
school board elections for a change.
</P>
<P>
   Current state law dictates that districts have to provide 180
instructional days a year plus a certain number of days for staff
development. Five of those teaching days were added in a 1993 law,
which doubtlessly contributed to the pressure for an early start to
the school year.
</P>
<P>
   But local school officials are otherwise free to set their own
schedules.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Eddie Lucio, D-Brownsville, plans to promote debate
in Austin by introducing another bill next session to prohibit
public schools from starting classes before Sept. 1. That would
return the schools to what used to be a traditional starting date
after Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   Lucio sponsored a similar bill last year. It was approved 25-6
by the Senate but died in the House Public Education Committee, at
least partly because of opposition from school board members and
administrators, who value whatever ``local control'' they can
salvage from the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Lucio acknowledged that his bill is important to the tourist
industry, which has a strong presence in his coastal South Texas
district. But he said he also has other concerns, including the
effects of the heat on children riding buses or walking to and from
school.
</P>
<P>
   The senator said he also was concerned about the plight of
migrant children, many of whom live in his district. These children
are among the poorest in the state and are already at high risk of
dropping out before completing school.
</P>
<P>
   Lucio said that many of these students don't start school until
late September, after they finish helping their parents harvest
crops. The earlier school starts, the more they miss and the
greater their chance of giving up on an education that is their
only hope for a better life.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
