<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YIP-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AVOID TEMPTATION OF POPULAR STOCKS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PAMELA YIP 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In these times of stock market turmoil, the inclination is to go
for what is the greatest, hottest stock _ a brand-name stock with a
kick-butt track record.
</P>
<P>
   Resist the urge, particularly now that the market is in a bad
mood. The popularity of those hot stocks is usually what ends up
doing them in.
</P>
<P>
   This doesn't mean that you should avoid all really large,
well-known companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the long run, it's very sensible to be concentrated in the
large companies because they have the best odds of success in terms
of earnings growth, but there are times when they are overpriced
and turn out to be poor investments for a while,'' said Bradlee
Perry, an investment manager at David L. Babson &AMP; Co. in Cambridge,
Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Figuring out if a stock is overpriced is the hard part. One of
the ways to gauge a stock's popularity is its price/earnings ratio,
which is the measure of how much investors are willing to pay for a
company's earning power. The higher the ratio, the more investors
expect out of a company.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that price/earnings ratios _ also known as the
P/E _ for many big-name companies are perilously high now.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the P/E for the benchmark Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index for current earnings is 26, Perry said. That's
almost twice the historical average of 14 to 14.5 for current
earnings for the large companies in this index.
</P>
<P>
   ``The excessive optimism that gets reflected in the prices of
such shares makes it virtually impossible for the companies
concerned to meet the euphoric expectations of investors,'' Perry
said. ``This is why so many popular stocks turn out to be
unrewarding investments, and some really disastrous holdings.''
</P>
<P>
   It's especially risky to go after the hottest big names now
because only a small number of stocks have accounted for the
market's gains this year.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-five percent of the gain through June of the S&AMP;P 500 came
from 25 stocks, said Brendan Connaughton, a portfolio manager at
Wells Fargo Bank in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's scary because it's too narrow,'' he said. ``What you
want to see is a market that's broad-based.''
</P>
<P>
   To demonstrate the perils of popularity, Perry, who oversees $20
billion in assets, conducted a study over the last 16 years tracing
what happens to the company on the New York Stock Exchange that
ranks as the most popular in the spring of each year.
</P>
<P>
   The stock with the highest P/E on the exchange in April
typically carried a price/earnings ratio that was about triple the
one for the average S&AMP;P 500 company.
</P>
<P>
   Perry found that, on average, the most popular stocks
appreciated less than half as much as the S&AMP;P if held from their
peak of popularity through June of this year _ 141 percent vs. 328
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Exciting new markets often fail to keep growing as rapidly and
profitably as investors expect,'' Perry said. ``The second problem
often encountered by popular companies is that when a business
achieves great success, competitors are attracted into the field,
sometimes very powerful ones. This slows growth and shrinks profit
margins for the early leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what happened to Advanced Micro Devices as archrival
Intel Corp. and some smaller companies developed superior
microprocessor chips for personal computers, Perry said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gotta-own stocks are very likely to be losers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If you seek big names, find the ones that don't carry the
bloated expectations of investors but still have strong earnings
potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look for fallen angels _ big-name stocks whose stock prices
have dropped a lot,'' Perry said. ``Look for good, strong companies
whose prices have come off because of a minor disappointment
because they're no longer popular.''
</P>
<P>
   Connaughton is looking for companies in an industry with high
barriers to competition, such as aviation. He also likes ones whose
stocks are at bargain prices but that have strong growth potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be going into names that have underperformed and therefore
don't have the high P/E, like GM,'' he said. ``GM was under the
strike cloud for a while and it's really cheap. This one has a
catalyst for growth.''
</P>
<P>
   If you own big-name stocks that you bought at a decent price,
don't sell them in a panic or you could be sorry.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is smart enough and nimble enough to hop off the
fastest horse on the track when he starts to slow down and hop on
another horse when he's speeding up,'' Perry said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Pamela Yip can receive electronic mail via the Internet. Address
your comments and questions to pamela.yip(at)chron.com, or call
(713) 220-2000 and enter access code 1003. &QL; 
