<HEADLINE>
TASTE THE CULTUREAT DIET'S EXPENSE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I am frequently amused by travel-related survey findings that
cross my desk.
</P>
<P>
   After all, how else would I know that more men than women locked
themselves out of their Novotel New York hotel rooms in a state of
undress last year?
</P>
<P>
   Or that 67 percent of travelers to Las Vegas consider shopping a
priority while only 18 percent cite gambling.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that the most popular mall is attached to a casino.
</P>
<P>
   If those studies offer food for thought, FITNESS Magazine's
newly released survey of ``diet-damaging regional delicacies''
really _ ahem _ takes the cake.
</P>
<P>
   According to the magazine's September issue, ``By and large, the
most popular dishes in the nation's top cities are also the most
likely to wreck your diet. Whether it's the Baltimore mainstay of
Maryland crab cakes (340 calories, 14 grams of fat) or Chicago's
deep dish pizza (280 calories, 13 fat grams), hometown favorites
are unhealthy fat traps.''
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia cheese steak (887 calories, 46 fat grams) is deemed
so threatening that the magazine suggests the town change its motto
from ``The City of Brotherly Love'' to ``The City of Brotherly Love
Handles.''
</P>
<P>
   So what else should we avoid while traveling? The following
regional delicacies round out FITNESS' ``fat city list.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Louisville, Ky.: Southern fried chicken (590 calories, 30
grams fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ Los Angeles: California burrito (550 calories, 22 grams fat).
</P>
<P>
   _ Dallas: Texas rib-eye steak (510 calories, 27 grams fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ New Orleans: gumbo (477 calories, 32 grams fat).
</P>
<P>
   _ Juneau: baked Alaska (380 calories, 12 grams fat).
</P>
<P>
   _ New York: bagel with cream cheese (340 calories, 11 grams
fat).
</P>
<P>
   _ Boston: cream pie (280 calories, 13 grams fat).
</P>
<P>
   Whew! For a moment there I was afraid the magazine was going to
shoo me away from chicken-fried steak and sliced beef po-boys. Or
tell me to keep the lid on Blue Bell key lime ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   I suppose it's OK to sample lobster in Boston. But beware the
drawn butter. As for Boston baked beans ...
</P>
<P>
   Addressing the findings, FITNESS editor-in-chief Sally Lee does
offer a caveat: ``That's not to say you shouldn't try the Boston
cream pie or enjoy the New Orleans gumbo,'' she says. ``Just think
twice before indulging in seconds.''
</P>
<P>
   If we live long enough for seconds, that is.
</P>
<P>
   ``The basic message you can take away from this survey is that
when in Rome, don't do as the Romans do,'' Lee says.
</P>
<P>
   Excuse me. I'm sure that from a fitness standpoint Lee is right.
And certainly I should be the first to heed the magazine's
cautions; I've sampled every regional delicacy on the list.
</P>
<P>
   But what's the point of traveling _ especially for those whose
trip to New Orleans or Boston or Rome is a once-in-a-lifetime
adventure _ if we can't fully immerse ourselves in a destination's
culture? Cuisine included. Isn't sourdough bread as much a part of
San Francisco tradition as the Golden Gate Bridge?
</P>
<P>
   Imagine what future surveys might tell us:
</P>
<P>
   _ Stay away from the mountains; the high altitude can cause
dizziness.
</P>
<P>
   _ Avoid national parks and other woodlands; the bugs bite.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't bother with museums; something old may break and fall on
you.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cancel that next cruise; the salty air may damage your hair.
</P>
<P>
   I prefer to rely on a separate fitness survey conducted by the
Shattuck Unscientific Institute: It discovered that more travelers
suffer broken bones _ even jawbones _ on hiking and biking tours
than while chomping on a juicy steak. Despite exhaustive research,
it also unearthed not one report of arm stress incurred spooning up
crawfish gumbo. And if you put enough hot sauce on a good burrito,
it's almost guaranteed to clear out your sinuses. Among other
things.
</P>
<P>
   But acknowledging a need to become more fitness-conscious and
seeking a compromise that appeases those dedicated both to healthy
living and savoring local cuisine, I consulted one of my favorite
little books, ``All Over the Map'' (Ten Speed Press, $9.95) by
David Jouris, and pinpointed these fitness-conscious vacation
destinations:
</P>
<P>
   Celeryville, Ohio; Honeydew, Calif.; Greens, Tenn.; Tomato,
Ark.; and Cereal, Alberta.
</P>
<P>
   And for anyone on a high-protein diet: Noodle, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   No fair stopping in Sugar City, Colo., though.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, we could just eliminate food from our vacation
activities. And proceed instead to Bourbon, Miss.; Scotch Village,
Nova Scotia; Gin City, Ark.; Beersville, Pa.; or Whiskeytown,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The Cayman Islands pose a real problem, though: Rum cake is the
regional specialty.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
