<HEADER>
A7377 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-TREMAIN-REVIEW-H     08-17 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TREMAIN-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIKABLE, PRECOCIOUS SCHOOLBOY MULLS A DISAPPEARANCE, LOVE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  `THE WAY I FOUND HER'; By Rose Tremain; (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux,
$25) 
 
By BARBARA LISS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sooner or later, Lewis Little, the narrator of Rose Tremain's
stylish new novel, is going to steal your heart. The speed with
which this happens depends on how you feel about books narrated by
adolescents, especially precocious adolescents.
</P>
<P>
   But trust Tremain, the author of seven imaginative novels,
including the highly praised ``Restoration,'' to put us in the
hands of a 13-year-old boy who knows how to tell a story. ``The Way
I Found Her'' is a carefully plotted mystery-cum-philosophical
meditation, and Lewis a likable protagonist. And, as he reminds us,
in a novel it is important to be on someone's side.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis is no ordinary English schoolboy, head buried in soccer
scores and video games. His interests run to chess _ ``solving
things'' _ Dostoevsky and introspection. If at times he appears too
knowledgeable _ he muses about not only Marilyn Monroe but also
Arthur Miller _ he credibly explains, ``There is a disparity
between what is meant to be in the mind of a 13-year-old boy from
Devon and what is actually in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, what a 13-year-old boy has experienced is another matter
altogether. The book begins with Lewis recounting the events of the
past summer. Until then he had been waiting for his life to begin.
It begins in Paris with his infatuation for the seductive Valentina
Gavril.
</P>
<P>
   Valentina, a best-selling writer of medieval romances, summons
Lewis' mother, Alice, her English translator, to Paris. The
publisher is pressing hard for completion of the latest book, and
Alice must translate as Valentina writes, a situation that has the
two women at odds.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, who comes along to practice his French, is left on his
own to explore the city. He spends the days wandering the shops and
parks _ gorgeously described _ contemplating his passion for
Valentina.
</P>
<P>
   Tremain introduces a diverse cast of characters, all of them
important to the mystery. Lewis befriends Baba, Valentina's maid, a
sorrowful young African who fears she will be deported because her
working papers have not come through. He visits Valentina's mother
in a musty apartment that recalls her Russian exile. Didier, the
man repairing Valentina's roof, takes Lewis under his wing, telling
him of the sad fate of his own father, who was also a roofer.
</P>
<P>
   Each portrait is rounded, yet subtle. Valentina's neighbor,
Moinel, we infer, is suffering from AIDS. In pushing back his chair
in a cafe, Grigory Panin, Valentina's Russian lover, shows us his
frustration has turned dangerous. One look at Didier's wife's dress
and we understand he is unhappily married and involved with Alice.
</P>
<P>
   Didier engages Lewis in thoughtful conversations, explaining his
existential philosophy. When Lewis tells Valentina about the
roofer's ideas, an amused Valentina replies that no one is an
existentialist anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not, but the characters at times sound dark and
existential. Cool, remote Alice tells Lewis, ``We're in a life we
don't understand.'' His father, Hugh, has warned him not to look
for too much happiness.
</P>
<P>
   Even Valentina admits that a person must make choices based on
circumstances. ``You do not know what you are capable of doing,
until that moment ... arrives,'' she tells him. More often,
Valentina, vowing ``never to be poor again,'' sounds suspiciously
like Scarlett O'Hara.
</P>
<P>
   A third of the way into the book, after leaving Lewis to meet
Grigory at his hotel, Valentina disappears. It will be up to Lewis,
``a person of resolution,'' according to the head teacher at his
school, to find her.
</P>
<P>
   At first, he has difficulty convincing anyone she has been
kidnapped. When it becomes clear even to the blas police
investigator that she has been taken, Lewis withholds his theory on
the motive for the crime. He has discovered that Valentina's latest
romance novel is plagiarized from Grigory's biography of Catherine
the Great. Lewis believes that Grigory, discovering this perfidy,
has forced Valentina to return with him to their native Russia. But
this is only one possibility.
</P>
<P>
   As Lewis delves deeper into Valentina's life _ modeling himself
after the inspector Petrovich in ``Crime and Punishment'' _ he
comes up with some revealing evidence. He doesn't realize how
closely he is approaching the truth of Valentina's abduction.
Closely enough, it turns out, that he too is kidnapped.
</P>
<P>
   Tremain positions the characters like pieces in Lewis'
well-loved chess game. She manipulates them a little too precisely
in the manner of mystery writers. Although clues are strewn
throughout, they are better read backward than forward. Even Lewis'
toy soldier, introduced in Devon, becomes a plot device. The only
thing that we can guess will be important is the French book Lewis
is translating into English for pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the sleuthing seems plausible for a clever, well-read
teen-ager. Even his rescue reveries of the woman he adores are
persuasive, the best dream a boy could ever have. The reader sees
Lewis as Tremain intends: a smart, resourceful youth but still a
child when it comes to capturing the attention of the adults who
are in charge.
</P>
<P>
   No one expects him to find Valentina, no one but Lewis himself.
He may be the book's hero, but his being kidnapped takes the story
across the line and turns it into an adolescent fantasy, complete
with half-crazed, bungling abductors.
</P>
<P>
   Tremain does redeem herself at the end. Having brought Lewis and
Valentina together improbably, she provides a bittersweet
conclusion that takes the story round to its opening.
</P>
<P>
   Yet underneath this competent mystery-adventure lies a richer,
more affecting coming-of-age story. In Lewis' voice, Tremain
achieves perfect pitch. Here is a boy at the end of childhood,
seeing his parents clearly for the first time. Tremain conveys his
dawning realization that his unworldly father is incapable of
holding on to the beautiful, complicated Alice. In his mother's
bretrayal Lewis senses his release from her.
</P>
<P>
   He is moving into his secrets just as she is moving into hers.
``Almost nothing turns out the way you think it will,'' Alice tells
him. It is a truth Lewis learns too early.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
