<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CRISIS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN RUBLE CRISIS TRIGGERS NEW JITTERS AROUND THE WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDs: FILED in ``i'' and ``f'' categories.)   News Analysis  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BERNARD D. KAPLAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Recent nervousness in global markets stemming from fears
that the ruble might be devalued is something new. Russia has
repeatedly teetered on the edge of economic ruin in the years since
the collapse of communism in 1991 without causing undue
international alarm.
</P>
<P>
   Except for its extensive mineral resources like natural gas,
Russia hasn't really been a player in the economic big leagues.
Most of its industrial products are inferior, if not downright
shoddy, and therefore uncompetitive.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the tribulations of President Boris Yeltsin's
regime have been greeted calmly abroad _ that is, until now.
</P>
<P>
   Last week as Russian markets plunged over the threat of
devaluation, foreign officials and investors reacted with evident
concern.
</P>
<P>
   As the ruble nosedived, U.S. officials said they expected Russia
to survive its problems, and Yeltsin, declaring there was no
crisis, ordered his government to put a strict limit on how much
the currency would be allowed to fluctuate against the U.S. dollar.
However, many financial authorities were skeptical that such
artificially imposed limits could be maintained for long.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time it's different,'' said Paris-based Robert
Vishnogradov, a specialist on the Russian economy. ``The worry is
that further trouble in Russia might be enough to trigger worldwide
difficulties because major economies everywhere are currently
treading on thin ice.''
</P>
<P>
   Asia's banking crisis, worsened by Japanese Prime Minister Keizo
Obuchi's warning last week that his country faces a lengthy slump,
rumbles on. Nervousness has grown that Wall Street's recent losses
may foreshadow a bear market. European officials fear their own
hoped-for upturn may be submerged by a big drop on the U.S. market.
</P>
<P>
   Russian economic disintegration could prove to be ``the drop of
water that causes the glass to overflow,'' Vishnogradov said.
</P>
<P>
   Although many analysts insisted that Russia's latest crisis is
mainly psychological, resulting from a general loss of confidence
in Yeltsin, Vishnogradov said there was little doubt the country's
financial system has ``broken down.'' He noted that ``the
government can't meet its bills and is unable to collect taxes
because people simply refuse to pay.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Russia has continued to soak up foreign loans ``the
way blotting paper soaks up ink,'' he said, estimating that $30
billion from the International Monetary Fund and other sources has
``trickled away'' during the past three years. ``Nobody can really
say what has happened to the money,'' he added. ``It certainly
hasn't helped the national economy or stabilized government
finances.''
</P>
<P>
   There's little reason to fear bankruptcy, he contended, because
``Russia is already effectively bankrupt.''
</P>
<P>
   Demonstrations by unpaid workers have become a daily event in
Moscow. For some, unpaid wages go back as far as 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Parts of Russia's industry have reverted to a primitive barter
economy. Last month, a company manufacturing combines sold five of
the harvesters to Bulgaria. The Bulgarians paid for them with a
shipment of 50,000 jars of dill pickles. Workers at the plant
received pickles, instead of rubles, as their back wages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
