<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARTIAL SUN, FREQUENT WATERING WILL HELP BLUE BUTTERFLY BUSH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY HUBER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I have a blue butterfly bush (``Clerodendrum ugandense'') in
a container. Could you tell me what it needs?
</P>
<P>
   A: Your blue butterfly bush can continue to grow in a container
in partial sun. It will require frequent watering, as everything
does, during summer. Therefore, you'll need to replenish nutrients
more frequently. A balanced fertilizer or a hibiscus-type (with a
high last number rather than a high middle number) is best.
</P>
<P>
   The blue butterfly bush should be root-hardy in Zones 8-9 in a
protected spot in the garden. Plant in moist but well-draining rich
soil in partial shade. Mulch to protect the roots. You will lose
the top during freezing weather, so you might want to continue
growing the plant in a pot.
</P>
<P>
   You'll find blue butterfly bush produces its 1-inch, two-toned
flowers best in spring and fall rather than in summer. I've even
seen our plant loaded with blooms during mild winter months.
</P>
<P>
   Prune to prevent excessive ranginess. The plant can reach well
above 6 feet. I like to give mine an application of diluted fish
emulsion from time to time.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: I bought four ``Thunbergia grandiflora'' this spring. I now
have a large fence covered with Thunbergia, but where is the
grandiflora? These vines haven't bloomed. I fed them a couple of
times with 10-10-10, and two weeks ago I applied 10-60-10 to no
avail. Do you have any ideas where I've gone wrong?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``Thunbergia grandiflora'' is a rapid grower that likes sun.
Commonly called sky flower vine, it produces beautiful, large,
sky-blue flowers late summer until frost. Flowering may continue
into early spring during winters as mild as the one just past. But
usually the top dies during freezing weather, and the vine returns
from the roots in spring and provides good shade by summer. Mulch
to protect the roots.
</P>
<P>
   I imagine there is an adequate supply of phosphorus in the soil.
Your vines should come around. Hold off on any further applications
of phosphorus, represented by the high middle number in the
fertilizer formula.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: My large ``Judge Solomon'' azaleas I've had for 20-25 years
seem to be afflicted with some disease. I first noticed signs of
trouble about a year ago. A small limb will droop, then the leaves
on that limb turn pale, then brown. Eventually the small limb dies,
then the entire larger limb goes through the same process. About
half of two large shrubs are gone now. Is this treatable or
helpless?
</P>
<P>
   A: There are fungal diseases that pester azaleas here. Symptoms
are similar. Phomopsis dieback, which is triggered by stress,
causes wilting and yellowing foliage and dying twigs and branches.
If you cut a stem of the plant and see brown streaks, Phomopsis is
the problem. Remove any affected branches to try to control the
situation. This may work, and with special care through this heat
and drought, your plants may make it. Keep the soil moist but not
soggy. Mulch well. You could try a copper or sulfur spray or ask
your nurseryman for a systemic spray.
</P>
<P>
   Another disease that strikes azaleas is root rot, which is
usually triggered by poor drainage. At work here is the fungus
Phytophthora, encouraged in warm, wet conditions. When this fungus
is at work, you'll see wilting, discolored, then dead leaves.
Branches may die. Ensuring good drainage is the best preventative.
A systemic fungicide also can be used as a control. Remove affected
branches. If the shrub does not survive, remove and replenish the
soil in that area.
</P>
<P>
   I, too, detected problems with a couple of azaleas last year. I
removed affected branches and gave those shrubs extra care and so
far have not had to use fungicides. The shrubs seem to have
recovered, but with the incredible extremes we've had these past
two years, it's not surprising when any plant falters or fails.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a tuberose that is planted in a medium-size black pot
that rests in a decorative planter. It has done well and put on two
flower stalks loaded with white buds. The flowers have never
opened. The plant is on my deck and gets afternoon and evening sun.
</P>
<P>
   A: Tuberoses like sun and a well-draining, organically enriched
soil. I'm not trying to duck a real answer here _ but if yours are
receiving proper culture, I think it's not only too hot by day, but
too hot at night for flowers to behave as they ``should.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mail garden questions to Kathy Huber, Garden Editor, Houston
Chronicle, P.O. Box 4260, Houston 77210. The bulk of mail prevents
individual replies to all unpublished letters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
