<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-17 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7387 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOT-WOODSTOCK-HNS &LR;      08-17 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOT-WOODSTOCK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAPPUCCINO AND KHAKIS: A WOODSTOCK WITHOUT THE PURPLE HAZE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ELIZABETH BENJAMIN  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BETHEL, N.Y. _ This time there was no mud, very little garbage
and no free-for-all at the entrance.
</P>
<P>
   But ``A Day in the Garden'' _ actually three days of rock music
_ on the site of the original 1969 Woodstock festival, has
generated a cultural critical mass of its own. Though it has drawn
a fraction of the 400,000 people who flooded Max Yasgur's farm for
the concert 29 years ago and fewer than the 30,000 promoters had
hoped for on Saturday, a sense of optimism and accomplishment
abounded in the countryside over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the first time around, there was no shortage of
bathroom facilities or food at ``A Day in the Garden.'' Vendors
were doing a brisk business selling cappuccino ($3.50 for a small,
$5 for a large), and grilled portabello sandwiches with french
fries for $5 a pop. Tye-dyed T-shirts, hemp dresses and rope
bracelets abounded. An enterprising Cornelius Alexy hawked metal
peace sign pendants he swore were crafted from pieces of the fence
that gate crashers ripped down 1969.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are stardust, we are golden and we've got to get ourselves
back to the garden,'' Joni Mitchell wrote in her 1970 anthem,
``Woodstock.'' On Saturday afternoon, Mitchell delivered a mellow
set to an appreciative crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The vast majority of people who attended ``A Day in the Garden''
weren't alive in 1969. Generation Xers with signature baggy jeans
and T-shirt and halter tops mixed with bikers with chest-long
beards and boomers sporting earrings and khakis.
</P>
<P>
   Concertgoers arrived with young children in tow. Families sat on
blankets or lounged in lawn chairs while listening to performers
like Melanie and Richie Havens _ both alumni of the original
Woodstock.
</P>
<P>
   Some even sprang for the wooden folding chairs, which were being
rented for $20 apiece or $30 for two.
</P>
<P>
   More than 200 State Police troopers set up nine traffic
checkpoints around the concert site, effectively barring those who
did not have either tickets or official credentials.
</P>
<P>
   The natural amphitheater was surrounded by five miles of wooden
split-rail fences, manned every 50 feet by plain-clothes officers
to discourage gate crashing, the police said. The few people caught
trying to sneak into the site were asked to purchase tickets or to
leave.
</P>
<P>
   Even though several ``beer gardens'' started serving at 11 a.m.,
the animated crowd remained well-behaved.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not the pasteurized, '90s version is a worthy
successor to the 1969 Woodstock Music and Art Fair that almost
instantly achieved cultural landmark status remains up for debate.
</P>
<P>
   Concert organizer and developer Allan Gerry, who made his
fortune in cable television, sees the new festival as a positive
change with a chance to improve the future of the region. So do
Bethel town officials, who hope Gerry's plans to turn fields
surrounding the 37-acre site into a park to showcase an array of
American music will bring a much-needed economic boost to
economically struggling region.
</P>
<P>
   The lower Catskills two hours from New York City are no longer
the thriving Borscht Belt resort area with bungalows, hotels and
entertainment. But the current concert's organizers have fixed
their gazes firmly on the future. Gerry's vision includes a
permanent stage where the original Woodstock stage stood along with
a hotel, restaurants and a museum of popular music.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday morning, Lynne DiCostanzo, a 46-year-old physician
from nearby Callicoon, and Maureen Baxter, a 49-year-old nurse
practitioner from Rock Hill, rented chairs and set themselves up
near the middle of the sloping lawn. ``Of all the things I have
done in my life, I will never, never forget Woodstock,'' said
DiCostanzo, who wore a T-shirt and shorts, herself a hippie at
heart. ``But this is wonderful, very pleasant. We really need
something like this here. The county is a mess.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Mike Rinaldi, who was born 18 years and several miles away
in Marrowsburg: ``I don't think this is anything like what happened
in 1969, but it's cool,'' he said. ``A lot of people are moving
away. Anything would be better than that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
