<SLUG> BC-ANTI-GAY-AD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTI-GAY AD STIRS CRITICISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM HERRON ZAMORA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Daniel Leifler said he spent ``20 years asking
God to make me straight, praying and praying and praying some
more.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Leifler is out of the closet and his faith in God is
stronger than ever. He said he spent years wanting God to make him
heterosexual instead of accepting ``that God made me gay.''
</P>
<P>
   Leifler, 40, was one of 16 gay Christians interviewed Sunday at
Metropolitan Community Church in San Francisco's Castro District
who shared their responses to a full-page advertisement published
Sunday in the San Francisco Examiner by a group that claims it can
cure gays and lesbians of homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   That ad features a photograph of about 100 smiling men and women
described as ``ex-gays'' and offers to help homosexuals change
their orientation through faith, saying, ``many have walked out of
homosexuality ... into sexual celibacy or even marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   It is one of four similar ads that have appeared in the New York
Times, Washington Post and other newspapers in the past month. A
coalition of 15 Christian groups paid $35,000 to the San Francisco
Newspaper Agency to place the ad in the news pages of the Sunday
Examiner, which also is received by subscribers of the San
Francisco Chronicle. The Chronicle had rejected the ad.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there are any newspapers that understand these issues, I
thought it would be in San Francisco,'' Leifler said. ``I'm very
disappointed. I thought you knew better.''
</P>
<P>
   Examiner Managing Editor Sharon Rosenhause said, ``The Examiner
accepted the ad because the newspaper does not believe in censoring
any group's views, however abhorrent they may be. While we accepted
the ad, we also published an editorial in Sunday's paper,
expressing the paper's view that the ad `represents a perversion of
Christian ideals.'''
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, the ads have sparked a firestorm of controversy
among gays, lesbians and psychologists specializing in sexual
orientation. They call the ads' claims wrong and hateful.
</P>
<P>
   The ads contend homosexuality is learned behavior, not innate,
as many gay activists have argued in their campaign for civil
rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Claiming that sexual orientation is chosen is like claiming
that the Earth is flat,'' Leifler said. ``There's no scientific
basis for their claims. They just want it to be true.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, there were a handful of callers to The
Examiner who were critical of the newspaper's decision to publish
the ad. No one could be reached Sunday at the toll-free number for
Exodus Ministries, the group that placed the ad. Exodus is an
umbrella organization of religious groups that uses counseling to
help gays and lesbians who want to be straight. The 25-year-old
organization moved from San Rafael, Calif., to Seattle two years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   The ad was denounced from the pulpit at the Metropolitan
Community Church.
</P>
<P>
   ``We of the Metropolitan Community Church refute the claims made
by the ad regarding the sinful nature of homosexuality, and we
refute the claim that any person's sexual orientation needs to be
changed,'' the Rev. Karen Foster, assistant pastor, told the
congregation.
</P>
<P>
   ``When violence against gay and lesbian people is on the rise,
when young people who suspect they are gay commit suicide at
alarming rates, rhetoric that claims homosexuality is a sinful
disease is both irresponsible and absolutely contrary to the love
and compassion central to the Christian ethic,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Most parishioners interviewed took issue with the claims made by
the ad and the right-wing groups behind it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ad is using the guise of religion to promote hatred and
intolerance,'' said Betsy Hosick, a parishioner from Castro Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Fellow parishioner Joe Miller agreed, saying: ``God created us
just as we are. This ad isn't designed to help anyone. This ad is
designed to play on the fear of the unknown and stir up support
among conservatives for the right-wing agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   For homosexual Christians such as Leifler, the ads' claims
stirred painful reminders of their own personal struggles to
reconcile their belief in the teachings of Jesus Christ with their
sexual orientation.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one group has a monopoly on faith in God,'' said
parishioner Paul Slaikeu of Hayward. ``The groups behind this ad
have a very limited perspective on God. ... It shows that some
people are rather out of touch.''
</P>
<P>
   Many conservative Christian groups believe that one can't be
both gay and religious, and they have taken strong public stances
against homosexuality. Sunday's ad praised football player Reggie
White and Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., ``for having
the courage to speak the truth about sexual sin.''
</P>
<P>
   But a whole wing of Christianity sees otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``For 29 years, we in this church have and continue to celebrate
ourselves as gay and lesbian Christian people,'' Foster said.
``Both our sexuality and our spirituality are gifts from God, and
we celebrate those gifts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
