</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLOPPINESS VS. MAKE-BELIEVE AT THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HARRY ROSENFELD  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The flap at The Boston Globe over different
punishments meted out to two transgressing columnists, one a black
female, the other a white male, illustrates how race impacts what
otherwise might have been just another dispute over journalistic
standards.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Smith wrote movingly about Boston's minorities, as
befits a writer who is also a poet. She resigned at the editor's
request because she had made up people and conversations for large
parts of four columns.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Barnicle made his reputation evoking Boston's blue-collar
world, and cultivated national stature from his frequent
appearances on television. Less than two months after Smith had to
leave, Barnicle was caught presenting as his own thoughts eight
one-liners that appear to have been rewritten from a book by comic
George Carlin.
</P>
<P>
   After Barnicle claimed he had not read the book, his editor
suspended him for one month without pay. Whereupon the television
station where he appeared regularly showed a clip in which he
recommended the Carlin book to his viewers. At this point, the
editor asked for his resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Barnicle refused. He took to TV and radio to drum up support and
an advertiser, readers and other Globe staffers all lobbied on his
behalf. The editor changed his mind and handed him a two-month
suspension without pay, which Barnicle agreed he deserved.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, editor Matthew Storin came under fire for
adopting a double-standard because of race and/or gender. Joining
in the escalating criticisms were Harvard law professor Alan
Dershowitz (with whom Barnicle has feuded in print), the Boston
chapter of the NAACP, a racially mixed group of Boston Globe
staffers, other African-American activists and even the editorial
page editor of The New York Times, owner of the Globe.
</P>
<P>
   In our time, self-consciousness about race almost invariably
tends to enmesh issues involving blacks and whites, heightening
tensions and the stakes in play. What might otherwise be an
ordinarily complicated dispute over fairness gets caught up in
racial politicking, making matters worse. That grim reality
underlies what is happening at The Boston Globe. To the contrary,
the American ideal is that race should not matter, that common
decency ought to command that everyone in the same boat be treated
equally. As hallowed as that proposition might have been in
national mythology, it did not flourish in fact.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, to assure fairness, the Civil Rights Act of 1964,
following by nearly 100 years an earlier civil rights law, made
discriminatory treatment of employees of different races and both
sexes illegal. For the first time, the mythology was given
practical means of achievement. Another law, the Civil Rights Act
of 1991, provides that ``the complaining party demonstrates that
race, color, religion, sex, or national origin was the motivating
factor'' in the discipline.
</P>
<P>
   At The Boston Globe, Barnicle partisans invoked race to defend
their man. They reasoned that his offense, copping a few jokes, was
not in the same ball park as making up all or large parts of
columns. They argued that Barnicle was being pressured to resign to
provide a perception of racial equity to the discipline meted out.
</P>
<P>
   Race was not raised by Patricia Smith's supporters until the
demand for Barnicle's resignation was withdrawn. Then her
punishment was no longer regarded as legitimate to preserve the
integrity of the newspaper. Yet examining the facts coldly,
Barnicle's offense was of a different magnitude from Smith's.
Moreover, her editor says she had been warned three years ago
against making things up in her column.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, questions were also raised about the factualness of
some quotes in Barnicle's columns. According to the editors,
nothing had been found to confirm fakery. Smith, on the other hand,
admitted to what she did.
</P>
<P>
   Barnicle belatedly explained about the column material that his
TV commentary had been filmed several months before it was telecast
and he had forgotten having recommended the book, which he insists
he did not read, but which his friends discussed with him.
</P>
<P>
   Newsroom staffers at the Globe were angered by Barnicle not
having been forced to leave, in part, apparently, because they felt
he is a prima donna not held to the same standards that the rest of
them were.
</P>
<P>
   In journalism, there is nothing worse than the writer who
concocts a story and presents it as fact. A newspaper columnist may
resort to fictional techniques to make a point, but the reader has
to be aware that is going on. The reader can be clued in through a
direct statement or by way of an obvious implication or hyperbole,
for example, the late Mike Royko's use of his alter-ego, barfly
Slats Grobnik, as a foil. Patricia Smith was properly disciplined
because she committed an intolerable offense over the years.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Barnicle, who is guilty of personal arrogance and
inattention to his job while pursuing television celebrity,
deserved reprimand, maybe more than he got, but not firing. Not
quite yet. He has to get back to earth and to work. If he gets
seriously sloppy again, he also should have to go. Stardom should
be an attribute of excellence, not a substitute for it.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Harry Rosenfeld is editor-at-large of the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
