<HEADLINE>
THE TROUBLE WITH CLINTON'S TROUBLES 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Dave Hepp thought it was a reasonable question.
</P>
<P>
   He and his partner, Lise Bang-Jensen, host a public television
program called ``Inside Albany.'' They were moderating a debate the
other night between the three candidates for the Democratic
nomination for the Senate seat now held by Alfonse D'Amato, a
Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Green, New York City's public advocate, has always been a
strong voice for integrity and truthfulness in government. Former
Rep. Geraldine Ferraro is an old Washington hand and has endured a
few trials of her own in public life _ her husband's real estate
operations in New York City, for example, her son's drug problems.
Rep. Charles E. Schumer sits on the House Judiciary Committee.
Conceivably, he could have to consider this question in concrete
form instead of just as a hypothetical.
</P>
<P>
   So the other night in a large meeting room at an Albany hotel _
during a political debate sponsored by the Public Employees
Federation, a big state government union _ Dave Hepp asked this:
``Before we go to questions from union members out here, I'd like
to just get a quick response to President Clinton's troubles.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd of public employee union people laughed nervously.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just got your quick response,'' Schumer snapped.
</P>
<P>
   Hepp plowed forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you know, he's about to testify before a grand jury. Isn't
it time for him to tell all?''
</P>
<P>
   The response was loud groans and boos from the crowd, as though
Hepp was some pro wrestler kicking the good guy in the crotch while
the referee was looking elsewhere. Undaunted, Hepp pressed for his
answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``And under what circumstances,'' Dave Hepp asked, ``would you
urge President Clinton to resign?''
</P>
<P>
   That question was greeted by a spirited chorus of boos from the
crowd. Schumer took the occasion to say that Ken Starr is a
wretched human being. It was one of the few things Mark Green
agreed with him on. And Ferraro responded that nobody cares about
any of this except reporters.
</P>
<P>
   I was there that night, watching that ugly scene. I talked with
Dave Hepp about it the next day.
</P>
<P>
   He told me, ``I was surprised that as soon as I mentioned
President Clinton's troubles the boos broke out ... It was the
first time I've gotten booed at a debate, not being a candidate. In
retrospect, I'm not really surprised. It was a Democratic crowd,
and afterward I talked to some people. And they said, `We don't
want to hear about this. It's you press people.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always, you know, when you can't find a whipping boy,
it's the press at fault ... As soon as the candidates got that
reaction from the crowd, they said, `Oh boy, we'll handle this.'
</P>
<P>
   ``So you just ask the question. I've been pounded on by the best
of them. What the hell?''
</P>
<P>
   I've gotten the same thing _ on my voice mail number, on my talk
radio show. Who cares if the president lied about a fling with some
woman? That's private. Why did they even ask him about that in the
first place?
</P>
<P>
   Here's why: Paula Jones sued him, alleging that he'd come on
like a pig with her in private. The judge in the case said, ``OK,
since it's your word against his, Ms. Jones, you can call other
employees on whom he might have hit to establish a pattern of
behavior on his part to bolster your case. And you can ask him if
he came on with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Private stuff? Sure. If, that is, you want to kiss goodbye to
enforcing sexual harassment laws, if you want bosses to lie with
impunity in these cases, regardless of the evidence. That's the
price of privacy in matters like this. But, really, who cares,
right?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
