<HEADER>
A7401 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-PROFILE-MACBETH-     08-17 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-PROFILE-MACBETH-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BARD GOES TO MANHATTAN IN NEW TAKE ON `MACBETH' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's a brilliant day in Manhattan, and the songbirds
are trilling their joy. Sunlight spills through a canopy of leaves
onto the stone walls and arches of Fort Tryon Park, a rolling snake
of green that undulates above the spikes-and-slabs topography of
Washington Heights.Macbeth and his Lady embrace on the path before
a small mob of filmmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your face, my thane, is as a book where men may read strange
matters,'' she says, reaching out to caress her husband's rugged
visage. The birds chirrup. A heavy camera skids back on a dolly.
Lady Macbeth moves closer, holds his hand to her lips, stares
lovingly into his eyes. They kiss.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on cue, the planes arrive. Two of them, searing across the
tufted sky from La Guardia Airport, adding ungodly 20th-century
noise to a sedate medieval scene. William Shakespeare would not
approve.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does the director, Greg Lombardo, a wiry 28-year-old with
quick blue eyes and a pronounced addiction to cigarettes. He takes
a drag, peers at the jets arcing overhead. He winces.``Cut!'' he
snaps at his entwined stars, who relax and step back in
late-afternoon slants of light.
</P>
<P>
   They are a handsome couple: Lady Macbeth, robed in a glorious
ankle-length wine sheath, is Gloria Reuben, best known as Jeanie
Boulet on ``ER.'' Playing her tortured general is Nick Gregory, a
veteran of independent film (``Last Summer in the Hamptons'') whose
Ceasar haircut tops an altitudinous figure. He doesn't stand; he
looms.
</P>
<P>
   Gregory and Reuben are the leads in ``Macbeth in Manhattan,'' an
aptly titled independent production produced and co-written by
filmmaker Joe Gagen.
</P>
<P>
   It's Gagen's first feature film. He's done industrial and
corporate videos before, and as a lifelong film buff he has long
dreamed of producing ``something tangible ... something that maybe
people could enjoy and get sustenance from.''
</P>
<P>
   But this brisk, 20-day shoot in the urban wilds of Manhattan
marks his real introduction to the insomniac madness of making
movies. ``A friend of mine who is a big-time producer said to me:
`Making a film is like going to war,' says Gagen, a
gentle-mannered, quietly persuasive man of 58. ``Filming just takes
over every minute of your day. There are so many demands whenever
you're the director or the producer. You are constantly, constantly
busy and it doesn't end with the 12-hour days that are allotted for
filmmaking.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a Monday in June, and Gagen has just come off a
particularly trying run: He and his wife, Vera, allowed their house
on West 94th Street to be used as a set for almost a week. For six
straight days, several dozen cast and crew members squatted in
their living room, ate, drank, perspired, used the bathroom, moved
furniture around and muscled sundry tech equipment into the nooks
and crannies of their home. It was not an easy fit. And while Gagen
is glad to trim fat from the budget, turning his abode into a
soundstage is one cost-cutting measure he isn't likely to try
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never use your home as a set,'' he says, his affable face
sagging with battle fatigue. ``That's the first rule of
producing.''
</P>
<P>
   .MDNM/A producer's woes are never-ending. The director may helm
the day-to-day filming, but the producer is responsible for keeping
the entire thing afloat. Gagen isn't just the bean counter: He
obtains the beans (in this case, from private investors), tallies
the beans, dishes out the beans and frets when the beans run short.
</P>
<P>
   It's been seven takes already, and for a small-budget film (less
than $500,000), that's a lot of celluloid. The sun is getting low,
and the director's getting itchy Lombardo isn't one for ordering
take after take after take. Besides, he says, ``This has to be the
last take I have to go to the bathroom.''
</P>
<P>
   He laughs, tugs at another cigarette, shuffles a foot on the
tarmac.
</P>
<P>
   Reuben and Gregory take their marks for the eighth time. Then
Gregory steps back, batting at his head ``a bug bite,'' he says.
``I could just feel it on my ear.'' Lombardo is willing to call it
a day, but Reuben wants another shot. So, take eight. Take nine.
And take 10, which gets Lombardo's relieved OK despite the jet
passing imperiously overhead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thumbs up! Cut! We got it!'' he says, then steps back from the
flicker of a video monitor. The shot is finished. ``Macbeth in
Manhattan'' is one scene closer to completion.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Movies are different on screen than on paper, but a read through
Gagen's and Lombardo's script reveals Shakespeare with a dash of
soap: It's the bickering behind the Bard, a contemporary tale of
actors rehearsing a stage production of ``Macbeth'' in New York
City. As work on the play progresses, cast members become embroiled
in their own tale of sex, betrayal and revenge, assuming the traits
of their characters in the play and engaging in an eerily similar
scenario.
</P>
<P>
   Macbeth, for those who haven't read the play since high school,
is a triumphant general with dreams of ruling Scotland.
Unfortunately for him, King Duncan already wears the crown. But
Macbeth's conniving, seductive wife persuades her morally
ambivalent husband to murder Duncan, pin the blame on a couple of
drunk guards and thereby assume the throne.
</P>
<P>
   Horrific consequences ensue; Macbeth slaughters several other
people, including the wife and children of his main rival, MacDuff
(played in the film by David Lansbury, Angela's nephew), while Lady
Macbeth is unhinged by guilt (``Out, damned spot!''). The king dies
by the sword of MacDuff. End of story.
</P>
<P>
   Shakespeare's oeuvre ``is fantastic, you can always reinvent
it,'' says Lombardo, whose work as artistic director of the touring
National Shakespeare Company caught Gagen's eye last year. When
Gagen approached Lombardo with an idea for an updated ``Macbeth,''
their first impulse was to write the script as a comic documentary,
similar to ``Looking for Richard,'' Al Pacino's sly exegesis of
``Richard III.''
</P>
<P>
   (MORE...MORE)
</P>
<P>
   But as the project progressed, it became less of a mockumentary
and more of a Russian nesting doll, a play-within-a-film that
embraces layers upon layers of storytelling.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the play, Macbeth wants to be a superstar,'' Lombardo
explains, ``so when you set that against a backdrop of people who
are ambitious or greedy... '' He trails off. After mulling over the
differences between film and stage, he says: ``The idea of a play
within a play is such a common theme in Shakespeare. To do a play
within a film is a natural.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The only downside to fiddling with ``Macbeth'' is its legendary
curse actors have expired performing the role. As a result,
superstitious thespians routinely refer to it as ``The Scottish
Play,'' hoping to avoid death, injury or other insult sparked by
the wrath of Shakespeare. ``Macbeth in Manhattan'' is no exception.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the beginning it was really kind of scary, because one
person fell off the stage,'' says Gregory. ``Then I stabbed David
Lansbury'' in the arm, during a swordfight; he recovered ``and I
had one incident on my third day of rehearsals when a person came
up to me and said, `Is it dangerous riding on those bicycles?' It
was like witches with omens. I really wondered whether I would be
injured by the end of the shoot.''
</P>
<P>
   For all its tinkering, the film stays true to the spirit of
``Macbeth.'' The screenplay blends scenes from Shakespeare's
original with contemporary sequences set amid the hubbub of modern
Manhattan; tying them together is a soliloquizing ``Chorus,'' a hip
young emcee who keeps the audience up to date on the political
rumblings in assorted Scottish castles. Played by actor Harold
Perrineau (of TV's ``Oz'' and last seen on the big screen as bear
food in ``The Edge''), he pops up throughout the film in different
guises as a costume designer, a makeup man, a fellow sweeping the
stage. The role was conceived as a bridge, an ambassador of sorts
between Shakespeare and his silicon-age interpreters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It actually gives me a lot of different things to do,'' says
Perrineau, a bolt of energy with a beaming grin. ``He's not really
one character, but he is there in different ways, as a stage hand
or a (street) person. It's been fun figuring out what to do with
each of them. `Oh, my God! What do I do for this character?'''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike his castmates, Perrineau doesn't utter any of the Bard's
actual dialogue. Reuben and Gregory get their share. ``For any
actor, it's really a good challenge,'' says Reuben, scooting across
an intersection at Broadway and 97th on her way to shoot another
scene. Juggling two distinct characters divorced by space and time
is, she says, a tricky proposition. ``It kind of gets intricate:
I'm an actress playing an actress playing Lady Macbeth. But it's
timeless. The messages and the relationships and the character
traits are timeless.''
</P>
<P>
   Gregory agrees. ``It's the best material in the world, you
know,'' he says of Shakespeare's text. He says Gagen's and
Lombardo's screenplay is one of the sharpest he's read ``in a few
years.''
</P>
<P>
   He has great expectations for the finished product. ``It's
really rare that you get a product where the director, actor and
the writing are all good,'' Gregory says. ``It's usually one good
actor, or it's not written that well, or it's got a bad director.
But this film has potential to turn out really great so I'm really
excited.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
