<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors,  &UR; The New York Times &LR;  is planning as many as six pages
of coverage of the president's grand jury testimony and its
aftermath. These are are among the stories now planned:
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-RDP (Washington) _ Ledeall: President Clinton testifies
from the White House to the Kenneth Starr grand jury. By James
Bennet.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-ASSESS (Washington) _ Analyzing the president's gamble
in testifying. Is his strategy likely to work? By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-SCENE (Washington) _ The scenes at the centers of power
in Washington today. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-REACT (Washington) _ A look at the short- and long-term
political impact of the president's testimony. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-FRIENDS (Washington) _ Reaction among the president's
defenders: how they feel about his testimony. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-HILLARY (Washington) _ The First Lady: her role and
reaction to her husband's testimony. By Jill Abramson.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-LEGAL (Washington) _ After the testimony, what are the
legal issues remaining, and how did today's developments affect
them? By Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-PROCESS (Washington) _ What happens next? More grand
jury witnesses? A report? On what and to whom? What does the House
do if it gets a report? A few answers. By Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-MEDIA (Undated) _ Watching the news media watching the
president. By Janny Scott.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to these, we are pursuing several other stories,
including a report of the whereabouts of Vice President Gore, a
reaction piece from citizens around the nation, and a comparison
between today's developments and crucial days in other
presidencies.
</P>
<P>
   We will update this advisory as developments warrant.
</P>
