<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DI-ANNIVERSARY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIANA REDUX: GET READY FOR THE MEDIA ONSLAUGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVIS ARMSTRONG  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ She haunts us still. When Princess Diana died
suddenly and tragically Aug. 31, 1997, in Paris, much of the world
plunged into intense, prolonged public mourning.
</P>
<P>
   A media icon in life, Diana is a de facto saint in death. She
will be canonized anew with documentaries and updated reports on
the fatal car crash in the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly everyone on Earth knew Diana secondhand, solely through
media images: Her wedding portraits, pictures of her charity work,
her carefully crafted confessional TV interview, the state funeral
watched by a tearful audience of 2.5 billion. Her many admirers
feel they knew her personally and easily accept her self-coronation
as ``the people's princess.''
</P>
<P>
   This is no mean feat for a rich blueblood, a pal of pop stars,
fashion designers and playboys. Yet, such is the power of the
camera that distant celebrities seem more ``real'' than people we
really know. Differences in class, race and nationality become
blurred in a facsimile of intimacy.
</P>
<P>
   Many media outlets are planning fresh Diana tributes,
culminating on and near the Aug. 31 anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Attenborough's ``Diana,'' a two-hour documentary film by
the director of ``Gandhi,'' will air in prime time Aug. 31 on NBC.
Additionally, ``Dateline NBC'' plans to devote a show to the late
princess.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be outdone, CBS will air Diana packages on the ``CBS
Evening News,'' ``The CBS Morning Show'' and ``48 Hours.'' MSNBC,
the cable network owned by Microsoft and NBC, will devote blocks of
programming to Diana over seven days, Aug. 28 through Sept. 3.
</P>
<P>
   MSNBC's ratings soared when the then year-old network pre-empted
programming to obsess about Di immediately after her death. ``We
had our highest numbers ever,'' recalls spokeswoman Cameron
Blanchard. ``Our numbers went to 3.0 for the top quarter-hour
during the funeral.'' That's about 1 million households. MSNBC
averaged a barely-there 0.1 rating, 39,000 households, before
Diana's death.
</P>
<P>
   After Diana's demise, MSNBC permanently dropped programs,
including the technology show ``The Site.'' ``We wanted to be more
reactive to breaking news,'' Blanchard says.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Epstein, the MSNBC programming executive overseeing this
year's ``Diana: The First Anniversary'' package, says, ``There's a
serious interest among the public on this, on her humanity and her
message. She's still huge. There's a continuing fascination with
this woman and the royals.''
</P>
<P>
   MSNBC will kick off Aug. 28 with NBC News' Donatella Lorch and
Charles Sabine reporting from Paris and London. On Aug. 30, MSNBC
anchor Jodi Applegate will host a live, one-hour special from
London, adding more updates the next day. Starting Aug. 31, ``Time
&AMP; Again's'' Jane Pauley presents the first of four nightly one-hour
reports on Di and the royal family.
</P>
<P>
   Blanchard declines to divulge how much the shows cost or how
much revenue MSNBC expects to take in, but Epstein says any efforts
devoted to Diana are well worth it. ``It's the story that put us on
the map,'' he says. ``It showed viewers the depth of NBC News.
Clearly we knew we would devote significant resources to it'' this
year.
</P>
<P>
   People magazine, which put Diana's face on the cover a
mind-boggling 43 times before she died and published an all-Diana
keepsake issue last September, does not plan to do a new
stand-alone issue. Instead People will include a Diana package in
an upcoming regular issue, says spokeswoman Susan Ollinick, who
doesn't say if Diana will again adorn the cover.
</P>
<P>
   Barring big Ken and Monica news, it wouldn't be wise to bet
against Diana. She has been a big money-maker for Time Inc.'s
People. Published reports say that four issues of People with Diana
as cover girl sold out, each issue bringing in an extra $1 million
in ad revenue. People, with a paid circulation of 3.5 million and
profits of more than $200 million a year, is America's most
profitable magazine.
</P>
<P>
   FOOTNOTE: On Sept. 5, 1997, six days after Diana's death, Mother
Teresa died. Like Diana, Mother Teresa did good works. Unlike Di,
36, Mother Teresa was old, 87, and not a glamorous dresser. How
many major network TV specials will air on the first anniversary of
Mother Teresa's passing?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
