<SLUG> BC-PHILIPINO-VETS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAVING PVT. TICAO, AND OTHER PHILIPPINE WAR HEROES 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EMIL GUILLERMO  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Everyone wants to save Private Ryan. No one
wants to save Pvt. Felizardo Ticao.
</P>
<P>
   Pvt. T. Cow? No, Ticao. He's Filipino. He's one of those heroes
no one seems to give a damn about. In a few short years, he's
likely to die, our debt to him unsettled.
</P>
<P>
   But Pvt. Ryan? He's hotter now than on D-Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saving Private Ryan'' has grossed over $100 million already.
Considering all the eventual revenue streams, the film's grosses
could finance a small war. Hooray for World War II. The one we
actually won. But not without help.
</P>
<P>
   The war in the Pacific was won with the capable support of
Filipinos _ like Pvt. Ticao _ enlisted to fight alongside American
forces. People know vaguely about Bataan and Corregidor. They know
of the death marches and the Japanese concentration camps. But few
people know of the more than 200,000 Filipino men who were promised
full benefits to fight for America _ only to be cruelly cut off at
war's end by something known as the Rescission Act of 1946.
</P>
<P>
   That makes the Pvt. Ryan phenomenon fairly ironic. While money
is rolling in buckets to the movie, there's not much money from
anybody, specifically the U.S. government, to save real heroes like
Pvt. Felizardo Ticao. Ticao was awarded the Purple Heart by Gen.
Douglas MacArthur. He got the same award, but not the same
benefits. You won't find Pvt. Ticao's tale of patriotism and
heroism at the movies.
</P>
<P>
   To experience the heartache of his continuing war, one can look
at photographer Rick Rocamora's exhibit, ``Unfinished Mission: The
American Journey of Filipino WWII Veterans,'' currently on display
at the San Francisco Art Commission Gallery.
</P>
<P>
   Stare into the proud but somber eyes of Ticao, 80. A hero who
helped defeat the Japanese, he's been whipped by the squalor of
American homelessness.
</P>
<P>
   See another Purple Heart recipient, Melecio Cayao, play with the
hook attached to the prosthetic device that replaces his right arm.
The Rescission Act slashed his veterans benefits in half. You'd
figure a right arm would be worth something to a right-wing
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Like many of the Filipino vets, they arrived in San Francisco
and Los Angeles in the 1980s, looking to be made whole. But with
Congress blocking veterans benefits (an estimated $1.4 billion),
most veterans are forced onto welfare.
</P>
<P>
   It's not the pot of gold they were seeking. They want their
benefits, not welfare, said Rocamora. But they're also afraid of
dying in America. They're willing to settle before they're sent
back to the Philippines in a box.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has until October to grant the money and end the
bureaucratic death march. But it's unlikely to happen. Is that
anyway to treat legitimate war heroes? It is when no one cares
about saving Pvt. Ticao.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Emil Guillermo is an independent syndicated columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
