<P>
   EDS: The following stories moved late last week and are being
updated and resent Monday morning for those who have not yet used
them:
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-PRESIDENCY _ WASHINGTON _ The prolonged investigations
into President Clinton's personal life and his past financial
dealings have forever changed the presidency. Experts believe that
court decisions requiring the testimony of Secret Service agents
assigned to the president, as well as rulings stripping away
executive privilege from top presidential aides, will cause future
presidents to alter their conduct, making them unreasonably
cautious about everything they say or do while in the White House.
And forcing the commander-in-chief to testify in civil trials and
grand juries, as Clinton did on Monday, could signal a future in
which presidents spend much of their time with lawyers prepping to
take part in court proceedings. (Shepard, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-REPORTERS _ WASHINGTON _ They slogged through Whitewater
despite a public that often preferred to hear less rather than more
about presidential scandal. They weathered the backlash of the
Clinton White House and sometimes faced resistance from fellow
reporters and their own publications. Now the handful of
journalists who have followed a trail of Clinton controversies for
six years are seeing their work lead to the first-ever appearance
by a president before a criminal grand jury. The persistence of
fewer than a dozen reporters has been largely responsible for
keeping the issue of Clinton's conduct before the country. ``The
heroes are the ones that have kept it alive,'' says Britt Hume, who
anchors an evening report on Washington for Fox Cable News. ``These
people have done tremendously well on this story, and it hasn't
been easy.'' Among them: Susan Schmidt of The Washington Post,
Newsweek's Mike Isikoff, Steve Labaton of The New York Times, Pete
Yost of the AP, as well as Jackie Judd and Chris Vlasto of ABC.
(Malone, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   US-ADULTERY _ WASHINGTON _ Despite President Clinton's high
approval ratings in the face of allegations of marital infidelity,
a huge majority of Americans still believe adultery is wrong,
according to polling data. And adultery among the average American
couple is far less common than the flurry of recent allegations
against Clinton and other public figures would suggest, say
sociologists, marriage counselors and clergy. But in cases of
divorce, adultery plays a much larger role. (Shepard, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND-BOMBING _ OMAGH, Northern Ireland ? Police arrested five
suspects at dawn today in connection with the car bomb that killed
28 people and shattered hundreds of lives as it ripped through this
religiously mixed town in Northern Ireland. The suspects were
arrested in two villages north and southeast of Omagh and taken to
the main police center in Belfast, 70 miles to the east. Under
Northern Ireland?s anti-terrorist law, they could be questioned for
up to a week before being charged or released. (Roughton, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: To move by 4 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ECONOMY _ MOSCOW _ Struggling to stem the bleeding of its
drained financial markets, Russia sharply devalued the nation's
currency on Monday, raising fears that hyper-inflation and social
instability could follow. Russia's weary consumers braced for a
decline in their buying power, particularly for imported items.
(Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: To move by 4 p.m. EDT. in both the (i) International and
(f) Financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   JAMAICA-VIAGRA _ KINGSTON, Jamaica _ A 70-year-old man accused
of raping a 27-year-old woman after taking a dose of Viagra goes
before a judge on Tuesday(Aug. 18) in what may be the world's
first-ever Viagra assisted rape case. But the case comes as no
surprise here. Although the male-impotency drug is supposed to be
illegal in Jamaica, it's smuggled in because of its soaring
popularity and sold for as much as $20 a pill. Throughout Latin
America and the Caribbean, where male virility is a much-prized
attribute, Viagra has ignited widespread interest. People have even
stepped up campaigns to get indigenous potency products -- such as
the bois bande tree bark -- out to men who might be unable to
afford Viagra. (Emling, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: To move by 3 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   BURMA-ANAND _ WASHINGTON _ The 21-year-old Atlanta woman
arrested along with 18 other Americans in Burma for distributing
pro-democracy leaflets, Nisha Anand, returned to Washington Monday
and described her six-day ordeal of detention, show trial and
deportation. (Foskett, Cox News Service).
</P>
