<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-GORTON-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORTON'S AID FOR MICROSOFT PAYS OFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. Slade Gorton's advocacy for Microsoft is being
rewarded with campaign contributions from company executives.
</P>
<P>
   During the first six months of the year, 23 Microsoft executives
have contributed to Gorton, even though the state's 70-year-old
senior senator isn't a candidate for anything and hasn't announced
whether he plans to seek re-election in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The amount of money Gorton has received from Microsoft _ $7,250
from January through June _ is a small fraction of the $200,000
Gorton raised during that period.
</P>
<P>
   But the number of contributors from Microsoft _ most of whom
gave at a fund-raiser two weeks after Gorton made his first major
speech on the Senate floor defending the company _ is an indicator
of growing appreciation for the senator at the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year we have an annual gala, and this year there were
350 people there,'' said Gorton's chief of staff, Tony Williams.
``We have not had that number of people from Microsoft in the past.
They were there because they want Slade to run again in 2000, and
they want to be supportive.''
</P>
<P>
   Already this year, Gorton has received money from nearly four
times as many Microsoft employees as gave to him in all of last
year. In 1996, no one at Microsoft gave him money, and in 1995, he
got a contribution only from company Chairman Bill Gates.
</P>
<P>
   Gorton has received money from more Microsoft employees than has
Sen. Patty Murray, who is running for re-election this year, and he
has received money from more employees than contributed to him the
last time he appeared on the ballot, in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Gorton's current Microsoft contributors also are mostly
high-ranking executives, in contrast to Murray's Microsoft
contributors, who are generally middle managers.
</P>
<P>
   Among this year's contributors to Gorton are half of Microsoft's
executive committee, including Steve Ballmer, the company
president; Bob Herbold, the executive vice president and chief
operating officer; Nathan Myhrvold, the chief technology officer;
and Jeff Raikes, group vice president for sales and support. The
contributors also include the company's top in-house lawyer,
William Neukom, and several of its other lawyers and lobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   Gorton, a former state attorney general, has been a passionate
defender of Microsoft and a relentless attacker of its critics,
including Senate Judiciary Committee Chairman Orrin Hatch and the
Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   A week after the fund-raiser, Gorton made another Senate floor
speech defending the company, and he has since given numerous
speeches and news conferences praising Microsoft and attacking its
critics. He has also opened his office for use by the company and
has agreed to represent Microsoft at a debate in Seattle this
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft employees are very appreciative of Senator Gorton,
Senator Murray and the whole congressional delegation,'' company
spokesman Vivek Varma said. ``It's really not surprising to see
some of our employees participating in the process and supporting
political campaigns.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorton, who has held elective office in Washington state for all
but two of the past 40 years, would turn 79 in the final days of a
fourth term in the Senate. Although he suffered a mild heart attack
in 1994, he says his health is fine _ he runs five miles a day _
and he seems energized by the power he possesses as a subcommittee
chairman and a confidant of Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott.
</P>
<P>
   According to a financial disclosure report recently received by
the Federal Election Commission, Gorton has $250,000 in his
campaign treasury. That is not much by Senate standards, but enough
to signal that he is not ruling out a future race.
</P>
<P>
   ``This shows that he wants to keep all his political options
open and wants to keep his troops energized,'' Williams said. ``He
is doing all the things that lead me to believe he's going to be a
candidate (in 2000), and he has told his staff to make sure that
option is open.''
</P>
<P>
   The report indicates that Gorton is spending money nearly as
fast as he raises it, mostly on direct mail to shore up his
contributor base. Most of Gorton's money is coming from Washington
state residents, not political action committees or out-of-state
residents.
</P>
</TEXT>
