<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PETE-WILSON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOV. WILSON'S GREATEST WORK MAY BE OVERSHADOWED 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PETER SCHRAG  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ With the completion of the 1998-99 budget,
the record on Pete Wilson's eight years as governor and California
policy-maker is now all but closed. Unless something totally
unexpected occurs in the next few months, it's a record in which
negative strokes of politics, though often successful, are likely
to be more memorable than the positive acts of policy.
</P>
<P>
   In assessing the record, the biggest mystery is the governor
himself, a man whose better angels seemed forever to be warring
with his darker side. And it was that darker side that, through
much of his tenure, seemed most often to prevail.
</P>
<P>
   It did not begin that way. Wilson arrived in office as a fully
credentialed moderate flying the flag of what he called
``preventive government'' _ early intervention, particularly among
young children to reduce the need for more costly remediation later
on _ in health, in education, in crime control.
</P>
<P>
   As a moderate _ and particularly as a supporter of abortion
rights _ and as a man who supported Gerald Ford over Ronald Reagan
in the 1976 primaries, Wilson was never close to the conservative
heart of the California Republican Party. But in 1990, on the eve
of the 1991 decennial reapportionment, California Republicans
needed Wilson more than he needed them. He was by far the most
electable Republican, and a little moderation was a small price for
preventing the Democrats from gerrymandering the state one more
time.
</P>
<P>
   The enormous recession-driven budget deficit of his first year _
ultimately a total of $14 billion _ sharply constrained Wilson's
ability to pursue his prevention agenda. Family planning money was
immediately restored and a few symbolic health care initiatives
were launched, but not much more. Yet even Wilson's resolution of
that first budget crisis _ through an almost even balance of tax
increases and spending cuts _ was moderate and, in the face of a
Legislature dominated by Democrats, admirably pragmatic.
</P>
<P>
   But in a state where parties are increasingly driven by
ideology, no pragmatic compromise earns much praise, and no good
deed, no matter how necessary, goes unpunished. Wilson got little
credit, particularly in his own party. The experience, combined
with the untimely death of his long-time friend and aide, Otto Bos,
early in his first term, seemed to have spooked Wilson so
profoundly that he has looked ever since like a man who has been
trying to make amends.
</P>
<P>
   One part of the amends-making was the dragged-in-by-the-heels
vehicle license fee cut that Wilson managed to win in the budget
negotiations just concluded. That, as some people charge, may just
be Wilson trying to make himself acceptable to conservative
Republican primary voters in New Hampshire in 2000. In part it may
also have been Wilson's effort to prove that the taxes he had to
approve in bad times were in fact repealed in good times.
</P>
<P>
   But there have been more fundamental consequences as well, most
particularly the emergence of the nasty-tough Pete who dominated
state affairs for much of the past eight years:
</P>
<P>
   _ The divisive wedge-issue politics of Proposition 187, the
initiative, since blocked by federal courts, that was designed to
deny schooling and other services to illegal immigrants, and the
inferential Mexican-bashing that accompanied it.
</P>
<P>
   _ The equally political exploitation of Proposition 209, the
measure prohibiting race-based affirmative action in California
public education, hiring and contracting.
</P>
<P>
   _ The heavy-handed attempt, in Proposition 226, to punish the
unions that have been his chief political adversaries.
</P>
<P>
   _ The blatant political arm-twisting in 1995, before Proposition
209 was passed, to make the University of California regents follow
his line on affirmative action. All this from a man who, as mayor
of San Diego and a state legislator, was a strong supporter of
affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   _ The neglect of officially sanctioned brutality in the state's
prisons. The failure during his first five years in office to
address any of the state's pressing educational issues, even as the
state's schools were falling further into disrepair and
dysfunction; the quixotic presidential bid of 1995, despite his
promise to serve the gubernatorial term to which he had just been
elected.
</P>
<P>
   The relative merits of any single measure on the list of old
Wilson favorites are debatable. But surely not many people in the
future will look back on them as great progressive acts in public
policy or as steps that have in any measurable way enhanced the
public climate and quality of life in California.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Wilson has done a good deal in recent years to improve
preventive health care for children. He helped eliminate a long
list of expensive and scandal-plagued practices in the state's
workers' compensation program. He forced into place California's
first real statewide school testing program in a decade, a program
that, for all its flaws, should ultimately give Californians a
fairly decent relative measure of how well their schools and
children are doing. He appointed a first-rate group of justices to
the state Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   The irony is that this list is likely to be overshadowed by the
other. It was ``three-strikes'' sentencing laws, the death penalty
and divisive proposals such as Propositions 187 and 209 that got
the public attention and Wilson's political energy _ the things
that he most wanted to be known for. Sadly, he will get his wish.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Peter Schrag is the retired editorial page editor of the
Sacramento Bee.)
</P>
</TEXT>
