</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERVIEW-LABUTE-PATRIC-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILMMAKERS AIMED FOR `THE TRUTH' IN `FRIENDS, NEIGHBORS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Jason Patric and Neil LaBute are an unlikely pair.
</P>
<P>
   One's an enigmatic, almost obscenely handsome actor, and the
other is a chubby, unkempt writer and director.
</P>
<P>
   But they've just completed collaborating on ``Your Friends and
Neighbors,'' LaBute's eagerly awaited second feature _ the followup
to his controversial, scathing comedy of corporative manners, ``In
The Company Of Men.''
</P>
<P>
   Patric has often played a loner anti-hero, teetering on the
precarious brink of stardom in a hit-and-miss string of movies like
``Rush,'' ``Sleepers,'' ``Geronimo,'' ``After Dark, My Sweet'' and
the dismal ``Speed 2.''
</P>
<P>
   Some projects never even opened in theaters _ indeed ``Denial''
tanked and went directly to video and ``Incognito'' has yet to be
released. But luck might be about to change for Patric, whose
granddad was comic Jackie Gleason and whose father is the
playwright Jason Miller.
</P>
<P>
   As Cary, the hard-core conscience and purveyor of truth in
``Your Friends and Neighbors,'' the actor finds himself in the
center of another dark, abrasive modern comedy of morals and
manners; this time set in the picture perfect apartments and trendy
homes of six ``friends'' in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Patric produced the film, along with Steve Golin, and it was
shot in brisk 22 days.
</P>
<P>
   The movie boasts a stellar cast _ Patric, Amy Brenneman, Aaron
Eckhart (who finally gets his due after playing the despicable Chad
in ``In The Company Of Men,'' and who put on 40 pounds to play this
role), Catherine Keener, Nastassja Kinski and Ben Stiller.
</P>
<P>
   It's an ``immorality tale'' about two couples and two singles
who are friends, and, if pushed, likely enemies. They scheme,
cheat, argue, love, covet and suffer together. ``Welcome to the
'90s,'' cautions the film's tag line.
</P>
<P>
   Patric and LaBute are anything but contentious on a hot Seattle
summer day. They have an easy camaraderie as they sip ginger ale in
their suite at the Olympic Four Seasons Hotel and eagerly talk
about the film that is sure to infuriate, distance and possibly
enlighten audiences.
</P>
<P>
   LaBute is keenly aware that he pushes buttons. He says though
``Your Friends and Neighbors'' might keep viewers at ``an
appropriate aesthetic distance,'' they can't help but be caught up
in what's happening onscreen because ``it uses human beings.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a conceit the playwright Brecht got wrong,'' says LaBute.
``He was great on paper but he forgot he was using people. That's
why I think we have a comedy here instead of a drama. People watch
it and laugh because there's a recognition factor. It isn't like,
say, a sci-fi film.
</P>
<P>
   ``As much as I use distance and shoot scenes in long takes,
we're still just presenting a situation and not passing judgment.
People always say, `Oh, I've been there,'' after they see it and
that's because no matter how far back I put the camera, it's still
human and it's still funny; it's funny in that awful, funny way we
humans get along with one another.``
</P>
<P>
   In fact, ``Your Friends and Neighbors'' often feels like a live
theater piece because it's so painfully intimate and full of
intense, talky scenes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The film could be perceived as cruel but I think it's just
that it's hurtful in the way people can be hurtful,'' says Patric.
``I personally see the vulnerability in all these people. They just
make specific choices that ultimately are their demise.''
</P>
<P>
   LaBute his goal wasn't to give the audience an easy ride, but to
find the truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The response I've gotten so far is, `I'm glad you're being
respectful to your characters because by doing so you're respectful
to us.' And all of these characters are surprising because they
aren't cookie cutter stereotypes of good and bad people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's right,'' asserts Patric. ``My character, Cary, for
example, isn't a braggart and he's not macho. I associate that with
people who are trying to impress. But he's the only character in
the whole movie who never lies. He's specific and that's what's
interesting about Neil's writing. Some of the best films are never
about whether we like the characters or wish they were real and we
could take them home with us, but just that they're human enough to
recognize them and to want to find out what eventually happens to
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the experience of making what might be perceived as a
cold-blooded, ruthless movie could have been a trauma for the
actors. But Patric says making the film was a pleasure, plus
``there was great joy in watching afterward how truly proud they
were of their work, which is not the norm.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The journey we went on in this film was very different from
how most movies are made,'' he insists. ``What I wanted to do as a
producer was create a great utopian existence for the cast because
I've never had that on a set. I knew it would cost money from the
budget but it had to be that way. It's what I believed acting was
really about _ the ensemble, the unity.''
</P>
<P>
   LaBute concedes that he, too, tried to make the set a welcome
place. ``I'm a director. I'm not onscreen, but directors these days
obliquely say, `Hey look at me, I'm over here.' Therefore the
tricks never stop and there's a perpetual signal that says
`director at work.' Actors like to act, not in 30-second scenes but
for a long time. In this film, the actors set the pace, not the
editor or director. It goes as fast as real life. I like talky
films.''
</P>
<P>
   So does LaBute believe these six characters are emanations of
his own personality? ``Oh sure,'' he smiles. ``I'm some piece of
all of them. Everything is a cocktail. They're part of me, part of
people I know. The things that happen in this film are not foreign
to me because I'm alive and living amongst people and I recognize
what they represent. There are six very distinct views presented.''
</P>
<P>
   LaBute, who has a gaggle of degrees and has written several
plays in addition to his two films, lives in Fort Wayne, Ind., with
his wife and two children.
</P>
<P>
   Patric says that he wasn't initially going to be an actor in the
film. ``I was just going to produce it. But when I read the script
I had a visceral response.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't had that kind of response to anything for a long
time. Early on in my career I was able to get good material and
some of the films I made were ahead of the dark indie curve.
Consequently, I spent a lot of time in the '90s with projects that
were only partially interesting. I'm at the point now where I want
to do things that I look forward to in a different way instead of
just making a career decision.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This film gave me the opportunity to be funny and it gave me
the chance to work with actors I wanted to work with. I liked the
fact it was hard-hitting because I don't like pandering to an
audience and I don't like fame for fame's sake.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-98 1436EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
