<DOCNO> NYT19980817.0202 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-17 14:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7466 &Cx1f; tth-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INITIATIVE-AFFIRMATIV     08-17 1737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INITIATIVE-AFFIRMATIVE-ACTION-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON INITIATIVE A BELLWETHER FOR ANTI-AFFIRMATIVE ACTION
MOVEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HEATH FOSTER  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two years ago, in the aftermath of California's passage of
Proposition 209, it seemed much of the nation was on the verge of
following the Golden State's lead and repealing affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   Legislatures in 16 states considered eliminating programs that
take race and gender into account in government hiring, contracting
or school admissions. Citizens in at least six states mounted
signature-gathering drives seeking to end affirmative action
programs.
</P>
<P>
   But all those statewide efforts have faltered, with one
exception: Washington state.
</P>
<P>
   Voters in Washington state will be asked to decide Nov. 3
whether to abolish preferences for women and minorities designed to
overcome historic racial and sexual discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   As the only state in the country considering a repeal this
election season, Washington is being watched by both sides of the
affirmative action battle.
</P>
<P>
   If Washington residents _ mostly white and known nationally for
being mild and reasonable _ abolish affirmative action, activists
believe they'll have a much better chance of making their
anti-affirmative action cause a mainstream movement.
</P>
<P>
   If the state retains its preference program, defenders of
affirmative action are hopeful an already faltering movement will
peter out.
</P>
<P>
   Houston voted last year to retain the city's affirmative action
program. But the effect of that vote was muddied after a judge
threw out the results because of a dispute over the ballot
language.
</P>
<P>
   ``The common wisdom is that if a mellow, laid-back state like
Washington, which isn't Mississippi, passes this, it will show this
effort is not a right-wing jihad, but a respectable debate over an
important con-
</P>
<P>
   stitutional principal,'' said Michael Greve.
</P>
<P>
   He is executive director of the D.C.-based Center for Individual
Rights, a non-profit law firm that has successfully defended
California's 209 from legal challenges.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Arnwine, executive director of the Lawyers Committee for
Civil Rights Under Law, a D.C.-based civil rights organization
tracking state efforts, said there's little question an Initiative
200 defeat would deal the movement a crippling blow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Opponents of affirmative action really thought after they were
successful in California they could spread this initiative like
wildfire across the country,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they found it just didn't have legs. So what they're
trying to do in Washington state is get a jump-start on batteries
that are running very low.''
</P>
<P>
   The story of how Washington became the only state to follow
California's lead this year sheds light on the difficulties
opponents of preference programs will face spreading their movement
farther.
</P>
<P>
   Washington, like California, had the key political ingredients _
grass-roots support, appealing ballot language and an infusion of
cash _ during the critical period in which signatures were being
gathered.
</P>
<P>
   California's Prop. 209 and Washington's I-200 also got their
starts in much the same way. Each was spurred by white men who
believed their state's affirmative action policies discriminated
against them and were damaging their careers.
</P>
<P>
   Two little-known San Francisco Bay-area academics, Glynn Custred
and Thomas Wood, were the masterminds behind California's ini-
</P>
<P>
   tiative.
</P>
<P>
   According to ``The Color Bind,'' a book recounting Prop. 209's
passage, the two scholars developed the wording of the initiative
after studying the language of the 1964 Civil Rights Act, as well
as polling data showing that voters who said they supported
affirmative action overwhelmingly disagreed with quotas and
programs that gave qualified blacks preference over equally
qualified whites.
</P>
<P>
   The final wording of the proposition, which is being copied on
Washington's ballot, said: ``The state shall not discriminate
against or grant preferential treatment to any individual or group
on the basis of race, sex, color, ethnicity, or national origins in
the operation of public employment, public education or public con-
</P>
<P>
   tracting.
</P>
<P>
   Prop. 209 didn't mention affirmative action; it focused on
preferential treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Custred and Wood failed to get their initiative on the 1993
ballot. And their 1995 effort nearly faltered until Republican Gov.
Pete Wilson persuaded Ward Connerly, a high-profile black
businessman who led the repeal of affirmative action at the
University of California, to take over.
</P>
<P>
   Connerly's own experience had taught him that hard work and not
race was the key to success. He strongly believes affirmative
action programs are a form of state-approved racism giving groups
advantages just because of their ethnicity.
</P>
<P>
   With the highly quotable Connerly at the helm, the state GOP
poured $500,000 into the campaign for Connerly to work with.
</P>
<P>
   Washington's story is uncannily parallel. I-200, too, was
dreamed up by two white guys _ state Rep. Scott Smith, a
35-year-old, plain-spoken Republican from Graham in Pierce County,
and Tim Eyman, a 32-year-old Seattle resident who owns a small
mail-order business.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's opposition to affirmative action is personal. He claims
that in 1991, his wife, Leslie, beat him out for a job offer from
the King County Sheriff's Office, even though she scored 260 places
behind him. He blames an affirmative action program that sought to
increase women officers in the ranks.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, as a freshman lawmaker, Smith decided to act on his
anger. He introduced a bill barring state and local governments
from using race or gender as a basis for granting jobs or
contracts.
</P>
<P>
   But the fireworks surrounding the issue made many lawmakers wary
of a debate in which charges of racism would be hurled across the
House and and Senate floors. Smith's bill never even came to a
committee vote and continued to languish in 1996 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But Smith was moving behind the scenes.
</P>
<P>
   He contacted Connerly and a new organization the UC regent had
founded to spread the anti-affirmative action gospel across the
country: the American Civil Rights Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Connerly had also been contacted by Eyman, who says watching
Connerly fight off personal attacks from other blacks convinced him
he was
</P>
<P>
   an ``inspirational, almost historic
</P>
<P>
   figure.''
</P>
<P>
   Eyman tracked down a Bellevue lawyer who drafted a nearly
identical initiative for Washington state. Then the American Civil
Rights Institute put Eyman and Smith together. And in March 1997,
they filed the Washington Civil Rights Initiative.
</P>
<P>
   Within a month, the ACLU challenged I-200 in Thurston County
Superior Court, arguing that the words ``affirmative action''
needed to be part of the ballot title because the initiative
effectively would undo affirmative action programs. The judge
disagreed, ruling that the ballot title and summary accurately and
objectively reflected the initiative's intent.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, voters here will be asked whether the state should
be prevented from discriminating against or granting preferential
treatment to any individual on the basis of race or sex.
</P>
<P>
   Eyman spent the summer striking deals to give local libertarian
and Republican groups $3,000 for every 10,000 signatures they could
deliver. Smith raised money.
</P>
<P>
   But by the fall, the two had only 17,000 signatures in hand and
little money in the bank. Smith said he knew they needed help. He
persuaded Connerly to call John Carlson, the provocative KVI-AM
radio host who had successfully taken two other initiatives to the
ballot, Three Strikes You're Out and Hard Time for Armed Crime.
</P>
<P>
   Connerly said I-200 needed a leader who was well respected
locally and not just another ``white guy whining that he lost a job
because of affirmative action.'' In Carlson,
</P>
<P>
   Connerly saw someone who could
</P>
<P>
   argue preferences are ``morally wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   With less than three months to deliver 180,000 signatures,
Carlson said he knew he'd need paid signature gatherers. He agreed
to become chairman on one condition: that the American Civil Rights
Coalition, the political arm of Connerly's rights institute, would
match every dollar raised with a dollar on its own.
</P>
<P>
   Connerly's group eventually provided $162,000, or about 45
percent, of the $373,458 that I-200 raised. Opponents raised just
$37,841.
</P>
<P>
   Connerly said his decision to pump money into Washington's
effort over drives in Florida, Michigan and other states was based
on a simple fact _ Washington is mostly white. He reasons that when
race becomes an issue of political debate, citizens
</P>
<P>
   tend to vote by the color of their
</P>
<P>
   skin.
</P>
<P>
   Connerly said he learned that lesson from experience in Houston,
where 54 percent of voters said they didn't want to end affirmative
action programs.
</P>
<P>
   The 1997 ballot language there specifically asked voters whether
they wanted to ``end the use of affirmative action for women and
minorities in the operation of city of Houston employment and
contracting.''
</P>
<P>
   But a judge recently overturned the vote, ruling that the ballot
language, which was altered by the City Council, didn't reflect the
intent of 20,000 voters who petitioned to put the issue on the
ballot using language similar to California's Proposition 209.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the race card gets played, people always vote their
identity, rather than on the basis of principle,'' Connerly said.
</P>
<P>
   He believes the cash infusion from the American Civil Rights
Coalition, and Carlson's success in prompting public debate on his
radio show, made the critical difference for I-200. In January,
Carlson, Smith and Eyman turned in more than 280,000 signatures to
the state, 100,000 more than were needed.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Komar of the D.C.-based Leadership Conference on Civil
Rights said the challenge for affirmative action defenders will be
educating voters about the initiative's true consequences. But with
polls reflecting as much as 69 percent support for I-200 statewide,
he conceded it'll be
</P>
<P>
   tough.
</P>
<P>
   Connerly, for his part, said a Washington victory here will be a
``real shot in the arm'' for his movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wouldn't be involved in Washington unless it was the only
way to keep the ball moving up the field,'' he said. ``We've got to
fight some highly selective battles until justice prevails.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
