<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LITERARY-RENAISSANCE-1200(2TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUDDENLY, SERIOUS BOOKS ARE HOT, AS READERS AND STORES GO HIGHBROW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM MADIGAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On a December night three years ago, New York book publisher
Morgan Entrekin knew he was onto something extraordinary.
</P>
<P>
   That night, Entrekin was reading a partially finished manuscript
from first-time novelist Charles Frazier, whose narrative traced
the journey of a Civil War deserter across the beloved mountains of
North Carolina, toward a reunion with a woman he hoped would be his
lover. The writing was poetic. The story gripping. The historic
detail impressive and illuminating.
</P>
<P>
   All of which led to a first printing by Entrekin's publishing
house, Grove/Atlantic, of 25,000 copies, a solid number for
literary first novels like Frazier's ``Cold Mountain.'' But the
bestseller list was a slender hope at best.
</P>
<P>
   ``A good success for a literary first novel would have been to
sell 40,000 to 50,000 copies,'' Entrekin said, incredulity still
apparent in his voice. ``And this one just exploded.''
</P>
<P>
   To say the least. By last week, ``Cold Mountain'' had hit 1.6
million in sales in its 57th week on ``The New York Times''
bestseller list, sales more commonly associated with the names of
John Grisham, Stephen King and Tom Clancy. And, perhaps more
surprising, ``Cold Mountain'' has plenty of company.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, similarly serious, literate books, both fiction
and nonfiction, have crashed bestseller lists in numbers not seen
in a generation. Witness ``Angela's Ashes,'' Frank McCourt's memoir
of childhood deprivation and grit in an Irish household, which
recently spent its 99th week on the ``Times'' list. ``Midnight in
the Garden of Good and Evil,'' John Berendt's quirky chronicle of
society in Savannah, Ga., has lingered on the ``Times'' list for a
staggering 212 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of other titles, though with somewhat less spectacular
sales, come to mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, at one time you had three literate first novels on
the bestseller list, `Cold Mountain,' Arundhati Roy's `The God of
Small Things' and Arthur Golden's `Memoirs of a Geisha,' ''
Entrekin said. ``I don't think that's happened in my 21 years in
the business. I know it hasn't, that you would have three literary
first novels on the bestseller list at one time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know exactly how to explain it, but I'm happy that
it's happening. It's good for the culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Julie Grau, co-editorial director at Riverhead Books in New
York, can scarcely contain her glee when discussing ``An Instance
of the Fingerpost,'' author Iain Pears' mystery set in 17th-century
Oxford, which lingered on the bestseller list for six weeks this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's the thing,'' said Grau, the editor of Pears' book,
which was published by Riverhead this spring. ``It's a really
intellectually rigorous, challenging book. It's a 700-page book,
and it's meticulously detailed and true to the period. I say it's a
murder mystery, but it's a deeply complicated plot ... and it hit
the `Times' list in its second week of sale.''
</P>
<P>
   She paused to laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Which is just amazing,'' Grau said. ``Miraculous. ... I think
there clearly is a constituency of people now who are ready to run
to the bookstore and buy books that come highly reviewed and
recommended regardless of the difficulty of the book. ... I think
it's healthy all around.''
</P>
<P>
   Particularly for the struggling authors of midlist books, the
modest publishing niche where literary, first-time novelists
generally find themselves.
</P>
<P>
   For these writers, advances and first printings are typically
small. Their careers generally require editorial patience, on the
bet a healthy readership can be acquired, often over a series of
books. Before their explosion, the books of Charles Frazier and
Frank McCourt would have fallen into the midlist category.
</P>
<P>
   It is precisely those writers who seemed at risk in a publishing
world increasingly controlled by huge conglomerates. Megacompanies
seeking double-digit profits usually prefer the cash cows like
Grisham, or Danielle Steel, or detective Mark Fuhrman, while
unknown writers of serious books are increasingly ignored. Or so
the industry moaning often went.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the opposite is increasingly true, editors and publishers
say. Publishers search the midlist, looking for the next ``Cold
Mountain.'' Entrekin, whose house has a long heritage of publishing
literary books often overlooked by the larger publishers, now finds
himself bidding against the giants for the same high-brow works.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it might be more apt to say that publishers are seeing
commercial potential in areas where they might not have seen such
vast potential before,'' said Grau, of Riverhead Books. ``The
success of one genre begets imitators. We rip ourselves off all the
time. This is just a more fruitful mimicry.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Editors and publishers, who enjoy the literary resurgence,
nonetheless have a hard time explaining it. A different marketing
approach may help, with publishers occasionally pushing literary
titles in the same, robust manner formerly devoted to the latest
celebrity bio.
</P>
<P>
   ``For instance, when I have a serious book that I think has some
talking points, I will myself, in addition to our publicity
department, call (National Public Radio talk show) ``Fresh Air'' or
Amazon.com (a bookselling Web site) to see if they're interested,''
said Daniel Menaker, senior literary editor at Random House. ``I
think we're learning that we're all competing for a little sunlight
to get into the serious corner of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The recent emergence of book superstores has also helped. Stores
like Barnes &AMP; Noble and Borders, with their coffee bars and plush
furniture, have become leisure destinations, the coffee shops and
libraries of yesteryear. And, as a matter of course, those stores
push serious literature next to the thrillers and the schlock.
Right now, a huge promotional poster in many Barnes &AMP; Nobles
features not Grisham or Steel, but author Ethan Canin and his new
literary novel ``For Kings and Planets.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, of course, there's Oprah.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's not picking dopey books,'' Julie Grau said, citing
Winfrey's promotion of novelist Toni Morrison as an example.
``Morrison's a world-class, provocative, important novelist. I dare
say that half the people who bought her books on Oprah's
recommendation had never read a book remotely like that before. So
Oprah's really introduced a whole broad spectrum of readers to
literary books.''
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps most encouragingly, the new enthusiasm for
literature is also because of a shift in cultural appetites. With
thriller entertainment now more readily available and easily
consumed on television, in the theater, or in video rental stores,
large numbers of consumers drift to books for greater edification.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be that people are really turning to books for what
books can do that no other medium can do, which is, in the hands of
a serious writer, take you places that no other medium can take
you,'' Entrekin said.
</P>
<P>
   Grau says that increasingly, when people invest the time
necessary for a book, entertainment is not enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people want to learn now,'' Grau said. ``It's not
merely enough to be entertained. They want to walk away with more
than a vague smile on their face.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
