A7497 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STELLA-FILM-REVIEW-TE     08-17 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STELLA-FILM-REVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`STELLA' NEEDS MORE THAN GROOVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Winston Shakespeare (Taye Diggs), the 20-year-old object of
affection in ``How Stella Got Her Groove Back,'' is a deep-dish
dream, a boy-toy sculpture carved out of Godiva chocolate who turns
out to be just the thing for on-the-go diva Stella (Angela
Bassett).
</P>
<P>
   ``Stella'' is probably the most unique picture in current
release because not only does it reverse the trend of older male
stars with younger female co-stars, it acknowledges the age
difference. If that isn't enough, it's also a glamour treatment for
African-American women, one in which they don't communicate in
hip-hop slang. Seeing black women in control of their own destinies
in a dramatic context is so unusual a film scenario that it's
thrilling.
</P>
<P>
   It's too bad we don't get to see it in a much better movie.
Except for the skin color of the cast, ``Stella'' is the kind of
thing that turns up with numbing frequency on Lifetime, sandwiched
between reruns of ``thirtysomething'' and ``Designing Women.''
</P>
<P>
   Stella is a 40-year-old single mother who thrives in her
professional life. As played by Bassett, she's all movie-star
dynamism _ the role seems mostly sketched from the outside.
Stressed out, Stella and her best friend, Delilah (Whoopi
Goldberg), pack off for a spontaneous trip to Jamaica. When the
20-year-old Winston sidles up beside Stella at breakfast, he
flashes teeth as white as bone china. And as Bassett is as perfect
a camera object as Diggs, they're a match made in screen heaven.
</P>
<P>
   Diggs' at-the-ready, eager-to-please grin makes him look like a
young (black) Tom Cruise. And in ``Stella,'' he's almost as bad as
the young Cruise, dropping the occasional ``Yeah, mon'' in a
Jamaican accent worse than the one Philip Michael Thomas used on
``Miami Vice.''
</P>
<P>
   Diggs has so little to do in his underwritten part that only
when I read the press notes did I realize I'd seen Diggs show
powerful presence on stage as the landlord in ``Rent.'' Winston is
not a part that requires Diggs to act, however. Instead, he follows
Stella around like a grateful puppy in a Jamaica that's been
sanitized in a ``Come back to Jamaica again and again''
tourist-mecca fashion. The dramatic high point for Diggs is a scene
in which he exposes his rock-hard booty in the shower, which will
probably get him a bigger ovation than any of his work in ``Rent.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Stella'' grinds along to its predictable finish as clumsily as
the Terry McMillan source novel _ Will the slapdash obstacles in
their path keep them apart? Because the book was a celebration of
McMillan's relationship under similar circumstances, it's not too
hard to guess.
</P>
<P>
   McMillan worked on the adaptation with Ron Bass; they also
adapted McMillan's ``Waiting to Exhale.'' ``Stella'' is a much
better movie than ``Exhale,'' if only because of the life Regina
King adds as Stella's younger sister.
</P>
<P>
   Because she's not required to carry the picture, King can relax
and show some humor and style. She has a familial rapport with
Bassett, and their scenes together are the only instances in which
Bassett doesn't seem like she's in the movie alone. Bassett and
Goldberg have no chemistry, and Goldberg makes cracks that probably
won't get as many laughs as those made by the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the wish fulfillment provided by a picture creates
such goodwill among audience members _ hungering for a fantasy they
don't normally see _ that it's easy to understand why they lean
close to a movie like ``Stella.'' When I saw ``Waiting to Exhale''
with its target audience _ African-American women who'd savored the
book, some of them holding dog-eared copies in their laps _ they
greeted the film with a thunderclap of applause that gave it a
great deal more power than it deserved. As their euphoria withered,
``Exhale'' still delivered a low level of satisfaction because
black women are so pitifully underserved by the movie industry. The
New Yorker critic Pauline Kael summed up this phenomenon: ``People
can be so hungry for a particular subject, it doesn't matter that
it's not very good.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the kind of response that ``Stella'' is likely to
trigger. Pandering to unsophisticated fantasies, rendering plot
points with the broadest melodramatic strokes, it's like the most
expensively mounted high-school play of all time. With any luck,
this fertile and underexploited ground _ dramas featuring
African-American women _ will peak soon, with the upcoming
adaptation of Toni Morrison's ``Beloved,'' starring and produced by
Oprah Winfrey. Until then, we'll have to make do with ``Stella's''
microwavable feel-good vibes.
</P>
<P>
   ``How Stella Got Her Groove Back'' is rated R for adult
language, brief nudity and sexuality.
</P>
<P>
   _ Film: How Stella Got Her Groove Back Director: Kevin Rodney
Sullivan Stars: Angela Bassett, Taye Diggs, Whoopi Goldberg Rated:
R Rating: 2 stars
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
