<P>
   SCI-ALASKA-THAW (Undated) _ Alaska is thawing, and much of
northern Russia and Canada with it, and many scientists say that
the warming of these cold regions is one of the most telling
signals so far that the planet's climate is changing. Experts have
long said that in an era of global warming, this bellwether region
should warm up more and faster than the earth as a whole, and so
far that is just how things are turning out. The signs are
everywhere. By William K. Stevens. (2500 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photos and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CRONIN-COSMIC-RAYS (Undated) _ At 67, with a great career as
a particle physicist and teacher already behind him, Dr. James W.
Cronin of the University of Chicago has embarked on a new one as a
kind of traveling salesman. He is campaigning in a score of
countries for help in building a pair of gigantic cosmic-ray
telescopes expected to reveal some tantalizing secrets of the
universe. By Malcolm W. Browne. (2000 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MAN-EATING-BEAR (Undated) _ Using the tools of forensic
scientists, biologists have been able to identify and track down
the bear family that devoured a 26-year-old hiker in Glacier
National Park headed by a matriarch known as Chocolate Legs. Yet
many mysteries remain, especially pinning down just what it was
that caused the bears to go bad _ a rare phenomenon among
grizzlies, despite their reputation. By Mark Derr. (1580 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DARK-MATTER (Undated) _ American and Australian astronomers
have found more evidence of dark objects apparently scattered
throughout the fringes of the Milky Way, and they say this could
solve the mystery of the dark matter that is unseen and accounts
for most of the mass in Milky Way galaxy. By John Noble Wilford.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BLACK-DEATH-RATES (Undated) _ Compared with whites, black
Americans have higher death rates from all kinds of serious
illnesses _ from heart disease, diabetes, stroke, some forms of
cancer and asthma. Black babies are more likely to be born small
and die in their first year, and black adults live fewer years than
their white counterparts. By Linda Villarosa. (1600 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PROSTITUTE-TRAUMA (Undated) _ The world's oldest profession
may also be among its most traumatizing. A new study has found that
a serious psychiatric illness resulting from exposure to physical
danger is more common among prostitutes than among troops who have
weathered combat duty. By Abigail Zuger. (600 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-COMPUTER-COLUMN (Undated) _ One of the most-overlooked
aspects of the underwhelming Windows 98 operating system is its new
WebTV for Windows. This is something that has huge potential,
particularly for those who are already watching television through
their computer screens. By Rob Fixmer. (1100 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Science questions answered: On seeing stars.
w/drawing
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ Shorts on science: Forget about keeping
valuable documents in a safe deposit box. The best place to
preserve them, scientists say, could be the fridge.
</P>
<P>
   BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ The American Council on Science and
Health recently updated and expanded its popular report, ``Facts
Versus Fears,'' reviewing what it considers the greatest unfounded
health scares of the last five decades. Although controversy
continues to rage about potential risks associated with some of
these ``scares,'' including hormones in beef and Agent Orange, most
_ including those that resulted in serious economic damage and
changes in public policy _ have been soundly discounted by
subsequent studies. A look at some of the most famous scares. By
Jane E. Brody. (1125 words) (``l'' code)
</P>
<P>
   TRIATHLON-HEALTH (Undated) _ Officials from the Centers for
Disease Control and 42 state health departments are investigating
an outbreak of leptospirosis, an infection contracted through
exposure to contaminated soil or water, among participants in a
Springfield, Ill., triathlon. They have concluded that this was the
largest recorded exposure in this country of the disease, which
sometimes goes by the appropriately murky name of swamp fever. By
John O'Neil. (550 words)
</P>
</TEXT>
