<SLUG> BC-FIRSTDAY-1500(2TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINDERGARTNER TAKES HIS FIRST STEPS AWAY FROM MOM ON FIRST SCHOOL
DAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY BINGHAM 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The boy bounds from the top bunk at 6 a.m.
because he hears his mom and dad stirring, and he can't sleep
anymore. This is a big day, and Kevin Langford is ready. This is
his first day of school.
</P>
<P>
   He sits at the kitchen table with his mom and dad and his
brother, 2-year-old Cade. They eat pancakes because pancakes are
Kevin's favorite. His are shaped like a dinosaur and a heart, and
one is supposed to be the letter K, for his name, but it spread so
much it looks like a truck ran over it.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin eats from ``the special plate.'' His mom drags it out for
birthdays most of the time. ``Today is Your Day!'' it says.
``Celebrate!''
</P>
<P>
   When breakfast is over, Kevin sits on his mother's lap and she
reads aloud the card they made the night before. On the front are
words for every letter of his name.
</P>
<P>
   ``K is for kind, E is for energetic, V for valiant. We had to
look that one up. I is for inquisitive. Do you know what that
means? N is for noble.''
</P>
<P>
   Lezlie Langford is Kevin's mom. She's 32 years old, and she was
a kindergarten teacher until Kevin was born. She tried to teach
that year but she missed him so much that she cried every day.
Three months later, she quit.
</P>
<P>
   She knows she will cry sometime today. But Kevin is so excited
she tells herself not to cry in front of him. She won't embarrass
him by crying at school, either.
</P>
<P>
   There have been moments she has almost cried just thinking about
this day. Memories are everywhere: Hank, the stuffed horse Kevin
used to sleep with; the white-blond lock of hair in his baby book;
the calendar where she recorded milestones and funny things he
said.
</P>
<P>
   June 22: ``Swim lessons at the Y.'' July 26: ``Mommy, can fish
live in milk?'' Aug. 13: ``You pretended to be a Dalmatian.'' Sept.
13: ``You made a soccer goal.'' Sept. 15: ``You counted to 20!''
</P>
<P>
   But Lezlie promised she would not cry. Every time she almost did
she thought of something else. She does it now, with Kevin on her
lap as she reads the card:
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear Kevin:
</P>
<P>
   ``We are so proud of you. You have grown into a truly wonderful,
sweet, smart little boy. We are very thankful to the Lord for
giving us the gift of you. Today you start a new adventure. Be
strong and courageous, and ALWAYS REMEMBER WHO YOU BELONG TO.
</P>
<P>
   ``Love,
</P>
<P>
   ``Mom and Dad''
</P>
<P>
   Lezlie eases him off her lap. ``Don't get too mushy now, Mom,''
she says. She rinses syrup from the special plate.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin is back in his room, climbing to the top bunk, where the
clothes he picked out last night hang on his bed. He wanted to wear
jeans but his mom said it was too hot so he wears the size 5 khaki
shorts his grandparents gave him on his birthday.
</P>
<P>
   He puts on the blue Gymboree shirt and the braided belt and he
sits on the floor beside Matchbox cars and a baseball bat that
pokes out from under the bed. He puts on white socks before he ties
the new laces on his old sneakers. His dad watches.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Langford is 34 and a highway construction project
engineer. He's not as emotional as his wife, but this morning he
tells Kevin that he couldn't wear shorts to school when he was a
boy. Kevin doesn't hear him because he's in the bathroom getting
Dad's aftershave. One squirt, and he's off to comb his hair.
</P>
<P>
   Chris says it seems like yesterday they walked out of the
hospital with a baby boy. Kevin Garth arrived at 6 a.m. on July 22,
1992, all 8 pounds, 9 ounces and 20 inches of him.
</P>
<P>
   The hardest thing about raising him was the surgery to mend the
collarbone broken during delivery. In the pictures, Kevin lies on a
hospital bed so big and white it looks like a cloud about to
swallow him whole. That was the hardest thing, Lezlie says. Until
now.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin went to preschool, but this is ``big school.'' From this
day forward he will be out of her sight for five days a week, 180
days a year, for the next 13 years. She tries to think of something
else.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look very handsome, Kevin _ very ready for school,''
Lezlie says. The video camera records Kevin picking up his book bag
from the spot beside the door where it spent the night. He packed
it before he went to bed, and now it slides down his back, heavy
with pencils, crayons, markers, paper and tissues.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're looking mighty sharp there,'' his dad says. Kevin
stands beside the piano in the living room and smiles for the
camera. Somebody notices the time. It's a little before 8 a.m.;
school starts at 8:05.
</P>
<P>
   The minivan rolls down Tucker Boulevard, and two blocks from the
school, you can already see the commotion: Cars, brake lights and
the flashing blue of a police car. You can hear it, too: the
policeman's whistle as he directs another gaggle of moms and dads
and children across the street.
</P>
<P>
   J.L. Hill Elementary is an established school in the center of a
subdivision old enough that nobody calls it by its name anymore _
Meadowbrook or Meadowcreek or something like that. The school
hasn't changed much in 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin walks up the steps past a girl in a green jumper posing in
front of the flagpole for a picture. The tide of people sweeps
Kevin and his mom through the doors.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Kindergartners take a left, past the cafeteria where the Scotty
terrier school mascot is painted in the clouds. They turn at the
first right, heading to Room 130, where Mrs. Speer is waiting.
</P>
<P>
   After 26 years of teaching, Liz Speer can hug a child and shake
a hand and at the same time sense that a camera flash is blinking.
She smiles in the nick of time.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Speer started teaching soon after the Texas Legislature
established kindergarten in 1970, deciding that every boy and girl
could benefit from a dose of early learning. Every one of her
classes has started something like this:
</P>
<P>
   Boys and girls sit on plastic chairs with chrome legs, hardly a
foot off the floor. Mothers and fathers stand above them,
spectators with cameras pointed. They expect something exciting to
happen and nothing does. The children ignore them, begin to draw.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Speer shepherds Kevin Langford to a seat at the center
table. To Kevin's left sits a boy named Andre; to his right, a girl
named Ellen. Across the table, a girl named Turner is drawing a
rainbow and a girl named Colleen is writing her ABCs with a pink
marker. The camcorders roll.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin's mother bends to kiss him goodbye. He doesn't see her
when she stands by the door and looks back. Kevin is coloring a
tree trunk when his mother leaves.
</P>
<P>
   It's close to 8:20, and the bell is about to ring. Mrs. Speer
smiles and nods and ushers the parents out.
</P>
<P>
   One little boy is crying and rubbing his eyes. His dad kneels,
and their foreheads touch. The boy's mom wipes tears from under her
glasses before Mrs. Speer closes the door behind them.
</P>
<P>
   So here they are: Eleven boys and six girls about to embark on
the rite of passage into adulthood. This is where it begins. This
is where children are taught respect, responsibility, the demands
of communal living.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Speer points to the classroom rules beside the black board:
``Look. Listen. Learn.'' She returns to them a dozen times.
</P>
<P>
   She reminds her boys and girls that following the rules will
result in praise and Happy Grams sent home to mom and dad. Breaking
the rules will bring her to her knees, at their side, where she
takes their little faces in her hands and warns them that a few
minutes alone in the corner will come if it happens again.
</P>
<P>
   Here, she explains, boys and girls clean up their own blocks and
put away their crayons. She instructs them to hold up the
index-card name tags dangling from their necks for formal
introductions.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Speer has their attention _ for now. She knows she has 10
minutes before their minds wander, and if she loses one, she is
like a comedian in front of a heckler and she risks losing them
all. When the bell rings, she is off and running.
</P>
<P>
   The clapping they do together will lead to adding and
subtracting. When they repeat the silly poem after Mrs. Speer says
it aloud, they are laying the foundation for reading. Their
drawings are the early stages of learning to write the 26 letters
of the alphabet, capital and lower-case letters alike.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin doesn't say much when the children sit in the circle and
hear a story about blue horses and purple cats. He quietly arranges
colored octagons when the class breaks into groups. His voice is
lost in the roar when all the children swing their arms with gusto
and shout the kindergarten motto: ``I can do it!''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Speer teaches them how to behave. They must share puzzle
pieces, stay in line on the way to the bathroom, wait their turn at
the fountain, walk and not run to their lockers, and refrain from
making animal or bomb noises during group activities.
</P>
<P>
   In three hours, she dispenses learning while she empties book
bags, fills lockers and nearly trips over a ``Toy Story'' backpack.
</P>
<P>
   She ties Sam's laces, tweaks Andre's nose, strokes Taylor's
ponytail, pats Carson's back, praises Xavier's puzzle, sorts Teddy
bears with Palak, Colleen, Taylor and Ellen. She thanks Kevin for
sitting so nicely at circle time.
</P>
<P>
   The children cling to her like burrs. Cody stops crying during
the pledge of allegiance and only sniffles during the moment of
silence. By the time two teachers sing ``This Land is Your Land''
over the intercom, shy Kevin is not so shy anymore.
</P>
<P>
   He is fourth in line behind Mrs. Speer when she marches around
the room while the record plays ``When the Saints Go Marching In.''
He buzzes like a bee and hisses like a snake and wiggles his hips
as the song tells him. He waits patiently when Mrs. Speer goes back
in the bathroom to fetch Blake and Richard, who have been delayed
by a bug in the toilet.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin sits so quietly at the end of the day that Mrs. Speer asks
him to hand out animal crackers. The day goes so fast that Andre
announced only twice that he was ready to go home and Mrs. Speer
said only twice that her hearing was fine and no one needed to
yell.
</P>
<P>
   All of a sudden the boys and girls are removing their name tags
and standing in line. Kevin is near the middle. Mrs. Speer sends
Matthew to the end for touching the knob without permission, and
she shuffles Ally from the boys line to the one for girls. She puts
a finger to her lips and down the hall they go.
</P>
<P>
   Lezlie Langford is among the parents waiting outside. Kevin runs
to her for a hug and then he takes off to climb on the wall with
the other boys. He's gone when his mom confesses. She made it out
of the school and to the car before it happened. She cried. She
knew she would.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
