r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRBUD-FILM-REVIEW-1S     08-17 0605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRBUD-FILM-REVIEW-1STLD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S FAMILY-FRIENDLY, BUT A DOG OF A TALE
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: FIXES box at bottom) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's no easy task, panning a movie with its heart in the right
place. Especially when it's a family movie that declines to stoop
to cheap jokes. Especially when you're a dog lover and the movie is
``Air Bud: Golden Receiver.''
</P>
<P>
   But the sad truth is that this ``Bud'' just isn't very good. A
sequel to last year's ``Air Bud,'' it's so by-the-numbers that it
makes the already formulaic original look like ``Old Yeller.''
Worse, though, it makes the same mistake as the original: It takes
a fun premise _ this time, it's a football-playing dog _ and
surrounds it with a gloppy, sentimental story that's no fun at all.
</P>
<P>
   You could almost forgive the original's maudlin aspects. After
all, it needed to introduce us to young hero Josh (Kevin Zegers),
who was despondent after his pilot father's death, and to canine
sidekick Buddy, an abused golden retriever who bonded with Josh
through their mutual love of basketball. But hey, they've bonded
already. You'd think the sequel would lighten up a bit.
</P>
<P>
   Zegers is an appealing actor, but Josh is fast on his way to
becoming the most screwed-up kid in movies. In this one, he's upset
because he might be getting a new father. Mom (the watchably quirky
Cynthia Stevenson, making the most of a slim role) is dating again,
and with the help of Buddy, she's found a good-natured hunk of a
veterinarian (Gregory Harrison) whose company she enjoys.
</P>
<P>
   Josh's anxiety at this would be more understandable if the vet
weren't such an obviously nice guy; maybe the kid's just perturbed
because his potential stepfather has a narrower range of facial
expressions than his pet. Even so, Josh's distress is more logical
than his solution to his mom's newfound love life: He joins the
football team! Of course, the players are so bad that even a team
of _ oh, film critics _ could beat them. And of course, Buddy comes
along to save the day.
</P>
<P>
   As forced as it is, the main plot is a gem compared with the
``comic relief.'' Nora Dunn and Perry Anzilotti make like Boris and
Natasha as a couple of evil Russian circus wranglers. Guys, ``The
Bullwinkle Show'' was a cool cartoon, but its Bolshevik villains
were a product of its time, not ours.
</P>
<P>
   Director Richard Martin (son of '60s ``Laugh In'' host Dick
Martin, who makes a lame cameo performance as an addled
sportscaster) had a lot on his hands here: kids, animals, three
plot lines that don't really intersect. Considering this, the
jagged, uneven product he puts on the screen is probably better
than it could have been.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is in the writing, and the premise itself. It is
kinda cool to watch a dog play football (Bud, the
basketball-playing pooch, died of cancer after the first film; a
pack of six dogs takes his place here). But it doesn't fill up a
feature film, and when the dog's not on the field, you might wish
you could zap to some other sporting event or run to the fridge.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't the final sequel: ``Air Bud: World Pup'' (you guessed
it _ Buddy plays soccer) is already in development.
</P>
<P>
   ``Air Bud: Golden Receiver'' is rated G. It includes some mildly
gross slapstick and scenes of imperiled animals, but it's family
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   _ Film: ``Air Bud: Golden Receiver'' &QL; 
Director: Richard Martin &QL; 
Stars: Kevin Zegers, Gregory Harrison, Cynthia Stevenson &QL; 
Rated: G &QL; 
Length: 91 min. &QL; 
Rating: 2 stars &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
