r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PARENTS-AZR &LR;      08-17 1071
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARENTS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUT-OF-TOWN KIDS HAMPERED IN HELPING AGING PARENTS  
 (RESENDING FOR THE NEWS &AMP; ADVANCE) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MAUREEN WEST  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - ``You can do everything possible by long distance, but
there's still that knowledge that you can't go over there in the
middle of the night.''
</P>
<P>
   That is 42-year-old Bonnie Hughes Marcus, expressing the anxiety
she feels about living in Ohio and trying to be a good,
long-distance daughter to her 81- and 82-year-old parents, Felice
and Warren Hughes, who live in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``I epitomize the sandwich generation, raising three kids
between 8 and 17 and, more and more, assuming a caregiving role for
my parents,'' said Bonnie who lives in Shaker Heights, a suburb of
Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   She believes that their family has a strong foundation of love,
but it's still hard for her to know if she's giving too much or too
little, she explained.
</P>
<P>
   ``In your 40s and 50s, you're faced with some pretty grueling
family issues. It can be overwhelming unless you figure a way to
find your balance,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bonnie is hardly alone in her situation, according to David
Helgeson, a psychologist who helps families with elder-care issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm seeing many more middle-age adults these days who want to
know how to deal more effectively with their parents,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also gets an earful of complaints from older patients about
their middle-aged children, who either don't call enough, or who
wrongly (say the seniors) think their parents are going senile.
</P>
<P>
   Helgeson sees denial on both ends: Many older people don't want
to admit the loss of their capabilities, and their kids refuse to
see their parents as aging because it reminds them of how old they
are getting, or because they don't think they have the time or
money to help them. They will chat about the weather rather than
about what's obvious and important.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, a serious or even life-threatening event has to occur
with a parent before everyone will face the situation. Solving the
problem is difficult under any circumstances, but it's compounded
when the parents live far away.
</P>
<P>
   Bonnie and her brothers kept out of their parents' financial and
legal affairs until five years ago, when Warren Hughes had a
life-threatening aneurysm and high-risk surgery. Bonnie frankly
discussed finances and health care options with her father. She
knew he had prepared a will, but she didn't know where it was
located or who he had named as an executor. They wrote a living
will and a medical power of attorney, just in case anything went
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Just as the family was relieved that he came through surgery
beautifully and that family financial affairs remained in order,
Warren's wife, Felice, was diagnosed with Alzheimer's.
</P>
<P>
   Warren tried to handle the care of his wife on his own. But as
the disease advanced, he hired someone to help three days a week,
then five, then seven. But even then it became too much for him.
</P>
<P>
   The Hughes children didn't know their father was having so much
difficulty until a year and a half ago, when Warren had to be
hospitalized for stress for five days.
</P>
<P>
   After that, even Warren couldn't deny that caring for her had
become too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dad was great,'' Bonnie said. ``He called us all home and we
had a meeting in a conference room he had arranged at his church.
He wanted us to meet in a place where we could try to make an
unemotional decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The family agreed it was time to put Felice into a nursing home.
They surveyed 15 homes, finally picking one close to her doctors.
</P>
<P>
   On most Saturdays and Sundays, Warren and his dog, Bordeaux,
visit Felice.
</P>
<P>
   ``She recognizes the poodle and me,'' said Warren.
</P>
<P>
   Four days each week, Warren volunteers as a counselor to
families going through similar experiences. He takes that work as
seriously as he ever did his career as an FBI agent.
</P>
<P>
   He tells other families that it is important that at least one
person besides the spouse should be there to help make decisions
and communicate with the family. Among his children, Bonnie is that
person. She helps him make decisions and she watches over his own
needs.
</P>
<P>
   Because she couldn't be in town to help her father manage her
mother's care, Bonnie hired a geriatric care manager to make
professional visits. The monthly report usually includes a note
about ``Mr. Hughes.''
</P>
<P>
   If the geriatric care manager sees a possible problem, she calls
the doctor directly or Warren.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted someone extra who would be objective. Whose
observations wouldn't be tied to emotion,'' said Bonnie. The
monitoring costs $65 a month, but she says it is worth it.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after her mother moved to the care facility, she and her
brothers strongly encouraged their father to move from the family's
3-bedroom ranch home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was our thinking that he would be better off in a smaller
place,'' said Bonnie.
</P>
<P>
   But Warren didn't agree and there were family arguments.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is all trial and error,'' she said. ``I have learned that I
have to be respectful of what he is going through as well. He was
going through a grieving period, too, and losing his house and
losing Mom to this disease in one big swoop was too much for him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As a daughter or son you may believe a change is for the best,
but they may not want that change,'' said Bonnie. ``If it isn't a
crisis situation, it should be their decision,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Psychologist Helgeson agreed, adding ``you can never really
become your parent's parent.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonnie gives this advice to other long-distance children: Stay
in touch and gather lots of information about options.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have learned to say, `Why don't you think about this?'
instead of telling him what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Next to her hometown telephone book sits Phoenix phone books,
used regularly to help her father find repair, landscaping or
cleaning services.
</P>
<P>
   She talks with doctors to check up on her parents' health and
she knows people in their church.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we try to get out and visit as regularly as we can,'' she
said. Almost every month, one of the Hugheses' children visits for
a few days or a week.
</P>
<P>
   They also encourage Warren to travel to them, but at his age
travel is becoming more difficult. And he doesn't like missing his
visits with Felice.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Maureen West can be reached at at maureen.west(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
