A7614 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAMAICA-VIAGRA-0818-C     08-17 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAMAICA-VIAGRA-0818-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    VIAGRA-FUELED RAPE CASE GOES BEFORE JUDGE IN JAMAICA
 &HT;    EDs: With optional trim at 550 words.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTEGO BAY, Jamaica _ An elderly businessman charged with
raping a young employee goes before a judge here Tuesday, and
prosecutors are expected to say that Viagra made him do it.
</P>
<P>
   At an initial hearing last month, prosecutors charged that Keith
Roberts, 70, who takes tourists on boat rides, sexually attacked
the 27-year-old woman after swallowing a dose of the wonder drug.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth McLeod, who will represent Roberts at Tuesday's
preliminary hearing, maintains that the whole thing is a set-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``My client is being framed,'' said McLeod, declined to discuss
specifics of the case. ``The woman wants his money.''
</P>
<P>
   The case -- while certainly alarming to many Jamaicans -- hasn't
stirred as much surprise on this tropical island as one might
expect.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of Viagra are not yet legal in Jamaica, yet pharmacists
say they've been bombarded by Viagra-related questions from men --
some desperate, some merely curious. Black markets for Viagra have
sprung up throughout the Caribbean, with the light blue
diamond-shaped pill, manufactured by Pfizer Inc., selling like snow
cones in a desert.
</P>
<P>
   Because of its popularity, many governments in the region are
pushing the anti-impotency drug through the approval process.
</P>
<P>
   ``The interest is definitely here because many people are asking
for it,'' said Norma Inniss(CQ), president of the pharmacy board in
the twin-island nation of Trinidad and Tobago. ``We're hoping to
get approval soon because everyone's talking about it.''
</P>
<P>
   In mid-May, Trinidadian customs officials raided several
pharmacies and confiscated hundreds of Viagra pills being sold for
as much as $20 each.
</P>
<P>
   Introduced in the United States last April, Viagra has become a
global phenomenon in just over four months. Prescription sales
indicate that as many as 3 million American men may have already
popped one of the so-called wonder pills, while Pfizer officials
expect worldwide approval of the drug by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The drug has, in particular, aroused a lot of interest in the
Caribbean and in Latin America, where male virility is a highly
valued attribute.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect the drug to do quite well in the Caribbean and Latin
America,'' said Pam Gemmel, a spokeswoman for Pfizer.
</P>
<P>
   Pfizer officials say Viagra doesn't cause men to act
aggressively and that it isn't an aphrodisiac, but that it
increases the flow of blood to the genitals.
</P>
<P>
   In South America, the sale of Viagra has been approved in
Argentina, Brazil, Colombia, Ecuador, and Venezuela. In late July,
Costa Rica became the first Central American country to approve
Viagra, which will be sold for about $11 a pill by prescription
only.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Optional trim begins here.)
</P>
<P>
   In Honduras, where sales are expected to be approved later this
month, Viagra is known as ``the love pill.'' The news media is full
of rave -- although usually unscientific -- reviews.
</P>
<P>
   In Mexico, where sales are permitted, humorists claim Viagra
means ``the old lady is grateful'' from the words ``vieja'' and
``agradecida,'' which mean ``old'' and ``thankful'' in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   The drug's hype has become so frenzied that the mayor of one
southern Brazilian town recently announced that he would hand
Viagra out free to townspeople in order to jumpstart a sagging
population and, thus, boost the amount of federal aid his town
receives.
</P>
<P>
   Elcio Berti, the mayor of Bocaiuva do Sul, said his town's
population dropped from 12,000 to 8,750 after it was divided into
two municipalities in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Berti, who only last year tried to ban condoms, said he will
spend $35,000 of his own money on Viagra.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Optional trim ends here.)
</P>
<P>
   Inniss said that the positive publicity surrounding Viagra has
increased the market for traditional, but cheaper, alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   Within Latin and Caribbean societies, where an emphasis is
placed on ``machismo,'' it's never been unusual to see men flocked
around dirty, roadside stands where raw oysters are sold despite
the threat of cholera.
</P>
<P>
   But besides shellfish, Inniss said men now are also in hot
pursuit of the ginseng root, the bark of the bois bande tree, and
anything else that's said to have sexual curative powers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see more interest in local products right now,'' she said.
``I think that Viagra just started the ball rolling.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
