<HEADER>
A7625 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-LOS-ANGELES-HNS &LR;      08-17 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LOS-ANGELES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOID IN L.A. LURES WALSH, DAVIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RAY RATTO  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Former San Francisco 49ers coach Bill Walsh is still intrigued
by the gaping maw of the Los Angeles market, celebrating its fourth
year of NFL-free living and showing no signs of moral, economic or
vitamin deficiency.
</P>
<P>
   He still sees the possibilities of unlimited wealth for the
lucky swine who gets in first with a team, a building and a plan to
un-jade the most encrusted sports fans in America.
</P>
<P>
   So, as we all know, is Al Davis, who is renting the Oakland
property while keeping his own covetous eye on L.A. for the same
reason.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles has money. Los Angeles IS money. Going broke with
the only NFL team in a population of 13 million takes the kind of
creativity one usually associates with tax cheats, narcotics
informers and other domesticated animals.
</P>
<P>
   So why, then, isn't there a team in Los Angeles? Why isn't there
a team being formed to go into Los Angeles? Why, most specifically,
aren't the Oakland Raiders already there waving tire irons wrapped
in injunctions at anyone casting a covetous eye toward their little
ranch in extremis?
</P>
<P>
   Give it time. As it becomes more and more evident the Raiders
are only visiting and not really planning to stay, all of these
things might happen, testing Walsh's grandiose theories, Davis'
rapacious instincts and commissioner Paul Tagliabue's legal skills.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, there's going to be blood on the moon, and we're
going to ruin a few good dress shirts getting too close to the
carnage.
</P>
<P>
   You see, the economic logic that sent Davis to Los Angeles back
in 1981 (``L.A. plus me equals zillions'') still applies, and the
absence of a second team in L.A. makes it an even more appealing
prospect. Knowing he can beat the NFL in court pretty much whenever
he wants to makes it even more exciting to him, and few things get
Al's blood a-bubble quite like sticking his index finger up to the
third knuckle in the NFL's legal eye.
</P>
<P>
   This is why Davis' complaints about the mistreatment and
treachery accorded him by Oakland officials, convicted as they are
of throwing great wads of money at him to bring him back, ring so
hollow. Not because he doesn't feel wronged, mind you, but because
legal trouble with the locals works just as well for him as peace.
</P>
<P>
   We all know what our local pols did to screw up the Raiders'
return, starting with giving Al the bulk of the money up front.
They deserve all the grief they get, for both their arrogance and
their stupidity.
</P>
<P>
   But Al hasn't done much to alter the status quo that wounds him
so. For one, he keeps pinning the seat license and attendance woes
on the pols and marketers who promised him full houses into the
Thursday before eternity. And yet, he does none of the obvious
things a businessman concerned with the bottom line would do _ say,
usurping control and running the joint the way he wants it run. In
this case, taking back control of his tickets and marketing.
</P>
<P>
   And no, let's not hear about how he can't. Al takes what he
wants, no matter how long it takes to get it. He beat the
unbeatable Pete Rozelle _ you think a couple of puddings from the
Oakland flats with a piece of paper bother him?
</P>
<P>
   Plainly, he doesn't want control of his tickets and marketing.
Either that, or he already does have control and has no intention
of changing a single decimal point.
</P>
<P>
   L.A. is still sitting there, and Al keeps asserting his rights
to the market as though he were still there.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, he looks like more of a threat to return if things are
going badly in Oakland than if they go well. He might have a harder
time convincing a judge of the merits of his L.A. claim if he is
minting money in Oakland. He would certainly have a harder time
convincing you or me.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving now, though, creates some annoying legal problems in
Oakland, and it puts him back in the rotting hulk that is the L.A.
Coliseum, which he fled four years ago holding his nose. Going back
now isn't progress but another spin on the hamster wheel, and Davis
has never been one to stand still. He marches ahead, he falls
behind, but he never just stands there. Not when it comes to
location, relocation or de-location.
</P>
<P>
   When the time comes, and the L.A. situation heats up, you will
see how much Davis wants to stay in Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   As for Walsh, who knows? He is 67, and by the time Los Angeles
becomes viable, he could be 77, or at its present rate of progress,
107. Right now all he can do is admire that team-less burg from
afar and wonder over a tall, cool, properly aged something or other
what it would be like to be in charge one last time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
