<HEADLINE>
(HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDITORS:
</P>
<P>
   New York Times editors are CONSIDERING these stories for
Saturday's Page 1:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLINTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Editors,  &UR; The New York Times &LR;  is planning as many as six pages
of coverage of the president's grand jury testimony and its
aftermath. These are are among the stories now planned:
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-RDP (Washington) _ Ledeall: President Clinton testifies
from the White House to the Kenneth Starr grand jury. By James
Bennet.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-ASSESS (Washington) _ Analyzing the president's gamble
in testifying. Is his strategy likely to work? By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-PSYCHE (Washington) _ Todd S. Purdum examines the
elements of President Clinton's character and personality that have
led him to this pivotal day in his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ECON (Moscow) _ After weeks of financial turmoil, Russia
sharply devalued the ruble today and put a 90-day moratorium on
foreign debt, a move expected to cause hardship for Russian
consumers. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-BOMB (Washington) _ Developments on the suspect in the
embassy attack being detained in Kenya. By David Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-BOMB (Omagh) _ Police arrest suspects in Saturday's
bombing. Reports say one of the arrested is a major figure in the
Real IRA. By James F. Clarity.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (``a'' coded)
</P>
<P>
   NJ-HARASS-SUIT (Undated) _ In a closely watched sexual
harassment case, a former N.J. state deputy attorney general was
found guilty yesterday of harassing a former employee. In its
ruling, a jury in Mercer County awarded a female lawyer who once
worked for Richard Carley, a former deputy director of the state's
Criminal Justice Divion, $300,000 in back wages, plus $50,000 for
emotional distress and pain and suffering. A hearing was set for
mid-September to determine how much Carley will have to pay in
punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Investors weigh the impact of the Russian
devaluation, the Clinton testimony and another decline on the Tokyo
market. The Dow industrial average closed up 149 points. In Asia,
Tokyo shares fell 2.2 percent. Prices were down 0.8 percent in
Frankfurt and up 0.3 percent in London. By Sharon R. King.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS &LR;  (``s'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BBO-HOMER-MATCHUP (Chicago) _ Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa go
head to head in Wrigley Field in a two-game series that begins
Tuesday night. It's a matchup between two men chasing Roger Maris
and two teams that already have a great geographic rivalry. By Ira
Berkow.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ALASKA-THAW (Undated) _ Alaska is thawing, and much of
northern Russia and Canada with it, and many scientists say that
the warming of these cold regions is one of the most telling
signals so far that the planet's climate is changing. Experts have
long said that in an era of global warming, this bellwether region
should warm up more and faster than the Earth as a whole, and so
far that is just how things are turning out. The signs are
everywhere. By William K. Stevens.
</P>
