<HEADER>
A7708 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-COMPUTER-COLUMN-N     08-17 1105
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT COMBINES TV, COMPUTER AND THE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ROB FIXMER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For all the recent media noise about the paucity of new features
in Windows 98, surprisingly little has been written about WebTV for
Windows, an intriguing addition to the operating system that
foreshadows both the promise and the growing pains of mixing
television with the personal computer.
</P>
<P>
   In its most basic form _ running on a standard PC connected to
the Internet _ WebTV for Windows acts as a sort of electronic TV
Guide that automatically gathers programming information for the
user's local broadcast area, cable system or satellite television
service.
</P>
<P>
   This information, plus brief descriptions of each program, is
delivered over the Internet and presented in a grid covering about
72 hours of programming _ generally, the current, previous and
following days.
</P>
<P>
   The guide is searchable by word or phrase, enabling the user to
hunt for a special program, character, actor, etc., without having
to read the entire guide, which can run to more than 100 channels
on some cable and satellite services.
</P>
<P>
   The object of the search does not have to be in the program's
title. Entering ``Mary Tyler Moore'' on Thursday, for example,
brought up two time slots for ``The Dick Van Dyke Show'' on
Nickelodeon and ``Ordinary People'' on the Movie Channel.
</P>
<P>
   In this basic configuration, WebTV for Windows is sort of useful
but no more so than TV Guide's TVGEN Web-based service or Gist, the
Web-only television guide.
</P>
<P>
   But WebTV for Windows gets a lot more interesting on a computer
with both an Internet connection and a TV tuner card, which allows
viewers to watch broadcast, cable or satellite programming on the
computer screen. In this configuration, the lines separating
television, computer and Internet begin to dissolve.
</P>
<P>
   The electronic program guide melds with channel selection, a
preview window and the interactive television/Web technology that
was created for the original WebTV system.
</P>
<P>
   The inclusion of this last feature is a rich irony, since the
original WebTV was designed by a small company of the same name as
a sort of antidote to the computer. By offering people e-mail, Web
access and other Internet features through their television sets,
the company hoped to attract customers who did not own _ or did not
want to bother with _ a computer.
</P>
<P>
   WebTV was arguably the first of an entire category of devices
known as ``Internet appliances'' that were intended as alternative
gates to cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   When Microsoft acquired the WebTV company last year for $425
million, many industry analysts saw it as a defensive move, since
people who did not want or need computers obviously did not need
Microsoft. But increasingly, the acquisition is looking like an
astute offensive move as the company builds a platform for
interactive digital television on the WebTV foundation.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Microsoft sealed a deal to provide key elements of
WebTV technology to Tele-Communications Inc., the cable giant
acquired last month by AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   Like all the major cable players, TCI is eager to sell customers
more products, many requiring a new generation of set-top boxes
that can meld cable television and Internet access into a seamless,
interactive information and entertainment system.
</P>
<P>
   In June, with the release of WebTV for Windows as part of
Windows 98, Microsoft demonstrated an eagerness not only to play in
the digital television market but to formulate the rules. This is
nothing new; Microsoft has tried to dictate the rules in every
industry it enters.
</P>
<P>
   But it does not always get its way. Among its major losses came
after an aggressive attempt in the last 18 months to dictate
standards that would have made digital television sets compatible
with computer monitors at the expense of high definition.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, it is the only company right now offering a product
that not only melds the Internet and television but offers a
rudimentary form of that long-promised but elusive Holy Grail of
the cable industry, interactive television.
</P>
<P>
   And it is not a bad attempt at that. No, WebTV for Windows will
not provide video on demand, but if a cable provider carries the
interactive portions of programming that has been enhanced for
WebTV _ not all do _ consumers can click their way through some
extra interactive features of a particular show.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a viewer could call up a pitcher's earned run
average while watching a game, open a chat window to compare notes
with other investors during a financial report or download recipes
while watching a program about cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Guggenheimer, who oversees development of WebTV for
Windows as Microsoft's group product manager for digital
television, said last week that he was not surprised by _ or
worried about _ consumer confusion about WebTV, which he called
``the first integration of television and Internet
infrastructure.''
</P>
<P>
   The technology will continue to advance, he said, and will
eventually be added to Windows CE, for hand-held devices, and
Windows NT, the industrial strength version of the operating
system.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think that Microsoft is trying to force everyone to
watch television on their PCs,'' Guggenheimer said. ``That's not
true. We're working to integrate two information platforms. The PC
is an information appliance, and television is another form of
information. There are many ways they can be used separately or in
combination.''
</P>
<P>
   The goal, he said, is to develop an information machine that
offers enough flexibility so that each user can take from it what
he or she needs, whether it is Guggenheimer's watching a Sonics
game in the corner of his screen on nights he works late or
students in a classroom using interactive educational television
with the Internet for enriched instruction.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, that enthusiastic vision is shared by the
companies that manufacture TV tuner cards for personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   A representative of ATI Research, the Toronto-based market
leader in both graphics and TV cards, said the company had seen ``a
very large increase in demand and sales'' in the few weeks since
the release of Windows 98.
</P>
<P>
   And while it is too early to know for certain how much of that
can be attributed to WebTV for Windows, he says he is certain that
consumers will eventually share his enthusiasm as they begin
simultaneously surfing channels and the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``First Microsoft added a Web browser to Windows,'' he said last
week. ``Now they've added a cable browser and, really, a lot
more.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-98 1637EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
