<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
 (jt)  
 By C.CLAIBORNE RAY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Seeing Stars &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Why can't you see the stars in photos or videos taken by
astronauts?
</P>
<P>
   A. Such pictures do not ordinarily show stars because the stars
are not bright enough in comparison with the nearby Sun and the
things it shines on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Virtually all of the astronaut photos are of objects that are
brightly illuminated by the Sun,'' explained Scott Kardel of the
Lake Afton Public Observatory in Wichita, Kan., ``so to capture
them on film without overexposing the image, you need a relatively
short exposure. These short exposures do not provide enough time
for the film to capture images of stars.''
</P>
<P>
   Some photos taken in darkness do show stars, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stars are visible from space as long as there is no other
strong source of light in the picture,'' said Dr. Douglas
Blanchard, chief of the Earth Science and Solar System Exploration
Division at Johnson Space Center in Houston Texas ``Cameras and
video cameras adjust to the strongest light source in their field
of view. If the Sun is in view, no stars will be seen, just as we
do not see stars in the daytime although we know they are there.''
</P>
<P>
   Usually astronauts' cameras are trained on parts of the
spacecraft or something else in the field of view, he continued,
and those objects reflect more light than the stars, so the stars
do not appear in the captured images.
</P>
<P>
   Readers are invited to submit questions about science to
Questions, Science Times, The New York Times, 229 West 43d St., New
York, N.Y. 10036. Questions of general interest will be answered in
this column, but requests for medical advice cannot be honored and
unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
