<SLUG> BC-SCI-DARK-MATTER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHEDDING NEW LIGHT ON THE MILKY WAY'S HALO OF DARKNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By JOHN NOBLE WILFORD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   American and Australian astronomers have found more evidence of
dark objects apparently scattered throughout the fringes of the
Milky Way, and they say this could solve the mystery of the dark
matter that is unseen and accounts for most of the mass in Earth's
galaxy.
</P>
<P>
   Or they may actually be observing dim stars in nearby galaxies,
and not any of the elusive dark matter. At least that is what some
skeptics suspect on the strength of other recent observations. As a
result, some astronomers think they may be just as much in the dark
about galactic dark matter now as before the concerted search began
early in the decade.
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Charles Alcock, an astrophysicist at the Lawrence
Livermore National Laboratory in California who directs the
research, said in an interview last week that observations of more
than 15 dark objects strengthen the argument that a halo of such
matter does surround the visible disk of the Milky Way and could
represent 50 percent of the galaxy's mass.
</P>
<P>
   The objects, detected at the Mount Stromlo Observatory in
Australia, appear to be composed of ordinary matter in chunks of
about half the mass of the Sun.
</P>
<P>
   Astronomers have long been puzzled by calculations of the
dynamics of the stars in the Milky Way and in other galaxies, which
suggest that the Milky Way contains as much as 10 times more mass
than can be accounted for by its visible stars.
</P>
<P>
   In early 1996, Alcock's team of American and Australian
dark-matter hunters first linked such machos, which stands for
massive compact halo objects, to this mysterious missing galactic
mass. At the time, they had recorded only six detections using an
indirect observational technique called gravitational lensing.
</P>
<P>
   When an otherwise unobserved macho passes in front of a
background star, the macho's gravitational field acts like a lens,
magnifying the star's light. The star's sudden brightening signals
the presence of a macho.
</P>
<P>
   Alcock will describe the 15 new gravitational-lensing detections
Tuesday at an international astronomy conference in Canberra,
Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now have two and a half times as much data, and so the
results are much more secure than when first reported,'' Alcock
said.
</P>
<P>
   Astrophysicists can only speculate on the identity and nature of
these halo objects. They could be dim collapsed stars called white
dwarfs, remnants of the galaxy's earliest stellar populations
billions of years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But if they are white dwarfs, they should have left detectable
traces of carbon in the diffuse gas of surrounding space, and
nothing like that has been observed.
</P>
<P>
   Another possibility is that the machos are primordial black
holes, extremely dense objects that might have formed about 10
microseconds after the origin of the universe in the theorized Big
Bang. But the existence of primordial black holes has yet to be
established.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Ken Freeman of the Mount Stromlo Observatory cautioned that
the macho detections might help solve the dark matter problem for
the Milky Way, but not for the universe. Astrophysicists estimate
that at least 90 percent of the mass of any galaxy takes the form
of a dark halo, which provides the gravity that holds the galaxy
together.
</P>
<P>
   The mystery has centered on whether the halo matter consists of
star-size lumps or exotic elementary particles. The current
findings have no bearing on the dark matter in the vast spaces
between galaxies, also presumably a major component of cosmic mass.
</P>
<P>
   Commenting on the new macho findings, Dr. John N. Bahcall, an
astrophysicist at the Institute for Advanced Study in Princeton,
N.J., said that serious questions have been raised over whether the
detected objects are in the Milky Way halo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever they have found is important,'' he said of the
American-Australian team. ``But they may have found answers to
different questions than they asked.''
</P>
<P>
   In June, for example, the astronomers alerted colleagues at
other observatories to an unusual brightening of one of the stars
in the Small Magellanic Cloud, a nearby dwarf galaxy. The
background stars that the machos magnify are in that galaxy or the
Large Magellanic Cloud.
</P>
<P>
   Focusing on the event, telescopes in Australia, Chile and South
Africa made a puzzling finding: The brightening event lasted many
hours or days, much longer than is consistent with the lensing
macho being in the halo of the Milky Way.
</P>
<P>
   In its July 17 issue, the journal Science reported several
observations indicating that the brightening had to be the lensing
effect of a slow-moving object passing close to the background
star. Several of the events thus had nothing to do with mass in the
Milky Way halo.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Andrew Gould of Ohio State University in Columbus was quoted
as saying that the long duration of the lensing event implies with
99.5 percent to 99.9 percent certainty that the lens is in the
Small Magellanic Cloud, not the halo.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, Alcock conceded that ``substantial uncertainty
and controversy'' surrounded the macho findings and that it was
often not possible to determine exactly where an observed dark
object lies along the line of sight to the background star, whether
near or far or in the halo or well beyond.
</P>
<P>
   He said that the position of only two machos could be reliably
determined by current techniques, and they were both inside the
halo.
</P>
</TEXT>
