<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CRUISE-HEALTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN SHIP INSPECTION MISSES STOWAWAY GERMS  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By EDWIN McDOWELL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   After at least 270 passengers became ill on three successive
Regal Princess cruises from Vancouver, Canada, to Alaska this June,
the cruise industry was abuzz over a British newspaper report about
a plan for an international network to monitor health standards
aboard all cruise ships. But no such monitoring network seems
likely any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been talk about an international conference in the
next two or three years to deal with health and sanitation on
cruise ships,'' said Dave Forney, the senior health adviser with
the Vessel Sanitation Program of the Centers for Disease Control
and Prevention in Atlanta. ``But with the exception of the U.S. and
the Canadian inspection programs, you can't really point to much
more. And we're not sure why there isn't more international
interest, since we get lots of calls from U.S. citizens who worry
about getting sick on cruises.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A 1996 study of cruise ship safety and health, commissioned by
the Coast Guard, noted that the number of outbreaks of
gastrointestinal disease had declined from 8.1 per 10 million
passenger days in 1975 to about 2.1 in 1996. But Forney said it has
probably risen slightly since 1996, because of the growing numbers
of cruises and cruise passengers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One reason there is no special urgency to embrace an
international monitoring system, aside from the cost, is that the
overwhelming majority of the more than five million cruise
passengers worldwide last year were North Americans. For tax
purposes most cruise ships are registered in Panama, Liberia and
the Bahamas, but, according to Forney, many have probably never
been to their countries of registry. In addition, United States
health and sanitation regulations apply to almost every ship that
pulls into an American port. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Established in 1975 under the authority of the Public Health
Service after several major disease outbreaks on cruise vessels,
the Vessel Sanitation Program keeps watch over every vessel with a
foreign itinerary arriving in United States ports with more than 13
passengers. Each such ship is given unannounced inspections at
least twice a year, and if it fails either one, the ship must
undergo another within 60 days.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Inspections, are paid for by the cruise lines. Results are
available from travel agents and are posted on the Internet at
www.cdc.gov under the Travelers' Health menu.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Each inspection checklist consists of 42 items, from water to
hand-washing facilities to food protection, and a passing score is
at least 86 points out of a possible 100. Five points are
subtracted for lapses in hygiene by food workers, for water and for
equipment that does not properly monitor the water.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian program, according to a spokesman in the Canadian
Embassy in Washington, amounts to one unannounced inspection a year
on ships traveling Canadian waters during the cruise season from
April through October.
</P>
<P>
   But after so many passengers became ill on the Regal Princess
cruises from Vancouver to Alaska this summer, Canadian authorities
inspected the ship after the first two cruises. During the outbreak
on the third cruise, Forney and Dr. David Kim, a medical
epidemiologist with the Vessel Sanitation Program, also boarded the
1,600-passenger Regal Princess in Juneau.
</P>
<P>
   The CDC coordinates with state, local and foreign health
departments when deemed necessary, as it did in the summer of 1994
when pneumonia and Legionnaires' disease were detected among
passengers who sailed the Celebrity Horizon from New York to
Bermuda.
</P>
<P>
   ``Intervention measures were taken both during and in between
each of the Regal Princess cruises,'' Forney said, ``and when those
measures were not successful, the company made the decision that
the best way to take care of the problem was to do the systematic
cleaning, disinfecting and sanitizing that can only be done without
passengers aboard ship. That's why they took it out of service.''
</P>
<P>
   Cruise lines usually hasten to cooperate with inspectors, not
least because failure to get a clean bill of health can quickly
cost $1 million in lost revenue. The Regal Princess was out of
service for a week.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The culprit in the Regal Princess outbreak was the Norwalk
virus, a fairly common cause of gastrointestinal-disease outbreaks
at sea or on shore, usually characterized by nausea, vomiting,
diarrhea and abdominal pain lasting 24 to 48 hours. However, the
source of the Norwalk virus aboard the Regal Princess is still not
known,  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the cause of the illnesses, the subsequent
stem-to-stern disinfecting of the Regal Princess, which scored a 92
in its inspection last January, appears to have done the trick. The
ship continues to sail its normal itinerary, and in its latest
inspection, on July 8, it scored a 95.
</P>
<P>
   But even the most detailed inspection is often powerless to
uncover or prevent illness aboard ship. Germs could lurk in
improper handling of food before it got aboard, or in the failure
of food handlers aboard ship to practice proper sanitation. There
is also no way to prevent passengers or crew who may be in the
early stages of an illness from boarding ships.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad wants to go to the Black Sea, and he asked me what ship
to go on,'' Forney said. ``I told him nobody could guarantee that
he won't come down with something, but that he should be sure to
pick a ship that's been inspected by the Public Health Service.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
