<HEADLINE>
ON MOUNT ST. HELENS, HISTORY IN MOTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM STIENSTRA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CASTLE ROCK, Wash. _ After climbing 4,500 feet through forest,
over and around boulders and finally across a steep snowfield, your
last steps take you to the rim of the Mount St. Helens volcano.
</P>
<P>
   The view is electrifying. The half-moon crater walls drop
straight down 2,100 feet to a lava plug dome, a mile across and
topped with crags, a wisp of steam emerging from its center. At its
edges, plumes of dust rising from continuous rockfalls trick you
into thinking a small eruption is in progress. The top 1,300 feet
of the old mountain _ once 9,677 feet high _ is gone, beheaded,
along with the entire north flank, which blew out. The summit now
peaks at 8,363 feet.
</P>
<P>
   The plug dome gives way to the blast zone, where the side of the
mountain, in a cataclysmic explosion, devastated 230 square miles.
It looks like a moonscape except for Spirit Lake on the north edge
where thousands of trees still float, logjammed by the volcanic
eruption on May 18, 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond are 14,411-foot Mount Rainier to the north, 12,276-foot
Mount Adams to the east, and 11,235-foot Mount Hood to the south,
all rising like pristine diamonds in contrast to the hulking ruin
in the foreground.
</P>
<P>
   As you take all this in, you swear you feel a tremor _ the Earth
shifting, perhaps like the movement that foretold the shocking
event 18 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Could it happen again? Here? At another mountain?
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many chapters still to be written in the story of
Mount St. Helens,'' said Ed Klimasauskas, of the U.S. Geological
Survey. But, he said, there will be ``adequate warning of any
explosive event.''
</P>
<P>
   The Earth is talking again, and a lot of people are listening _
and watching.
</P>
<P>
   The frequency of earthquakes at Mount St. Helens increased from
60 per month last winter to 165 in May, 318 in June and more than
450 in July. The USGS released a statement that concluded the
volcano was ``replenishing the magma reservoir'' for some kind of
outburst in the future, most likely a ``steam explosion.'' Because
the hundreds of recent quakes have been deep in the Earth below the
volcano and relatively minor (rather than shallow and major), the
USGS believes another catastrophic eruption is not imminent here.
</P>
<P>
   There has also been seismic activity at Mount Rainier near
Seattle, which some believe will be the next big one to blow. The
epicenters of its earthquakes are directly below the centerline of
its summit, an old lava pinnacle.
</P>
<P>
   And in California, repeated earthquakes near Mammoth Mountain in
the eastern Sierra include a 5.1-magnitude quake in mid-July and
several aftershocks measuring 3.0 to 4.1. There also has been
significant venting of carbon dioxide, enough to kill several
groves of trees there. A team of USGS scientists said this venting
indicates a ``larger, deeper magma source and/or major reservoir of
high-pressure gas (that) is being tapped.''
</P>
<P>
   But such hints of danger do not seem to deter the curious. Mount
St. Helens _ 57 people died when it erupted _ has become one of the
most popular tourist destinations in America. It has attracted 3
million to 4 million visitors five years running, nearly equal to
the record numbers visiting Yosemite National Park.
</P>
<P>
   It is also the most climbed volcano in North America, with
13,000 people hiking to the rim each year, second in the world only
to Mount Fuji in Japan. Mount St. Helens holds its distinction
despite a quota of 100 hikers per day _ 60 of whom reserve permits
and another 40 who win a daily lottery. All must pay a $15 fee.
</P>
<P>
   It is a demanding climb for most, 11 miles round-trip, with a
rise of 4,500 feet to the rim. The last three miles are half-hike,
half-scramble along Monitor Ridge amid pumice boulders and
snowfields.
</P>
<P>
   At dusk, the mountain is a ghostly site. In ancient times, the
Cowlitz Indians believed it to be a sacrilege to stand on its
summit. They named the mountain ``Las-We-Lat-Klah,'' which evolved
in the 1800s to ``Loowit,'' which translates as ``Person From Whom
Smoke Comes.'' Somehow that has been corrupted into ``Fire
Mountain'' at the visitor centers.
</P>
<P>
   The name ``Mount St. Helens'' came from explorer George
Vancouver, who named it in 1792 in recognition of his friend
Alleyne Fitzherbert, the Baron of St. Helens in England.
</P>
<P>
   My hiking partner, Michael Furniss, and I began our trek after a
quick camp breakfast with an easy walk through the woods. Ptarmigan
Trail climbs gently, shaded and cool through old-growth forest,
then rises more steeply near the tree line. At 2.5 miles you emerge
from the forest to face Monitor Ridge, a 3-mile succession of
pumice boulders of all sizes cast by the volcano atop a ridge line.
A faint trail has been worn by previous hikers, and where it
disappears in the rubble, the Forest Service has placed poles to
mark the route.
</P>
<P>
   It follows and climbs the ridge, a gain of about 1,000 feet per
mile. It's steep, dry, often hot and the menace of cracking a shin
or knee against a boulder is constant.
</P>
<P>
   Above the tree line, other climbers came into view along the
ridge. They were all ages and, as it turned out, from all parts of
America. Ten straight were from different states.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be here with my son, to make this climb _ there are a lot
of lifetime feelings for me,'' said Fred Sibeanman, 70, of Moline,
Ill. ``This is not something you suddenly decide to do, and what
I'm feeling here won't suddenly leave me.''
</P>
<P>
   (MORE ... MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
