<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-17 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7737 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-2NDTA     08-17 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-2NDTAKE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 CASTLE ROCK, Wash: x x x leave me.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   He smiled and trudged on. Everybody seemed bonded by the
adventure.
</P>
<P>
   Most people require about four or five hours to reach the
summit, grinding out the last mile. Finally, it's a few last steps
and to the north Mount Rainier comes into view.
</P>
<P>
   You scan miles of landscape, from the plug dome out the blast
zone, across the mud flow and pumice to Spirit Lake and beyond to
the scorch zone and the ravaged Toutle River Valley, a view like no
other. Sitting on the crater rim, scanning the panorama, I swore I
felt an earthquake. Later in the week, checking seismograph
records, it turned out I had.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Few would have wanted to be in that spot on a soft spring
morning 18 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of small earthquakes had rumbled ominously for months
before a 5.1-magnitude quake jolted Mount St. Helens at 8:32 a.m.
on May 18. The bulging north flank of the mountain collapsed,
creating a gargantuan landslide. Part of it swept through Spirit
Lake, pushing up a wall of water 600 to 800 feet high _ an estimate
based on the wash line, since nobody who saw it survived. The
largest portion of the slide rampaged 15 miles down through the
Toutle River Valley.
</P>
<P>
   A blast exploded out of the side of the mountain, venting
700-degree gases mixed with pulverized rock and ash at an estimated
650 mph, leveling everything for 15 miles on the north flank of the
mountain. The devastation continued downstream through the Toutle
River Valley and another 100 miles south along the Columbia River.
A vertical column of billowing dark smoke and ash then rocketed 17
miles into the sky, blocking the sun and turning eastern
Washington's day into night.
</P>
<P>
   Four hours later, magma rose into the crater and hardened,
forming superheated rocks called pumice, which then were ejected
out the side of the mountain. The heat from the volcano melted 70
percent of the snow and ice that had covered the peak, creating a
steaming, flooding ooze of mud down the Toutle River that crushed
everything in its path, closed Interstate 5 between Seattle and
Portland, and soon blocked traffic in the shipping channel of the
Columbia River.
</P>
<P>
   According to historian Christine Colasurdo, the eruption
destroyed or damaged 27 bridges, 200 homes, 185 miles of roads and
stranded 31 ships. Spirit Lake was filled with 150 feet of mud,
burying everything and creating a new lake atop the flow, 40
percent of it covered by 35,000 trees. An entire forest was
despoiled, the trees toppled and scattered like tiny Lincoln Logs.
</P>
<P>
   In all, enough ash fell to bury a football field 150 miles deep.
Two weeks later, ash from the eruption had circled the planet and
fell near its source in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   At least 170 people were taken to safety, but 57 died or
vanished. The most famous was Harry Truman, 83, who for 50 years
operated St. Helens Lodge on the south shore of Spirit Lake. In an
eerie recording, complete with piano music and glasses clinking in
the background, Truman explained why he refused to leave despite
being warned of the danger.
</P>
<P>
   ``That mountain is a part of me, and I'm a part of it,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He is now buried 300 feet down, under 200 feet of mountain,
deposits and mud flows, with the new lake on top of that.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michael Furniss and I sat for four hours on the crater rim
talking about the eruption, absorbing the view and watching the
reaction of hikers as they ascended the final steps and took in the
panorama.
</P>
<P>
   ``My face may be dirty and streaked, but the dirt is volcanic
ash from Mount St. Helens and the streaks are because I was crying
when I made the rim,'' said Nicole Sultana of Northville, Mich.
``It is all so unbelievable. I felt so much emotion, and it found a
way out in my tears.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing; this is one of the special places in this
country,'' said Carol Dailey of Lincoln, R.I., who climbed up with
her husband, Joe. ``Film can not do it justice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
