<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHEAP COMPUTERS ARE GOOD DEALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID HOYE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED -So you stroll through the doors at the local Kmart,
walk down the main aisle and hang a left to reach the electronics
department.
</P>
<P>
   There, stuck between the boomboxes and color TVs is your goal: A
row of computers in designer colors.
</P>
<P>
   You spend 10 minutes comparing the features, choose the
middle-priced model and reach below the display to grab the boxed
version of the machine you want.
</P>
<P>
   On your way to the checkout line, you pat your pocket to make
sure you brought those four $20 bills to pay for your new toy.
</P>
<P>
   Once you get home, you unbox the computer, plug it in and use
it, as though it was nothing more significant than a new telephone.
</P>
<P>
   It's a dream, I know. But we sure seem to be headed in that
direction!
</P>
<P>
   I base this claim on many things, including the computer ads I
run across every day in the newspaper, in magazines and online, and
a spiffy new iMac computer that Apple sent us last week to review.
</P>
<P>
   If you hunt through the ads a bit, and if you're not picky about
brand names or getting cutting-edge equipment, you can now find
yourself a basic Pentium-level computer for $400 and change _
including a monitor!
</P>
<P>
   Good grief, Hazel! It wasn't long ago that experts wondered
whether it was possible to produce a $1,000 computer. We've blown
through that roadblock, and show no signs of slowing.
</P>
<P>
   That's the kind of news that makes consumers jump for joy, but
leaves computer company executives with that sour, I-need-some-Tums
feeling in the pit of their stomach.
</P>
<P>
   It's no mystery why the Intels and Motorolas of the world are
going through rough times, laying off workers and floundering about
as they try to cope with the millions of people who have always
wanted, and are now demanding, low-cost computers.
</P>
<P>
   There remains a segment of the market that desires
top-of-the-line stuff. Corporate buyers and computer enthusiasts
will always line up to shell out several thousand bucks for Pentium
IIs, 21-inch, flat-panel displays, 16-gigabyte hard drives or
8-megabyte 3D video cards.
</P>
<P>
   But it looks like the great unwashed masses don't care for that
stuff. The software doesn't require such power, and certainly
neither does surfing the World Wide Web or trading e-mail. Keep
your Lexus, Mr. Grove. All I need is an '82 Chevy, thanks.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the masses might only be asking for an '82 Chevy, but
computer companies are giving them '98 models!
</P>
<P>
   The Sept. 1 issue of ``PC'' magazine includes the results of
tests conducted on 37 sub-$1,000 PCs. After looking at what
consumers could get for less than a grand, the magazine concluded
that seekers of low-end machines should expect Pentium II-266
chips, 4 gigabytes of hard drive space, 4 megabytes of video RAM,
32-speed CD-ROMs and much more.
</P>
<P>
   The days when ``cheap'' meant ``slow'' or ``outdated'' are gone.
</P>
<P>
   As for the iMac, we pulled the $1,299, all-in-one unit out of
its box, plugged it in and it worked! And that included a
connection to our in-house network. It was almost as easy as
installing a new telephone. (We'll be writing a review of the unit
soon. Watch for details on www.azcentral.com/computing).
</P>
<P>
   So where will it all end? Will my Kmart dream come true?
</P>
<P>
   I have no idea. But I'd like to think we will some day reach the
point where the machine is secondary to the content, where how we
use the machine is more important than the machine itself and where
the machines become so affordable, reliable and easy to use that
the equipment fades into the background and we can focus on
communicating, learning, working or just playing.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it is just a dream. &QL; 
 &QL; 
WHO USES THE INTERNET? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The September issue of ``Yahoo! Internet Life'' magazine has the
answers.
</P>
<P>
   One of the magazine's best issues is full of statistics about
how many people use the World Wide Web, average ages, average
incomes, levels of education and lots more. The mag even has a cool
history of the Net.
</P>
<P>
   This is the kind of information you'd typically have to pay a
research firm thousands of dollars to collect. And you would, too,
if you wanted to launch an online business and actually make money.
If you don't understand your customers, how can you serve them?
</P>
<P>
   Even if you're just an occasional surfer, you'll enjoy browsing
the issue. Here's a few tidbits:
</P>
<P>
   - 51.7 million people use the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   - 72 percent of American small businesses use e-mail to connect
with customers.
</P>
<P>
   - The average Net user is 37, up from the 1995 average age of
35.
</P>
<P>
   - 59 percent of Net users do their surfing at home.
</P>
<P>
   - 15 percent of Net users have published a personal Web page.
</P>
<P>
   Net-related statistics have always been a difficult thing to
come by, although that's never stopped anybody from trying. I
remember a time two years ago when the population of the Net was
estimated by one research firm at more than 40 million, while
another source doubted more than 10 million people were online. Go
figure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Internet Life'' did a good job providing the sources of all
its stats. But are they accurate? You'll have to be the judge. Some
sound like they're accurate. Others make you stop and wonder. I
mean, the average age of Web users is rising? If that's true, it
must be another baby boomer effect. (It would be interesting to see
if the average age of rock and roll fans is rising, too!) &QL; 
(at)j  &QL; 
IT BEATS A GARAGE SALE! &QL; 
(at)j  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you have stuff to sell or if you're looking for a particular
item to purchase, you should check out one of the latest Web sites
available: www.azauctions.com.
</P>
<P>
   Auction Universe has partnered with Arizona Central, Web site of
``The Arizona Republic,'' to offer people across the country an
easy way to conduct business over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Azauctions is essentially a virtual swap meet. Buyers and
sellers complete a free registration. Then, sellers can post items
for sale in any category, from antiques and Beanie Babies to
computers and recreational equipment. Buyers are free to browse the
thousands of items for sale. If they find one they want, they
simply make a bid on the item.
</P>
<P>
   If their bid is selected, Azauctions puts the buyer in contact
with the seller. They are then free to complete the deal directly.
Those who participate in such transactions can rate the people they
deal with so future users can be assured of honest and reliable
deals. &QL; 
 &QL; 
David Hoye is an online editor and covers computer- and
Internet-related issues for Arizona Central, the Web site of The
Arizona Republic. He can be reached at dhoye(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
