<HEADER>
A7751 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-CENSUS-AZR &LR;      08-17 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CENSUS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATISTICAL SAMPLING TO DETERMINE U.S. POPULATION A BAD IDEA  
 (THIS EDITORIAL APPEARED IN THE ARIZONA REPUBLIC ON MONDAY, AUG.
17) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Since 1790, census-takers have counted heads and
collected volumes of data on how we live. These census-takers don't
take a poll and, based on a sampling of 1,800 people, determine
that three people live in your house, four next door and 4.6
million in all of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   No, they count heads _ one by one, as the Constitution requires
in its reference to an ``actual enumeration'' of Americans every 10
years. In the same way, we hold elections instead of relying on a
sampling of voters to determine our elected officials.
</P>
<P>
   The traditional method of taking a census is being challenged by
President Clinton and most Democrats. They want to use statistical
sampling _ that is, polling _ in the 2000 census. It's a bad idea
that invites bias, fraud and all sorts of other problems.
</P>
<P>
   At stake in this controversy _ as is usually the case when
politics rears its head _ are money and power.
</P>
<P>
   Data collected from the 2000 census will be used to divvy up
nearly $200 billion a year in federal funds among cities and
states. The data also will determine which states pick up seats and
which lose them in the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Local governments and businesses depend on the census data being
honest and reliable. Cities use the information in their planning
for police and fire stations, among other facilities. Businesses
rely on it to target customers and help decide where to locate
everything from restaurants to medical centers.
</P>
<P>
   The debate boils down to this: Republicans believe census-takers
should count heads for reasons of accuracy, fairness and because
the Constitution requires it. Democrats, saying too many Americans
were missed in the 1990 census, particularly in larger cities,
propose using a statistical sampling method to supplement the
standard head count.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Democratic proposal, the census would count 90 percent
of the population. Then, a statistical sampling would be used to
make estimates of the other 10 percent _ or about 27 million
people, give or take a few million.
</P>
<P>
   All of which sparks the question:
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you know when you're at 90 percent if you don't know
what 100 percent is?'' asks U.S. Rep. John Shadegg, R-Ariz., who
serves on the newly-formed House subcommittee on census.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another problem is that sampling becomes less accurate as an
area gets smaller. For example, sampling a neighborhood block is
subject to great error _ plus or minus 28 percentage points,
according to one study. That has enormous implications because
redistricting starts from very small census blocks.
</P>
<P>
   For all their stated concerns about undercounting among
inner-city Blacks and rural Hispanics, Democrats don't propose
sampling to tally the most undercounted minority in the last
census: Native Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Their rationale is that counting heads is the most accurate
method on reservations _ which doesn't say much for the polling
argument. What's really going on, of course, is that there aren't
enough undercounted Native Americans to interest Democrats. For
Democrats, the next census is largely about finding those groups
traditionally viewed as Democratic voters.
</P>
<P>
   While the census isn't perfect, it can be made to work by
returning to the basics of knocking on doors to make sure everyone
is contacted and completes a survey in this $4 billion process.
Many of the 4 million who were missed in the last census were poor.
Half were estimated to be children. If all else fails, let's
explore reaching the undercounted when they come into contact with
the government for medical and other services.
</P>
<P>
   Polls, as any politician knows, can be inaccurate. They can be
biased, depending on how you decide to conduct them. They can also
be easily manipulated for political purposes. In 1990, the Census
Bureau suggested five formulas for adjusting numbers, and each
would have produced a different apportionment of House seats.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Democratic method of counting, there is even talk that
some surveys would be rejected if they didn't fit the statistical
scenario. That's wrong. Americans participating in the census have
every right to expect that their surveys will be counted _ and that
they count, too. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
