<HEADER>
A7772 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIFETIME-TV-SPI &LR;      08-17 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIFETIME-TV-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIFETIME OFFERS THREE SHOWS THAT ASSERT THE FEMININE SIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Research people at the Lifetime channel probably don't spend
much time down at the VFW waiting for some guy to say, ``Hey,
anybody see that `Intimate Portrait' piece on the Queen Mum last
night? Some kinda woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Cable TV is all about narrowcasting _ the opposite of what the
mainstream networks try to do _ and Lifetime's slogan is
``Television for Women,'' a not-too-subtle attempt to stake out a
testosterone-free viewing zone. Given a choice, however, and based
solely on pilot episodes, here's one guy who'd choose the Lifetime
alternatives over much of tonight's offerings on the Big Four.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's just the feminine side asserting itself here. Or
maybe it's the irresistibility of Annie Potts, Ann Cusack and
Joanna Gleason. If they were in the same show, I'd have season
tickets. Not that any of these original new series _ a milestone
for Lifetime, by the way _ is likely to be remembered as a TV
pioneer. They're not so much cutting edge as just slightly
different and, at bottom, the sort of programming that wouldn't
likely show up on the networks.
</P>
<P>
   There's some irony in that, because ``Any Day Now'' is a series
with noble aspirations and an interesting history. It was conceived
as a half-hour drama about an interracial friendship between two
girls growing up in Alabama in the early '60s. CBS planned to
introduce it in the summer of 1990, but an executive at the studio
developing the series balked, feeling the timing wasn't right. (He
was probably correct. A year later, NBC introduced ``I'll Fly
Away'' to critical applause and audience apathy.)
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Miller, co-creator of ``Any Day Now,'' evidently didn't
burn any bridges. She and Gary Randall, the studio exec who pulled
the plug on her eight years ago, are working together now as
executive producers of the new ``Any Day Now.'' But where the
original idea was to focus on two Birmingham girls in the
tumultuous '60s, this version centers on them as adults, with
frequent flashbacks to their youth.
</P>
<P>
   It's an effective conceit, though not particularly
groundbreaking. A steady reliance on the childhood scenes could be
little more than theatrical overstatement. In any event, we know
that the two women, Rene and Mary Elizabeth, now in their 40s,
haven't spoken to each other in more than two decades because of a
rift that drove them apart at 19. Rene, who always dreamed of
marriage and a family, is single, childless and a prominent
attorney in Washington, D.C.; Mary Elizabeth, who vowed to remain
single and leave Birmingham as soon as she could, never left,
married her childhood sweetheart and had three kids, one of whom
died.
</P>
<P>
   When Rene (Lorraine Toussaint) returns to Birmingham for her
father's funeral, Mary Elizabeth (Potts) initiates a reunion that,
we presume, will re-cement the bond that was once, in the words of
Rene's father, the best hope for the future.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge for ``Any Day Now'' is to remain a smart show
about two women struggling to understand their own imperfect lives
while trying to reinvent what once seemed the perfect friendship.
</P>
<P>
   In Toussaint and Potts, the series has formidable actors who can
handle thoughtful, sensitive material with amazing grace. Their
youthful counterparts, Shari Perry and Mae Middleton, also seem
capable of conveying the brilliant simplicity of an unlikely
friendship that grew more complicated as they grew taller.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any Day Now'' could be something very special, and if it
avoids the slide into lazy melodrama it could give the networks one
more reason to worry about cable.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Cusack is another reason. Though not as well known as
siblings Joan and John, she is certainly their equal in bringing a
real-world sensibility to the screen.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Maggie'' (not to be confused with Faith Ford's upcoming
``Maggie Winters'' on CBS), Cusack plays a married mom whose 40th
birthday is cause for alarm. If the ``values'' police were
contemplating a Lifetime achievement award for the lofty aim of
``Any Day Now,'' they might be reconsidering after a look at Maggie
Day, who has gone from having fantasy liaisons with ``Melrose
Place'' hunk Jack Wagner to having make-believe trysts with the
doctor she sees every day at the veterinary clinic.
</P>
<P>
   Maggie's self-absorbed husband, a ``real'' doctor, finally tunes
in to her mid-life malaise, but is it too late to rekindle their
romance?
</P>
<P>
   The typical sitcom would likely take the safe route, but
``Maggie Day'' might surprise us. Creator/producer Dan O'Shannon,
who earned his stripes on ``Newhart'' and ``Cheers,'' isn't letting
the cat of the vet's office, but he hopes the ``reality'' of
Maggie's situation will keep viewers coming back.
</P>
<P>
   Viewers also will appreciate Cusack's innate ability to bring
truth to a comedic character _ she was easily the best thing about
NBC's version of ``The Jeff Foxworthy Show'' _ without making it
silly.
</P>
<P>
   Another practitioner of truth-in-acting is the elegant Joanna
Gleason. Alas, she is not the star of ``Oh Baby.'' Cynthia
Stevenson (``Hope &AMP; Gloria'') is.
</P>
<P>
   No problem. Stevenson is more than agreeable in the role of
Tracy, a woman whose career (marketing executive) is nearly perfect
and whose personal life (single with commitment-phobic boyfriend)
is not nearly. Tracy wants to have a baby, and she decides
artificial insemination is the only viable alternative.
</P>
<P>
   The witty interplay between Stevenson and Gleason, as Tracy's
best friend, Charlotte, is bright and refreshing.
</P>
<P>
   Less so is a gimmick involving a TV set and remote-control wand
that Tracy uses to explain her life, complete with fast-forward,
stop-action and rewind features.
</P>
<P>
   It's the sort of device we've all wished we had when describing
a particular passage in our lives, and Stevenson has fun with it in
the first episode. It could become tiresome after a while, but ``Oh
Baby'' can easily survive without the gimmickry.
</P>
<P>
   TV REVIEWS
</P>
<P>
   _ Any Day Now. Hourlong drama about an interracial friendship.
Starring Annie Potts and Lorraine Toussaint. Tuesday, Lifetime.
Check local listings. Parental guideline rating: TV-PG.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _ Maggie. Half-hour comedy about a 40-year-old woman facing a
mid-life crisis. Starring Ann Cusack and John Slattery. Tuesday,
Lifetime. Check local listings. Rating: TV-PG.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   _ Oh Baby. Half-hour comedy about a single woman who decides to
have baby through artificial insemination. Starring Cynthia
Stevenson and Joanna Gleason. Tuesday, Lifetime. Check local
listings. Rating: TV-PG.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   To reach John Levesque, call 206-448-8330, or send e-mail to:
tvguy(at)seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
