<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-BLACK-DEATH-RATES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAILORING A HEALTHY MESSAGE TO BLACKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Texas, Ky., Ala.)   (af) 
By LINDA VALLAROSA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Compared with whites, black Americans have higher death rates
from all kinds of serious illnesses _ from heart disease, diabetes,
stroke, some forms of cancer and asthma. Black babies are more
likely to be born small and die in their first year, and black
adults live fewer years than their white counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, many of these problems could be attributed to the
fact that blacks are more likely than whites to be poor, to have
received less education and to have inadequate access to health
care. In recent years, though, the economic gap between blacks and
whites has narrowed, yet the health gap persists.
</P>
<P>
   This problem is attracting the attention of researchers, health
officials and the president, who has made it a priority. He is
seeking $400 million over five years for the Initiative to
Eliminate Racial and Ethnic Disparities in Health, which would
target six health categories that disproportionately affect
minorities: infant mortality, diabetes, cancer screening and
management, cardiovascular disease, HIV and AIDS, and
immunizations.
</P>
<P>
   A large part of the problem, experts say, is the difficulty in
communicating health information to the black community. Despite an
increased public appetite for the latest news about medicine,
nutrition and exercise, and increased coverage in the press,
several studies and experts say health educators may not be
communicating the message clearly or appropriately to blacks. Or,
blacks may be ignoring it.
</P>
<P>
   For example, three studies reported in a recent issue of The
Journal of the American Medical Association found that black
parents often missed hearing about a campaign to reduce the
incidence of sudden infant death syndrome, or SIDS.
</P>
<P>
   The Back to Sleep campaign was created in 1994 by the United
States Public Health Service, the American Academy of Pediatrics
and several other organizations after experts who attended a
National Institutes of Health conference concluded that placing a
newborn in a side or back sleep position helped reduce the risk of
SIDS.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign seems to have had impressive results: In 1992, 70
percent of parents put their babies to sleep on their stomachs,
which increased the risk of SIDS, and in 1996, only 24 percent did
so. Since 1992, the rate of SIDS has declined by 56 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But the research also showed that low-income black and Hispanic
mothers are less likely to put their babies to sleep on their
backs, and their rates of SIDS remain higher than those of their
white counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Back to Sleep message is not being adequately transmitted
to the black population,'' Dr. Michael H. Malloy, a pediatrician at
the University of Texas Medical Branch in Galveston, wrote in an
editorial accompanying the research reports.
</P>
<P>
   Malloy, a member of the American Academy of Pediatrics task
force that helped devise the campaign, noted that it had not been
designed with any particular group in mind, though, at the time, it
was widely known that the rate of SIDS was much higher for blacks
than whites.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, he said, ``we were more interested in a generic
campaign,'' with brochures and posters mailed to health care
providers to pass along Back to Sleep information to their
patients.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the medical journal studies, researchers found that
the greatest influence on a mother's decision to put her baby to
sleep on her back was advice from a health care professional. Yet,
in a small study conducted in Louisville, Ky., researchers found
that 72 percent of parents in a predominantly white private
practice setting reported that their physicians had recommended
putting their children to sleep on their backs compared with only
48 percent in a predominantly black inner-city clinic.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Reed V. Tuckson, the highest-ranking black in the hierarchy
of the American Medical Association, said, ``The public health
information network in every major city is being dismantled, and
the opportunity for a health care provider to spend quiet,
deliberate time in conversation with patients is diminishing.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuckson, the AMA's senior vice president for professional
standards, added: ``There is a need to increase the cultural
competence of doctors dedicated to service in poor communities. In
the sleep studies, it wasn't that the mothers were stupid or
irresponsible. They were concerned that the babies couldn't sleep
on their backs or that they would choke. There is a need for their
health care providers to go a little deeper.''
</P>
<P>
   Another study, by the Kaiser Family Foundation and the National
Association of Black Journalists, involved surveys of 804 blacks
and 664 whites to determine the effectiveness of the press in
delivering health information. Compared with whites, blacks were
much less likely to think the press provides enough health and
health care coverage and more likely to think the press does a poor
job of ``telling people in this country what they need to know
about health and health care.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
