(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following stories
today for use by NYTimes News Service clients. They will move in
the ``e'' entertainment news file. For questions, contact Jimmy
Johnson at the Daily News, (818) 713-3695. 
. 
LABUTE-MOVIE (Los Angeles) _ Neil LaBute is the film world's
unlikeliest Mormon. Last year, the writer-director burst upon the
scene with the controversial ``In the Company of Men,'' a movie
where two middle managers deliberately set out to woo a woman and
then heartlessly dump her. Now he's back with another cynical look
at love and relationships, ``Your Friends and Neighbors.'' By Glenn
Whipp. 
. 
MULAN-HAIR (Los Angeles) _ Call it the real parent trap. Inspired
by the spirited heroines of two new made-for-little-girls movies,
some youngsters are taking up scissors and trying their hands at
shearing their own locks. Snip. ``Look, Mom, I'm Mulan.'' By
Jenifer Hanrahan. 
. 
MOVIES-FASHION (Los Angeles) _ Movies make stars, but they also
make fashion statements. Consider the film ``Titanic'' and that
dazzling ``Heart of the Sea'' necklace. It's being knocked off all
over town, and it's ditto with the dresses. By Barbara De Witt. 
. 
UMA-FASHIONS (Los Angeles) _ Say what you will about the new
``Avengers'' movie _ that you don't remember the 1960s TV series,
that you didn't even know there was a TV series, that English twits
(even in parody form) are still English twits and therefore about
as enjoyable as boiled beef and cabbage for breakfast _ but this
film does have one thing working for it, a selling point so vivid,
so delectable, that you can see why they green-lighted the whole
thing in the first place. 
. 
PARTY-SOCIAL (Los Angeles) _  Benefits and balls are swell, but the
CaliforniaMart's lingerie party was a nice change of pace on the
social circuit. This wasn't one of those parties in people's homes
where they sell nightgowns like Tupperware but a lavishly staged
runway show of the latest in undies, presented while guests sipped
wine and nibbled pate, focaccia and chicken on a stick. By Barbara
De Witt. 
. 

