<SLUG> BC-MULAN-HAIR-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN MULAN CUTS, SO DO GIRLS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENIFER HANRAHAN 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; At least it's not as bad as when little boys
jumped off the roof to be like Superman.
</P>
<P>
   Little girls have found their own idol in Mulan, the spunky
heroine of the animated film by the same title who shears off her
long dark locks with a sword to masquerade as a man and defend her
family's honor.
</P>
<P>
   So what are little girls up to this summer? Hacking off their
own hair to be just like Mulan.
</P>
<P>
   Frantic parents are dragging their little girls into hair
salons, hoping stylists can undo the do-it-yourself 'dos.
</P>
<P>
   Hair stylist Maria Navarro recently had a 5-year-old come into
Halos Kids Cuts in Reseda dressed in a Mulan T-shirt, Mulan shoes
and a Mulan haircut to match. She had chopped off her bangs to the
scalp.
</P>
<P>
   ``She only stopped there because her mom walked in on her,''
Navarro said. ``I asked her why she did it. She said, `I want to
look like Mulan'.''
</P>
<P>
   Ozy Raissian, owner of Land of Ozy in Encino, had a customer who
loved her 3-year-old daughter's long, reddish-dark brown hair.
</P>
<P>
   Then the mother left her daughter with a baby sitter who took
the girl to see ``Mulan.'' While the mother was away, the little
girl chopped off her hair, leaving little clumps here and there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked,'' Raissian said. ``She cut it like a mushroom.
I fixed it nice. Now the little girl is happy because her hair is
short. But the mom is very unhappy.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it doesn't take a movie to get a kid to cut her own
hair. Between 2 and 6, kids cut the bangs off dolls and Barbies.
And, if the mood strikes them, sometimes they take liberties with
their own hair, too, stylists say.
</P>
<P>
   Movie and cartoon characters always have inspired children to
yearn longingly for that certain look. Long, flowing hair captured
little girls' fancies when Pocahontas was the Disney gal of the
moment. Flat tops were the hit among boys when Bart Simpson first
hit the tube, said Sabrina Feldman, manager of Yellow Balloon in
Studio City.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, banning your child from theaters may not be the
answer, either. Jessica Conway, 7, of Reseda went to Halos Kids
Cuts to get her long locks chopped into a bob just like Posh Spice,
who Jessica is playing in a summer camp skit.
</P>
<P>
   Let's just be thankful it's not Edward Scissorhands who captured
kids' imaginations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-98 1703EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980817.0246 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-17 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7790 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LABUTE-MOVIE-LADN     08-17 1586
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABUTE-MOVIE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORMON SCREENWRITER`S CHARACTERS ELICIT STRONG REACTIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GLENN WHIPP  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Neil LaBute loves the power of words. He's
practically inebriated over the idea that words _ his words! _ can
move audiences to shout at his characters on a movie screen, to
write angry screeds in newspapers and magazines, to confront him on
the street, to even spit in his face. LaBute will take your saliva
and wear it as a badge of honor. Don't misunderstand. He wants your
love. But he doesn't mind if some hate comes with it. Just don't
ignore him. Indifference would be like a death sentence.
</P>
<P>
   LaBute _ whose new movie, ``Your Friends &AMP; Neighbors,'' opens
Wednesday _ will never forget when his first movie, ``In the
Company of Men,'' premiered last year at the Sundance Film
Festival. Now, remember, this is Sundance, an event dominated by
Movie People, hardened cynics who watch hundreds of films a year
and think they have seen it all. Then the lights go down and
LaBute's movie starts unspooling and there are these two
businessmen who blow into a town and scheme to romance the same
deaf woman and then, just when she's all doe-eyed and dewy, they
dump her _ simply for the sport of it!
</P>
<P>
   ``She'll be reaching for the sleeping pills within a week, and
you and me, we'll laugh about this until we're very old men,'' said
Chad, the duo's charismatic, stinkbomb of a ringleader.
</P>
<P>
   When the movie ends and the credits start rolling, LaBute thinks
that some people are going to grab a rope and lead him to the
nearest tree. Aaron Eckhart, who played Chad, was walking out the
door when a woman found him and hissed, ``I HATE you!'' Eckhart,
who has known LaBute since college and has seen this type of
reaction before, replies, ``No. No. You've got it wrong. It's not
me you hate. It's the CHARACTER.'' But the woman doesn't see it
that way. ``No. I hate YOU.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, LaBute doesn't help matters much with his casual
intellectualism and blase dismissals during the question-and-answer
session that follows the screening.
</P>
<P>
   Sample Question: Why is the movie's victim a deaf woman?
</P>
<P>
   LaBute: I don't know. I guess I've just always thought deaf
people were funny.
</P>
<P>
   And there you have it. Neil LaBute. Sundance Scofflaw.
Filmmaking Firebrand. World-class Hun. Except ... what's this? ...
LaBute, 35, has a wife of 13 years and two kids, ages 10 and 7.
Lives in Indiana. Is unfailingly cordial and polite. Is loved by
friends and family. (Although his mother wishes he'd make a
``nice'' movie.) Has worked with mental patients in spare time. Is
a devout and practicing Mormon.
</P>
<P>
   With each new fact, the picture becomes a little fuzzier. Who is
this guy? And what exactly is he up to, anyway? That's precisely
what LaBute wants people to ask. He doesn't believe in heroes or
villains, whether they populate the movies he writes and directs or
walk the streets of our neighborhoods. LaBute lives for the gray
areas. That's where he feels most comfortable, except for those
times when he's making his audience feel uncomfortable. Comfort in
discomfort is his working motto.
</P>
<P>
   It certainly is the idea behind LaBute's new movie, an
unflinching look at the intimate relationships of six upscale
suburbanites. The film's three men and three women lie, cheat and
betray each other and themselves in a variety of perverse, twisted
ways. The film has no nudity and the audience sees the sex either
immediately before or immediately after the act. It's all talk.
Words! Brutal, unsparing, emotionally wrenching words.
</P>
<P>
   ``His language is precisely shocking,'' says Eckhart, who
appears in the film playing an impotent man who's the polar
opposite of his character from ``In the Company of Men.'' ``Neil
has always been able to open up a can of worms that no one else
seems willing to touch. And the great thing is, he doesn't feel the
need to explain these people or have some big emotional catharsis.
They are who they are. There are no judgments.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, not exactly. Because while in one breath LaBute will tell
you, ``I'm not passing judgment on behavior. I'm just exposing it
and asking, `What do you think?' minutes later he's telling you
about his Mormon faith and explaining how it influences his work.
</P>
<P>
   LaBute converted to Mormonism after winning a scholarship to
Brigham Young University's acclaimed drama program following
graduation from his school in Tacoma, Wash. While there (and LaBute
returned later for graduate studies), he didn't exactly sing in the
Tabernacle Choir. Mostly he did what he's doing now, pushing the
envelope with his words and ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Example: One of the first plays LaBute wrote was called
``Bash,'' which featured a well-heeled Mormon discussing a previous
night's gay-bashing while he waits to take a family portrait. BYU
administrators didn't come right out and say, ``No. You can't do
this.'' They simply asked LaBute if he could maybe make the
character, say, a Catholic instead. LaBute refused.
</P>
<P>
   Later in his BYU days, LaBute staged a production of David
Mamet's ``Sexual Perversity in Chicago.'' This time he had to cut
much of the play's language and situations. By the time he was
done, the show was almost incomprehensible. Still it was ``Sexual
Perversity'' at ... Brigham Young University! (Words! The power of
words!'')
</P>
<P>
   ``He has always liked to shock people,'' says Eckhart, a
longtime friend and a fellow Mormon. ``His plays at BYU had the
same themes of betrayal and portrayals of the dark side of
humanity. People didn't know what to make of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, practicing Mormon LaBute acknowledges that most in the
church feel his Mormonism needs a little more practice. LaBute
thinks his faith is just fine, if, admittedly, a little improbable.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't look at my work and say, `That's what I'd expect
from a Mormon,' '' LaBute says. ``But I think you need to give
voice to subjects. I felt that way at BYU and I feel that way now.
The church's tendency is to feel that there's enough bad in the
world, so let's have some positive examples, especially in the
media. They're wary of being able to find good by showing the
bad.''
</P>
<P>
   LaBute, naturally, takes the complete opposite approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of good can come from showing evil,'' he says.
``It promotes thought and discussion. Both of my films and most of
my plays have had a very staunch moral point of view by looking at
these people, these Philistines, as if from on high, and saying,
`Hmmm ... I'm not so sure I like how these people are operating.'''
</P>
<P>
   It's very Old Testament, very condemning, very judgmental, in
its own subtle way. You just have to look at the movies from the
proper perspective _ from LaBute's perspective. That way you don't
look at two guys stringing along a deaf woman and think ...
misogynist! You see two reprehensible human beings who will, upon
their demise, spend all of eternity shoveling brimstone in the Lake
of Fire. Or something like that. Just don't expect LaBute to hold
your hand and help you make the call. That's not his method of
operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very surprised that women felt that `In the Company of
Men' was misogynistic,'' says Alix Madigan, a producer on LaBute's
new film who met the filmmaker at that fateful Sundance festival.
``I mean, yes, it was brutal, and when I first met Neil, I kind of
expected to see him walking around in a dark cape. But he doesn't
shock you for the sake of the shock itself. He's showing some
terribly flawed people and not making any apologies for their
behavior. He trusts the audience to draw their own conclusions.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Steve Golin, another ``Friends &AMP; Neighbors'' producer:
``His movies have this weird blend of drama and comedy, and it's
the kind of humor where you hate yourself later for having laughed.
And after getting to know Neil and spending time with him, it's
hard to figure out where all this cynicism comes from. Maybe the
work is therapy for him. Maybe that's where he gets all the dark
stuff out.''
</P>
<P>
   LaBute's wife, Lisa, a therapist and lifelong Mormon, might have
something to say about that. She reads all his scripts, checking
for the characters' psychological accuracy. Lisa was very pleased
with ``In the Company of Men,'' but was less enthusiastic about
``Your Friends &AMP; Neighbors.'' Oh, Neil got the mental underpinnings
down all right, she thought, but did he have to make a movie about
couples and, um, sex? After all, what would their friends and, yes,
neighbors think?
</P>
<P>
   ``Like most people, she's a little squeamish talking frankly
about sexuality,'' LaBute says. ``People can watch a movie sex
scene with two people writhing around in bed with saxophone music
playing in the background and it doesn't bother them nearly as much
as watching two people sitting and talking about it. So, yes, I
think she found it a little unnerving.''
</P>
<P>
   But unnerving is good. Discomfort is the goal. Push-pull,
pull-push. Love-hate, hate-love. Bad is good because good comes
from seeing bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see any harm from shaking up a can of bees just to see
what happens,'' LaBute says. ``I think we have enough niceness in
our culture, too many entertainments that leave absolutely no
ripple in anyone's consciousness. They just take up time. To me,
that's the most damning kind of review you could receive. It was
`nice.'''
</P>
<P>
   Not to worry, Neil. Chances are, nobody will ever feel inclined
to write that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
