<HEADLINE>
UNDIES OUT IN THE OPEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARBARA DE WITT 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Benefits and balls are swell, but the
CaliforniaMart's lingerie party was a nice change of pace on the
social circuit.
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't one of those parties in people's homes where they
sell nightgowns like Tupperware but a lavishly staged runway show
of the latest in undies, presented while guests sipped wine and
nibbled pate, focaccia and chicken on a stick. Definitely not a
party husbands had to be dragged to ...
</P>
<P>
   Typical of social events in L.A.'s Fashion District, the female
guests expressed themselves in swaths of tulle, slinky black
cocktail sheaths, and peasant dresses in washed-out pastels worn
with slashes of pink eye shadow, while men favored loud
Italian-looking sport shirts or dark linen tees with sport coats.
</P>
<P>
   On stage, the fashion parade was presented by Cosabella and
Calida. Other manufacturers previewing their fall and holiday lines
included Lise Charmel, La Perla, Lou, Nina Ricci, Only Hearts,
Simone Perele, Natori, Ripcosa, Keiko Ono, Jonquil, Hanro and Flora
Nickrooz.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, from the looks on the runway, underwear is no longer an
unmentionable. According to Sue Scheimann, president and chief
executive officer of the CaliforniaMart, ``Last year we hosted our
first intimate apparel fashion show, the only one of its kind on
the West Coast, and responding to the monumental interest displayed
at the debut show, we naturally decided to make this an annual
event.''
</P>
<P>
   The news? Several guests, such as fashion mavens Linda Arroz and
Jane Mannfolk, talked about how lingerie sales are up and how the
G-string, once a stripper's staple, has influenced the fashion biz.
Later, I chatted with Sergio Oxman, co-owner of the Italian
lingerie firm Cosabella, and he agreed that bikini panties have
been replaced by lacy thongs _ which, by the way, were given as
party favors. He also said decorative bustiers are the newest trend
in underwear as outerwear. His portion of the fashion show included
them, plus heavily embroidered rich gold and red lingerie and saucy
see-through peignoirs inspired by the '50s. His finale was a
``bride'' in a white leaf-print bustier and sheer skirt over a
G-string, who was serenaded by an opera singer in black tie.
</P>
<P>
   The CaliforniaMart's next round of parties will be Oct. 4, when
the California Designer of the Year and Rising Star awards will be
presented at the Beverly Hilton Hotel in Beverly Hills. For ticket
information, call Dana Forster at (213) 630-3618.
</P>
<P>
   For more fashionable soirees, circle your calendars for Sept. 24
and 25, when the Los Angeles County Museum of Art will hold Art of
the Palate '98. A major fund-raiser for the museum, the event is
all about eating in a unique setting. Instead of everybody going to
one place, you choose your dream date locale from among 51 parties.
For instance, the ``Pleasures of Prague'' is a night of Eastern
European cuisine and music with the Consul General of the Czech
Republic, Ivana Hlavsova, priced at $225 a person. Or how about
``Picasso's Paris,'' an intimate soiree designed to be a fantasy
journey to Paris in the decadent '20s; or ``The Mayor Who Came to
Dinner,'' which is a dinner party at the Brentwood home of Mayor
Richard Riordan, priced at $500 a person. Most events are for 14
guests and don't require a tuxedo. For more information, call (323)
857-6182.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-98 1705EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
