<HEADER>
A7798 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UMA-FASHION-LADN     08-17 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UMA-FASHION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENGLISH LEATHER REACHES NEW HEIGHTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GLENN WHIPP  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Say what you will about the new ``Avengers'' movie
_ that you don't remember the 1960s TV series, that you didn't even
know there was a TV series, that English twits (even in parody
form) are still English twits and therefore about as enjoyable as
boiled beef and cabbage for breakfast _ but this film does have one
thing working for it, a selling point so vivid, so delectable, that
you can see why they green-lighted the whole thing in the first
place.
</P>
<P>
   Namely: Uma. Emma.
</P>
<P>
   And, really, what more do you need? Uma. Emma. Which, roughly
translated, means Uma-leather, since Uma Thurman's ``Avengers''
character, sexy super-sleuth Emma Peel, spends half the movie
prowling about in a leather catsuit.
</P>
<P>
   For men, Uma and leather are two words that have a certain
inevitability to them, not to mention a precise, lyrical beauty.
They go together like peanut butter and jelly or Bill Clinton and
subpoena. If David Letterman had used Uma-leather as his mantra
instead of Uma-Oprah four years ago at the Oscars, he might have
been invited back to host. Alas, he didn't, and he was
unceremoniously shunted back to the late-night wasteland, never to
don a tux again.
</P>
<P>
   But we digress. Uma-Emma, Uma-leather. Uma is the kind of
statuesque beauty (not to mention crackerjack actress!) who
``Avengers'' costume designer Anthony Powell said would ``look sexy
wearing a garbage can liner.'' (Uma-Hefty? Hmmm...) In ``The
Avengers,'' she and her bowler-hat-wearing partner John Steed
(played by Ralph Fiennes) drolly engage cartoon criminals in
methods only a little less silly than Austin Powers, International
Man of Mystery.
</P>
<P>
   No one remembers Emma for her crime-fighting exploits, though.
It was her clothes, specifically the leather catsuit that she
occasionally wore to the office. Actress Diana Rigg only slipped
into the outfit a few times during the run of the television series
because it would split whenever she tried to run or pull off a leg
kick. (These were the prehistoric days before stretch leather.)
</P>
<P>
   When it came time to update the catsuit, Powell tried to come up
with a look that, like Uma-Emma, Uma-leather, had a certain
inescapable destiny to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``At my first meeting with Uma, she asked where the catsuit
would hang in Emma's wardrobe,'' Powell says. ``That's a very good
question. You just don't get up one morning and think, `Today, I
may fall off the top of a skyscraper, so I'd better wear the black
leather'.''
</P>
<P>
   No, you don't. But if retailer J. Peterman has his way, a number
of women might start thinking along those lines. His new catalog
features a replica of Uma's ``Avengers'' catsuit under the heading:
Only Slightly Perverse. The typically droll caption goes on to say
that the outfit is ``High Risk. High Reward.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, for $2,000, Peterman's catsuit isn't the kind of impulse
buy women are likely to make for the upcoming fall season. There's
also the nagging question of accessorizing the outfit (what kind of
earrings go with a catsuit?) and where, precisely, today's woman
would wear such a thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's different, unique, sexy,'' Peterman says.
</P>
<P>
   And it could give those casual Fridays at the workplace a whole
new lyrical beauty of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe not.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-98 1706EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
