<P>
   &UR; QUOTABLES FROM NBC'S 'THE TONIGHT SHOW WITH JAY LENO' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Paula Jones showed her new nose last night on 'Primetime.' She
showed off her old nose on 'This Old House.' She's using it to
build an extension on a trailer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Big heat wave in Europe. In Paris, it's 100 degrees. The
French government is advising its citizens to stay inside and try
not to do anything --you know, like they did in World War II.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you seen this new commercial for a toothpaste for smokers
called Tar-gone? It's supposed to get the tar off the teeth of
smokers. Is that really the biggest concern of people who smoke?
How about coming out with a toothpaste called lung-come-back?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Know whose birthday it is? Hulk Hogan's. I don't want to say
Hulk is old, but instead of having a stripper jump out of a cake,
they had a registered nurse come out of a giant bran muffin.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TOUCHE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A German tourist walks into a McDonald's in New York City and
orders a beer. The local guy in the line behind him immediately
gives him a verbal jab, `They don't serve beer here, you moron!'
</P>
<P>
   The German fellow felt embarrassed, however he turned to the New
Yorker with a surprised look on his face and begins to chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   `And what's so funny?' the New Yorker demands.
</P>
<P>
   `Oh, nothing really, I just realized how stupid you are. You
came here for the food!'
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FARM COUNTRY HUMOR &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A motorist, after being bogged down in a muddy road, paid a
passing farmer five dollars to pull him out with his tractor. After
he was back on dry ground, he said to the farmer, `At those prices,
I should think you would be pulling people out of the mud night and
day.'
</P>
<P>
   `Can't,` replied the farmer. `At night I haul water for the
hole.'
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CITY STREETS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   On a flight from Hartford, Conn., to Chicago recently, a lovely
lady who has to be everyone's idea of a grandmother settled into
the seat next to me. Obviously not a frequent flier, she looked
about with lively interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not a spacious seat,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' I replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``They certainly don't give you a lot of room for your knees, do
they?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, they don't,'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   When our meals arrived, she examined the salad closely, and she
poked the cellophane-wrapped roll with an inquiring finger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bread,'' I said, anticipating her question.
</P>
<P>
   Then the main course arrived, which bore a faint resemblance to
chicken. She looked at it and tested it with her fork. Then, very
quietly, she mused: ``So this is life in the fast lane.''
</P>
<P>
   Rachel Hirshorn, on the verge of her fifth birthday, is ``a real
New Yorker,'' according to her grandmother, Nancy Yanes-Hoffman.
Recently, after finishing her dinner, Rachel jumped up from the
table, eager to read a new book.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you say before you leave the table?'' her mother
asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Check,'' Rachel replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, Rachel,'' her mother groaned. ``That's not what you say.''
</P>
<P>
   Rachel thought for a minute. ``I know,'' she said. ``Check,
please.''
</P>
<P>
   The softball field is a short walk from Robert T. Quade's house
in Bernardsville, N.J., and for more than three decades he has
strolled down on summer evenings to watch the men's teams in
action.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, there have been changes: uniforms and equipment,
sponsors, haircut styles, cellular phones.
</P>
<P>
   Many players, coming directly from work, have wolfed down pizza
slices, hamburgers and sub sandwiches, but on a hot dusty day last
month there was another innovation. As his team was at bat, an
infielder took over third-base coaching, keeping a keen eye on the
batter and runners while, with great aplomb and handling his
chopsticks faultlessly, he munched sushi.
</P>
<P>
   Sheila Stuart was looking for a parking space on East 71st
Street recently when she spied a car about to pull out. So did the
motorist ahead of her. As she attempted to pull forward into it,
the driver ahead simultaneously tried to back in. Stalemate. Both
sat there, neither one able to claim the spot, and neither one
willing to give it up.
</P>
<P>
   After a few minutes, the other driver got out of his car and
walked back toward Ms. Stuart, who rolled down her window and
asked, ``Are you a gambling man?'' He was, he said. How about
flipping a coin for the space, she asked. He produced a quarter,
flipped it and said, ``Your call.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Heads,'' Ms. Stuart called _ and it was. The man smiled, got
into his car and drove off, no doubt to continue his search.
</P>
<P>
   Scene: Express train from Old Greenwich to Grand Central.
</P>
<P>
   Players: Two businessmen
</P>
<P>
   Observer: Jennifer Sherwood
</P>
<P>
   First businessman: ``We finally got our new Suburban. It's
perfect. It has two pull-down movie screens in the backseat and two
matching headsets. We don't have to worry about the kids bothering
us on long car trips. You should look into it.
</P>
<P>
   Second businessman, not missing a beat: ``Well, I'll have to
come over soon with the kids, and we'll put them in the driveway.''
</P>
<P>
   Trying on a bathing suit at Bloomingdale's, Menorah Rotenberg
overheard the following conversation between the woman in the next
dressing room and the woman's husband, waiting outside.
</P>
<P>
   He: Honey, are you hungry?
</P>
<P>
   She: After trying on these suits. I'll never be hungry again.
</P>
<P>
   Commuters to New York are so used to traffic jams that they
generally take them in stride. In five years of commuting from New
Jersey to Manhattan over the George Washington Bridge, Leslee
Fetner has seen drivers reading newspapers, styling their hair,
applying makeup and, of course, talking on their cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   But she was pleasantly distracted one day recently when traffic
was particularly heavy. A sleek blue sports convertible pulled
alongside. The driver _ white plastic baton in hand _ was earnestly
conducting a symphony that was obviously coming from his radio or
CD player. Next stop, Carnegie Hall?
</P>
<P>
   Verla C. Gabriel was in an elevator with two other women,
obviously friends. One, who had seen a list of to-do chores posted
in the other's kitchen, asked what ``metal'' meant.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means cleaning silver,'' the friend replied. ``I didn't
want to write silver because if a burglar came, he'd start looking
for it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You could write `argent' or another foreign word,'' the first
woman suggested.
</P>
<P>
   No way, said the woman. ``New York burglars are multilingual,
everyone knows that.''
</P>
<P>
   Scene: Evelyn Murphy in her local supermarket, watching:
</P>
<P>
   Action: A woman in the soup aisle, looking tired and completely
uninterested. She glances at the rows and rows of soup labels and
takes out her cell phone. She punches several buttons, still
looking bored. ``So, what do you want for supper?'' she asks.
</P>
<P>
   Francine Silverman enjoyed this sign on the United Methodist
Church in Fleischmanns, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU'RE NOT AS CLOSE TO GOD AS YOU USED TO BE, GUESS WHO
MOVED.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
