<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BY-DESIGN-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACCESSORY OF THE WEEK: RED RIDING HOOD AT THE OFFICE  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANNE-MARIE SCHIRO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hoods may once have been worn only for warmth, but
now they have entered the fashion scene on all manner of clothing,
including dresses and tailored jackets.
</P>
<P>
   The trend is just one more way in which designers are being
influenced by athletic styles like sweatshirts and anoraks, making
them suitable for work, not just workouts.
</P>
<P>
   Saks Fifth Avenue has a tailored gray-hooded jacket with a zip
front by Bisou-Bisou ($158); a sleeveless white matte jersey top
($118) and a red matte jersey dress ($145), both by ABS; a fitted
gray cap-sleeve sweater by Diabless ($148), and a belted long
cardigan from Weekend by Max Mara ($375).
</P>
<P>
   Donna Karan's charcoal wool hooded pullover ($580) and Theory's
gray zip-front jacket ($240) are at Bergdorf Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   At Barneys New York, there are black cashmere sweaters with
hoods by Urchin ($120); pale blue rayon pullovers by Yesin ($120),
and black stretch rayon tops with three-quarter sleeves by Page
($92).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-98 1713EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
