<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-17 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7848 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-TRIATHLON-HEALTH-     08-17 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-TRIATHLON-HEALTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SWAMP FEVER' CASES LINKED TO TRIATHLON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ill., Wis., Ga.)   (af)  
 By JOHN O'NEIL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Officials from the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention
and 42 state health departments are investigating an outbreak of
leptospirosis, an infection contracted through exposure to
contaminated soil or water, among participants in a Springfield,
Ill., triathlon.
</P>
<P>
   They have concluded that this was the largest recorded exposure
in this country of the disease, which sometimes goes by the
appropriately murky name of swamp fever.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-July, three triathletes were hospitalized with
unexplained high fevers in Madison, Wisc., just a few days after a
triathlon there. The cases were alarming enough to city and state
officials that they contacted the centers in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators soon learned that only two of the three patients
had participated in the Madison triathlon, but that all three had
taken part in the June 21 Springfield Ironhorse Triathlon, which
included a 1.5-mile swim through Lake Springfield, a 45-mile bike
race and a 10-mile run.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend of July 18-19, Illiniois state health officials
and more than 100 CDC volunteers hit the phones, working from the
registration lists for the events, which included names from 44
states and seven countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We began doing a lot of calling,'' said Dr. John R. Lumpkin,
Illinois' director of public health. ``Every time we reached one
participant, we asked how we could reach others. We had to reach
some by mail, fax or e-mail, because that's how they registered.''
</P>
<P>
   What they found was a large number of sick triathletes, which
attracted notice, because ``they are normally a young, healthy
group of people who don't like to be ill for any reason,'' said Dr.
Jordan Tappero, a CDC official who coordinated the tracking effort.
``It interrupts their training.''
</P>
<P>
   As of Aug. 4, investigators had contacted 1,133 of the 1,432
people known to have participated in either event. The numbers
pinpointed Springfield as the source: of the 870 athletes
contacted, 89, or 10.2 percent, had symptoms that met the case
definition of leptospirosis, primarily high fever, headache, muscle
pain or red eye.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy-two had felt bad enough to seek medical attention, and
23 had been hospitalized. Of those, two had suffered kidney failure
and one had received an operation under the false impression that
an abdominal disorder was at work. Only one case of the infection,
which is generally not life-threatening and is treatable with
antibiotics, was diagnosed correctly.
</P>
<P>
   If there had not been a triathlon, putting so many bodies in the
same place at the same time, Lumpkin said, the cases ``would have
probably been written off as the flu.''
</P>
<P>
   Leptospirosis is ``ubiquitous in the environment,'' Tappero
said, many strains are harmless and only a scattering of cases are
reported each year. A spirochete that is found in livestock, wild
animals, rodents and some dogs and cats, the bacteria are released
through the animals' urine.
</P>
<P>
   People are exposed by coming into contact with freshly
contaminated mud or water, usually in a small river or stream. The
bacteria enter the body through skin abrasions, the mouth or eyes.
Symptoms appear anywhere from a few days to a month later, and
positive diagnosis requires detection of antibodies in a patient's
blood, which can take several weeks longer to develop.
</P>
<P>
   After state officials publicized the outbreak, more than 100
swimmers and boaters who had been in Lake Springfield after the
triathlon came forward reporting similar symptoms. Although only a
few proved to have leptospirosis, the state shut down most of the
lake's beaches.
</P>
<P>
   Though the outbreak seems to be winding down, the ban remains.
``There's a strong basis to believe that a good, hard winter may
decrease the risk of transmission next spring,'' said Lumpkin,
``but we will need to be vigilant.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
