<P>
   The actions Monday raised more questions than they answered.
Most analysts feared more instability in the markets and the
possibility of social unrest if Russian consumers suffer massive
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The stock market ended the day down about 4.5 percent on light
trading.
</P>
<P>
   Sonja Gibbs, chief strategist at Nomura International in London,
said investors were in ``a state of shock.''
</P>
<P>
   The decline of the ruble also was expected to lead to the
collapse of many of Russia's 1,500 commercial banks, some already
near bankruptcy before Monday's announcement.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to devalue the ruble came despite firm assurances
Friday by President Boris Yeltsin and other high-ranking government
officials that no devaluation would occur. A Central Bank
spokeswoman had told reporters Friday that devaluation ``would
bring this country problems, and mostly for our people.''
</P>
<P>
   The government decided -- with apparent nudging over the weekend
from officials of the International Monetary Fund, which last month
assembled a $22.6 billion bailout package for Russia -- that it
must devalue the ruble to improve Russia's bottom line in its
effort to prevent bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tougher and more effective measures were necessary. That is
exactly what we are doing,'' said Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF package had been intended to buy time for Russia to
improve its finances and lure investors back. But the market
free-fall was so acute by late last week that trading had virtually
ceased.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, the White House urged Russia's government to
quickly stabilize the ruble and reassure international investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Russian government has had to make some painful
decisions,'' White House spokesman Michael McCurry said. ``Building
market confidence at this point is fundamental. Strong effective
actions offered by the Russians are the key to restoring
confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   In part, the problems are not the fault of Russia. The Asian
financial crisis has driven foreign investors out of emerging
markets in Russia and elsewhere. The declining world price of oil,
Russia's biggest export earner, coupled with the country's own
difficulties in collecting taxes, has left the government strapped
for cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government, as much as it tried, could not deal with the
situation and it became a victim of circumstances. Of course it
will be a hard hit for most citizens of Russia,'' Sergei Baburin,
deputy chairman of the Duma, the lower house of parliament, said of
the devaluation.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition-led Duma, dominated by Communists, announced it
would interrupt its summer recess to meet in emergency session on
Friday. The government wants the Duma to approve measures to raise
more tax revenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is total bankruptcy,'' said Communist leader Gennady
Zyuganov. ``We think that it (devaluation) is first of all a blow
for the poorest. Prices will jump high, most banks except the
biggest will collapse.''
</P>
<P>
   Stung in previous years by erratic fluctuations in their
currency, most Russians hold their savings in dollars and exchange
them into rubles only as they need to purchase goods.
</P>
<P>
   A doctor, Alexei Vachensov, reluctantly gave up a $100 bill at a
Moscow exchange bank Monday afternoon. ``I need rubles to buy
things, otherwise I wouldn't be trading,'' he said. ``Who knows
what to expect next from our foolish government.''
</P>
<P>
   By mid-day, many banks and currency-exchange points were
refusing to sell dollars or had closed for business altogether.
Some retailers -- especially those selling big-ticket items like
automobiles and home appliances -- shut their doors to re-tag their
goods with higher ruble prices, reflecting the devaluation.
</P>
<P>
   At Jumbo, an upscale supermarket, prices for imported fish went
up 10 percent as suppliers Monday raised the wholesale prices, said
manager Olga Ivanuychkina.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may take a week or so to see how things shake out before we
determine whether prices must go up on all items,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The cautious mood affected foreigners in Russia, too. Following
the morning announcement, American Express in Moscow suspended its
banking services and refused to release wire transfers of dollars
to expatriates.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
