<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-17 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7876 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT &LR;      08-17 0413
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, Aug. 18, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Temperatures will soar past 90 degrees Tuesday afternoon along
the Northeast Seaboard as winds from the west strengthening ahead
of a cool front warm by compression on descent from the
Appalachians. Westerly winds will average 12 to 25 mph in the
afternoon, slightly easing the effects of heat and humidity. Widely
separated clusters of thunderstorms will develop later Tuesday
afternoon and evening as the cool front and a trailing jet stream
disturbance rapidly lift moist air. A few of the storms could
produce strong wind gusts.
</P>
<P>
   Clusters of thunderstorms will roam the northern Plains Tuesday
as a tandem of Pacific disturbances interact with invading humid
winds from the south. The first disturbance will arrive in the
predawn hours over North Dakota and northwest Minnesota, spawning a
system of showers and storms, some of which will be heavy. The
second disturbance will arrive later Tuesday afternoon or evening,
setting the stage for an eruption of burly thunderstorms in the
Dakotas. A few of these storms will become severe, producing
damaging winds and hail. Though the probability of tornadoes is
low, it is not zero percent. Thus, a few twisters are possible.
</P>
<P>
   Heat will build in the southern Plains under the warm auspices
of a high pressure system centered several thousand feet aloft over
southeast Kansas. Meanwhile, thunderstorms, fueled by tropical
moisture and the uneven heating of mountains and valleys, will boil
up over the Southwest. Gusty storms moving over deserts in Arizona
could cause localized sand storms.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Black Blizzards
</P>
<P>
   The season of black blizzards is underway in the Arizona
deserts. Strong daytime heating leads to invisible updrafts,
precursors of desert storms. Each year by mid-summer, the
atmosphere at 15,000 feet above the ground has been moistened by
winds from the gulfs of Mexico and California, while air near the
ground can be quite dry. The moisture is fuel for thunderstorms.
Often, rain falling from the incipient thunderstorms evaporates in
the dry air near the earth's surface. Then, blasts of wind, cooled
by evaporation, raise palls of dust, which are black blizzards that
roam the desert floor. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
