<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-17 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7887 &Cx1f; taf-z
s k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV23-NY     08-17 1146
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUMMER GIFTS OF GAB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 23)  
 (Eds: Items in boldface should be set in italics. Double
parentheses should be set as brackets.)  
(lb) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'm fixin' to go on vacation and want you to have a book bag of
word books.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Fixin' to &LR;  is a Southernism covered in ``Jesse's Word of the
Day From Abacinate to Yonic,'' lively scholarship by Jesse
Sheidlower (Random House paperback, $12.95). As we all know,
 &UR; abacinate &LR;  means ``to blind cruelly,'' and  &UR; yonic &LR;  is the female
equivalent of  &UR; phallic &LR;  (a doughnut, Sheidlower notes, is a  &UR; yonic &LR; 
symbol), but the primary meaning of  &UR; fix &LR;  is ``to repair''; where
did the sense of ``to prepare to'' come from?
</P>
<P>
   That sense dates to the early 18th century and is an extension
of the sense of ``put in order; establish, settle definitely,'' and
I presume it is the basis of the political  &UR; fix &LR; . The extension of
that meaning to ``get ready'' has been expressed since the 1930s in
the Gulf and South Atlantic states as  &UR; fixin' to &LR; . It is always
followed by an infinitive, is only used with actions in the near
future and, as Sheidlower points out, ``remains one of the
best-known indicators of Southern speech, along with such words as
 &UR; reckon &LR;  and  &UR; y'all &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   The book is drawn from his Internet page
(www.randomhouse.com/jesse), which answers surfers' queries and is
a demonstration of the Web as a progenitor of books. (With the
onset of electronic books, we will need a retronym for
old-fashioned books with paper pages and a nice heft.) He raises an
interesting etymological question with his entry on  &UR; the skin of my
teeth &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   That's from Chapter 19, Verse 20 of the Book of Job, as the
bedeviled innocent man wails, ``My bone cleaveth to my skin and to
my flesh, and I am escaped with  &UR; the skin of my teeth &LR; .'' That's
the King James translation of 1611, taken from the Geneva Bible
translation of 1560, ``I have escaped with  &UR; the skin of my
teeth &LR; .'' Sheidlower notes that ``the point is that Job is so sick
that there's nothing left to his body.''
</P>
<P>
   That's true; I once wrote a book about Job, and discovered that
recent translators find both  &UR; skin &LR;  and  &UR; teeth &LR;  but no  &UR; skin of my
teeth &LR;  in the original Hebrew, written three to six centuries
before the birth of Christ.
</P>
<P>
   Marvin H. Pope's translation in the 1965 Anchor Bible renders
that verse as ``My flesh rots on my bones, my teeth drop from my
gums,'' and the translator notes that ``The KJ's `I am escaped with
 &UR; the skin of my teeth &LR; ' has become proverbial for a narrow escape,
but the context offers no support for this idea.'' It's a mistake
in translation that has become a familiar part of the language.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Professor and the Madman,'' by Simon Winchester
(HarperCollins $20), is the linguistic detective story of the
decade. Dr. William Chester Minor, an American who studied medicine
at Yale, served in the Union Army as assistant surgeon during the
Civil War and contributed more than 10,000 citations to the Oxford
English Dictionary. When the lexicographer James Murray and a
committee wanted to honor this stalwart reader for his work, it
turned out he was a murderer incarcerated in the Broadmoor Asylum
for the Criminally Insane outside London.
</P>
<P>
   Delusional but scholarly, the man in the asylum had stumbled
across Murray's appeal for volunteers to help survey all that had
been written in English. He wrote in, giving the accurate hospital
address. ``I thought he was either a practicing medical man of
literary tastes with a great deal of leisure,'' Murray said years
later, ``or perhaps a retired medical man or surgeon who had no
other work.''
</P>
<P>
   Winchester does a superb job of historical research that should
entice readers even more interested in deeds than words. Language
mavens owe a lot to a madman.
</P>
<P>
   ``New Yawk Tawk,'' by Robert Hendrickson (Facts on File,
$14.95), will not be out until October, and will have entries like
 &UR; gizza &LR; , which is a slurred pronunciation of ``give us a,'' as in a
tender moment in Richard Condon's ``Prizzi's Money'': `` &UR; Gizza &LR; 
kiss, Al.'' But this gives me a chance to recommend a range of
recent Hendrickson dialect works that also cost $14.95 in paper,
from ``Yankee Talk'' to ``Whistlin' Dixie'' to last year's Ozarkian
``Mountain Range.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Happy Trails,'' a 1994 dictionary of Western expressions,
he provides the original, full name of Los Angeles:  &UR; El Pueblo de
Nuestra Senora la Reina de los Angeles de Porcinuncula &LR; : the town
of our Lady Queen of the Angels of Porcinuncula. (Digging deeper:
 &UR; Porcinuncula &LR;  is the Spanish spelling of the Italian
 &UR; Porziuncola &LR; , which means ``little portion.'' It is a church in
Assisi often visited by St. Francis.)
</P>
<P>
   His entry for  &UR; goodnighting &LR; , a word not found in most
dictionaries of eponyms, deserves to be reproduced in full:
``Students of the old West may be aware that bulls on long cattle
drives often suffered from chafing of the testicles, which
frequently swelled so large that the animal sickened and died. The
remedy was to cut off the testicle bag, push the testicles up into
the body and sew the cut _ a process that enabled the bulls to
travel well and did not impair breeding. The remedy was called
 &UR; goodnighting &LR; , after the cattleman Charles Goodnight, who invented
it, and is surely among the most unusual of words named after
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever meet a cranky yachtsman? I was thumbing through The
Illustrated Dictionary of Boating Terms (Norton, $23.95) and came
across  &UR; cranky &LR; . The preceding word,  &UR; crank &LR; , is defined as ``to
turn. To  &UR; crank &LR;  a winch is to turn the winch handle.''  &UR; Cranky &LR;  is
then defined as ``difficult to steer, unstable.''
</P>
<P>
   Is that the origin of what some call me (along with
 &UR; curmudgeonly &LR; ,  &UR; cantankerous &LR;  and other endearments)?
</P>
<P>
   No. J.E. Lighter's Historical Dictionary of American Slang
(three volumes now out, $50 a crack) has it: Gertrude Lefferts
Vanderbilt wrote in her 1880 social history of the Flatbush section
of Brooklyn, N.Y.: ``A child who was querulous was said to be
`krankie,' from ((Dutch))  &UR; krank &LR; , weak, sick.'' The Smith and Dale
vaudeville skit was titled ``Dr. Kronkheit and His Only Living
Patient.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there's a new edition of Wilson Follett's ``Modern
American Usage'' (Hill &AMP; Wang, $25 _ nice round number, none of
that $24.95 baloney), revised by Erik Wensberg.
</P>
<P>
   Despite solid guidance from the great usagist Jacques Barzun,
this guide never matched the popularity of Fowler's ``Modern
English Usage.'' It's tough going up against that bible, but I like
MAU's scholarly sassiness in its entry on  &UR; grammatical error &LR; : ``A
few stuffed shirts will always contend that this expression is a
contradiction in terms and itself in error. ... To condemn phrases
that are perfectly clear and have long been accepted is pedantry.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-98 1733EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980817.0268 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-17 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7892 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOODSTOCK-MUSIC-REVIE     08-17 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOODSTOCK-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AND THERE WAS WHOOPING ... AND THERE WAS MOSHING ... THE THIRD
DAY  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JON PARELES    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BETHEL, N.Y. _ Everything changed but the site, the hillside
where the Woodstock Festival was held in 1969, for the third ``Day
in the Garden'' festival show here Sunday. The careful, relatively
decorous, professional music of the first two days was replaced by
rowdy, noisy, hormonally charged (though equally professional)
rock. Onstage and off, people started to jump around. The
headliners were current hit makers in their 20s and 30s, not
performers who had been established for decades, and the audience
had fewer parents and many more teen-agers, including a large
contingent of squealing girls for the final band, Third Eye Blind.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd was larger than it was on the festival's first two
days; 28,000 tickets were sold, some for as little as $10 each. The
music was louder, male band members took off their shirts, and a
mosh pit roiled for seven hours, not even stopping when Joan
Osborne sang a ballad like ``One of Us.'' And where Joni Mitchell,
Pete Townshend, Stevie Nicks, Richie Havens and Melanie had paid
tribute to the site's history on Friday and Saturday, the bands on
Sunday were decidedly less reverent. ``I have no desire whatsoever
to live in the past,'' Stephan Jenkins of Third Eye Blind declared.
</P>
<P>
   He may not be offered a choice. In the 1990s, very few rock
bands have generated the kind of loyalty that bands from the '60s
and '70s came to expect. Radio stations, MTV and recording
companies now market hit songs, not the musicians who make them,
training listeners for short attention spans.
</P>
<P>
   The Woodstock Festival in 1969 was encouraged by the newly open,
semi-underground tastes of FM rock stations that disdained the
commerciality of the Top 40. Now, commerciality has triumphed. Many
of the fans here Sunday had decorated themselves with the call
letters of a local radio station running a promotion, voluntarily
turning themselves into billboards. In six months, that station
probably won't be playing half the headliners.
</P>
<P>
   The day's lineup was a modern-rock sampler, largely devoted to
blaring guitars and varieties of responses to adolescent
frustrations. ``You're burning up inside and no one cares,'' the
Goo Goo Dolls sang in one of their punk-charged power-pop songs.
Third Eye Blind and Dishwalla chose melodramatic earnestness and
big crescendos; Marcy Playground played catchy, sardonic pop-rock
that sometimes erupted into power chords, and the Flys latched on
to the guitar-driven funk of the Red Hot Chili Peppers.
</P>
<P>
   While Third Eye Blind is a San Francisco band, its musical
models are British. Its music marches and builds like U2 songs,
parades its guitar riffs like David Bowie's glam-rock and
occasionally revs up to Clash-style punk-rock. Jenkins bawls his
lyrics in a mysteriously acquired English accent, as fervently
off-pitch as the typical English rock belter. Third Eye Blind's
songs are the testimony of a sad-sack Romeo promising that his
misery will make him a sympathetic partner or contemplating how
much he's going to suffer after a breakup. ``Jumper'' urges a
suicidal friend to come back off the ledge, proclaiming, ``If you
do not want to see me again, I would understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Zeroing in on an adolescent market, one song yells, ``Can I
graduate?'' The band's big hit, ``Semi-Charmed Life,'' gloats and
gripes at the same time, recounting sprees of sex and drug use as
the chorus complains, ``I want something else.'' Once the band had
played that hit, a good part of the audience started to head for
the parking lots.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Osborne was rambunctious in her own more rooted way. Her
band leaned hard on blues and funk grooves for songs, many from a
forthcoming album, about the untrammeled power of desire, while Ms.
Osborne pushed her voice hard. She had a sweet understatement in
``One of Us,'' but the blues has taught her how roughness can cut
to the heart. She used harrowing, penetrating nasal tones and a
rasp that approached Janis Joplin's double-stops; she made notes
break and ululate. She also tried some of the slides and percussive
attacks of Pakistani qawwali music. The songs were about abandon
and exaltation, and Ms. Osborne made them vivid without ever losing
control.
</P>
<P>
   Marcy Playground is a bare-bones trio: acoustic guitar, bass and
drums, though the guitar had electric-guitar capabilities. John
Wozniak, its songwriter, has a knack for offhanded pop melody,
touching on anything from lightly strummed folk-rock to big grunge
buildups; his sly lyrics don't take themselves too seriously. In
three days at the Woodstock site, only Wozniak confessed onstage to
writing a song while tripping. Dishwalla's set was a modern-rock
anthology. One song used the ominous crunch and haggard vocals of
Nine Inch Nails, another cranked up the Beatles chords and spacious
guitars like Oasis; another marched like U2. The band has a good
sense of melody while it hedges its bets about style.
</P>
<P>
   The Goo Goo Dolls pulled off a difficult combination: sincerity
without pomposity. With raw-throated fervor, they sang about
growing up too fast and searching for romance and meaning, but
their chosen style doesn't allow them to wallow much. Their music
is an update of the 1980s Minneapolis rock of the Replacements and
Soul Asylum, using punk's fast strumming to rev up the tunefulness
of the Beatles.
</P>
<P>
   A self-conscious generational anthem goes down a lot easier with
a big beat and a surging melody. And Johnny Rzeznik, the band's
main lead singer, wasn't about to let the site make him
sanctimonious. ``Promise us that in 30 years you're not going to
get stupidly nostalgic and come back here in your BMW's,'' he said.
``All we've got is now.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-98 1734EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
