<HEADER>
A7902 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-REVIEWS-NYT &LR;      08-17 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-REVIEWS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ANY DAY NOW': PROMISING PLAYERS, MARRED BY LACK OF CREDIBILITY  
 `MAGGIE': APPEALING AND FUNNY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of reviews. Time, channel are
for New York area. Check local listings.) 
(nk) 
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The saddest moment in ``Any Day Now'' comes right after little
Renee Jackson and Mary Elizabeth O'Brien pay their bus fares. Mary
Elizabeth, who is white, plops down in the nearest available seat.
Renee, who is black, walks back out of the bus' front door, goes to
the back door and boards. In Birmingham, Ala., in 1962, apparently,
sitting in the back of the bus isn't enough. Black people can't
even walk past the white passengers in the good seats.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to trust that depiction, though, since so much of
``Any Day Now,'' a new Lifetime drama series that has its premiere
Tuesday night at 9, strains credibility, embraces stereotype and
generally falls short of expectations.
</P>
<P>
   The series, set in Birmingham in the present, opens by showing
the two girls all grown up. Renee (Lorraine Toussaint) is a
high-powered Washington lawyer who lives on her cell phone and has
lunch dates with senators. Mary Elizabeth (Annie Potts) is still in
Birmingham, smoking cigarettes, handing out Happy Meals to her
troubled children rather than cooking, and getting fed up with her
unemployed, beer-drinking husband. The two women haven't spoken to
each other for 24 years, but when Renee's father dies suddenly and
she decides to move home to take over his law practice, the former
childhood pals are reunited.
</P>
<P>
   This could be the beginning of an interesting portrait of a
friendship that survived tumultuous times, but the two personable
stars have a lot of earnest, obvious dialogue to deal with. Mary
Elizabeth's reaction at first sight of Renee: ``You look beautiful,
like something out of a magazine.'' Renee to Mary Elizabeth: ``I
travel a lot, mostly in Europe and Asia.'' Mary Elizabeth to Renee,
later, when threatened: ``You might be some big-shot lawyer but
you're alone. You've got no husband, no kids.'' And in one of the
show's many flashbacks, Renee and her father (who is, of course, a
lawyer working with the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr.) have this
exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Dad: ``And fear and ignorance breed _ what?''
</P>
<P>
   Renee: ``Prejudice.''
</P>
<P>
   Dad: ``That's my girl.''
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, when Mary Elizabeth and Renee have a serious argument
at age 19, they end up trading racial epithets.
</P>
<P>
   In 1962, I was growing up about 30 miles from Birmingham, and I
have trouble believing that this friendship between school-age
girls of different races could have existed in that time and place.
If the series grows stronger, maybe we'll gladly suspend disbelief.
But the first episode doesn't look promising, with its use of
unlikely coincidences like Renee's return visit to a lingerie shop
where she and her mother (who looked and dressed like a black
Jacqueline Kennedy) were once treated badly. She finds the same
saleswoman still working there and seems genuinely surprised that
the woman doesn't remember her.
</P>
<P>
   What happened in Birmingham and throughout the South in the
early 60's could be the inspiration for thought-provoking,
multilayered drama. The subject deserves much better than this.
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `ANY DAY NOW'
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m. ET Tuesday on Lifetime
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to sympathize with Maggie Day, wife, mother and
would-be veterinarian. Maggie (Ann Cusack) is ignored by her
husband, who is too busy being thrilled with having been declared a
``leading'' cardiologist in a news magazine. For Maggie's 40th
birthday, her teen-age daughter gives her a book called ``You're
Over the Hill When . . . '' No wonder Maggie regularly fantasizes
about being ravished in her kitchen by a hunky actor from ``Melrose
Place.''
</P>
<P>
   And no wonder she's drawn to Richard (John Slattery), her boss
at the animal clinic. He's handsome, he takes her seriously, and
he's funny. When a man brings in his pet rabbit who has been bitten
by a pet duck, Richard explains that this is clearly a case of
Warner syndrome, the belief that ducks and rabbits hang out
together.
</P>
<P>
   Back home, the teen-age daughter's best male friend, an aspiring
artist, has decided to become gay because so many great artists
have been. This puzzles Maggie. ``Are you attracted to men?'' she
asks. The young man answers hopefully, ``Not yet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Maggie'' has a lot going for it: an appealing heroine played
by the fabulous Ms. Cusack, a great supporting cast and jokes that
are actually funny. What a concept!
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `MAGGIE'
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday at 10 p.m. ET on Lifetime.
</P>
</TEXT>
