<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-17 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7928 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LLOYD-COLUMN-LADN     08-17 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LLOYD-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY DOES COMPANY TOLERATE TARDY EMPLOYEE?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Ken Lloyd _ a specialist in organizational behavior _ is a
columnist for the Los Angeles Daily News. His column moves Mondays
in the ``f'' financial news file. Send your questions to P.O. Box
260057, Encino, Calif. 91426 or by electronic mail to
LloydOnJobaol.com. Names will be withheld upon request.) 
By KEN LLOYD  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Question: Our company hired a young man who
brought in a great deal of business. However, he often arrives
late, leaves early, goes out every hour to smoke for 15 minutes,
and comes back late from lunch, usually inebriated and obnoxious to
all of us. I reported this to management, who completely
disregarded what I had to say. The company will do nothing about
him because of the business he brings in. What can I do? P.C. &QL; 
Answer: If you truly enjoy working at this company, one strategy is
to try to keep your contact with this individual to a minimum,
which might not be so difficult in light of the fact that he is
hardly around.
</P>
<P>
   The larger issue is that management of your company feels that
the best way to handle this situation is to overlook it and ignore
you. You alerted them to a situation in which an employee is
destroying himself, creating substantial liability, and conceivably
undercutting cooperation and productivity. And yet, the top-siders
figure that this is not a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Based on managerial inaction in this situation, it appears that
you are in a company that is reactive rather than proactive,
minimally concerned with employee health and safety, oblivious to
the notion of teamwork, uninterested and unresponsive in dealing
with the employees' concerns and fixated on short-term thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the time has come for you to think about spending more
time away from this company, permanently.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am a doctoral student in organizational psychology, and I
have just begun a fellowship program with a municipal organization.
I work on a team of specialists in engineering, financial
management, and related areas. Since I am a part-time employee and
full-time student, I am restricted from leading higher-profile
projects, even if I have expertise in them. How can I communicate
my abilities without coming across as intimidating and/or
theoretical? P.D.
</P>
<P>
   A: Since you are new in the organization, part-time, and more in
the role of student than teacher, it might be a little early to be
thinking about leading those high-profile projects. This is an
important objective, and clearly one that you should pursue.
However, it may make more sense to use the early months of
employment to study the organization, build your network, and
establish your credibility through solid performance.
</P>
<P>
   When there are opportunities to discuss new and creative ways to
approach various projects or problems, you should be ready to
present some ideas based on your expertise. In such situations, try
to emulate the style of your professional peers. For example, if
they are fast-paced, brief and concise, you should be too. In a
word, let them see that you are knowledgeable and have a great deal
in common with them.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, this approach can increase the likelihood of your
associates and departmental management looking to you for some
leadership. There's nothing intimidating or theoretical about that.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I recently left a job where I worked for nearly two years. I
made a terrible mistake when I was there. My boss was willing to
let me stay on, but the pressure was too great, so I left. I can't
put this job on my resume because I fear a future employer will
find out what happened and not hire me. And, by not having it on my
resume, it will look like I haven't worked in two years. Do you
have any suggestions? M.P.
</P>
<P>
   A: No matter how terrible your mistake may have been, you will
be making an even greater mistake if you leave that job off your
resume. You can assume that any potential employer will take
references on you, and when the missing job is found, the job
opportunity will be lost. And, if you are miraculously hired
without having that job on your resume, you will most likely be
terminated if your employer learns about it.
</P>
<P>
   It makes far more sense for you to have it on your resume, and
when you are asked why you left that job, you can present your side
of the story and take away any element of surprise when a reference
is taken on you. Let the potential employer see how much you have
learned and grown from this experience, and how it will actually
make you a better employee.
</P>
<P>
   Every working person has made mistakes and experienced failure.
In fact, some companies feel particularly positive about applicants
who openly discuss a failure, a mistake or a termination.
Willingness to be open about such matters can be viewed as signs of
confidence, self-assurance, honesty, and self-insight. Why deny
yourself the opportunity to demonstrate these characteristics
during the hiring process?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
