<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-17 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7934 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAINE-MUSIC-2TAKES-NY     08-17 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAINE-MUSIC-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOTING CHAMBER MUSIC TO SOME UNEXPECTED CHAMBERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ore., Ga.)   (af)  
 By PAULA DEITZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISLESFORD, Maine _ As the headlands and mountains of Mount
Desert Island merged behind them in a distant summer haze, 16 young
musicians from the Kneisel Hall Chamber Music School and Festival
disembarked here from a ferry boat ride across the harbor for the
group's second annual invasion of the island.
</P>
<P>
   After they had hauled cumbersome violin, viola and cello cases
along a dock stacked high with colorful lobster pots, a station
wagon drove up to take the four cellos to the Neighborhood House,
the island's community center and library.
</P>
<P>
   Kneisel Hall on Tour, as this new program is called, began last
summer as a way of giving performance experience to student artists
seeking to become professional musicians. Equally important, it
provides chamber music concerts to people in outlying Maine
communities who usually do not have access to live performances.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Islesford, the program serves towns including
Bangor, Belfast, Deer Isle, Ellsworth and Machias. But the
picturesque setting of this island and the enthusiastic response of
its residents to the student concerts poignantly brought home the
isolation of Maine's rural communities.
</P>
<P>
   This outreach program is the ultimate realization of the goals
of Franz Kneisel, the Austrian violinist who came to this country
in 1885 at age 20 as concertmaster of the Boston Symphony. He also
founded the Kneisel Quartet, the first professional string quartet
in America.
</P>
<P>
   When it was suggested in 1902 that his devotion to chamber music
might be interfering with his symphony responsibilities, he quit
the symphony. That summer he began to bring gifted music students
to Maine to continue their training at his summer home in the
coastal town of Blue Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the students were from the Institute of Musical Art, now
the Juilliard School, where Kneisel was chairman of the department
of strings.
</P>
<P>
   In 1922, his friend Felix Kahn, brother of the financier and
arts patron Otto Kahn, built the lodge-style concert hall on the
wooded slopes of Blue Hill where faculty artists of the school
still give twice-weekly summer concerts. Kneisel Hall on Tour was
conceived as a midseason opportunity for the students to perform.
This year, the program was supported by a grant of $2,500 from the
Presser Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   The students arrived in Islesford in time to give a 3 p.m.
children's concert. At the Neighborhood House, a wooden lodge built
in 1913 with an indoor basketball hoop, they were met by Katy
Fernald, their host for the day, whose husband, Dan, is a lobster
fisherman.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Fernald announced the schedule: the children's concert; a
walk around the 400-acre island (one mile long by two-thirds of a
mile wide); a casserole supper, prepared by residents, back at the
Neighborhood House; and finally, the main concert at 7 p.m. in the
Islesford Congregational Church.
</P>
<P>
   Then she told them about the two committals, the local term for
burials, that had taken place that week on the island. ``We have
had eight deaths since last fall,'' she said, a great loss in a
place with a year-round population of only 80. Summer visitors
swell the island's population to 300 to 500. ``I hope the music
will bring us peacefulness today,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   While awaiting the arrival of the children who would be their
audience, the young artists disappeared into corners of the hall or
out on the lawn to tune their instruments. The cacophony of these
individual sounds and melodies seemed a metaphor for the
performers' different origins, Peruvian and Taiwanese in addition
to American from 10 states. The students on the trip were part of a
larger group of 50 ranging in age from 15 to 29 and representing
nine countries.
</P>
<P>
   By the time sunburned youngsters, many with parents, filed in to
take their seats or sit on the floor, the first trio was already in
place rehearsing Dohnanyi's Serenade in C Major (Op. 10). Patricia
Hawkins, 21, a violist who teaches elementary school music students
in Oregon, introduced the afternoon's selections, an abbreviated
version of the evening program.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``We make music better in small ensembles,'' she explained,
``and all of us play stringed instruments.''
</P>
<P>
   She suggested that everyone march in place to the ``Marcia''
movement of the Dohnanyi. She explained how the violin differed
from the cello, with the viola positioned between the two.
</P>
<P>
   In Schubert's Cello Quintet in C Major (Op. 163, D. 956), Brook
Bennett, 17, a cellist, told the children to listen for the ``angry
parts when we sound like we are fighting each other.'' At that
point, Lane Rylander, age 5, did a few ballet turns in place,
wearing homemade paper deer's ears on a head band, in hope, said
her mother, of becoming an acceptable playmate to the deer that
grazed on their lawn.
</P>
<P>
   Before Beethoven's String Quartet in E flat major (Op. 74), the
children were told to raise their hands whenever they heard music
that sounded like a harp, and a forest of hands went up each time
the strings were plucked in the pizzicato arpeggios of the first
movement.
</P>
<P>
   At the end, Hung-Wei Huang, 19, a violist from Taipei, asked his
fellow musicians to demonstrate the high and low notes of each
instrument and the finger position that results in a vibrato sound.
</P>
<P>
   By then summer breezes wafting through the windows beckoned
everyone outside again, and the young artists packed their
instruments and set out to explore. Their first stop was the post
office/general store for ice cream before the trek along narrow
roads to the Coast Guard beach on the Atlantic side, where, among
rocks and rugosa roses, they wandered and chatted in groups _ a
Winslow Homer come to life.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting on the beach, Wilson Pedrazas, 27, a violinist from
Peru, talked about the difficulties the players sometimes
experience during practice. ``It is a kind of marriage of from
three to five people, and sometimes even good friends can become
nasty during rehearsals,'' he said. Having already won an
international competition and performed as a soloist with the
Brazilian Symphony Orchestra, he is also preparing for a solo
career.
</P>
<P>
   When everyone returned to the Neighborhood House, the buffet
tables were filled with bowls of steaming chowder, casseroles,
platters of cold salmon, salad, blueberry cake and other local
dishes. The entourage was joined by State Sen. Marge Kilkelly, who
is also director of community services for the Island Institute,
which assists Maine island communities in sustaining their
independent way of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are now only 14 islands on the Maine coast with
year-round populations compared to 300 at the turn of the
century,'' she said. Islesford, also known as Little Cranberry, is
in the cluster called the Downeast Islands. Suddenly, the young
women artists began to appear in long floral-patterned skirts they
had tucked into their knapsacks for the free evening performance in
Islesford's 1898 half-shingled, half-clapboard Congregational
Church.
</P>
<P>
   More than 100 people, mostly families with children, attended
the concert, which added Mozart's Viola Quintet in C minor (K. 406)
to the afternoon program. The music sounded full as it resonated
off the wood paneled walls.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an amazing concert; I didn't expect anything so
serious,'' said Dr. Mark Pentecost, visiting from Georgia. There
was resounding applause, and many bows. The invasion had been a
success.
</P>
<P>
   But this evening, when the young artists returned to the dock
under a sky streaked with red, they were in high spirits. All the
seriousness was gone as they laughed and joked all the way home on
the ferry, and the lights on the island faded into the distance
across the dark waters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-98 1758EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
