<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: UNIVERSITY SUES OVER A FILM; AWARD FOR SANDRA
BULLOCK; PBS BEGINS GOING DIGITAL; `POWER PLAYS' CAST CHANGES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The American University in Cairo is suing the chief censor of
the Egyptian government for permitting the release of a film that
it says uses the university's name without permission. The suit,
filed on Thursday, seeks to pull the hit comedy ``A Saidi at
American University,'' out of theaters in Egypt and to have its
posters taken down.
</P>
<P>
   The film, directed by Said Hamed, tells the story of a peasant
who gets a scholarship to the university, which is portrayed as a
sanctum of the upper class.
</P>
<P>
   The chief censor of Egypt, Ali Abu Shadi, told the news service
Agence France-Presse that he considered the suit frivolous. ``There
is nothing in this film that hurts AUC,'' he said, referring to the
university. He added that the suit ``only gives the film more
publicity.''
</P>
<P>
   Who Needs Critics?
</P>
<P>
   She may be in a professional slump, but Sandra Bullock is still
on top in Canada. The Montreal World Film Festival has announced
that the actress will receive a career excellence award at the
festival on Sept. 6.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bullock, who received lukewarm reviews this summer for
``Hope Floats,'' was chosen because ``she's quite a popular actress
here,'' said Lorraine Jamison, a spokeswoman for the festival.
``She is somebody that the people of Montreal would like to meet,''
Ms. Jamison added. The festival, which will also include a tribute
to the Swedish director Ingmar Bergman, runs from Aug. 27 to Sept.
7.
</P>
<P>
   Going Digital
</P>
<P>
   The Corporation for Public Broadcasting announced Monday that it
would establish a program to encourage producers to integrate
digital technology into offerings for public television.
</P>
<P>
   The program, which will begin awarding grants this year, is to
focus on two applications of the technology: enhanced television,
which allows large amounts of supplemental information to be
incorporated into the screen, and multicasting, which involves
broadcasting multiple channels on a single signal. Federal laws
mandate that public television networks switch to digital
broadcasting by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Incoming
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On the set of ``Power Plays,'' the Alan Arkin and
Elaine May comedy at the Promenade Theater in Manhattan, it seems
that the best way to replace one ``Catch-22'' veteran is to simply
find another.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 22, Richard Benjamin, who played Major Danby in the
1970 film version of Joseph Heller's novel ``Catch-22,'' will step
in for Arkin, who played the war-maddened bombardier Yossarian.
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin will be joined in the cast by his wife, Paula Prentiss,
who is replacing Ms. May. The show, which opened in May, will take
a vacation before the changeover, going dark from Sept. 13 to 21.
Jeannie Berlin and Anthony Arkin, Alan Arkin's son, will remain in
the cast.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-98 1759EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980817.0275 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-17 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7937 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWSSTAND18-COX     08-17 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSSTAND18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mother Jones hopes makeover will appeal to a younger crowd
 &HT;    By Don O'Braint
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even bell bottoms go out of style eventually. After 22 years as
the counterculture voice of political activism, Mother Jones
($3.95) has gotten a makeover.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to broaden the magazine's appeal among readers who are
looking for a hip, substantive alternative to the increasingly
celebrity-driven media,'' says publisher Jay Harris. In other
words, the publisher wants younger readers.
</P>
<P>
   The September/October issue is a giant step in the right
direction. Graphics are bolder, colors are brighter, and the
reporting is irreverent. The cover story on Rupert Murdoch is
presented as a tabloid pullout with typical tab headlines: ``World
Domination Plot Exposed! World-Class Tax Dodger!'' Reporter Zev
Borow tracks Murdoch's empire building and concludes that he is
successful because of his political connections and emphasis on TV
sports programming.
</P>
<P>
   BAD TIMING: This week's newsmagazines were caught in the awkward
position of writing about what President Clinton was going to say
to the grand jury before he said it. Time ($2.95) hedged its bets
by examining the damage the scandal will have on the presidency _
and the media. ``I'm filled with disgust with what has become of
this country,'' says journalism scholar Todd Gitlin, ``and I hold
the media crucially responsible.'' As for the presidency, Time
notes that the right man or woman can go a long way toward
restoring the mystique of the office, just as Ronald Reagan did.
</P>
<P>
   In Newsweek ($2.95), Jonathan Alter compares Clinton to a
political Dr. Jekyll and Mr. Hyde. One Clinton ``uses the English
language with obvious skill to comfort, as he did once again last
week when the bodies of the American victims of the Africa bombings
came home. The other uses it with obvious slickness to confuse.
...'' Meanwhile, a Newsweek poll taken on the eve of Clinton's
testimony indicated that only 29 percent of the public believes the
president should be impeached.
</P>
<P>
   LIFE WITH LINDBERGH: In kindergarten, Reeve Lindbergh thought
her father was God. Why else, she reasoned, did she call him Father
when her friends called their fathers Daddy? And why did she have
to eat Pepperidge Farm bread rather than Wonder bread? In a
poignant essay in The New Yorker ($3.95), the daughter of the
famous aviator describes a regimented life with a man who always
had to be in control. He was as meticulous with his family as he
was with his airplanes, she writes, maintaining detailed checklists
for each child. ``He exercised affection and discipline in like
measure, often at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   HOT STAR: With an Oscar in hand for ``Good Will Hunting'' and an
upcoming role in Cormac McCarthy's ``All the Pretty Horses,'' Matt
Damon has not done too badly as a Harvard dropout. His biggest
burden, says Steven Daly in a Details ($2.50) profile, is his image
as a regular guy. Well, a regular guy who's involved with Winona
Ryder.
</P>
<P>
   SOCIAL SCENE: Forget about dinner and a movie. Atlanta magazine
($3.50) suggests 41 ideas for great dates, including a sunrise or
sunset balloon ride or a Martinis &AMP; Imax evening at Fernbank Museum
of Natural History. Also of note in this issue: A visit with TV
chef Nathalie Dupree at her new home in Social Circle and a road
trip to the North Carolina resort town of Highlands.
</P>
<P>
   COVER STORIES: You expect nudity in Playboy and Penthouse, but
some magazine covers have stretched the limits of good taste. The
current issue of Vanity Fair features an actress wearing
transparent lingerie, and the Aug. 20 issue of Rolling Stone ($3)
showcases model Laetitia Casta wearing a seductive expression and
nothing else. Inside the magazine (Yes, you have to turn the cover)
is a ``hot list'' of people and trends. Hot actress? Christina
Ricci. Hot TV? On-air funerals of celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
