<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-17 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7938 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLD-YOUNG-COX     08-17 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLD-YOUNG-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Older women dating younger men is still rare, but is starting to
gain momentum
 &HT;    By Alma E. Hill
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Terry McMillan plans to keep her groove on.
</P>
<P>
   Like Stella, the central character in her novel turned movie
``How Stella Got Her Groove Back,'' McMillan is engaged to a stud
muffin she met in Jamaica.
</P>
<P>
   No, she isn't worried about how long the relationship will last.
And, yes, she's using her 46 years of wisdom to keep her romance
with a guy in his ``mid-20s'' in perspective.
</P>
<P>
   McMillan and Jonathan Plummer, who makes a cameo appearance in
the movie, have been an item for three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we get three more good years, it's still three more years
of happiness I've had that I wouldn't have had if I hadn't given
myself permission to do it,'' McMillan said from California. ``Our
attitude is: `Yeah, we're going to get married. However long it
lasts, it lasts.'''
</P>
<P>
   Men have been bedding and wedding women half their age since the
beginning of time, and Hollywood has been depicting such romances
for almost as long.
</P>
<P>
   But when women hook up with guys they could have burped and
diapered, in life or on the screen, people whisper.
</P>
<P>
   Some movie critics, for example, find it a little unbelievable
that Stella, a woman who has everything, would fall for a youngster
whose biggest asset is his biceps.
</P>
<P>
   ``High-powered stockbrokers with six-digit salaries don't risk
it all for a mere hunk,'' writes critic Karen Hershenson of the
Contra Costa Times in Walnut Creek, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stella's retrieval of her groove is totally dependent on her
surrendering herself to this youthful sexual fantasy, and it's
inconsistent with the smart, grounded ... corporate trader we see
in the first half-hour,'' carps Sara Voorhees of The Albuquerque
(N.M.) Tribune.
</P>
<P>
   Hershenson and Voorhees obviously haven't met women like Terry
McMillan _ who are smart and grounded, but also in love with
younger men.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think times have changed,'' McMillan said. ``I'm in a
position where I don't need a man to pay my mortgage or car
payment. I'm in a position where I can like anybody I want to.''
</P>
<P>
   She is not alone. But relationships like hers are still the
exception.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, according to the Census Bureau, at least 379,000 of
the 57.1 million married or live-in couples nationwide were women
with men at least 10 years younger.
</P>
<P>
   The older-man relationship is still more common, of course. In
1997, more than 2.1 million men were with women at least 10 years
their junior.
</P>
<P>
   Relationship experts say that when older women date younger men,
the woman is the trophy _ not the man.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can attract a young guy then you're pretty hot,'' said
Lillian Glass, a New York psychologist who wrote ``He Says/She
Says: Closing the Communication Gap Between the Sexes'' (Putnam,
$9.95).
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're an older guy and you're with a young woman, it's no
big deal. If you have money, you could look like Frankenstein and
they'll go with you.''
</P>
<P>
   With some exceptions, young men aren't looking for a sugar mama
when they date older women, Glass said. The chemistry typically
stems from the older woman's uninhibited sexuality, her maturity,
her willingness to mingle with his friends and try new things and
her ability to communicate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The generation of the Betty Friedans raised some amazing boys
... who treat women like ladies. They're not going to go with a
Monica Lewinsky type _ a woman who has no skills but is looking to
get ahead on someone else's coattails. They're looking for somebody
with substance and intelligence. Not that spoiled princess type,''
Glass said.
</P>
<P>
   Older women, on the other hand, admire younger men for all the
qualities older men often lack, she added.
</P>
<P>
   For example, young guys don't tend to be as rigid about gender
roles as men their fathers' age, because they are more accustomed
to working with women as equals in the workplace, Glass said. They
also are more malleable, not as set in their ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``Younger men have more energy to do sports, to dance, to have
sex with. ... He hasn't been jaded by life,'' said Joan Irvine, a
former matchmaker in Marina del Rey, Calif., who co-wrote a book
titled ``Recipes for Hot Sex'' (Lions' Head, $9.99).
</P>
<P>
   McMillan's muse seems to be all that, and a bag of chips.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jonathan is teaching me how to swim,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has forced me to slow down and take two hours in the middle
of the day to read a book and not feel guilty about it. He'll say,
`Terry, forget about the laundry. Forget about cooking. Let's go
out to dinner, let's go for a walk.' He braids my hair. He's not
intimidated by me in the least. He's very, very open.''
</P>
<P>
   McMillan said being with a man so much younger has also given
her a chance to experience a part of life she forgot.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, part of the beauty of it is, I've been given an
opportunity to look at things a second time that I either glossed
over or overlooked or was moving too fast to pay attention to. It's
kinda nice,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Plummer was not available for comment.
</P>
<P>
   In the movie, Stella and her young beau, Winston Shakespeare,
play a joke on a flirtatious bartender who thinks they are mother
and son. McMillan, whose own son, Solomon, is 14, said she and
Plummer get the same kind of questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever someone says, `What does your son want?' we just kind
of play it off, and I'll say, `Son, what are you having?' It's a
private joke between us.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Angela Bassett, who plays Stella, McMillan says she's in
good shape physically and isn't worried that she will age or that
Plummer will find a woman his age more attractive.
</P>
<P>
   But again, she's keeping things in perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chances are, he's going to meet a younger woman. That's fine.
I could also meet someone. But right now, we have each other,''
McMillan said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the movie was based on the book, which is as close to
an autobiography as McMillan has ever written, she said there are
few similarities between how she fell in love with Plummer and the
couple in ``How Stella Got Her Groove Back.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, McMillan said with a laugh, ``My version was better
than the movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
