<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SURFER18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lifetime unviels its ``Man-Free TV'' lineup
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Women have needs, too.
</P>
<P>
   TV needs, that is. Whadja think we were talking about? Sex?
Careers? Even, God forbid, the occasional cigarette?
</P>
<P>
   All that and more is covered in three series debuting tonight on
Lifetime _ but that's hardly what matters about the cable network's
``Original Tuesdays.''
</P>
<P>
   This is Man-Free TV, the way the small screen world undoubtedly
would look if women wore all the programming pants.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that men don't exist in these shows. They just don't
matter as much. The focus is on 40-something females facing
real-life dilemmas that would never pass through that funky purple
front door on ``Friends.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, some of it is unreal (C'mon, a recurring Jack Wagner
fantasy?). And some is just plain dumb (Jack's black velour top).
But any minute now on ESPN (owned, like Lifetime, by Disney), the
``World's Strongest Man'' contest is starting, so it's all pretty
much the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   And it's about damn time.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Any Day Now'' 9 p.m. EDT Call it ``I'll Fly Back.'' And not
just because this hour drama puts a human face (albeit through
flashbacks) on the civil rights era.
</P>
<P>
   Single, successful D.C. attorney Rene (Lorraine Toussaint) goes
home to 1998 Birmingham after her father's death. There, she sees
her childhood best friend, Mary Elizabeth (Annie Potts), now a wife
and mother.
</P>
<P>
   Rene decides to stay, but first, the duo picks at 25 years worth
of emotional scabs that underscore two things about being female:
No one can betray you worse or support you better than your best
friend.
</P>
<P>
   That Rene is black and her pal ``M.E.'' white both enriches and
complicates this saga. A scene in which young Rene boards a bus
twice _ once to pay and once to sit in the rear _ is silent and
heartbreaking. But too many flashbacks could detract from the main
story.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever that is. From romantic breakups to unemployed husbands,
there's too much going on. Thanks to Toussaint and Potts, it never
deteriorates into melodrama, but any day now, producers might want
to focus more.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Maggie'' 10 p.m. EDT Here's what we learn: Cartoons, this
show tells you, are funny; ``Maggie,'' you find out on your own,
isn't.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, Maggie (Ann Cusack) has too many problems,
including turning 40, going to vet school, being ignored by her
husband and lusting for a co-worker at the animal clinic. Whew! All
that's missing is a crazed stalker. (Although if ``Melrose
Place's'' Wagner shows up in Maggie's fantasies many more times
...)
</P>
<P>
   Here's an idea. Dump the husband (John Getz), a cardiologist so
lifeless he must've been cast from his hospital's morgue. Set
things in the clinic, where the situations _ a fish having
nightmares _ and people are funny.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what you're thinking: I'm too good for him,''
receptionist Amy (Melissa Samuels) says of a date who tastes all 12
of his cats' food. ``But I had a long talk with my mother, and it
turns out I'm not.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Amy can't do any better. But ``Maggie'' could.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Oh Baby'' 10:30 p.m. EDT Oh boy. Do we really think women
are waking up and saying, ``Omigod, I forgot to have a baby!''?
</P>
<P>
   Tracy (Cynthia Stevenson) does. Talking to the camera, like it's
secret-sharing time at the school locker, she tells us why she's
been artificially inseminated.
</P>
<P>
   It's all the usual stuff: Not getting an engagement ring from
the boyfriend she's consistently lied to about wanting to stay
single. Baby clothes that are s-o-o cute. Something about office
collections.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing, meanwhile, about love, wanting to produce the next
Albert Schweitzer or carrying on the family genes. So why is this
show still so annoyingly appealing?
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, it's Stevenson, who's funny (she says of dating for 22
years: ``No one should have to be polite for that long''). And
sweet when talking about what could be her ``only chance to make
(my) own family.''
</P>
<P>
   We'll give her the first trimester.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
