<SLUG> BC-CHINA-INDONESIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDENT, WOMEN GROUPS PROTEST ABUSE AGAINST CHINESE DURING
INDONESIA RIOTS  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Students and women's groups held emotional protests
Monday over the looting, killing and rape directed against ethnic
Chinese during riots in Indonesia in May.
</P>
<P>
   The rioting in Indonesia originally received only cursory media
coverage in China. It was not until this month, when two Chinese
newspapers published photo essays showing the violence, that the
issue was thrust before the Chinese public.
</P>
<P>
   Those reports have prompted anger directed primarily at
Indonesia's leaders. But China's government and its official press
have also been criticized by some citizens who say they should have
reacted sooner and with greater force.
</P>
<P>
   Both a women's group and students from Beijing University had
applied to the Public Security Bureau for permission to hold
organized demonstrations Monday, Indonesian Independence Day, and
were turned down.
</P>
<P>
   But individuals from both groups went ahead with events that
were small but had a powerful impact, contending they were not
organized demonstrations. It was an unusual move in a city where
political demonstrations are tightly controlled.
</P>
<P>
   Though tiny by comparison, the student protests were the largest
since the pro-democracy demonstrations of 1989 in Tiananmen Square.
</P>
<P>
   At a hotel banquet room in central Beijing decorated with
feminist slogans and pictures of women who had been reported raped
and tortured, 150 people attended a protest meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than 10,000 demonstrated in Hong Kong _ more than 10,000
signatures were collected in New York,'' Zhao Shuqing, a television
news reporter who wore a yellow ribbon in support of the ethnic
Chinese Indonesians, said at the meeting. ``And I wondered, what
has mainland China done in this matter?''
</P>
<P>
   At the Indonesian Embassy in Beijing's trendy Sanlitun district
Monday, small groups of somber looking university students, also
wearing yellow ribbons, arrived throughout the morning to protest
the abuse, each in its own way.
</P>
<P>
   A group of several dozen from Beijing University staged a short
sit-in outside the ambassador's residence and presented a T-shirt
signed by more than 100 students protesting the atrocities. Others
unfurled posters bearing grisly photographs that have appeared in
the Chinese press in the last week. Two groups also presented
petitions to the embassy last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came spontaneously,'' said a young man who would identify
himself only by his surname, Xiong, and who said he is an
undergraduate at Beijing University. ``This was not organized. It
was a matter of conscience,''
</P>
<P>
   Security was heavy, with far more police officers than students
lining the street outside the embassy.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights groups have said 1,200 people were killed and 150
women raped in the riots in Jakarta, the Indonesian capital, in
addition to the widespread looting of Chinese businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The ethnic violence in Indonesia, as well as the protests in
Beijing, presents a quandary to Chinese officials. China's longtime
policy has been not to meddle in the affairs of other countries and
not to tolerate other countries' meddling in its affairs,
particularly when human rights is involved.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as China has grown as a regional power, it has begun to
shed its traditional isolationism. With world outrage growing over
the reports of abuse of the ethnic Chinese in Indonesia, the
Chinese government started in mid-July to lodge protests, which
have grown louder over time. In a recent editorial, the Communist
Party newspaper, The People's Daily, urged the Indonesian leaders
to ``punish the criminals strictly.''
</P>
<P>
   Although both the women's group and the students had to sidestep
the authorities somewhat to get their message out, they also
received some support from the government. Officials passed on a
student petition protesting the violence to the Indonesian
government, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   After women from the China Women's News were denied permission
to demonstrate, some of them reserved a banquet room in the Qi Lu
Hotel for an event they called Intellectual Women of the Capital
Voicing their Support for the Ethnic Chinese Victims of Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   Just before the speeches were to start, the hotel managers
became alarmed and asked the organizers if they had official
permission. The organizers replied that none was needed since it
was not a demonstration. In the end, the hotel allowed them to stay
_ as long as the hotel's name on the stage was covered.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chinese media didn't act quickly enough when the riots
broke out,'' Zhang Kangkang, a well-known author, said at the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no human rights under a dictatorial government,''
she said later. ``This is a point we must realize.''
</P>
<P>
   The students also ultimately had their say. On Saturday, a huge
poster appeared on the Beijing University campus with a letter of
protest addressed to the Indonesian ambassador in Beijing. It
quickly gathered 1,500 signatures, at a time when the university is
not even in session.
</P>
<P>
   University officials from around Beijing were summoned to a
meeting during the weekend where they were instructed not to permit
demonstrations to leave campus.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday students slipped out from Beijing University and
Qinghua University in dribs and drabs and made their way to the
Indonesian Embassy for their protests.
</P>
<P>
   The hundreds of police officers generally allowed the students
to briefly make their point, then politely urged them to go home.
But the police presence was intimidating. Representatives from the
women's meeting who had intended to deliver a letter to the
Indonesian ambassador turned back and decided to fax it instead.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
