<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DESIGNS-LEVI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESIGNS TO BUT 25 STORES FROM LEVI STRAUS UNIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After reporting another quarterly loss, Designs Inc. said Monday
it plans to acquire 25 outlet stores from a subsidiary of Levi
Strauss &AMP; Co. as part of an ongoing turnaround strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Designs, a Needham, Mass. retail chain that relies heavily on
Levi's denim clothing, said it has agreed to pay $12 million for
nine Levi's Outlet stores and 16 Dockers Outlet stores.
</P>
<P>
   For Levi's, the sale is a chance to exit the outlet business and
stress urban stores that showcase its gear as a fashion brand. For
Designs, which operates 121 stores in five different formats, the
sale is a chance to grow the store group that has fared better than
any other of its retail divisions.
</P>
<P>
   Designs operates 70 stores in a Levi's outlet format, including
some as joint ventures with Levi Strauss; the proposed sale will
position Design as the largest US operator of outlet stores that
offer the Levi's and Dockers brands, said Designs president and
chief executive Joel H. Reichman.
</P>
<P>
   The sale would partly offset revenues lost from closing 36
underperforming stores over the last 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the troubles at Designs can be traced to Levi's, whose
jeans are now viewed as old hat by some young consumers. Meanwhile,
other consumers have passed up Levi's to buy cheaper jeans that
department stores sell under their own brand names.
</P>
<P>
   At Designs, such trends have hurt the bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Designs reported a loss of $3.1 million on sales of
$47.1 million for the quarter ended Aug. 1; at stores open for at
least a year, sales dropped 23 percent. For the same quarter last
year, Designs lost $16.6 million on sales of $64.5 million when it
operated far more stores.
</P>
<P>
   Designs said it's poised for a 1999 turnaround. Levi's jeans
have fallen out of fashion before, only to rebound strongly.
Designs is counting on that happening again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still too early for them to have an evidence of a
turnaround; they're still in transition,'' said president Ward
Mooney of BankBoston Retail Finance Inc., which extended a $50
million line of revolving credit to Designs in June.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday's proposed acquisition should be ``a postive'' for
Designs, Mooney added.
</P>
<P>
   On Nasdaq, shares of Designs were up 1/32 to close at 1 5/32.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-98 1802EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
