A7950 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRANE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT     08-17 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRANE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BADGE OF COURAGE': STEPHEN CRANE, MAKING REAL A WAR HE NEVER
FOUGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Publication notes are at end of review.) 
(nk) 
 By HERBERT MITGANG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Reading a new biography of Stephen Crane, you wonder what fresh
insights it offers about ``The Red Badge of Courage'' and the
story's relevance today. How does that Civil War novel hold up
against the blood-red images of real warfare, from Kosovo to
Normandy, in print and on film, at the end of this dying century?
The novel's opening paragraph, one of the most stunning in American
literature, hints at the answer and demands rereading:
</P>
<P>
   ``The cold passed reluctantly from the earth and the retiring
fogs revealed an army stretched out on the hills, resting. As the
landscape changed from brown to green the army awakened and began
to tremble with eagerness at the noise of rumors. It cast its eyes
upon the roads which were growing from long troughs of liquid mud
to proper thoroughfares. A river, amber-tinted in the shadow of its
banks, purled at the army's feet and at night when the stream had
become of a sorrowful blackness one could see, across, the red
eye-like gleam of hostile camp-fires set in the low brows of
distant hills.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon the armies of the night confront each other and men fall in
``grotesque agonies'' under a red sun that is ``pasted in the sky
like a fierce wafer,'' memorable phrases that appear in Crane's
masterpiece. (The word ``fierce'' was excised by the publisher in
the 1895 edition; I am quoting from the authentic 1982 Norton
edition of the restored novel, which follows the original
manuscript.) It's still a source of wonder that Crane, who was born
six years after the end of the Civil War, could imagine it so
vividly.
</P>
<P>
   But more than his imagination was at work. He studied the
memoirs of Union Army veterans in the Century and other magazines.
And as a freelance writer for various newspapers, he covered the
front lines of life in the lower depths of New York, a battlefield
of its own in the 1890s.
</P>
<P>
   One of the welcome facts we learn from Linda H. Davis'
well-documented biography is that Crane's opening paragraph
practically wrote itself. He told Hamlin Garland, the generous
fellow writer who helped him simplify the novel's characters, that
the language came to him with ``every word in place, every comma,
every period fixed.'' To his artist friend, Corwin Linson, he said
it was as if he were taking dictation, writing ``throughout with
the unhesitating speed of one who did not have to contrive incident
or think it through at all; it was simply the labor of writing.''
</P>
<P>
   The labor of writing. Much of Crane's prose was hurried and
uneven, produced for Grub Street to survive; yet behind the hack
work hovered an idealist who wanted to break out of the narrow
newspaper columns and say something larger about human nature. At
his best, Crane did so in fiction by creating realistic
individuals, just as the muckrakers did reportorially in McClure's
magazine before and after the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
   In his first novel, ``Maggie: A Girl of the Streets,'' which he
paid a New York job printer to produce, Crane exposed prostitution.
In ``The Red Badge of Courage,'' he made a bitter statement about
the physical and psychological horrors of war. The ``red badge''
symbolized two different things in the story: for one character, it
was a deadly wound; for another, a wound of conscience. In ``Red
Badge,'' Crane calls war ``the red animal _ the blood-swollen
god.'' He proves that any authentic war novel _ in any country's
literature _ is perforce an antiwar novel.
</P>
<P>
   For Crane fans, Ms. Davis describes the origins of his work in
loving detail. She is a diligent researcher, building on much
earlier scholarship and original sources, including Crane's
correspondence with editors, agents and publishers. Her previous
biography, ``Onward and Upward,'' was about Katharine S. White, who
had been a revered editor at The New Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Badge of Courage'' leaves the impression that Crane's own life
as a street reporter, war correspondent, novelist and aspiring bon
vivant was perhaps his most original piece of work. Stephen Crane
was more or less married to Cora Crane, the madam of the most
elegant ``sporting house'' in Jacksonville, Fla., which had an
inviting name, the Hotel de Dream.
</P>
<P>
   Cora nursed Stephen back to health after he had been
shipwrecked, went off with him as a correspondent in her own right
to the Greco-Turkish War in 1897, then became the hostess of an
English manor house. With more fame than money, they somehow
entertained Joseph Conrad, H.G. Wells and Henry James, all admirers
of Crane's Civil War novel. Ms. Davis quotes Wells on Crane: ``I do
not think that American criticism has yet done justice to the
unsurpassable beauty of Crane's best writing.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to think of an American author who matched Crane's
accomplishments in a 10-year career. He turned out a series of
novels, short stories, poetry and daring journalism before dying of
tuberculosis at the age of 28 in 1900. In addition to ``Maggie''
and ``Red Badge of Courage,'' several of Crane's stories _ ``The
Open Boat,'' ``The Blue Hotel,'' ``The Bride Comes to Yellow Sky''
_ have become part of the American literary canon. Had Crane lived,
wrote A.J. Liebling in a 1961 New Yorker piece, he ``might have
been the great correspondent that the First World War failed to
produce.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, his labors left him a poor man. As Ms. Davis tells us:
``In four years Stephen had published five novels, two volumes of
poetry, three big story collections, two books of war stories, and
countless works of short fiction and reporting. And yet in three
years he had earned just over $1,200 for his entire American
output, at a time when the country's per capita income was $1,200
annually.'' Crane told a friend that he couldn't afford a
typewriter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Badge of Courage'' bears the burden of a rather obvious and
ambiguous title. But Ms. Davis has written an impressive biography,
with many fascinating facts about Crane's rough-and-tumble career,
series of romantic liaisons and adventurous writing. The book helps
to call attention to the realism in Crane's own life. By chasing
wars as a newspaper correspondent, he strove to prove the validity
of his imagined stories. In a remarkable turnabout _ fact following
fiction _ Crane told Conrad that he went to war to see if his ``Red
Badge'' was right.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `BADGE OF COURAGE: The Life of Stephen Crane'
</P>
<P>
   By Linda H. Davis
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 414 pages. Houghton Mifflin Co. $35.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
