<DOCNO> NYT19980817.0289 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-17 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7957 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COX-CLINTON-SCENE     08-17 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-CLINTON-SCENE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THE SCENE FROM THE WHITE HOUSE FENCE AND PEBBLE BEACH
 &HT;    PHOTOS are available in the National Folder on the server.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ America's scandal-driven media circus moved from
Monica Beach to Pebble Beach on Monday as correspondents, shaded by
golf umbrellas, stood on a patch of crushed gravel on the White
House grounds and speculated on what President Clinton might be
telling independent counsel Kenneth Starr inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know nothing, but the imperative is to say something,''
conceded veteran ABC newsman Sam Donaldson in the early afternoon
as several colleagues reported nearby about the on-going,
closed-door interrogation of the president.
</P>
<P>
   By testifying to a federal grand jury from the White House Map
Room via closed-circuit TV, Clinton shifted the scandal focus away
from Monica Beach, the name photographers have given the sunny
sidewalks and plazas outside the E. Everett Prettyman U.S.
Courthouse where former White House intern Monica Lewinsky and
other witnesses have testified over the past seven months.
</P>
<P>
   On this steamy August afternoon, the action _ at least what the
public could see _ was at Pebble Beach, the name those ever-glib
photographers have given the rocky area designed to spare the north
lawn as camera crews set up and TV correspondents perform
``stand-ups'' with the White House in the background.
</P>
<P>
   A sense of history and of humidity hung over the scene as scores
of sweaty tourists stood outside 1600 Pennsylvania Avenue and
peered through the wrought-iron fence to the familiar building
where, for the first time, a president was testifying to a criminal
grand jury investigating his own actions. Impromptu sidewalk
debates were as hot as the weather.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're having our own 'Crossfire','' said Matt Focht of
Rockville, Md., referring to the weeknight political debate program
on CNN. ``This is a defining moment,'' he said. ``I want the
president to tell the truth and to have the character to accept the
consequences of that truth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I support Monica,'' said Karen O'Shea of Hoboken, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   ``What? That woman is twisted,'' retorted Michael Rogers of
Washington, D.C. ``You don't save clothing with stains from sexual
encounters.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a young woman, very vulnerable to men of power,
particularly presidential power,'' said O'Shea. ``I compare her to
a groupie. So when she made it with the president, she kept a
souvenir.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just got to 'fess up and tell the truth,'' said Yolanda
Treiguts, a self-described ``lifelong Democrat'' visiting from
Chicago. ``Then I think the people will forgive him.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, forgiveness might be unlikely from the group of people on
the sidewalk dressed in overcoats and wool scarves to ward off the
``snow job'' they said Clinton has pulled on the populace. And
there was little sympathy for the president from the folks handing
out peaches _ symbolizing ``impeachment'' _ and carrying signs that
said ``Honk If You Want to Impeach Clinton.'' They were from the
Council of Volunteer Americans, which has been protesting Clinton's
ethics for the past several years.
</P>
<P>
   Starr had his detractors, too, with signs comparing his
investigation to McCarthyism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a witch hunt with the independent counsel and the
media out to get him,'' said Emoke Pelay, a student from
Fayetteville, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the White House briefing room, UPI reporter Helen Thomas,
dean of the press corps, said she had only seen this kind of
atmosphere a handful of times in a career stretching back to the
Kennedy administration.
</P>
<P>
   ''It resembles Watergate and the end of the Vietnam War,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 200 journalists, four times the usual number, showed up
the morning ``gaggle'' _ an informal briefing _ and prompted
presidential press secretary Michael McCurry to speak in the White
House briefing room rather than from his office desk.
</P>
<P>
   McCurry acknowledged the difficulty of the day, describing how
Chief of Staff Erskine Bowles had already instructed aides in ``the
importance of sticking together.''
</P>
<P>
   McCurry said Bowles recalled a lesson he learned from his father
while growing up in North Carolina: ``It's easy to be there for
someone when they're up. But it's the good ones who are there for
you when you're down.''
</P>
<P>
   (Washington Correspondents Bob Deans and Danielle Shook also
contributed to this story)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
