<HEADLINE>
JURY SELECTION BEGINS IN 32-YEAR-OLD KLAN MURDER CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CURTIS WILKIE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HATTIESBURG, Miss. _ Jury selection began Monday in the fourth
trial of Sam Bowers, the 73-year-old imperial wizard of the White
Knights of the Ku Klux Klan, more than three decades after he was
first accused of the murder of Vernon Dahmer, the president of the
local chapter of the NAACP.
</P>
<P>
   After prosecutors said that they had new evidence that
identified Bowers as the man who ordered Dahmer's slaying in 1966,
the state moved to revive the case earlier this year. Bowers, a
Klan leader in neighboring Jones County, is accused of dispatching
two carloads of ``night riders'' who firebombed Dahmer's house to
punish him for his activism in registering black voters.
</P>
<P>
   Dahmer, a prominent Mississippi civil rights activist, died from
burns he suffered in the fire.
</P>
<P>
   Bowers and a dozen other Klansmen were charged in the case
shortly after the attack. Three men were convicted, but Bowers'
three trials in the 1960s resulted in mistrials. He served six
years in federal prison for an unrelated conviction growing out of
the 1964 murders of three civil rights workers in Neshoba County,
Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   Bowers was in the courtroom Monday as the new proceedings began,
wearing a worn suit and sporting two Mickey Mouse buttons in his
lapel. He refused to speak to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   As he entered the courthouse, District Attorney Lindsay Carter
said, ``We're trying to get some closure in this matter for the
Dahmer family. They deserve it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dahmer's son, Vernon Jr., was on hand as Circuit Judge Richard
McKenzie began the tedious job of selecting a panel of 12 jurors
and two alternates from several hundred residents called for duty.
McKenzie sought to establish a comfortable environment in the
courtroom with gentle jokes and comment that provoked laughter from
a racially-mixed group of potential jurors. But outside, two
pickets carried signs that said: ``White Revolution is the only
solution.''
</P>
<P>
   By mid-afternoon, McKenzie had excused a handful of prospective
jurors who said they were convinced of Bowers' guilt or expressed
concern over political pressure that forced the Klan leader to
trial again.
</P>
<P>
   The judge said he expected more than a week of testimony.
</P>
</TEXT>
