<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-17 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7968 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DNA-TESTING-BILLBOARD     08-17 0651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DNA-TESTING-BILLBOARD-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILLBOARD FOR DNA TESTING CREATES DOUBTS ABOUT PATERNITY, CRITICS
SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DONALD BRADLEY  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (KANSAS CITY, Mo.) _ The little boy, 6, looked just like his
daddy.
</P>
<P>
   The little girl, 3, did not. So the divorced Johnson County,
Kan. man loaded the girl in his car and told her they were going to
the dentist to get their teeth cleaned.
</P>
<P>
   Instead he took her to a Kansas City, Mo., laboratory where a
worker took a cotton ``cheek swab'' from both their mouths. A test
would compare their DNA and determine whether the girl was really
the man's daughter.
</P>
<P>
   The idea came from a billboard the man saw alongside Interstate
70. The sign at the Jackson curve east of downtown asks in big
letters, ``Who's The Father? Call 1-800-DNA-TYPE.''
</P>
<P>
   Identigene, based in Houston, apparently has hit an untapped
market.
</P>
<P>
   With its billboards in Kansas City and 23 other cities
nationwide, the company is peddling DNA paternity tests _
traditionally a legal procedure.
</P>
<P>
   There's even a home kit so customers don't have to go to a lab.
They just mail in the cotton swabs.
</P>
<P>
   The company boasts that the test, which costs about $600, is
quick and 99.9 percent accurate.
</P>
<P>
   Business is booming, Identigene president Caroline Caskey said.
She founded the company five years ago based on a technology called
polymerase chain reaction that was developed by her father, a
geneticist.
</P>
<P>
   Before the billboard promotion, the company did about 40 tests a
week.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's doing 175.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to do about 9,000 this year,'' Caskey said.
</P>
<P>
   But she's heard from critics who think the billboard pitch is a
little tacky.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Carl Herbster, pastor of Tri-City Ministries in Blue
Springs, Mo., isn't so much bothered by the billboard as he is the
appeal the tests seem to have.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tragic that we've come to this level of immorality in our
society,'' Herbster said. ``It shows the distrust that we have in
relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   Caskey said that complaints, mostly from Christian
conservatives, have come from most cities where the billboards are
used.
</P>
<P>
   ``They prefer not to see that kind of sign on the side of a
freeway,'' Caskey said. ``They say they don't want their children
to read that.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Family Research Council in Washington wonders how many
seeds of doubt are planted by Identigene's billboards.
</P>
<P>
   ``People drive to work and they see that billboard and it gets
them to thinking something they never would have suspected
otherwise,'' said Kristin Hansen, spokeswoman for the council,
which monitors family issues relating to public policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this company is playing on fears and suspicions that
probably aren't valid. And it's probably breaking up some
families.''
</P>
<P>
   But Caskey said that she's responding to market demand.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki Breen, a Kansas City lawyer who specializes in family law,
isn't surprised that people are calling Identigene. She handles a
lot of child custody cases and has witnessed a lot of suspicions
and doubts.
</P>
<P>
   What prevented those parents in the past from pursuing DNA tests
was their hesitancy to subject a child to needles and blood.
</P>
<P>
   ``By using the cheek swab, there's no needle...a child doesn't
even have to know what's going on,'' Breen said.
</P>
<P>
   The Johnson County father, 29, who took his daughter in for the
``teeth cleaning'' had long suspected his former wife of
infidelity. So one day, while visiting his parents, they got out an
old calendar and tried to pinpoint the date of conception.
</P>
<P>
   They concluded that perhaps he wasn't in town those days.
</P>
<P>
   He says he's paying $900 a month in child support to his former
wife.
</P>
<P>
   He should hear the test results this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she's mine _ great,'' he said of the little girl. ``If
she's not, I'll still love her...but it'll save me some money.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
