<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-BOMB-625&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
6 SUSPECTS ARRESTED IN NORTHERN IRELAND ATTACK 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JAMES F. CLARITY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OMAGH, Northern Ireland _ British police arrested six men Monday
in towns near this city for questioning in the car bomb attack here
on Saturday that killed 28 people and injured 220.
</P>
<P>
   The blast, the deadliest in 29 years of sectarian violence in
this predominantly Protestant British province, is widely believed
to have been the work of a group that calls itself the Real IRA, a
splinter group whose members left the Irish Republican Army this
year.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Prime Minister Tony Blair of Britain and Prime
Minister Bertie Ahern of Ireland pledged to hunt down the killers
and made it clear that they thought that the Real IRA was
responsible for the attack. The group is thought to be,
effectively, the military wing of a political splinter group, the
32-County Sovereignty Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The Sovereignty Committee vehemently opposes the new Northern
Ireland peace agreement because it leaves the six northern
counties, which constitute a British province, under British
sovereignty. The group wants those counties subsumed in the
overwhelmingly Roman Catholic Irish Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Two London newspapers reported that the leader of the Real IRA
was a former weapons expert for the Irish Republican Army who
defected after the IRA decided to observe a cease-fire 13 months
ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Royal Ulster Constabulary gave no details about the arrested
suspects. But the identity of one was disclosed by his father, a
leader of the Sovereignty Committee in Omagh.
</P>
<P>
   The father, Francie Mackey, an Omagh City Council member, said
his son, Shane, had been arrested Monday morning. Mackey, a
prominent member of the 32- County Sovereignty Committee, said that
the arrest was harassment and that his son had nothing to do with
the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was sorry for the victims, but declined to condemn
the attack categorically. He also said his group had no links with
the Real IRA.
</P>
<P>
   But security officials in Belfast and Dublin say there is a
connection. The identity of the Real IRA leader has been a matter
of widening public concern since the attack. Several British and
Irish newspapers have said he is believed to be a middle-age man
who lives near Dundalk, Ireland, near the border.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, two London newspapers, The Express and The Daily
Telegraph, named the leader as Michael McKevitt, former IRA weapons
quartermaster. The papers published a photograph of him on their
front pages.
</P>
<P>
   The Telegraph reported that McKevitt lived with a leader of the
Sovereignty Committee, Bernadette Sands. Ms. Sands' brother Bobby
became an IRA hero and martyr in 1981, when he starved himself to
death in a British prison.
</P>
<P>
   The Telegraph said, ``McKevitt was formerly in control of all
IRA arms dumps and the movement of arms, ammunition and explosives
across the border to Northern Ireland.''
</P>
<P>
   When he resigned in October from the IRA, the newspaper said, he
said he would not ``use anything in the IRA arsenal for his own
ends.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sands, who was highly visible in the campaign against the
new peace agreement in May, has issued no statements in recent
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The widespread official view, held by the British and Irish
prime ministers, is that the Real IRA does not have the backing of
the main group. That conclusion is based on intelligence officers'
analysis of the relationship between the main group and the
dissident splinters. In addition, the intelligence assessments are
based on information from Sinn Fein, the political wing of the IRA.
</P>
<P>
   Right-wing Protestant hard-liners assert that the Irish
Republican Army supports the splinter groups. But the Protestant
groups have produced no evidence to support that. They also say
that to them it does not matter whether the IRA is allied with the
splinter groups, that the effect is the same if there is violence.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In Omagh Monday afternoon, several hundred people milled around
and talked quietly near the police barrier that blocked the way to
Market Street, where the bomb exploded. British troops in full
combat uniform, holding automatic rifles at the ready, guarded the
street.
</P>
<P>
   A white-haired Catholic man was looking at the hundreds of
bouquets placed on the sidewalk to express the sympathy of this
town of 27,000, about 70 percent Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   Both Catholics and Protestants were killed in the attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wonder why it should happen,'' a bystander said almost in
a whisper.
</P>
<P>
   A few yards away a Protestant man who would not give his name
because, he said, he feared terrorist reprisals, said the attack
proved that ``all this nonsense about peace'' was futile. He said
the death penalty should be restored for terrorists, as well as
preventive detention without trial of suspects.
</P>
<P>
   His friend Eileen Goldsmith, who described herself as ``a good
Protestant,'' said: ``Everybody worked together, went out together.
Now this is the worst thing that ever happened.''
</P>
<P>
   On a wall above the bouquets, a hand-written poem had been
taped, apparently by a British soldier's wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I know why my husband is here,'' it said. ``I want to
gather up my family and run from your town. Pray for the strength
to stay.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
