<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980817.0301 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-17 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7979 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BURMA-ANAND-0818-COX     08-17 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BURMA-ANAND-0818-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    STILL DEFIANT, AMERICAN STUDENT RETURNS TO U.S. AFTER TIME IN
BURMA JAIL
 &HT;    EDs: With optional add at 600 words.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (w) Washington
categories.
 &HT;    By KEN FOSKETT 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Twenty-one-year-old Nisha Anand spent, who six days
as a political prisoner in one of the world's most repressive
military dictatorships and briefly faced the possibility of
five-years hard labor, returned here Monday with some advice to
other would-be democratic activists:
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd encourage any foreigner to go in and try it again,'' said
Anand, a graduate student of international studies at American
University.
</P>
<P>
   Anand, however, won't be traveling back to Burma in southeast
Asia any time soon. One of six Americans and 17 other young people
from around the world, Anand was arrested Aug. 9 for distributing
pro-democracy literature in Burma's capital, Rangoon. She was
deported from the country on Saturday after a seven-hour trial that
found her guilty of violating Burma's harsh civil disturbance laws.
</P>
<P>
   Anand, of Atlanta, said she never once feared for her safety or
that of her fellow prisoners and remained confident throughout the
ordeal that the Burmese military government would release she and
her friends to avoid the glare of the international spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   Burma, also known as Myanmar, has been ruled by the military
since 1962. The military leaders have refused to recognize a
democratically elected Parliament voted on by the people in 1990.
The country's pro-democracy leader, Aung San Suu Kyi, has set an
Aug. 21 deadline for the government to comply with the 1990 vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever it was like for us, it was nothing compared to what
it was like for the Burmese people,'' Anand said. ``We were treated
royally . . . They're the true heroes here . . . I'm glad to be
home. I'm glad to be free. But the people of Burma are not free.
They need our help.''
</P>
<P>
   Anand, a member of AU's Free Burma Coalition, left for Thailand
on July 28 with three other AU students. Initially, the group
planed to make contact with Burmese dissidents living in Bangkok,
visit a Burmese refugee camp in Thailand and perhaps engage in a
protest of the Burmese embassy on the anniversary of a failed
pro-democracy uprising in Burma.
</P>
<P>
   But in Bangkok, the students met other pro-democracy activists
who were planning to enter Burma Aug. 7 to distribute pro-democracy
literature. The students signed up for the three-day trip, securing
student visas to visit Rangoon.
</P>
<P>
   They arrived Aug. 7 and spent the following day scouting the 12
sites around the city where they planned to distribute the
literature, which they smuggled in with their personal belongings.
</P>
<P>
   Each carried 200 cards that read simply, ``Goodwill Message. We
are your friends from around the world. We have not forgotten you.
We support your hopes for human rights and democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   The cards concluded with the number 888, a reference to the
failed uprising in August 1988 in which more than 3,000 people were
killed, and said, ``Don't forget -- Don't give up.''
</P>
<P>
   Dissident organizers sent the contingent of six Americans to the
most visible sites in the Capital, Anand said, because they
believed that the U.S. government would fight the hardest to have
the group released if they were captured by authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Anand said the group fully expected to be arrested or detained,
but believed that authorities would simply put them on their plane
back to Bangkok later in the day on Aug. 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``Worst-case scenario was we thought we'd be interrogated for
two to three hours,'' Anand said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, all 18 student activists were arrested and detained in
a police barracks in Rangoon. They were fed and treated well, but
not told what would happen to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``A week in jail, it was boring,'' Anand said. ``We sat there
and read.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add begins.)
</P>
<P>
   While Anand's parents fretted, U.S. State Department officials
and representatives of five other nations worked behind the scenes
to urge the government to deport the captives. U.S. Rep.
Christopher H. Smith, R-N.J., a member of the House International
Relations Committee, also traveled to Thailand to lobby for their
release.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were some tense moments, some very tense moments,'' said
Vijay Anand, Anand's father, who lives in Atlanta. ``It's easy to
forget all that, now that she is here.''
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 14, the captives were rounded up and taken to a military
courtroom with one judge. They had no lawyer present. Government
officials brought witnesses who testified against them for seven
hours.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the proceeding the judge asked the group if they
pleaded guilty to the charge of violating the Emergency Provisions
Act, a 1950 law used to prosecute political prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   ``The judge was smiling the whole time,'' Anand recalled.
</P>
<P>
   About 15 minutes after the judge pronounced a five-year sentence
of hard labor, another official entered the room to say the
sentence would be suspended and the group would be deported
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   After her arrival at Ronald Reagan Washington National Airport
on Monday, Anand and one of her fellow political prisoners, Sapna
Chhatpar(CQ), held a news conference across the street from the
Burmese ambassador's house, where Burmese dissidents had been
holding a candle-light vigil for their safe return.
</P>
<P>
   The two young women, wearing matching T-shirts that read
``Respect all -- Fear No One,'' received praise from members of
Burma's government in exile.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best media we've ever had,'' said Beaudee Zawmin,
liaison officer for the National Coalition Government of the Union
of Burma.
</P>
<P>
   Anand's father, putting aside the anger and frustration he felt
at his daughter's brush with danger, was also touched.
</P>
<P>
   ``These girls have guts,'' he said. ``I guess some good doesn't
come unless there are some sacrifices.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
