<DOCNO> NYT19980817.0304 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-17 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7985 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-O'HAIR-MISSING-HNS &LR;      08-17 1413
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-O'HAIR-MISSING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLIGHT OF LEADING ATHEIST, OTHERS REMAINS A MYSTERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN MacCORMACK  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Madalyn Murray O'Hair was a renowned atheist
leader and American cultural icon when she disappeared from San
Antonio in late September 1995 along with her two adult children
and a half-million dollars in gold coins.
</P>
<P>
   Danny Fry was a green-eyed charmer from Florida with a taste for
whiskey and easy money when he vanished from San Antonio in late
September 1995.
</P>
<P>
   One case became a Great American Mystery, the other a forensic
footnote.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, the O'Hair disappearance has inspired a book, a
network television special and numerous newspaper and magazine
articles, as well as comparisons to other celebrity disappearances,
including Amelia Earhart and Jimmy Hoffa.
</P>
<P>
   It also fueled relentless speculation about the fate of O'Hair,
her son Jon Murray and daughter Robin. Theories range from
kidnapping and murder, to a self-imposed exile sustained by assets
skimmed from atheist accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a three-year global search by reporters, investigators
and the police, no one seems to know if O'Hair and her children are
dead or alive.
</P>
<P>
   Fry, on the other hand, sank without a ripple.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, family members tried to find him. Missing person
reports were filed in Austin, Texas, and in Florida. Psychics were
consulted. But little effort was made by the police or outsiders to
learn his fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me and my dad were real close. I was the one he raised. So for
him to disappear like this is not normal. Something had to have
happened, and it's been driving me crazy for three years,'' said
his daughter, Lisa Fry, 18.
</P>
<P>
   Fry, then 42, moved to Texas in 1995 to stay with David Waters,
a friend from years past in Florida. Waters, 50, also worked for
O'Hair in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1995, Waters pleaded guilty to stealing $54,000 from
O'Hair's atheist organizations and is now on probation. He has
prior convictions for forgery, battery and murder.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview, Waters said he knows nothing of the two
disappearances, but he believes O'Hair and her children are
probably living it up right now, having executed a long-planned
getaway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was in the works for a long time. I think they are
kicked back somewhere, very comfortable and having chuckles,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Waters said he has written a book, yet unpublished, about the
O'Hair disappearance. He declined, however, to share its
conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   He said Fry asked to come to Austin and stayed with him briefly
in the summer of 1995, before drifting out of the picture. Waters
said his later attempts to find Fry were futile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he was having some personal problems. I just kind of
got the impression he was trying to get away from things for a
while,'' Waters said of Fry.
</P>
<P>
   However, acquaintances of Fry say it was Waters who induced him
to travel to Texas in July 1995 with promises of big money and a
place to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took him to the airport. He was going up there to Austin to
work with a friend, Dave Waters,'' Fry's daughter recalled.
</P>
<P>
   She said her father described the Texas job as ``a big deal''
that would bring her the ``biggest shopping spree'' of her life
when he returned to Florida. Friends of Fry and family members
interviewed for this story requested that their hometowns not be
published.
</P>
<P>
   But Fry was close-mouthed about the details of the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would never really say if it was something bad, but I'm
positive it was illegal because most of the stuff he did was,''
Lisa Fry said.
</P>
<P>
   She said the last time she spoke to her father was in a brief
and tense conversation at 2:30 p.m., Sept. 30, 1995. It came during
her 16th birthday party, and her father said he would be back in a
couple of days.
</P>
<P>
   But Fry never made it home from Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly a month earlier, O'Hair and her children had abruptly
left their comfortable home in northwest Austin and resurfaced 75
miles to the south in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   In their haste, they left their breakfast on the table, their
beloved Cocker Spaniels unattended, and a cryptic note advising
staffers the atheist offices were closed.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hair, a diabetic, also left all her medicine at the house.
</P>
<P>
   Over the following weeks, according to cellular phone records,
they kept in regular contact with anxious atheist officials in
Austin and New Jersey, saying they were taking care of urgent
business but would return.
</P>
<P>
   On several occasions during the month, callers said, the
cellular phone was answered by an unknown male, who then handed the
phone to Jon Murray.
</P>
<P>
   But at 12:24 p.m., Sept. 29, 1995, Murray made his last call
from San Antonio. After that seven-minute call to atheist
headquarters in Austin, the cell phone went dead, and neither he,
his sister nor his mother was seen or heard from again.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the coincidence of time and place, the two
disappearances could not be more different.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hair, a larger-than-life figure who rose to prominence more
than three decades ago for her often-exaggerated role in a landmark
Supreme Court decision outlawing mandatory Bible reading in school.
</P>
<P>
   A combative, irreverent unbeliever, O'Hair spent the rest of her
life battling all forms of organized religion while aggressively
soliciting money for her nonprofit atheist organizations in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   But the self-described ``most-hated woman in America''
antagonized atheists as well as believers. By 1995 she was an old
woman battling health problems and a marginalized status in
American atheist circles.
</P>
<P>
   Fry, on the other hand, never rose above obscurity.
</P>
<P>
   A single father, he was devoted to his daughter Lisa. But he
struggled with alcohol and unemployment, and when whiskey loosened
his tongue, he became a big talker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Danny was a scam artist, so I wouldn't put a lot of things
past him,'' said his ex-wife, Jeanetta Camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did a lot of things to make extra money scamming people,
but I don't think he would harm anyone intentionally. But people
change, and I haven't been with the man for many years,'' Camp
said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hair, her children and Fry all disappeared right after a
peculiar event. In the early afternoon of Sept. 29, San Antonio
jeweler Cory Ticknor delivered $500,000 in gold coins to Murray in
a bank parking.
</P>
<P>
   Murray had ordered the coins a week earlier and paid for them
with $600,000 wired to a San Antonio bank through a New Jersey bank
from an atheist organization account in New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hair had invested both personal and organization funds in New
Zealand and had talked about someday retiring there.
</P>
<P>
   But the money transfer apparently hit a snag in New Jersey. So,
according to travel records, Murray, accompanied by a man using the
name Conrad Johnson, flew to Newark on Sept. 21, 1995. The two men
returned to San Antonio the next day, and the money soon followed.
</P>
<P>
   But not all the gold coins Murray had paid for arrived by Sept.
29. Murray, however, never returned to take delivery of the final
$100,000 shipment.
</P>
<P>
   Fry made his final phone call home the following day.
</P>
<P>
   Family members say in the nearly three years since, little
information was forthcoming from Waters in Austin. Waters said
there was little he could tell them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't help her (Lisa Fry). I assured her that if I had
anything I could do to alleviate her concerns, I would do it,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   O'Hair's other son, Bill Murray, who has been estranged from his
mother since becoming a fundamentalist Christian decades ago, said
he now is convinced his family was killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the crowning thing is that over $100,000 in my
brother's name is sitting in a New Zealand account and hasn't been
touched in three years. That pretty much says they are dead,'' Bill
Murray said.
</P>
<P>
   Friends and family of Fry also believe he is dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``That man went down in the water somewhere, or he is buried
somewhere. I just feel it. He would never have left his daughter,''
said Lisa Jones, who was Fry's fiancee.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Jones said she would like to have the mystery resolved.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say a book opens and a book closes, and this book has
never closed,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than anything, for Danny's mother, so she can let go. So
she can die knowing her son is gone. I think that's the most
important thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
