<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-17 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7991 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-17 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOESN'T ANYBODY CARE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A new Census Bureau study confirms earlier reports
that fewer voters bothered to go to the polls in the last
presidential contest than in any such election since 1968 and
offers some theories about this disturbing indifference to our
civic duty.
</P>
<P>
   It is clear that getting citizens to take seriously their
important role in the elections that produce our political
leadership and determine our national future is not going to be
easy.
</P>
<P>
   We thought we had found at least a partial answer in the
``motor-voter'' law that took effect in 1995. It made it easier to
register to vote by replacing past complicated procedures with a
simple way to sign up while getting a driver's license or filling
out forms for disability and welfare aid. Residents were also given
the right to simply mail in a registration form without further
fuss.
</P>
<P>
   The reform was successful in getting more people to register
than might otherwise have gone to the trouble. But it was not
successful enough to reverse a pattern of three decades of steadily
declining voter registration and turnout.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Census report, ``Voting and Registration in the
Election of November 1996,'' 28 percent of eligible adults who
registered to vote in the year before the election did so when they
renewed or obtained driver's licenses. That figure represented more
voters than registered by any other single method. Another 19
percent registered by mailing in forms.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, however, registration was 2.3 percentage points lower
than registration for the 1992 presidential election. Approximately
128 million people, or 65.9 percent of those of voting age, were
registered to vote in 1996, the lowest proportion for any
presidential election in 28 years.
</P>
<P>
   Without motor-voter, those figures would be even more
distressing.
</P>
<P>
   The decline in the numbers of those who actually voted was far
sharper, 7 percentage points lower than in 1992. Just 54.2 percent
of the voting-age population cast ballots in the contest between
President Clinton and Republican nominee Bob Dole.
</P>
<P>
   Why is this so? More is at work here than inconvenience and
inertia.
</P>
<P>
   The Census study tried to find out, but the answers seem
disingenuous and unsatisfactory. When queried, nearly 5 million
people who had not voted said they were simply too busy. Another
3.5 million said they didn't give a fig about the whole process.
Nearly 3 million confessed to not liking any of the candidates.
</P>
<P>
   My own theory is that being busy with no time off work is a lame
excuse. We can always find room for things that are really
important to us.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps too many people just feel their votes don't count in a
crowded nation of 266 million souls (our population will relatively
soon be twice that of 1950, when President Harry S Truman could be
observed strolling alone in the White House neighborhood like a
regular human being). We have become both cynical and disengaged.
</P>
<P>
   And the more ideological the political issues, the less
interested mainstream voters seem to be. The so-called cutting-edge
moral issues that dominate political debate these days drive only a
minority on either side.
</P>
<P>
   Today's campaigns are rife with simplistic social slogans that
bear little relevance to the everyday complex lives of most people,
who find politicians poor role models for moral guidance.
Meaningless ``family values'' provide insufficient motivation to
make people want to elevate one candidate over another.
</P>
<P>
   They will be moved to vote when they feel that something dear to
them is threatened or could be greatly improved, whether it is
Social Security, tax relief or the highway system. Changing the
process to encourage registration can be helpful, but that alone is
not enough.
</P>
<P>
   Expectations were unrealistically high for motor-voter, which
was a controversial partisan issue for 40 years before it finally
passed. It has neither lived up to its civic promise nor to its
partisan presumptions.
</P>
<P>
   Yet strangely, Republicans are still fixated on it as somehow
dangerous to the republic. This, despite the fact that three
circuit courts of appeals have already upheld its legitimacy.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans also reject the notion that it makes sense to
smooth the passage to participation for ordinary Americans in the
world's greatest democracy. The GOP fought the concept for years
out of fear that more poor, young and minority Democrats would take
advantage of it than middle-class Republicans familiar with the
old, restricted way of registering. President George Bush vetoed
the motor-voter measure, but it passed a second time after Bill
Clinton was elected.
</P>
<P>
   This summer House Republicans attempted to attach to the
campaign finance bill amendments that would allow states to kill
mail-in registrations and to require photo identification for all
voters. Fortunately, the measures lost.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, motor-voter provisions have not helped Democrats
over Republicans, as both parties had anticipated. The Federal
Election Commission recently reported that while the number of
independent voters increased under the law, neither major party
seemed to benefit over the other in the 26 states where voters must
declare a party affiliation to register.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
