<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE TUESDAY BUSINESS BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These business stories for release Tuesday, August 18, 1998, are
moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the financial (f) category. Stories also
moving in lifestyle will be marked with (f, l).
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, features, sports and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   All stories have moved, except those with an ETA.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   ECONOMY _ ATLANTA _ Alan Greenspan warned us about the bull
market, fretting at one point about the ``irrational exuberance''
he thought was pushing stock prices to extremes. Greenspan is
concerned about what might happen to the economy if a sharp and
sustained drop in the market robs consumers of a substantial part
of the enormous wealth they have accumulated during the bull run.
(Walker, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   PAYOFF-DEBT _ ATLANTA _ What are consumers learning from the
stock market correction? Or what should they be learning? What
dangers lie ahead? It is dangerous to carry too much debt at any
time. (Tharpe, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GEEWAX-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ This month, two multimillion-dollar
guns were fired in metro Atlanta. Taxpayers, retailers and property
owners will be paying for those guns for years. One of the weapons
was used to kill a young man in the food court at Greenbriar Mall
in southwest Atlanta. The ultimate cost of that single crime could
be staggering. (Geewax, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   JOBGROWTH _ ATLANTA _ Georgia's red-hot employment market is
showing signs of cooling. Is the slide due to the crisis in Asia or
Wall Street's woes? Not necessarily. ``We're just having trouble
keeping the expansion going,'' lamented Kevin Mulcahy, a labor
market expert in the Georgia Labor Department. ``We don't have a
pool of unemployed to draw from anymore.'' Hence, the domino
effect: Lack of workers means slower growth and expansion. (Joyner,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution.) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CYBERSCENE _ ATLANTA _ The real miracle of the Internet's World
Wide Web is that _ with so much information squirreled away in so
many different Web sites _ we find anything at all. That is, of
course, the mission of the search engine. (Husted, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NETWATCH _ ATLANTA _ For many students, August is the cruelest
month. For students with PCs and laptops filled with bookmarks for
the Lillith Fair, ``The X-Files'' and ``South Park,'' it might be
time to add a few Web sites to your list that might actually help
you once you're off the beach and back at the books. (Katz, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ELECTRONIC-GADGETS _ ATLANTA _ Americans are taking their
microchips out to play with increasing frequency. Whether you're a
golfer, hiker, angler, ballplayer or participant in any of a dozen
other sports, there's a device to help you get closer, walk
smarter, find fish deeper or hit harder. (Ghirardini, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ELECTRONIC-BAT _ ATLANTA _ Technology is putting a charge into
the grand old game of baseball. The world's first ``electric bat,''
the aluminum Copperhead ACX by Worth Inc., hit store shelves Aug.
1, billed as having a nearly unlimited sweet spot and promising to
reduce or eliminate the sting that results from hitting the ball
near the handle or close to the end. (Ghirardini, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBUDDY _ ATLANTA _ Let's start by agreeing that Windows 98
is not as good as it could be. But danged little is. If I insisted
on pure excellence in my life, I'd have to stop eating in the
cafeteria here at work, would give my golf clubs away and would
never again sing in the shower. (Husted, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECHREPORT _ The Lego Mindstorms Robotics Invention System,
which should hit store shelves in the fall and retail for about
$200, lets kids 11 and up design and program real robots that can
move, think and act on their own. (Ghirardini, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECHTOOLS _ ATLANTA _ Let us now remember famous men, those
stalwarts of old who made computers what they are, or perhaps what
they are not, today. My favorite is George Morrow. Chairman George,
as he was known, was once the Bill Gates of the computer industry.
(Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
