<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-17 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7999 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOLPHINS-ERICKSON18-C     08-17 0554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLPHINS-ERICKSON18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Backup job is not Erickson's just yet
 &HT;    By Mark Woods
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVIE, Fla. _ Craig Erickson's Sunday consisted of meetings, a
brief warmup, a couple snaps during an offensive line drill and an
hour of watching Dan Marino and Damon Huard throwing passes.
</P>
<P>
   When asked why his No. 2 quarterback had spent practice as a
spectator, Miami Dolphins coach Jimmy Johnson didn't answer in
words.
</P>
<P>
   He merely tapped his right shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nothing serious,'' Johnson insisted. ``We're just resting
him a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins did play two pre-season games in six days, with
Erickson handling the bulk of the quarterback duties, throwing more
than twice as many passes (25) as Marino (12), Huard (12) or Chad
May (8).
</P>
<P>
   That work hasn't produced the kind of results that Johnson or
Erickson wanted. The seventh-year pro completed only 44 percent of
his passes (11 of 25) and threw two interceptions and no touchdowns
for a passing rating of 20.6.
</P>
<P>
   To top it off, Johnson has refused to name Erickson as the
clear-cut backup to Marino. Johnson says that Huard, a free-agent
who holds the No. 3 spot after the release of Chad May and John
Dutton, still has a shot at moving up the depth chart.
</P>
<P>
   Erickson shrugs this off. As he explains, he's had to deal with
debate about his play for years, dating back to when he was at the
University of Miami and Cardinal Newman High School.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try not to let a whole lot bother me,'' he said. ``Believe
me, I've had a lot worse criticism.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Coaches in the dark: Fans and the media aren't the only ones
who wait until cut-down days to see who survives cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant coaches also are kept in the dark.
</P>
<P>
   That's the way Johnson wants it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes the coaches want to bring up (who will or won't make
the team) and I am very emphatic with them that they don't
speculate,'' Johnson said. ``That's not their concern. ... I talk
to them about who's playing well, who's not playing well. We do not
discuss who's going to be on the roster.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson discusses that with one person: himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to affect the coaches in a negative way and plant
a negative seed,'' he said. ``I don't think it's really productive
for a coach to be working with a player who thinks he's going to
get cut. And I don't think it's very productive for a player to try
to make our team when he reads in the paper that he's going to get
cut.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Talk about bulletin board material: How about Dan Marino and
David Hasselhoff, separated at birth?
</P>
<P>
   Two sports magazines have noted the resemblance between the
Dolphins' quarterback and the actor. ESPN Magazine noted the
similarity. Sport went one step further, making the two a ``Sport
morph'' _ a line of mug shots that gradually transforms from Marino
on the left to Hasselhoff on the right.
</P>
<P>
   That feature ended up taped to a board in the Dolphins' locker
room.
</P>
<P>
   _ Good deed of the week: The Dolphins brought 2,400
disadvantaged children from South Florida to Pro Player Stadium for
the pre-season home opener Thursday against Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   (endit)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PALM BEACH POST, WEST PALM BEACH, FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-08-16-98 2309E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
