<HEADER>
A8004 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-TALLAS-BOS     08-17 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-TALLAS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS KEEP TALLAS _ FOR $625,000 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ For the second time in less than a week, the Bruins got
considerably more than they bargained for, as they were informed by
arbitrator Claude Foisy Monday that it would cost them $625,000 to
keep netminder Rob Tallas in uniform for the 1998-99 season.
</P>
<P>
   It was only Thursday that Foisy set Dmitri Khristich's salary at
$1.95 million, about twice his pay last season and roughly
one-third more than the Bruins hoped to pay their 29-goal scorer.
</P>
<P>
   To no one's surprise, it is getting significantly more expensive
by the hour to put an NHL team on the ice. The Bruins wanted to pay
Khristich about $1.5 million. They had Tallas pegged for $440,000,
but only if he spent the year in Boston. They were angling to pay
him only $110,000 if he were to spend the year in the minor
leagues, offering what is termed a ``two-way'' contract.
</P>
<P>
   Foisy's answer: No way on the two-way; if the Bruins want to
keep Tallas on the payroll, be it in Boston or Boise, it will cost
them $625,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my hands are still shaking,'' said a thrilled Tallas,
reached Mondayat his Rhode Island home. ``I'm totally relieved. I
think it shows the Bruins I'm a strong backup in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins could have opted not to pay Tallas, cutting him loose
as an unrestricted free agent. The league's Collective Bargaining
Agreement allows clubs to ``walk away'' from one arbitration case
per season.
</P>
<P>
   But in an afternoon press release, the Bruins made it clear that
they'll keep the 25-year-old Tallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are glad to have this settled,'' said Bruins
president/general manager Harry Sinden. ``Robbie fits into our
plans and he, along with (Jim) Carey and (Byron) Dafoe will battle
for the No. 1 spot at training camp.''
</P>
<P>
   It is now up to the Bruins to decide whether they also will move
ahead with Khristich next season. They have until Thursday morning
_ 72 hours after their last arbitration settlement (in this case
Tallas) _ to declare a walkaway.
</P>
<P>
   Walkaways virtually never occur, for one simple reason: Unless
an award is outrageously high, to the point of being punitive, a
club is far wiser to trade the player and at least receive
something, if only a draft pick, in return.
</P>
<P>
   What will the Bruins do with Khristich? In all likelihood,
they'll keep him. Remember, two other forwards, Montreal's Mark
Recchi and St. Louis's Pierre Turgeon, received huge awards last
week. Recchi got $4.5 million and Turgeon $4.65 million. Khristich
for less than 50 cents on the dollar is a relative bargain.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you put it that way, I suppose it's true,'' said
assistant general manager Mike O'Connell. ``We haven't made a final
decision, but right now we're leaning toward having Khristich back.
I don't want anyone to get the idea we're crying about these
decisions. It's business. We accept that and move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Tallas's agent, Jay Fee, whose highest-profile Bruin over the
years was Cam Neely, said he felt he had no option but to go to
arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key issue in our minds was the two-way,'' said Fee, who,
along with Bruin Hall of Famer Bobby Orr, continues to build a long
NHL client list at Boston-based Woolf and Associates. ``When it was
clear they didn't want to change their stance there, we felt
arbitration was the only way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins will enter training camp with $3.775 million tied up
in their top three netminders: Carey ($2.3 million), Dafoe
($850,000), and Tallas ($625,000). It's pricey, but remember, the
Sabres will pay Dominik Hasek $8 million for stopping the puck next
year. None of Boston's goalkeepers comes close to matching Hasek's
talent, but their bucks don't equal half of what the Dominator
makes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so excited,'' said Tallas. ``We talked about it, sure, and
if the cards hadn't gone the way I'd wanted, I just would have gone
back again and have done the best I could.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, this is great. I'll be in there in a couple of weeks,
fighting for the No. 1 job. And I hope I'm back in arbitration next
year, fighting for the money that goes with being a No. 1 goalie.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
