<DOCNO> NYT19980817.0318 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-17 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8024 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAMAICA-VIAGRA-COX     08-17 0475
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAMAICA-VIAGRA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Viagra expected to get blame in rape
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving in (i) International and (f) Financial categories.)
 &HT;    By Shelley Emling
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTEGO BAY, Jamaica _ A 70-year-old businessman charged with
raping a young employee goes before a judge here today, and
prosecutors are expected to say that Viagra made him do it.
</P>
<P>
   At an initial hearing last month, prosecutors charged that Keith
Roberts, who takes tourists on boat rides, sexually attacked the
27-year-old woman after swallowing a dose of the wonder drug.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth McLeod, who will represent Roberts at the preliminary
hearing, maintains that the whole thing is a set-up: ``My client is
being framed. The woman wants his money.''
</P>
<P>
   The case _ while certainly alarming to many Jamaicans _ hasn't
stirred as much surprise on this tropical island as one might
expect.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of Viagra are not yet legal in Jamaica, yet pharmacists
say they've been bombarded by Viagra-related questions from men _
some desperate, some merely curious. Black markets for Viagra have
sprung up throughout the Caribbean, with the light blue
diamond-shaped pill, manufactured by Pfizer Inc., selling like snow
cones in a desert.
</P>
<P>
   Because of its popularity, many governments in the region are
pushing the anti-impotency drug through the approval process.
</P>
<P>
   ``The interest is definitely here because many people are asking
for it,'' said Norma Inniss, president of the pharmacy board in the
twin-island nation of Trinidad and Tobago. ``We're hoping to get
approval soon because everyone's talking about it.''
</P>
<P>
   In mid-May, Trinidadian customs officials raided several
pharmacies and confiscated hundreds of Viagra pills being sold for
as much as $20 each.
</P>
<P>
   Introduced in the United States last April, Viagra has become a
global phenomenon in just over four months. Prescription sales
indicate that as many as 3 million American men may have already
popped one of the so-called wonder pills, while Pfizer officials
expect worldwide approval of the drug by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The drug has, in particular, aroused a lot of interest in the
Caribbean and in Latin America, where male virility is a highly
valued attribute. ``We expect the drug to do quite well in the
Caribbean and Latin America,'' said Pam Gemmel, a Pfizer
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Pfizer officials say Viagra doesn't cause men to act
aggressively and that it isn't an aphrodisiac, but that it
increases the flow of blood to the genitals.
</P>
<P>
   In South America, the sale of Viagra has been approved in
Argentina, Brazil, Colombia, Ecuador and Venezuela. In late July,
Costa Rica became the first Central American country to approve
Viagra, which will be sold for about $11 a pill by prescription
only.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-98 1841EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
