<DOCNO> NYT19980817.0320 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-17 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8026 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KENKIDS-COX     08-17 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENKIDS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Children suffering from physical, mental wounds in bomb
aftermath
 &HT;    By Don Melvin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAIROBI, Kenya _ The stitches run from just under David Maina's
right ear down under his chin. Surgeons have used bone from his
ribs to replace his jaw, which was blown off in the terrorist
attack on the U.S. embassy nearly two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   He's 13 years old. He's in pain. And still his parents haven't
come.
</P>
<P>
   Relatively few children were injured physically when the bomb
exploded in downtown Nairobi on Aug. 7. The buildings that bore the
brunt of the blast were office buildings: a bank, a secretarial
school, the embassy. Most of the people injured or killed were
adults.
</P>
<P>
   Still, one question echoing through Nairobi this week is: Who
will heal the children?
</P>
<P>
   For, as David Maina could painfully tell you, not all injuries
are physical. And many children in Nairobi have suffered deep
psychological wounds.
</P>
<P>
   Lupita Nyong'o is 15, and she was nowhere near the embassy when
the bomb exploded. Yet this week, her parents brought her to the
site of the carnage to look, to weep and to grieve.
</P>
<P>
   Lupita's friend and classmate, Gloria Mtuiri, who was 16, died
here. So did Gloria's sister, Caroline, who was 17. So did Lupita's
teacher, Mutegi Njiru.
</P>
<P>
   As Lupita stood and looked at the rubble, thoughts of her
friends flooded in.
</P>
<P>
   ''I keep wondering exactly where they were,'' she said. ''I keep
wondering if they died at once.''
</P>
<P>
   She wondered, too, how school would be without her teacher. And
she remembered the play she and Gloria acted in together. It was
about heaven's gates and hell's fire.
</P>
<P>
   Gloria played an angel.
</P>
<P>
   Lupita is by no means alone in her tortured thoughts. Most of
the more than 200 Kenyan adults who died in the bombing, as well as
the 4,000 or so who were injured, were presumbably related to
children. Families seeking counseling have overwhelmed the staff at
Kenyatta National Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Margaret Makanyengo, who as chief of the hospital's mental
health department supervises about 100 counselors, worries about
the children. She spent part of last week trying quickly to train
her staff to treat post-traumatic stress syndrome. Kenya is
normally so peaceful that the syndrome is virtually unknown here.
And counselors are so busy they have not had time to consult their
textbooks.
</P>
<P>
   Makanyengo would like help for the children, if possible, from
overseas.
</P>
<P>
   ''We need more child psychologists, perhaps, to come and and
help us start an intervention program,'' she said. ''That is what
we need right now, because we have no experience in this type of
tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   She fears that Nairobi's children, left untreated, will in the
future develop problems such as depression, truancy, irrational
anger and drug addiction.
</P>
<P>
   She is not the only one concerned. A member of parliament,
Waithaka Mwangi, proposed this week that a portion of a bomb
disaster fund being developed be used to educate the newly
orphaned.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the victims in the secretarial college, Mwangi said,
were single mothers. Their children have no one to care for them
now.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond even the issues of care and education are the attempts of
children to make sense of a disaster that came with no warning and
destroyed so much. All week, parents have been bringing their
children to look at the bomb site because their children have seen
violence only on movies.
</P>
<P>
   Children have to know, said Dorothy Nyong'o, Lupita's mother,
that this is different. ''It needs to be real,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Lupita's 10-year-old sister, Esperanza, looked quietly at the
devastated buildings. All bombs should be illegal, she said, and a
tear slid down her nose.
</P>
<P>
   ''Why are you crying?'' asked her brother, Peter, who is 4.
</P>
<P>
   Lupita walked toward a mound of flowers people had left at the
foot of the bombed-out buildings. Her mother quietly joined her.
They hugged each other. Lupita cried and her mother wiped the tears
from her cheeks.
</P>
<P>
   No family members brush the tears from David Maina's cheeks. He
lies alone in Kenyatta National Hospital, having had one operation
to replace his jaw and facing many more.
</P>
<P>
   He was riding a public bus, on his way home from a boarding
school in Nairobi, when the bomb exploded. His father, who lives in
the Rift Valley about 50 miles away, has been notified, doctors
say, but no one from David's family has come to the hospital yet.
No one has any explanation.
</P>
<P>
   David's tongue protrudes awkwardly from the space where his lips
ought to be. His throat hurts him so much that sometimes he cries
out in pain. He misses his mother and father.
</P>
<P>
   But he says he's going to be OK.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
