<HEADER>
A8053 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATTERNS-FASHION-NYT &LR;      08-17 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATTERNS-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASHION NOTES AND NEWS  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CONSTANCE C.R. WHITE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _
</P>
<P>
   British Chic at Saks
</P>
<P>
   Saks Fifth Avenue has invited the British to invade New York,
and 25 fashion designers and an equal number of artists have agreed
to storm the store on Sept. 9. A party that night to benefit the
Rainforest Foundation and the Ovarian Cancer Research Fund will
celebrate the influence that contemporary London is having on
fashion, art and music.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Blair, the British Prime Minister, and his wife have lent
their names as honorary chairman and chairwoman. There will be
entertainment throughout the store, and the Met Bar from London's
trendy Metropolitan Hotel will be recreated on the second floor,
complete with its signature red banquettes and 10 bartenders flown
in to mix martinis.
</P>
<P>
   The event is part of a weeklong promotion of British chic that
Saks is calling ``British Invasion, Part II,'' figuring that the
Carnaby Street-Mary Quant-Biba-Twiggy 1960s was the first British
invasion. (Historians might disagree.)
</P>
<P>
   This invasion will feature personal appearances by designers,
with video images flashed on a round wall in the fragrance area, an
exhibition of David Bailey's current and vintage photographs and
fashion mannequins displaying current styles in the store's 35
windows and perched on ledges on the main floor.
</P>
<P>
   Designers expected to attend include Alexander McQueen, Antonio
Berardi, Hussein Chalayan, Stephen Jones, Philip Treacy, Julien
MacDonald and Lainey Keogh. They are among the raft of British
designers whom the store has been carrying. Virginia Antiques, a
vintage couture shop on London's Portland Road, will set up a
temporary outpost.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for the event has been percolating for two years, said
Philip B. Miller, the chairman and chief executive of Saks Holdings
Inc. ``We were going to the London Markets and saw a lot of newness
and vitality that we hadn't seen in recent years,'' he said. ``We
wanted to be the first store in America to present in a cogent,
intelligent way a host of British designers, artists and people in
the music world. It's a celebration of their creativity, as
complete a statement as has been made anywhere about contemporary
England.''
</P>
<P>
   Promoting a country's products to help develop business is
something that Bloomingdale's pioneered in the 1970s with a series
of parties and storewide displays featuring the wares of countries
like France, Italy, China, Israel, Russia, Ireland and, of course,
Britain. It worked then.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; On-Line Trade Show &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The trade show is going on line. Instead of traipsing through
miles of aisles at a convention center, store buyers will be able
to simply click on to the Internet to see fashion designers' and
manufacturers' offerings through an online trade show called
Fashion Millennia. It should be fully functional by September, said
its organizer, Joanne Roaman.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Roaman, who runs her own buying office in New York,
explained that there would be no fee to retailers to browse Fashion
Millennia but that manufacturers would pay for a Web site to be
operable for three months. The sites will be designed to individual
specifications with still or moving images. She said that each site
would be password-secured so that the only people with access would
be those given passwords by manufacturers. There will be order pads
on the computer to allow buyers to e-mail orders, if they desire.
</P>
<P>
   The concept seems to be of value mainly to small design houses
that don't put on fashion shows, offering them a forum to be seen
by buyers unfamiliar with their lines. Among the designers who have
already signed up are Felicia Ferrar, Antonio Garcia, Lisa Leonard
and Lisandro Sarasola.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could also be of value to stores that haven't seen a
line,'' Ms. Roaman said. ``This can give them a quick look without
their having to go to a showroom.''
</P>
<P>
   Fashion Millennia's Web site address is
www.fashionmillennia.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
