<HEADLINE>
BOND INVESTORS CAUTIOUS IN ADVANCE OF FED MEETING 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Treasury bond prices ended slightly lower Monday,
while shorter maturities edged higher, as investors grew more
concerned about the economic situations of Russia and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Investors were also cautious in advance of Tuesday's meeting of
Federal Reserve Board policy-makers.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond slipped 2/32,
to a price of 99 13/32, leaving the bond's yield at 5.54 percent,
unchanged from Friday. The price of the two-year note rose 1/32, to
100 4/32, for a yield of 5.31 percent, also unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's decision to float the ruble, effectively devaluing it
by a third against the dollar, bolstered the Treasury market as
investors moved from the riskier debt of emerging markets to the
relative safety of U.S. and European securities.
</P>
<P>
   Should such a so-called flight to quality continue, some
Treasury market analysts said, bond yields could fall as low as 5
percent, while the yield on a two-year note might fall by a full
percentage point.
</P>
<P>
   Most market participants expect no change in interest rates to
come from Tuesday's meeting of the Federal Open Market Committee,
the Fed's rate-setting panel. But some analysts and traders are
looking for the central bank to change its bias toward raising
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   Fed policy-makers, said Scott Grannis, director and chief
economist at Western Asset Management Co. in Pasadena, Calif.,
``should first pat themselves on the back for a job well done,
because inflation is truly dead.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Next they should start to worry, because there are increasing
signs that they have stepped on the monetary brakes too long and
too hard,'' Grannis said. ``If they don't step on the gas pretty
soon, the U.S. economy may be in danger of following Asia into a
recession.''
</P>
<P>
   Grannis said it was time the Fed began lowering short-term
rates, to relieve the deflationary pressure felt by commodity
producers, and reduce the dollar's strength against other
currencies.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in the market, the Treasury sold $13 billion of new
three-month and six-month bills Monday in its regular weekly
auction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-98 1908EDT &QL; 
