<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-ECON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NIKKEI DROPS ON UNCERTAINTY ON WALL STREET AND IN RUSSIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The stock market fell sharply and flirted with the
year's lows on Monday, pressured by the wobbliness on Wall Street
last week and an expanding global economic upheaval that is now
ravaging Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Further pressuring the market was the persistent fear that the
Japanese government will fail to overcome the country's banking
crisis and a renewed concern about the impact of Asia's troubles on
corporate profits.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, the Nikkei Stock Average sank below this year's
low of 14,664.44 before rebounding slightly to close at 14,794.66,
down 329.27 points, or 2.18 percent, from Friday. It was the lowest
closing level in two months.
</P>
<P>
   The yen, which hit an eight-year low of 147.35 to the dollar
last Tuesday before a mild rebound to 146.35 yen by the weekend,
fell to 146.45 to the dollar in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   Some traders said the weakness on Wall Street last week
contributed to the selling mood in Tokyo. Others said the deepening
crisis in Russia also weighed on the Japanese markets. Although
Japanese financial institutions have relatively little exposure in
Russia, the problems there reinforced a sense that the economic
malaise born in Asia more than a year ago is spreading. Russia's
decision to devalue the ruble came after the Japanese financial
markets had closed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Increasingly, Japanese stock market events are out of the
Japanese government's control,'' said Pelham Smithers, chief
strategist at ING Barings in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   Except for its ``price-keeping operations,'' in which the
government sometimes buys shares to strengthen the market, it has
few tools for restoring confidence at the moment.
</P>
<P>
   It has already announced tax cuts and extensive public works
programs in hopes of goading the economy into recovery and
restoring investor confidence, and it is currently wrangling in
Parliament with the opposition parties over legislation to overhaul
the banking system.
</P>
<P>
   But those measures seem to have done little to ease investors
concerns. Banking stocks have been among the hardest hit in the
selloffs that began in June and keep pushing the Nikkei toward its
lowest level since the ``bubble'' economy collapsed in 1990. That
was hit on Aug. 18, 1992, when the Nikkei sank to 14,309.41.
</P>
<P>
   Strategists worry that if the average penetrates that level, it
will have difficulty finding a new floor. Banking stocks tested
decade-old lows about two weeks ago, according to Craig Chudler,
equity strategist at Salomon Smith Barney in Tokyo, and have had
trouble regaining their footing since.
</P>
<P>
   But Chudler also said that if the Nikkei dropped under its
post-bubble low, Japanese politicians might finally realize the
extent of the crisis. ``A Nikkei below 14,500 is far better than
having a U.S. politician or bureaucrat yelling at Japan about what
it should be doing,'' he said. ``The government will panic if that
happens, and maybe that's what's needed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-98 1908EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
