A8063 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BO     08-17 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JIM MURRAY: A DEITY AMONG SPORTSWRITERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Los Angeles Times sports columnist Jim Murray died of a heart
attack late Sunday night at the age of 78, and dozens of wannabes
like myself spent Monday trying to describe Jim, and explain what
he meant to the world of sports.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad we didn't have Jim Murray around to do what he always
did _ write the story better than anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   If you are one of those folks who love the sports pages, you
should know about Jim Murray. He was the ranking god of American
sportswriters, and pity the poor New Englander who never got to
read him. Around these parts, the closest thing we ever had to Jim
was the late, great Ray Fitzgerald, who died too young in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   Jim grew up in Hartford, Conn., went to Trinity, and got his
first newspaper job as a campus correspondent for the Hartford
Times. He went to Time magazine in 1948 and was one of the original
writers for a startup magazine called Sports Illustrated in 1953.
He began his column for the LA Times in 1961 and won the Pulitzer
Prize for commentary in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Only Jim could go to the Indianapolis 500 and write,
``Gentlemen, start your coffins!'' Only Jim could look at the folks
from Iowa, in town for the Rose Bowl, and describe them as
``thousands of people in calico and John Deere caps in their
Winnebagos with their pacemakers and potato salad looking around
for Bob Hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Murray was hilarious, fair, never preachy. He sought to
entertain and usually succeeded. He was strong, humble, helpful,
and kind to young writers who wanted to be like him. He loathed
self-importance. As one who dedicated his life to the same
profession, I was honored to speak with Jim, occasionally share a
World Series flight, ask questions, and listen to his stories.
</P>
<P>
   When I was 24 years old I was on a writer's charter from New
York to Los Angeles and remember Jim worrying that he was going
blind as we flew west. It turned out Jim did lose his sight for
several years, but even when he couldn't see, Jim Murray described
the action better than the rest of us.
</P>
<P>
   I called Jim to get a Larry Bird anecdote in 1993. Murray
covered the pulsating Celtic-Lakers Finals of 1984, '85, and '87,
but this was his favorite Bird story: ``The one thing I remember is
Barcelona (1992 Olympics). I decided one day to go out to watch a
baseball game, and it was a long trip. You had to go by train, then
bus, then metro. I get there and who do I see standing in line but
Larry Bird? And he was way back in line, like the 55th guy, just
standing there waiting to get in like everyone else. I thought that
was pretty amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   That was Jim. He could see the ordinary and make it
extraordinary.
</P>
<P>
   Covering the World Series in 1995, I encountered Jim at
Hartsfield Airport in Atlanta. Seizing the moment, I went to the
airport bookstore, bought's Jim's autobiography, and asked him to
sign it as we waited at the gate. I felt like Archibald
``Moonlight'' Graham (one game in the big leagues) getting an
autograph from Babe Ruth.
</P>
<P>
   From Jim's autobiography:
</P>
<P>
   _``I knew one thing no athlete could have was imagination. If he
thought what was at stake he could never catch that ball.''
</P>
<P>
   _``Tommy (Lasorda) never talked, he shouted. He always managed
to sound as if the building were on fire.''
</P>
<P>
   _``Managing or general-managing a baseball team is probably the
easiest thing to do in our society next to being a guard at a
railroad crossing where two trains a week come through.''
</P>
<P>
   _``A column is more than a demanding mistress. It is a raging
master. It consumes you. It is insatiable. It becomes more than
you. You are not a person, you are a publicly owned facility.
Available on demand.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim had stories that we could only imagine. When he was Time's
cinema correspondent in the 1950s, he interviewed and wrote stories
about John Wayne and Humphrey Bogart. He also pitched an idea for a
profile of an upcoming actress named Marilyn Monroe.
</P>
<P>
   Jim took Marilyn to a restaurant on Sunset Strip, had dinner,
and conducted his interview. Late in the evening, she asked if it
would be OK if she went home with someone else who was in the
restaurant. She introduced Jim to Joe DiMaggio. Joe D. went home
with Marilyn and Jim went home and wrote his story.
</P>
<P>
   Jim was a columnist to the finish. Last Saturday, he covered the
Pacific Classic horse race and wrote about the comeback victory of
Free House at the Del Mar rack. The veteran horse was a long shot
and Jim concluded, ``It's nice to know getting older has its flip
side.''
</P>
<P>
   The story ran Sunday morning and Jim died that night, his byline
etched on newspapers still resting on coffee tables and kitchen
counters throughout Greater Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
