<SLUG> BC-ABC-APPOINT-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANNE SWEENEY NAMED PRESIDENT OF ABC CABLE NETWORKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By LAWRIE MIFFLIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anne Sweeney was named president of Disney/ABC Cable Networks on
Monday, in an appointment that had been expected ever since her
mentor, Geraldine Laybourne, resigned from the position in May. Ms.
Sweeney had been executive vice president of the division for two
years, reporting to Ms. Laybourne, as well as president of the
Disney Channel.
</P>
<P>
   In her new position, which makes her the highest-ranking woman
in the cable industry, Ms. Sweeney will oversee all of ABC's cable
interests except in sports. They include half-ownership of the
Lifetime network and slightly smaller interests in A&AMP;E, the History
Channel and E! Entertainment Television.
</P>
<P>
   She will also continue as president of the Disney Channel, one
of the fastest-growing basic cable networks, and its spinoff
channel, Toon Disney, and will oversee the ABC network's Saturday
morning children's programming.
</P>
<P>
   ``This company is progressive when it comes to its cable
division,'' Ms. Sweeney said Monday. ``I expect to be looking at
new properties and at developing properties, as well as continuing
to manage the assets that we have.''
</P>
<P>
   Before joining Disney/ABC in February 1996, Ms. Sweeney had been
chairwoman and chief executive of FX Networks Inc., a cable unit of
News Corp., since 1993. Before that she spent 12 years working in
various positions at Nickelodeon, when Ms. Laybourne was that
network's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anne's record at Disney Channel has been impressive, with
dramatic growth, breakthrough original kids' and family programming
and record high ratings,'' said Robert Iger, president of ABC,
which is a unit of Walt Disney Co. Ms. Sweeney will report to Iger.
</P>
</TEXT>
