<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-SUSPECTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ULSTER POLICE QUESTION FIVE IN BOMBING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OMAGH, Northern Ireland _ Five men, including the son of a
leader of the political wing of the group that is suspected of
planting the car bomb that killed 28 people and injured 200, were
arrested Monday for questioning.
</P>
<P>
   Shane Mackey, son of Omagh councilor Francie Mackey, was
arrested on the outskirts of this market town and taken to the
Castlereagh interrogation center in Belfast with four other men.
Under law, they can be held for questioning up to seven days.
</P>
<P>
   Francie Mackey attended an emergency town council meeting Monday
morning and later emerged to say his group, the 32-County
Sovereignty Committee, had nothing to do with Saturday's bombing,
the worst atrocity in 30 years of violence in Northern Ireland.
Mackey also said his son was innocent.
</P>
<P>
   Mackey, who works at the local hospital where most of the dead
and injured were taken, signed a book of condolences opened by the
council. He said the bombing was unjustified, but he refused to
condemn it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're back to the word game,'' he said. ``No amount of
words from me can alleviate the suffering of the bereaved and
injured.''
</P>
<P>
   High-ranking officials from the British and Irish governments
held a series of lengthy meetings to plot strategy on how to combat
the ``Real IRA,'' the breakaway group that is suspected of planting
the bomb that exploded amid an afternoon crowd of civilians, most
of them women and children doing back-to-school shopping.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting with Ronnie Flanagan, chief of the Royal Ulster
Constabulary, and Pat Byrne, commissioner of the Garda Siochana,
Ireland's national police force, British Secretary of State for
Northern Ireland Mo Mowlam and Irish Justice Minister John
O'Donoghue said they were prepared to act.
</P>
<P>
   Mowlam and O'Donoghue, however, would not elaborate on their
plans, saying that would tip off the people they were aimed
against. Mowlam said the changes being considered would tighten
security at the border between Northern Ireland and the Irish
Republic, and make it easier to convict someone of membership in an
illegal paramilitary organization.
</P>
<P>
   British Prime Minister Tony Blair and his Irish counterpart,
Bertie Ahern, talked at length last night by telephone about a
security crackdown in wake of the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   But while the governments turned the heat up on the group they
believe perpetrated the atrocity, leaders of the Real IRA's
political wing, including Mackey and Bernadette Sands McKevitt,
denied involvement in the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Sands McKevitt, who is the sister of the dead IRA icon Bobby
Sands, and the wife of Mickey McKevitt, the alleged leader of the
Real IRA, said Ahern was ``very irresponsible'' in accusing the
group of dissident republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Ahern's government, however, remained unmoved by such
protestations of innocence and said it is considering introducing
internment of suspects without trial.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Omagh, meanwhile, the human cost was still being
tallied. The first of dozens of funerals is scheduled to take place
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Kells returned from his vacation to learn that nine of the
dead had died in his clothing shop because the car bomb was parked
in front of the store. One of his salesgirls bent down to retrieve
a pair of shoes from a bottom shelf at the very moment the bomb
exploded. The salesgirl was not seriously injured, but the body of
the woman she was serving was thrown on her by the force of the
blast.
</P>
<P>
   Police also disclosed that one of the dead was a 21-month-old
girl, Breda Devine, who was shopping for shoes with her mother to
be the flower girl in her uncle's wedding next Saturday. Her
mother, Tracey, is one of eight people who remain in critical
condition, among some 100 people still hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Gallagher's brother, who served in the local militia,
was shot dead by the IRA 15 years ago. Monday, Gallagher was
preparing to bury his 21-year-old son, Adrian, killed Saturday by
the bomb when he went shopping for a pair of jeans.
</P>
<P>
   ``My son was raised to respect other people,'' Gallagher said.
``He was killed by those who weren't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
