<P>
   &QL; 
VOL-PROTOUR (Los Angeles) _ The endless summer is a myth. When it
all started in the 1970s, accelerated in the '80s and skyrocketed
in the early '90s, those at the controls of volleyball saw only
upside and prosperty. They saw no sunset, no blustery autumn, no
cold winter on the horizon. The Association of Volleyball
Professionals is barely surviving, as seen by the fact that its
Miller Lite U.S. Championships, which concluded Sunday, plunged
from a $300,000 grand slam to a $50,000 tournament. Years of poor
management forced the Women's Professional Volleyball Association
to scrap its 12-year-old women's doubles tour and the American
Beach Volleyball League to disband its 7-year-old men's and women's
fours circuit this year. Both were overcome by debt. &QL; 
By Dana Haddad. (Will move on the ``s'' sports file.)
</P>
