<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-PAKISTAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICANS IN PAKISTAN URGED TO LEAVE, PROMPTING SKEPTICISM 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By RAYMOND BONNER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan _ The U.S. Ambassador told an anxious
audience of some 150 Americans on Monday afternoon that a charter
plane would be arriving on Tuesday morning to evacuate dependents
of embassy employees and other Americans who wanted to leave the
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has to do with a range of threats against Americans and
especially to American officials,'' Ambassador Thomas W. Simons Jr.
said, explaining why embassy families had been ordered to depart
and the State Department had urged all Americans ``to seriously
consider leaving Pakistan.''
</P>
<P>
   Although there was much skepticism among the audience about the
seriousness of the threat, the fact that a charter plane was coming
added to the tension among those faced with deciding whether to
uproot their families on the day the school year begins.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we leave we are jeopardizing our financial and professional
positions,'' said Kris Steinberg, a high school science teacher at
the International School here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to make reservations but we're going to wait to
find out a little bit more,'' said his wife, Eli Abreu, a
seventh-grade science teacher.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department issued its warning on Sunday, the day it
became widely known that the Pakistani authorities had sent a
suspect in the bombing of the American Embassies in Nairobi and Dar
es Salaam back to Kenya, where he was being interrogated by the
FBI.
</P>
<P>
   One man in the audience asked Simons about rumors that the
United States was about to launch an attack on Osama bin Laden, the
Saudi-born millionaire who has pledged a holy war on the United
States, at bin Laden's base in Afghanistan, and thus wants to clear
Americans from neighboring Pakistan. The ambassador said he would
not comment on that.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly an hour, the Americans badgered Simons with
questions, often sounding like reporters trying to get an American
official to be more forthcoming with intelligence information.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are strongly urged to leave, yet we don't know what we're
running from,'' said one woman, asking Simons if he could be more
specific. He said he could not. He suggested that Washington knew
more than he did.
</P>
<P>
   Simons made it clear, in response to questions, that the
decision to order an evacuation had been made in Washington. And
between his carefully chosen words, there were suggestions that
even Simons, a diplomat with more than 30 years' experience,
thought the State Department had overreacted.
</P>
<P>
   ``This warning indicated to me that people are excited in
Washington,'' Simons said, eliciting mild laughter.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Americans left the auditorium unconvinced and
unhappy. ``I've just gone to a meeting my government held and they
haven't given me one good reason why I should leave, yet they're
bringing in a charter flight to take people out,'' said Mark
Hausfeld, a 40-year-old father of three.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-98 1916EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
