<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-FOCUS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW POLITICAL, LEGAL WOES COULD BESET CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's grand jury testimony is over,
but his legal and political problems may just be beginning.
</P>
<P>
   Legally, Clinton faces the prospect of perjury charges because
he testified seven months ago in a deposition that he did not have
an affair with former White House intern Monica S. Lewinsky.
Independent counsel Kenneth W. Starr, in a report expected to be
sent to Congress, could also outline whether he believes Clinton
urged Lewinsky to lie about their relationship and obstructed
justice, which some Republicans consider an impeachable offense.
</P>
<P>
   Politically, while Clinton held a remarkable 70 percent job
approval rating in one recent poll, the same poll shows the public
has a much lower view of his character, which could embolden some
Republicans to call for hearings that could result in new and
embarrassing revelations about the president.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the coming months could be as exasperating for Clinton
as the year already has been. If Clinton's grand jury testimony
from Monday is released, as is eventually expected, there will be a
dissection of the president's words that could ignite new turmoil
about whether Clinton purposefully evaded the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a guide to what could come next:
</P>
<P>
   _Consequences of the president's changed story. This could be a
publicly painful look at how the president may have used linguistic
contortions to maintain he did not have ``sexual relations'' or an
``affair'' with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   In Clinton's Jan. 17 deposition in the Paula Jones sexual
harassment lawsuit, sexual relations was defined as ``contact with
genitalia, anus, groin, breast, inner thigh, or buttocks of any
person with an intent to arouse or gratify the sexual desire of any
person.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of Clinton's allies have said it is possible Clinton will
say his contact with Lewinsky fell outside the bounds of this
definition, suggesting that oral sex or some other activity didn't
fit this definition.
</P>
<P>
   Still, political leaders as well as legal analysts disagree over
whether Clinton could have committed perjury in the Jones
deposition.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Baron, who brought the impeachment trials of two federal
judges before the Senate in 1989, said he thinks Clinton probably
has some ``maneuvering room'' and can avoid facing perjury charges
stemming from the Jones deposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably as a matter of law there is some legal gray area,''
said Baron, of the Boston law firm Foley, Hoag &AMP; Eliot.
</P>
<P>
   But Senator John Ashcroft, a Missouri Republican who is
pondering a 2000 presidential bid, said on CNN Monday that if
Clinton admits he lied in the Jones deposition, ``it should be the
basis for his resignation.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, some Republicans have asked how Clinton could say in
the Jones deposition that he couldn't remember meeting privately
with Lewinsky in the White House if he is now admitting to some
sort of inappropriate relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Judiciary Committee Chairman Orrin G. Hatch of Utah said
Monday that if Clinton lied in the Jones deposition but told the
truth Monday, Hatch could accept Clinton's apology and would not
seek impeachment hearings.
</P>
<P>
   But Hatch warned that if other wrongdoing by Clinton is
discovered by Starr, or if Clinton lied to the grand jury, then
Hatch would support impeachment hearings. In any case, Hatch said,
``It sickens me'' that some Clinton backers have argued that
Lewinsky's relationship with Clinton was consensual. Hatch said
Congress may look at ``why did this happen'' and whether there is
an ``emotional'' problem that caused it, apparently referring to
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   _Report to Congress. While it has been expected for months that
Starr will deliver a report to the House, this action is more
serious than many people may realize. Starr is authorized to
deliver a report to Congress only if he thinks he has found grounds
for impeachment. Thus, the mere delivery of the report signifies
that Starr believes Congress should act against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   _Possible impeachment hearings. After the House receives Starr's
report, it has the authority to accept it, reject it, or hold its
own investigation. This could lead to months of hearings, including
the first public testimony from Lewinsky and others.
</P>
<P>
   _Possible indictment of others. If Starr finds that Clinton
conspired with others to cover up his relationship with Lewinsky or
another woman, Starr could seek indictment of those
co-conspirators. That information, however, would probably be
turned over to the special three-judge panel that oversees the
independent counsel. Those who might be indicted could seek
immunity from prosecution in exchange for testimony against the
president, possibly at House hearings as well as before the grand
jury.
</P>
<P>
   _Impeachment and aftermath. Most legal analysts said a sitting
president cannot be indicted, but instead would face judgment by
Congress. If the House recommends that Clinton be impeached, the
Senate would hold a trial. If the Senate convicts Clinton, then the
president would be forced out of office.
</P>
<P>
   If that happens, Baron said, Clinton would be an ordinary
citizen and could face indictment like anyone else. If things go
that far, Vice President Al Gore would become president and
inevitably would have to deal with the question of whether to
pardon Clinton for whatever charges he might face.
</P>
<P>
   _Political fallout. Having strongly insisted that he did not
have sexual relations with Lewinsky, Clinton has to reconcile his
changed explanation to his aides, his party, and the public.
</P>
<P>
   It was Hillary Rodham Clinton who said on Jan. 27 that it would
be ``a very serious offense'' if a president committed adultery and
lied about it. But, she added, ``that is not going to be proven
true.'' She maintained that the allegations against her husband
were being put forward by ``a vast right-wing conspiracy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
