<SLUG> BC-REGROWN-THUMB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THUMB TIP COULD LEAD TO DESIGNER ORGANS, DOCTORS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY TYE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The thumb tip that doctors engineered and attached last week to
a Massachusetts man could point to much bigger things to come.
</P>
<P>
   If the thumb grows back as firmly and precisely as they hope,
doctors could soon be using a patient's own tissue to design
everything from jaws to windpipes, leg bones to ligaments.
Eventually, researchers predict, they will even grow new hearts and
livers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first instance of our growing an isolated bone or
virtually any other tissue,'' said Dr. Charles Vacanti, who oversaw
the procedure and runs the Center for Tissue Engineering at the
University of Massachusetts Medical Center in Worcester. ``This
gives us the potential to predesign or preconfigure any tissue in
any shape, from bones to nervous tissues to liver.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Langer, a professor of biomedical engineering at MIT and
a pioneer in tissue engineering, also was enthused: ``This is very
important, it's incredibly important. But at the same time we need
to see what happens over time with this patient.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you do something like this in a person, if it works
well, that's a milestone.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week's procedure is an outgrowth of work Langer and others
launched 15 years ago, when they began molding polymers into
scaffolds onto which living cells could be seeded. Growth factors
were then applied, causing the cells to multiply, fill in the
scaffold, and form a three-dimensional tissue structure that can be
implanted into the body, where it presumably will attach to blood
vessels and grow on its own.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers a decade ago began using the technique to grow new
skin, and last spring the US Food and Drug Administration approved
the first off-the-shelf living skin to treat leg ulcers. The next
step, Langer and others say, is to show they can use a patient's
own cells to grow new cartilage and bone, and to do it not just to
fill in holes or defects, as they have been doing for years, but to
produce free-standing structures like a new ear, trachea or even
the tip of a nose.
</P>
<P>
   Vacanti has succeeded in doing all that _ in mice, rats, sheep,
rabbits and pigs.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's two-hour operation was the first where he and his
associates tried their technique on a human. The patient,
36-year-old Raul Murcia, lost his thumb down to the first knuckle
in an accident seven weeks ago at the recycling company where he
works in Framingham, Mass. The surgeon who treated him sent to
UMass the inch-long severed segment of thumb, along with bone
membrane from Murcia's arm.
</P>
<P>
   The thumb segment proved too contaminated to work with, so
researchers harvested the cells from his arm, fed them nutrients
and kept them in an incubator, eventually turning a couple of
hundred cells into 30 million, which was how many they felt they
needed to reconstitute Murcia's thumb.
</P>
<P>
   The 30 million cells were then suspended in a solution made of
seaweed, giving it a consistency of gelatin. A piece of sea coral,
which is biologically compatible with the bone membrane cells and
chemically similar to bone, had been cut to resemble the missing
thumb and tucked under the loose skin at the top of the severed
digit. The seaweed solution was injected into the coral, a
procedure that protected the solution while it hardened and ensured
it would grow in the shape of the missing thumb tip.
</P>
<P>
   If all goes according to plan, Vacanti explained, the cells will
grow like any new bone, strengthening to the point where tendons
and ligaments can be hooked up and cartilage taken from behind
Murcia's ear can be attached. All that should take four months.
</P>
<P>
   Murcia was sporting a small bandage and a removable plastic cast
Monday, and was ``doing very well,'' said Cary Espinosa, who has
been acting as Murcia's interpreter while her husband serves as his
lawyer. The Guatemalan native, she added, is ``a very humble person
and he thinks this is too much attention on him.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Michael Yaremchuk, a plastic surgeon at Massachusetts
General Hospital, thinks the attention will be well deserved if the
new thumb works. ``It's a big step forward,'' he said. ``Only a
small amount of bone was used but if it works it tells you there is
a potential to replace bigger bones.''
</P>
</TEXT>
