<SLUG> BC-CHECK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STORES TURN TO ELECTRONIC DEBITS FOR COLLECTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAWN GILBERTSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Next time you're asked to endorse a check, it might
not be by your bank.
</P>
<P>
   As part of a push to cut their losses on bad checks, some
retailers are asking check-paying customers for their John Hancock.
The wording varies, but customers are basically giving their OK, if
a check bounces, to electronic collection and the possible
automatic debit of any fees.
</P>
<P>
   Electronic collection, which is quicker and cheaper than
physically sending bounced checks back through the system, has been
around for a couple years but hasn't been widely used because there
were no guidelines, especially in the area of consumer protection,
experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some merchants that didn't want to start this
because there were no rules,'' said Chuck Floyd, vice president of
education for the American Clearing House Association's regional
office in Phoenix. The non-profit group clears checks for banks,
credit unions and other financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
   The National Automated Clearing House Association developed
rules that go into effect on Sept. 18. In a nutshell, they require
merchants and others who accept checks to notify customers of any
electronic collection, or re-presentment, policy. With such a
policy, merchants who previously had to redeposit returned checks
and wait for them to clear _ again _ can now treat them like an
electronic check and have the amount directly debited from the
customer's account.
</P>
<P>
   For stores, the notice could be a sign posted on the counter;
for utilities, a reminder in the monthly bill. Those who plan to
electronically withdraw bounced-check fees from customers' bank
accounts must go a step further and get written permission from
customers.
</P>
<P>
   The 14 Subway stores in Arizona owned by Phoenix-based Food 2000
Inc. have been using an electronic collection policy for a few
weeks. Clerks stamp the authorization form on the back of each
check, and ask customers to initial it. It reads: ``I understand
this store's check collection policy and authorize electronic
debits to my account in accordance with that policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Owner Rick Ueable says the new system is the only reason his
stores are accepting checks again after a two-year hiatus. They
stopped in 1996 because 20 percent of the checks customers wrote
bounced.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a terrible time collecting them,'' Ueable said.
</P>
<P>
   He said they'd send the returned checks back to the banks and,
when that didn't work, would call customers directly to ask them to
come in and make good on the check.
</P>
<P>
   ``That wasn't fun,'' he said. ``It really eats up more of your
time than anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Subway started taking credit cards instead of checks and even
with credit-card processing fees ``it was far cheaper than trying
to collect on bad checks,'' Ueable said.
</P>
<P>
   Ueable says it's too early to know if the electronic collection
system is cutting Subway's bad check losses.
</P>
<P>
   The national clearing house association estimates that
collection efforts could improve by 25 to 50 percent under
electronic collection. About 258 million of the 65 billion to 66
billion checks written every year bounce.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is just a matter of reducing costs for the merchant because
they don't have to go through the whole paper process and run it
through the system,'' said Holly Merrill, executive director of the
ACHA in Phoenix. ``They can get their funds sooner.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if there's no money in the customer's account, it
doesn't matter if the returned check is sent back manually or
electronically. So the program isn't targeting fraud as much as
bounced checks that result from lapses in checkbook math or an
ill-timed play on the float.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd said there already are big success stories from electronic
collection.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's Food and Drug Centers, which has been using an
electronic system for a couple years, has seen its bad check
write-offs fall to $1.8 million last year from $6 million in 1994,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the ways Smith's has used electronic collection to its
advantage is to time the resubmission of returned checks, Floyd
said.
</P>
<P>
   With paper checks, the retailer has no control over when they
are run through the account again. With electronic debits, which
are automatically posted the next day, they're more in control.
</P>
<P>
   ``They might say, `We're going to put them in so they hit on
payday.' '' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dawn Gilbertson may be reached at dawn.gilbertson(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
