<SLUG> BC-CHECKQ&AMP;A-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW RULES HELP BUSINESSES COLLECT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAWN GILBERTSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Retailers and other businesses will be able to collect
on bad checks and fees electronically beginning next month under
new rules by the clearing house network used by banks and other
financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Here, from the National Automated Clearing House Association,
are answers to some commonly asked questions:
</P>
<P>
   Q: What does it mean if a store has an ``electronic
re-presentment'' policy?
</P>
<P>
   A: If your check is returned unpaid for nonsufficient funds, the
merchant can re-present the check electronically. This means an
electronic check transaction is posted to your account instead of
the actual check, which requires a lot of paper shuffling. For
merchants it means quicker collection of their money, assuming
check fraud isn't involved.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's in it for me?
</P>
<P>
   A: Your bad check clears more quickly (assuming this was a lapse
and your account has been replenished) than it would under the
traditional method, so your name will be quickly dropped from
bad-check writer lists many merchants subscribe to and you can
write checks without a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What gives the store permission to electronically debit my
account?
</P>
<P>
   A: Merchants using electronic check collection are required to
provide notice to you before you write your check. As long as this
notice is provided, the merchant can process your bounced check
electronically.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can the merchant or billing company add a collection fee and
charge my account for the total of the check and the fee?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. The merchant can only seek to recover the face amount of
the check. The company may charge your account for a collection fee
only if you have provided express written authorization.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Will my bank or credit union charge a fee for an electronic
check re-presentation?
</P>
<P>
   A: That's up to each financial institution. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Source: National Automated Clearing House Association &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
