<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-17 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8104 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-CLINICS-HNS &LR;      08-17 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-CLINICS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS HEALTH COMMISSIONER TO STOP START-UP FUNDING FOR SCHOOL-BASED
CLINICS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RUTH SoRELLE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Texas health commissioner has decided to halt start-up
funding for school-based clinics, claiming they duplicate existing
facilities and force services such as family planning on
communities that do not want them.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by Dr. William R. Archer III elicited shock and
dismay from advocates for the clinics that usually serve low-income
children with limited access to health care.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the state's anti-abortion movement, meanwhile,
applauded the move as a blow for parental rights.
</P>
<P>
   The change is just one of many planned that will alter the face
of the Texas Department of Health, said Archer, an appointee of
Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Archer said he expects the health department to slowly get out
of providing health services.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not doing any more Band-Aids,'' he said. ``I don't see it
working.''
</P>
<P>
   Archer said he realizes that the school clinic decision may draw
opposition, but he sees problems with the clinics.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, there are historical problems with school health
clinics because they have been viewed a means by which a central
force can come in and implement programs that the community does
not want,'' Archer said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he meant family planning, Archer said yes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am neither for or against school-based clinics,'' Archer
said. ``I am against duplication of services in a community.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a community itself values that (a school) as a site for
delivery of services and they want to build that as a medical
deliverer of service, they better look and say, `What are we
duplicating in the community that we might link with before we
invest a lot of money in a medical model for a school-based
clinic?'''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Stephen Barnett, chairman of the Texas Medical Association's
child and adolescent health committee, disagrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say it's a duplicative service is specious,'' Barnett said.
``People don't just set up school-based clinics willy-nilly. They
go through a needs-assessment process. They ask, `Is there a
population of children who do not have a medical home or who have
trouble accessing health care?' That's sort of the primary reason
you want to have a primary school-based system.''
</P>
<P>
   The school-based health clinic movement in Texas began to build
up steam about six years ago when the health department started
awarding start-up funding for such clinics in three-year grants of
as much as $125,000 annually.
</P>
<P>
   Experts estimate that there now are as many 125 clinics
statewide.
</P>
<P>
   According to the health department, the most frequently used
services include minor injuries, health maintenance exams,
immunizations, ear infections, asthma, allergic ear, nose and
throat problems, eye disorders, respiratory infections and mental
health concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Those clinics that have received grants previously will continue
to be paid during the term of their grants, but there will be no
more money.
</P>
<P>
   Archer's move will affect mainly the development of new clinics,
particularly those in areas of the state where charitable funding
is scant.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Several school-based clinics are scattered throughout the
Houston area. Many began with charitable funds; others depended on
the state health department for seed money.
</P>
<P>
   Vickie Johnson oversees operations at the eight clinics operated
by the Harris County Hospital District. Clinics at Jackson Middle
School in the Houston Independent School District and Smiley High
School in the North Forest ISD were started with state money, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't offer family planning or any reproductive services,''
Johnson said. ``We deal primarily with preventive health care and
treatment for minor acute problems such as ear infections.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bill Price, lobbyist for Texans United for Life, said he thinks
that many of those who are unhappy with the commissioner's decision
are those whose clinics received money.
</P>
<P>
   He said his group opposed school-based clinics because ``by law
you cannot prevent that clinic from abortion counseling and
referrals. You cannot prevent them from dispensing contraceptives
and prescription drugs to teen-agers.''
</P>
<P>
   Archer, however, said that getting out of funding school-based
clinics will be less controversial.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I come in and say the model (for the clinic) should be this
way, it doesn't matter what my position is. I'm going to offend
someone in the community, and I don't think that's my job,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Federal agencies such as the Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention and the National Institutes of Health are recommending
that state health department get out of providing health care
services entirely, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us to be the safety net and to think that we are going to
have a voice compared to that Goliath over there and compete in
service delivery ... we will never make a difference,'' Archer
said.
</P>
<P>
   Archer said he knows that rural areas are a major concern, but
he said the department has funded only two rural clinics.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we are trying to do comprehensive care, why would we set
out to fund duplicative sets of facilities?'' he said. ``Should I
fund two more school-based health clinics in the state of Texas? I
don't think that's the best use of our funds.''
</P>
<P>
   Retta Knox, founder and leader of the school-based clinic in the
Panhandle town of Hart, received one of the first state grants. ``I
actually couldn't have started the clinic any other way,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most small school districts aren't going to gamble and don't
have the financial backing to put money into it,'' Knox said. ``The
start-up money allowed me to prove to them it was a worthwhile
project.''
</P>
<P>
   Her clinic is the only health care available in Hart, Knox said,
and it does not duplicate services.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
