<HEADER>
A8105 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PLAYMATE-COX     08-17 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLAYMATE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Decades after `Playboy' heyday, playmate shows off again
 &HT;    By Jeff Houck
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOCA RATON, Fla. _ There are a couple ways you could analyze
DeDe Lind.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe she's a middle-aged former pinup model angling for one
more grab at the glamour and notoriety she enjoyed as Playboy's
August 1967 Playmate.
</P>
<P>
   Or she could be someone who, at age 51, continues to make a
living exhibiting her abundant physical gifts.
</P>
<P>
   Just for fun, let's say it's the latter because, hey, it is a
lot more fun.
</P>
<P>
   That this beach-going, water-skiing, roller-skating, divorced
mother can relaunch her nude modeling career from her Boca Raton
condo at an age when most women are concerned with just keeping
body parts from sagging south, is enough to give aging Baby Boomers
a glimmer of hope. Or a pang of jealousy.
</P>
<P>
   Lind sells _ by mail order _ pictures of herself in skimpy
lingerie or bathing suits or nothing at all. Videos shot in the
Cayman Islands and Key West show her posing and frolicking with her
mixed-breed dog, Tasha. The outfits and frilly lingerie she wears
are also for sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``My whole outlook is that I don't feel age is a big deal,''
says Lind, who has a few wrinkles that betray her years, but whose
tanned, toned body could qualify her as a senior lifeguard on
``Baywatch.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not because I'm afraid of aging . . . I'm just vain,''
she said with a breathy giggle as she sat on the couch in her small
condominium. From her porch you can see a glassy Atlantic Ocean.
Piles of sea shells and pieces of coral collected from shoreline
strolls sit in bowls and trays or on the floor next to the wicker
furniture. She's the portrait of a grown-up beach girl, with her
beaded flip flops, low-cut sarong-style wrap dress and gold sand
dollar medallion hanging on a thin chain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Age is just a number for me,'' she says. Her age doesn't seem
to bother her fans, either.
</P>
<P>
   Lind still has a legion of followers who remember her first
Playboy photo layout. Wearing a pea-green bikini and a yellow bow
in her poofy blond hair, the photos struck a chord, especially with
soldiers overseas in Vietnam who adored her coquettish, homespun
quality. She wasn't glamorous or intimidatingly gorgeous. She was
cute, petite and approachable. (For the record: 34C-22-33. Turn
ons: Water skiing, horseback riding. Turn offs: Phony people.
Ambitions: To be healthy and happy.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up with Playboy, saw it for the first time when I was
about 14 or 15,'' she said. ``I always wanted to be in Playboy.''
</P>
<P>
   After the photos ran, more than 1,600 letters arrived at the
magazine from fans, most of whom begged for autographed pictures.
To this day, that total ranks Lind as one of the magazine's most
popular playmates ever, said Mary O'Connor, longtime personal
secretary and administrative assistant to Playboy publisher Hugh
Hefner.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's as sweet as could be, a girl's girl with a million and
one friends,'' O'Connor said. ``She's a typical Playmate. . . a
real girl next door with the ponytail and braids.''
</P>
<P>
   Playboy wasn't Lind's first modeling job. Discovered by a
photographer at 14 while at a public swimming pool in Burbank,
Calif., she posed for teen magazine covers and acted in commercials
and on The Donna Reed Show, The Rifleman, and Leave It To Beaver.
</P>
<P>
   She got pregnant and married right after graduating from high
school, had a baby at age 19 and was divorced by 20.
</P>
<P>
   A newly minted single mom who had to earn a living, she thought
of posing for Playboy. A photographer had shown pictures of her to
the magazine's editors when she was 17, but when they found out her
age, they told her to come back when she was older.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pretty well developed for my age,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1967, she finally got her shot as the Playmate of the Month.
It wasn't easy _ she had never posed nude before and was shy about
doing so. But the photographer was easy to work with and made the
job easier.
</P>
<P>
   She married again after her 1967 centerfold ran and continued to
pose for occasional layouts and calendars, but her career cooled.
</P>
<P>
   On her 30th birthday, Lind broke down and cried, thinking her
career was over. ``Very few models other than, say, Cheryl Tiegs,
have much of a career after 30 or 35,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She dedicated herself to being a dutiful mother and housewife.
Lind later moved to Florida in 1984, and was divorced again in
1989. She worked as a restaurant hostess for a while, but it wasn't
until about four years ago that modeling re-entered her life.
</P>
<P>
   Lind rediscovered her fans when she was invited with other
Playmates to appear at a convention called Glamourcon (featuring
pinup art, Hollywood actresses and models).
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe that after all this time people would pay
for an autograph,'' she said, noting one fan put one of her poses
on his belt buckle. ``It's amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   At one show, a Vietnam vet told the tale of how his barracks
were bombed and half the building was destroyed, but he went back
and retrieved her centerfold, which was torn in half by the blast.
``I offered him another one but he didn't want it,'' she said. ``He
said it brought him good luck.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Bucha, a president of the Congressional Medal of Honor
Society, wrote a few years ago to say that it was her picture that
hung on the wall of his Army company's shelter. ``I can assure you
that many guys were inspired to make it back (to the U.S.) because
of the pictorial.'' Lind framed the letter and displays it proudly.
</P>
<P>
   Lind began selling her old Playboy photos at conventions,
expanding the selection about two years ago when a boyfriend took
some nude shots during a vacation in Cancun. Though the amateur
images don't have the Playboy look, but they're selling well, she
said. A friend set up a page for her on the World Wide Web
(http://www.getup.net/centerfolds) so fans could place orders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to keep shooting until I can't do it anymore,'' she
said. ``You have to keep yourself out there. I love what I do.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Houck writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-98 2003EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
