<DOCNO> NYT19980817.0349 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-17 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8106 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STOCKS-PRIMER-COX     08-17 2072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STOCKS-PRIMER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bulls, bears and the big board
 &HT;    By Douglas Kalajian
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The president's testifying about his sex
life, Iraq's acting feisty again and it seems like half the players
in the major leagues are threatening to break Roger Maris' home run
record.
</P>
<P>
   Who has time for any of it? We're all watching The Dow go up and
down.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, we. It's OK to admit it. Nobody rants about the excesses of
capitalism any more, not since 401(k) entered the national
vocabulary.
</P>
<P>
   Problem is, who knew? Some of us wasted too much of our youth
reading Rolling Stone instead of Barron's, Jack Kerouac instead of
Milton Friedman. Some of us were just wasted, period.
</P>
<P>
   So now that we're at least as worried about saving for
retirement as saving the Earth, it's sometimes a little hard to
follow the news about the effect of declining issues on broad
market indicators.
</P>
<P>
   You just want to know if your money's safe, but all you hear is
that the Big Board closed higher as the bulls out-muscled the
bears, but we may be overdue for a correction, so watch the yield
on the long bond.
</P>
<P>
   That's why we bring you The Accent Stock Market Guide, written
by one of your own _ a man who, most of his life, paid as much
attention to the stock market as to, well, the bond market. Or the
Olympic curling competition.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, a man who knew absolutely nothing about it until
last week. So be warned: This is not for the sophisticated
investor. And sophisticated or not, you should look elsewhere for
investment advice. But this may just help you translate the advice
you get into something you can understand. THE DOW
</P>
<P>
   The yo-yo that has the nation transfixed is properly called the
Dow Jones industrial average, the stock market's version of the
Nielsen ratings. It's a small sample of influential stocks, 30 big
companies, used to gauge the market's overall performance. The
average is translated into a number that doesn't really correspond
to anything except itself, so a Dow of 8,000 doesn't mean there are
8,000 Dows somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   There are other indicators, too, drawn from other stock prices.
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500, for example, is an index of 500 big
corporations.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow hit 9337, its highest point ever, just three weeks ago.
Then it bumped down and jumped up several times before landing at
8434 last Friday. But that's still up from 7908 at the end of last
year.
</P>
<P>
   The people who analyze such things seem to think the drop is
related to spreading economic trouble in Asia and worries about a
drop in corporate profits in America that could be partly caused by
the Asian turmoil. _ What it all means
</P>
<P>
   The Dow and other indicators measure the value of stock based on
the latest day's trading on the New York Stock Exchange and the
American Stock Exchange. Stocks listed on the NYSE (known as the
Big Board) or the AMEX are traded by brokers on the floor of the
exchanges. You're not allowed to join in, so you have to pay a
broker to buy and sell for you.
</P>
<P>
   (There's also the Nasdaq, which, surprisingly, has nothing to do
with automobile racing. Nasdaq listings, including many high-tech
companies, can be bought from security dealers. That's called over
the counter.)
</P>
<P>
   If you own stocks that kept pace with The Dow, you made money
this year but not as much as you would have if it kept going up. Of
course, there is no stock that keeps pace with The Dow. Your stocks
may have gone up and stayed there, or gone higher. Or, they may
have disappeared from the financial radar screen.
</P>
<P>
   _ So why buy stock?
</P>
<P>
   When you buy a company's common stock, you become one of the
company's owners, except they don't give you an office. What they
do, if you're lucky, is pay you a dividend, which is a share of the
company's profit. That's one way to make money in the stock market.
But big money usually comes from selling stock to someone who
thinks it's worth more than you paid.
</P>
<P>
   There are lots of reasons someone might think that: He might see
that the company is increasingly successful, or have a hunch it
will be; he might know something about the company's management or
product plans; or, he might just be a cheese brain. As long as
people keep wanting to pay more for the stock, you can hold onto it
and celebrate every time the price goes up. But you never know when
people will stop wanting to buy your stock, which will make the
price go down. It could even go way below what you paid and not
come up again. Then you're the cheese brain.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bulls and bears
</P>
<P>
   Investors, being more polite as well as poetic, prefer to think
of each other as Bulls and Bears. Bulls charge ahead and buy, so a
market with rising prices is a bull market. Bears, named by someone
who was never chased by one, are more cautious. A falling market is
a Bear market. We've been in a Bull market for years, even though
prices have fallen recently. That's at least partly because no one
likes the idea of calling it a Bear market because that might touch
off a panic, which is even worse. So a short-term drop in prices is
called a correction, which sounds much better.
</P>
<P>
   _ You must believe
</P>
<P>
   Bulls and Bears are powerful figures, but the more apt image
might be Peter Pan: The stock market soars only as long as people
believe it will. That's called investor confidence. The biggest
confidence booster is a rise in corporate profits, or some reason
to think they'll rise. That's why investors get excited about new
products or technology. Any hint of a drop in profits has the
opposite effect, but not necessarily on the entire market. That's
why it's smart to spread out investments, not just among companies
but across different types of companies. That's called
diversification. You might lose a little on toothpicks but gain on
dental floss and then pick up a few shares of false teeth, just in
case.
</P>
<P>
   _ Picking a winner
</P>
<P>
   So how do you decide what stock to invest in? That depends what
you're looking for. Stocks that aren't likely to rise can be good
investments if they pay strong dividends and also aren't likely to
go down. Some stocks of big, well-known companies fit into this
category. They're called blue chips. But you can't rely on size or
even reputation, because stock in big companies can take big drops.
Cheaper stocks in smaller companies may more easily double or
triple in price, but may be just as likely to turn into wallpaper
overnight. Anyone who wants to invest money in individual stocks
needs to first invest time in learning about the market and in
deciding how much risk is acceptable. In other words: How much
could you lose before you start crying in front of the neighbors?
</P>
<P>
   _ Flying solo
</P>
<P>
   If you decide to buy a stock, you have two basic choices: Go to
a broker, or sit at your computer. There are lots of discount
brokers on line these days. Discount brokers charge less than full
service brokers but don't offer all the advice. Whether you want a
broker's advice is another matter. You can find plenty of advice in
newspapers, magazines and on the Internet, and you can pay an
investment adviser. Once you decide what you want, you'll pay a fee
to buy and probably another fee to sell. That's another of the
stock market's little catches: You might make a few hundreds
dollars trading stocks but spend just as much in commissions if
you're not careful.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mutual interests
</P>
<P>
   Small investors today are likely to choose mutual funds over
individual stocks. It's especially true for 25 million Americans
who contribute to 401(k) retirement plans that allow them to put
off taxes on their savings and interest until they retire. Mutual
funds pool money from many investors; the fund manager picks the
stocks and decides when to buy or sell. The ``load'' you hear so
much about is a fee, which can seriously reduce your earnings. A
no-load fund sounds more attractive, but it can have less-obvious
fees. The main benefit of a mutual fund is that you can leave all
the decisions to a professional. The main drawback is that you're
likely to do just that. Some do a brilliant job. Some don't. There
are high-risk funds that aim for growth and lower-risk funds that
take a more conservative approach, but there's no such thing as a
no-risk mutual fund.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hauling with history
</P>
<P>
   If this still sounds intimidating, consider the long haul
theory. Stock market fans are quick to point out that the market's
value has always risen over time and that the historic return is
greater than for most other forms of investment. So while stock
prices may drop over a few weeks, months or even years, hang on
long enough and they're almost sure to bounce back and rise even
higher.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there's a catch or two. The long haul can get pretty
long; it took more than 20 years for the market to climb back to
where it was before the Depression. Even then, a rise in the
market's average won't do you any good if you invest in today's
version of whaling ships or Hupmobiles.
</P>
<P>
   Both probably seemed like sure bets in their day, so before you
dive into the market with some high-tech gem touted by your
brother-in-law, you need to think hard about how much you can
afford to lose and how long you can wait to make a profit. And
about whether there's even a vague resemblance between a computer
chip and, say, a whaling ship.
</P>
<P>
   Long-range view best for investors
</P>
<P>
   Out of respect for our readers' life savings, Accent also asked
a professional for her thoughts on the stock market. Maria Crawford
Scott is editor of the AAII Journal, which offers advice to the
175,000 members of the American Association of Independent
Investors.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What should the average investor make of all the stock market
news these days, especially when so much is hard to follow?
</P>
<P>
   A: A lot of investment professionals don't know what it means
either. A lot of what you hear day to day comes out of Wall Street,
from traders rather than from investment managers. They have
different mentalities. A lot of the feeling you get from the
jargon, the buzzwords, is from a trading perspective, not a
long-term investment perspective. You hear the Dow was down on a
volume of blah-blah. That doesn't tell you whether the economy is
sound.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's making prices drop?
</P>
<P>
   A: Stock prices follow the long-term trend of the economy.
They're based on what people expect. When people realize they're
been too optimistic, prices come down to a more realistic level. As
for what's happening now, some trader could give you an answer
based on day-to-day trades, and that might be correct in terms of
the moment, but it's harder to tell what translates into a
long-term trend.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What if this is the beginning of a downward trend? Should
average investors, especially people who have their savings in a
401(k), be worried?
</P>
<P>
   A: Only if you're in the market and don't understand it. You
need to know how the stock market works so you can adjust your
portfolio to avoid taking risks you don't want to take. If you do
that, you probably won't run into trouble. But if you don't
understand that market, if you don't understand that there are
periods of over-valuation and times the market will fall, then you
can be over-committed to an area or pull out at the wrong time and
be hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Sounds like anyone who doesn't know what adjustments you're
talking about should be worried. Is that accurate?
</P>
<P>
   A: You might want to learn quick. Most plans offer information
about risks and ways to lower it. Most employers offer good
information. There are lots of books available. The great thing
about a 401(k) is you don't have to understand all the ins and out
of financial analysis. If you want to just forget about it, you can
go to a lower-risk investment option: Treasury bills or short-term,
fixed-income. But those have risk too, mainly the risk of not
earning as much as you expected so that you don't save as much as
you need for retirement.
</P>
<P>
   AAII is a not-for-profit organization formed in 1978 to help
individuals manage their assets. The journal is published 10 times
a year and accepts no advertising. More information about the
organization is available on the Internet at http://www.aaii.com or
at (800) 428-2244.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Kalajian writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
