<SLUG> BC-TV-ANYDAYNOW-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Acting superb in Lifetime's poignant `Any Day'
 &HT;    By Kevin D. Thompson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ TV's a strange business. Just when you
think you'll never see a promising new show again, Lifetime _ yes,
Lifetime of all places! _ serves up three potential winners.
</P>
<P>
   The first is ``Any Day Now,'' a poignant, heartwarming show
about race relations that could easily become the season's best _
and most intelligent _ drama.
</P>
<P>
   Debuting Aug. 18, ``Any Day Now'' tells the story of two
childhood friends (one white, one black) who grew up in Alabama
during the height of the turbulent civil rights movement.
</P>
<P>
   As they got older, the women, Mary Elizabeth (Annie Potts) and
Rene (Lorraine Toussaint), grew apart and didn't speak for more
than 20 years. While a career-minded Rene left to become a
high-powered, Washington, D.C., attorney, the often-bitter Mary
Elizabeth stayed behind, married her childhood sweetheart and had
three children.
</P>
<P>
   The two are reunited when Rene goes back home after her civil
rights leader dad (a quietly dignified Courtney B. Vance) dies. Now
both women must come to grips with the choices they made in life.
While Mary Elizabeth wonders if she made a mistake by having
children at 19, the driven Rene ponders if she'll ever have a
family.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Elizabeth and Rene also struggle to heal their
relationship, which became strained when Rene didn't support Mary
Elizabeth's pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   Potts and Toussaint are superb as the still ill-at-ease friends.
What a joy to watch two old _ well, they're not so old _ pros work.
One moment they're drinking coffee and catching up on old times,
the next they're remembering the trying days when they hurled
epithets at each other.
</P>
<P>
   We care so much for these multilayered characters because
through telling black-and-white flashbacks, we learn how this taboo
friendship developed. The fact that those flashbacks are set in a
racially divided Birmingham (or Bombingham, as it was called in
those days), makes ``Any Day Now'' more interesting and chillingly
disturbing.
</P>
<P>
   Potts doesn't believe ``Any Day Now'' would work on a major
network. She's probably right. NBC tried in 1991 with ``I'll Fly
Away,'' a well-meaning show about race relations in the South in
the late 1950s. It was canceled after two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to do a show much like this and dealing with the same
issues in `Dangerous Minds','' says Potts, of the axed ABC
inner-city teacher drama. ``And they didn't give it a proper
shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Potts notes that playing Mary Elizabeth is not much of a stretch
for her. She grew up on a farm where a black family lived in a
tenant house. While the husband worked on the farm, the wife was
her family's cook.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up with all of her children,'' she recalls. ``They were
my closest playmates because there wasn't anybody else around. I
was raised by this wonderful black woman, so it was always hard for
me to understand hard feelings between different (races). She
rocked me to sleep every night of my life until I was about 8 years
old.''
</P>
<P>
   Toussaint, a Trinidad native, says she had no reference points
for racism after coming to the United States when she was little.
In fact, Toussaint had never even heard of The Rev. Dr. Martin
Luther King Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember my first experience with Martin Luther King,'' she
remembers. ``It was my sixth birthday, or something, and my mom was
making a birthday cake. She was standing in the kitchen, icing my
cake and she was crying while she was doing it. I went over to her
and said, `Why are you crying?' And she said, `A very important man
was killed today and his name was Martin Luther King.' And I was
just so angry at him. I wanted to know who in the world had enough
power to make my mother cry on my birthday?''
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years later, a powerful drama called ``Any Day Now''
should bring a few tears to your eyes.
</P>
<P>
   By Kevin D. Thompson is a television critic for the Palm Beach
Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
