<HEADER>
A8108 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-LIFETIME-COX     08-17 0521
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-LIFETIME-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lifetime's new sitcoms both hip _ and funny
 &HT;    By Kevin D. Thompson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Talk about girl power!
</P>
<P>
   Forget The Spice Girls. Check out Lifetime's new
I-am-woman-hear-me-roar comedies. Both ``Maggie'' and ``Oh, Baby''
are fresh, clever sitcoms. But, more importantly, they're pretty
funny too.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Lifetime's programs are geared toward women, men
should also get a kick out of these somewhat groundbreaking shows.
And it'll be a nice switch to turn on the channel for one night
without having to look at those awful women-in-danger movies.
</P>
<P>
   Of the two new entries, ``Maggie'' (Tuesday night at 10) stands
out. Ann Cusack (``The Jeff Foxworthy Show'') stars as Maggie Day,
a bored, 40-year-old woman stuck in a rut. (Think Ally McBeal 10
years from now.) Her cardiologist husband (John Getz) barely
notices her. Her 17-year-old daughter (Morgan Nagler) hangs out all
the time with her best friend, a budding cartoonist who pretends to
be gay.
</P>
<P>
   Maggie takes charge of her life by going to veterinarian school
and working part-time at an animal clinic. There, she meets Richard
(John Slattery), a fun-loving, silly vet who is everything her
self-absorbed hubby isn't.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the twinkle is back in Maggie's eyes. Although that's
a good thing, Maggie feels a tad guilty since she can't stop
thinking about her goofy boss.
</P>
<P>
   As Maggie, Cusack is positively delightful. She has a breezy
style and lighthearted touch that work well here. And the chemistry
between Maggie and Richard is fun to watch. Although we know Maggie
won't give in to her obvious desires, it's fun watching her keep
herself in check.
</P>
<P>
   While ``Maggie'' features a bored married woman, ``Oh, Baby''
(Tuesday at 10:30) is about a thirtysomething career woman who
desperately wants to get hitched and start a family. But Tracy
(``Hope &AMP; Gloria'''s Cynthia Stevenson) is tired of waiting for Mr.
Right to pop the question. After Tracy's dense boyfriend (Daniel
Hugh Kelly) gives her the wrong kind of ring (a friendship ring, as
opposed to one of those 18-karat jobs) she decides to get
artificially inseminated and have a baby on her own.
</P>
<P>
   Her boyfriend doesn't get it, though, since he thinks only
lesbians get pregnant with that ``turkey baster thing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, Baby'' uses a clever device that has Tracy talking
directly to the viewer while she watches her life unfold on TV.
With a remote in hand, she can pause whenever she wants and add any
commentary she likes.
</P>
<P>
   Like ``Maggie,'' ``Oh, Baby'' also benefits from fine casting.
Stevenson is instantly likable as Tracy; Joanna Gleason is
pleasingly sarcastic as a tart-tongued shrink and the ageless
Jessica Walter is in fine form as the skeptical mom.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the broadcast networks can take some lessons from
Lifetime. After all, the cable network is batting 1.000. Two new
comedies. Two funny shows.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin D. Thompson is a television critic for the Palm Beach
Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
