<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves notebook: Wohlers' problems continue
 &HT;    By I. J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Mark Wohlers' 10-day stay at Class AAA Richmond ends
later this week, but the reliever doesn't seem to be getting much
better.
</P>
<P>
   In three appearances since going to Richmond, Wohlers has thrown
2 1/3 innings and struck out four, but he has allowed two runs,
walked seven and thrown six wild pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a ways to go,'' Richmond pitching coach Bill Fischer
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Wohlers has only three more days at Richmond, under the deal
he worked out with the Braves when he agreed to return to the
minors. It seems clear that he needs more time in the minors, but
the club is unsure what he wants to do.
</P>
<P>
   If he does want to return to Atlanta, the Braves might have no
choice but to put him on the disabled list. The Braves, trying to
get their bullpen ready for the postseason, are concentrating on
getting another lefthander to go along with rookie John Rocker.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta has two other lefties in the pen, Norm Charlton and Adam
Butler, and additional help might be at Richmond, where Pedro
Borbon has five strikeouts in his last three appearances. Borbon,
who was instrumental when the Braves won the World Series in 1995,
hasn't pitched in the majors in more than two years after elbow
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets, tickets, tickets
</P>
<P>
   The best chance to catch the Braves on this seven-game homestand
will be the next three nights, with 40,000 tickets sold for each
game. The Braves expect to sell standing-room-only tickets for
games Friday and Saturday, and they have sold 42,000 tickets for
Sunday night's game and 37,000 for Monday's game, which starts at
1:10 p.m. Also, tickets remain on sale for the division playoff
series; they can be purchased at the Turner Field ticket office,
which opens at 8:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Around the horn
</P>
<P>
   The Braves swept the Giants 10 days ago, but San Francisco comes
to town on a three-game winning streak. The Giants took three from
the Marlins over the weekend while Barry Bonds served a three-game
suspension. ``We got the best of both worlds,'' manager Dusty Baker
said. ``We won without Barry, and he got a well-deserved and
unplanned rest.'' The Giants are 5-2 without Bonds in the lineup
this season. . . . The Braves bullpen had a 1.88 ERA on the recent
nine-game road trip. . . . In Richmond, manager Jeff Cox has left
the team for personal reasons. Cox told his players he was leaving
because of his ill mother. Coach Max Venable has taken over.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
