<SLUG> BC-BBN-WILDCARD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thanks to the Wildcard addition, much is still to be decided
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When Bud Selig introduced an expanded playoff format
and two wild-card spots in the winter of 1993, he upset many
baseball purists.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would have thought I defiled motherhood,'' Selig,
baseball's commissioner, said Monday. ``But you don't hear a peep
out of them now. And I have said to many people recently, 'Can you
imagine where we would be this year if we didn't have have the wild
card?'''
</P>
<P>
   With no wild card, baseball's regular season would, for the most
part, be finished. Five of the six division races have been
decided:
</P>
<P>
   _ The Braves lead by 14 1/2 games in the National League East.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Astros lead by eight games in the NL Central.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Padres lead by 14 games in the NL West.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Yankees lead by 19 1/2 games in American League East.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Indians lead by 11 1/2 games in the AL Central.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the AL West offers the only race: The Angels lead the
Rangers by 1/2 game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is working brilliantly,'' Selig said. ``It is working like
we thought it would. Then I think of the criticism I took
personally. Our fans like it; it is preserving September.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants, for example, would be out of the playoff picture
without the wildc ard, but they arrive in Atlanta today for an
important two-game series against the Braves. San Francisco trails
the Cubs by two games. The Mets are half a game behind the Cubs,
and four other teams are within nine games.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants, Cubs and Mets all have seen increases in attendance
because of the wild card. The Cubs are up 12 percent over last
year, the Mets are up 23 percent, and the Giants are up 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The AL race is not as close, but the Orioles remain seven behind
the Red Sox and have made a strong recovery from a 15 1/2-game
deficit at the All-Star break. Baltimore and Boston play six times
during the final two weeks of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now live in a world with 30 teams, and I think you need
more than four in the postseason,'' said Braves president Stan
Kasten, who was on the committee that voted to adopt the wild card.
``Realistically, you have to give enough teams a chance to have
something to work for their entire season. We thought it would
extend the interest in twice as many cities.''
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies are a good example of how the system works. The
team is rebuilding, yet it has stayed in the race. Attendance has
increased by 16 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the wild-card situation creates hope in other cities,
where in the past, things would have locked up two months ago,''
Phillies general manager Ed Wade said. ``It has created another
dynamic for us. Our fans are looking at progress, and out of the
corner of their eye they are still looking at the wild-card
standings, trying to figure out if, we can get on a seven or
eight-game winning streak, we can get right in the thick of it. In
the other format, they looked at the first-place club and were
waiting for football to start.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
