<DOCNO> NYT19980817.0355 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-17 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8112 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-GATORS-COX     08-17 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GATORS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAINESVILLE, Fla. _ For the first 19 years of his life, Doug
Johnson was quite comfortable playing the role of golden boy here.
</P>
<P>
   He was handsome, popular and a superstar athlete here at
Buchholz High. Fellow students admired and envied him. Parents
wanted their sons to be like him.
</P>
<P>
   Professional baseball beckoned with promises of riches, but the
Florida Gators offered him a chance to play quarterback and become
the ultimate hometown hero.
</P>
<P>
   A tough decision? Hardly. Always confident, Doug would simply do
both. For Johnson, it all came so easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``All through high school, I really didn't have to work at
all,'' Johnson said. ``I've really never had to work hard in
anything I ever did.''
</P>
<P>
   Those days are over, Johnson concedes. In the past year, reality
has hit Doug Johnson in a series of waves, each one a little
harder, each one making it more difficult to climb to his feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I look at it, things can't get any worse than they did
last year,'' he said. ``It can only get better. At least that's
what I keep telling myself.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Johnson realized one of his lifelong dreams when he
became the starting quarterback at Florida. He replaced Danny
Wuerffel, the Heisman Trophy winner and perhaps the most admired
player in school history. Then the roller-coaster ride began:
</P>
<P>
   _ He played well with a 7 TD performance against Central
Michigan. Some sports writers dared to link his name with the
Heisman.
</P>
<P>
   _ He played poorly with four interceptions in a 28-21 loss at
LSU. For the first time in his life as an athlete, Johnson received
significant criticism.
</P>
<P>
   _ The criticism grew worse a few days later when it was revealed
he broke curfew partying at a local nightspot the Thursday before
the LSU game. He was suspended from the team and publicly
embarrassed.
</P>
<P>
   _ When Johnson returned to the team, he had lost his job and his
confidence. After throwing two first-half interceptions against
Georgia, he was yanked in favor of Noah Brindise, a former walk-on.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sharing the job with Brindise, Johnson made the play of the
season when his 63-yard pass to Jacquez Green set up the winning
touchdown in a 32-29 upset of No. 1 Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   _ Just when it appeared that the clouds over Johnson's football
career were clearing, his athletic body, the one thing he could
always count on, betrayed him. Johnson had shoulder surgery on May
8 to repair damage to the rotator cuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guess you could say my life's been pretty complicated
lately,'' said Johnson, who turns 21 on Oct. 27.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of his junior season at Florida, Johnson is trying to
get his shoulder back in shape. He is in a dogfight for the
starting quarterback job with sophomore Jesse Palmer _ not exactly
where he hoped to be at this point of his career.
</P>
<P>
   The surgery, however, has provided unexpected dividends.
Rehabbing the shoulder forced him to give up minor-league baseball
for the summer and remain in Gainesville to work on his
conditioning. As a result, Johnson is physically more mature than
he has ever been.
</P>
<P>
   The hours spent in therapy also forced Johnson to take stock of
his emotional maturity. In retrospect, Johnson realizes he wasn't
ready for the mental demands of becoming a starting quarterback at
the SEC level. After watching Weurffel win the Heisman and just
about every other major award in 1996, Johnson assumed the same
praise automatically was awaiting him.
</P>
<P>
   The summer before the 1997 season, while Johnson was playing
minor-league baseball in West Virginia, he was constantly hearing
from those who already has annointed him as the next great Gator
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had four or five reporters calling every day. I was high on
life,'' Johnson said. ``I was 19 years old, and I was the the
starting quarterback for the defending national championships.I was
eating it up and loving it.''
</P>
<P>
   But after the LSU game, and all the fallout that came with it,
Johnson discovered how quickly the crowd can turn. The love the
Gator faithful had showered on Wuerffel every week, which Johnson
had had for a few precious Saturdays, was nowhere to be found. ''It
was like everybody was waiting for me to mess up.
</P>
<P>
   There's a different feeling when I go out there than when
Wuerffel went out there,'' he said. ``I can feel it. There's not as
warm a feeling. I think they want me to succeed, but they also want
me to carry my weight.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson learned that the respect and admiration Wuerffel
received came from four years of exemplary behavior, both on the
field and off. Wuerffel had struggled as a freshman with limited
skills. He became a Heisman winner and the school's all-time
leading passer through hard work and personal sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always saw Danny talking to people and accepting all those
awards, but I never saw how he got there,'' Johnson said. ``Danny
made a lot of sacrifices to be successful. I was thinking all I had
to do was just go out on the field and play well, but that's not
it. That's not even half of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is convinced that Johnson has turned an emotional
corner. One of those still waiting for proof is Spurrier. When
others suggest that the events of the past year have matured
Johnson, Spurrier's verbal response is muted. But his body language
is clear: Johnson must prove it every single day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel confident we have two quarterbacks capable of playing,
but we don't know how it's going to play out,'' Spurrier said in
his standard assessment of the position. ``If we have to use both
of them to win for the Gators, then that's what we'll do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know coach Spurrier wants one of us to step up and take the
job. He's not going to give it to either one of us,'' Johnson said.
``I also know that, no matter what, coach Spurrier will always put
the best player on the field. I have to prove to him that it's
me.''
</P>
<P>
   So now, Doug Johnson's mission is clear. For the first time in
his charmed life as an athlete, he has faced adversity. His
confidence has not been shaken, but it has been tempered. And as
the 1998 season approaches, Johnson has been forced to face this
uncomfortable fact: For the fair-haired boy of Buchholz High, time
is running out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want people looking back (on my career) and saying,
'That Johnson kid had a lot of potential, but he didn't know when
and where to use it,''' Johnson said. ``I can't let that happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
