<HEADER>
A8113 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-TRAINING-CARDINAL     08-17 1053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-TRAINING-CARDINALS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLAGSTAFF, Ariz. _ The two-lane interstate that connects Phoenix
to the training camp site of the Arizona Cardinals is a
topographical kaleidoscope. It winds through miles of barren desert
and long stretches of cactus and scrub grass, then passes east of
new-age mecca Sadona, before gently easing into the kind of terrain
more frequently associated with Colorado ski resorts.
</P>
<P>
   Cynics might suggest that the Cardinals' summer aerie, 7,000
feet above sea level, is the highest this perennial loser will ever
rise. Visible beyond three practice fields ringed by majestic pine
trees, however, lies Humphreys Peak. And at 12,633 feet, the
tallest point in the state is a daily reminder to Arizona players
of the lofty aspirations they harbor for 1998.
</P>
<P>
   This is the 100th anniversary for a club once dubbed ``The
Futile Franchise'' during its ramshackle run in St. Louis, and
players would like it to be something special.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, it's there for us every day, and it's become a symbol of
where we feel we can go _ all the way to the top,'' fullback Larry
Centers, one of the team's long-suffering veterans, said after a
morning practice last week. ``The way it's been here for too long
is that we've gone through the motions of being a football team.
But this year seems to be different. There's more purpose, . . .
and there's certainly more belief in each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden, we're a 'buzz' team,'' Centers said. ``People
are actually talking about us.''
</P>
<P>
   The once-woeful Card have become a chic pick among league
insiders seeking a dark-horse playoff candidate for this season.
</P>
<P>
   Six of 10 general managers surveyed by The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution cited Arizona as the NFC doormat most likely
to surprise fans with a breakthrough performance. All 10 agreed
that Arizona is considered an ascending team.
</P>
<P>
   Given that the Cardinals haven't qualified for the postseason
since the truncated 1982 season, the longest current drought in the
NFL, some skeptics can be forgiven.
</P>
<P>
   Originally founded in 1898 as the Morgan Athletic Club on
Chicago's rough-and-tumble Southside, the team, despite owning the
distinction as the oldest continuously run pro football franchise,
has made just six playoff appearances. No team in existence at the
time of the 1970 merger has fewer playoff appearances than
Arizona's three. Over the last decade, the Cardinals' 55-105 record
is the NFL's second-worst.
</P>
<P>
   Even last year, the Cardinals won just four times, hardly a
victory total that justifies the rampant optimism by team
management and fans in the Valley of the Sun.
</P>
<P>
   All-Pro cornerback Aeneas Williams and other players try to make
sure that the Cardinals' nucleus of young talent isn't burdened by
the hideous history. One of the league's classiest players off the
field and a four-time Pro Bowl performer on it, Williams typically
is the last guy into the locker room. He finishes every practice
with a short prayer circle, then follows that with a tutorial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eight years and I never lost faith, so I don't want these
young guys getting down,'' Williams said. ``I measure my own
success by my ability to raise the performance of those around me.
Sometimes that's with words. Sometimes it's by pulling. Other times
it's by pushing. And there are times it's a combination of the
three. I tell the younger players, 'Men, the environment for change
is always present if the attitude is good.' What we've done now is
eliminate all those old excuses for our failures, and we've
accomplished it by keeping a great attitude. I think that message
is pretty well-rooted around here.''
</P>
<P>
   These Cards certainly have more talent than in the past to heed
Williams' sales pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Oft-criticized owner Bill Bidwill, as easy a target in St. Louis
and Phoenix as Rankin Smith was in Atlanta, still is apt to show up
at practices in a bush jacket and with a scruffy beard, as he did
last week. But he has turned over much of the operation to his
sons, Bill Jr. and Michael, and vice president of player personnel
Bob Ferguson, and the results have been encouraging.
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson, with John Butler, now Buffalo general manager, did
much of the scouting leg work during the Bills' four-year stretch
of AFC championships but Bill Polian got most of the credit. With
the Cardinals, the affable Ferguson has drafted well, gone into
free-agency judiciously and persuaded ownership to retain such
valuable veterans as Centers, Williams, defensive tackle Eric Swann
and wide receiver Frank Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   The team now has four tailback candidates all superior to '97
starter Leeland McElroy. The addition of mercurial all-purpose
player Eric Metcalf to the tandem of Sanders and Rob Moore provides
a big-play threat. The defensive line is one of the NFL's best
young groups, even without first-round end Andre Wadsworth, who
remains unsigned.
</P>
<P>
   Second-year quarterback Jake Plummer, a fan favorite because of
his derring-do while at Arizona State, gives the club a charismatic
drawing card and local hero.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've sent a message with those (acquisitions),'' said
Sanders, the burgeoning star who played at Auburn. ``We're at the
edge of something real good happening here, and the front office
has done a nice job of saying it's committed and then backing up
those words.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Cards could be another season or two away from
challenging seriously, even in a watered-down NFC East. The
offensive line and both safety positions are obvious problems.
Plummer has struggled with the West Coast offense installed by new
coordinator Marc Trestman. The stalled negotiations with Wadsworth
are maddening. The kicking game appears to be weak.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who has witnessed the worst of times in Arizona, said
he thinks the team is better prepared to deal with such problems,
however. And he noted that a Cardinals outfit that lost seven games
in '97 by a touchdown or less, including four by 3 points or fewer,
doesn't require much improvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life, to me, is like a movie,'' he said. ``Everything goes
frame to frame. One frame can be good, the next one bad. This year,
I see us with lots of good frames.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
