<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-17 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8121 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-REACTION-HNS &LR;      08-17 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-REACTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOURISTS SEEM TO SHRUG OFF CLINTON-LEWINSKY MATTER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Fla., S.C.) 
 
By GREG McDONALD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Contrary to what politicians and the media were
reporting, the nation was not holding its breath Monday awaiting
word on whether President Clinton lied about his relationship with
former White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Many Americans, if public opinion polls are accurate, already
seemed to know the answer was ``yes'' even before Clinton made his
appearance via closed-circuit television before a federal grand
jury investigating the Lewinsky matter.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the White House, for example, tourists seemed more
concerned with finding a good place to eat after touring the
presidential estate than finding out if its chief resident had
engaged in improper behavior with Lewinsky or had committed perjury
trying to cover it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not something that I think impacts on the country one way
or the other,'' said Scott Webber, a South Carolina visitor, who
was asking a local policeman where he could find ``a good steak''
when he was asked about the Lewinsky matter.
</P>
<P>
   Webber and his wife, Marsha, say they came to terms with ``who
Bill Clinton is'' when they voted for him in 1992 and again in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't bother me whether he lied about it or not,'' said
Marsha Webber. ``I think politicians have lied about much worse.''
</P>
<P>
   That view was echoed by other tourists around the White House,
although some acknowledged that they would take a dim view of
Clinton if he tried to obstruct justice by asking Lewinsky to lie
on his behalf. But most seemed as eager as the president to put the
matter behind them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leave him alone is what I say,'' said Shirley Nagey of Miami.
``I think it's a private matter. It doesn't have anything to do
with Whitewater, and it's a waste of money.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a waste. I mean if it were me, I'd lie,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether she would change her mind if it turns out that
Clinton committed perjury or tried to obstruct justice, Nagey said,
``My view is, like I said, this is a private matter, and some
questions just shouldn't be asked.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's between his wife, him and Monica,'' added Nancy Kagy,
another tourist from Miami. ``It doesn't have anything to do with
me or the rest of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican lawmakers on Capitol Hill, however, said the
Clinton-Lewinsky relationship was much more than a private sexual
matter. Some lawmakers described it as an ``abuse of power'' and
``serious enough'' to warrant the start of impeachment proceedings
in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't about sex. This is about abuse of the office of
president. This is about abuse of power. This is about lying under
oath,'' said Sen. Orrin Hatch, who, as chairman of the Senate
Judiciary Committee, would help oversee impeachment proceedings if
it comes to that.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch described the allegations against Clinton as more sordid
than the sexual harassment charges leveled by Anita Hill against
Supreme Court Justice Clarence Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   ``If these allegations about Monica Lewinsky are true, it
sickens me,'' Hatch said. ``The most powerful man in the world and
a 21-year-old intern, consensual or not, it's still abysmal, if it
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hatch acknowledged that he would not press for impeachment
hearings if Clinton's testimony proves to be truthful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm one of those who does not want impeachment if he tells the
truth,'' Hatch told reporters as Clinton was answering questions
put to him by grand jurors and independent counsel Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that's the case, he has asked for forgiveness and we should
do that,'' Hatch continued. ``I've always been taught to forgive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally hope it works out well for the president,'' Hatch
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Forgiveness, however, was the last thing that Sen. John
Ashcroft, R-Mo., was thinking during an appearance Monday on CNN.
He said the president should consider resigning if it turns out
that he deceived the American people about his relationship with
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've dragged the country through eight months of this deal
because the president hasn't been telling the truth,'' said
Ashcroft, who is considering a run for the presidency in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   He added that Congress would have ``a responsibility to carry
out impeachment procedures'' if Starr's upcoming report to Congress
includes evidence of perjury or obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The House Judiciary Committee, chaired by Rep. Henry Hyde,
R-Ill., has been preparing for the possibility of impeachment
proceedings. A lawyer who would serve as the committee's chief
counsel has already been hired, and funding has been earmarked to
begin initial hearings. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
