<SLUG> BC-DELTA-PILOTS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delta refuses to let pilots have a seat on board, risks alliance
with United
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Delta Air Lines won't give its pilot union a voting
seat on the board of directors, a decision that could scuttle plans
for a joint venture between Delta and United Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   The union had demanded the seat as a prerequisite to contract
change needed to allow the alliance, in which the airlines would
sell seats on each others' flights in a practice called
code-sharing.
</P>
<P>
   But on Monday Delta said its board rejected the demand ``because
of its belief in the principal that an independent board best
serves Delta and its constituents.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Giambusso, chairman of Delta's Air Line Pilots
Association unit, said the union is ``very disappointed'' and will
cease consideration of the needed contract change.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point you could say it's over,'' he said, though he
added the union would entertain any new company overtures. The
union's leadership council meets again in a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Delta President and Chief Executive Leo Mullin said he remains
hopeful.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will await the view of the union leadership on this and
that will remain to be seen,'' he said. ``I hope they will decide
to give further consideration on this. It's not at all a reflection
on the pilots but a decision in favor of good corporate
governance.''
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, Mullin said Delta and United will proceed with joint
frequent flier benefits, an aspect of the alliance that doesn't
require union approval. As of Sept. 1, the airlines will give
fliers the option of logging miles in either airline's program.
</P>
<P>
   Delta's pilots based their demand on the fact that United pilots
have a voting board seat, and a belief it would help them protect
members' career interests. The union now has a non-voting
representative not privy to all matters.
</P>
<P>
   Mullin noted that United pilots own a sizable chunk of the
airline.
</P>
<P>
   The Delta-United alliance followed similar pairings announced by
Northwest and Continental, and by American and US Airways. But
neither of those alliances is moving quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, some analysts say the urgency behind the
Delta-United deal has waned, which they add could contribute to
hard-line stances by the company and the pilots.
</P>
<P>
   Delta's stock closed up $4.31 1/4 at $119.75 on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
