u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIAMI-FINANCIAL-COX     08-17 0382
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIAMI-FINANCIAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Once on brink of bankruptcy, Miami offers up 'realistic' budget
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ This cash-strapped city appears to be skating back from
the brink of financial disaster once again, as reluctant city
officials have tentatively approved tax and fee increases that
should balance Miami's budget.
</P>
<P>
   The move comes only after a state board appointed to help clean
up the city's messy books threatened to take over Miami's
government if commissioners didn't adopt a realistic budget.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the appointed board's intermediary _ called an
estimating committee _ got its first look at the proposed new
budget and gave general approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what I've seen this is absolutely a positive step toward
putting the city back on firm financial footing,'' said Alan
Johansen, an accountant representing Gov. Lawton Chiles on the
estimating committee.
</P>
<P>
   But the document still must win approval from the five-member
oversight board, which meets next week to discuss it.
</P>
<P>
   Miami city commissioners could still wiggle out of their
politically undesirable decision to raise taxes and fees _ they
won't put the new budget to a final vote until September.
</P>
<P>
   Interim City Manager Donald Warshaw, however, believes the
commission will stand firm on raising revenues, and was pleased at
the initial approvals Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big step,'' he said. ``Of all the events this is the
most significant because these are the people who have been hired
by the oversight board to really scrutinize the numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   Miami's financial crisis came to light in 1996 when Mayor Joe
Carollo found the city was near bankruptcy after years of poor
financial management. But Carollo was tossed out of office by
voters last fall during a tumultuous election, only to be
reinstalled two months later after a judge ruled the election was
tainted by massive absentee ballot fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Carollo and the commission submitted a preliminary five-year
budget in the spring, winning the oversight board's approval. Last
month, however, they drew the board's ire with an updated budget,
which contained an estimated $16 million shortfall for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
