<DOCNO> NYT19980817.0364 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-17 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8128 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-LEWINSKY-HNS &LR;      08-17 1278
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-LEWINSKY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TELLS GRAND JURY OF LEWINSKY RELATIONSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Clinton address at 10 p.m. EDT; will update)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton acknowledged an inappropriate
relationship with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky in
sworn testimony to a federal grand jury Monday, seven months after
first denying the relationship.
</P>
<P>
   The president then prepared to apologize for his conduct in a
nationally televised address to the American people.
</P>
<P>
   White House Chief of Staff Erksine Bowles advised Democratic
lawmakers prior to Clinton's address that the president would
``take full and complete responsibility and express real regret''
for his conduct.
</P>
<P>
   David Kendall, the president's lawyer, emerged from Clinton's
testimony in the historic Map Room of the White House to emphasize
that Clinton had testified forthrightly during a five-hour,
25-minute session that included more than four hours of questions
and answers with special prosecutor Kenneth Starr and his deputies.
</P>
<P>
   The president ``testified truthfully,'' declared Kendall, a
trusted Yale Law School classmate of the president and first lady
Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hopeful that the president's testimony will finally
bring closure to the independent counsel's more than four year and
over $40 million investigation, which has culminated in an
investigation of the president's private life,'' Kendall added.
</P>
<P>
   Aides said Clinton chose to deliver his 10 p.m. EDT explanation
from the Map Room, a formal sitting room adorned with antiques and
dominated by a World War II-era map showing allied troops closing
in on the Nazi capital of Berlin in April 1945.
</P>
<P>
   President Franklin D. Roosevelt and British Prime Minister
Winston Churchill charted allied strategy there at the outset of
the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   .MDNM/Kendall made his statement at the White House diplomatic
entrance overlooking the South Lawn shortly after Starr and his
deputies exited the White House and boarded a passenger sedan
without public comment.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's secret testimony was relayed by closed-circuit
television to a 23-member federal grand jury seated in a courtroom
at the federal courthouse a dozen blocks away from the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The grand jury has been looking into allegations that Clinton
carried on an 18-month sexual relationship with Lewinsky when she
was a 21-year-old intern and then coaxed her to lie about their
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky initially denied a sexual relationship with Clinton in
a sworn deposition taken in Paula Jones' $700,000 sexual harassment
lawsuit against Clinton. That lawsuit was later dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   But Lewinsky reversed course after winning immunity from
prosecution from Starr to tell Starr's grand jury on Aug. 6 that
she and Clinton carried on a sexual relationship while she worked
at the White House, according to lawyers familiar with her
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had repeatedly denied a sexual relationship with
Lewinsky, who came to work at the White House in June 1995 as an
unpaid intern. Clinton emphatically reiterated his denial in an
appearance at the White House on Jan. 26 with Mrs. Clinton by his
side.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not have sexual relations with that woman, Miss
Lewinsky,'' Clinton declared, waving his index finger for emphasis.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials, speaking privately, said that Clinton
used his testimony to acknowledge an improper relationship with
Lewinsky without going into details.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials privately portrayed Clinton's admission as
a heart-rending challenge for the first family. Rev. Jesse Jackson,
saying he was invited to the White House late Sunday by the
Clintons' daughter Chelsea, told reporters Monday: ``Suffice it to
say (the president) is in the pain of all of this.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said that Mrs. Clinton and Chelsea expressed ``unbroken
devotion'' to the president, adding: ``Fortunately for him, they
are greeting him with open arms and devotion.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowles similarly tried to buck up senior presidential aides who
had echoed Clinton's denials early in the scandal. Bowles
emphasized the ``importance of sticking together'' in his remarks
to the senior staff at a Monday morning meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to be there for someone when they're up,'' Bowles
told presidential aides. ``But it's the good ones who are there for
you when you're down.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons, accompanied by Chelsea, a student at Stanford
University, planned to leave for a two-week vacation on Martha's
Vineyard, Mass., on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton became the American president to testify before a grand
jury investigating his conduct just two days before his 52nd
birthday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's testimony was a crucial milestone in White House
efforts to quell a seven-month scandal that has obscured the
president's domestic agenda and hampered his efforts to bolster
Democrats' chances for retaking control of the House in the
mid-term congressional elections.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's aides say the special prosecutor hopes to present a
report to Congress within three to five weeks on the results of his
four year inquiry into the Clintons' failed 1978 investment in the
Whitewater land scheme in Arkansas, their firing of White House
travel office personnel, the alleged abuse of FBI background
reports on prominent Republicans and the Lewinsky affair.
</P>
<P>
   Starr may recall Lewinsky for a second appearance before the
grand jury before his inquiry ends. Starr's spokesman, Charles
Bakaly, said that prosecutors are near the end of their inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to complete the investigation as quickly as
possible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   By law, Starr must report his findings to the House Judiciary
Committee which then weighs whether an impeachment inquiry is
warranted. Republican lawmakers in the House are divided, with some
conservatives insisting that the House undertake a full inquiry
into Starr's findings before reaching a decision on recommending
impeachment to the full House.
</P>
<P>
   But Senate Judiciary Committee Chairman Orrin Hatch, R-Utah,
reiterated at a news conference in Des Moines, Iowa, on Monday that
he did not believe impeachment proceedings are warranted if Clinton
told the truth before the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally hope it works out well for the president,'' Hatch
said. Truthful testimony is ``the one thing that he can do that
might not only save his presidency but allow him to finish the
presidency through the year 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   White House Press Secretary Mike McCurry said that Clinton had
hoped that his candor and apology after more than seven months of
denials would help douse a scandal that dogged his presidency and
raised the specter of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looks forward to getting this matter behind him,'' McCurry
said shortly before Clinton began his testimony at 12.59 p.m. EDT.
It testimony ended at 6:26 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   William Schneider, a public opinion specialist at the American
Enterprise Institute, said that Republicans in Congress already are
acting as though Clinton has ``lost his moral authority,''
dismissing his proposals because he is ``an illegitimate
president.''
</P>
<P>
   Schneider added: ``The bottom line is they're not afraid of this
president anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Schneider said that Vice President Al Gore could face problems
in his planned Democratic campaign for president in 2000. ``I think
Al Gore is locked in the truck of Clinton's car _ where Clinton
goes, he takes Al Gore with him,'' Schneider said.
</P>
<P>
   .MDSD/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-98 2022EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
