u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-LEGACY-HNS &LR;      08-17 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-LEGACY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEX INVESTIGATION TO BE FOREVER LINKED TO CLINTON, SCHOLARS SAY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ARMANDO VILLAFRANCA 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Monica Lewinsky sex scandal will leave a lasting impression
on President Clinton's long-term reputation and may overshadow the
accomplishments of his administration, two Houston scholars said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suspect this will be a lasting legacy of Mr. Clinton,'' said
Paul Brace, political science professor at Rice University.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sets precedents in so many different areas. It's
titillating in the extreme; it's comical, tending on your sense of
humor. For all these reasons it will have the effect of dominating
his legacy. I think it will be what he will be mostly remembered
for.''
</P>
<P>
   In the way the memory of Richard Nixon evokes Watergate and
Lyndon B. Johnson is linked to the Vietnam War, Brace said, ``The
thumbnail sketch of the (Clinton) administration will be attached
to this event.''
</P>
<P>
   But Brace said historians may be less influenced by the scandal
than the general public.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other scandals that involved abuse of presidential power
and public policy, Clinton's problems are more personal in nature.
</P>
<P>
   Brace believes scholars may remember Clinton more for such
accomplishments as the elimination of the deficit, economic
recovery, national health care, ending the killing in Bosnia and
opening the trade door to Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The scholarly community may not be influenced by this legacy,
but I think the public legacy will be (the Monica Lewinsky
scandal),'' Brace said.
</P>
<P>
   The most surprising development in the scandal is that public
opinion of Clinton's job performance remains high. An NBC News poll
taken over the weekend showed Clinton's approval rating at 70
percent, significantly higher than his job rating before the
scandal broke.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could not have foreseen that a president could be involved
in a sexual scandal and it not have pulled down his approval
rating,'' said John W. Sloan, political science professor at the
University of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Brace speculated that Nixon would have survived Watergate and
maybe even averted impeachment proceedings if he had the strong
economy Clinton currently enjoys.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the polls it seems in many ways that the
Americans are becoming more French in many ways. As long as the
country is moving along very well, people don't really care,''
Brace said.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, Clinton has a chance of weathering the sex
scandal, especially since, in comparison to past presidential
scandals, the public appears to be in a forgiving mood.
</P>
<P>
   Incidents such as the Teapot Dome scandal so marred Warren G.
Harding's presidency that historians consider him among the worst
presidents in the nation's history.
</P>
<P>
   Ulysses S. Grant's administration was so racked with scandal _
Black Friday, Credit Mobilier, Whiskey Ring and Belknap bribery _
that his presidency is remembered for nothing else.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grant and Harding are generally rated at the bottom mainly
because the scandals outweighed anything they were able to
accomplish during their administrations,'' Sloan said.
</P>
<P>
   Sex scandals are not new to the presidency and the men who held
the office. Thomas Jefferson is said to have fathered children by a
former slave, Dwight D. Eisenhower had an affair with his chauffeur
during World War II and Franklin D. Roosevelt was rumored to have
cheated on his wife while in office.
</P>
<P>
   The editor of the New York Sun described Grover Cleveland as a
``coarse debauchee who would bring his harlots with him to
Washington and hire lodgings for them convenient to the White
House.''
</P>
<P>
   Harding's father told his son, ``Warren, it's a good thing you
wasn't born a gal because you'd be in the family way all the time.
You can't say no.''
</P>
<P>
   The president best known for his sexual escapades, however, was
John F. Kennedy, who was rumored to have had countless affairs,
including one with star Marilyn Monroe.
</P>
<P>
   Sloan said presidents in the past enjoyed a special relationship
with the media that allowed them to keep their sexual trysts out of
the public eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was off the record; the press simply didn't report any of
this,'' Sloan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The media had a kind of gentlemen's agreement not to raise
those allegations publicly, and the same was true with Kennedy,''
Sloan said. ``Kennedy was a well-known womanizer, but the press had
a kind of off-limits attitude about that type of story.''
</P>
<P>
   The same is not true today.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Kennedy were alive today he would have been involved in
exactly the same scandal,'' Brace said.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Brace said presidents were able to control what
journalists wrote about them because Washington press corps careers
were based on access to the president. Reporters, he said, were
more insiders than investigators.
</P>
<P>
   ``Johnson and Nixon ruptured that cohesiveness with the press
such that the press has never trusted presidents to give them the
story, and now it's adversarial,'' Brace said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
