r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-KRIKORIAN-LADN     08-17 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-KRIKORIAN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMEMEMBERING SPORTSWRITING GREAT JIM MURRAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a newspaper columnist who would ascend to the pinnacle of his
profession, Jim Murray was such an innovative stylist that he was
responsible for some of the most memorable sporting prose ever
written his own and some of the worst his imitators.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it was a reflection of Murray's greatness at putting
together clever phrases that inspired a generation of impersonators
who tried vainly to emulate Murray's masterful usage of metaphors
and similes.
</P>
<P>
   There never has been a sportswriter in this country who was
copied as much as Jim Murray, who passed away Sunday evening after
a distinguished Pulitzer Prize winning career with the Los Angeles
Times.
</P>
<P>
   There never has been a sportswriter in this country who
transcended sports more than Jim Murray, whose list of devoted
readers included many people who never cared about athletics until
Murray began dispensing his unique perceptions in a most
entertaining manner in 1961.
</P>
<P>
   There never has been a sportswriter in this country who became
as famous, if not more famous, than many of the superstar athletes
he covered than Jim Murray, who was treated at sporting events as
though he were a member of royalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim was such a towering figure that the athletes themselves
were honored when he chose to interview one of them,'' said Fred
Claire, the former general manger of the Los Angeles Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Murray now joins the pantheon of his craft, right up there
alongside the Ring Lardners and Red Smiths and Jimmy Cannons and
Grantland Rices.
</P>
<P>
   His printed trademark was his litany of biting and light-hearted
one-liners, especially those directed at cities. There were a lot
of Chamber of Commerce officials in America who loathed his humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chicago was a town where Al Capone didn't have a police record
even though he kept the coroner's office on night shifts,'' he once
wrote about the Windy City.
</P>
<P>
   He was just as merciless with Philadelphia: ``Philadelphia was a
town that would boo a cancer cure. It was a place to park the truck
and change your socks or go unload a freighter. It was a place even
the British gave up without a fight.''
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, he didn't spare New York: ``You are not safe in
a church, taxi, elevator or lobby. The only safe place in New York
City is Grant's Tomb. Which is to say, Grant is safe, not you.''
</P>
<P>
   Or Los Angeles: ``L.A. is underpoliced and oversexed. Its
architecture has been (accurately) described as ``Early Awful'' or
``Papier-Mache Provincial'' or ``Moorish Nauseous.''
</P>
<P>
   And even Long Beach: ``It was the seaport of Iowa, settled by a
slow leak in Des Moines. It is sinking under the skeletal work of
millions of dollars' worth of oil wells. The only reason for going
to Long Beach is to see if it is still there.''
</P>
<P>
   While Murray enjoyed reporting events in a comical manner
replete with hyperbolic utterances ``the pickpockets were the only
ones who went home winners on Kentucky Derby day'' he also could be
fiercely acerbic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gentlemen, start your coffins!'' still ranks among Murray's
most fabled lines in one of his early columns he wrote about the
Indianapolis 500.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Murray was a gentle, unassuming man who never took his
exalted station seriously, and never was a pecking order person who
based his friendships on status.
</P>
<P>
   He was nice to everyone he met, and I first met Murray on a road
trip with the Los Angeles Lakers in 1969, sitting next to him on a
train as we traveled from New York to Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, like almost every journalism school graduate of that
era who went into sports, I attempted to write like Murray. But I
found out quickly that his style was impossible to duplicate.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of other authors didn't, and the newspaper business soon
was brimming with a lot of lousy Jim Murray impersonators, which it
suffers from to this day.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Murray and I would sit together in a lot of pressboxes over
the years, and I'll never forget that Murray was next to me at
Dodger Stadium that mild October evening in 1988 when we both
witnessed one of the more historic home runs in baseball history.
</P>
<P>
   It was the opening game of the World Series, and Murray already
had wrapped up a column he had done on Jose Canseco, who had hit a
first-inning grand slam homer that seemed destined to give the
Oakland A's a victory over the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   But Kirk Gibson would become the hero when he hit his dramatic
two-out, game-winning homer for the Dodgers, forcing Murray to tear
up his column and write a new one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gibson slayed both the A's and us writers on deadline,''
cracked Murray.
</P>
<P>
   I remember another time we were seated next to each other at the
Aaron Pryor-Alexis Arguello rematch in Las Vegas when Murray
noticed I was ashen-faced at the start of the fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you sick?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I made a big bet on the fight,'' I admitted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then you are sick,'' he replied tartly.
</P>
<P>
   I enjoyed talking to Murray about his early newspaper days at
the Los Angeles Examiner, and the characters he met around town
like Bugsy Siegel and Mickey Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone called Bugsy by his real first name, Ben,'' related
Murray. ``You'd take your life in your own hands if you dared
called him Bugsy.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Murray was bedeviled by tragedy in the later years of his
life, losing one son to drugs, losing his first wife, Gerry, to
cancer, almost going blind because of a detached retina.
</P>
<P>
   But not once did I ever hear him complain.
</P>
<P>
   He always was in a civil mood and never whined, although he told
me during the 1996 World Series between the New York Yankees and
Atlanta Braves that the grind of covering such an event had become
too difficult for him.
</P>
<P>
   He did not attend last year's Fall Classic between the Cleveland
Indians and Florida Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   Still, at 78, Jim Murray was putting out two columns a week for
the Times, and his final one appeared in Sunday's paper from Del
Mar.
</P>
<P>
   He got married again a few years ago to a supportive lady named
Linda McCoy, and he had seemed quite content the last time I saw
him about six weeks ago at a boxing press conference at the Friars
Club in Beverly Hills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had brought him to the Friars that day, and that also was
the last time I saw Jim,'' said Bill Caplan, the fight publicist
and friend of Murray for 35 years. ``When I drove him back to his
home afterwards, I did something I had never done before. I hugged
him and gave him a kiss on the cheek. He was the easiest columnist
to sell a story to of any I've ever worked with. I'm going to miss
him.''
</P>
<P>
   So are a lot of other people.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PRESS TELEGRAM, LONG BEACH, CALIFORNIA
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-98 2029EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980817.0371 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-17 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8138 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PITNEY-BOWES-ART-2NDT     08-17 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PITNEY-BOWES-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 STAMFORD, Conn.: Securities Research.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Moreover, Pitney has had plenty of time to plan for change. As
far back as 1992, George Harvey, then the chairman, was forming
task forces, hiring outside consultants, even sending anthropology
students to study how customers process messages _ all to figure
out whether desktop computers and changes in the way people
communicate meant that mail was on the way out.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were drawing all kinds of doomsday scenarios,''
recalled Meredith Fischer, vice president for corporate marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Warding off those scenarios took a toll on Pitney. The company,
already struggling with the aftermath of some bad investments in
overseas businesses, took numerous write-offs relating to training
and factory retooling.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Postal Service issued regulations that prevented Pitney
from collecting postage money from customers in advance, a practice
that had enabled Pitney to earn more than $25 million a year in the
``float,'' or interest income.
</P>
<P>
   Although operating earnings remained healthy, by 1995 investors
had had enough and share prices plunged. ``We gave them too many
bad surprises,'' Critelli recalled.
</P>
<P>
   A year later the task forces came back with a few surprises of
their own. Digital technologies, they reported, were adding new
ways of communicating, yet not replacing old ones, so Pitney was
not facing a zero-sum game. But if Pitney was to be a player in a
digitally integrated world, they said, it could no longer let its
mailing, fax and other divisions do their own thing.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Critelli has been transforming the company from a
decentralized group of stand-alone businesses into Team Pitney.
</P>
<P>
   He has combined its office-equipment sales forces so that
customers could have one-stop shopping for copiers, faxes and
mailing equipment. Last year the mailing systems and
financial-services division, which helps customers finance major
Pitney Bowes purchases, moved to a joint profit-and-loss statement.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president for fax sales, a division that has better
long-term relationships with customers than the copier division,
just became vice president for copiers.
</P>
<P>
   Pitney's executive leadership council, once a tiny group of
senior people, now includes more than a dozen managers, who meet
monthly. Last year Critelli created a central planning department.
And he ruled that divisional chief financial officers, including
European ones, be appointed out of Stamford. ``We want them to be
loyal to the company, not just to the people who hired them,''
Critelli said.
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps most important for driving the culture change home,
he has changed compensation plans so that managers have a personal
stake in the whole company's performance, not just their divisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's really an incentive to help each other out now,''
Suzanne Grey, the new vice president for corporate strategy, said.
</P>
<P>
   The newly knit teams are already going after new markets. Small
businesses are a prime target. Two years ago Pitney teamed up with
Brother Industries _ a big move into collegiality for what had been
a pretty insular company _ to introduce the Personal Post Office, a
set of low-end mailing machines aimed at small businesses, and it
has been fervently pursuing that market ever since.
</P>
<P>
   The company is testing a Pitney Bowes Visa card, and is offering
to help small businesses create direct mail and Internet campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the move to digital meters looks as if it might be a
financial blessing for Pitney. They require fewer inspections and
rarely need repairs. They enable customers to reload postage by
telephone, a convenience that will allow Pitney to raise its rental
charges, and to collect reloading fees.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, companies reload their meters five times a year.
``Even at just a $10 fee, that's $50 per meter that goes straight
to the bottom line,'' Jonathan Rosenzweig, an analyst with Salomon
Smith Barney, said.
</P>
<P>
   Digital meters will enable Pitney to offer customers the option
to print logos or marketing messages along with postage. They will
also let the postage on, say, prepaid return envelopes, carry
electronic code that can send signals back to the mail's originator
when they are mailed _ for example, it could signal to a utility
company that is about to cut off a customer's electricity that a
return envelope, presumably with a check, is in the mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Envelopes, stamps, all kinds of documents are going to get a
whole lot smarter,'' said Maynard Benjamin, executive director of
Papercom Alliance Inc., an inter-industry group formed in 1995 to
study how the Internet will affect the use of mail. The question,
of course, is whether Pitney will continue to grow smarter with
them.
</P>
</TEXT>
