A8146 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-MEDIA-BOS &LR;      08-17 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MEDIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDIA FILLS AIRWAVES WITH HYPE _ UNTIL THE LEAKS BEGIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With nothing less than what CNN's Bernard Shaw called ``a
presidency on the line,'' reporters spent much of Monday waiting
impatiently for the outcome of President Clinton's unprecedented
grand jury testimony. And by the 6:30 p.m. network news, a
breathless media announced nothing more than what had been reported
days earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an eerie time,'' said NBC's Tim Russert on cable network
MSNBC. There is ``obviously pain in the media because no one has
relished covering a story as squalid as this.''
</P>
<P>
   What made it eerier was the lengthy wait for confirmation of a
story that many news outlets had reported long before the testimony
began about 1 p.m. Minutes after that testimony concluded about
6:25 p.m., the networks announced that the president had indeed met
expectations and acknowledged a relationship with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   In a strange symbol of Monday's media vigil, CNN initially ran
an ``elapsed time'' clock showing how long the president had been
testifying. The ticking clock was a metaphor for a day in which
much news from the White House watch was so trivial as to provide
relief from the overwhelming tension.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the afternoon, MSNBC's Brian Williams reported that a
boombox had been installed in the federal courthouse to keep
reporters from overhearing Clinton's testimony. Less than an hour
later, CNN's Bob Franken reported that it had been removed. Shortly
after 2 p.m., Russert announced that White House staffers _
participating in a kind of gallows-humor wagering pool _ were
betting that Clinton would use the word ``inappropriate'' rather
than ``improper'' to describe his relationship with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, news reports suggesting the direction of Clinton's
testimony began to proliferate with Friday's New York Times Page 1
screaming headline: ``President Weighs Admitting He Had Sexual
Contacts.'' By Sunday night, that buzz had amplified into a roar.
(The Political Hotline newsletter noted that last weekend featured
30 hours of special Lewinsky-related television programming.)
</P>
<P>
   On CNN's ``National Town Meeting'' Sunday night, correspondent
John King reported that Clinton would acknowledge an
``inappropriate relationship with Monica Lewinsky.'' At the same
time, ABC anchor Peter Jennings said the ``betting money'' in
Washington was that the president would change his story and admit
to some wrongdoing. On MSNBC, Williams described Washington as a
city leaking like a sieve and predicted that the president would
``admit to some sort of relationship here.''
</P>
<P>
   In a story Monday morning, Washington Post media critic Howard
Kurtz compared all this reporting and punditry to ``the pregame
hype before the Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the kickoff arrived and Clinton began testifying, news
became very rare. In the search for public opinion Monday
afternoon, a CNN reporter stopped in a Little Rock, Ark.,
restaurant to sample public opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I care who the president sleeps with?'' said one woman with
a syrupy Southern accent. ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   But at the Illinois State Fair near the Springfield home of
``Honest Abe'' Lincoln, another citizen told MSNBC that if Clinton
admitted to a sexual relationship, ``I think he has totally
diminished the office of the president.''
</P>
<P>
   As the day _ and the president's testimony _ dragged on, the
talk inevitably turned to the political implications. On CNN's
``Inside Politics,'' Jeff Greenfield said Clinton was probably
doomed to a ``crippled presidency,'' and former presidential
advisor David Gergen predicted that anywhere from 30 percent to 40
percent of the population would favor resignation or impeachment if
Clinton acknowledged a sexual relationship.
</P>
<P>
   In the surest sign of desperation to fill the long hours before
Clinton finished answering questions, CNN ran the inevitable
navel-gazing story about the horde of journalists descending on the
White House. Mercifully, the testimony broke up about a half-hour
later and the official leaking began.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Jurkowitz is the Globe's media writer.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-98 2032EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
