<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-17 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8149 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-CAUCASUS-$ADV2     08-17 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CAUCASUS-$ADV23-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MYSTICAL AURA OVER GEORGIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 23)  
(lb) 
 By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cool mist from the nearby Caucasus Mountains enveloped the
stately Sveti-tskhoveli Cathedral as a bus full of Orthodox monks
pulled up in front one afternoon last spring. After stepping off,
they formed a single file led by the local bishop. Bearded and clad
in flowing robes, they walked slowly around the cathedral, their
chants adding to the evocative spirituality that surrounds this
place.
</P>
<P>
   After completing their circuit, the monks entered the cathedral
and greeted priests inside. As they offered a benediction beneath
the frescoes and towering dome, three young nuns beside the altar
began to sing in lilting harmony, sounding as if they could compete
with any doo-wop combo in the world. A while later the monks filed
out, stopping to kiss gold-framed icons of Georgian saints.
</P>
<P>
   A mystic aura hangs over Sveti-tskhoveli, about 15 miles north
of Tbilisi, the capital of Georgia, and over the many other
churches and monasteries that dot Georgia's verdant countryside.
During a 10-day trip there, I made a special effort to visit these
sites.
</P>
<P>
   Taken together, Georgia's famous religious buildings constitute
a magnificent architectural and ecclesiastical heritage. Their
ascetic facades, great domes, towering round spires, intricate
relief sculptures and majestic interiors have made them a central
part of the Georgian consciousness, contributing to a sense of
nationhood that has held this land together through successive
invasions and conquests.
</P>
<P>
   They teach a visitor much about the history of a country that is
again emerging as a force in regional politics and hopes to become
a tourist destination.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia has not had an easy time of independence, which it
declared in 1991 after the breakup of the Soviet Union. A nation of
4.5 million about the size of West Virginia, it has been shaken by
civil conflict. Even today nearly one-fourth of its territory,
including some famous Black Sea resorts, is controlled by
separatist groups.
</P>
<P>
   These regions and places near them are out of bounds for most
visitors, but much of the country is completely peaceful, thanks
largely to the wise leadership of President Eduard Shevardnadze.
</P>
<P>
   The tourists who are beginning to arrive in small numbers are
rediscovering Georgia's wonders: high mountains and vast expanses
of meadows, unspoiled villages of warmly hospitable people and a
remarkable architectural tradition that reached its peak in dozens
of churches, cathedrals and monasteries where visitors are welcome.
</P>
<P>
   The history of the Georgian Orthodox Church is full of legends
as rich and amazing as its edifices. Touches of the secular and
even the pagan are often close to the surface. One of the grand
columns supporting Sveti-tskhoveli, for example, is ringed with
carved grapevines, a vivid tribute to Georgia's age-old love of
wine.
</P>
<P>
   On the eastern facade, which dates from the fifth century, two
carved bulls' heads emerge boldly from the masonry, apparently
reflecting pre-Christian beliefs. And on the northern facade is a
carving of an arm and hand, with the fingers clutching a bevel.
This is not a freemason's symbol, as it first appears, but a
reference to an eerie tale from the 11th century, when much of the
present cathedral was built.
</P>
<P>
   According to the story, a renowned architect named Arsukidze was
commissioned to rebuild the original fifth-century basilica. He
succeeded triumphantly, creating what one historian has called a
``masterpiece of the early Georgian Renaissance.''
</P>
<P>
   But a royal minister who had been Arsukidze's mentor was
outraged that his pupil had so brilliantly surpassed him, and
ordered his right hand severed as punishment. An inscription above
the carving reads: ``This is the hand of Arsukidze, servant of God.
Pray for him.''
</P>
<P>
   That story is only one of many connected with this cathedral.
Another is about Sidonia, a first-century convert to Christianity
who is said to have died from the emotion that surged through her
as she clutched Christ's robe. Sidonia's brother was said to have
bought the robe from a Roman soldier, and in death she held it so
tightly that it could not be pried from her grasp. She was buried
with it beneath what is now the floor of Sveti-tskhoveli.
</P>
<P>
   This story, according to Georgian theology, makes
Sveti-tskhoveli the second most sacred place in the Christian
world, following only the Church of the Holy Sepulcher in
Jerusalem. To symbolize the tie between the two, a scale model of
the Holy Sepulcher was built inside Sveti-tskhoveli 700 years ago.
The gold that originally covered it was later stolen by Tamerlane,
but the model, which is about the height of a man, remains full of
intricate detail.
</P>
<P>
   Like most foreigners who come to Georgia, I began my trip in
Tbilisi, the capital. Only a few years ago Tbilisi was in ruins as
rival factions fought for control, bringing the country to its
knees and leading many to wonder if it could survive. Today the
headquarters of one faction is a school, while another is being
renovated and is to emerge next year as a luxury hotel. Buses run
regularly and restaurants are opening.
</P>
<P>
   Tbilisi's main avenue, Rustaveli Prospekt, reflects the city's
contrasts, with chic boutiques facing a hotel overflowing with
refugees from civil conflicts. It is an enjoyable place to walk,
but I preferred the old town, a warren of streets and buildings
that is also home to the Sioni Cathedral, the seat of Georgian
Orthodoxy.
</P>
<P>
   There has been a church on this site since about 600 A.D., and
most of the existing edifice dates to the 13th century. Its walls
and ceilings are completely covered with murals, including some
startlingly modern ones on the high rear wall. Facing the altar is
an elaborate wooden throne whose armrests are supported by carved
griffins, mythological beasts not normally associated with
Christianity. The Georgian patriarch sits here when he comes for
mass.
</P>
<P>
   On the day I visited, a priest in an immaculate white-and-orange
robe was kneeling in prayer. A trio of novices chanted from one
corner, and a quartet of kerchiefed young women answered with their
own chants from another corner. Hundreds of small candles flickered
through the dim light, and the scent of incense hung in the air.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Outside, a vendor of icons refused to sell me or my Georgian
friend a hand-painted portrait on wood of St. Nino, one of the
great figures of Georgian Christianity. She did not think a
foreigner would properly revere it, and after interrogating my
friend decided that she, too, was insufficiently religious to
deserve it.
</P>
<P>
   St. Nino was a young woman from Cappadocia who, in the third or
fourth century, set out to spread the Christian faith. Guided by
what she said was divine inspiration, she made her way to Georgia
and was able to cure the beloved monarch, Queen Nana, of what had
been considered a fatal illness.
</P>
<P>
   Later she is said to have saved Nana's husband, King Mirian,
when he was lost in a wilderness and abandoned by the pagan idols
to whom he prayed for deliverance. After these incidents the royal
family embraced Christianity and decreed it to be the official
state religion.
</P>
<P>
   Queen Nana and King Mirian are buried at the Samtavro monastery
on the outskirts of the town of Mtskheta, only a few miles from the
Sveti-tskhoveli Cathedral. Samtavro is a tranquil and intimate
place, a complex of four buildings set among grassy groves. I was
greeted by a group of nuns sitting outside drinking wine in memory
of one of their departed companions. They told me that St. Nino
herself had often prayed at this site.
</P>
<P>
   The existing Samtavro church, made of flat stone bricks and
topped with a classic round steeple, dates to the first half of the
11th century. Frescoes that once covered the walls, like many in
Georgia, were whitewashed by 19th-century czarists or 20th-century
bolsheviks. The church has some fine details of carved stone, but
the simple coffins of the two ancient monarchs are its most
affecting feature.
</P>
<P>
   From Samtavro I drove to the top of a high cliff outside
Mtskheta, which was Georgia's ancient capital, to visit one of the
country's oldest churches. The Dzhvari Church of the Holy Cross was
built in the sixth century, supposedly on a spot where St. Nino had
overseen the destruction of pagan idols and erection of a Christian
cross 200 years earlier. A small and harmonious gem of early
Georgian architecture, not in perfect condition, it has mercifully
been left alone by restorers.
</P>
<P>
   Reliefs on the facade depict early Georgian monarchs, including
one kneeling in front of Jesus Christ and the archangels Gabriel
and Michael. Icons decorate the walls inside, among them several
portraits of St. Nino and her patron, Queen Nana.
</P>
<P>
   But Dzhvari is not an intricately ornamented church, and it
conveys an air of quiet religiosity. Its location and sweeping
views over the confluence of two rivers, as well as its role as the
symbol of Christianity's triumph in Georgia, combine with its
austere architecture to make it a deeply memorable place.
</P>
<P>
   No trip to Georgia is complete without a visit to the ancient
wine-growing region of Kakheti, where every village claims to
produce the world's finest wine. Georgian wine is available at
cafes and restaurants, but is best sampled in private homes. In
places like Kakheti, where villagers feel almost insulted if
visitors will not sit down and share their wine, it is a challenge
to balance thirst and good manners with sobriety.
</P>
<P>
   Before sitting down to sample the local wine, I stopped at the
ruins of the sixth-century fortress and cathedral complex at
Ninotsminda. The walls, built to protect the complex from Persian
invaders in the 16th century, are in fine condition, and what
remains of the cathedral is even older than the one at Dzhvari.
</P>
<P>
   The highlight of my visit was a climb up the four-story bell
tower, in which each floor is designed in a different style and
each has a fireplace around which monks warmed themselves for many
centuries.
</P>
<P>
   Back in Tbilisi, I realized that I had not visited the city's
most visible church, the Metekhi Church of the Virgin, which is
perched on a rocky hill overlooking the old town. I was especially
interested in it because of its connection with one of Georgia's
greatest leaders, Queen Tamara. Together with St. Nino and Queen
Nana, she reflects a remarkably strong female influence over the
course of Georgian history.
</P>
<P>
   The 11th, 12th and early 13th centuries were Georgia's golden
age. The age was launched by the formidable king known as David the
Builder, who defeated Muslim armies and captured Tbilisi but
established a policy of religious tolerance and encouraged art and
culture.
</P>
<P>
   It reached a peak under David's great-granddaughter Tamara, who
ruled from 1184 to 1212 and presided over an epoch that produced
the national epic poem, Shota Rustaveli's ``The Knight in the
Tiger's Skin.'' Rustaveli dedicated the poem to her, and some
historians suspect they were lovers.
</P>
<P>
   There has been a church at the Metekhi site since the earliest
days of Georgian Christianity. On the same site another Georgian
heroine, St. Shushanik, was buried after being tortured to death
for refusing to renounce Christianity in 544.
</P>
<P>
   David the Builder erected a palace here, and here Queen Tamara
married her second husband, an Ossetian prince whom she chose after
divorcing the ambitious Russian plotter who had been imposed on her
by courtiers. In the 19th century czarist authorities built a
prison on the site, where many revolutionaries and dissidents,
among them Maxim Gorky, were incarcerated.
</P>
<P>
   The present edifice, built in the 13th century, is made of
sandstone blocks and topped with a golden cross. While certainly
not the most moving of Georgia's churches, it is perhaps the most
symbolic. Inside there are four portraits of Queen Tamara,
including a full-length one in which she wears a richly jeweled
crown, an intricately embroidered robe and golden bracelets.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the church stands an imposing equestrian statue of King
Vakhtang Gorgasali, who ruled in the fifth century and played an
important role in consolidating Georgian Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   Standing under it you can see not just the old town but the
surrounding hills. Try to ignore the enormous and tasteless British
Airways billboard that defaces what was once a regal hillside, and
gaze out at the towering, inspiring statue of Mother Georgia, the
all-inclusive national symbol and perhaps not coincidentally a
female. She holds a sword in one hand to symbolize Georgia's will
to resist enemies, and a wine goblet in the other to show the
pleasures she offers to her friends.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
