<HEADLINE>
CROWD ADDS CADENCE TO THE SOAP OPERA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ESTELLA DURAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Outside the White House gates Monday, many of
President Clinton's constituents came to debate, to protest, and to
say the sex-and-coverup scandal is a national soap opera they hoped
would end.
</P>
<P>
   The day's saga even had a theme song or two.
</P>
<P>
   Bolaman Sarumi played his rhythm-and-blues recording ``Let
President Clinton alone. Let him be'' on a boombox and passed out
free cassettes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're here to send a message to America that people should
just let the president do his job,'' explained Sarumi, 45, from
Sacramento, who recorded the tune with his group, Bola-Monet.
</P>
<P>
   One man, who appeared to be homeless and refused to give his
name, alluded to the daytime drama. ``We've only got one life to
live. We're all sinners,'' he kept repeating.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the hundreds who gathered outside the White House while
Clinton was inside testifying for the grand jury said they didn't
care if the president had had a sexual relationship with former
intern Monica S. Lewinsky and lied to the country about it. Few
said the president should be impeached over the matter, and most
said they wished it would all go away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who's had an affair would lie about it. It's not a big
deal,'' said Susan Gandy, 35, a homemaker from Kershaw, S.C., who
stopped by the White House during a day of sightseeing.
</P>
<P>
   As they approached 1600 Pennsylvania Ave., Gandy and other
tourists _ as well as nearby workers on lunch breaks _ were greeted
by a throng of television reporters doing standups on the lawn and
several demonstrators yelling or singing.
</P>
<P>
   Six protesters, calling themselves the Clinton Snowjob Removal
Squad, offered their own song to the tune of ``O, Susannah.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, he's coming from the White House with a girl upon his knee
... Oh, I'm freezing in a blizzard of Clinton lies. The snow job's
piled up so high that now it's reached my thighs,'' they sang,
prompting laughter from tourists _ and reporters _ encircling them.
</P>
<P>
   On nearby 17th Street, passing drivers honked their car horns at
four demonstrators whose signs read: ``Peaches for impeachment''
and ``Perjury is an impeachable offense.'' The group, calling
themselves the Clinton Investigation Commission, passed out peaches
with stickers saying ``Monday, Aug. 17. Impeachment begins...''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Derek Anunciation, 31, a pastor from Huntington Beach,
Calif., gripped the White House fence as he prayed on his knees:
``The Bible says our leaders are not just chosen by us; they're
chosen by God. We need to trust God's judgment that he picked the
right person to lead us.''
</P>
<P>
   One man slashed at his throat with a screwdriver, leaving his
neck bloody with a superficial flesh wound. The 26-year-old was
sent to a hospital for treatment; US Park Police would not release
his name. Police said no charges were filed against him.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said the man shouted that the United States should be
worried about Iraq or Iran _ it was unclear which country he
mentioned _ instead of the president's personal life.
</P>
<P>
   But most people had comments similar to Richard Bursch, a
management analyst on his lunch break.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like everybody else, I think Clinton hasn't told the whole
story, but he has done a great job as a president,'' Bursch said.
``The economy is stable. President Clinton has supported some very
important policies, including ones on education and racial
relations, and I don't think anything else matters.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
