<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-17 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8153 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-PSYCHE-2TAKES     08-17 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PSYCHE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR BILL CLINTON, PROMISE IS AGAIN SHADOWED BY SHORTCOMINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Also see: CLINTON-RDP, CLINTON-PROCESS, CLINTON-HILLARY,
CLINTON-FRIENDS, CLINTON-GORE, CLINTON-SCENE, CLINTON-LEGAL,
CLINTON-MEDIA, CLINTON-ASSESS, CLINTON-REACT.) 
 (JT)  
 By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On Jan. 20, 1997, as an ebullient Bill Clinton took
the oath of office for the second term that he hoped would secure
his place in history, he returned to a theme that had been at the
core of his claim to be a new kind of Democrat, declaring: ``Each
and every one of us, in our own way, must assume personal
responsibility, not only for ourselves and our families but for our
neighbors and our nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Exactly one year later, Clinton learned that Independent Counsel
Kenneth Starr was investigating allegations that the president had
started a sexual affair with a White House intern in 1995, and then
tried to cover it up.
</P>
<P>
   Had the man who won the presidency speaking out for the people
who ``play by the rules'' once more surrendered to a lifelong
compulsion to bend and break them?
</P>
<P>
   Just a few days ago, Clinton was still in denial about the
affair, one close friend of the president said Monday, and only the
pained reaction of aides and advisers as he began to acknowledge
the truth to them over the weekend seemed to make the situation
real.
</P>
<P>
   How a man of such surpassing intellect and such protean
political talents could indulge in such reckless conduct _ at a
time when he knew a special prosecutor was already scrutinizing his
administration and his own re-election still hung in the balance _
remains the most puzzling question about William Jefferson Clinton.
But it is not a new question, and in some ways it was entirely
predictable that this president should have come to this pass, his
promise once again shadowed by his shortcomings.
</P>
<P>
   For Clinton has always been convinced he could outsmart,
outtalk, outcharm and outlast any adversary, and very often, enough
to confirm that conviction, he has. In the darkest days of the 1992
primaries, he dared to campaign on a platform of personal
responsibility, despite widespread questions about his own marital
fidelity, marijuana use and draft record, and widespread doubt that
his answers were candid or complete. In his first term, he shifted
ground on issues so many times that even his best friends sometimes
confessed they did not know where he stood.
</P>
<P>
   Time and again in the risky running melodrama of his public
life, he has treated the truth as an a la carte menu.
</P>
<P>
   Last Jan. 21, as news of the allegations involving Monica
Lewinsky came out, Clinton told National Public Radio: ``I don't
know any more about it than I've told you, and any more about it,
really, than you do.''
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, one friend said Monday, ``The president told me
he never had sex with Monica.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, such sweeping elisions of reality lie far beyond the
ken of conventional political analysis. But professionals who have
studied the arc of Clinton's life and career have suggested some
answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people wish to think well of themselves,'' wrote Stanley
Renshon, a political scientist and psychoanalyst at New York
University in his 1996 study of Clinton, ``High Hopes.'' ``However,
Bill Clinton appears to have come to believe the  &UR; best &LR;  of himself,
and either to avoid or discount evidence from his own behavior that
all is not as he believes it to be. He attributes to himself the
most sincere and best of motives. His errors, when acknowledged,
are the result of basically correct efforts gone temporarily awry,
misunderstandings that, if one knew more of what  &UR; he &LR;  knew, would
disappear or be mitigated, or else are attributable to naivete and
inexperience.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton comes by his capacity for denial and
compartmentalization naturally. They were among the qualities that
allowed his widowed mother, Virginia Kelley, to persevere after
Clinton's father died three months before he was born, and that
allowed Clinton to make what most critics regarded as a splendid
State of the Union address just days after the intern scandal
broke.
</P>
<P>
   ``When bad things do happen, I brainwash myself to put them out
of my mind,'' Mrs. Kelley wrote in her autobiography, published
after her death in 1994 under the president's review. ``Inside my
head, I construct an airtight box. I keep inside it what I want to
think about and everything else stays behind the walls. Inside is
white, outside is black: The only gray I trust is the streak in my
hair.''
</P>
<P>
   But gray is Clinton's favorite weapon. It has been central to
his successes _and to his setbacks. As governor of Arkansas and
then as a presidential candidate, he succeeded in blurring old
distinctions of ideology, proclaiming himself neither liberal nor
conservative but ``new.'' As president, he at first promised both a
tax cut and new spending, then raised taxes instead. Two years
later, he apologized for raising taxes too much, claiming liberal
Democrats had forced him to do so, a claim at sharp variance with
the facts.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   This is the man who pledged not to raise taxes ``to pay for my
programs,'' (he raised them to cut the deficit) who said he had
never ``broken the laws of my country'' (he tried marijuana as a
Rhodes Scholar in England), who defended his campaign finance
practices by saying he had never ``changed government policy solely
because of a contribution.'' His reputation for shading the truth
grew so encrusted that he faced semi-serious questions from
reporters over trivial matters, from his golf scores to whether he
really shot two ducks on a New Year's outing in Arkansas, or just
carried in some shot by others.
</P>
<P>
   Innumerable times, Clinton has accepted responsibility and
forsaken blame. After his 1980 defeat after one term as governor of
Arkansas, his political consultant Dick Morris advised him that the
key to a comeback was to apologize for past mistakes. Clinton
resisted repeated entreaties to say he was sorry, devising his own
folksy formulation for a television commercial: ``When I was a boy,
my daddy never had to whip me twice for the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the only daddy Clinton knew was an alcoholic stepfather
who sometimes beat his mother, not him. And the president has spent
a great part of his life being whipped, often quite publicly, for
repeating his own mistakes. In his very first run for office, in
1974, his girlfriend Hillary Rodham, sent her father and brother to
help on his congressional campaign, not only because she was tied
up as a lawyer on the Watergate investigation in Washington but
because, associates have recalled, she worried about the rumors of
his multiple romances on the road.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, faced with allegations by Gennifer Flowers of a 12-year
sexual affair, Clinton said, ``That allegation is false,''
acknowledged causing pain in his marriage and largely put to rest
an issue that had derailed the 1988 campaign of Gary Hart. But
under oath in his deposition in the Paula Jones civil suit this
year, the president acknowledged sexual contact with Ms. Flowers.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Clinton has occasionally articulated a personal
hierarchy of relative wrongdoing, once blurting out in a
conversation with reporters aboard Air Force One that it was the
moneychangers in the temple who really made Jesus mad, not the
adulterous woman, of whom Jesus said in the book of John: ``He that
is without sin among you, let him first cast a stone at her.''
</P>
<P>
   Morris, who was forced to resign on the day of the president's
renomination _ after his own affair with a prostitute became
public, wrote in his book, `Behind the Oval Office,'' that despite
his legendary outbursts of rage at advisers, Clinton ``doesn't
really blame others for his own errors.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Clinton savages himself for his mistakes,'' Morris wrote.
``He doesn't articulate his responsibility because his mind is so
filled with self-criticism.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
