<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BURMA-STUDENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDENT DEPORTED BY BURMA SAYS TRIP MADE HER AN ACTIVIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARCELLA BOMBARDIERI  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTSMOUTH, N.H. _ On the road from Rangoon, a city so tense
people would not look her in the eye, to her living room in
Portsmouth, where she was blinded by television camera lights, an
activist was born.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I considered myself an activist before this
trip,'' said Anjanette Hamilton, 20. ``I guess I am one now.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton came home Monday after an odyssey in which she was
sentenced to five years' hard labor by a Burmese court, but was
instead deported. Another trial awaited her after her arrival at
Newark International Airport early Monday morning: The naturally
shy young woman faced cameras and microphones and even appeared on
``Good Morning America'' to champion the cause of democracy in
Burma.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton, known as Angie, had been visiting Burmese refugee
camps in Thailand when her group, 18 activists from six Western and
Asian nations, decided to cross the border to mark a 1988 uprising
in which 3,000 Burmese were killed. Tourist visas in hand, they
signed up for a two-day tour of Rangoon, the capital city.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Aug. 8, the anniversary of the uprising, ``it was
very eerie, the city was very quiet and people were afraid to look
at us,'' Hamilton said. ``We went into one restaurant and the whole
place cleared out. There was a sense of fear and intimidation.''
</P>
<P>
   The next day, hoping the city would be more relaxed, Hamilton
and the other activists took to the streets. For five minutes at a
time, they would dash down a road handing out prodemocracy
leaflets, wearing T-shirts that said, in Burmese and English,
``8/8/88: Don't forget. Don't give up.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Hamilton looked relaxed in her American University
T-shirt. She will be a sophomore in the fall, and it was at
American that she joined a group called the Free Burma Coalition.
The organization is so devoted to ending the repressive military
regime that has held power since 1962 that its members, like
Hamilton, were willing to face detention and even prison in Burma.
</P>
<P>
   The foreigners, picked up while handing out the leaflets, were
well-treated in detention, though kept away from embassy
representatives for several days. Even when she received the prison
term Hamilton remained calm, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had confidence in our governments' ability to get us out of
there,'' she said. ``I thought maybe we'd be there a few months. It
was not that appealing, but I thought I could deal.''
</P>
<P>
   To Hamilton, putting herself at risk for the sake of a cause was
an obvious choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government is completely illegal, and the only reason it's
there is because they have guns and weapons,'' she said. ``If you
don't do anything to help, you can't really feel good about
yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Before she left the United States, Hamilton told her parents
that she would stay on the Thai border without entering Burma.
Though the group's reversal of that decision produced days of
suspense and drama, Hamilton's family stand by her actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's 20, she's really an adult, and it's her choice,'' said
Hamilton's mother, Alison. ``I think they know it was a little
naive, and I hope she wouldn't go into a country like that again.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton can never return to Burma, where she would face
immediate imprisonment. But she intends to continue working for
democracy in the Southeast Asian nation. A February fund-raiser is
already in the works, she said.
</P>
<P>
   In the short term, however, she plans to recover from jet lag
and visit with family and friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``This makes me realize how much I love everyone here,'' she
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
