<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-17 20:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8160 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-GORE-NYT &LR;      08-17 0483
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GORE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE ON FAMILY VACATION IN HAWAII AS CLINTON FACES LONGEST DAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Also see: CLINTON-RDP, CLINTON-PSYCHE, CLINTON-PROCESS,
CLINTON-HILLARY, CLINTON-FRIENDS, CLINTON-SCENE, CLINTON-LEGAL,
CLINTON-MEDIA, CLINTON-ASSESS, CLINTON-REACT.) 
 (JT)  
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When President Clinton appeared Monday before the
grand jury hearing evidence in the Monica Lewinsky investigation,
hardly anybody had a better reason to be closely tuned in than Al
Gore. But in fact the vice president was about as far away from
Washington as he could get and still be in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   He was in Hawaii with his wife, Tipper, and several of their
children, taking his annual August vacation, a trip that had been
`in planning' for at least three months, according to Jennifer
Devlin, a press spokeswoman for Mrs. Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vice president and his family always take a two-week
vacation at this time of year,'' Ms. Devlin said. ``He's staying at
a private home on one of the islands _ we're not saying which one _
and his schedule is private except that on August 25 he'll do a
Democratic fundraiser in Honolulu and also will speak to a meeting
of the American Federation of State, County and Municipal
Employees.''
</P>
<P>
   Did he spend the day on the beach or next to the television?
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing on that,'` Ms. Devlin replied.
</P>
<P>
   Any comment on the day's Washington events?
</P>
<P>
   ``No comment.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the Lewinsky investigation, Gore has made no
noticeable effort to distance himself from the president but
neither has he crisscrossed the country aggressively speaking out
in defense of Clinton. Rather, he has taken the position that the
president's denial of wrongdoing seemed straighforward enough and
he saw no reason to question it.
</P>
<P>
   The Gores arrived in the islands on Aug. 11 and will depart on
Aug. 26 for San Francisco, where they will participate in several
Democratic Party events before returning to Washington on Aug. 28.
Ms. Devlin said the couple have a sentimental attachment to Hawaii,
having spent their honeymoon there in 1970 and having subsequently
returned a number of times.
</P>
<P>
   At one point on Wednesday, the Gores were spotted swimming with
dolphins in a pool at the Hilton Waikoloa Village on the island of
Hawaii _ but not until after security personnel had plunged in
first to check things out.
</P>
<P>
   When Gore meets with Hawaii Democrats on Aug. 25, he likely will
face a warm and eager audience.
</P>
<P>
   Hawaii has traditionally been dominated by Democrats. But
because of cutbacks in military spending, a decline in the farm
sector and a sharp falloff in tourism from Asia, the state is one
of the few that face economic hard times and polls indicate that,
as a result, Democratic candidates throughout the islands will need
all the help they can get in this year's elections.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
