<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-SAVINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIANS WONDER WHAT WILL BECOME OF THEIR NEST EGGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also RUSSIA-ECON and RUSSIA-ASSESS) 
(mk) 
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Monday's de facto devaluation of the ruble and
rescheduling of government debt is supposed to spare the Russian
government financial ruin. Then there is Valeriya Yan, who is not
being let off so easily.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Ms. Yan set a goal: to raise $24,000 so she and
her husband could buy a two-room apartment for themselves and their
10-year-old son, away from the tiny one they share with two
parents. She gave up teaching for a mindless but more lucrative job
routing calls for a paging service for $300 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, a welder, is seldom paid, but they managed
nevertheless to squirrel away several thousand dollars' worth of
rubles. Monday afternoon she was hitting the currency shops that
glut Moscow's Arbat, converting her rubles into German marks at a
rate that only hours before seemed exorbitant. By her calculations,
the family nest egg bought one-third fewer marks than it would have
Monday morning, before devaluation was announced. ``I'm simply in
shock,'' she said. ``I'm doing this because I don't know what's
going to happen to my money.''
</P>
<P>
   In one sense, the answer is simple: Ms. Yan's rubles, along with
everyone else's, will buy a lot less from now on. After striving
for weeks to hold the key exchange rate at about 6.2 rubles per
dollar, the government gave up and announced Monday morning that it
would let the ruble sink as low as 9.5 rubles per dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours, currency traders who had been selling dollars for
6.3 and 6.4 rubles raised their rates to 7.5, 8 and even the
maximum 9.5 rubles per dollar. Rates for German marks and other
major currencies took similar routes.
</P>
<P>
   The harder questions, however, are where the value of the ruble
will eventually settle, and who will be most hurt by the change.
The government offered no hint in its announcement Monday, and so
millions of Russians are wrestling with the same dilemma: whether
to convert their rubles into a stable currency, and suffer a big
and immediate loss, or hold onto them and risk losing even more to
devaluation and inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Economists said Monday that there was no way to predict how many
rubles would buy a dollar in six months _ or in six weeks. Even
controlled devaluations like the ones announced Monday can easily
spiral out of control.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the price, Russian consumers could suffer most broadly
because devaluation raises the prices of imports _ and in Russia,
some 50 per cent of consumer goods and services are imported.
</P>
<P>
   The share of imports has risen swiftly in everyday commodities
like food, automobiles and household goods, where the availability
of better-quality Western products has been among the few widely
enjoyed benefits of capitalism _ and one that may now diminish.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow, where dollars are an unofficial second currency and as
much as 80 per cent of consumer products are imported, could suffer
disproportionately. The city is a center of Western investment and,
as Ms. Yan's nervousness demonstrates, a place where the dollar can
sway even purely local commodities like real estate.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts are already calculating that the banking and
currency problems spell the end of a boom that has changed the
Moscow skyline and created thousands of high-paying jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The average Russian hasn't felt it up till now,'' said Jesse
Loeb, a trader in the Moscow office of Regent European Securities.
``You're starting to see a major cash crunch on the street economy,
and that's going to get worse now. You're going to see a lot of
Mercedes 500s and 600s for sale. You'll be able to buy them for the
price of a Nissan. Whoever's in possession of cash now is king.''
</P>
<P>
   Devaluation has an upside, but largely for corporations, and
only some of them at that. Exporters like the oil industry gain,
because devaluation makes exports cheaper and thus more
competitive. Importers suffer, as would many companies whose
revenues are measured in rubles.
</P>
<P>
   Though Moscow was neck-deep in rumors Monday, there was scant
evidence of panic or even, at most places, lines of worried bank
customers. Some banks posted signs saying they had closed, like a
downtown Mezhkombank with a sign saying ``technical reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Many automatic teller machines did not work, or dispensed only
rubles. Currency traders interviewed Monday generally reported that
their business declined after rates were raised. But some said
business was greater than usual, and one reported a customer who
sought to change $50,000 in rubles into dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Some sellers of big-ticket items closed, perhaps out of
confusion over what their goods were worth. And on the western edge
of downtown, near the gingerbread-style station that serves trains
to Belarus, an unemployed handyman named Kolya Nikolayev was
competing with a nearby currency window, trying to buy dollars from
queued-up customers for resale at a higher rate.
</P>
<P>
   Like more than a few Russians, Nikolayev said the latest crisis
worried him not even a bit. ``Maybe it's because it's happened so
many times,'' he said. ``And because I have no money. I won't lose
anything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
