<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-LAWYERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYERS PLAY KEY ROLE IN PRESIDENT'S HISTORIC TESTIMONY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As President Clinton testified before a federal
grand jury Monday, six lawyers played a role in the historic moment
_ three on his side, three as prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   For more than five hours, the president responded to questions
from the team headed by independent counsel Kenneth Starr. Like
their boss, Starr's deputies have spent much of their careers
working for the government.
</P>
<P>
   Starr, who grew up in Thalia and Centerville before moving to
San Antonio, was appointed four years ago to take over the
investigation of President Clinton's business dealings,
specifically the failed Arkansas land deal called Whitewater.
</P>
<P>
   Starr had served as a judge on the U.S. Court of Appeals for the
District of Columbia under President Reagan, and President Bush
tapped him for solicitor general, the lawyer who argues government
cases before the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   While working as independent counsel, he kept his $1
million-a-year law practice until he took a leave of absence in
July.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's top deputy in Washington is Jackie M. Bennett Jr., who
supervises day-to-day operations, staff attorneys and paralegals,
and FBI computer and security experts.
</P>
<P>
   As senior trial lawyer in the Justice Department's Public
Integrity Division in the 1990s, he oversaw the department's
investigation and prosecution of San Antonio Rep. Albert
Bustamante, who was found guilty of bribery and racketeering.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Emmick joined Starr's staff a year ago after spending
almost 16 years in the U.S. attorney's office in Los Angeles. For
seven years, Emmick was head of the office's public corruption and
government fraud section.
</P>
<P>
   Emmick was involved in the secret taping of Monica Lewinsky in
January. That tape was used by Starr to convince Attorney General
Janet Reno and a three-judge panel to expand his investigation to
include a possible cover-up of the president's relationship with
the former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   On Clinton's side of the room Monday, were two law partners _
David E. Kendall and Nicole K. Seligman _ and Charles F.C. Ruff,
the White House counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike his voluble client, Kendall prefers not to speak
publicly, especially to reporters. In a speech to the American Bar
Association, he told colleagues that he lives by three words when
dealing with the press: ``Off the record.''
</P>
<P>
   A Quaker who grew up in Indiana, Kendall was arrested 10 times
at civil rights protests during the Mississippi Freedom Summer in
1964.
</P>
<P>
   He graduated from Wabash College in 1966, and two years later
attended Oxford University on a Rhodes scholarship. In 1971,
Kendall graduated from Yale Law School, where he overlapped a year
with Clinton and two years with Hillary Rodham.
</P>
<P>
   An ex-journalist, Seligman is defending her second client under
attack by an independent counsel. In the mid-1980s, a few years out
of Harvard Law School, she was paired with Brendan Sullivan to
defend Lt. Col. Oliver North in the Iran-Contra scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Although friends say she is more politically in tune with
Clinton than North, Seligman keeps her politics private. She was
managing editor of the Harvard Crimson and worked for the Asian
Wall Street Journal before returning to Harvard for her law degree.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton-Lewinsky investigation is the second inquiry of a
president in which Ruff has been involved. He was a prosecutor in
the Watergate case that brought down President Nixon in 1974. This
time, he's sitting alongside the president as White House counsel _
Clinton's fifth in almost six years.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans and Democrats alike cast Ruff as a lawyer of
intellect, fairness and integrity, and some White House aides
grumble that he does not pay enough attention to the political
impact of his advice to the president.
</P>
<P>
   Ruff has used a wheelchair since contracting a paralyzing
disease while working in Africa in the 1960s. In addition to his
days as a Watergate prosecutor (he was the fourth and final head of
that investigation), Ruff has worked as an associate attorney
general and U.S. attorney for the District of Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
