<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-17 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8172 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-ECON-2TAKES-NY     08-17 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ECON-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA TAKES DRASTIC STEPS TO RESCUE ECONOMY 
</HEADLINE>
   (See related: RUSSIA-SAVINGS, RUSSIA-ASSESS)  
(lb) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The Russian government moved hastily Monday to avert
financial collapse with a series of drastic measures, including
delaying payments for 90 days on foreign debt owed mostly by banks,
a restructuring of government bonds and the sacrifice of the ruble
to market forces.
</P>
<P>
   Holding Monday night at 6.43 rubles to the dollar, off slightly
from Friday's level, the value of the Russian currency is now free
to float as low as 9.5, a risky step _ tantamount to devaluation _
that many fear could trigger a new round of inflation. It could
also wipe out as much as a third of the ruble's purchasing power in
an economy heavily dependent on imports.
</P>
<P>
   Unleashing the ruble marks a major change in strategy for
President Boris Yeltsin's government, which after seven years of
economic reforms could point to a stable currency and a low rate of
inflation as its two major achievements. But that policy has been
overwhelmed by a crisis brought on by Russia's other economic
realities, including the insolvency of its risk-prone banking
system.
</P>
<P>
   The decision came over the weekend after Russian officials had
once again asked the nation's foreign allies for more financial
aid. Coming one month after a major drive, spearheaded by
Washington, to put together a $22.6 billion package of loans and
credits to Russia, the request was denied, and top Russian
officials on Monday acknowledged that further help from the West
was unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Monday morning, Prime Minister Sergei
Kiriyenko said the steps had been made necessary by the
near-collapse of Russia's banking system last week, and by the
exodus of foreign capital from Russia's markets. Foreign investors
have shunned markets here, spurred in part by the Asian financial
crisis and a drop in oil prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``The measures are tough ones, quite radical ones,'' said
Kiriyenko, a 36-year-old banker whose three months in office have
been marked by continuing crisis. ``But they are inevitable ones.
We do not have the right to put them off.''
</P>
<P>
   As word of the ruble's downward drift hit the streets, more and
more Russians headed for banks or currency-exchange booths, looking
to retrieve their savings or convert rubles into dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Although the official exchange rate shifted only slightly from
6.31 to 6.43 rubles to the dollar after a day of light trading on
the local currency market, some traders were offering rates as weak
as 9 rubles to the dollar, which some analysts took as hint of a
steeper devaluation to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, we don't know where the ruble will settle down
and when,'' said Charles Blitzer, director of emerging-markets
research at Donaldson, Lufkin and Jenrette, Inc. ``They are
allowing it to float, and will try to use monetary policy and
currency interventions to control it. But it remains to be seen
whether they will be able to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Technically, the government on Monday allowed the ruble to float
within a band that now ranges from 6 to 9.50, whereas the ruble's
previous band had held its value at between 5.27 and 7.13.
</P>
<P>
   The government, which late last week was trying hard to downplay
the imploding crisis in Russia's banking system, swung into action
over the weekend amid fears that the crisis would spark a run on
the banks, and spiral out of control.
</P>
<P>
   ``After last Friday, when a run on the banks was starting, there
was not much they could do,'' said Holger Mueller, banking analyst
at the Moscow office of the investment concern Fleming UCB. ``By
defaulting on foreign creditors, they would like to protect the
Russian population, but I think it is quite dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   Standard &AMP; Poor's, the credit-rating agency, on Monday cut
Russia's long-term foreign-currency debt rating two notches from a
B_ to a CCC. Other rating agencies followed suit but noted that in
announcing the 90-day moratorium on privately held foreign debt,
the government said the obligations would be honored.
</P>
<P>
   According to one Russian economist, the package was discussed
over the weekend with officials from the International Monetary
Fund and leading Western governments. But it is not known which
elements were supported by Russia's Western allies.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night John Odling-Smee, the IMF director in charge of
Russia, met with Anatoly Chubais, Yeltsin's special envoy to
Western financial institutions. After the meeting Chubais said the
crisis program had received lukewarm support.
</P>
<P>
   ``International monetary organizations, naturally, were not
enthusiastic about our proposal to restructure the state debt,''
Chubais told the RIA news agency. ``But they showed understanding
of the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Until the very last moment we hoped we would be able to avoid
such steps,'' said Chubais, the architect of Russia's privatization
program. ``But unfortunately last Friday it became clear we could
not avoid them.''
</P>
<P>
   The goal, he said, was to protect the Russian banking system
from an ``unmanageable chain of bankruptcies,'' and Russia's own
budget from ``disastrous scenarios.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Russian banking crisis erupted last week, economists
debated whether the government would opt to restructure its
domestic debt, default or at least defer its foreign loans or
devalue its currency. In the end, as several experts noted, they
chose all of those steps.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement released Monday, Michel Camdessus, managing
director of the IMF, stressed the importance of promises made by
Russia last month when the fund approved a new $22.6 billion
package of credits and loans. He pointedly mentioned a series of
revenue-raising and budget-tightening measures due to go before the
Duma, Parliament's lower house, on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be especially important for the Russian authorities to
take all necessary steps to strengthen the fiscal position,''
Camdessus said.
</P>
<P>
   Several Western economists said that unless accompanied by tough
new controls imposed on some of Russia's banks, the moratorium on
bank-held debts could be interpreted abroad as a bailout for those
politically well-connected institutions that until now have thrived
on risky loan strategies.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``The danger is that they could not use this opportunity to
solve these problems,'' said Al Breach, chief economist at the
Russian-European Center for Economic Research. ``If they don't, the
whole thing smacks of rule by oligarchy.''
</P>
<P>
   Twelve leading Russian commercial banks announced Monday that
they would pool together to resolve their inter-bank debts and
protect depositors.
</P>
<P>
   Several banks were reported to have received special credits
from the Central Bank late last week to keep their operations going
and to protect Russian depositors, who by one estimate have $4
billion in savings deposited in private commercial banks. Eighty
percent of private Russian savings are held by the giant Sberbank,
which is fully guaranteed by the government.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's package also includes a restructuring of an estimated
$60 billion worth of Russia's domestic debt _ in particular bonds
known as GKOs and OFZs due to mature before Dec. 31, 1999. Details
of those conversions will be released on Wednesday, but experts on
Monday were expecting a variety of options, which could include a
schedule of payments staggered over several years.
</P>
<P>
   For foreign investors, the bitterest pill is the 90-day
moratorium on the foreign debts now held mostly by major Russian
banks that by late last week were already defaulting on payments.
</P>
<P>
   The moratorium applies explicitly to forward ruble contracts and
loans backed by Russian government securities _ two loan mechanisms
favored by Russian bankers that have been undercut by the collapse
of Russia's financial markets and the weakened ruble. It is not
clear if the moratorium will apply to the $850 million in
syndicated loans that come due in the next three months.
</P>
<P>
   Since the IMF package was approved last month, the Russian
government has been criticized for its failure to coordinate its
response to the crisis and to clearly articulate its policy. On
Monday, Yeltsin named Boris Fyodorov, the tough-talking head of the
Russian Tax Service, as a deputy prime minister in charge of
macroeconomics, a post that some had expected to be filled by
either Chubais or Yegor Gaidar, Yeltsin's first prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin had said Friday that he would not interrupt his August
vacation for fear that a sudden change in plans would stir panic.
But as the crisis quickened, he returned to a country house near
Moscow over the weekend, where he held several meetings with top
officials.
</P>
<P>
   At its special session Friday, the Duma, dominated by a
Communist-led opposition, is expected to lash out at the Kiriyenko
government for the failure of its policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is total bankruptcy,'' said Gennady Zyuganov, leader of the
Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
   Nikolai Ryzhkov, who served as prime minister of the Soviet
Union and heads a small opposition party, said: ``The collapse has
come. This will bring numerous disasters to the people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
