<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-17 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8176 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SCENE-700(2TA     08-17 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SCENE-700(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S DAY: HISTORIC? DRAMATIC? SHAKESPEAREAN? ALL THAT AND
MORE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Also see: CLINTON-RDP, CLINTON-PSYCHE, CLINTON-PROCESS,
CLINTON-HILLARY, CLINTON-FRIENDS, CLINTON-GORE, CLINTON-LEGAL,
CLINTON-MEDIA, CLINTON-ASSESS, CLINTON-REACT.) 
 (JT)  
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It was a typical August day in the capital _ air
heavy with humidity, skies pewter-gray, a thunderstorm in the
afternoon, traffic slack. Vacationers' Bermuda shorts outnumbered
locals' business suits.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it was also a momentous day, a day like no other in the
republic's long history. For the first time ever, a president was
giving testimony to a grand jury investigating possible criminal
conduct on his part. Sitting in the ground-floor Map Room at the
White House, where Franklin D. Roosevelt kept track of the struggle
against Hitler and the Axis, Bill Clinton was grilled by his
nemesis, Kenneth Starr, the independent counsel, in the kind of
taut, face-to-face confrontation that few presidents ever endure.
</P>
<P>
   Historic? Dramatic? Shakespearean in its grand conflicts? That
and more. The president's predicament, and especially the
suggestion that he had been lying from the start about his
relationship with Monica Lewinsky, rasped against national myth.
Truth-telling is a salient feature of American heroes, and even in
a cynical age, the images of ``Honest Abe'' Lincoln and George
Washington, who could not tell a lie, lurk in the public
consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   But this was a play without an audience. The few who gathered
outside the White House and the E. Barrett Prettyman Court House,
where the grand jury sat, linked by closed-circuit television to
the Map Room, saw nothing and heard nothing. There were no shadows
on the wall or echoes on the wind for imagination to feast on.
</P>
<P>
   Gazing at the horde of camera crews on the White House lawn,
Cynthia Young, a 26-year-old social worker from Philadelphia,
sensed the magnitude of the occasion but said she felt curiously
unplugged. ``It's kind of strange walking around here and not
knowing what is actually happening,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The government, as is its wont, ground on. The Treasury
Department sold $5.79 billion in three-month bills at an average
discount rate of 4.910 percent; the Parole Commission met in
suburban Chevy Chase, Md., to discuss its budget, and the
Environmental Protection Agency considered ways to enable people to
use home computers to detect impurities in drinking water.
</P>
<P>
   But everyone in Washington waited and waited, all day long _
Hillary Rodham Clinton, Chelsea Clinton, lawyers, bureaucrats,
reporters, tourists _ for word that the testimony had ended. Then
they waited some more for the president's speech to the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians were on their guard, especially Republicans. But
some Democrats, including both members of Congress and presidential
aides, said privately that they felt betrayed, having doggedly
upheld Clinton's early denials only to be told at the last minute
that he was changing his story.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the president's private lawyer, Donald Kendall, came
out into the White House driveway to make what on one level sounded
like a perfunctory statement but on another sounded like a polemic
salvo in this war of words. A certain contempt dripped from his
description of a ``four-year, $40-million'' investigation that had
reached into Clinton's ``private life.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside the White House, aides passed the four hours and more
that the president testified, accompanied only by three lawyers, by
telling each other raunchy jokes and making ribald puns _ the same
jokes, the same puns that lobbyists and others exchanged at water
coolers around the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like election day,'' one presidential adviser said,
``except there aren't any exit polls.''
</P>
<P>
   Another remarked: ``Everything is on hold. You wait, hope it
goes well, but you can't do much.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, you can always spin. In Washington, that never stops
completely.
</P>
<P>
   So the White House let it be known that Erskine Bowles, the
chief of staff, had done his best to rally the troops at the senior
staff meeting on Monday morning. He stressed ``the importance of
sticking together,'' two participants said; he apparently did not
echo the other half of Benjamin Franklin's famous injunction to his
colleagues at the signing of the Declaration of Independence, ``We
must all hang together, or assuredly we shall all hang
separately.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson reported that he had been asked to come
to the White House at 10:30 on Sunday night, meeting for more than
two hours with Hillary Rodham Clinton and the Clintons' daughter,
Chelsea, and then with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Bill has a sense of embarrassment,'' Jackson reported
later. ``Hillary, as the wife, there's a sense of humiliation.
Hillary is dedicated to her marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   On days like this in Washington, there is often some bizarre
incident on the periphery, and so there was Monday. As a group of
10 tourists, standing outside the iron fence running along the
north side of the White House, debated the pros and cons of the
Lewinsky matter, a man in a white shirt, sandals and jeans listened
silently. Then he bolted away, shouting that the group was
discussing the wrong issue. What mattered, he said, was starvation
in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who cares about Clinton and Lewinsky when there's thousands of
people dying,'' he yelled, and started slashing at his own neck
with a screwdriver. Within a minute or two, Secret Service agents
put handcuffs on him.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   It was probably the most perilous day faced by the Clintons
since they met the challenge of Gennifer Flowers' allegations in
New Hampshire in 1992, one of those days with the potential to
leave an indelible mark on history. It could lead to impeachment
proceedings, even to a presidential resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Washington reacted to it with that curious mixture of
fascination and distaste, like a young student confronting
something particularly gross in biology lab, that has characterized
the nation's response all along.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton spent the day in the private quarters of the White
House. Monica Lewinsky's whereabouts was one of the day's minor
mysteries. But another of the president's closest confidants, Vice
President Al Gore, was vacationing with his family about as far
away as he could get while staying in the United States. Aides
reported that he was somewhere in Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   Few have as much at stake as Gore, whose political future is
unalterably linked to Clinton's. If Clinton approaches the end of
his term in 2000 in good shape, Gore's chances of winning the
presidency will be substantial; if not, not.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is this,'' one of the vice president's intimates
said, talking a little politics because it helped to pass the time,
``will Al Gore be George Bush, inheriting the magic mantle of
Ronald Reagan, or will he be Hubert Humphrey, drinking from Lyndon
Johnson's poisoned chalice?''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton chose the Map Room for his testimony and for his
subsequent nationally televised speech because of its very
ordinariness. Aides said that he wanted nothing at all showy.
</P>
<P>
   The room, where some of Clinton's infamous fund-raising coffees
were held, is decorated with American antique furniture in the
Chippendale style from New England and Philadelphia, with a Heriz
rug on the floor. A portable lap desk that belonged to Thomas
Jefferson is in the room, as is the last combat situation map drawn
for President Roosevelt, nine days before he died.
</P>
<P>
   From there, the president's testimony was transmitted across
town to the Prettyman court house, which is named for a former
federal appellate judge. Audio and video were carried on an
underground fiber-optic cable, scrambled to prevent eavesdropping.
</P>
<P>
   At the courthouse, between 16 to 23 grand jurors, seated in the
spectators' section of Judge Norma Holloway Johnson's courtroom,
watched on two large television sets. Reporters were kept 80 feet
away lest they overhear anything. It was not immediately known
whether the jurors availed themselves of a special telephone link
to suggest questions to Starr.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
