<DOCNO> NYT19980817.0394 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-17 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8179 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIA-POLITICS-ART-2T     08-17 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-POLITICS-ART-2TAKES(700)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL MELODRAMA: DON'T CRY FOR HER, TAMIL NADU
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By BARRY BEARAK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADRAS, India _ Among great melodramas about politically
powerful women _ the Evitas and Imeldas, the risen and fallen, the
adored and despised _ India these days offers Jayalalitha Jayaram,
a former movie star whose fickle control over a 27-vote bloc in
Parliament threatens to topple the five-month-old Hindu nationalist
government.
</P>
<P>
   Notoriously imperious, clad in ornate capes, Jayalalitha, as she
is known, was the Chief Minister of Tamil Nadu, a state in south
India, from 1991 to 1996, when she was voted out of office in
disgrace.
</P>
<P>
   Outlandish displays of sudden wealth gave credibility to
allegations of corruption, and she faces charges in state courts in
eight serious scandals.
</P>
<P>
   Her political resurrection occurred after the national elections
in February.
</P>
<P>
   With no single political group any longer dominant in India,
regional parties have assumed extraordinary importance. Her state
party, the All India Anna Dravida Munetra Kazhagam, won 18 seats in
Parliament and then, in an alliance, picked up nine more.
</P>
<P>
   The Hindu nationalist Bharatiya Janata Party won 178 seats but
needed to forge a coalition with 18 smaller parties to form a
government. Jayalalitha's 27 votes made her Bharatiya Janata's
biggest partner.
</P>
<P>
   Coalition governments often make for the strangest of
bedfellows, and the challenge is always to keep enough fellows in
the bed. Bharatiya Janata has long declared itself a party of good
governance. But its mating with Jayalalitha's party made it seem
compromised and left it vulnerable to the demands and tantrums of a
woman preoccupied with the prospect of prison.
</P>
<P>
   This past week, in what has become a staple of Indian headlines,
Jayalalitha, 50, threatened to abandon the coalition. She promised
a major announcement but then delayed it, saying ``appropriate
decisions'' would be made at ``an appropriate time.''
</P>
<P>
   Her latest complaint is that she was ignored during the
settlement of an interstate water dispute, but she has made no
secret of her chief problem with the agreement. She said there had
been an implied promise to invoke an article of the Constitution
that permits the national government to dismiss a state government.
</P>
<P>
   Tamil Nadu's current Chief Minister, Jayalalitha's archrival, is
Muthuvel Karunanidhi, himself often accused of ethical lapses and
moral amnesia. If the government had dismissed him, the state's
willpower to pursue criminal cases against Jayalalitha might well
have diminished.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her urgent need is to get out of these cases,'' said Cho
Ramaswamy, a journalist whose own roots are in the Tamil film
industry and who once was one of Jayalalitha's closest friends.
``She wants to bring down the central government, but she doesn't
realize that no matter who is at the center, they will not be
kindly disposed to this. Jayalalitha is not so politically sharp.''
</P>
<P>
   What she has been is one of India's mythic characters, whose
loves and triumphs and humiliations have been an ongoing public
soap opera.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm perceived as a strong and ruthless woman, it's because
life has turned me into someone like that,'' Jayalalitha recently
told an Indian film magazine in one of her infrequent interviews.
``If I hadn't been tough, I wouldn't have survived.''
</P>
<P>
   Educated in a convent, she dreamed early on of being a doctor or
lawyer. Instead she made her debut in Tamil movies at 13, pressed
into the career by her mother, herself an actress. ``I hated every
minute of being in films,'' Jayalalitha once reflected morosely.
</P>
<P>
   Within three years, the voluptuous teen-ager, big-eyed with a
dimpled smile, began playing her many lead roles as a spirited
heroine. Soon she was chosen to appear opposite the swashbuckling
M.G. Ramachandran, the biggest star in Tamil films.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the two appeared in 28 movies and, though Ramachandran
was married, it was widely believed that Jayalalitha was his
leading lady off screen as well.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually he also would prove wildly popular as a politician.
Though he was a Brahmin, he was a champion to the lower castes and
rural masses. Elected Chief Minister, he brought Jayalalitha,
another Brahmin, into the All India Anna Dravida Munetra Kazhagam
as something of an apprentice.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Whether Ramachandran remained her mentor until his death in 1987
is a matter of some dispute. The writer Valampuri John, who was a
friend to both, said the actor considered Jayalalitha disloyal at
the end and ``instructed that there be no communications with
her.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the truth, at his funeral she clung to his coffin
despite the protests of many in his entourage. At one point she
boarded the carriage that slowly transported the coffin, but she
was pulled off and, by her account, taunted, punched and cursed.
</P>
<P>
   Jayalalitha then tried, but failed, to stake claim immediately
to Ramachandran's political base. She has recalled falling into
depression, a condition that did not abate until she befriended
Sasikala Natarajan, the woman she has lived with off and on for a
decade.
</P>
<P>
   With Ms. Natarajan, once a maker of videos, as her chief
adviser, Jayalalitha was elected Chief Minister of Tamil Nadu in
1991, and she finally seemed to have joined Ramachandran on the
common man's pantheon of heroes.
</P>
<P>
   She felt comfortable on a pedestal. She demanded fealty. Others
were made to stand while she sat. People bowed when greeting her.
Plywood cutouts of her image, some of them eight stories high, were
placed in busy intersections here in Madras, the state capital.
Posters portrayed her as a Hindu goddess or the Virgin Mary.
</P>
<P>
   Gangs of loyalists attacked Jayalalitha's opponents. One of
those opponents was a Harvard-educated economist and political
maverick named Subramanian Swamy. He investigated Jayalalitha and
began passing evidence of her alleged corruption to prosecutors
here and in New Delhi.
</P>
<P>
   ``She made a public statement that she would crush me like a
mosquito,'' Swamy said. ``I must have escaped 12 attacks that might
have ended my life.''
</P>
<P>
   V.S. Chandralekha, a state official, made a critical remark
about Jayalalitha's government. Ms. Chandralekha was removed to a
lesser job. Then, nine days later, someone tossed a bottle of acid
into her face.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot say for sure that Jayalalitha did this, but she would
have knowledge about who did and she did not bring them to book for
this,'' said Ms. Chandralekha, whose face has been reconstructed
with skin grafts.
</P>
<P>
   The queenly Chief Minister seemed to be accumulating new wealth.
Some began to call her friend Ms. Natarajan ``the walking jewelry
store.''
</P>
<P>
   Jayalalitha adopted one of her friend's nephews as her ``foster
son,'' and when he married she gave him a spectacular wedding
party. Like a movie set, entire avenues in central Madras were
recast as scenes from Tamil mythology. Regiments of mounted
horsemen marched in parade. Lunch was served to 12,000 guests.
</P>
<P>
   ``This marriage was almost a confessional statement of her
corruption,'' said Ramaswamy, the journalist. ``It was her undoing.
People were disgusted.''
</P>
<P>
   But Tamil politics have long revolved around larger-than-life
personalities, and disgust has had a shorter shelf life than might
be imagined. Now, in India, the world's largest democracy, with
nuclear weapons at the ready and the rupee at a record low, the
fate of the national government may well rest upon the whims of
Jayalalitha.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Bharatiya Janata emissaries have repeatedly made
pilgrimage to Jayalalitha's residence, trying to soothe her hurt
feelings. Coincidentally, perhaps, a government official who has
pursued tax cases against Ms. Natarajan has been removed from
office.
</P>
<P>
   Jayalalitha has refused all requests for interviews. Oddly
enough, a new confidante has been speaking for her _ Subramanian
Swamy, the political maverick who once brought corruption charges
against her.
</P>
<P>
   Her alleged wickedness now seems to him no more a character flaw
than a bad hairdo. For him, like others, the bigger goal is to
bring down the governing party. Swamy has been trying to steer
Jayalalitha toward the once-dominant Congress Party, now headed by
Sonia Gandhi, the reluctant heir to the Nehru family's political
dynasty.
</P>
<P>
   It remains unclear whether the Congress would be any more
responsive to Jayalalitha's petulant demands, though Mrs. Gandhi
has said some discussion has gone on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jayalalitha is in a terrible dilemma,'' Swamy said
sympathetically. ``She asks herself: `Do I pull down this
government? And if I do, will something worse for me take its
place?'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
