</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLANSMAN-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-KLAN CHIEF GOES ON TRIAL IN 1966 KILLING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Miss.)   (af)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Monday, for the fifth time in 30 years, a former imperial
wizard of the Ku Klux Klan went on trial accused of masterminding a
firebombing that killed a black civil rights leader in 1966. This
time, prosecutors say they are confident that the jury in
Hattiesburg, Miss., will reach a different conclusion from the four
that deadlocked in the late 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very optimistic,'' Mike Moore, Mississippi's attorney
general, said about the trial of the former Klan wizard, Samuel H.
Bowers, 73, of Laurel, Miss. ``This is not going to be easy. It is
not a slam dunk. Bowers was tried several times. Still, I don't
think the state ever got a fair trial back in those days. And I
think there was some jury tampering going on. But because we have
new evidence and new witnesses I think we have a good chance for a
conviction.''
</P>
<P>
   The home of Vernon F. Dahmer (pronounced DAY-mer) was firebombed
on Jan. 10, 1966, because, prosecutors say, Dahmer had helped
register black voters in Hattiesburg. Four Klansmen were convicted
in Dahmer's murder, but Bowers went free. He served six years in
prison after his conviction on federal charges in three other civil
rights slayings in 1964.
</P>
<P>
   In May, state and Forrest County prosecutors cited new evidence
and new charges against Bowers and two other men. Bowers and
Charles Noble are charged with murder and arson. Deavours Nix,
another former Klansman, is charged with arson. Trial dates have
not been set for Noble and Nix.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the deadlocked juries in Bower's trials in the 1960s,
Monday's jury pool of more than 400 registered voters included
blacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that black people are registered to vote, and can sit on
juries and black political power is mobilized,'' said David
Ingebretsen, executive director of the American Civil Liberties
Union Mississippi, ``pressure can be brought to bear on elected
officials to have a trial like this. That is all a direct result of
the civil rights movement.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-98 2059EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980817.0397 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-17 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8189 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-PROCESS-NYT &LR;      08-17 1209
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PROCESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH CLINTON HAVING TESTIFIED, WHAT HAPPENS NOW? 
</HEADLINE>
  (Also see: CLINTON-RDP, CLINTON-PSYCHE, CLINTON-HILLARY,
CLINTON-FRIENDS, CLINTON-GORE, CLINTON-SCENE, CLINTON-LEGAL,
CLINTON-MEDIA, CLINTON-ASSESS, CLINTON-REACT.) 
 (JT)  
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton has now testified before the
grand jury. So have Monica Lewinsky and dozens of other witnesses.
So where does the investigation by Independent Counsel Kenneth
Starr, which began as an inquiry into a real-estate deal four years
ago, go now?
</P>
<P>
   Starr could still call witnesses before the grand jury to see if
they can contradict Clinton's testimony. He might recall Ms.
Lewinsky for that purpose. It is especially likely that Starr would
summon deputy White House counsel Bruce Lindsey, a key Clinton
advisor, since he fought in court here for the right to question
him.
</P>
<P>
   But over the next few weeks, Starr is expected to shift most of
his attention from evidence collecting to evidence sifting as he
combs through the facts and testimony for any ``substantial and
credible information'' that ``may constitute grounds for
impeachment.'' It is his duty under the Independent Counsel law to
report that evidence to the House.
</P>
<P>
   Using that ``credible'' information as his foundation, Starr
would write a report focused on what he considers ``impeachable
offenses,'' including relevant testimony and facts. Unless he finds
evidence of such offenses in the other issues he has investigated,
starting with the Whitewater land deal, he would probably limit his
report to the Lewinsky matter: to allegations that Clinton had an
affair with Ms. Lewinsky and subsequently attempted to cover it up.
</P>
<P>
   Impeachable offenses include ``treason, bribery or other high
crimes and misdemeanors,'' according to the U.S. Constitution, a
category left intentionally vague by the framers of the document.
</P>
<P>
   In 1970, when he was the House minority leader trying to impeach
Justice William Douglas, Gerald Ford called an impeachable offense,
``basically whatever a majority of the House of Representatives
considers'' it to be.
</P>
<P>
   Before turning his report over to the House, Starr would have to
make one last request to U.S. District Judge Norma Holloway
Johnson, who presides over the grand jury. Since grand jury
testimony is secret, Starr would have to ask the judge permission
to release all or part of the testimony to the House. Leon
Jaworski, special prosecutor in the Watergate investigation,
received such permission from Judge John Sirica in 1974 when he
forwarded a report to the House Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Starr would try to indict Clinton is constitutionally
unclear, but his supporters and critics say he is disinclined to
pursue an indictment, a tricky legal and political move that could
prompt drawn-out court challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think any prosecutor would relish a trial against the
president,'' said Judge Lawrence Walsh, the independent counsel in
the Iran-Contra investigation. But Starr is free to indict others
in the case, if the evidence warrants it, and that could enable him
to name the president as an unindicted co-conspirator, as
Jaworski's grand jury designated Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   Over on Capitol Hill, the House has been making preliminary
arrangements to receive the report, a prospect that pleases neither
Republicans nor Democrats who view it as a risky complication in an
election year.
</P>
<P>
   Once Starr is ready to submit the report, he is expected to
contact House Speaker Newt Gingrich of Georgia. Gingrich would ask
Starr to hold off for about 10 days, until the House can establish
new rules for how to handle the report, said a House Republican
aide familiar with the leadership's plan.
</P>
<P>
   The rules, which the full House would have to approve, would
grant the Judiciary Committee jurisdiction over the report, a
precedent that was set during Watergate. And they would allow only
the 21 Republicans and 16 Democrats on the Judiciary Committee _ a
wildly partisan bunch _ to have access to the report, an attempt by
congressional leaders to diminish the potential for leaks to the
news media.
</P>
<P>
   Once that groundwork has been laid, Starr would turn over the
report and the House Judiciary Committee, chaired by Rep. Henry
Hyde, R-Ill., would assume a role that is not unlike that of a
grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Committee members would read the report and do one of two things
_ ignore it or go forward with a preliminary ``review.'' The
committee could hold public or closed-door hearings and begin
calling witnesses to determine whether an impeachment inquiry is
warranted.
</P>
<P>
   If a decision is made to move ahead, the full House would vote
on a ``resolution of inquiry,'' which is when impeachment
proceedings would formally begin.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, most likely after the November elections, the
Judiciary Committee would intensify its investigation as it tries
to decide whether there is enough evidence of ``high crimes and
misdemeanors'' against Clinton to constitute an impeachable
offense. The panel could hold more elaborate hearings, summon grand
jury witnesses, as well as call new witnesses and expert witnesses.
It could ask Clinton to appear.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like a judicial proceeding where you have to show
probable cause, or some threshold,'' said Michael Dorf, a law
professor at Columbia University. ``The House itself defines the
threshold of evidence that they deem impeachable.''
</P>
<P>
   Impeachment is ultimately a political decision, with legal
overtones. It is not a process which most politicians regard with
enthusiasm, especially when the target is a president, like Nixon
or Clinton, who has been re-elected solidly. The only president
whom the House has ever impeached was Andrew Johnson, Abraham
Lincoln's vice president who became president on Lincoln's
assassination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think one of the lessons to come out of the Watergate
hearings is that the House took its responsibility quite seriously
and they understood that in order to to have credibility with the
people they would have to act on motives other than just
politics,'' Dorf said.
</P>
<P>
   Once the committee is satisfied with the evidence, the panel
would vote on articles of impeachment, followed by a full House
vote on impeachment. A simple majority vote is all that is needed.
</P>
<P>
   Then the process would shift to the Senate, which would conduct
an impeachment trial presided over by Chief Justice William
Rehnquist. The votes of two-thirds of the Senate _ 67 senators _
are required to convict and remove a federal official from office.
</P>
<P>
   There have been 16 impeachments in American history, most of
them judges. Only one president has been impeached by the House:
Andrew Johnson. The Senate failed to convict him by one vote.
</P>
<P>
   Even after Starr submits his report to the House, however, it's
not quite over for him.
</P>
<P>
   The independent counsel must piece together an exhaustive second
report for the three-judge panel that appointed him. This report,
which is mandatory, will offer a full accounting of what he did,
and what he found, during the past four years, beginning with his
investigation of the Whitewater land deal. The judges would decide
whether to make that report public.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-98 2103EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
