<DOCNO> NYT19980817.0398 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-17 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8191 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AFRICA-BOMB-515&AMP;ADD-N     08-17 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-BOMB-515&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. INVESTIGATORS BELIEVE BOMBING SUSPECT WILL COOPERATE WITH
THEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (See related: AFRICA-PAKISTAN)  
(js) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Law enforcement officials said Monday that a key
suspect in the bombing of the American Embassy in Nairobi had been
interviewed at length by American investigators, but had not
admitted any role and had not implicated Osama bin Laden, the
shadowy Saudi-born extremist thought to have inspired the bombings
in Kenya and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the officials said they believed that the suspect,
Mohammed Saddiq Odeh _ initially identified as Mohammed Sadik
Howaida _ was an important figure in the Nairobi bombing plot and
had knowledge of most of the details.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said they expected that Odeh would eventually
cooperate with American authorities. Pakistani officials said he
had cooperated when apprehended, shortly after landing in Karachi
on a flight from Kenya on Aug. 7, the day of the nearly
simultaneous bombings at the embassies.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the officials did not dispute reports from Pakistan
that Odeh had voluntarily confessed there, and that he had
identified several collaborators, calling bin Laden the driving
force behind the bombing and his spiritual guide in an Islamic holy
war against the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But a spokesman for the Taliban militia, which has protected bin
Laden at a stronghold in Afghanistan, previously said he had
pledged not to engage in terrorism while living under Taliban
protection and had nothing to do with the embassy bombings.
</P>
<P>
   Odeh was arrested when Pakistani immigration authorities found
that his face did not match the photograph on his Yemeni passport.
The document, in the name of Abdull Bast Awadah, was apparently
stolen. Afterward, Odeh took responsibility for the Nairobi bombing
and said he had visited Kenya over the course of several years to
plan the attack, Pakistani authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the Pakistani national newspaper, The News, said Odeh
was a 34-year-old Palestinian engineer who had helped supervise
technical details of the bombing plot. Other reports said that he
was married to a Kenyan and that his home base during his visits to
Nairobi was Mombasa, Kenya.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper said Odeh had told his Pakistani interrogators
that he was a follower of bin Laden. ``Osama bin Laden is our
supreme commander,'' Odeh was reported to have said, ``and by
blasting the United States embassies in Nairobi and Dar es Salaam,
we have shown our determination to meet our pledge to the Muslim
world.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Kenyan authorities and the FBI issued a statement
suggesting that Odeh had grown taciturn since American officials
returned him to Kenya on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Saddiq Odeh has not admitted any responsibility in the
bombings in Nairobi or Dar es Salaam,'' they said in the statement.
``Nor has he implicated anyone else in those events.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the possibility that American authorities have been
handed an important suspect who could help solve the case has
raised optimism among law enforcement officials. They are
meticulously assembling evidence in a manner that suggests that the
government would be prepared to try the plotters in an American
court.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The first planeloads of evidence from the Nairobi bombing
arrived at the FBI's main crime lab over the weekend. Officials
said experts had identified the explosive in the Kenya blast, but
no one could confirm earlier reports identifying it as Semtex, a
Czech-made explosive.
</P>
<P>
   As the investigation in Nairobi continued, some high-ranking
American officials were planning trips to Africa this week.
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright was to visit Nairobi and Dar
es Salaam on Tuesday to express support for the bombing victims and
to display American resolve.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will bring a message of friendship, made deeper by our
shared grief,'' Ms. Albright said before departing from Washington
Monday, ``and of support in doing all we can to ease their
suffering and help them start anew.''
</P>
<P>
   The FBI director, Louis Freeh, is also expected to visit Kenya
and Tanzania this week.
</P>
<P>
   Kenyan officials are likely to raise the issue of victim
compensation and financial assistance. Although some officials have
estimated that the blast caused more than $500 million in losses,
authorities have no detailed estimate of damages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
