<HEADER>
A8194 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-ASSESS-680&AMP;ADD     08-17 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ASSESS-680&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA HAD TO DO SOMETHING, ADMINISTRATION CONCEDES 
</HEADLINE>
   (See related: RUSSIA-ECON, RUSSIA-SAVINGS)  
(nk) 
 By SYLVIA NASAR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Russian government was denied additional
assistance from the United States and several other allies over the
weekend, causing it to take the steps that the Clinton
administration had opposed: allowing the ruble greater fluctuation,
imposing a moratorium on repaying foreign debt owed mostly by banks
and restructuring much of the government's debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``These particular choices were Russian choices in an
exceptionally difficult environment,'' a senior administration
official said Monday. ``We certainly expressed concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials acknowledged that the Russians,
faced last week with a spreading banking crisis, had little choice.
``Given the inability to restore confidence, some change was
necessary,'' said another administration official.
</P>
<P>
   A package of loans and credits totaling $22.6 billion announced
last month by the International Monetary Fund was supposed to buy
Russia time to enact the reforms that might restore investor
confidence. But as the currency and security markets continued to
weaken after the IMF package was unveiled, the strategy announced
Monday seeks to buy time another way, by lessening Russia's debt
burden and restoring confidence in its ability to get its fiscal
problems under control.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's view is that no further funds would be
forthcoming and that the onus is on the Russian government to
implement economic reform, according to both administration and IMF
officials who say that foreign aid is no substitute for Russia
cleaning up its own financial house.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe it is critically important that the Russian
authorities move quickly to take actions to restore confidence,
including the adoption of a careful and cooperative approach in
dealing with its creditors and the full implementation of the
measures outlined in the Russian stabilization program agreed with
the IMF,'' Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin said in a statement
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Having little leverage over the direction of events in Russia,
officials in Washington went to great lengths to reassure investors
that the United States was not abandoning Russia. ``We wanted to be
frank about the pros and cons,'' said one administration official.
``But there were no easy choices. It was the Russians' choice, but
now that Russia has made its choice, we're committed to working
with them to advance reform.''
</P>
<P>
   The roots of the current crisis go back to the early 1990s when
Russia was battling hyperinflation. The Russian government switched
from simply printing money to finance the budget deficit to issuing
bonds. The deficits kept growing, at one point reaching about 7
percent of the value of its economy. As the debt ballooned, nervous
investors were only willing to buy short-term instruments. That
meant that the bulk of domestic debt matured quickly and constantly
had to be refinanced.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, Russia has suffered a series of blows, namely
a collapse of oil and commodity prices as well as the economic
contagion from Asia. As investors grew more nervous, interest rates
of 100 percent to 200 percent were required to entice buyers.
Russia found itself in a classic debt trap: The investor requires a
high rate of return to invest in government bonds, raising the cost
of servicing the debt and the possibility of a default.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, when the IMF package clearly had failed to restore
confidence, the Yeltsin government opted for a combination of
time-honored, but risky, escapes. First, the prospect of a devalued
ruble could trigger inflation, which shrinks existing debt values.
Second, the government announced that it would restructure the
ruble-denominated debt, which involves involuntarily forcing the
holder of short-term maturity debt to accept longer-term
maturities.
</P>
<P>
   This tactic is analogous to a borrower taking a three-month IOU,
but later forcing the lender to accept a note for several years _
and at a new interest rate.
</P>
<P>
   The new maturities, interest rates and other details of the
restructuring are expected to be announced Wednesday, the Russian
government said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Initial reactions indicate that Russia's dramatic gestures may
work. It is certainly not a case, as in Japan, of too little too
late. Financial markets reacted relatively well Monday and
investors seem to be waiting to learn more details. Whether the
Russian gamble works will be evident in next few weeks. Investors
are waiting to see whether the run on the banking system and the
currency subsides. The political fallout in Russia will focus on
how the population views the government breaking its promise to
prevent a return of inflation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the time to abandon Russia,'' said Robert Hormats,
managing director at Goldman Sachs. ``It's a time to help them deal
with some of the critical issues that led them to take these
measures.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
