<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-17 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8196 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-FRIENDS-700(2     08-17 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-FRIENDS-700(2TAKES)--NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON FRIENDS, AIDES ADMIT FEELINGS OF BETRAYAL, ANGER,
HUMILIATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (Also see: CLINTON-RDP, CLINTON-PSYCHE, CLINTON-PROCESS,
CLINTON-HILLARY, CLINTON-GORE, CLINTON-SCENE, CLINTON-LEGAL,
CLINTON-MEDIA, CLINTON-ASSESS, CLINTON-REACT.) 
(JT) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE and DON VAN NATTA  Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Even before he addressed the nation, President
Clinton called in some of his closest aides over the weekend and,
one-by-one, told them the news that for months they had feared was
true: that he had an affair with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The meetings, which took place Saturday and Sunday, were
described by close Clinton associates as informal and involving
only some of his aides. And only in some cases, they said, did
Clinton express regret for his conduct.
</P>
<P>
   After seven months of public denials and private anguish over
the inquiry by Kenneth Starr, it was those confessionals that
helped Clinton fully come to terms with the toll the sex scandal
has wrought on his friends and on his presidency, according to two
close people close to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It him him hardest on Sunday,'' one close friend said. ``This
was a very, very difficult weekend for him. Nothing is more
important to him than his place in history. He is worried that this
investigation will eclipse everything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Even while Clinton's associates were telling reporters that he
might acknowledge having sexual relations with Ms. Lewinsky, the
friend said he was still ``in denial.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Four days ago, he said, ``the president told me he never had
sex with Monica.''
</P>
<P>
   Some who met with the president _ and who had loyally stood by
the president _ expressed feelings that they were betrayed, sullied
and even humiliated, according to people close to Clinton. One
friend said there was ``a lot of disappointment,'' and that it was
the aides' reaction that was most distressing, and caused the
president to ``beat himself up.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, even if the American public forgives him for bending the
truth in explaining his relationship Ms. Lewinsky, Clinton now
faces a problem closer to home: repairing relations with aides,
friends and Cabinet members who for months have steadfastly, and
publicly, defended him. Collectively, these people face hundreds of
thousands of dollars in legal bills related to the investigations
that have punctuated his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Mike McCurry, the White House press secretary, was unequivocal
when the Lewinsky matter first broke, declaring, ``The president is
outraged by these allegations. He's never had any improper
relationship with this women.''
</P>
<P>
   Does he now feel like a chump?
</P>
<P>
   Monday, McCurry sidestepped the question, saying he was still
figuring out how he feels. But he seemed to acknowledge his
discomfort. ``I'm not so self-preoccupied to be thinking about how
I feel,'' he said in an interview. ``I think it's important that
the president talked to the American people because whatever
position I'm in, they're in much the same position. I'm sure all
the rest of us will sort out how we feel in due course.''
</P>
<P>
   Lanny Davis, an outside adviser who has been one of the most
aggressive Clinton defenders, spoke of his disappointment in an
interview Monday night: ``My disappointment is not personal. I'm a
friend and a supporter and I will stand by him in a difficult time
like this. My disappointment is that his presidency should be
judged as a great one and we've got to work even harder now for his
legacy because of what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides Hillary Rodham Clinton, who ridiculed the allegations as
the product of a ``vast right-wing conspiracy,'' Clinton's most
unwavering defenders include Ann Lewis, the communications director
who for years has been close to Mrs. Clinton, and two senior aides
who have been with Clinton since the 1992 campaign, Paul Begala and
Rahm Emanuel.
</P>
<P>
   Asked Monday night if he feels betrayed, Emanuel said, ``This
guy is dealing with something very personal. He is taking
responsibility for it. Where I come from you don't choose high and
low moments around your friends. I'm a staff person and I'm going
to be loyal to him. He and I have a history together.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewis, who had insisted that Clinton was not making any
distinctions between different forms of sex, said in January, ``Sex
is sex. Even in Washington, I've been assured.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, Ms. Lewis refused to talk about her own feelings
about the president, saying, ``I'm not going to go there. It is
more appropriate today for people to hear the president.''
</P>
<P>
   The highest profile members of the administration, no doubt,
will also be sorting out their feelings. In January, Clinton
assured his Cabinet he was innocent and Madeleine Albright, the
secretary of state, stepped out on the White House driveway to back
him up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the allegations are completely untrue,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll second that. Definitely,'' said William Daley, the
commerce secretary.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Third it,'' said Donna Shalala, the secretary of health and
human services.
</P>
<P>
   The last seven months have been particularly trying for some of
Clinton's defenders who, speaking on the condition of anonymity,
said they suspected he was guilty but pressed on, or tried to
convince themselves of his innocence, not wanting to abandon him.
Some, like Jack Quinn, a former White House counsel, have been
careful to preface their defenses of Clinton with phrases like,
 &UR; ``If he says he didn't do this, &LR;  I believe him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever their inner suspicions, they went out there,'' said
Leon Panetta, Clinton's former chief of staff. He said he has
spoken with some current White House aides whose only solace Monday
was that their ordeal may finally be ending.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to some who said it was almost a relief,'' Panetta
said in an interview. ``Their greatest fear was if this had to go
on for another six or seven months and what it was doing to them
and to the president.''
</P>
<P>
   Panetta, who was Clinton's budget director and a longtime
congressman from California, said he was personally disappointed in
the president. But most of all, he said, Clinton owes his staff
``an eye-to-eye'' apology. ``You don't want to hang your staff out
there with false statements,'' he said. ``When you're asked to spin
something that's not truthful, that's where you have to draw the
line.''
</P>
<P>
   Another person close to Clinton said the president this weekend
fully began grappling with many of the emotions his friends have
dealt with for months. ``He had to deal with the mixed emotions of
relief and anger and remorse.'' He said that Clinton relied
particularly on Hillary Rodham Clinton this weekend to keep up his
spirits over the weekend. As she has in the past, she was described
as focused on the task before facing them, preparing for the grand
jury's questions and for an address to the nation.
</P>
<P>
   There has been a perceptible shift in tone in recent weeks among
Clinton's staunchest defenders, particularly at the White House,
where aides have been less energetic in defending Clinton and in
condemning Kenneth Starr, the independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   George Stephanopoulos, the former senior adviser to Clinton,
said he expected Clinton's defenders to become even more angry as
time wears on. ``I can imagine in the short run being numb by the
crush of events,'' he said. ``A kind of battle fatigue takes over.
Where it may get difficult is in the coming days when people have
to confront what happened and go on.''
</P>
<P>
   For some people the anger is already open. Dee Dee Myers,
Clinton's former press secretary, said she did not specifically say
the president had not had an affair, but did speak out in support
of him when the scandal erupted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel disappointed in him, I'm angry,'' she said. ``He put
people through hell, including the staff and people who are my
friends. The president has to apologize or they have to quit. The
president has to be truly, truly contrite. I'm sure he didn't
intend to hurt or embarrass them. But he did.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
