u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGO-REBELLION-ART-5     08-17 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGO-REBELLION-ART-510&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS REBEL THREAT GROWS, CONGO RALLIES AROUND KABILA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KINSHASA, Congo _ Rebels again cut electricity and water to this
capital of 5 million people on Monday, heightening fears about an
imminent attack. As the threat intensified, support for President
Laurent Kabila apparently grew.
</P>
<P>
   Hours after the blackout began, the government acknowledged its
loss of control over the huge Inga hydroelectric dam. On Friday,
government ministers privately reported that the dam had fallen.
</P>
<P>
   The dam supplies most of this country's electricity, as well as
power to nearby areas of other countries. Senior government
officials faulted Rwanda for the loss and called the rebels' use of
the dam an example of state terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Information Minister Didier Mumengi said that the government was
fighting the rebels, in small groups southwest of Kinshasa, and
that it would establish an emergency plan on Tuesday to provide
electricity and water here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rwandan aggressors have brought their genocidal culture
onto our territory,'' Mumengi said, adding that Congo was
``prepared to fight Rwanda and to take and finish the war in
Kigali,'' its capital.
</P>
<P>
   The government campaign to depict the rebels as tools of Rwanda
appeared to be working. Some residents voiced strong support for
Kabila and rising anger with the Rwandans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rwandan Tutsi want to establish a Tutsi empire in the
Congo,'' an economics student, Jean-Felix Tshobo, said. ``Last time
we were sick of Mobutu and so we welcomed the rebels here. But this
time it's different. We're ready to take arms if they come here.''
</P>
<P>
   The insurgency recalls the movement that led to the fall of
Mobutu Sese Seko, the dictator for more than 30 years. But this war
is producing different reactions. It has galvanized support for
Kabila, whose popularity had tumbled after he had cracked down on
political liberties and demonstrated a lack of diplomatic skills.
And the fighting has led to a surge in nationalism, fueled by
government propaganda and animosity toward the Tutsi, who propelled
Kabila to power but from whom he later distanced himself.
</P>
<P>
   Conversations here indicate that the ethnic Tutsi rebels are
being viewed as invaders. In a country that has avoided the
murderous ethnic rivalries that have erupted elsewhere in Africa,
that could prove explosive.
</P>
<P>
   On a sleepy summertime campus at the University of Kinshasa,
Mapasahi Ndengo put the final touches on a wood panel that he was
transforming into a checkerboard. ``We need peace in our country so
that we can build things,'' Ndengo, 25, a law student, said. ``Last
time was a war of liberation. This is an unjust war that they are
waging against us. We are all behind Kabila.''
</P>
<P>
   As a score of classmates gathered, they began denouncing the
rebels who are trying to topple the 15-month-old government.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Tutsi are unbearable,'' said Elsin Falasi, 24, an
agriculture student, referring to the ethnic Tutsi who had
immigrated from Rwanda not many generations ago. ``We have 255
tribes in this country. They're the 255th, and right away they want
to be No. 1.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Residents seemed to overlook misgivings about Kabila and focused
on how some of his policies had improved public works, safety,
shopping and public spirit.
</P>
<P>
   On the main commercial road, Avenue de la Victoire, men milled
around a square near a gasoline station.
</P>
<P>
   ``During Mobutu's regime, we couldn't assemble here like we're
doing now,'' Paul Kitwanda, 34, who teaches in an elementary
school, said. ``Now I can go out of my house and go anywhere. I
don't have to worry about carrying money in my pocket and having it
stolen by some soldiers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Under Mobutu I'd go buy a loaf of bread,'' Bompoku Ngele, 30,
said, ``and every morning it would be more and more expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The gutters have been drained,'' Joseph Kakoudi, 28, said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Volunteers are draining them,'' Ngele said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Volunteers!'' Kakoudi said.
</P>
</TEXT>
