<DOCNO> NYT19980817.0405 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-17 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8207 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-MEDIA-700&AMP;add     08-17 1112
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MEDIA-700&AMP;add-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETWORKS LOOK FOR ACTION, SETTLE FOR WORDS ... AND MORE WORDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Also see: CLINTON-RDP, CLINTON-PSYCHE, CLINTON-PROCESS,
CLINTON-HILLARY, CLINTON-FRIENDS, CLINTON-GORE, CLINTON-SCENE,
CLINTON-LEGAL, CLINTON-ASSESS, CLINTON-REACT.) 
(JT) 
 By JANNY SCOTT    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the interminable television coverage of all that was not
known about President Clinton's testimony during his long afternoon
in the White House Map Room Monday, one moment seemed to exemplify
the bizarre challenge facing the 24-hour-news networks: the arrival
at the White House of the independent counsel's sedan.
</P>
<P>
   It was, after all, the only action for most of the day _ a day
on which MSNBC and CNN were devoting almost undivided attention to
the mostly invisible doings in Washington. So the approach of
Kenneth Starr's car shortly before 12:30 p.m. was greeted with the
kind of rapt attentiveness the networks usually reserve for the
coffin at the funeral of a head of state.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's in the back seat,'' Frank Sesno of CNN interrupted an
interview to announce. (``He traditionally travels in that
fashion,'' Sesno added as an aside.) A few minutes later: ``Ken
Starr, if I may now interrupt, is getting out of the car, putting
on his jacket.'' Then more: ``It seems to be, if we can judge from
this distance, a somewhat leisurely, relaxed Ken Starr.''
</P>
<P>
   Hour after hour Monday, the two cable news networks tried
mightily to eke high drama out of an event that no reporter or
camera was allowed to witness. They televised portentous headlines,
played scary music, interviewed experts with ``former'' after their
names and replayed the greatest hits from their videotape libraries
of the Lewinsky case.
</P>
<P>
   They did their best to create suspense: Would Clinton change his
story? Did Starr have the goods? Would the prosecutors and the
defense lawyers get into a spat? ``Stay with the people who brought
you the year's biggest story,'' one MSNBC promo urged. On CNN, Mary
Tillotson signed off from ``CNN &AMP; Company'' cheerily: ``More on the
president's legal and political problems tomorrow. See you then.''
</P>
<P>
   CNN took a novel approach, as if covering an athletic event like
the Tour de France. It parked a scoreboard in the upper right-hand
corner of the television screen. Under the heading ``President
Clinton's Testimony,'' a clock tracked the number of hours and
minutes elapsed. A mysterious second category, entitled ``Status,''
was followed most of the day by the answer ``Testifying.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, anchors seemed to strive for dignity (at a
time when the news media have been accused of everything but).
Brian Williams, the MSNBC anchorman, assured his viewers that
nobody was having any fun. Other networks skipped wall-to-wall
coverage for much of the day in favor of occasional discreet
interruptions of their regularly scheduled soaps. ``We're trying
hard to be pillars of accuracy today,'' said Dan Rather, the CBS
anchorman, popping in briefly about 1 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   In early evening, with Clinton already having completed his
testimony, reporters were still reading tea leaves: Clinton's
lawyer, David Kendall, emerged from the White House shortly before
6:45 p.m. and, stationing himself at the awaiting microphone,
anticlimactically announced that any comment on Clinton's testimony
would have to come from Clinton himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there is much to be added to what he said,'' Bob
Schieffer, the CBS reporter and analyst, replied bluntly when
Rather invited him to do some analyzing.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As might have been expected, television coverage of the day
began bright and early. On the morning news programs, pundits were
out in force. In fact, much of the day was whiled away with
interviews with presidential historians, presidential biographers,
bureau chiefs, former White House special counsels, former
prosecutors, former senior Justice Department officials.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters and anchors scrambled to explore every conceivable and
not-so-conceivable angle. How would Clinton's testimony affect his
marriage? Where are the heroes of today? How was Wall Street
reacting? How about the folks at a ``popular lunch place'' in
Little Rock? At the Illinois State Fair? At the Richard M. Nixon
Presidential Library?
</P>
<P>
   The pundits could generally be counted on to adhere faithfully
to their appointed roles. Partisans of the president took pains to
point out how much money Starr's office had spent. Those with more
conservative affiliations invoked the gravity of the situation and
used phrases like ``the linchpin of our democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   As for whatever it was Clinton was in there saying, pundits
commented on recent news reports that he would testify that he had
had an inappropriate relationship but had not committed perjury.
``No American with 20 neurons working simultaneously in their brain
is going to accept such a puerile and nonsensical explanation,''
said Mona Charen, a syndicated columnist speaking on ``CNN &AMP;
Company.''
</P>
<P>
   Every time news looked as if it might surface, reporters and
anchors jumped. MSNBC reported that officials had stationed a
boombox playing classical music in the hall outside the courtroom
where the grand jurors were sitting, lest reporters overhear any
rumblings from the closed-circuit telecast of the president's
testimony. CNN then reported a new development: ``There will be no
boombox after all,'' Bob Franken reported, looking amused.
</P>
<P>
   CNN quoted Paula Corbin Jones' husband as announcing that Mrs.
Jones was ``taking a wait-and-see attitude.'' Anchors periodically
stepped in to say things like ``President Clinton is in his 54th
minute of testimony.''
</P>
<P>
   To fill time, there was plenty of familiar old video footage:
Clinton and Monica Lewinsky in that infamous slow-motion hug, Starr
smiling tightly as he steps into and out of various cars, Linda
Tripp emerging from the grand jury room, Clinton earnestly speaking
to the country early this year about the sexual relations he did
not have with ``that woman, Miss Lewinsky.''
</P>
<P>
   At every commercial break came the music, sounding variously
like the background for a chase scene or an original soundtrack for
a made-for-television movie about child abduction. There were
fancy, computer-generated schematics of the White House, showing
the Map Room and tracking the fiber-optic hookup transmitting
Clinton's testimony to the federal courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things have been very, very quiet,'' John Palmer, a reporter
for NBC, announced glumly about one hour into Clinton's testimony.
``It already seems like a long afternoon.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-98 2121EDT &QL; 
