</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-RULING-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT WARNS OF `MEDIA CIRCUS' IF PRESS, PUBLIC ATTEND
DEPOSITIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WARREN WILSON  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Microsoft Monday warned a federal appeals court that the
depositions of chairman Bill Gates and other executives will turn
into a ``media circus'' if reporters and the public are allowed to
attend.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson, who is overseeing
the government's antitrust case against Microsoft, ruled a week ago
that the depositions must be open to the public. Various news
organizations had requested access to them, citing a 1913 law
called the ``Publicity in Taking Evidence Act.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft quickly appealed, saying valuable trade secrets would
be at risk if 25 remaining depositions are open to the public
reporters. Twenty have already been taken, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides creating a ``carnival atmosphere,'' the presence of
reporters and the public might bring up issues of confidentiality
that only the judge can settle. That raises the prospect of
frequent delays that will disrupt and prolong the taking of
depositions with just a few weeks remaining before the trial,
schedule to start Sept. 8.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, discussions continued Monday among Microsoft, the
government and the news organizations about what procedures to
follow if the depositions are indeed open _ when and where they
will be taken, how many extra people will have to be accommodated
and whether any recording devices would be allowed, among other
questions.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever terms they agree on will be submitted to Jackson for
his approval. The discussions were said to be nearly complete
Monday, but if an agreement was reached it apparently didn't reach
Jackson in time for him to act on it.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did Jackson rule on requests by Microsoft and the government
that he postpone the start of the trial for two weeks because of
the delays that already have occurred in the deposition process.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has also asked Jackson to issue a summary judgment
dismissing the government's claims, a prospect that is regarded as
unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   Federal and state antitrust regulators filed suit against
Microsoft on May 18, accusing it of violating the Sherman Antitrust
Act by ``tying'' its Internet browser to its Windows operating
system.
</P>
<P>
   Computer makers had no real choice but to accept the browser
because they had no practical alternative to Windows, which is
installed on the vast majority of new computers sold today, the
government argues. Microsoft's actions amount to an abuse of
monopoly power that has harmed competition in the market for
Internet browsing software, where Microsoft is steadily gaining on
the leader, Netscape Communications, the government said.
</P>
<P>
   The allegations echo those of an earlier federal lawsuit that
said the tying of the browser to the operating system violated a
consent decree Microsoft entered in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft argued that it didn't ``tie'' the two software
products together; rather, it ``integrated'' the browser into the
operating system in a way benefits consumers.
</P>
<P>
   A three-judge appeals panel ruled in Microsoft's favor in June.
Although the ruling came in the consent-decree case, the issues so
closely paralled those of the second case that Microsoft and many
outside observers viewed it as a major victory for the company.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
