<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLDEN-MERGER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOTE CLOSES OUT GLENFED'S 64 YEARS AS GOLDEN STATE ABSORBS AREA
THRIFT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DEBORAH ADAMSON  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With a short statement adjourning Monday's
shareholders meeting, Golden State Bancorp Chief Executive Stephen
Trafton quietly ended the 64-year existence of Glendale Federal
Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Several hundred shareholders in nearby Glendale sat in silence
as a Golden State executive read aloud that 98.4 percent of votes
cast favored its merger with First Nationwide Holdings in San
Francisco, the owner of California Federal Bank.
</P>
<P>
   The $1.8 billion merger, which already received approval from
regulators, is expected to close on Sept. 11.
</P>
<P>
   The deal creates a thrift with $52 billion in assets, $28
billion in deposits _ the fourth-largest in California _ and 359
branches. The new company will retain the Golden State Bancorp name
but operate California Federal Bank branches. Only a handful of
former Glendale Federal executives will stay.
</P>
<P>
   Current Golden State shareholders will end up with 58 percent of
the new company, while owners of First Nationwide _ mainly
billionaire financier Ron Perelman and his top assistant, Gerald
Ford _ will get a 42 percent share.
</P>
<P>
   But some shareholders at the meeting weren't clear about the
benefits of the merger to minority shareholders and expressed
concern about Perelman. When asked what he knew about the reclusive
billionaire, Trafton called him a ``value builder'' and a ``tough
financier'' but said he has only met him once, to the chagrin of
many in the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Other shareholders were upset that the stock price has dropped
substantially from a high of $35.5625 on June 9 to a low of $21.75
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Trafton explained that the general market downturn hurt the
company's stock and the exercise of options and conversion of
preferred stock to common shares increased the number of floating
shares and diluted its price.
</P>
<P>
   However, ``the fundamental values (of the company) have not
changed since we presented them to you,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shareholders also wondered whether Trafton's exercise of his
stock options, of which 333,333 remain out of 2.1 million, shows a
lack of confidence in the new company. Trafton explained that he
wanted to diversify his holdings, so he cashed out his Golden State
stock and invested the money elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Trafton and Richard Fink, vice chairman of Golden State, will
stay with the new company to handle the lawsuit both thrifts filed
against the federal government. The lawsuits stem from the
government's breach of contract that led to the thrifts losing
hundreds of millions of dollars in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Final oral arguments on the case will be made in September and a
ruling is expected by year's end, Trafton said. But any decision
likely will be appealed by the losing side, Trafton warned, and
shareholders should not expect to benefit until after the year
2000.
</P>
<P>
   Trafton and Fink have 3-year and 2 1/2- (one-half) year
contracts as litigation managers to which they are paid $600,000
and $400,000 a year, respectively. They also will get 0.25 percent
of any pretax windfall they get from the lawsuits, which some
analysts have said could be about $1 billion. That comes out to
$2.5 million each.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Trafton gets a lifetime pension of $1 million a
year and Fink $325,000 annually. When they die, their wives will
get half of the yearly pension.
</P>
<P>
   These golden parachutes aren't unreasonable, said Keith Davis,
director of compensation at SNL Securities, a Virginia-based
research firm specializing in the financial services industry.
</P>
<P>
   Trafton will be paid less than his annual salary at Golden State
while Fink will be paid at about the same level, he said. Their
pensions also aren't too far out of line from that of other
employees, who will get more than half of their annual salary as
their yearly pension if they stay for at least 30 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
