<HEADLINE>
(HLW)
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories that New York Times editors are planning
for the Page 1 of Tuesday, Aug. 18. The N.Y. Times News Service
supervisor is Henry Louis Warnken.
</P>
<P>
   For copy info: (212) 556-1927.
</P>
<P>
   For graphics, map, photo info: (212) 556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TOP: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lead story: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-RDP (Washington) _ Ledeall: President Clinton testifies
from the White House to the Kenneth Starr grand jury. By James
Bennet.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move this story by 10:15 p.m. ET in `w' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   6-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Off-lead: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   4-column photo layout with CLINTON-RDP.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOLD: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-FRIENDS (Washington) _ Reaction among the president's
defenders: how they feel about his testimony. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved; `w' category.)
</P>
<P>
   1-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-PSYCHE (Washington) _ Todd S. Purdum examines the
elements of Clinton's character and personality that have led him
to this pivotal day in his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved; `w' category.)
</P>
<P>
   3-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ECON (Moscow) _ After weeks of financial turmoil, Russia
sharply devalued the ruble today and put a 90-day moratorium on
foreign debt, a move expected to cause hardship for Russian
consumers. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved; `i' category.)
</P>
<P>
   1-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BOTTOM: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   4-column photo with CLINTON-RDP.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-BOMB (Washington) _ Developments on the suspect in the
embassy attack being detained in Kenya. By David Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved; `i' category.)
</P>
<P>
   4-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INSIDE STORIES PROMOTED ON PAGE 1: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-BOMB (Omagh) _ Police arrest suspects in Saturday's
bombing. Reports say one of the arrested is a major figure in the
Real IRA. By James F. Clarity.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved; `i' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BLACK-FEMALE-INCOME (Charlotte, N.C.) _ Long situated at the
bottom of the economic scale, the income for single black female
heads-of-household has been rising sharply in recent years, pushed
by a strong economy, tight labor markets, increases in the minimum
wage, more stringent welfare eligibility requirements and
government training programs. By Steven A. Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move this story by 9 p.m. ET in `a' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ALASKA-THAW (Undated) _ Alaska is thawing, and much of
northern Russia and Canada with it, and many scientists say that
the warming of these cold regions is one of the most telling
signals so far that the planet's climate is changing. Experts have
long said that in an era of global warming, this bellwether region
should warm up more and faster than the Earth as a whole, and so
far that is just how things are turning out. The signs are
everywhere. By William K. Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved; `a' category.)
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-GREEN (Undated) _ Julian Green, the prolific and highly
idiosyncratic novelist, playwright and memoirist who was the first
American elected to the Academie Francaise, France's gallery of 40
literary luminaries, died on Thursday in Paris. He was 97. By
Richard E. Nicholls.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved; `a' category.)
</P>
