<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 8/17/98. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or (212) 556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) STAMFORD, Conn. -- Aug. 17, 1998 -- PITNEY-BOWES, 8-17
-- When Michael Critelli became chief executive of Pitney Bowes two
years ago, he remembers being told that ``we'd drop off a cliff.''
Actually, the company has kept its footing quite well. Its meters
and fax machines are renting briskly, and its management services
division is finding new customers. ``Now we're looking to compete
in every messaging niche,'' says Critelli. (Jonathan Levine/New
York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) WASHINGTON -- Aug. 17, 1998 -- CLINTON-RDP-2, 8-17 --
Members of the media, including, from left, ABC's Sam Donaldson,
CNN's Wolf Blitzer and Henry Champ of Canadian television, during
live broadcasts Monday at the White House. After more than four
hours of questioning under oath from independent counsel Kenneth
Starr, President Clinton testified Monday that he had engaged in an
inappropriate relationship with White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
(Rick McKay/Cox News Service Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) WASHINGTON -- Aug. 17, 1998 -- CLINTON-RDP-1, 8-17 --
Members of the media setting up on the grounds of the White House
on Monday before President Clinton's testimony in front of the
federal grand jury. Forced by prosecutors and political reality to
reverse course after months of denial, Clinton testified under oath
Monday that he had engaged in an inappropriate relationship with
White House intern Monica Lewinsky. (Justin Lane/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- Aug. 17, 1998 -- SWIMSUIT-FASHION-2, 8-17 --
``Swimwear is very important,'' says Nicole Fischelis, the fashion
director of Saks Fifth Avenue. ``Our cruise catalog will have 25
pages of beachwear.'' From left, Speedo calls this
athletic-inspired swimsuit the Euro tank (Andrea Mohin/New York
Times Photo); Bikini by Nautica is worn with a miniskirt coverup
(Barbara Alper/New York Times Photo); Liz Claiborne's tank swimsuit
in a stretch cotton that looks like blue denim; her denim-look
tankini bares the midriff. (Ruby Washington/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- Aug. 17, 1998 -- SWIMSUIT-FASHION-1, 8-17 --
Cruise is the most important season for swimwear because the suits
are in stores for more than six months, starting in October, and
account for the greatest percentage of swimwear sales. From left,
bikini, cut-out tank and high-necked suits are among the styles
modeled in Calvin Klein's showroom (George M. Gutierrez/New York
Times Photo); Anne Klein swimsuit has a sheer layer over opaque bra
and bikini; Bergdorf Goodman will have Tomas Maier's suit. (Librado
Romero/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) BETHEL, N.Y. -- Aug. 17, 1998 --
WOODSTOCK-MUSIC-REVIEW-2, 8-17 -- Robby Takac of the Goo Goo Dolls,
among the current groups performing at ``A Day in the Garden''
festival in Bethel. The headliners were current hit makers in their
20s and 30s, not performers who had been established for decades,
and the audience had fewer parents and many more teen-agers,
including a large contingent of squealing girls for the final band,
Third Eye Blind. (Suzanne DeChillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) BETHEL, N.Y. -- Aug. 17, 1998 --
WOODSTOCK-MUSIC-REVIEW-1, 8-17 -- An enthusiastic crowd and sunny
weather are the right ingredients for moshing at ``A Day in the
Garden'' festival in Bethel - the site of the original Woodstock.
The crowd was larger than it was on the festival's first two days;
28,000 tickets were sold, some for as little as $10 each. The music
was louder, male band members took off their shirts, and a mosh pit
roiled for seven hours. (Suzanne DeChillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) ISLEFORD, Maine -- Aug. 17, 1998 -- MAINE-MUSIC, 8-17 --
Kneisel Hall students head for a performance in Isleford. Kneisel
Hall on Tour, as this new program is called, began last summer as a
way of giving performance experience to student artists seeking to
become professional musicians. Equally important, it provides
chamber music concerts to people in outlying Maine communities who
usually do not have access to live performances. (Ed Quinn/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) GLACIER NATIONAL PARK, Mont. -- Aug. 17, 1998 --
SCI-MAN-EATING-BEAR, 8-17 -- The body of 16-year-old female grizzly
bear Chocolate Legs lies in the back of a pickup truck after being
shot by a park ranger in Glacier National Park. Chocolate legs was
the matriarch of a bear family that recently devoured a 26-year-old
hiker in Glacier National Park. Just what it is that causes bears
to go bad - a rare phenomenon among grizzlies, despite their
reputation - eludes scientists. (New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) CHICAGO -- Aug. 17, 1998 -- SCI-CRONIN-COSMIC-RAYS, 8-17
-- Dr. James Cronin of the University of Chicago. At 67, with a
great career as a particle physicist and teacher already behind
him, Cronin has embarked on a new one as a kind of traveling
salesman. He is campaigning in a score of countries for help in
building a pair of gigantic cosmic-ray telescopes expected to
reveal some tantalizing secrets of the universe. (Steve Kagan/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) VALDEZ, Alaska -- Aug. 17, 1998 -- SCI-ALASKA-THAW-3,
8-17 -- In summer, thousands of waterfalls carry increased flows
from melting snow and glaciers. Alaska is thawing, and much of
northern Russia and Canada with it, and many scientists say that
the warming of these cold regions is one of the most telling
signals that the planet's climate is changing. (William K.
Stevens/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) VALDEZ, Alaska -- Aug. 17, 1998 -- SCI-ALASKA-THAW-2,
8-17 -- The permafrost, ground that is perpetually frozen, is
thawing in Alaska's interior, and pockets of underground ice
trapped in the frost are melting with it. Over thousands of miles,
big patches of forest are drowning and turning gray as the ground
sinks under them and swamp water floods them. Roadside utility
poles, destabilized by the melting, tilt at crazy angles. So do
trees, creating a phenomenon known as drunken forest. (William K.
Stevens/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) VALDEZ, Alaska -- Aug. 17, 1998 -- SCI-ALASKA-THAW-1,
8-17 -- Columbia Glacier is not what it used to be. The front of
the glacier, in the foreground, has retreated eight miles in the
last 16 years, and ships are separated from it by melting icebergs.
(William K. Stevens/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Aug. 17, 1998 -- SCI-BLACK-DEATH-RATES, 8-17
-- At Merita's beauty salon in Brooklyn, customers getting their
hair done can watch an American Cancer Society videotape about
breast cancer risks and prevention. Compared with whites, black
Americans have higher death rates from all kinds of serious
illnesses. Black babies are more likely to be born small and die in
their first year, and black adults live fewer years than their
white counterparts. (Barbara Alper/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) ROCKPORT, Maine -- Aug. 17, 1998 -- CHILDREN-NEEDS-BOS,
8-17 -- In a remote corner of the Sea View Cemetery is this jarring
grave. The tombstone reads ``Unknown, Unwanted, Baby Boy. Body
Found In Rockport Quarry, April 20, 1940, Age About Five Mos.'' The
infant was discovered floating in the quarry waters near the town
dump by a passerby. His identity was never discovered and the case
remains unsolved. (Stan Grossfeld/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEEDHAM, Mass. -- -- Aug. 17, 1998 --
AUTHOR-DELINSKY-B&AMP;W-BOS, 8-17 -- Author Barbara Delinsky on the
porch of her home. Ms. Delinsky has written 66 books, with 25
million copies published in two dozen languages. ``I know those
numbers are mind-boggling,'' she says. ``And when I go through an
