<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-VALLEY-HOMES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REALTY IN L.A.'S SAN FERNANDO VALLEY BLISTERING HOT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The real estate market in L.A.'s San Fernando
Valley area matched the summer's torrid heat wave during July with
home sales and prices rising like mercury in a thermometer, a trade
group says.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of single-family homes in the San Fernando Valley jumped
18.5 percent and the median price, the point at which half sold for
more and half for less, jumped 22.2 percent, the Southland
Association of Realtors said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, sales in the Santa Clarita Valley, a much smaller
market, skyrocketed a record 61.3 percent and the median price
jumped 9 percent, the group said.
</P>
<P>
   The hot market shows no signs of cooling in the immediate
future. Pending escrows, an indicator of sales in the pipeline,
increased 15 percent and 44 percent from July '97 in the San
Fernando and Santa Clarita valleys, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing that appears to be holding sales in check is a
tight market.
</P>
<P>
   The number of active listings in the San Fernando Valley fell
7.4 percent last month and plunged 28 percent in the nearby Santa
Clarita Valley compared to a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Nima Nattagh, an analyst at Experian, a real estate market
research firm, said that second-quarter sales in Los Angeles County
rose 21 percent from year-ago levels, indicating that the market
has broad-based strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``This clearly is one of the best housing markets we've had so
far in the 1990s. The market will probably continue at this pace
for another four or five months,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, escrow closed on 1,316 single-family homes in the
San Fernando Valley, an increase of 205 from July 1997 but only one
more than in June. The median price was $204,000, up $37,000 from a
year ago but $4,000 less, a decline of 2 percent, from June's
median.
</P>
<P>
   The local condominium market also gained ground.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, escrow closed on 315 condos, up nearly 7 percent
from July 1997. The median price soared 41.5 percent to $123,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Realtors groups said there is no shortage of buyers but they
are resisting paying more than properties are worth. For example,
owners tacking two, three or more percentage points on top of what
the market suggests are not selling their properties, said Bud
Mauro, president of the San Fernando Valley chapter of the Realtors
group.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that appraisers are ``increasingly'' resistant to
loans being made on property that is overpriced.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally, loans are closing in schedule but Realtors have to
do a lot of explaining and justifying of the price to convince the
appraiser,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
