<HEADLINE>
FOR RUSSIA, OLD PROBLEMS, NEW ERA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even foreign observers who have watched Russia reel from crisis
to crisis since the Soviet collapse in 1991 have acquired the
Russian habit of quoting Marx's famous dictum that history repeats
itself, first as tragedy and then as farce.
</P>
<P>
   But as the Russian ruble plunged Monday to a new nadir, raising
the spectre of economic, political, and social meltdown, both
stalwart humor and a sense that the trauma was just another chapter
in a long crisis were lacking among many observers. This time,
market strategists said, things are different _ both for Russia and
for the global economy in which the former communist giant now
participates.
</P>
<P>
   From tremors in Brazilian debt markets to worries among Hong
Kong traders about a possible devaluation of their own currency,
world markets have shuddered at Moscow's latest turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, officials at the International Monetary Fund are
wondering where they went wrong since agreeing to lend Russia $22.6
billion barely a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, economists rushed to declare Russia the latest victim
of Asia's economic turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Russia's currency shed more than one-third of its value
against the US dollar, as the central bank lowered the band in
which the ruble trades to 9.5 rubles per dollar. The move was in
effect a devaluation, reversing months of defiant statements from
Moscow that such a &UR;  &LR; measure &UR;  &LR; was not needed. While the official
rate rose only slightly to 6.43 rubles per dollar, banks and
exchanges, jammed with panicked Russians, jacked up their rates for
dollars to as high as 9.5 rubles.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has lurched through plenty of scares in the last seven
years, ranging from currency collapses and government reshuffles to
tax collection shortfalls and unsustainably high interest rates.
But it has always had fast sources of assistance and rescue _ the
IMF and the World Bank, German banks, foreigners who buy its
high-yielding Treasury bills, even George Soros, the billionaire
financier-philanthropist, who secretly lent millions to the
government in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Those avenues may now be exhausted _ and a review of Russia's
previous currency crisis yields insights about what the future may
hold for the post-Soviet state.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 11, 1994, a day christened Black Tuesday, the ruble
underwent what was then its steepest one-day decline, plunging more
than 25 percent &UR;  &LR; after the central bank failed to regulate a
liquidity crisis among Russian banks. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   At that time, the world's newest emerging market had almost no
government debt traded on foreign markets. Moscow had not yet
rescheduled tens of billions in Soviet-era debt owed to the world's
governments and banks. And Russia had plenty of leeway to tap
international funding from groups like the IMF.
</P>
<P>
   Shaken but not defeated by Black Tuesday, reformers pushed ahead
with privatization and vowed to undertake major reforms in areas
ranging from tax laws and collection to budget subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has made some progress in recent years _ but in the wake
of its latest crisis, never has it seemed so far from real
stability. ``This time, it is a much broader and much more
significant event,'' said Charles R. Blitzer, head of emerging
market research at Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Since Black Tuesday, the Russian &UR;  &LR; government has become one of
the biggest issuers of debt among emerging nations. &UR;  &LR; In
partnerships now deemed risky, its nascent blue-chip companies
allied with domestic banks and issued billions of dollars in
Eurobonds. Far-flung regions unknown to the world issued their own
debt. Traders laughed off the stock market's double-digit swings,
boasting that the toughest could stomach them and win. For 1996 and
1997, Russian stocks handed investors triple digit dollar gains.
</P>
<P>
   Against a stable currency and government committed to economic
reform, investors grew optimistic about Russia's chances to grow.
Bumps along the way were cushioned by international lenders, mainly
the IMF.
</P>
<P>
   That picture changed Monday. As investors and foreign officials
wrestled with uncertainty over how far the ruble will fall, how
Moscow will restructure banks near default, and whether the crisis
will spark a major government reshuffle and panic in the streets,
Russian officials acknowledged that new loans were at worst
unlikely _ at least in the amounts seen in the past _ and at best
only a temporary fix to deeper problems.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Black Tuesday, Russia has now stepped close to the abyss
of being locked out of foreign markets for years. In declaring
Monday a 90-day moratorium on some payments due to foreign
creditors, Moscow came one step shy of default _ a huge no-no for
any country desiring to borrow abroad in the near future. The move
prompted Standard &AMP; Poor's, the ratings agency, to downgrade
Russia's already noninvestment grade long-term foreign currency
debt to an ugly CCC. Russia's rating is now below that of troubled
Indonesia. For a country with $135 billion in foreign currency
obligations and $60 billion in short-term domestic debt, the blow
is severe.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Russian Eurobonds _ debt issued for
international markets _ plunged 30 percent in trading Monday on
fears their issuers, which include banks, companies, the regions,
and the government, would default.
</P>
<P>
   When the IMF granted Moscow its latest aid package on July 17,
most countries' emerging debt traded at around 575 basis points, or
5.75 percentage points, over US Treasuries. Monday the figure had
risen to nearly 1,000 &UR;  &LR; basis points. Long-term bonds for Brazil,
Argentina, Bulgaria, and Ecuador all fell Monday, victims of
Russia's woes.
</P>
<P>
   For emerging market economies like Brazil, the ruble devaluation
may ultimately result in higher borrowing costs and bigger current
account deficits.
</P>
<P>
   There are other possible knock-on effects that could not have
happened after Black Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong and Venezuela, with troubled currencies, could face
their own devaluations in the wake of the ruble's fall _ especially
if traders question the wisdom of spending billions to prop up
ailing currencies, as Russia did in previous weeks. And Central and
East European countries with exports to and investments in Russia
could find their balance sheets ruffled.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the IMF, which performed an about-face Monday in
switching to muted support for the ruble's devaluation, came under
renewed criticism for having insisted Russia adhere to austerity
measures in the wake of a recession. Just as it failed to see
Asia's crisis coming, so it would appear that the IMF failed to see
Russia's dire straits.
</P>
<P>
   The ruble devaluation is also an about face for Russia. A stable
currency had been a showpiece of the Russian economy in recent
years, trumpeted by President Boris N. Yeltsin and US officials as
evidence that Moscow was finally getting its act together. Having
gotten hyperinflation earlier this decade under control, privatized
many crown-jewel industrial assets, created nascent stock and bond
markets, and attracted a few foreign investors, Russia seemed
headed on the right path.
</P>
<P>
   Many economists now deem that progress a chimera.
</P>
<P>
   As during Black Tuesday, there are widespread fears that a
free-falling ruble will spark inflation, social unrest, and
political instability. From the need to restructure bankrupt and
inefficient enterprises to reigning in government spending, the
problems of years past remain.
</P>
<P>
   But this time, the solutions that materialize will likely
reflect Russia's new linkage to the world economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problems in Russia are not unlike the problems Mexico
had,'' Mariscal said. ``It will require a global, orchestrated
solution.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
