<SLUG> BC-YUGO-WARCRIMES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYER FOR DEAD SERB DEMANDS PAYMENT FOR HIS FAMILY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)  (af)  
 By MARLISE SIMONS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ A Bosnian Serb who died this month in a cell while being
tried by the U.N. war crimes tribunal in The Hague, the
Netherlands, bled to death because he did not get proper medical
care, his lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer, Dusan Vucicevic, said the tribunal was guilty of
negligence and of causing the ``wrongful death'' of his client. He
said he would demand that it pay damages to his client's family in
Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   His client, Milan Kovacevic, a former politician and medical
doctor in Prijedor, Bosnia, died on Aug. 1 at age 57 from what the
tribunal called a heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   Vucicevic is a Serbian-American who practices law in Chicago and
is also a physician who attended his client's autopsy. In a
telephone interview from his office, he contended that Kovacevic
had not died of a heart attack but had bled to death because of
errors by the prison staff.
</P>
<P>
   He said other inmates had reported that in the crucial hours
before Kovacevic died, the prison guards had initially ignored his
cries of pain and the calls of other prisoners who had been
awakened and alarmed by his screams.
</P>
<P>
   When the prison doctor arrived an hour later, the lawyer
contends, the doctor misdiagnosed Kovacevic's crisis as a kidney
problem and gave him a painkiller instead of rushing him to the
nearby hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer said the autopsy had shown that Kovacevic had not
died of a heart attack but of a ruptured major blood vessel in his
abdomen, which could have been repaired surgically.
</P>
<P>
   The autopsy report has not yet been released, and the tribunal's
press office has declined to answer further questions, saying it
must await the outcome of an internal investigation. The prison
authorities have also declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   The tribunal prison just outside The Hague is a separate cell
block on the grounds of a Dutch jail, but it is run by a warden and
guards who are appointed by the United Nations. The Dutch jail
provides basic services, like meals and medical care.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden death of Kovacevic came as a shock to the tribunal.
Although he suffered from high blood pressure and had earlier had a
stroke and a heart attack, the cardiologist and psychiatrists who
had treated him had deemed him well enough to stand trial.
</P>
<P>
   He had been arrested by NATO troops, and his high-profile case
was important to the tribunal. As its first trial involving charges
of genocide in Bosnia, the case was expected to set important
precedents.
</P>
<P>
   The trial opened on July 6. Among other charges, Kovacevic was
accused of complicity in genocide because of his role in 1992 in
helping to organize detention camps near Prijedor, Bosnia, in which
numerous Bosnian Muslim inmates were tortured and killed.
</P>
<P>
   But with his death the case has been closed. On Aug. 1, about
six hours after Kovacevic died, the tribunal spokesman, Christian
Chartier, said he had died of a ``massive heart attack.'' The death
certificate, dated Aug. 1, says only that Kovacevic died of natural
causes.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer said it was unforgivable that the patient had not
been sent immediately to the nearby hospital. In February the
hospital had found that Kovacevic had an aneurysm, or widening, of
a major blood vessel. ``That aneurysm was never treated,'' the
lawyer said. ``It was like a time bomb ticking in his body. We
repeatedly asked for treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   The autopsy on Aug. 4 showed that it was that blood vessel, the
aorta, that ruptured and caused an abdominal hemorrhage, the lawyer
said.
</P>
<P>
   Chartier has denied that the tribunal has been lax in its care
of Kovacevic or any of its other 26 detainees, many of whom have
physical and mental health problems.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
