<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-17 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8239 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-HOMER-MATCHUP-NYT     08-17 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-HOMER-MATCHUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOMERUN HITTERS MCGWIRE AND SOSA FACEOFF IN 2-GAME SERIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (af)  
 By IRA BERKOW   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Standing in a formidable line at the ticket window
outside Wrigley Field Monday morning was Tim Foil, a Chicago sales
representative, who was under as much pressure in his way as Mark
McGwire and Sammy Sosa have been in theirs.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire and Sosa, as a large segment of the American population
is aware, are neck-and-neck in pursuit of Roger Maris' home run
record, with 47 each. And now they will go head-to-head as their
teams, the St. Louis Cardinals and the Chicago Cubs, meet in a
two-game series starting Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Foil was hoping to get some of the last tickets for what was
certainly going to be a sold-out series. ``This series is huge,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not only are McGwire and Sosa going after a record, but the Cubs
are also in contention for the playoffs _ imagine, it's August and
they have not folded _ and they have a long tradition of battling
the Cardinals, their virtual Western neighbors, in a rivalry akin
to that of the Yankees and the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``My brother is flying in from Boston to see it,'' Foil said.
``I have to get him tickets _ or I may have to pay his plane
fare.''
</P>
<P>
   Foil smiled wanly. ``But there is an upside if I don't get him
tickets,'' he said. ``Maybe he'd stay home.''
</P>
<P>
   Also in line was Jim Berman of suburban Winnetka, Ill., who
identified himself as a stay-at-home dad. He was seeking three
tickets for Tuesday's game, for him and his 9-year-old son and
6-year-old daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there something particularly exciting?'' he said. ``Tell me
about it. I'm not much of a baseball fan. I take my kids to one
game a year. I just picked this one more or less out of a hat.''
</P>
<P>
   Berman was told about McGwire and Sosa. ``Don't they have
something like 65 homers apiece?'' No, he was told, just 47. But
both are on pace to at least match Maris' mark of 61, which has
withstood challenges for 36 years.
</P>
<P>
   Inside Wrigley Field, Frank Maloney, director of ticket
operations, said that yes, there was something special about this
series as far as sales were concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to sell out _ and that means we're going to sell
all 38,000-plus seats as well our 2,000 standing-room-only tickets
_ and for two weekday games,'' he said. ``That's highly unusual.
And most of the tickets have been sold for about two months in
advance.''
</P>
<P>
   Maloney said he had received telephone calls from angry fans who
reported that scalpers were selling $12 bleachers seats for $85 and
$21 box seats for $150. Cubs tickets generally sell well, but Sosa
has certainly heightened the intrigue.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa has been edging up on McGwire ever since he hit 20 homers
in June. On Aug. 10 in San Francisco, Sosa hit his 45th and 46th
homers to tie McGwire for the first time. McGwire hit his 47th the
next night against the Mets, and then Sosa tied him again on Sunday
in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   While McGwire comes in as a red-headed Paul Bunyan, Sosa is a
late-comer to national fame _ and local adoration. He was traded
from the White Sox to the Cubs in 1992, and until this year he was
often regarded as a great but undisciplined talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``And a selfish player,'' Barry Holt, a Chicago lawyer, had said
the night before. ``He'd swing at bad pitches and rarely hit the
cut-off man on throws from right field, and he'd steal bases in
blowouts just to pad his statistics. But he's a changed man this
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Holt wondered if Michael Jordan might have had some effect on
Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sosa saw how Jordan was respected as a professional,'' Holt
said, ``and then there was that invitation from the president of
the Dominican Republic. He asked Sammy, who is from the Dominican,
to ask Jordan if he'd visit that country. And he did. Jordan said
he'd try to make it. Sammy talked about the respect that Jordan
commanded.''
</P>
<P>
   Beth Murphy, the proprietor of Murphy's Bleachers, a tavern at
the corner of Sheffield and Waveland Avenues, across from the
Wrigley Field bleachers, said she liked Sosa's smile and
good-natured attitude. She was also looking forward to a lot of
people showing up in her bar wearing Cardinals red.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get a lot of Cardinal fans in here _ St. Louis is about 400
miles south, only about a five-and-a-half-hour car ride,'' she
said. ``It's a rivalry that's been going on for years.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the Cardinals of Hornsby and Frisch and Grover
Cleveland Alexander and the Cubs of Grimm and Hartnett and Riggs
Stephenson battled for National League pennants in the 1920s and
30s.
</P>
<P>
   ``They come up here, and we go down there,'' Murphy said. ``And
Cardinal fans are friendlier than Mets fans. I don't know. Maybe
it's just us. Because we haven't forgiven them for 1969.'' That was
the year the Cubs appeared to be headed for post-season play for
the first time since the 1945 World Series _ until the Mets
dramatically overtook them.
</P>
<P>
   Maloney, the director of ticket operations, said that when the
Cubs play in St. Louis, it sometimes looks as if half of the fans
in Busch Stadium are wearing Cubs blue. And when the Cardinals
visit Chicago, half of the fans in Wrigley are wearing red.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Jim Frey was the manager of the Cubs in the 1980s,''
Maloney said, ``he complained that I sold too many tickets to
Cardinal fans. I told him, `Jim, how do I know someone's a Cardinal
fan when I sell a ticket?'''
</P>
<P>
   When Foil got to the ticket window, he was told that there were
only a handful of single tickets left for the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' he said, ``I guess I'll sit in left field and my
brother will sit in right field.'' It didn't seem like such a
terrible idea to him. But Berman, not a fan, did not want to sit
apart from his children.
</P>
<P>
   He asked the ticket seller, ``Is there a game on Thursday?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
