<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ARKANSAS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Where there's Hope, there's strong support for Clinton
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOPE, Ark. _ A place called Hope is still full of just that, and
residents of the Arkansas town where President Clinton was born are
hoping their hometown boy will survive the most challenging moment
of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not Clinton had an ``innapropriate relationship''
with White House intern Monica Lewinsky and whether or not he lied
under oath, Hope residents say Clinton should stay in office and
finish what has been, they say, a stellar presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody could have done as good as he has,''
said Gary Johnson, who runs the Hope Visitor Center, a sort of
shrine to Clinton. ``He doesn't have to stand for that criticism.
He could have come home a long time ago.''
</P>
<P>
   But indications that Clinton would admit that the relationship
was not pure were a disappointment, Johnson admits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It bothers me, but it's politics. That doesn't make it right,
but President Clinton has done a better job than anyone else would
have done in his shoes. I don't think the public is going to have a
lynch mob waiting for him tomorrow morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Residents of Hope aren't even all that focused on Clinton's
historic testimony before a grand jury. They're relaxing after a
blockbuster watermelon festival that attracted 50,000 folks to
town. And the local paper, the Hope Star, ran the story of Clinton
testifying on page 2 of Monday's paper. The watermelon festival got
the front page, accompanied by a picture of Gov. Mike Huckabee
playing the guitar.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think every president has had affairs,'' said Rebecca Jones,
21. ``If you have that much power, you think you can do anything.
But I don't think it's affected what he's doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Autry Hatfield, who was taking a smoke break outside Wal-Mart,
said telling the truth is the right thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I hope it works out and he continues to be president,''
said Hatfield, 61, who was born and raised in Hope. ``I wish it
hadn't happened, but I still think Ken Starr was out to get him.
And I wouldn't be surprised if he doesn't get him for this, then
he'll try to get him for something else, like campaign financing.''
</P>
<P>
   Demonizing Starr, the special prosecutor who has been
investigating Clinton for years, is a favorite activity here.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's who they should get _ Starr,'' said Luther Lee Scoggin,
who was mowing lawns down the street from one of Clinton's boyhood
homes. ``I don't think Clinton did it. Even if he says he did, I
don't think he did. I think he is just trying to get past this.''
</P>
<P>
   There's a bumper sticker some Hope cars sport that says, ``Pray
for those who hate our president.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton does have his detractors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a disgrace,'' said the Rev. Billy Porter.
``Here's a guy we trusted to lead the country, and he talks about
family values _ it just looks bad. It ain't right.''
</P>
<P>
   And although Porter says an admission helps him forgive Clinton,
his feelings about him won't be the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't trust him now,'' he said. ``I could overlook who he
goes to bed with, but if he'll lie about this, he'll lie about
something else.''
</P>
<P>
   No one seems to think this will end his presidency though.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's in trouble, but he'll wiggle out of it,'' Porter said.
``He always does.''
</P>
<P>
   Anne Rochell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
