<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-INTERNET-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    News Web sites spin network of information on testimony
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The frenzied Internet search for information about President
Clinton's testimony began hours before Clinton's afternoon
testimony. Web sites for major news organizations were stretched to
the breaking point while online-only publications began posting
exclusive information early in the day.
</P>
<P>
   In the early morning, Matt Drudge, the one-man publishing
machine behind the Drudge Report (http://www.drudgereport.com),
took to the Web with allegations independent counsel Kenneth Starr
planned to play some of the Monica Lewinsky/Linda Tripp tape
recordings ``to provoke a reaction.'' Although critics say Drudge
is hardly a bona fide journalist, he was the sole source of news
early in the day for a public hungry for any scraps of information.
Drudge's Web site was frequently busy and difficult to access.
</P>
<P>
   It was Drudge who broke the news that the online magazine Salon
(http://www.salonmagazine.com) had an exclusive on Clinton's
testimony. Once word spread, Web traffic at Salon came to an
instant standstill.
</P>
<P>
   Until the story was posted mid-afternoon, a simple message
across the top read ``Stay tuned for exclusive report on the
president's testimony.'' The article appeared around 3 p.m., with a
Washington dateline and no byline except a tag at the end noting
the contributions of Salon's Little Rock correspondent Murray Waas,
who was given a byline later in the day. The story largely revolves
around first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton's role in helping prepare
her husband's testimony. Waas writes that Hillary Clinton helped
orchestrate a defense that combined an admission of ``inappropriate
relations'' with Lewinsky, followed by an aggressive assault on
Starr's investigation as ``a political assault on his presidency
masked as a legal inquiry.'' Waas' story also delves into the
Clintons' complex marriage.
</P>
<P>
   While Salon delved into the back-room strategies of Clinton's
testimony, the traditional news organizations focused on facts and
whether Clinton would address the nation following his testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, only MSNBC (http://www.msnbc.com) and Fox News
(http://www.foxnews.com) were reporting that Clinton would make an
address on television.
</P>
<P>
   Despite daylong server problems attributed to heavy traffic and
a busy start page that made access difficult, if not impossible, at
times, MSNBC was still reporting that a speech to the nation was a
``virtual certainty,'' according to an unnamed White House source.
Fox News was one of the few news sites to attribute its quotes
including a telling comment from spokesman Mike McCurry during a
White House briefing saying, ``I think the president needs to talk
to the American people, but that may happen soon enough.''
</P>
<P>
   CNN Interactive (http://www.cnn.com) prepared for the onslaught
by stripping down its start page to bare bones text and one picture
allowing more users to access the page and access it quicker. CNN
chose not to run the news of the speech until after the official
announcement was made. Immediately after that, CNN posted a story
quoting unnamed sources saying Clinton would speak from the same
room in the White House in which he testified and would admit to
his relationship with Lewinsky and apologize.
</P>
<P>
   CNN spokesman Kerrin Roberts said CNN predicts the site will
surpass its previous daily record of 15.5 million page hits.
</P>
<P>
   Once Clinton completed his testimony, all the major news
organizations posted Web stories quoting unnamed White House
sources detailing the testimony and the mood in the White House as
well as what Clinton might say in his speech. Major newspapers were
posting an Associated Press story allegedly detailing the early
drafts of the speech.
</P>
<P>
   Frances Katz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
