<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-17 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8244 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-SCHOUREK-B     08-17 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-SCHOUREK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOUREK IN THE ROTATION; SO IS AVERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The guillotine blade that has been hanging over the Red
Sox rotation since Pete Schourek arrived dropped Monday afternoon,
and perhaps to his surprise, Steve Avery's neck remained intact.
</P>
<P>
   Schourek, the lefthander acquired on waivers from Houston 12
days ago, is scheduled to make his first start for the Red Sox
Thursday afternoon in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   But Schourek didn't bump Avery from the rotation. John Wasdin is
returning to the bullpen, though Monday's rainout against the Texas
Rangers, which was rescheduled Tuesday day as part of a
split-admission doubleheader (1:05 p.m., 6:05 p.m.) means he'll
draw another start Saturday in Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox manager Jimy Williams doesn't want to bring back either
of Yirdfsu day's starters, Pedro Martinez (Game 1) or Bret
Saberhagen (Game 2) on short rest, so for this week Wasdin will be
the sixth man in a six-man rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a demotion,'' Williams said diplomatically. ``It's a
better utilization of the staff.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Red Sox using at least three relievers a night in a
stretch of seven games until Sunday, when they needed just two
calls to the bullpen, Wasdin is in a better position to lighten the
load on the relievers than Schourek, who made two relief
appearances last week but requires special treatment because of his
history of elbow problems.
</P>
<P>
   And Avery already has proven he is of little use out of the pen,
with a 9.53 ERA in 10 appearances earlier this season. Wasdin
became the choice by process of elimination.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Schourek) made two good relief stints, but are we pushing it
too much?,'' said Williams. ``Maybe that's not the best way to
handle him.''
</P>
<P>
   Schourek has pitched exclusively as a starter the last four
seasons for the Reds and Astros. He was an 18-game winner for the
Reds in 1995 before his elbow gave out, and he isn't assuming
there's anything permanent about his place in the Boston rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a start,'' he said. ``Obviously, I'm going to have to
perform.''
</P>
<P>
   Schourek was the fifth man in Houston's rotation, and odd man
out when the Astros traded for Randy Johnson. He was 7-6 with a
4.50 ERA for the Astros, and one of his best starts came June 5
against the Royals, when he allowed just two hits in seven innings
and struck out a season-high eight in a 1-0 loss to Tim Belcher.
</P>
<P>
   There shouldn't be added pressure making his first start for the
Sox, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe if it were my first appearance, but I've had two out of
the pen, so I've gotten my feet wet, so to speak,'' Schourek said.
``I've got to concentrate on what I'm doing on the mound, not who
I'm doing it for. If I take care of my job, everything should be
all right.''
</P>
<P>
   Wasdin, who complained bitterly when he was demoted to Pawtucket
in June, then handled a second demotion with equanimity in July,
chose the high road again Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it's to the point where I want to start, yeah, but I want
to win more,'' said Wasdin, who was 1-2 with a 6.16 ERA in six
starts but had allowed three runs or fewer in four of the five
starts he made since rejoining the rotation last month, when Korean
Jin Ho Cho was demoted.
</P>
<P>
   Avery, meanwhile, in the aftermath of his three-inning meltdown
Sunday, talked about how he expects to be pitching elsewhere next
season. There is little chance, he said, of the club picking up his
$3.9 million option for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he felt like he were on trial every time he pitches, he
said, ``Yeah. It doesn't affect me performance-wise, but in between
starts, you come in here and wonder if you'll get another one.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't a knock at my friends and other players, but you
look at Wasdin, and he's on more solid ground than I am. (Schourek)
came over, and it was, `When's Avery coming out of the rotation?
That's frustrating. The questions aren't there when I make two good
starts, but make a bad one, and it's time to get rid of this guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Avery acknowledged there's pressure that comes ``from looking
over your shoulder.'' That had nothing to do with his nine-hit,
three-walk, six-run outing Sunday against the Twins, he said, but
it has made his tenure here more uncomfortable than it already was.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since my (groin) injury last year, it's kind of been, `What
have you done for me lately?''' Avery said. ``Not so much from Joe
(Kerrigan) and Jimy, but from you guys (reporters), the fans. All
of a sudden everything changes. It's like a report card once every
five days, instead of once every month or two.''
</P>
<P>
   As much fun as it has been to win here this season, Avery said,
he expects that he'll be better off elsewhere next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I've ever been a real good fit here for some
people,'' he said, ``and that's probably not going to change much
before the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans, you guys, Dan (Duquette), I understand. I haven't
pitched as well, so stuff like that happens, I guess. I don't think
my option will be picked up. That's not a big deal to me. I'll sign
somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may have to try and go someplace and work things out without
worrying about the same stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Avery, who never has had arm trouble but is not the same pitcher
he was in his early years with Atlanta, still hasn't accepted that
he has to become a finesse pitcher in the Frank Tanana mode, the
way Kerrigan has counseled him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I want to throw this way the rest of my
career,'' he said. ``I've had some success doing it. But I don't
think it's the style I want to keep up. If the changeup's not
there, or my location, I can't afford any mistakes. I've got to be
perfect with every pitch. It's hard to pitch that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Told later that he was still in the rotation and Wasdin had been
bumped, Avery shrugged and said, ``I guess I don't pay attention to
that stuff. I'll just worry about when I'll pitch.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
