<HEADLINE>
? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ?????  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; EUROPE'S IDEA IS NOT SUPER
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Last year, Kaiserslautern became the first German club to win
the Bundes-H liga in its first year of promotion. This was a
remarkable accomplish- ment, since most newly promoted teams
require at least a year to establish themselves against the
country's best compe- tition.
</P>
<P>
   The coach, Otto Rehhagel, had been dis- missed from Bayern
Munich after what man- agement considered a disappointing second-
place finish in 1996. Rehhagel guided Kaisers- lautern to promotion
in 1997, then won the Bundesliga.
</P>
<P>
   The second-place team in the Bundesliga in 1997-98? Once again,
Bayern Munich.
</P>
<P>
   Underdog-makes-good is a universal story line not only in soccer
but in all sport, and is especially compelling in the context of
the club system used by nearly every country. Even if the club
system has been adapted to differing cultures and financial
philosophies, it always retains the basic sporting traits of
promotion/-relegation and usually respects the integrity of all
clubs, regardless of size.
</P>
<P>
   In the US, professional sport is controlled by a small number of
rich owners, who dole out franchises for profit. In most other
coun- tries, there is just the opposite scenario. Each and every
village has the right to enter the national competition in any
sport, with L promotion/-relegation determining who is in the top
divisions. This precept short-circuits franchising efforts and
allows sport to operate as a meritocracy and to retain its soul.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, Europe's biggest clubs are threatening to form a
Super League, which would exclude not only the Kaiserslauterns but
dozens of other formidable teams. Oppo- nents of the project fear
that the medium-H sized and small clubs will deteriorate, player
development will be ignored, teams' identities will suffer, and
national team competitions will be marginalized. Proponents of the
Super League say that such a league is an inevitabil- ity, and
since they control digital television in Europe, they should be the
ones to profit.
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to brand TV moguls Silvio Ber-H lusconi, Leo Kirch,
and Rupert Murdoch as the patronizing villains. Berlusconi's AC
Mi-H lan has twice been relegated in Italy's Serie A in recent
years, and finished in ninth and 10th place the last two years, yet
Milan would be among the 16 teams in the Super League. Bayern
Munich and Borussia Dortmund L  &UR; -------------------- &LR;  would
represent Germany, leaving champion Kaiserslautern out. There are
dozens of other examples of worthy teams being jilted.
</P>
<P>
   The Super League presumes that such a project is needed. This
ignores the Champi- ons Cup, which has been modified into a
Champions League, and which will be further modified to satisfy the
elite ``breakaway'' clubs.
</P>
<P>
   If the sporting elements _ meritocracy, promotion/-relegation _
are removed from the equation, soccer will no longer exist as we
know it. The sport's value might actually be increased by the huge
television revenues that are being proposed, but this will be an
artificial boost.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiserslautern president Herbert Kessler made a formal protest
regarding the pro- posed Super League last week. Fortunately, the
bullying policies of Berlusconi and Co. are being resisted.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HDsub1,s5,14 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Who's the future king?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; xr &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Michael Owen  &LR; got Liverpool off to a fast Premier League start
by setting up  &UR; Karl- &LR; H  &UR; Heinz Reidle  &LR; and scoring the game-winner
in a 2-1 victory Sunday at Southampton.
</P>
<P>
   But though Owen was crowned the future king of soccer during the
World Cup, Inter defender  &UR; Francesco Colonnese  &LR; believes he is
overrated, especially compared with Inter's 19-year-old midfielder,
 &UR; Andrea Pirlo &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   ``If Owen is worth 100 billion lire, Pirlo is worth 200 billion,
that's for certain,'' Colon-H nese said after facing Owen in an
exhibition recently. ``There is really no comparison be-
 &UR; -------------------- &LR;  tween the two. I realized quickly that he
wouldn't trouble me technically because he can only go one way. He
is very fast but not strong. This kid is certainly destined to im-
prove, but he doesn't seem to me to be top- class.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Pirlo and  &UR; Nicola Ventola &LR; , &UR;  &LR; 20, will be battling to
find starting positions with Inter, raising questions about the
develop- ment of young Italian players. The top teams are not only
stockpiling young talent, but they also are signing more top
foreigners than ever. Teams will be obliged to justify their
investment in outside talent, leaving the L youngsters on the
bench.
</P>
<P>
   If a Super League is formed, young do- mestic players will be
further ignored.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HDsub1,s5,14 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   United takes stand
</P>
<P>
   D.C. United will likely meet Brazil's Vasco da Gama for the
InterAmerican Cup cham-H pionship. United won the CONCACAF L
Champions Cup tournament, defeating To-H luca of Mexico, 1-0, on
 &UR; Eddie Pope's  &LR; 41st-min-H ute goal Sunday at RFK Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Vasco da Gama will be protecting a 2-0 lead in the return leg of
the Copa Liberta-H dores final against Barcelona in Guayaquil Aug.
26.
</P>
<P>
   United's victories over Leon and Toluca in the tournament should
help develop a rivalry between the United States and Mexico, which
the Mexicans believe will aid the progress of both countries.
</P>
<P>
   The win also could clinch the US national team coaching position
for United's  &UR; Bruce  &LR;   &UR; Arena &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who has little more to prove in
D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever takes over the US team will not have it easy. Arena
realizes he will have to revamp the squad. Hopefully for him, he
can find someone with half the talent of  &UR; Marco  &LR;   &UR; Antonio
Etcheverry  &LR; to lead the way.
</P>
