<DOCNO> NYT19980817.0426 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-17 21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8251 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BANK-STOCKS-MARKETPLA     08-17 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANK-STOCKS-MARKETPLACE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW THE MIGHTY HAVE FALLEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bank stocks, among the sizzlers in the stock market's bull run
of the last few years, have been battered in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The villains are varied _ financial turmoil abroad, concern
about how easily some banks will deliver on the promises of their
mega-mergers, escalating worries from regulators about bad loans
both here and abroad. The extent of the drubbing is sobering.
</P>
<P>
   Since mid-July, bank stocks have fallen twice as much as the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index. The S&AMP;P money-center banks
index, representing the country's largest international banks, has
plunged 15.3 percent since July 15. Its counterpart, the S&AMP;P index
of major regional banks, has sunk 14.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The downturn has far outpaced the 7.8 percent drop in the broad
stock market and exceeds the weakness among other financial
services companies sensitive to market sentiment, namely investment
banks and brokerage firms.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts are of many minds about the outlook for banking stocks,
with some sounding alarms and others remaining cautiously
optimistic. But investors' opinions have been more unified. They
have punted their bank holdings over the last month.
</P>
<P>
   To wit, a brief stroll through the wreckage:
</P>
<P>
   Suntrust Banks, down 23 percent; Banc One, down 22 percent;
First Chicago, down 21 percent; BankBoston, down 21 percent; First
Union, down 19 percent; Citicorp, down 17.5 percent; Bankers Trust,
down 16.3 percent; American Express, down 16 percent; Nationsbank,
down 15 percent; BankAmerica, down 15 percent; Norwest, down 15
percent; Wells Fargo, down 14.3 percent, and Chase Manhattan, down
11.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Bank stocks posted a solid rebound Monday. And the fact that the
bottom has fallen out of some bank stocks with such unforgiving
rapidity may be just another sign that investors are too quick to
flee stocks in an uncertain market.
</P>
<P>
   Some stock analysts suggest that the sell-off in bank stocks has
been overdone because of inflated fears about a possible downturn
in the American economy and further spillover from the Asian
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think all of these companies have been oversold unless you
believe the U.S. is going into a recession on the heels of problems
in emerging markets,'' said Diane Glossman, a stock analyst with
Lehman Brothers Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Dickson, a stock analyst with Salomon Smith Barney, sided
with Ms. Glossman. He noted that the stock price of any bank he
covers with a market capitalization of more than $2 billion has
doubled since the end of 1994. That performance was due, he said,
to a historic reversal in the way that banks do business.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1967 and 1992, banks did not earn high enough returns to
justify their borrowing costs, Dickson said, culminating in the
commercial real estate debacle of the late 1980s. Since 1992, banks
have been earning far more than their borrowing costs, leading to a
run-up in stock prices _ a trend he said would continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The recent decline in bank stocks appears due to the belief
that the banking industry will destroy value,'' he observed in a
research report issued last week. ``However, we expect the group to
continue to create value as the banks are well positioned to
continue to perform at or above the strong operating levels
witnessed in the first half of 1998.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all bank stock analysts are as sanguine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe investors are starting to realize that these stocks are
still cyclical,'' said Charles Peabody, an analyst with Mitchell
Securities in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Banks historically earned money off the spread between what they
paid for money and the rate they charged customers for that money.
But in recent years, they have concentrated on fees earned for
various services.
</P>
<P>
   ``People tended to believe that as banks replaced spread income
with fee income, a new era in bank earnings had arrived,'' Peabody
said. ``Now people are starting to see that there are some credit
risks associated with fee income _ for example, from activities
like trading.''
</P>
<P>
   Banks with exposure to the tattered economies of Southeast Asia
and other emerging markets in Latin America and Eastern Europe were
among the first to scare off investors this year. Their ranks
include Chase, Citicorp, J.P. Morgan, BankAmerica, Bankers Trust
and BankBoston.
</P>
<P>
   Now investors are focusing on economic woes overseas that may
wash ashore here, and stocks of other American banks are being
savaged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Asia could continue to put sustained deflationary
pressures on industrial economies like the U.S. and that will have
an impact on the credit quality at banks,'' said Judah Kraushaar, a
Merrill Lynch stock analyst. ``People are starting to ask what
happens if market-sensitive earnings come under increasing
pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Another drag on bank stocks has been fears about how sound some
of the multibillion-dollar mergers will prove to be. Analysts and
bank advisers said that the financial merits of Nationsbank's
merger with BankAmerica and Travelers Group's merger with Citicorp
are not in question as much in three other big deals: Banc One's
acquisition of First Chicago, Norwest's acquisition of Wells Fargo,
and Suntrust's acquisition of Crestar Financial.
</P>
<P>
   There are doubts that Banc One can achieve the cost savings
described as an important part of its merger. Norwest's purchase is
fraught with doubts about how compatible it is with Wells.
</P>
<P>
   And Suntrust is seen as possibly overpaying, offering stock
valued at more than $9 billion at the time the deal was announced.
If the unease about any of these deals proves to be well founded,
profits will suffer.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, many investors have already fled or are
hovering around the exits. Stay tuned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
