<SLUG> BC-STATES-MOOD-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        CLINTON TESTIMONY BRINGS OUT THE FRINGE ELEMENT
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Paul Kane  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Aug. 17 -- While President Clinton was inside
describing his relationship with Monica Lewinsky Monday afternoon,
the scene outside the White House took on an almost anticlimactic
atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   With hundreds of reporters and camera crews huddled beneath
their colored umbrellas inside the compound, waiting for word of
what Clinton had said, outside the gates stood a normal smattering
of tourists, passersby and protesters.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, some of the most bizarre acts appeared to have nothing
to do with the Lewinsky scandal. One young man stabbed himself with
a screwdriver on the sidewalk just north of the White House after
screaming something about the Persian Gulf, the Associated Press
reported. The man, who was taken away in an ambulance, was believed
to be in stable condition.
</P>
<P>
   Across the street in Lafayette Park, a handful of anti-nuclear
protesters assembled to push their cause, just as they have since
the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   And on the sidewalk in front of the White House, several Clinton
supporters and opponents carried signs and hawked somewhat unsavory
T-shirts outlining their position on the seven-month-long scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe there aren't more people out here,''
complained a 20-something law school student from Fairfax, Va.,
just outside Washington.
</P>
<P>
   At $15 apiece, he was selling T-shirts bearing fake quotes from
Clinton, first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton and Lewinsky --
suggestive of the oral sex allegations surrounding the affair.
</P>
<P>
   He claimed to have sold about 20 shirts in his first half hour
outside the White House, beginning around 3 p.m., two hours after
Clinton had begun his testimony.
</P>
<P>
   But another protester took exception with the way Independent
Counsel Kenneth Starr has handled the investigation. With two
wooden signs strapped over his shoulders, one in front of him, one
behind, he compared Starr's tactics to ``McCarthyism'' and said the
entire scandal was driven by Paula Corbin Jones' ``piggy bank.''
</P>
<P>
   Four more protesters huddled underneath a few branches as a
driving rain began to fall just after 4 p.m., forcing them to fold
up their cardboard placard hailing the day as: ``The patriot vs.
the Perjurer'' (Starr vs. Clinton).
</P>
<P>
   Inside the gates, the press remained huddled under their
umbrellas. Outside, most of the crowd left for cover from the rain,
leaving the bemused law school student still wondering why there
wasn't more commotion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
