<HEADER>
A8255 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FPL-COX     08-17 0510
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FPL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Some gas customers online again after fire hits pipeline
 &HT;    By Michael Utley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Utility company workers restored about
half the natural gas flow into South Florida on Monday, following a
lightning-sparked fire that crippled a 1,400-mile pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the Florida Gas Transmission Co., which owns and
operates the line, said they expect to have 80 percent to 90
percent of the gas flow restored by Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's working now, and that's good news,'' said Bill Swank, a
spokesman for Florida Power &AMP; Light Co., the state's largest
utility and a major customer of the pipeline. ``We believe we have
sufficient energy to meet the demands ... throughout the week.''
</P>
<P>
   At the height of the fire-induced gas shortage on Saturday and
Sunday, FPL lost about 10 percent of its generating capacity. Eight
of FPL's 15 electric plants use generators that run on natural gas.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday afternoon, a lightning bolt sparked a fire near a gas
compression station in Perry, about 50 miles southeast of
Tallahassee. The spectacular fire ruptured the pipeline, destroyed
six homes and injured four firefighters.
</P>
<P>
   The disaster cut off all natural gas shipments to Central and
South Florida, prompting FPL to urge its 3.6 million customers to
conserve energy until the pipeline is fixed. FPL, a subsidiary of
Juno Beach-based FPL Group Inc., repeated that request Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are asking our customers to continue their conservation
efforts through mid-week,'' said Swank. This is the first time FPL
has made such a request since February 1996, when South Florida was
in the grip of an unusual cold spell.
</P>
<P>
   The utility asks that customers reduce their electricity use by
raising thermostat settings, shutting off electric water heaters,
closing curtains and blinds, and turning off nonessential lighting
and electrical appliances. Business also are asked to cut back.
</P>
<P>
   FPL idled eight generating units after losing its natural gas
supply. The company met demand by converting some gas-fueled
generators to burn oil, relying on coal-fired and nuclear power
plants, and buying power from other utilities. It doesn't expect
the supply problem to hurt third-quarter earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, workers for Florida Gas Transmission continued Monday
to build bypass lines around the ruptured pipeline. The natural gas
line runs long the Gulf of Mexico, from Corpus Christi to Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made significant progress over the weekend,'' said Elaine
Thomas, a spokeswoman for Houston-based Enron Corp., which jointly
owns Florida Gas Transmission with Sonat Inc. of Birmingham, Ala.
``We've got about 50 percent of the volume flowing back to Florida
now.''
</P>
<P>
   The 30-inch pipeline can move about 1.5 billion cubic feet of
compressed gas each day.
</P>
<P>
   Post wire services contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Utley writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
