A8256 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-LIFETIME-SFCHRON &LR;      08-17 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-LIFETIME-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE PREMIERES WITH PROMISE ON LIFETIME 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1998, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cable is basking in its own little season before the autumn guns
start booming for the big broadcast networks.
</P>
<P>
   Showtime coughed up a couple of comedies, ``Linc's'' and ``Rude
Awakening,'' last month. HBO carried Jerry Seinfeld's stage act and
has a movie curiosity, ``The Rat Pack,'' on Saturday. The Family
Channel just became the Fox Family Channel, with a fusillade of
original shows.
</P>
<P>
   FX found a spicy variety series in ``Penn and Teller's Sin City
Spectacular.'' Ready or not, Comedy Central has a fresh batch of
``South Park'' episodes, beginning Wednesday, and they lead into a
new sketch comedy series called ``The Upright Citizens Brigade.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, it's Lifetime, the ``Television for Women''
channel. (Men can attend, but their pictures will be posted and the
police have their instructions.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Maggie'' and ``Oh Baby'' (at 10 and 10:30 p.m.) are Lifetime's
first original comedy series. ``Any Day Now,'' at 9 p.m., isn't the
channel's first drama series, but its predecessor was long ago and
mercifully forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   This trio might stick. All three shows are well cast and
smartly, if not spectacularly, written. Even the comedies are about
something. And the usual cable budget-paring is only minimally
apparent.
</P>
<P>
   Flip-flopping the normal TV procedure, Lifetime runs the hour
drama ahead of the comedies. That might not be wise. ``Any Day
Now,'' starring Lorraine Toussaint and the underrated Annie Potts
as interracial buddies in Birmingham, Ala., has its assets.
Lickety-split pacing isn't one of them.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's pilot has Toussaint, as a high-powered lawyer in
Washington, D.C., returning to Birmingham for the funeral of her
father, a prominent civil rights attorney. She decides to stay and,
along the way, revives her long-severed friendship with Potts, a
housewife.
</P>
<P>
   So on one level, ``Any Day Now'' zeroes in on a close friendship
between women. But it also means to be a barometer of racial
progress. Frequently using flashbacks to cut to 1962, when the lead
characters (played by Shari Dyon Perry and Mae Middleton as
children) forged their friendship, it tries to reflect where we've
been and where we are.
</P>
<P>
   The ambitious effort yields moderate results. It's not that the
show overstates the fact of racial discrimination in 1962, but it's
laced into the pilot too thickly and obviously. Conversely, the
present might seem a bit Pollyannish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any Day Now'' might just need to work out the kinks. Any new
show with signs of intelligence behind the camera, as well as
talent in front of the lens, deserves a chance to find its stride.
</P>
<P>
   The first of the comedies, ``Maggie,'' is a sort of diary of a
mad housewife. Ann Cusack, less famous than her siblings Joan and
John, is threatening to fall apart as she hits the big four-oh.
</P>
<P>
   She won't, of course. Comedies that dark aren't on TV, or even
under the sofa. Instead she'll persevere, Lifetime-style, in a home
where her self-obsessed teenage daughter (Morgan Nagler) and her
equally oblivious husband (John Getz), a prominent cardiologist,
take her for granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maggie'' has a gimmick, albeit borrowed from ``Ally McBeal,''
or perhaps from James Thurber. Maggie's active imagination leads to
warped realities _ Jack Wagner of ``Melrose Place'' pays regular
and passionate visits to Maggie's kitchen _ and they're on the
screen to contemplate.
</P>
<P>
   Maggie has returned to school to become a veterinarian, and her
part-time job at a clinic fires her fantasies about the whimsical
vet (John Slattery) who might or might not become her lover in
future shows.
</P>
<P>
   If ``Maggie'' rates about a B, ``Oh Baby'' is a B-plus. Of the
three new series, ``Oh Baby'' is most conspicuously lodged in the
relative freedom of cable. Its chief plot engine is artificial
insemination.
</P>
<P>
   Dimpled Cynthia Stevenson, who couldn't quite keep ``Hope &AMP;
Gloria'' afloat on NBC, despairs when her boyfriend (Daniel Hugh
Kelly) gives her a turquoise friendship ring after three years.
</P>
<P>
   First she gives him an ultimatum, then she retracts it and
decides on single motherhood via artificial insemination. That's as
far as we get tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh Baby'' has a sprightly gimmick of its own _ Stevenson,
addressing viewers directly, wields a remote control and stands
beside a TV monitor to guide us through her chaotic life.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have about nine minutes left,'' she tells us cheerily at
one point, ``so I'm just going to fast-forward right to my nervous
breakdown.''
</P>
<P>
   There's a sentiment for the '90s. Zip right to the nervous
breakdown, fast-scan through it, then check your mascara and take a
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
