<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-APOLOGY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON RELYING ON THE SOFT HEART OF AMERICA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Will it work?
</P>
<P>
   Never has an American president gone on television to apologize
for having an extramarital affair, for lying about it for seven
months, for letting his family and friends defend what, it turns
out, was indefensible.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people are forgiving,'' said Alan Wolfe, a
sociologist at Boston University. ``We like to give people a second
chance, and Clinton will get one because he's been a naughty boy,
and you have to forgive naughty boys.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the president testified Monday to a grand jury about his
sexual relationship with former White House intern Monica S.
Lewinsky, 70 percent of the American people said they approved of
the way Clinton was doing his job. That high level of customer
satisfaction, combined with the country's fatigue with the story,
and its soft heart for contrition, might just pull the president
through the tightest bind of his political career, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   The key may not even be what the president said in his brief
address Monday night, but what Hillary Rodham Clinton does.
Americans will be much more likely to forgive the president if Mrs.
Clinton, however humiliated by her husband's behavior and her own
public pronouncements of his innocence, continues to stand by his
side.
</P>
<P>
   ``The attitude will be: If she can forgive, so can we,'' said
Steven Schier, a political science professor at Carleton College.
``Without Hillary lies the abyss.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has been on the edge of disaster before, only to be
saved by a public confession and apology. In 1992, his presidential
campaign, rocked by reports that he had carried on a 12-year affair
with Gennifer Flowers, Clinton appeared on CBS's ``60 Minutes''
with his wife and said he was sorry for ``wrongdoing'' and causing
pain in his marriage. Nine months later, the country elected him
president.
</P>
<P>
   Schier said the president's strategy of stonewalling for seven
months about the Lewinsky affair probably served the purpose of
inoculating the public from its sting and making people more likely
to forgive him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that people are sick of this story and completely
revolted by the details helps the president in an odd way,'' Schier
said. ``They really want to forgive him, move on, and close this
sordid chapter.''
</P>
<P>
   But not at any cost, said J. Bryan Hehir, a professor at Harvard
Divinity School.
</P>
<P>
   ``The forgiveness will be contingent on a clear, unambiguous
statement of fact by the president and a recognition by all the
parties that he really did do something wrong,'' Hehir said.
``People will only forgive if there is something relevant at stake,
if there is something that needs to be forgiven.''
</P>
<P>
   Ethicists like Hehir say forgiveness is rooted deep in the
Hebrew and Christian social traditions, but is far less notable in
the political arena, where it's much more common to seek justice,
or even revenge, than forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there such a thing as political forgiveness? Receiving it
depends on two conditions: genuine political confession and
repentence,'' said Donald Shriver, past president of the Union
Theological Seminary in New York and author of ``An Ethic for
Enemies: Forgiveness in Politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Some countries have been much better at repenting than
individual politicians. South Africa's new government, under
President Nelson Mandela, has forgiven the perpetrators of
apartheid atrocities who came forward and confessed. In the 1980s,
the US government apologized and made reparations for the World War
II internment of Japanese Americans.
</P>
<P>
   President Reagan was vague in his apologies for the Iran-contra
affair, which tarnished his presidency. And President Nixon didn't
exactly apologize for the Watergate scandal that traumatized the
nation and brought down his presidency. He said he felt deep
``regret'' if anybody had gotten hurt by it.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon had survived an earlier close call: Accused in 1952 of
making personal use of an $18,000 Senate slush fund, Nixon went on
television and said the only gift he had kept was Checkers, a dog.
The public believed him, and Nixon's spot as the vice presidential
candidate on the GOP ticket was secured.
</P>
<P>
   In his recent book, ``One Nation, After All,'' Alan Wolfe
surveyed thousands of middle-class Americans and found them far
more tolerant and forgiving of their neighbors than he had guessed.
He said he has been equally surprised by Americans continuing
support for Clinton throughout this sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one really knows the limits of our tolerance,'' Wolfe said.
``When this all started, I thought we were living in Nathaniel
Hawthorne's Massachusetts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
