<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-17 21:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8264 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-ROBERTSONCOLUMN-H     08-17 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-ROBERTSONCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DaleRobertson
</P>
<P>
   Hunt for next Bear &QL; 
a futile undertaking
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
IT was probably appropriate. In a year that saw the Golden Bear,
Jack Nicklaus, growl one last time, then finally take his leave,
nobody leaped forward to occupy the void. If there is indeed a next
Jack Nicklaus lurking on the PGA Tour, he refused to identify
himself in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   We heard nary a peep from any of the wanna-Bears.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods? Nope. Phil Mickelson? Nope. Justin Leonard? Nope.
David Duval? Nope. Collectively, the best and the brightest of
golf's new ``it'' generation took a deflating, humbling oh-fer in
the four majors. And it's probably too late for Mark O'Meara, 41,
Vijay Singh, 35, or Lee Janzen, 33, to enter the chase.
</P>
<P>
   One of two things has happened here: Either the burden of
expectations weighted down Tiger and his wealthy young friends,
allowing the aforementioned late bloomers, grinders all, to steal
the headlines, or we have grossly underestimated what it's going to
take for anyone to retrace Nicklaus' Himalayan trail.
</P>
<P>
   It's likely more the latter than the former. Based on the hard
evidence of late, chances are there will be no next Nicklaus, in
terms of either quantity or quality. It's far too much to ask. I
mean, look at what having to be the first next Nicklaus has done to
Greg Norman.
</P>
<P>
   Some major numbers, indeed
</P>
<P>
   Jack's uniqueness screams out in those 18 majors he won between
1962 and 1986. His durability, proof of his unabashed passion for
golf, speaks no less loudly in his streak of 154 consecutive majors
entered, a 36-year run that concluded when he skipped this summer's
British Open. Before the past weekend, he hadn't been a no-show at
the PGA Championship since the Kennedy presidency.
</P>
<P>
   His absence at Sahalee went largely overlooked, with all the
attention having already been focused on the end of his impossibly
long run when he sent his regrets to Royal Birkdale. But that's not
to say he wasn't missed. Nicklaus' specter dogs every one of the
feisty lads who want _ and whom, by all accounts, we want _ to be
like Jack.
</P>
<P>
   Five of Nicklaus' Slam titles came at the PGA, with three of
those victories in a five-year span. As hard as it is to picture
anyone on the tour today playing nonstop for almost four decades,
it's at least as difficult to see anybody dominating one of the
majors to that extent.
</P>
<P>
   I mean, no active, currently competitive player _ Tom Watson
missed the cut at all four majors for the first time in his career;
Nick Faldo was a forgotten figure as well _ has more than a couple
of Slam titles to his name.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Tiger is only 22, Duval and Leonard 26, Mickelson and
Ernie Els 28. But by the age of 28, Nicklaus had already won seven
majors. And the year he turned 23, he took the Masters and the PGA.
It wasn't just an advertiser's clever nickname. The guy was a bear.
</P>
<P>
   It's also worth noting that the best single interlude of this
year's Grand Slam circuit, O'Meara's out-of-nowhere dual
breakthroughs notwithstanding, would still be Nicklaus' keeping
himself in contention at the Masters through the early holes of the
fourth round.
</P>
<P>
   Limping along on a deteriorating hip, he couldn't sustain the
charge, but the brief, glowing reminder of what he used to be
should have been duly noted by those who would dare dream of
replacing him as the game's ranking icon.
</P>
<P>
   Even Tiger is no Nicklaus
</P>
<P>
   With Mickelson looking more and more like the next Norman,
dragging his spikes, Woods remains the obvious candidate despite
his disappointments of late. Tiger's last round at the British and
his first round at the PGA _ both 66s _ told us he is learning to
rein in his huge game. More maturity should beget more consistency
and steady his weekend nerves, which can put him back on a
championship track in '99.
</P>
<P>
   He will win a goodly number of majors before he's done. He won't
come within sniffing distance of 18, however.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the best tribute to Woods' talent surplus is the
Player-of-the-Year charge O'Meara has had. Being neighbors, the two
practice together extensively. It's a bit much to call O'Meara's
sudden tardy arrival at the tour's summit a total coincidence.
Tiger's influence has clearly ratcheted his steady game up several
notches. In their odd-couple case, the child definitely appears to
be the father of the man.
</P>
<P>
   But Woods can't carry golf by his lonesome. As influential as he
has become, bringing unprecedented interest in the sport to
neighborhoods where Big Berthas aren't a hot commodity, the
industry at large is in a worrisome slump. Several high-profile
golf companies, Nicklaus' publicly held one included, are teetering
on the brink, and others have seen their stock prices tumble.
</P>
<P>
   It's probably no more than a normal ebb in the flow, another
market correcting itself after a crazy growth spurt. Nonetheless,
the timing has been poor all around. O'Meara, Janzen and Singh
picked the wrong moment to say hello _ just as Jack was saying
goodbye.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
