<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCKS IGNORE GLOBAL FEARS, RISING STEEPLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By SHARON R. KING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Wall Street shrugged off Russia's currency
devaluation, another decline in Japanese stocks and news coverage
of President Clinton's grand jury testimony Monday, pushing major
market indexes higher and helping the Dow Jones industrial average
post its largest one-day gain in two months.
</P>
<P>
   Many investors _ apparently deciding that they had absorbed all
the bad news they could handle and that all those negatives were
reflected in current stock prices _ dived back into stocks, pushing
the Dow up 149.85 points, or 1.78 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The blue-chip index, led by gains in Merck, Eastman Kodak and
American Express, closed at 8,574.85.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index rose 20.92 points, or
nearly 2 percent, to 1,083.67, and the NASDAQ composite index, an
important technology-stock barometer, rose 27.85 points, or 1.56
percent, to 1,818.04.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the strong showing, the gain was not broad based, and
some stock strategists called it only a short-term rebound.
Overseas, shares were mostly lower as investors took a less
sanguine view of the Russian economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   In Germany, which is considered the most vulnerable to Russia's
travails, stocks fell 0.8 percent as 20 of the 30 stocks in the DAX
index declined. In London, stocks rose 0.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In Japan, the benchmark Nikkei index of 225 issues fell 2.18
percent, to its lowest level in two months, largely reflecting
concerns about further weakness in that economy and the region. On
Tuesday morning, the Nikkei rose 280.41 points, or 1.9 percent, to
stand at 15,075.07 at midmorning.
</P>
<P>
   Most other Asian markets fell Monday; Hong Kong and Australia
were closed.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, a litany of bad news has battered stocks in the
United States, pulling major market indexes down 10 percent and
more from highs reached a month ago. Investors have been rattled by
corporate earnings disappointments and by Asian economics, in
particular Japan's deepening recession, which has raised fears of a
currency devaluation by China, which might deepen Asia's troubles.
</P>
<P>
   The political scandal surrounding President Clinton has also
weighed on the market, which fears uncertainty. But on Monday, as
Russia floated the ruble, effectively devaluing it, and the public
awaited news of Clinton's grand jury testimony and Japan's
benchmark index reached a two-month low, investors finally saw
bargains and started buying shares.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this kind of economy, you need high interest rates to kick
the equity market'' down, said Mitchell Held, co-manager for U.S.
economics at Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went down too far too fast,'' said Harvey Hirschhorn, chief
economist and investment strategist at Stein Roe &AMP; Farnham
Investment Management in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of buying opportunities for people who
continue to believe the economy is OK,'' Hirschhorn said. ``Russia
has been a risk out there. It's a smaller economy. The ruble has
been declining in value for years, and another partial collapse
isn't going to make or break the German banks.''
</P>
<P>
   American financial exposure to Russia is relatively limited.
</P>
<P>
   The benchmark Russian trading system stock index fell 4.8
percent Monday. Among funds trading in the United States, the
Templeton Russia Fund fell 15/16, to 16 11/16. The Lexington Troika
Dialog Russia fund remains near a 52-week low.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, the funds saw steeper declines in May when the
Russian central bank raised overnight interest rates to defend the
ruble and when oil prices slumped.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Monday's renewed appetite for stocks, several analysts
said the market could soon fall further. ``I think this is a rally
to sell into,'' said Byron R. Wien, U.S. investment strategist at
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is becoming narrower and narrower; you could see
this coming back in June,'' Wien said, noting that almost 75
percent of the issues on the New York Stock Exchange are down 20
percent from their highs this year.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, only 31 Big Board stocks reached new highs, compared
with 265 new lows. Advancing issues narrowly exceeded decliners on
trading volume of 584.4 million shares.
</P>
<P>
   The limited breadth of the advance leaves the market vulnerable
to further declines, Wien and other economists said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, more corporate earnings disappointments are
expected, and Wien said he believed that analysts had yet to reduce
earnings forecasts enough to take account of that.
</P>
<P>
   While the market seemed to shrug off Clinton's problems Monday,
the scandal is presenting difficulty, Wien said, adding: ``You
don't want the American presidency preoccupied with survival. You
want it to take on world initiatives.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia's problems also illustrate that much of the rest of the
world, outside the United States and Western Europe, is in a
downturn, said Bruce Steinberg, chief economist at Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   ``The downward trend we're in is not broken,'' said Steinberg,
who forecasts that the stock market's slide will cause a profound
slowdown in consumer spending in the second half of the year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
