<SLUG> BC-CBS-NEW-EXECS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CBS FILLS PRESIDENT'S POST AT ENTERTAINMENT DIVISION 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CBS named Nancy Tellem president of the network's entertainment
division Monday, the position vacated in April by her longtime
associate, Leslie Moonves, who is now the chief executive of CBS
Television.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tellem becomes the second woman to head a network
entertainment division. Jamie Tarses is president of ABC
Entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tellem had previously headed both CBS' Business Affairs
office and its in &UR; - &LR; house &UR;  &LR; production company. In both positions
she worked closely with Moonves, and she will continue to report to
him in her new position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Leslie and I complement each other with respect to our
talents,'' she said. ``We've always taken a team approach and we'll
continue to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tellem will be in charge of the day-to-day operations of CBS
Entertainment, but Moonves, who has led the department since 1995,
will continue to be involved, he said Monday, with ``all the
biggest deals we make.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that might mean anything from a contract with a big star
to the negotiations for a package of feature films. But Moonves
said he would now be freed up to concentrate more on the other
divisions he is in charge of including CBS News and CBS Sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nancy has a great business background and she is an
exceptional manager of people,'' Moonves said.
</P>
<P>
   Moonves noted that the entertainment side of the business
remains his first love and for that reason _ and the fact that he
is the only chief executive of a television network based on the
West Coast _ he will retain an active role in CBS' entertainment
decisions, such as which shows are programmed and how they are
scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   Underscoring that point, Moonves made a series of other
personnel moves Monday in conjunction with promoting Ms. Tellem.
For example, Kelly Kahl, the executive in charge of program
scheduling for the network, was promoted to senior vice president
and will continue to report to Moonves. Chris Ender, the head of
publicity for CBS in Los Angeles, was also promoted to senior vice
president and he also will continue to report to Moonves.
</P>
<P>
   Moonves also promoted to senior vice president the department
heads of comedy and drama development, Gene Stein and Nina Tassler;
the head of the movie department, Sunta Izzicupo; the head of
casting, Peter Golden; the head of current programs, Terry Botwick;
and the head of East Coast Entertainment, Mitch Semel.
</P>
<P>
   All those executives will report to Ms. Tellem.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
