<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASKETBALL COLUMN: POINT GUARD GETS INSTINCTS FROM HOME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio)  (lb) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There are times when the night job is not all that
much different from the day job. Four people want her attention,
her assistance, her touch. Suzie McConnell Serio's role is to
deliver, no questions asked.
</P>
<P>
   Would it be much of a reach to call her the mother of all point
guards? Probably not. A decade ago, she became the career college
assist leader at Penn State. She was a gold medalist at the 1988
Summer Olympics and is the author of one of the more inspirational
stories in contemporary professional sports.
</P>
<P>
   Six years after her previous competitive experience, having had
four children who now range in ages from 1 to 7, McConnell Serio
came back this season to wear No. 4 and take charge of the four
players around her in the Cleveland Rockers' lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes she feels as if the last half-dozen years raising her
children and coaching a girls' high school team was the equivalent
of honing her pure point-guard skills for the Women's National
Basketball Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job is to take care of my teammates, sort of like the way I
take care of my children,'' she said before the Rockers dropped in
on the New York Liberty on Monday night at Madison Square Garden
for a preview of a possible playoff showdown next week. ``If you
think about it, there are similarities, because while I'm trying to
take care of one, I'm also trying to not slight the other.''
</P>
<P>
   The discussion continued with her passing around words like
``nurture'' and ``control'' and ``discipline,'' and that got
McConnell Serio to remembering that she had better check in on her
husband, Pete, and the kids back at their apartment in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   It was Peter Serio, actually, who looked at her one day last
summer and nodded at the women running around on the television
screen at their Pittsburgh home. ``You're still as good as they
are,'' he told his wife, who was cradling a newborn at the time.
``You should think about playing next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten sometimes excruciating and always laborious months later,
McConnell Serio walked into the visitors' locker room at Cleveland,
into the embrace of her opening-night opposite, Teresa
Weatherspoon, the tireless Liberty point guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome back,'' Weatherspoon told the woman to whom she was
competitively linked for a half-dozen years.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Teresa was at Louisiana Tech, it was always her and Suzie
and the question of who was the best point guard in the women's
game,'' Peter Serio said.
</P>
<P>
   Then they were teammates on two Olympic teams until McConnell
Serio began turning over diapers at a faster rate than the Knicks'
point guards relinquish the ball. Weatherspoon figured she had seen
the last of pony-tailed Suzie Mac. ``It never even entered my mind,
her coming back, after she had four kids,'' Weatherspoon said.
``But when Suzie McConnell sets her mind to something, she's going
to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The serious workouts began last January, McConnell Serio running
the Pittsburgh streets with her players at Oakland Catholic,
announcing her intentions to no one but Peter.
</P>
<P>
   There were time constraints, nagging injuries, lingering doubts.
But there came, in April, the WNBA tryouts in Chicago, where
McConnell Serio's body fat was down to 12 percent and she could
again experience the exhilarating feeling of the dribble, of having
having every young wannabe frantic for her to make something good
happen for them. It felt, she had to admit, like the best times at
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt like I had control,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said all along, my wife's only 5-5, 120 pounds,'' said
Peter Serio, himself a coach of high school girls. ``Her eyes and
her mind have always kept her apart.''
</P>
<P>
   A common male complaint about women's basketball is that ``they
don't finish,'' meaning that all the selfless teamwork doesn't
compensate for the inability to punctuate a play from
high-percentage air space.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, but was it really last summer when the Garden
management's Liberty game plan was to drape curtains around the
arena so it wouldn't look empty? The escalating crowds for the
women's summer league suggest that the sport is reaching an
audience more interested in basketball as a team sport than a
three-ring circus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the women's game offers that team quality you usually
don't find with the men,'' Peter Serio said.
</P>
<P>
   When she planned her return, McConnell Serio said she didn't
want to play unless she could be what she once was. On Monday she
was named the WNBA player of the week. She plans to play next
summer, continue to make her point with the pass, with a
nourishment that is reminiscent of Magic, or mom.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-98 2210EDT &QL; 
