<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL NEWS AND NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., Aug. 23)  
 (JT)  
 &HT;     
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Russian Companion For the Queen Mary &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Travelers to Southern California have a new attraction to visit
this summer: a Soviet submarine. The Povodnaya Lodka B-427, a fully
restored diesel-powered vessel that once patrolled the Pacific from
its base in Vladivostok, is docked alongside the Queen Mary in Long
Beach. Visitors can tour the same torpedo room and cramped bunks
where Soviet seamen once worked and lived. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The submarine, which is also called the Scorpion, was
commissioned in 1973, measures 300 feet long and has a displacement
of 2,475 tons when submerged. It accommodated a crew of 78, most of
whom had to sleep in shifts because of the shortage of bunk space. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An Australian company bought the submarine after it was
decommissioned in 1994 and put it on display at the National
Maritime Museum in Sydney. In June the vessel was moved to Long
Beach, where it will be moored for five years alongside the Queen
Mary, now a luxury hotel. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Admission to the submarine is $10; to the Queen Mary $13, and
slightly less for seniors and children. A combination ticket to
both ships plus an exhibition of artifacts from the Titanic is $25.
The Queen Mary is at 1126 Queens Highway. Information: (562)
435-3511.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A Cautious Opening To Lebanon &LR;
</P>
<P>
   After Washington lifted its 10-year ban on travel to Lebanon in
July 1997, United States airlines were still not permitted to fly
there or sell tickets to Lebanon-bound Americans and non-United
States citizens for travel even on foreign airlines. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright emphasized that Lebanon remained very
dangerous and urged United States citizens not to go there except
for ``compelling reasons.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In mid-June of this year, President Clinton authorized United
States and foreign carriers in this country to sell tickets to and
from Lebanon, but there is still no direct air traffic between the
two countries. British Airways, Air France, Swissair, KLM,
Alitalia, Sabena, Lufthansa, Royal Jordanian and Olympic Airways
fly to Beirut, and Middle East Airlines, the Lebanese national
carrier, flies between Beirut and many European and Middle Eastern
cities. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But would-be tourists should bear in mind that President Clinton
did not necessarily endorse travel to Lebanon. In fact, while the
last terrorist attack on a Western target in Lebanon occurred six
years ago, and the country's brutal 16-year civil war ended in
1990, the latest State Department consular information sheet
continues to warn United States citizens of potential dangers.
Americans have been ``targets of numerous terrorist attacks in
Lebanon,'' the notification says, adding: ``The perpetrators of
these attacks are still present in Lebanon, and retain the ability
to act.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But having urged the removal of all impediments to travel, the
Lebanese government is pleased with President Clinton's recent
move. ``The ruling makes it easier for tourists who want to visit
our beaches and archeological sites,'' said Hala Abi-Saleh, a
spokeswoman for the Lebanese Embassy in Washington, ``and makes it
easier for Lebanese in this country to return home on visits.'' In
fact, Albright lifted the travel ban in part because many Americans
with dual passports were traveling to Lebanon anyway, but lacked
consular protection because they refrained from registering with
the United States Embassy. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among the travel agencies that specialize in Lebanon and the
Middle East are Profile Travel and Tours, Washington, (202)
463-2015, GB Travel and Tours, Paterson, N.J., (973) 742-5900, and
Kutrubes Travel, Boston, (617) 426-5668 or (800) 878-8566.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Lebanon has posted an array of tourist information on
its Web site, www.embofleb.org.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Tiepolo in Paris, 300 Years Later &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Until Oct. 15, visitors to Paris can view the painstaking
restoration of three frescoes by Giambattista Tiepolo at the Musee
Jacque-mart-Andre. The museum, opened in 1996 and still something
of a secret to many tourists, is the only museum in France with
frescoes by the Venetian master. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Henri III's Arrival at the Villa Contarini'' is part of a
collection of 18th-century art purchased by Edouard Andre and his
wife, the portraitist Nelly Jacquemart, in 1893 to decorate their
mansion, which became the museum, at 158 Boulevard Haussmann in the
eighth arrondissement.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A circular staircase in the marble winter garden leads to the
scaffolding where six restorers are uncovering the original blue,
pink and yellow pastels used by Tiepolo when he painted the
frescoes in the mid-1750's. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The works _ one central fresco and two side panels _ depict
spectators on balconies viewing Henri III's arrival in Venice,
where he visited Federigo Contarini, the doge, in 1574. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Three other Tiepolo frescoes decorate ceilings elsewhere in the
mansion: ``The Announcement of Henri III's Arrival'' in the dining
room, ``Hercules' Triumph'' in the study and ``Peace and Justice''
in the boudoir. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The artist will be the subject of the first special exhibition
since the museum's inauguration. It will run from Oct. 20 through
Jan. 20 and will also include drawings and sketches by Tiepolo from
numerous European and American museums. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Until then, lectures by the chief restorers are given every
Thursday at 4 p.m. The museum is open daily from 10 a.m. to 6 p.m.
The restoration takes place during museum hours except on weekends.
The permanent collection includes works by Chardin, Fragonard,
Botticelli, Rembrandt and Van Dyck. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Admission is $8 (including an audio tour of the museum), $6 for
students and children. The tearoom in the mansion's dining room is
open daily from 11:30 a.m. to 5:30 p.m. Information: (33-1)
42.89.04.91.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Spiffy New Theater In Lancaster County, Pa. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Sight and Sound's new Millennium Theater will open Sept. 1 in
the heart of Pennsylvania Dutch country with a new production of
the biblical drama ``Noah.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The theater has been built in Lancaster County on the site of
the old Sight and Sound Entertainment Center that was destroyed by
fire in January 1997. The new theater has 2,000 seats (600 more
than the earlier theater), larger side stages and better sight
lines. Access to the theater has been improved with the
installation of a traffic light at the entrance and the expansion
of Route 896 to ease the traffic flow. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Noah,'' which originally opened at the Sight and Sound
Entertainment Center in 1995, includes a cast of more than 50
actors, about 80 live animals (camels, donkeys, llamas and
chickens) and about 125 animatronic animals. The latter, operated
by computer, include lions and tigers and bears. New sets,
including an ark five stories high, have been built since the
fire. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Friday and Saturday, ``Noah'' will be presented at 1, 4:15
and 7:30 p.m.; Tuesday, Wednesday and Thursday at 1 and 4:15 p.m.
The theater is closed Sunday and Monday. Tickets range from $32 to
$37, depending on the day of the week, and can be purchased at the
box office, Route 896, Strasburg, Pa., (717) 687-7800. More
information is available at www.noahonstage.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; In Oregon, a Portrait of Tribal Life &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Tamastslikt Cultural Institute, a new $17 million center
that presents the story of the Cayuse, Umatilla and Walla Walla
tribes of the Pacific Northwest, opened July 31 on the Umatilla
Indian Reservation, near the old Oregon Trail in northeastern
Oregon. The institute's name (pronounced tuh-MUST-slikt) means
``interpret'' in the Walla Walla language. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The facility _ a long, low building of wood and stone _ fronts
an 18-hole golf course and blends into a backdrop of rolling hills.
The building houses changing and permanent exhibitions, a cafe and
a store selling Indian art. There is also a theater in which the
story of the different tribes' creation by the coyote is told
through the recorded voices of female tribal elders. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Using dioramas, sound and video _ as well as artifacts like
moccasins and beaded dresses _ the exhibits illustrate tribal
history and contemporary tribal life. One exhibit documents the
huge herds of horses once kept by the Cayuse, Walla Walla and
Umatilla, and the gradual shift away from a horse-based society
that was triggered when 300,000 pioneers emigrated along the Oregon
Trail between 1843 and 1873.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The institute is the last in a series of five interpretive
Oregon Trail centers built across a 350-mile stretch of northern
Oregon over the past nine years. The other centers are in Ontario,
Baker City, The Dalles and Oregon City, south of Portland. The
Tamastslikt Cultural Institute is off Interstate 84, six miles east
of Pendleton. Admission is $6; $4 for seniors, students and
children under 12. Information: (541) 966-9748. For information
about the other Oregon Trail centers, call (800) 332-1843.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
