<HEADLINE>
FORMER UCLA RECRUIT SCHEA COTTON BEGINS CLASSES AT LONG BEACH CITY
COLLEGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE STEVENS  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ As Long Beach City College began classes on
Monday, Schea Cotton was looking for a fresh start and a way to
forget the pitfalls of his past.
</P>
<P>
   Cotton, one of the most celebrated high school basketball
players in the history of Southern California, announced last week
that he would attend LBCC this fall. His decision came after he had
signed three letters of intent for three different colleges. But
the NCAA revoked his eligibility to play Division I basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a hard-fought battle,'' Cotton said. ``I chose to go
to LBCC because I wanted to put an end to all of that and get a
feeling of closure.''
</P>
<P>
   By ``all of that,'' he means his past, clouded with perpetual
sidetracks and expectations that never were met.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-6 swingman is said to have NBA potential. He has
considered entering the NBA draft, but has yet to play one minute
of college basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Cotton, 20, had his latest pitfall on June 5, when the NCAA
denied an eligibility appeal and deemed his SAT scores
unacceptable. Cotton originally had taken the SAT and failed, but
he and his family argued that he had a learning disability called
test anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   So SAT officials allowed him to re-take the test, designed for
those with learning disabilities. The test had no time limit and
bigger print. Cotton passed.
</P>
<P>
   But the NCAA Eligibility Clearinghouse invalidated the score and
said it did not receive proper documentation on Cotton's
disability.
</P>
<P>
   Cotton had previously signed letters of intent with Long Beach
State in the fall of 1996, with UCLA in the spring of 1997, and
with North Carolina State this spring.
</P>
<P>
   For more than six months, Cotton said he had studied for the SAT
four hours per day on five days a week. When he learned that his
score was invalid, he was stunned. He had a difficult time, not
showing his disappointment and anger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've tried to keep an even keel with everything,'' he said.
``When I heard about the test, I kind of felt devastation at first,
but eventually, I just learned to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Cotton has moved to a two-year college, which is a
five-minute drive from his home in West Long Beach and close to St.
John Bosco High School, where he starred as a freshman and junior.
He played at Mater Dei as a sophomore, missed his senior season
with a shoulder injury and played last season at St. Thomas More
Academy, a prep school in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   He will have to complete 48 credit hours at LBCC to be eligible
to play for a Division I school. He finished eight hours this
summer, but will need at least a year and a half to complete the
other 40 hours.
</P>
<P>
   LBCC coach Gary Anderson said Cotton will add ``a special
element'' to his team, which frequently graduates players to
four-year colleges.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said he expects Cotton to play one season at LBCC, then
go to the NBA. But Cotton said that is not his plan. ``That would
be putting the cart, before the horse,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cotton, the highest profile prep star ever to enter LBCC, did
not talk in detail about his past. He focused on his future,
upcoming season at LBCC and his key philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my motto is 'you have to take what you have, to get
what you want,''' Cotton said. `` ... Right now, I'm really
ecstatic about coming here to play in front of the hometown. It
really means a lot to play in front of people you know are on your
side.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PRESS TELEGRAM, LONG BEACH, CALIFORNIA
</P>
</TEXT>
