<HEADLINE>
HARTSBURG READY FOR DUCKS' CHALLENGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just before Craig Hartsburg was fired by the Chicago Blackhawks
last April he said the team, which missed the playoffs for the
first time in 29 years, needed a ``total overhaul.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a month before the Mighty Ducks go to training camp,
don't count Hartsburg among those who believe that Anaheim is in
need of a major tuneup even though the team is coming off the most
disappointing season in franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me to say that would be wrong, said Hartsburg, who became
Anaheim's third head coach in 14 months when he was hired on July
21. ``That's not the coach's job. I know there are quality people
here and I'm excited about the opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks have yet to make a major free agent signing, have a
unproven defense corp and very suspect depth. But Hartsburg, who
signed a three-year contract worth just over $1.2 million, at least
has the dynamic offensive duo of Paul Kariya and Teemu Selanne to
work with after having virtually no offensive talent in Chicago
last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a team that can skate and generate offense, he said.
``The area we need to focus on is to become a solid defensive team.
Our defense as a team needs to improve and not just the defensemen.
</P>
<P>
   Hartsburg, who filled the NHL's last coaching vacancy after
Butch Goring turned it down, obviously is happy to have another
job, even if it's with an organization many consider to be in a
state of disaray as it begins its sixth season.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an outsider I didn't have that opinion, he said. ``I know
(former general manager) Jack (Ferreira) and I'm excited about
working with (new president and GM) Pierre (Gauthier). So I
couldn't ask for a better situation.
</P>
<P>
   Like the deposed Pierre Page, Hartsburg is a former employee of
Ferreira in Minnesota. After finishing a 10-year career as a
defenseman with the North Stars, Hartsburg, three times an
all-star, was hired by Ferreira as an assistant coach for the
1989-90 season.
</P>
<P>
   Being Ferreira's friend didn't mean much in the way of job
security for Page, who lasted only 10 months. But Hartsburg did get
a good review from from Gauthier, who had yet to take over the GM
role when the coach was hired.
</P>
<P>
   ``As team and franchise, he's the franchise's guy, said
Gauthier, when asked if Hartsburg could be considered his choice as
well as Ferreira's. ``I know Craig, he's a solid hockey man and
he's really grown as a coach. I feel very comfortable with him
being here. I did interview him when he came through the second
time around, and Jack had my full support in hiring him.
</P>
<P>
   But after his experience in Chicago, Hartsburg doesn't come to
Southern California with any preconceived notions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to be here for 20 years, but I'm not worried about
anything else but making the (Ducks) a team.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was worried (about job security) I'm not going to do a
good job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to be intense and have fun. If you're not enjoying
it why bother.
</P>
<P>
   After four years as an assistant in Philadelphia and one very
success head coaching stint in the Ontario Hockey League (47-14-5
with Guelph), Hartsburg was 104-102-40 in three years with the
Blackhawks. Chicago made the playoffs twice before the miserly ways
of Chicago owner William Wirtz caught up with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very disappointed and hurt, he said of being let go with
two years left on his contract. ``But I had to move on ... I knew
I'd be back. I'm excited about the future, not worried about the
past.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago GM Bob Murray sounded apologetic when he announced
Hartsburg's firing, a move that most believe was ordered by Wirtz,
who was no doubt unhappy with his coaching calling for a
``overhaul.
</P>
<P>
   ``Craig Hartsburg sold out his soul to try to get this team
going, Murray said. ``The things he tried to motivate this team ran
the gamut and nothing worked.
</P>
<P>
   But words such as that don't mean much to Hartsburg, who is
known for his stoic personality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't let myself get up or down by what is said ... good or
bad, he explained. ``I don't pay a lot of attention to what is said
(in print), what's said behnd closed doors means more to me.
</P>
<P>
   Already Hartsburg has had some private conversations with
Kariya, who was on the receiving end of a Gary Suter cross-check
that ended his season last Feb.1. Suter, Hartsburg and the
Blackhawks were soon public enenmy No. 1 among Ducks fans,
especially when Suter and Hartsburg doubted the severity of
Kariya's injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it didn't set off angry words (on both sides) we wouldn't
be worth a darn, he said. ``(But) to me it's over and done with.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked to Paul about it. I was protecting my side, they
were protecting there's. Emotions were a little high and things
were said on both sides that probably shouldn't have been said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year I was protecting Gary Suter, this year I'm only
concerned with protecting Paul Kariya.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody knows what Kariya and Hartsburg have said in private, but
before Hartsburg was named coach the Anaheim star said he could
play for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't hold a vendetta against everybody who says something
bad about ... you can't hold grudges, it's impossible, you just
can't function in the sports world. Everybody says something to
everybody else and you've got to deal with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't have a problem with him personally, you've got
to take what's on the ice and leave it there.
</P>
<P>
   Hartsburg now only expects the Ducks to leave it all on the ice
for him.
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The SAN GABRIEL VALLEY TRIBUNE, WEST COVINA,
CALIFORNIA
</P>
</TEXT>
