<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MOOD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE DAY OF RECKONING, PAIN, HOPE TO MOVE ON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On a day fraught with peril for the presidency of
Bill Clinton, the people's business had to take a back seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president of the United States of America, as you know, is
occupied in the Map Room today,'' the White House press secretary
Michael D. McCurry, told reporters as he began his morning
briefing.
</P>
<P>
   The day of reckoning had arrived. The scandal that Clinton had
so meticulously boxed off from the nation's business would suddenly
become part of it.
</P>
<P>
   The story that began in the cold of winter seven months ago cast
a dark shadow over the White House, and the weather provided a
metaphor for the occasion: hot and humid before turning cloudy and
rainy.
</P>
<P>
   Even the most loyal among Clinton aides suspended with any
pretense that it was business as usual at the White House.
Publicly, they promised to soldier on and let the American public
be the judge. Privately, they expressed hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes me physically ill,'' said one female midlevel aide.
``How can the president have any moral authority to talk about
issues when his feet are made of sand?''
</P>
<P>
   A midlevel male aide said, ``People aren't concentrating on
whether they feel betrayed or not, but it's what do we do now, how
do we get back on track?''
</P>
<P>
   Yet another said, ``We all just want to get through this.''
</P>
<P>
   But beyond their words, their faces were long and their smiles
seemed forced, even at the surprise birthday party for a press
aide, Elizabeth Newman, over hot dogs, chocolate cake, and
champagne in plastic cups.
</P>
<P>
   Some staff members expressed anger and sadness for themselves
and for the Clintons. Others felt frustration. In a few cases,
there was bewilderment that their boss would risk what they all had
worked so hard to accomplish, but mostly there was determination to
weather the storm.
</P>
<P>
   Several aides said they would wait to hear Clinton's televised
explanation Monday night before they began to sort out their
feelings.
</P>
<P>
   That address followed a long and embarrassing day for Clinton
that took him back to the place where he sought refuge seven months
ago, the Map Room. It was there in January, as the Lewinsky scandal
swirled around him, that he rehearsed his State of the Union
speech. Monday, he spent more than five hours there testifying
before a federal grand jury that watched on a secured, one-way
video feed.
</P>
<P>
   Before his testimony, Clinton spent two hours with his lawyers
going over last-minute preparations. He later looked glum as he
participated in his normal morning briefings with the chief of
staff, Erskine Bowles, and the national security council adviser,
Samuel R. ``Sandy'' Berger.
</P>
<P>
   Bowles was left to cheer up the troops. At a senior staff
meeting, he told aides to stick together: ``It's easy to be there
for someone when they're up, but it's the good ones who are there
when you're down.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowles also told them, according to one person who was there,
``Everyone makes mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, Bowles, his deputy, John Podesta, and other
administration officials worked the phones, providing courtesy
calls to the president's Cabinet and his political allies and
supporters on Capitol Hill, notifying them of Clinton's address and
rallying support behind him.
</P>
<P>
   One staff member who is among the longest-serving in the Clinton
White House said: ``I don't feel betrayed. I feel sad. I feel sad
for him, I feel sad for his family. It's got to be just hell to
live through this publicly _ for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   The female midlevel aide compared the situation to counseling a
girlfriend about having an extramarital affair. ``Honesty is best,
but it hurts a hell of a lot and it causes a lot of other stuff to
happen that you can't forecast,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we going to be proud to say that we served in the Clinton
administration, or is it going to be something you have to explain
away and is going to be an albatross on your resume?'' she asked,
adding, ``I hope not.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
