<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Desperate to Ease Crisis, Russia Devalues the Ruble
</P>
<P>
   The Russian government moved hastily to avert financial collapse
with drastic measures that included a devaluation of the ruble. The
step eased the pressure on Moscow to defend the ruble's value by
spending billions in dwindling foreign currency, but it also means
the ruble's purchasing power has been radically reduced, which will
hurt Russian consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko said the anti-crisis program,
which also includes a 90-day moratorium on some debt payments, had
been made necessary by the near-collapse of Russia's banking system
last week.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials said the Russians had little
choice in taking such steps, even though $22.6 billion in aid from
the International Monetary Fund announced last month had been
designed to buy Russia some time to restore confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese Stocks Near 1998 Lows
</P>
<P>
   The stock market in Tokyo fell sharply and flirted with the
year's lows, pressured by the wobbliness on Wall Street last week
and an expanding economic upheaval that is now ravaging Russia.
Further pressuring the market was the persistent fear that the
Japanese government will fail to overcome the country's banking
crisis and a renewed concern about the impact of Asia's troubles on
corporate profits.
</P>
<P>
   Bonds End Little Changed
</P>
<P>
   Treasury bond prices ended slightly higher while short-term
maturities ended slightly lower, reflecting investor concern about
Russia and Japan as well as caution ahead of Tuesday's meeting of
Federal Reserve policy-makers. The 30-year bond yielded 5.54
percent, unchanged from Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Women TV Executives Move Up
</P>
<P>
   CBS named Nancy Tellem president of the network's entertainment
division, the position vacated in April by Leslie Moonves, now
chief executive of CBS Television. Ms. Tellem becomes the second
woman to head a network entertainment division. Jamie Tarses is
president of ABC Entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Sweeney, president of the Disney Channel, was named
president of Disney/ABC Cable Networks, making her the
highest-ranking woman in the cable industry.
</P>
<P>
   Toy Seller's Earnings Drop
</P>
<P>
   Toys ``R'' Us earnings fell 63 percent in the latest quarter,
reflecting the No. 1 toy retailing company's failure to find a hit
product that could help it offset declines in sales lost to
discount chains.
</P>
<P>
   Waste Haulers in $1.3 Billion Deal
</P>
<P>
   Waste Management said it would buy Eastern Environmental
Services for $1.3 billion in stock, a deal that would expand the
geographic reach of the largest U.S. waste disposal company by
giving six landfills on the East Coast. Eastern Environmental
shares fell 4.3 percent on the news.
</P>
<P>
   GE Capital Buying Met Life Unit
</P>
<P>
   GE Capital said it had agreed to buy Metropolitan Life
Insurance's commercial finance division. Terms weren't disclosed
but the price was estimated at $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Effort to Organize Tourist Industry
</P>
<P>
   The AFL-CIO is campaigning to organize workers in one of the
nation's fastest-growing sectors: tourism, hotels and casinos. The
effort, now focused on the booming tourist industry in New Orleans,
represents an important new direction for labor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
