<SLUG> BC-RAC-ADIRONDACK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THINGS CHANGE WINS ADIRONDACK AT SARATOGA 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ A gray filly named Things Change showed
Monday just how much things can change for 2-year-old horses trying
to make the big leagues of racing at Saratoga.
</P>
<P>
   When they ran the first of the three major stakes for juvenile
fillies at Saratoga three weeks ago, Call Me Up was the winner,
followed by Brittons Hill, Fantasy Lake and Round Robin.
</P>
<P>
   When they ran the second race in the series Monday, the
Adirondack, only Brittons Hill made the first four, while the
newcomer Things Change was winning and getting her name on the
marquee for possible stardom.
</P>
<P>
   Things Change is a daughter of Stalwart out of the Gato del Sol
mare Romanticat, and this was only her third race. But she has
stepped smartly into her career: second at Belmont Park on July 11,
first at Saratoga on Aug. 2 and first again Monday over Extended
Applause, who has run in the money in all five of her starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little worried at first because in the paddock she was
very quiet,'' said Jose Santos, who has ridden Things Change in all
three of her races. ``But as soon as she stepped onto the track,
she was pumped up. I decided to let her stalk the pace, and
thankfully she had just enough kick to win the race.''
</P>
<P>
   Linda Rice, who trains the filly, said that the race had set up
well for Things Change because she had the speed to withstand the
fast fractions set by the leader, Blushing Deed, with Round Robin
dueling. The early leaders ran the first quarter of a mile in a
zippy 21 3/5 seconds and half a mile in 45 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   But Things Change drove from sixth place into second as they
turned for home, caught the tiring Blushing Deed in the deep
stretch and won by a length over Extended Applause, who had three
lengths on Brittons Hill.
</P>
<P>
   The volatile nature of young racehorses could be seen in the
changing fortunes of the four who had run well in the Schuylerville
on July 29. Call Me Up, who won that race, finished this one in
seventh place. Brittons Hill slipped from second to third. Fantasy
Lake, third in the Schuylerville, ran sixth this time. And Round
Robin dropped from fourth place to fifth.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Things Change ran the six and a half furlongs in
1:18, paid $8.80 for a $2 bet to win and earned $90,000.
</P>
<P>
   The next big date for the 2-year-old fillies is Sept. 4, in the
Grade I Spinaway at seven furlongs for $200,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-98 2223EDT &QL; 
