<SLUG> BC-LEAFBLOW-SOLUTION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW LEAF BLOWER PRESENTED AS QUIET SOLUTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICK ORLOV  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It resembles a ray gun from an old TV show,
generates no pollution, makes little noise and could fix Los
Angeles' disputed ban on leaf blowers, city officials say.
</P>
<P>
   The electric-powered leaf blower presented to City Council
members was developed by the Los Angeles Department of Water and
Power, which hopes will solve problems with the leaf blower ban and
earn the city money.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are enthusiastic that we are on the right track toward
finding a viable solution that meets the varying needs of our
city's residents,'' said DWP General Manager David Freeman.
``Everyone is eager to advance this prototype into the
commercialization stage.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the city hopes to be able to cash in on the
prototype by convincing a manufacturer to develop and sell them
across the country and provide a royalty to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are certainly hopeful that will be the case,'' said
Angelina Galiteva, who was in charge of the project for the DWP.
``We think there will be a market for these blowers across the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   The blower, with red and blue wires coiled along a plastic tube,
generates as much force as the gas-fueled machines, officials said.
A battery pack weighing up to 27 pounds powers the device.
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles, she said, the DWP would agree to buy a number of
devices to replace its own gasoline-powered leaf blowers.
</P>
<P>
   The city has banned gas-powered leaf blowers in residential
areas, but gardeners have gotten around the law by using _ or
saying they are using _ methanol fuel to run the blowers.
Prosecutors said gardeners must provide a declaration of their own
and one from the person who modified the machines to run on
methanol.
</P>
<P>
   Councilwoman Cindy Miscikowski, who has pushed for the ban, said
she is trying to find a way to close the loophole. She is waiting
to hear from the California Air Resources Board to determine if the
city can issue a ban on the use of methanol.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, she was enthusiastic about the electric leaf
blower, developed by AeroVironment Inc., in consultation with the
DWP and a Leaf Blower Task Force appointed by the City Council.
</P>
<P>
   AeroVironment developed the prototype under a $60,000 contract
with the DWP as part of its public benefits program required under
the new state law deregulating the electric industry, Galiteva
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Board of Water and Power Commissioners has set aside $1
million for two years for this program.
</P>
<P>
   However, not everyone was pleased with the new machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It solves the problem of noise and emissions, but it still
doesn't deal with the dust that is blown,'' said Jack Allen of
suburban Pacific Palisades, a member of the Leaf Blower Task Force.
``We still are going to have the problem of gardeners blowing
leaves and dust on neighboring properties and then driving off.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, he complained the task force had little significant
impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost like we were window dressing,'' Allen said. ``We
didn't look at all the alternatives.''
</P>
<P>
   But Galiteva said the group was shown alternatives the agency
felt would be competitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal was to come up with a machine that has zero emissions
and the same power as the ones now in use,'' Galiteva said. ``We
did that. The existing electric machines don't generate enough
power unless they are noisier than what's out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Gardeners and others praised the device, but said they remain
concerned over the existing prohibition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We support anything that will let us do our job,'' said Adrian
Alvarez of the Latin American Gardeners Association. ``But, we want
to keep our jobs now. We have families to feed. We aren't your
opponents, but we want some kind of compromise.''
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez urged the council to suspend its existing law until the
new machine can be developed.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Zambrano of AeroVironment said his firm wanted to have at
least one month of further testing around the area and would need
through December to develop specifications for a manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   After that, he estimated, it would take a manufacturer three to
six months to gear up to produce the machine because it is made
with readily accessible items.
</P>
<P>
   It is much quieter than gasoline-powered blowers, with a decibel
level of 64 at 50 feet, which officials described as two or three
times louder than normal conversation. That compares to the 70
decibel level of gasoline-powered leaf blowers, said to be
comparable to a loud party.
</P>
<P>
   The device can operate 10 to 45 minutes depending on the size of
the batteries used, and expels air at a velocity of up to 150 miles
per hour, officials said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-98 2227EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
