<HEADLINE>
CELLUCCI TO PRESS CIGARETTE MAKERS FOR TOXIN DETAILS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK PHILLIPS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In an attempt to bypass the tobacco industry's legal
fight against Massachusetts' ground-breaking ingredient disclosure
law, Acting Governor Paul Cellucci will Tuesday propose regulations
requiring cigarette makers to publicly reveal toxins in cigarette
smoke, administration sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said Cellucci will unveil his plan,
which would mark a new national front against the embattled
industry, at a morning meeting of the Massachusetts Public Health
Council.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed regulations would require any cigarette maker
selling products in Massachusetts to annually list by brand the
toxic substances in the smoke emitted from its products.
</P>
<P>
   The Cellucci-appointed council, which is required to set a date
for a public hearing regarding the proposal, must approve the
regulations before they can be implemented.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is going to say no,'' said one source of the council's
expected decision to go along with the acting governor's plan.
</P>
<P>
   But observers who have followed the battle over the state's
tobacco ingredients disclosure statute _ the so-called Tolman Law _
say that any implementation of the regulations will face a vigorous
legal challenge from the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   Approved in 1996, the Tolman Law _ named after its sponsor,
Senator Warren E. Tolman, a Watertown Democrat _ would require
tobacco companies to disclose the ingredients in cigarettes, snuff,
and chewing tobacco. Administration officials familiar with the new
regulations say Cellucci's move is an attempt to enact a key
section of the law that has been tied up in a federal court
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   The tobacco industry won an injunction last year on the law's
implementation, arguing that it would be forced to give up vital
trade secrets if it had to make public the ingredients in its
products.
</P>
<P>
   But administration officials are confident they can argue that
requiring the manufacturers to disclose toxic substances in
firsthand and secondhand smoke would not be forcing the industry to
divulge trade secrets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to see the tobacco industry argue that the poison
produced by their products are trade secrets,'' said Attorney
General Scott Harshbarger, whose office will be responsible for
defending any challenge to the regulations. ``We will be happy to
defend this initiative, as we have the Tolman ingredient disclosure
law.''
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci's move on the regulations is his first major
anti-smoking initiative. He and former governor William F. Weld had
generally ignored tobacco control issues and had even opposed some
major initiatives, such as the 1992 referendum to raise taxes on
cigarettes for an anti-smoking program.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci and Weld also scoffed at Harshbarger's
multibillion-dollar suit in 1995 against the tobacco giants to
recover medical costs from smoking-related diseases. With similar
suits winning concessions in other states, Massachusetts stands to
gain a huge windfall from the case.
</P>
<P>
   Administration sources said Monday that Cellucci's regulations
would focus on 12 toxic substances, such as ammonia, hydrogen
cyanide, mercury and other toxic trace metals, tar, nicotine, and
carbon monoxide.
</P>
<P>
   The Cellucci proposal comes several days after a US appellate
court in Virginia ruled that the federal Food and Drug
Administration had no authority to regulate tobacco products.
President Clinton had declared cigarettes drug-delivery devices
and, therefore, should come under FDA regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci administration health officials said that another court
ruling in Boston last year bolsters the administration's proposed
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   The 1st District Court of Appeals ruling said that Massachusetts
has the right to regulate tobacco products as long as it did not
require any warnings on the package. A federal statute already
mandates such warnings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
