<SLUG> BC-INFORMIX-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INFORMIX LEADER SENSES GAIN AFTER FILL OF PAIN  
 BY JAMIE BECKETT 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - INFORMIX   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
It's a good thing Bob Finocchio is a marathon runner _ he's needed
the endurance since becoming chief executive of Informix a year
ago.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Each time it seemed the troubled database-software maker had
turned the corner, new problems cropped up.
</P>
<P>
   Twice in the past year, Informix had to restate sales due to
accounting problems, a costly and embarrassing move for a large,
public company.
</P>
<P>
   Its share of the database market slipped from 6 percent in 1996
to 5.6 percent in 1997 and is expected to fall slightly this year,
according to IDC Research. Informix is No.3 after Oracle with a 39
percent share and IBM with 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Informix's stock _ which hit an all-time high of $35.88 in
February 1996 _ slid to an all-time low of $4 in December 1997. It
closed at $5.56 yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   To run a marathon, ``you have to be able to plow through pain,''
Finocchio said. ``There are a lot of parallels to running the
company.''
</P>
<P>
   Finocchio said he believes the worst pain is past.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Informix reported a second-quarter profit of $12.3
million _ three times what analysts were expecting. Revenues were
$174.2 million. For the first time since he took the job in July
1997, Finocchio is making positive predictions.
</P>
<P>
   He told analysts recently he expects revenues in the second half
of 1998 to be bigger than both the second half of last year and the
first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a terribly daring forecast: Except for 1997, Informix
typically has a strong second half. But the positive prediction is
a big step for Finocchio, who has been reluctant to raise
expectations during a grueling year.
</P>
<P>
   There are other encouraging signs:
</P>
<P>
   _After more than a year of cutting jobs or losing employees to
rivals such as Oracle, Informix is growing again. Since the
beginning of the year, the company has expanded its staff by about
10 percent to nearly 3,600.
</P>
<P>
   _Last month, the company announced it has several new customers,
including DDI Corp., one of Japan's largest telecom carriers, and
Korea's seven national libraries.
</P>
<P>
   _For the first time, the company is creating a unified marketing
theme, and it has hired a new vice president for corporate
marketing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Informix has a future today that wasn't possible a year ago,''
Finocchio said.
</P>
<P>
   But what is emerging is a much different company from the
high-flying Informix of the past. It's a lot more cautious, with
strict controls intended to prevent future financial blunders. It's
also a lot more humble.
</P>
<P>
   Once considered a rival to giant Oracle, the company has lowered
its sights. ``We don't have to be a $5 billion company to make
money,'' Finocchio said.
</P>
<P>
   One way Informix got in trouble was selling databases at
cut-rate prices to anybody who would buy one. Now the company wants
to focus on higher-profit niche markets like electronic commerce,
retailing and media, where it believes its technology gives it an
edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like us to be viewed as the BMW of the database
industry,'' said Finocchio. ``Our challenge is to go to customers
where the database is critical.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Oracle and other competitors such as IBM and Microsoft,
which sell software applications and tools as well as databases,
Informix is betting solely on the database.
</P>
<P>
   It's a strategy some say is a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``The database isn't the center of the universe anymore. It's
only one link in the (software) chain,'' said Merv Adrian, vice
president at Giga Information Group in Santa Clara.
</P>
<P>
   Many customers are looking for a package of products _ not just
a database but also applications, tools and services _ to track an
entire operation such as customer service or human resources.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Adrian expects Informix will retain current customers but sees
difficulty winning new ones without a broader product line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't consider them a competitor anymore,'' said Mark
Jarvis, senior vice president of marketing at Redwood Shores-based
Oracle. ``The era of the pure database company is gone.''
</P>
<P>
   But Michael Murphy, publisher of the California Technology Stock
Letter, thinks Informix's niche strategy will pay off. ``They're
doing the right thing, walking away from the commodity end of the
business where Microsoft is chopping up prices and heading to
e-commerce and places where people have to manage new data types.''
</P>
<P>
   The company is also focused on achieving financial stability,
which is essential to regain Wall Street's confidence.
</P>
<P>
   The company has spent the past year trying to come out of a
financial tailspin that began when it discovered that salespeople
eager to boost their commissions had booked business that wasn't
complete. Eventually, it had to restate results, lowering reported
revenues by $278 million between January 1994 and June 1997 and
lowering earnings by $236 million for the same period.
</P>
<P>
   After the restatement last November, the company reported two
consecutive profitable quarters. But then it faced the
embarrassment of restating again _ this time after a dispute with
auditors over how the company recognized sales to customers who
installed Informix databases in other products for resale.
</P>
<P>
   The second restatement, in May, reduced first-quarter revenues
by $6.2 million to $161 million and turned a $4.9 million profit
into a $400,000 loss.
</P>
<P>
   The company is determined not to slip again. New Chief Financial
Officer Jean-Yves Dexmier has instituted strict financial controls
to sharply divide sales and accounting functions. Among other
things, Dexmier created an in-house audit group that reports
directly to the board of directors and a management committee
responsible for reviewing all major sales. Most sales reviews
include a visit to the customer.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're doing what they should be doing,'' said James Pickrel,
an analyst at Hambrecht &AMP; Quist. ``Their growth rate won't be as
exciting as some investors are looking for, but it's good for the
long term.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
