<SLUG> BC-HP-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HP'S Q3: HO-HUM AGAIN  
 BY DAVID EINSTEIN 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - HP   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
In what has become a depressing routine, computer giant
Hewlett-Packard turned in another lackluster financial performance
yesterday.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Blaming Asian turmoil and falling PC prices, HP reported a tiny
increase in earnings and only 5 percent revenue growth for the
third quarter that ended July 31.
</P>
<P>
   The Palo Alto company said net income was $621 million, compared
to $617 million for the same period a year ago. Earnings per share
were 58 cents, the same as last year, when there were fewer
outstanding shares.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterly revenue was $11 billion, up from $10.5 billion a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
   HP warned last month that it was about to disappoint Wall Street
for the ninth time in 10 quarters. The earnings came in just above
analysts' diminished estimates of 54 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're clearly not pleased with our Q3 results,'' said Chief
Financial Officer Bob Wayman.
</P>
<P>
   However, HP appeared to make good progress in reigning in
expenses, which were just 4 percent higher than in last year's
third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The company has slowed the pace of hiring and also saved some
money by temporarily closing some facilities in early July.
</P>
<P>
   HP has been particularly plagued by weakness in Asia, mainly in
Korea and Japan, which are major markets for its semiconductor and
communications testing and measurement equipment. HP's revenue from
the Asia Pacific region dropped 13 percent in U.S. dollars during
the quarter, while orders declined 19 percent.
</P>
<P>
   HP said its PC business continued to suffer from ``intense
pricing pressure.'' Despite good growth in unit sales, revenue from
PCs was flat during the quarter as customers shifted to
lower-priced PCs.
</P>
<P>
   The brightest spot in HP's lineup was its Unix servers _
computers designed to manage corporate networks. Both the high-end
and mid-range models showed ``excellent revenue growth,'' the
company said.
</P>
<P>
   HP estimated that revenues for the fourth quarter will exceed
those reported yesterday. ``But our planning assumptions for fiscal
year 1999 have revenue growth below the mid- to high teens that
we've achieved over the long term,'' said Wayman.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it will continue to pare expenses by limiting
hiring and curbing employee travel.
</P>
<P>
   HP also has announced plans to close its operations worldwide
for two weeks in December.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're in a tough situation,'' said J.P. Morgan analyst
Daniel Kunstler. ``They're really trying to cut expenses, because
they're not planning for any explosion of the top line.
</P>
<P>
   ``HP remains a good company, but they're sort of caught right
now. The environment in which they operate simply isn't very
hospitable, and there's no easy way to break out of that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
