<SLUG> BC-INCYTE-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INCYTE SAYS IT WILL MAP DNA WITHIN A YEAR  
 BY ILANA DEBARE 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - INCYTE   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
Incyte Pharmaceuticals Inc. said yesterday it plans to map most of
the human genome within one year, part of a drive to capture an
emerging new market for data on gene variations.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Palo Alto-based Incyte announced plans to achieve that goal by
purchasing a British firm called Hexagen for $5 million in cash and
1 million shares of stock, a total purchase price of about $41
million.
</P>
<P>
   The company will incorporate Hexagen into a new division to be
called Incyte Genetics, which will issue its own stock and will
specialize in selling information about gene variations _ data that
can be useful in figuring out why identical drugs affect people
differently.
</P>
<P>
   Incyte's one-year timetable for genetic mapping is much faster
than the government-funded Human Genome Project, which set 2005 as
its goal for a thoroughly documented map of human genetic material.
</P>
<P>
   It also would be faster than Incyte's main commercial
competitor, Perkin-Elmer Corp., which last spring formed Celera
Genomics Corp. and promised to produce a gene map within three
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perkin-Elmer rattled some cages with their decision to enter
the field, but this (acquisition) reaffirms Incyte's leadership
role in the technology needed for gene splicing,'' said Richard van
den Broek, a biotechnology stock analyst with Hambrecht &AMP; Quist.
</P>
<P>
   Incyte is a leader in the field of genomics, a part of the
biotechnology world focused on finding and analyzing the 120,000 to
150,000 genes that make up human beings.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials said their main division will continue to sell
general gene-mapping equipment and software, along with genomics
data that can help drug companies develop new products.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the new division will market software and data about
genetic variations _ tiny differences within similar genes that can
determine how individual people respond to diseases or drugs.
</P>
<P>
   These variations are known as single nucleotide polymorphisms or
SNPs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a response to our customers in the pharmaceutical
industry,'' said Incyte CEO Roy Whitfield. ``There is a lot of
enthusiasm in the industry for creating a database of SNPs, which
can tell us why certain drugs work for some people but not others,
or why drugs have side effects for some people but not others.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitfield said the new division also will map out most of the
human genome _ naming and locating all human genes _ within a year.
</P>
<P>
   Incyte was founded in 1991 and has more than 700 employees,
including 500 at its Palo Alto headquarters and 80 in Fremont.
</P>
<P>
   It's one of the few biotechnology startups that has generated a
profit. For the quarter ended June 30, Incyte reported net income
of $5.2 million (18 cents per diluted share) up from $1.3 million
(5 cents) a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Incyte's new business unit that is focused on gene variations
won't generate any revenues until 1999 and won't generate any
profit until 2002, company officials said.
</P>
<P>
   That's probably one reason why the company decided to issue
separate common stock known as tracking stock for the new division.
Other companies that have issued tracking stock for their
subsidiaries include General Motors, which issued separate stock
for its EDS software division.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about Incyte is that it's a company that earns
money, unlike much of their competition,'' said van den Broek.
``They probably have more earning-sensitive investors and may have
wanted to shield them from uncertainty about earnings.''
</P>
<P>
   Incyte officials said they intend to plow $20 million to $30
million of the firm's money into the new gene-variation division,
on top of the initial $40 million purchase price. Then they intend
to raise another $130 million to $140 million from outside sources,
such as drug industry investors or licenses from drug companies.
</P>
<P>
   Incyte's stock fell $2.25 to close at $30.63 yesterday. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
