<HEADER>
A8320 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIGITAL18-3SC1GD &LR;      08-17 0633
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL18-3S </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEHIND THE HIGH-TECH PUBLIC RELATIONS GAME AT ORACLE CORP.  
 TOM ABATE/DIGITAL BAY 
</HEADLINE>
 C1 GD   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Behind every great tech company stands a public relations firm.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oracle Corp. caused quite a stir in local PR circles last week,
when it abruptly replaced a PR firm it had just hired, Avalanche,
with its former agency, Applied Communications.
</P>
<P>
   Avalanche was the new kid on the PR block. It had only been
formed in January, when Palo Alto-based Cunningham Communications
teamed up with Hill &AMP; Knowlton and Ogilvy, Adams &AMP; Rinehart to take
on Oracle's multimillion-dollar account.
</P>
<P>
   The idea was to create one PR firm with global and local
high-tech savvy.
</P>
<P>
   Avalanche had stepped into this demanding role after Oracle
forced Applied to compete for the PR contract it had held for the
five previous years _ a period during which Applied helped get
Oracle beaucoup coverage of the Network Computer, which never took
off.
</P>
<P>
   But for reasons glossed over in the official release, Oracle
decided last week that Applied, not Avalanche, had the right stuff
to lead its global PR effort.
</P>
<P>
   PR pros weren't surprised that Avalanche fell, because no one in
the biz had ever tried what it set out to do _ fuse three different
companies into one firm. Nor did it help that this novel alliance
would be working for Oracle.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were bets on the street how long Avalanche was going to
last,'' said one PR insider. ``Everyone on the street knows Oracle
is the client from hell.''
</P>
<P>
   Karen Hodskins, the Cunningham exec who led Avalanche, said her
firm resigned the account after Oracle replaced former marketing
chief Karen White _ who signed the Avalanche deal _ with Gary
Bloom, who brought Applied back.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``The management we were working with changed,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Oracle spokesman Kevin McGuirk demurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``This had nothing to do with management changes,'' he said.
``After six months of trying to make this happen, we had to get a
different agency in there.''
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; PR Postscript: &LR;  There's no such thing as losing in the PR biz
these days. Every PR firm in the region is turning business away,
as the Bay Area's 3,000 to 5,000 PR pros try to keep up with the
demand for hype.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no such thing as an unemployed high-tech PR person,''
said Barry Shulman, who runs a recruitment firm in Mill Valley that
bears his name.
</P>
<P>
   Wanna work at home? No problem, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two- and three-year &UR;  &LR; `seasoned' people _ and I use
the term &UR;  &LR; advisedly _ who are billing $100 to $150 an hour for
elementary work,'' like cold-calling reporters in search of
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Didja realize? &LR;  In doing a recent column item on IBM, I asked
for a local head count. IBM spokesman Dave Berman said IBM employs
8,600 people in the Bay Area, with the largest chunk at the
disk-drive division in San Jose and two nearby research outposts.
</P>
<P>
   That gives Big Blue a larger local payroll than Intel, Silicon
Graphics, Apple or Chevron, according to The Chronicle 500, a list
of the Bay Area's largest companies.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Mudfest: &LR;  Berkeley-based Net Studio has found four computer
industry notables to judge its recently announced Mud Brick
contest, which will reward the ugliest Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   The firm will announce today that ugly is in the eye of these
beholders: New York industry analyst Esther Dyson, San Mateo
newsletter editor David Coursey, Bay Area radio and television
personality John C. Dvorak and humor columnist Lincoln Spector.
There's still time to nominate a site for the Mud Brick award
before losers are announced in September.
</P>
<P>
   (See  &LR; www.netstudio.com). &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Got a tip, gripe or brainstorm? Tom Abate wants to hear it by phone
(650) 961-2689, fax (650) 961-5023 or e-mail  &LR; lf
 &LR; (abate &LR; sfgate.com). &LR; li
</P>
