<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-17 22:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8329 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-MARKETING-IMAGE-N     08-17 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-MARKETING-IMAGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HORSE-RACING COLUMN: NEW AD CAMPAIGN FOR RACING TAKES THE LOW
ROAD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga., N.Y.)  (js) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ The marketing specialists hired to save
horse racing from its deepening troubles reviewed their ``first 100
days'' on the job the other day and found them to be a howling
success.
</P>
<P>
   They determined that public awareness of racing had more than
doubled since they arrived on the scene April 1 and set up a
``league office'' in Atlanta. They announced that racing now
surpassed the awareness level of tennis and was moving closer to
golf. They took some credit for the crowd of 81,000 that jammed
Belmont Park in June to watch Real Quiet shoot for the Triple
Crown.
</P>
<P>
   They even claimed credit for the fact that auction prices for
yearlings had jumped by 15 percent at last week's Saratoga horse
sales.
</P>
<P>
   They proclaimed these signs of success during a well-rehearsed
report by Tim Smith, the commissioner of the National Thoroughbred
Racing Association, and several of his vice presidents and
advertising deputies, who spoke at the 46th annual Round Table
conference of the Jockey Club.
</P>
<P>
   It was held Sunday morning at the Gideon Putnam Hotel in
Saratoga Springs, not far from Saratoga Race Course, where the
130th season of racing is booming. And they can probably take
credit for that, too.
</P>
<P>
   The timing was right, coming after two thrilling Triple Crown
series in a row that went down to the wire. And the audience was
right, too: several hundred of racing's most important owners and
breeders, who have been told for years that they must form an
alliance to solve the sport's problems of declining attendance and
declining interest at a time when team sports are exploding.
</P>
<P>
   The self-congratulations began when the stage was turned over to
Smith, an articulate and engaging lawyer from Atlanta who won the
job of commissioner from racing's second search committee in four
years. The earlier committee searched and found Brian McGrath, who
beat out a promoter from professional wrestling but who unhappily
lasted only nine months before that ``league office'' was
disbanded.
</P>
<P>
   Smith was endowed with five or six vice presidents and an
advertising budget of $22 million, and he spent some of it
searching for a slogan. He found one when Steve Bowen of the New
York-based Merkley Newman Harty advertising agency came up with
``Go, Baby, Go.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Bowen created a series of television spots starring Lori
Petty, an actress who shrieked the slogan while running up and down
the sideline of the homestretch before telling the heavens, ``Pay
the lady, pay the lady.''
</P>
<P>
   The tone of the advertising was described to the Round Table
conference as ``hip, cool, slightly naughty'' and intended ``to get
attention.'' It was aimed at picturing horse racing as a ``social,
sensual'' sport in which ``you don't just get escorted to your
seat.'' Also, as the only sport with live, legal wagering.
</P>
<P>
   But the commercial took the low road to reach a young, new
audience and was so implausible that you might wonder how it got by
the fathers of racing and breeding when they auditioned it. They
included Dinny Phipps of the Jockey Club; William Farish, the
chairman of Churchill Downs; Tom Meeker, the president of Churchill
Downs, and Robert Clay, the owner of Three Chimneys Farm in
Kentucky, none of whom would appreciate being portrayed as hip,
cool, slightly naughty.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody who attended the meeting reported that the reaction had
been ``Well, since everybody hates it, maybe it'll work.''
</P>
<P>
   It worked for Bowen, who said at the Round Table conference:
``You can feel the excitement of thoroughbred racing is beginning
to permeate the culture out there. Entertainment people are
starting to talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   He backed up that contention by showing film clips of the Triple
Crown with Jack Nicholson, Sylvester Stallone and Donald Trump
among the crowds, and reaching a neat, dramatic high when the
trainer Bob Baffert, wired for the moment, shouts to his horse,
Real Quiet, the magic words: ``Go, Baby, Go.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith also announced a new series of handicap races next year on
the Fox Sports network. Will racing make any money for awarding the
rights to major races to Fox? No. Who pays the production costs?
Racing.
</P>
<P>
   Well, then, how extensive a sampling was used to determine that
the awareness of racing had doubled since the marketers arrived?
Just 400 people in four cities. Many of them presumably hip, cool,
slightly naughty.
</P>
<P>
   The league office likes to quote Albert Einstein, ``The
definition of insanity is doing the same thing over and over again
and expecting a different result.'' How about trying something new
and proclaiming success after the first 100 days? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-98 2238EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
