r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BACKTOSCHOOL-SFCHRON-     08-17 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BACKTOSCHOOL-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PICKING YOUR STUDENT'S PC  
 BY DAVID EINSTEIN 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - PERSONAL TECHNOLOGY   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
As summer winds down, it's time for students and their parents to
start thinking about school supplies. Things like binders, paper,
pencils _ and computers.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once a luxury item for the well-heeled household, a personal
computer is fast becoming a must-have item for students from
elementary school through college.
</P>
<P>
   The question no longer is whether to have a computer. Now, it's
what kind of computer to have. Do you need a state-of-the-art PC
with the latest Intel Pentium II chip, or is an entry level system
good enough? Should you get a desktop computer or a notebook? And
what about software and the Internet?
</P>
<P>
   Many middle schools and high schools now recommend that students
have computers so that they can type assignments and do online
research. Colleges are going further, in some cases requiring
students to have a PC.
</P>
<P>
   Many colleges have put library resources on the Internet and are
making class material available online. (The University of
California at Los Angeles is asking all professors to create a Web
site for each class they teach.)
</P>
<P>
   Computer-makers, who know a profitable trend when they see one,
have launched unprecedented campaigns to capture as much of the
emerging educational market as they can.
</P>
<P>
   _PC leader Compaq Computer has created special centers in 5,000
Radio Shack stores across the country to promote its Creative
Learning Series PCs. All the systems in the series come with a
bundle of 15 educational software titles from companies such as the
Learning Company and Broderbund.
</P>
<P>
   _Dell Computer ( &LR; www.dell.com &LR; ), the largest direct seller of
PCs, has a program that lets students lease a multimedia desktop PC
for as little as $64 a month, or a Pentium II-based notebook for
$75 a month. For an extra $11 a month, students can get a DVD
drive, which takes discs that hold many times more information than
a CD-ROM. (That way if a class gets boring, you can stop taking
notes and watch a DVD movie instead.)
</P>
<P>
   _Gateway ( &LR; www.gateway.com &LR; ), another leading direct seller,
announced a program last week that allows students to order
customized Gateway systems from Barnes &AMP; Noble-run campus
bookstores. Gateway and Barnes &AMP; Noble plan to offer the program
this fall in about 100 universities.
</P>
<P>
   _Apple Computer, long a leader in the education market, offers
special prices on computers and peripherals through campus
bookstores at more than 300 colleges and universities. Apple also
has started offering discount prices to higher-education students
through its online store at  &LR; www.apple.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   What should you expect to pay for a back-to-school PC? That
depends on the needs of the student. A fourth-grader, who will use
a PC for word processing, CD-ROM encyclopedias and Web surfing, can
get along nicely with an entry-level system costing as little as
$1,200 including monitor and printer.
</P>
<P>
   A third-year engineering student, however, likely would use a PC
with a fast Pentium II chip, gobs of memory and a big monitor. If
you buy direct from Dell or Gateway, such a system may cost about
$2,200.
</P>
<P>
   College students also should seriously consider a notebook. Some
universities, such as Wake Forest, even require incoming students
to have one for note taking.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Notebooks have the obvious advantage of portability, so they
can be taken to class, to the dorm and even home for the holidays.
But they also have a couple of big drawbacks: They're more
expensive than comparable desktop systems; they're heavy, averaging
between 6 and 7 pounds (more expensive models are lighter); and
they're easily stolen.
</P>
<P>
   For less than $2,000, you can get a notebook based on a Pentium
II, with a 12.1-inch screen, a CD-ROM drive and 2 or 3 gigabytes of
hard disk storage.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to a computer, your student probably will need a
color printer ($200 and up) and an Internet connection. A home
Internet account will cost about $20 a month, but many colleges now
give students free Internet access in their dorms.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Basic software for schoolwork includes a good word processor
and an encyclopedia. You can get both in Microsoft's Home
Essentials (street price under $90). It comes with Word 97 and the
Encarta 98 encyclopedia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
