<HEADER>
A8336 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BUCCANEERS-HNS &LR;      08-17 1253
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BUCCANEERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Moving into the fast lane
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once-downtrodden Buccaneers now reach for the stars
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN McCLAIN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
TAMPA, Fla. _ Before the Tampa Bay Buccaneers can think seriously
about Super Bowl XXXIII, they have to figure out a way to beat
Green Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, the Buccaneers got a whiff of the playoffs, and
they liked the smell. But they were 0-3 against the Packers, the
third defeat coming in a second-round playoff game at Lambeau
Field.
</P>
<P>
   Like other NFC teams, the Bucs believe the road to the Super
Bowl goes through Green Bay. And they are confident they have the
pieces in place to overthrow the Packers and win the NFC Central.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last season, we were raw and hungry, and we ate the
appetizer,'' says Bucs guard Jorge Diaz, a three-year veteran from
Texas A&AMP;M-Kingsville and a Katy native. ``This season, we want to
eat the whole meal.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tampa-St. Petersburg area is excited about the Buccaneers,
who reached the playoffs last season for the first time since 1982.
They proved they weren't just happy to be there by beating Detroit
in a wild-card game.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first came here, we were the Tampa Bay Yucks,'' says
Warren Sapp, one of the best defensive tackles in the NFL. ``Now,
it's great to be a Buc. We came from the ruins of this league.
Everybody laughed at us. They're not laughing now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time for everybody to be excited. This organization has
waited too long to have a team like this. We realize what's at
stake. We represent a part of Florida that's waited too long to
have a winner. We're going to get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Expectations are sky-high. Fans and media believe the Bucs are a
bona fide Super Bowl contender. The players are trying to not get
caught up in the hype, but it's almost impossible.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as you have realistic expectations, you understand
what you're trying to do,'' coach Tony Dungy says. ``I think our
players understand. But if they start thinking like the fans, we
could get into trouble. It's good for the area to have this
excitement, but the players have to keep it in perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   Reality is that Green Bay is favored to win the NFC Central.
Although the Packers lost several important players through free
agency, they remain loaded. And as long as Brett Favre is the
quarterback, they will be favored to reach a third consecutive
Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got an excellent team with outstanding coaching and
great offensive weapons,'' Dungy says. ``They've also got a lot of
tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's going to be a situation where they're going
to come back to the rest of us. We're going to have to improve to
catch them.''
</P>
<P>
   Sports Illustrated predicts Tampa Bay will reach the Super Bowl.
If that happens, the Bucs will have overcome a lot of hardship.
</P>
<P>
   Before they move into their new Raymond James Stadium, Tampa Bay
will have to play on the road against Minnesota and Green Bay. And
just surviving the NFC Central _ the league's best division _ may
be the most difficult assignment of all.
</P>
<P>
   The Packers, Bucs, Vikings and Lions made the playoffs last
season, and all are capable of doing it again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes it sweet to have our measuring stick right in our own
division,'' Sapp says. ``We have six division games against
playoff-caliber teams. Hey, I want to play the roughest schedule
because it'll benefit us in the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bucs have gone from 6-10 to 10-6 in Tony Dungy's first two
seasons as coach. Dungy is loved by his players and respected by
the rest of the league. If the players become a mirror image of
their coach, they will not be prone to the emotional peaks and
valleys that can derail talented teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the last two seasons, you've seen us improve and take the
steps necessary to reach the next level,'' Diaz says. ``We learned
a lot last season by getting playoff experience. We know what it's
like to overcome hard times. We've grown up a lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, you can sense it in the locker room, that everyone is
ready to lay it on the line to reach our goals.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Rich McKay was promoted to general manager and Dungy was
hired as coach, the Bucs' philosophy hasn't changed. They use the
draft to build the team. Owner Malcolm Glazer opened the vault to
sign players to long-term extensions.
</P>
<P>
   When they have a need they don't fill in the draft, they will
use free agency.
</P>
<P>
   In the offseason, the Bucs identified two areas of concern: They
needed to bolster the receiving corps to give quarterback Trent
Dilfer better targets, and they wanted to add depth at cornerback.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta receiver Bert Emanuel, a restricted free agent, was
signed. The Buccaneers used their top draft choice on receiver
Jacquez Green. They traded up in the second round to get cornerback
Brian Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the components are where we want them,'' McKay says.
``We started with defense. Then, we made sure to have a sound
running game. We had to get a quarterback we liked and make sure he
could play within our scheme. And we wanted speed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bucs have a rare combination of speed and power on both
sides of the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Their running game is built around 248-pound fullback Mike
Alstott, who has missed the first three preseason games because of
a hip injury, and 5-8, 178-pound halfback Warrick Dunn, the NFL's
Offensive Rookie of the Year last season.
</P>
<P>
   Adding Emanuel and Green at receiver with Reidel Anthony gives
Tampa Bay one of the speediest units in the league.
</P>
<P>
   The defense features linemen who explode off the ball and
linebackers who run like backs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been a coach who likes speed,'' Dungy says.
``Speed gives you a chance to make big plays. That's one of the
things we didn't have two years ago. But speed and quickness are
such an important part of this game that we've constantly gone
after it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bucs are confident they won't be one-year wonders. They feel
they have too much talent on offense, defense and special teams to
go backward. They have a coaching staff that knows how to handle
players.
</P>
<P>
   About the only thing that could interrupt their playoff plans
would be an inordinate number of injuries to key players.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a close-knit team,'' McKay says. ``Tony creates a
working environment that brings the players together. It's peaceful
and family-oriented.''
</P>
<P>
   Going to a Bucs game is going to be an event. Every seat for
every game is sold out at the new stadium, and so many luxury
suites were sold, they decided to add more. And those sold
instantly.
</P>
<P>
   In one end zone, the Glazer family forked over $3 million for
Pirate Cove. The area will include a pirate ship more than 100 feet
long. Cannons will shoot confetti when the Bucs score. Cheerleaders
will dance on the ship.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the stadium is a state-of-the-art scoreboard
that features several screens. Fans can come early to watch
pre-game shows or other games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything starts with the head man,'' Sapp says, referring to
Dungy. ``He's great to play for. You never find him too high or too
low, yelling, ranting and raving. Whenever you have somebody like
that steering your ship, it's a lot easier to do the things we need
to do to be great in this league.
</P>
<P>
   ``When your head man is that calm and collected, it trickles
down. He's not a dramatic, in-your-face guy, and we appreciate
that. He just expects each man to do his job. He gets a lot of
productivity with that philosophy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
