u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUDOLPH-SEARCH18-COX     08-17 0578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUDOLPH-SEARCH18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Possible Rudolph sighting reported
 &HT;    By Kathy Scruggs
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANDREWS, N.C. _ V olunteers looking for Birmingham bombing
suspect Eric Robert Rudolph hid in the night and watched houses as
a man they believed to be the fugitive _ or a decoy _ twice
approached in what appeared to be a food raid, retired Green Beret
Bo Gritz said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   A federal spokesman said Monday that Gritz has agreed to call
them with any news of sightings, but no such calls had come.
Investigators had no comment about the report.
</P>
<P>
   Gritz said that on Sunday his volunteers received
``intelligence'' about a ``series of homes ... where people have
observed Eric Rudolph going in and out, securing food and a
sleeping bag.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people were allowing it to happen because he hadn't stolen
anything else,'' Gritz added.
</P>
<P>
   So, Gritz claimed, three volunteers, with night vision
equipment, set up on three houses and a trail. A 15-foot creek
separated two of the men from the other, so they developed a code
for ``intruder'' by placing their fingers over a flashlight to make
spheres of light, he said. At about 9:30 p.m., an ``intruder''
rushed by and they chased him up the trail shouting ``we're part of
Bo Gritz's team and we're here to help you; we had food for him,
etc.''
</P>
<P>
   Gritz said he was asked to come to Andrews by a member of the
Southeast Bomb Task Force and to appeal to Rudolph to surrender and
face charges in a Jan. 29 bombing of a Birmingham abortion clinic
that killed an off-duty police officer and severely wounded a
nurse. He is wanted for questioning in a series of Atlanta
bombings.
</P>
<P>
   Through his shortwave radio show, Gritz called for volunteers to
commit a week to ``Operation Cross,'' which means to ``Convey
Rudolph Obligingly (and) Safely (into the) System.''
</P>
<P>
   By Friday, they hope to have convinced Rudolph that his odds of
survival are better in court, where he could face the death
penalty, than hiding in the woods where federal agents and bounty
hunters are also tracking him. They will not, however, force him
in. But Gritz said he would muster ``all the mental judo'' he could
to bring Rudolph in willingly.
</P>
<P>
   All of Gritz's volunteers _ numbering about 37 in the woods _
agreed to waive the reward of up to $1 million for information
leading to Ruolph's arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Gritz has agreed to allow two media photographers to accompany
the search in a pool agreement to share their videos and
interviews. In return, other reporters are barred from the
Nantahala Forest command post and can't ask questions. Each
morning, Gritz recounts the previous day's events to the television
photographers, who then drop off the video to a producer.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Gritz said the second alleged sighting occurred about
4:30 a.m. in the pouring rain when the same team ``reset the whole
mousetrap.'' This time, however, one of the volunteers lay down by
the door, which was set up higher on a deck, he said.
</P>
<P>
   This time, as the intruder came around to the door, the
volunteer stood up and announced he was unarmed and with Gritz'
team, the former Vietnam soldier said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy bolted _ ran down around the deck and up the trail,''
Gritz said.
</P>
<P>
   Gritz admitted it was ``strange'' the man came back a second
time. Asked if it was Rudolph, Gritz replied: ``If it wasn't, it
was an excellent imposter.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
