<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MOOD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE NATION'S CAPITAL, A DAY SOMBER AND SURREAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It was a day that made everyone miserable: gray,
drizzly, a muggy oppressive haze contributing to the surrealism.
</P>
<P>
   Russia was on the brink of economic collapse; Iraq continued to
defy the United Nations; a suspect in the devastating embassy
bombings that killed hundreds in Africa, including 12 Americans,
was in custody.
</P>
<P>
   But there was only one issue that commanded the attention of the
media and official Washington on Monday: President Clinton's
unprecedented testimony from the White House via closed-circuit
television to a grand jury probing perjury and obstruction of
justice allegations.
</P>
<P>
   At 12:59 p.m., EDT, a minute earlier than planned, Clinton
entered the historic ground-level Map Room beneath the White House
residence. The Map Room served as President Franklin D. Roosevelt's
situation room during World War II and the maps that plotted global
troop movements still show the allies advancing on Berlin as they
were the day before Roosevelt's death.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly 5 1/2 hours, the president answered questions about
his relationship with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
Later, the president sat in the Map Room again to make his address
to the nation, conceding he misled Americans when he denied a
sexual relationship with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   But throughout the day, the White House remained quiet and
somber.
</P>
<P>
   White House Chief of Staff Erskine Bowles sought to bolster
senior White House aides at their Monday morning meeting with a
saying his father taught him as a child in North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `It's easy to be there for someone when they're up,
but it's the good ones are there when you're down,''' White House
spokesman Mike McCurry said. ``And Erskine told us that we have a
lot of important work to do and the president and the American
people expect us to do our jobs. And I think that reflects the
attitude of the staff here today.''
</P>
<P>
   Many senior staff members kept their dates for scheduled
vacations, adding to the quiet that enveloped the official White
House. The Clintons originally intended to leave for a two-week
break to Martha's Vineyard, Mass., on Saturday but now will leave
today.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the White House, a crowd of cameras, hurried crews and
anxious television anchors gathered at Pebble Beach, the gravel
outcropping on the North Lawn where the television networks are
stationed. The humidity forced television reporters to mop their
faces between takes.
</P>
<P>
   The fevered atmosphere that erupted in January, when the scandal
began, appeared to have dissipated somewhat. But so many reporters
tried to crowd into McCurry's office that his first meeting with
the press was moved to the more formal briefing room.
</P>
<P>
   McCurry described Clinton's mood as ``confident and determined
to tell the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the strangeness was the crowd gathering outside the
White House fence.
</P>
<P>
   A man shouting ``remember Iraq'' tried to puncture his throat
with a screwdriver and was carted away to an ambulance.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you care about Clinton, just remember the Iraqi. Just
remember the Iraqi nation ... gonna die,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of wilting demonstrators dressed in winter coats and
scarves carried placards saying ``Stop the Blizzard of Lies.''
</P>
<P>
   Another man walked back and forth in front of the White House
wearing a bright yellow T-shirt emblazoned on the back, ``Clinton,
Liar, Coward, Adulterer, Perjurer, Traitor.''
</P>
<P>
   CNN initially ran an ``elapsed time'' clock on its programs to
keep track of how long Clinton answered prosecutors' questions but
dropped it as the hours ticked by.
</P>
<P>
   Former staff members continued to offer unsolicited advice on
news programs and in appearances, suggesting that Clinton apologize
to the nation and that Congress and independent counsel Kenneth
Starr begin to put this issue to rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been through seven months of hell. It's weakened the
presidency. It's undermined confidence in our judicial system. It's
bankrupted a lot of staff people who have had to testify. I think
it's challenged families with their kids. And, it's produced
gridlock in Congress,'' said former chief of staff Leon Panetta,
appearing on NBC's ``Today'' show.
</P>
<P>
   And the paradox of Clinton continued: on the lowest day of his
presidency; the president hit his highest approval ratings ever.
</P>
<P>
   Some 70 percent of those polled believe he is doing a good job.
Almost an equal percentage believe he lied about his relationship
with Lewinsky when he denied an affair. And, the stock market,
whose bullish rallies have helped bolster Clinton's popularity,
rose by 149 points.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
