<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALCULATOR-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHOOSING A CALCULATOR NO EASY EQUATION  
 BENNY EVANGELISTA 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRONICLE, PERSONAL TECHNOLOGY   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
If you have a middle or high school student in the house, chances
are you'll be making a calculator purchase in the near future.
<TEXT>
<P>
   We're not talking about a little $10 job that can add, subtract,
multiply and divide.
</P>
<P>
   Sophisticated graphing calculators that cost $50 to $200 and let
students see their complex calculations plotted on a little screen
are becoming de rigueur &UR;  &LR; for students beyond first-year algebra.
</P>
<P>
   More and more schools and universities are requiring graphing
calculators as the devices become integrated into class curriculums
and textbooks.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, the right calculator is the one recommended by
the teacher.
</P>
<P>
   If a math professor, for example, is using the overhead
projector to demonstrate a problem using a Texas Instruments
calculator ``and you're using a Casio, you're own your own,'' said
Megha Shyam, owner of DaVinci Technologies, a Corvallis, Ore.,
developer of calculator-software upgrade programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who take SAT tests are required to have a graphing
calculator,'' Shyam said. ``If you don't have one, you're out of
luck.''
</P>
<P>
   The two leading brands are Texas Instruments and Hewlett
Packard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some engineering schools are recommending the high-end Hewlett
Packard HP 48, but if you're in math and some of the sciences,
you're using the TI,'' Shyam said.
</P>
<P>
   Chance are better, however, that you'll have to buy a TI brand,
the dominant player in a $400 million-per-year U.S. education
calculator market. Texas Instruments aggressively built its market
by providing calculators to professors and schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the education market, they have about 80 percent,'' Shyam
said.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Instruments makes several models of graphing calculators,
starting with the TI-80, which costs about $50.
</P>
<P>
   This is a small calculator for middle school pre-algebra and
algebra I students, said Andy Selle, who helps maintain a Web site
devoted to TI calculators at  &LR; www.ticalc.org. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Selle said the next model up, the TI-83, which costs about $95,
is a better ``workhorse'' for high school students who are taking
algebra I, geometry, algebra II, pre-calculus and calculus.
</P>
<P>
   A comparable model from Hewlett-Packard is the HP 48, which
costs about $100.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard, which has about 15 percent of the U.S.
education calculator market.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Instruments' models can be upgraded by downloading
software via the Internet, Shyam said.
</P>
<P>
   A bigger price tag doesn't necessarily mean you'll get the
calculator you need. However, buyers should try to look at the
calculator as an investment in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I generally recommend buying something you're going to use
beyond the one term in which the calculator is required,'' Shyam
said. ``The calculator is a lot more useful animal than most people
give it credit for.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
