<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTINGQ&AMP;A-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTING Q&AMP;A/DAVID EINSTEIN  
 MAKING FREE PHONE CALLS VIA THE NET 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - PERSONAL TECHNOLOGY   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 Q:  I've heard that you can use the Internet to make 
 long-distance phone calls for free. Is this true, and if so,   how
do you do it? 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; A:  &LR; It's true. Using special telephony software, it's now
possible for people with PCs anywhere in the world to have voice
conversations without paying a phone bill. But don't toss out your
telephone just yet. Internet telephony is a young technology with
some significant drawbacks:
</P>
<P>
   _Because there still is no standard for the technology, both
parties in an Internet call must have the same software loaded on
their PCs. And you'll need a headset or a microphone and speakers.
</P>
<P>
   _You have to arrange things ahead of time because the person
receiving the call has to be online.
</P>
<P>
   _Depending on the speed of your Internet connection, the audio
quality of an Internet call, especially a long-distance one, might
not be up to telephone standards. And you might experience minor
delays in transmission.
</P>
<P>
   You also can make a call from a PC to a regular phone, which
doesn't have to be prearranged. That's not free, but it's still
cheaper than a phone-to-phone call because, for the most part, the
call is routed via the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to give Internet telephony a try, a couple of good
programs are Internet Phone from VocalTec, which lets you make
PC-to-PC or PC-to-phone calls, and Net2Phone, which as the name
implies, is just for calling from a PC to a phone. The software,
along with more information, is available at  &LR; www.vocaltec.com &LR;  and
 &LR; www.net2phone.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q:  &LR; My 9-year-old daughter spends a lot of time on the &LR; 
 &LR; Internet. She's fascinated by such things as Leonardo &LR;   &LR; DiCaprio's
page, the Barbie page, etc. I would like to be able &LR;   &LR; to review the
Web sites she visits to see if she's been to any &LR;   &LR; objectionable
sites and to help me set standards for where she &LR;   &LR; should surf.
Does any software exist for this purpose? I use &LR;   &LR; Netscape 4.  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A:  &LR; Netscape itself can help. The browser keeps a history of
all the pages visited. Go to the Communicator menu and choose
History. You'll see the name of each site visited, its address, the
date it was first visited and last visited, and the total number of
visits. By default, pages stay in the history for nine days, though
you can increase the time with Netscape's Preferences.
</P>
<P>
   You also might consider a software program that blocks
objectionable Web sites. Two popular ones are Cyber Patrol
( &LR; www.cyberpatrol.com &LR; ) and SurfWatch ( &LR; www.surfwatch.com &LR; ).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q:  &LR; I have a Macintosh IIsi that I would like to donate to a &LR; 
 &LR; charity or school. Do you know of an organization that would &LR; 
 &LR; take this machine? It works fine but is obviously out of date.  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A:  &LR; There are a couple of ways to go about donating used PCs
and peripherals. You can go directly to a local school or school
district or call a favorite nonprofit. Or your can go through an
organization that specializes in recycling old equipment. Check out
the PEP Computer Recycling site on the Web at
 &LR; www.microweb.com/pepsite/Recycle &LR;   &LR; /recycleindex.html &LR; . There
you'll find names, phone numbers and descriptions of organizations
across the country that accept computer equipment for distribution
to schools and charities.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q:  &LR; I can't seem to find a way to display my e-mail folders &LR; 
 &LR; on the same screen as my messages in Netscape Communicator. Can &LR; 
 &LR; you tell me how to do that, so I can drag messages between &LR; 
 &LR; folders?  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A:  &LR; As far as I can tell, Communicator doesn't let you view a
list of messages and a directory of mail folders in the same
window. You can display either a Message List window, showing the
contents of a folder such as the Inbox, or the Message Center,
which shows the folders themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, you can easily move messages to another folder. To
move a single message, select it in the Message List window, then
click the File icon on the toolbar and choose the target folder
from the list of folders that appears.
</P>
<P>
   You also can select one or more messages (for multiple messages,
press the Ctrl key while selecting), drag them to the File icon,
then to the target folder.
</P>
<P>
   TIP OF THE WEEK &QC; 
Add an item to your Windows Start menu the easy way: Just drag the
program or shortcut icon to the Start button from the desktop or
from Windows Explorer. Next time you hit the Start button, the
program will be listed and you'll be able to click right to it.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Got a question about computing? E-mail it to computers &LR; sfgate.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
