<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEE-STADIUM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 EVEN 3 MILLION FANS MAY NOT BE ENOUGH FOR YANKEES 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By CHARLES V. BAGLI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Though the New York Yankees are on target to draw a
record 3 million fans to their historic home in the Bronx this
season, a spokesman for George Steinbrenner said Monday that still
may not be good enough to keep his team from moving to Manhattan or
New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Steinbrenner said he would consider keeping the team
in the Bronx if home attendance climbed over the 3 million mark for
the first time in Yankee history and if the Yankees could be
guaranteed similar attendance in future years. The four-game series
with the Texas Rangers that ended Sunday drew more than 200,000
fans, leaving the team well on its way to reaching 3 million for
the season.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the impressive attendance, the Yankees owner appeared to
be edging away from any commitment to stay in the Bronx, which
Steinbrenner complains has insufficient parking and high crime. And
his spokesman, Howard Rubenstein, played down the team's chances of
meeting the goal of 3 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steinbrenner is hoping that they go over the 3 million mark,
but it's a long shot,'' Rubenstein said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has promised that he will sit down and talk about the Bronx
if they go over 3 million. But he's made no commitment to staying
in the Bronx if they do.''
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, the team has drawn 2,109,004 fans, 18 percent
more than last year at this time. That is also 11 percent more than
at the same point in 1988, the best year ever for Yankee home
attendance, which ended with 2,633,703 fans going to the Bronx
stadium. If current trends continue, attendance should surpass 3
million by the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   For the past 11 years, Steinbrenner has kept three mayors and
five governors in two states guessing about where he intends to put
the Yankees when the team's lease at Yankee Stadium expires in
2002. He has signaled his preference for a new billion-dollar
stadium on the West Side of Manhattan or in New Jersey. But he has
yet to announce his plans, despite many self-imposed deadlines for
an announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Yankees are the most valuable team in major-league
baseball and has the most lucrative cable television contract in
professional sports, the team ranks fourth in attendance in the
American League and ninth in the major leagues. Steinbrenner wants
a new, publicly subsidized stadium that he says will draw more fans
and generate more revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Rubenstein said that the Yankees would need a new stadium even
if they decided to stay put.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-98 2245EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
