A8346 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAMBLING-SFCHRON-GAMB     08-17 0542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAMBLING-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLINE GAMBLING LOSSES CHALLENGED  
 BY DAN FOST  
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - GAMBLING   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
   A Marin County woman who is being sued for refusing to pay
$70,000 in online gambling debts is countersuing three credit card
companies on the grounds that wagering on the Internet is illegal.
<TEXT>
<P>
   If her suits are successful, they could rock the already shaky
foundations of the $600 million Internet gambling industry.
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia Haines allegedly used a dozen credit cards to play
craps, blackjack and other online games over a three-month period
early last year. Haines visited over 50 sites, including Cyber
Thrill, Inter Casino and Casinos of the South Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   When she didn't pay her losses, one of her credit card
companies, Providian National Bank, filed a lawsuit to collect the
money.
</P>
<P>
   Haines countersued Providian, as well as Visa International,
MasterCard International and 50 online gaming operators based
outside the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The suit, filed last month in Marin County Superior Court,
charges the credit card companies with illegal business practices
for issuing merchant licenses to the online casinos, said her
lawyer, Ira Rothken of Corte Madera.
</P>
<P>
   By granting merchant accounts to offshore casinos, the credit
card companies are ``essentially ratifying illegal gambling
operations,'' Rothken said.
</P>
<P>
   Internet gambling is illegal in the United States under a 1961
law that bars betting over phone lines. Although it is also illegal
for Americans to gamble in virtual casinos that are based offshore,
individuals are rarely prosecuted for doing so.
</P>
<P>
   A bill passed 90-10 by the U.S. Senate last month would require
Internet service providers to block customer access to virtual
casinos and establish fines and jail sentences for Americans caught
gambling online.
</P>
<P>
   Rothken said some of the offshore casinos ``outright stole
virtual chips'' from Haines. He said Haines sent letters protesting
the charge to Providian, but her letters were ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Rothken described his client as a middle-aged woman, ``involved
in various types of businesses.'' She was not available for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Providian Financial, the San Francisco institution that is the
parent of Providian National Bank, would not directly discuss the
case, but a spokeswoman did address the issues raised.
</P>
<P>
   ``Providian lends money to consumers on the basis of their
credit worthiness, and it expects to be paid back when it makes
loans,'' said spokeswoman Laurie Cole. ``To the extent the customer
incurs a debt, we believe they should bear the responsibility of
paying it back.''
</P>
<P>
   Cole also said that the problem of gambling on the Internet ``is
a concern to a lot of people, us included, and it needs to be
addressed.''
</P>
<P>
   A Visa spokeswoman declined to comment, and no one from
MasterCard was available for comment.
</P>
<P>
   If Haines' lawsuit is successful, it could cause the collapse of
the Internet gambling industry, said I. Nelson Rose, a Whittier
College law professor and American Bar Association expert on
gambling law.
</P>
<P>
   Rose said credit card accounts are the key to betting at
Internet casinos. ``Anything else is too slow,'' Rose said.
``Without credit cards, online gambling is doomed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-98 2247EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
