<SLUG> BC-CANADA-LIVENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIVENT MAY BE REQUIRED TO BUY BACK NEW BONDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MELODY PETERSEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Livent Inc., the company that brought the hit musical
``Ragtime'' to Broadway, may be legally required to buy back $125
million of bonds that it issued just months ago under a
little-noticed provision in its bond agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The provision states that the company must offer to buy back the
bonds at a higher price if the company's founders, Garth Drabinsky
and Myron Gottlieb, no longer manage the company from executive
positions.
</P>
<P>
   The company's new management suspended Drabinsky, the chief
creative director, and Gottlieb, a vice president, last week. The
new management team, headed by the Hollywood power broker Michael
Ovitz, said it had found millions of dollars of accounting
irregularities in the company's books.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Livent said that management believed it could
resolve the issue without having to buy back the bonds at 101
percent of the bonds' principal plus interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not expect the matters disclosed last week to have a
significantly adverse effect on the company's cash flows,'' he
said, ``and we would hope that if this provision is triggered at
some point, we could satisfactorily resolve the situation with our
bondholders.''
</P>
<P>
   Livent, under the leadership of Drabinsky, a flamboyant
impresario known for his extravagant spending habits, has long been
known for its aggressive accounting policies.
</P>
<P>
   Drabinsky and Gottlieb have denied any wrongdoing. And they have
questioned why the company's new management is now bringing their
allegations. They noted that Ovitz had financial experts review the
company's books earlier this year before he bought $20 million of
Livent's stock.
</P>
<P>
   The stock of Livent, a public company based in Toronto, has not
traded since Aug. 7.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-98 2248EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980817.0478 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-17 22:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8351 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-TESTIFY-BOS &LR;      08-17 2333
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TESTIFY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`I MISLED YOU,' CLINTON SAYS, ADMITTING TO LEWINSKY AFFAIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Staring history and the American public in the eye,
President Clinton reversed months of staunch denials Monday night
and admitted to a relationship with former White House intern
Monica S. Lewinsky that he described as ``not appropriate,'' in a
public confession meant to salvage the remainder of a troubled
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, speaking in the Map Room of the White House where he
had testified to a federal grand jury earlier in the day, admitted
that he had misled the nation and his own wife for the past seven
months about his relationship with Lewinsky. He denied, however,
ever pressuring Lewinsky to lie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Indeed, I did have a relationship with Miss Lewinsky that was
not appropriate,'' Clinton said. ``In fact, it was wrong. It
constituted a critical lapse in judgment and a personal failure on
my part for which I am solely and completely responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton added: ``I misled people, including even my wife. I
deeply regret that.''
</P>
<P>
   To the overriding question of whether Clinton attempted to
obstruct justice in the Paula Jones sexual harassment suit, Clinton
said, ``I told the grand jury today and I say to you now that at no
time did I ask anyone to lie, to hide or destroy evidence or to
take any other unlawful action.''
</P>
<P>
   In the five-minute speech, delivered in a voice tightened by
nerves, Clinton also struck back at independent counsel Kenneth W.
Starr, saying the investigation began with his business dealings 20
years ago and has now spread to his private life.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has gone on too long, cost too much and hurt too many
innocent people,'' Clinton said. ``Now this matter is between me,
the two people I love most _ my wife and our daughter _ and our
God. I must put it right, and I am prepared to do whatever it takes
to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   In an age when media consultants and pollsters dominate the
political and public agenda, the testimony, followed by the speech,
provided a stretch of raw political theater unseen in this city
since the resignation of Richard Nixon in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   The speech followed five grueling hours of testimony by Clinton
before the federal grand jury that has investigated his
relationship with Lewinsky since late January.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Clinton provided no details of his relationship
with Lewinsky. A White House official, speaking on the condition of
anonymity, said that Clinton also refused to tell the grand jury
specific details of his physical relationship with Lewinsky, and
for that reason, he may be summoned back before the panel, possibly
by subpoena. To some of the prosecutors' questions, Clinton
provided no answers. To other questions, he was vague.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were very explicit, highly intrusive questions,'' the
official said, speaking on condition of anonymity. ``The president
felt that personal privacy and institutional dignity did not
require a graphic answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Within the White House Monday night, there were crosscurrents of
fury and betrayal _ fury at Starr for the rawness of his handling
of Clinton during the testimony, and betrayal toward Clinton for
allowing his staff to promote what they learned Monday was little
more than a lie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll sort out my own feelings down the road,'' said White
House press secretary Michael McCurry Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Officials confirmed that Starr left open the possibility that he
may summon Clinton before the grand jury again to ascertain
specifics of his relationship with Lewinsky, though David Kendall,
Clinton's personal lawyer, told White House aides that he believed
that prospect was ``highly unlikely.''
</P>
<P>
   In the speech, Clinton seemed to try to put the issue behind
him, although a lengthy report from Starr to the Congress is
expected as early as next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing is more important to me personally,'' Clinton said of
his family life. ``But it is private, and I intend to reclaim my
family life for my family. It's nobody's business but ours. Even
presidents have private lives. It is time to stop the pursuit of
our personal destruction and the prying into private lives and get
on with our national life.''
</P>
<P>
   At 12:25 p.m., a silver sedan paused at the gates to the White
House, then whisked up the drive, carrying independent counsel
Kenneth W. Starr and a pair of deputies toward their encounter with
the president. It marked the culmination of the sometimes far-flung
four-year Whitewater probe and the spinoff investigation into
allegations that Clinton had sexual relations with Lewinsky and
pressured her to lie.
</P>
<P>
   Starr sat in the back seat of his parked car for about two
minutes, then emerged in the shadow of the White House and entered
through the north portico, usually reserved for visiting
dignitaries and heads of state. He was led to the historic Map Room
on the ground floor of the main residence, where President Franklin
Delano Roosevelt plotted troop movements during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   The testimony was itself historic. Never has a sitting president
appeared before a grand jury in a case in which he is the presumed
target, and never has a president been compelled to reveal so much
about his private life and possible criminal activity to
prosecutors and the public that elected him.
</P>
<P>
   The testimony began at 12:59 p.m., when Clinton, accompanied by
his lawyers, arrived downstairs from his private quarters and began
explaining himself to the grand jurors at the federal courthouse a
dozen blocks away. The testimony was broadcast live to the grand
jury by a scrambled video transmission, with cardboard covering the
windows to the grand jury room and court security guards keeping
reporters far from the doorway.
</P>
<P>
   The testimony stretched into early evening. Clinton paused for
several breaks before prosecutors ended the session at 6:25 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   In the dusky gloom of a cloudy Washington evening, Starr,
grim-faced, emerged with his aides, waved a few times to the
collection of reporters gathered outside, then was chauffeured off
in silence.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, Clinton's personal lawyer, David E. Kendall,
strode outside to a waiting microphone, announced the end of the
testimony and took an uncharacteristic swipe at Starr.
</P>
<P>
   ``This afternoon the president voluntarily testified for more
than four hours about his relationship with Ms. Lewinsky and the
questions he was asked about that relationship in the Jones
deposition last January,'' Kendall said. ``He testified truthfully.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hopeful that the president's testimony will finally
bring closure to the independent counsel's more than four-year and
over $40 million investigation, which has culminated in an
investigation of the president's private life,'' Kendall said.
</P>
<P>
   Around Washington and the country Monday, reaction was mixed and
muted, with significant questions remaining over the damage that
Clinton's wholesale reversal has done to the presidency in general
and his own presidency specifically.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Judiciary Committee Chairman Orrin Hatch of Utah again
openly signaled that Clinton's apology would render impeachment
proceedings unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen the American people forgive an awful lot of things,
and I believe they'll forgive him,'' Hatch said at a news
conference in Iowa. ``We're a great nation, and a forgiving
nation.''
</P>
<P>
   But Republican Senator John Ashcroft of Missouri said: ``If he
has subverted the truth, if there are the serious crimes of
perjury, the Congress has a responsibility to impeach.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton remained in the main residence throughout the day
Monday, never venturing to the West Wing and the Oval Office. After
meeting with the Rev. Jesse Jackson late into Sunday night and
early Monday morning, he awoke early and met with his lawyers from
9 to 11:30 a.m. to work out the final details of his testimony.
Shortly after, he received his customary daily briefing from chief
of staff Erskine Bowles and National Security Adviser Samuel
Berger.
</P>
<P>
   At some point in the morning, Clinton presented aides with a
handwritten draft of his proposed national address and ordered them
to refine it, though he declined to tell them if he would
definitely deliver it. For many senior aides who have publicly
defended Clinton in the darkest days of the prior seven months, the
scrawls were his first acknowledgement that he had not told the
truth to the American public.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton testified, aides gathered in the West Wing to
create what they said was the most difficult address of the
presidency _ a speech that, would endure through history and try to
salvage a sense of credibility between Clinton and the American
electorate.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as Starr left the White House, Clinton's political aides
were summoned to the residence, to the upstairs solarium, for their
first full briefing of his relationship with Lewinsky. The group
consisted of Bowles, White House counselors Paul Begala and Doug
Sosnik, senior stategist Rahm Emanuel and deputy chief of staff
John Podesta.
</P>
<P>
   One participant said the meeting was very businesslike. Clinton
did not offer apologies, and no one in the session confronted him
with any accusations or regrets. ``It was neither light nor
heavy,'' said the one official. ``It was all very much business. We
had a job to do.''
</P>
<P>
   For seven months, Clinton refused to discuss his legal problems
with his closest political aides for fear that any information
shared with his senior advisers, who are not protected from a grand
jury subpoena, could be wrung out by Starr. During that silence,
many of those aides had been his staunchest defenders, arguing that
when Clinton made his vehement denials in January, he meant he
never had any kind of sexual contact with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 26, standing in the Roosevelt Room, Clinton glared at
the cameras with a look of pain and anger and said, ``I want to say
one thing to the American people. I want you to listen to me. I'm
going to say this again: I did not have sexual relations with that
woman _ Miss Lewinsky. I never told anybody to lie. Not a single
time. Never. These allegations are false and I need to go back to
work for the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Immediately afterward, his aides heralded his denial as proof of
innocence. ``Sex is sex, even in Washington, I've been assured,''
White House communications director Ann F. Lewis said hours later.
</P>
<P>
   ``He used very plain language and very strong language, and
America knows exactly what he means,'' Begala said on that same
day. ``He did not have a sexual relationship with this woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Emanuel in April: ``Did he have sex? No. Sexual relations?
No.''
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear last night if Clinton sat privately with Hillary
Rodham Clinton and his daughter Chelsea, prior to his testimony and
speech, though aides said that Mrs. Clinton continued to advise her
husband on legal and political strategy right up until Monday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, who arrived at the White House late Sunday night at the
request of Chelsea Clinton, said he met with Clinton's wife and
daughter for nearly two hours before climbing the stairs to
Clinton's private office and talking with him for several minutes
after midnight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that Bill has a sense of embarrassment, that all the
speculation about this has created an embarrassing situation for
him,'' Jackson told reporters Monday. ``Hillary, as the wife,
there's a sense of humiliation.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was originally planning to leave for Martha's Vineyard
and a two-week family vacation on Saturday, but his departure was
delayed for the testimony. White House officials said the family
now plans to fly to the Vineyard sometime today and remain until
Aug. 30.
</P>
<P>
   A person close to Lewinsky declined to say where Lewinsky was
Monday and whether the former White House intern planned to watch
the president's address. Lewinsky has been informed that she could
be called back before the grand jury this week. Lewinsky has made
no plans so far to make a public statement of her own.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts and historians wondered whether Clinton can
salvage the final 2 1/2 years of his second term, or whether he
will spend his time warding off congressional critics while he
tries to recreate a sense of credibility with the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole process has dragged the presidency down in a very
serious way,'' said Sheldon Stern, the head historian at the John
F. Kennedy Library in Boston. ``This is a really significant step
in promoting and legitimizing the cynicism that young people feel
today about politics and government. More and more they're saying
they don't care about politics and democracy, that it has nothing
to do with them. They're saying they're all phonies and frauds and
you can't believe anything they say. If that's going to be Bill
Clinton's legacy, he's going to have a lot to answer for.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvard University presidential scholar Richard Neustadt said
Clinton's reversal may strengthen the precedent set by the
Watergate break-in and cover-up in the early 1970s, which caused
significant public distrust in government and its leaders. Still,
he said the issue of sex was a relative wild card that could not
yet be measured and may create a different, or indifferent, dynamic
within the electorate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe this is just a different category, where lying about sex
is different,'' Neustadt said. ``And you can't create a credibility
gap when you lie about sex. It is crummy, but it may not be serious
in the way the other things came to be serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Neustadt: ``If there's a public reaction, it will be a
slow burn. You're not going to know tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   White House officials appeared heartened Monday by public
opinion polls that put Clinton's approval ratings near all-time
highs and showed that most Americans already believed Clinton was
lying when he had said he did not have a sexual relationship with
Lewinsky.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
