<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-17 22:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8352 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-FRIENDS-1STLD     08-17 0603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-FRIENDS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-700(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON FRIENDS, AIDES ADMIT FEELINGS OF BETRAYAL, ANGER,
HUMILIATION  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to tighten lead, add attribution)   By RICHARD L. BERKE and DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Before he addressed the grand jury and then the
nation, President Clinton called in some of his closest aides over
the weekend, associates said, and, one by one, he told them that
the accusation they had steadfastly denied for months was true: he
had had an improper relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The meetings, which took place on Saturday and Sunday, were
described by close Clinton associates as informal and involving
only some aides. And only in some cases, they said, did Clinton
express regret for his conduct.
</P>
<P>
   After seven months of public denials and private anguish over
the inquiry by Kenneth Starr, it was those conversations that
helped Clinton fully come to terms with the toll the sex scandal
has wrought on his friends and on his presidency, two people close
to him said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hit him hardest on Sunday,'' one close friend said. ``This
was a very, very difficult weekend for him. Nothing is more
important to him than his place in history. He is worried that this
investigation will eclipse everything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Even late last week while Clinton's associates were telling
reporters that he might acknowledge having had sexual relations
with Ms. Lewinsky, the friend said he was still ``in denial.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Four days ago,'' he said, ``the president told me he never had
sex with Monica.''
</P>
<P>
   Some who met with the president _ and who had stood loyally by
the president _ expressed feelings of betrayal and humiliation,
people close to Clinton said. One friend said that there was ``a
lot of disappointment'' and that it was the aides' reaction that
was most distressing to the president, leading him to ``beat
himself up.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if the American public forgives Clinton for bending the
truth in explaining his relationship with Ms. Lewinsky, he now
faces a problem closer to home: repairing relations with aides,
friends and Cabinet members who for months have adamantly, and
publicly, defended him. Collectively, these people face hundreds of
thousands of dollars in legal bills related to the investigations
that have punctuated his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Michael McCurry, the White House press secretary, was
unequivocal when the Lewinsky matter first became public,
declaring: ``The president is outraged by these allegations. He's
never had any improper relationship with this women.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday, asked whether he feels misled, McCurry sidestepped the
question, saying he was still figuring out how he felt. But he
seemed to acknowledge his discomfort.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not so self-preoccupied to be thinking about how I feel,''
he said in an interview. ``I think it's important that the
president talk to the American people, because whatever position
I'm in, they're in much the same position. I'm sure all the rest of
us will sort out how we feel in due course.''
</P>
<P>
   Lanny Davis, an adviser outside the White House who has been one
of the most aggressive Clinton defenders, spoke of his
disappointment in an interview Monday night. ``My disappointment is
not personal,'' he said. ``I'm a friend and a supporter, and I will
stand by him in a difficult time like this. My disappointment is
that his presidency should be judged as a great one and we've got
to work even harder now for his legacy because of what happened.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Besides Hillary Rodham Clinton, who ridiculed the accusations as
the product of a ``vast right-wing conspiracy,'' Clinton's most
unwavering defenders include Ann Lewis, the communications director
who for years has been close to Mrs. Clinton, and two senior aides
who have been with Clinton since the 1992 campaign, Paul Begala and
Rahm Emanuel.
</P>
<P>
   Asked Monday night whether he feels betrayed, Emanuel said:
``This guy is dealing with something very personal. He is taking
responsibility for it. Where I come from you don't choose high and
low moments around your friends. I'm a staff person and I'm going
to be loyal to him. He and I have a history together.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewis, who had insisted that Clinton was not making any
distinctions between different forms of sex, said in January: ``Sex
is sex. Even in Washington, I've been assured.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, Ms. Lewis refused to talk about her own feelings
about the president, saying: ``I'm not going to go there. It is
more appropriate today for people to hear the president.''
</P>
<P>
   The highest profile members of the administration, no doubt,
will also be sorting out their feelings. In January, Clinton
assured his Cabinet he was innocent, and Madeleine Albright, the
secretary of state, stepped out onto the White House driveway to
back him up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the allegations are completely untrue,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll second that. Definitely,'' said William Daley, the
commerce secretary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Third it,'' said Donna Shalala, the secretary of health and
human services.
</P>
<P>
   The last seven months have been particularly trying for some of
Clinton's defenders who, speaking on the condition of anonymity,
said they suspected he was guilty but pressed on, or tried to
convince themselves of his innocence, not wanting to abandon him.
Some, like Jack Quinn, a former White House counsel, have been
careful to preface their defenses of Clinton with phrases like,
``If he says he didn't do this, I believe him.''
</P>
<P>
   Leon Panetta, Clinton's former chief of staff, said of the
defenders, ``Whatever their inner suspicions, they went out
there.'' Panetta said he had spoken with some current White House
aides whose only solace Monday was that their ordeal might finally
be ending.
</P>
<P>
   Panetta, who was also Clinton's budget director and a longtime
Congressman from California, said he was personally disappointed in
the President. But most of all, he said, Clinton owes his staff
``an eye-to-eye'' apology.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to hang your staff out there with false
statements,'' Panetta said. ``When you're asked to spin something
that's not truthful, that's where you have to draw the line.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as Clinton acknowledged Monday night that he misled the
public, some of his defenders refused to back down. ``He did it to
protect his family,'' said Mandy Grunwald, a Democratic media
consultant. ``And it's none of our business.''
</P>
<P>
   People close to Clinton said that this weekend he fully realized
the profound effect his grand jury appearance could have on his
legacy, and that he seemed sad about that _ and still angry at
Starr.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had to deal with the mixed emotions of relief and anger and
remorse,'' said one close associate of Clinton. ``He's angry that
it has come to this.''
</P>
<P>
   The associate said that Clinton relied particularly on Mrs.
Clinton this weekend to keep up his spirits. She was described as
focused on the task before them, preparing for the grand jury's
questions to Clinton and for his address to the nation.
</P>
<P>
   There has been a perceptible shift in tone in recent weeks among
Clinton's staunchest defenders, particularly at the White House.
Aides have been less energetic in defending Clinton and in
condemning Starr.
</P>
<P>
   George Stephanopoulos, Clinton's former senior adviser who for
months has spoken out about his behavior, said he expected the
president's defenders to become more angry as time wore on. ``I can
imagine in the short run being numb by the crush of events,'' he
said. ``A kind of battle fatigue takes over. Where it may get
difficult is in the coming days when people have to confront what
happened and go on.''
</P>
<P>
   For some, the anger is already out in the open. Dee Dee Myers,
Clinton's former press secretary, said: ``I feel disappointed in
him; I'm angry.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He put people through hell, including the staff and people who
are my friends,'' she said. ``The president has to apologize or
they have to quit. The president has to be truly, truly contrite.
I'm sure he didn't intend to hurt or embarrass them. But he did.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
