<HEADLINE>
LEADERS OF MILLION YOUTH MARCH ASSAIL MAYOR AND PRESS AHEAD
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By ABBY GOODNOUGH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Taking another step toward a showdown with Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani, organizers of a planned Million Youth March in
Harlem said Monday that they would seek a federal judge's
permission for the event but that the march would take place no
matter what.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor himself took a new tack in the confrontation Monday,
accusing the news media of hyping the event even as he tried to
play down its significance.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's pronouncements were the latest volleys in a weeks-long
battle over the planned march. Organizers have billed the event as
a show of unity and strength by young blacks, but the mayor has
denounced it as a ``hate march,'' citing anti-Semitic and
anti-white remarks by the main organizer, Khalid Abdul Muhammad.
With the proposed march less than three weeks away, neither side
has shown any inclination to retreat.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at two news conferences in Harlem, the organizers
stepped up their criticism of Giuliani and said they were going to
court because the city's refusal to grant them a permit was
unconstitutional. City officials have denied Muhammad a permit to
hold the rally on Sept. 5, a Saturday, on Malcolm X Boulevard,
saying the neighborhood cannot safely accommodate the 1 million
participants the organizers say they expect.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, who has fiercely criticized the Million Youth March in
recent weeks, refused to discuss it Monday. Instead, he complained
that reporters have written too much about the planned event.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you've really paid way too much attention to it,''
Giuliani said at a morning news conference. ``I pay very little
attention to it. This is a media creation more than anything
else.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it was largely Giuliani who drew reporters' attention
to the march in the first place. At several recent news
conferences, he pointed to Muhammad's anti-Semitic statements and
questioned why newspapers had not printed them. He also criticized
news organizations for not reporting what he considered one of the
most disturbing aspects of the planned march: that the organizers
planned to bring gang members from across the country to New York
City.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Al Sharpton, who has endorsed the concept of the march,
on Monday assailed the mayor's handling of the issue, saying
Giuliani's harsh criticism and efforts to stop the march have
created deep resentments. ``When he said he was going to stop the
march and called it a hate march, I think that was very
provocative,'' Sharpton said. ``The mayor's statements have created
a climate that could possibly lead to some kind of confrontation.''
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad, a former senior aide to Louis Farrakhan, leader of the
Nation of Islam, did not attend either Harlem news conference
Monday. He and other organizers have said that the march, involving
black teen-agers from across the country, was modeled after the
1995 Million Man March in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The city has offered Randalls Island and Van Cortlandt Park in
the Bronx as alternative locations for the march. It has also
recommended Sept. 19 as a more suitable date to avoid conflicts
with parades and other community events already scheduled for the
Labor Day weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad has called that later date and the locations the city
has offered `'totally unacceptable.'' He has also vowed to hold the
event on Sept. 5 in Harlem or in the Crown Heights section of
Brooklyn as a ``direct confrontation with the Jews of that area.''
</P>
<P>
   But city officials said Monday that when the organizers first
applied for a permit last winter, they asked to march on Sept. 19,
on Malcolm X Boulevard, on Eastern Parkway in Brooklyn or on
Randalls Island. Organizers did not return telephone calls seeking
an explanation Monday afternoon.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Muhammad was dismissed by the Nation of Islam as its spokesman
in 1994 after a 1993 speech in which he referred to Jews as
bloodsuckers and made other inflammatory remarks against Roman
Catholics, whites and homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   But he has continued making anti-Semitic statements. In a speech
last year he said: ``There is absolutely no evidence to
substantiate, to prove that 6 million so-called Jews lost their
lives in Nazi Germany.'' In the same speech, at San Francisco State
University, Muhammad said: `'Who's pimping the world? The hairy
hands of the Zionist in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Roger Wareham, a lawyer for the organizers of the march, said he
thought that the courts would be on their side. He said the
organizers would seek an injunction in U.S. District Court in
Manhattan on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a human rights issue,'' he said, ``and it's simply the
right of young people in their own community to assemble and to
exercise their right to freedom of speech and freedom of
association.''
</P>
<P>
   Malik Zulu Shabazz, a lawyer who is one of the primary
organizers of the march, said gang members would indeed be coming
from around the country, but that the march will be peaceful.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're bringing so-called gang members here to show that they
can put down the foolishness and the fratricide and the bloodshed
and the violence,'' he said. ``Why can't we as a black community
now take those who you consider to be criminal or gangsters or
thugs, why can't we use these young men as a foundation for
resurrecting the interests of our community and rebuilding our new
world order?''
</P>
</TEXT>
