<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-17 23:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8362 &Cx1f; paxxx
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-REACT-PA     08-17 0422
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-REACT-PA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        SPECTER, SANTORUM HOLDING DOUBT ON CLINTON
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Paul Kane  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Aug. 17 -- As President Clinton tried to put the
Lewinsky scandal behind him, Sen. Arlen Specter said he had some
serious concerns about how the president handled his testimony and
suggested the matter could be headed for congressional inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Specter, R-Pa., said he was very troubled by the legalistic way
the president described his testimony during the extraordinary
nationally televised speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's one we can accept at face value,'' he said
after the speech on CNN's ``Larry King Live.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said his ``inappropriate'' relationship did not
constitute perjury in the Paula Corbin Jones case, when he
testified under oath that he did not have ``sexual relations'' with
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also refused to answer questions that involved sexual
acts with Lewinsky. Those questions, Specter said, could be ``real
critical issues'' in determining if the president did have ``sexual
relations'' -- as defined in a written statement before his January
testimony -- and therefore committed perjury.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to know the facts and go through the constitutional
process,'' Specter said. He said he hopes Starr will send a report
to Congress by the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could be going on and on,'' Specter said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Murtha, D-Johnstown, was not available for comment
because he is traveling in Saudi Arabia on a fact-finding mission,
and Rep. Bud Shuster, R-Everett, was not available for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Some members of the Pennsylvania delegation remained behind
Clinton, despite his admission that he had not told the truth in
January. Rep. Chaka Fattah, D-Phila., said there was no taste in
Congress to take up impeachment hearings if Starr's report is based
solely on perjury in sex-related matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is dead in the water in Congress,'' Fattah said. ``If
that's at the basis of all this, I think it's an embarrassment to
Starr and the Republican Party.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Rick Santorum, R-Pa., said that the issue would focus
on perjury, not private sex acts. ``It's important for the
president to do what every other citizen of this country is bound
to do -- that is, when you raise your right hand and swear to tell
the truth, (you) tell the truth. The whole truth. And nothing but
the truth,'' Santorum said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything less from the president,'' Santorum added, ``would be
a slap in the face to the American justice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
