u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-HARASS-SUIT-450&AMP;AD     08-17 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-HARASS-SUIT-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY FINDS LAWYER WAS HARASSED BY BOSS AT NEW JERSEY AGENCY 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ Ending a sexual harassment case that had
tarnished the image of New Jersey's most powerful law enforcement
agency, a state jury awarded $350,000 Monday to a former assistant
attorney general who said her boss had made inappropriate sexual
advances and lewd comments about women in the office and had
touched her breasts and buttocks.
</P>
<P>
   After deliberating for less than two days, the jury ruled that
Barbara Davis, 40, had been subjected to ``severe, pervasive and
unwelcome'' harassment by her supervisor, Richard T. Carley, the
former deputy director of the division of criminal justice.
</P>
<P>
   The Mercer County jury, composed of five men and five women,
also found that the state had failed to investigate her complaints
aggressively in 1993. The judge forbade the jurors to speak,
because they still had to deliberate next month on whether to
assess punitive damages against Carley, 51.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict came after an eight-week trial that offered an
unflattering portrait of the state's criminal justice division in
the early 1990s, with some testimony describing it as a unit rife
with the machismo of a boy's high school locker room.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses testified that male supervisors made crude passes at
their female subordinates, decorated their offices with photos of
bikini-clad models and a statue of a penis, and made salacious
comments about the body parts of female murder victims in grisly
crime scene photos.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Davis said the harassment forced her to quit her
$50,000-a-year job in 1993, and said the stress of the legal battle
contributed to the failure of her marriage. Although the state may
appeal the verdict, Ms. Davis said the award _ $300,000 in back
wages and $50,000 for emotional distress _ should send a message
that such conduct is unacceptable, even in the traditionally
male-dominated world of law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have been happy with anything that they gave me, even
a dollar, as long as they came back with a verdict that said you're
credible,'' Ms. Davis said Monday. ``Because, believe me, it
happened, and we're going to make it stop. It's going to stop now.
There's a sexual harassment hot line now so no more women will have
to go through this.''
</P>
<P>
   The case was the third in the past year in which a high-ranking
state official was charged with workplace harassment.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Gov. Christie Whitman was widely criticized for
agreeing to pay, at taxpayers' expense, the legal fees of former
Assembly Speaker Garabed ``Chuck'' Haytaian, who was accused of
harassing a female employee. That case was settled and cost
taxpayers $345,000.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey officials also paid the legal bills of Harold
Berkowitz, a former supervisor in the office of legislative
services, who was the target of a sexual harassment complaint that
was eventually settled for $347,000.
</P>
<P>
   Legal fees for Carley will cost the state more than $1 million,
in addition to the $350,000 in damages awarded Monday. Some
Democrats said the case highlighted the need to strengthen the law
to shield both female employees and New Jersey taxpayers. &QL;
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``We have to have policy in place that protects employees and
make sure the state does not enable a hostile work environment,''
said Assemblywoman Loretta Weinberg, D-Teaneck. ``And we have to
have a policy in place to protect taxpayers so we are not paying
out settlements that we should not be paying out for defending
people who shouldn't be defended.''
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia Jacob, the lawyer who represented the state in the case,
said New Jersey already had a thorough policy prohibiting workplace
harassment. Attorney General Peter Verniero, who took office in
1996, said that any of the offensive conduct described in the
testimony would not be tolerated today.
</P>
<P>
   ``The picture of the division of criminal justice alleged in
this lawsuit does not reflect the current atmosphere or management
of the division,'' Verniero said.
</P>
<P>
   Carley declined to discuss Monday's verdict, but during
testimony he denied touching Ms. Davis. In a preliminary
investigation by the state attorney general's office, he did
acknowledge making crude remarks about women other than Ms. Davis.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of that investigation, the state transferred Carley
to the division of alcoholic beverage control in 1994, stripped him
of his supervisory powers and cut his pay by $10,000 per year, Ms.
Jacob said.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Jacob argued that Ms. Davis failed to notify the proper
authorities and said Ms. Davis' lawyers had overstated the sexually
suggestive nature of the office decorations. She said that there
were only two photos of bathing beauties and that the statue of a
penis was actually a fertility symbol that had been given to Ms.
Davis' supervisor, Gregory Sakowicz, by his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jacob also suggested Ms. Davis was motivated by money and
only filed her complaint after she was passed over for a promotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're judging with 1998 glasses something that happened in
1993,'' Ms. Jacob said. ``There has been an evolution in the law
since then, although I think the state handled it appropriately in
any event.''
</P>
<P>
   During the trial, Carley's lawyer, Donald Belsole, said that his
client had a habit of making suggestive comments, but that he was
not abusive or malicious. ``His bark was worse than his bite,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors will reconvene in mid-September to weigh possible
punitive damages against Carley, but the judge has already ruled
that the state is not liable for punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Davis, a spokesman for Verniero, said Carley would have to
pay his own legal expenses in that phase of the case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
