<SLUG> BC-STATES-CONG-PA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        FATTAH, A BELIEVER UNTIL THE END
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Paul Kane  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Aug. 17 -- U.S. Rep. Chaka Fattah was a true
believer until the end.
</P>
<P>
   Fattah, D-Phila., despite streams of reports over the weekend
that President Clinton would change his story, said he fully
expected the president to stand by his original claim: ``I did not
have sexual relations with that woman.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing that I've seen that he's moving away from
that,'' Fattah said early Monday afternoon, just as Clinton was
beginning to do just that.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the seven-month, sex-and-lies scandal, Fattah
steadfastly said he believed Clinton's original denials, avoiding
the sort of lawyerly defenses offered by the likes of former White
House counsel Lanny Davis. Davis often told TV audiences that even
if the affair was true it didn't rise to the level of ``high crime
and misdemeanor'' calling for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``On this matter, the president's been very straight forward,''
Fattah reiterated Monday. ``I'll deal with the facts as they
come.''
</P>
<P>
   By Monday night, it was clear Fattah, and the nation, had not
been originally told the facts. And the fallout on Capitol Hill
remained unclear.
</P>
<P>
   While Fattah said any case against Clinton based solely on
perjury related to sex was ``dead in the water in Congress'', Sen.
Arlen Specter, R-Pa., said he was very troubled by the president's
refusal to answer certain questions by Independent Counsel Kenneth
Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton refused to answer questions that involved his sexual
acts with Lewinsky, questions that Specter said could be ``real
critical issues'' to determining if the president engaged in
``sexual relations'' and therefore comitted perjury.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to know the facts and go through the constitutional
process,'' Specter said on CNN's ``Larry King Live''. He said he
hopes Starr will send a report to Congress by the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could be going on and on,'' Specter said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bob Borski, D-Phila., is out of town on vacation and not
available for comment. Rep. Bob Brady, D-Phila., did not comment.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Rick Santorum, R-Pa., said that the issue would focus on
perjury, not private sex acts. ``It's important for the president
to do what every other citizen of this country is bound to do --
that is, you raise your right hand and swear to tell the truth,
(you) tell the truth. The whole truth. And nothing but the truth,''
Santorum said.
</P>
<P>
   But Fattah remained confident that Clinton would not have agreed
to testify before the grand jury unless he was certain he had his
legal background covered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the president's stupid,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
