</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DAMATO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
D'AMATO'S APPEARANCE WITH GINGRICH SURPRISES DEMOCRATS 
</HEADLINE>
 - GINGRICH-NYT  
 (ATTN: Ga.)  (mk) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., has agreed to allow House Speaker
Newt Gingrich to hold a fund-raiser in Georgia on his behalf
Tuesday, even as his prospective Democratic challengers have sought
to hurt D'Amato by repeatedly linking him to Gingrich's policies.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato's decision to fly to Georgia and appear with Gingrich at
the event was a surprise, if a pleasant one, to the three major
candidates for the Democratic nomination to oppose D'Amato this
fall.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, Rep. Charles Schumer of Brooklyn had been
planning to begin using a new television advertisement Tuesday that
for the first time directly linked D'Amato to Gingrich and to what
the commercial describes as the speaker's attempt to reduce
Medicare benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``A coincidence,'' Schumer said.
</P>
<P>
   The fund-raiser, which will cost $1,000 a head, is to be held at
a country club in Gingrich's hometown, Marietta. Aides to D'Amato
and Gingrich were unable to provide an estimate of how much D'Amato
expects the event to bring in.
</P>
<P>
   The fund-raiser itself will not be open to journalists. D'Amato
did not announce the event, which was first reported in a column by
Robert Novak and was confirmed Monday by D'Amato's advisers.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato's prospective opponents _ Schumer, Mark Green and
Geraldine Ferraro _ have made it clear that they would seek to use
D'Amato's association with Gingrich against him this fall. As a
result, several Democratic strategists said they were surprised
that D'Amato, who is known for his political astuteness, had agreed
to this fund-raiser just when attention to the campaign was
beginning to increase.
</P>
<P>
   The Gingrich fund-raiser does not appear to be a sign that the
senator has any financial difficulties. D'Amato has already raised
$20 million, about twice as much as his nearest possible rival, and
has about $12 million on hand to spend. He has had a steady stream
of television advertisements on the air recently.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato's campaign spokesman, Harvey Valentine, said Gingrich
had offered to sponsor a fund-raiser for D'Amato when they ran into
each other a few months ago. He said D'Amato was not concerned
about the event being used against him. ``You know, the senator has
made his disagreements with the speaker known,'' Valentine said.
``When it's appropriate, we'll continue to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the fact that D'Amato decided to go to Marietta for the
event rather than invite Gingrich to New York suggested that he was
not looking for much attention.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, D'Amato's political associate, Gov. George Pataki,
who is also up for re-election, has repeatedly gone out of his way
this year to distance himself from Gingrich. And the governor has
often criticized Gingrich for policies that Pataki said hurt the
Republican Party, especially in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer's aides, who viewed the joint appearance as the
political equivalent of a hanging curveball, quickly produced a
list of quotes from Gingrich from over the years that were critical
of New York. ``These guys are two peas in a pod,'' Schumer said.
``D'Amato went along with all of Gingrich's cuts on Medicare, so
now Gingrich is giving him his reward.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Green, Joe DePlasco, said the planned
fund-raiser demonstrated that ``as much as D'Amato tries to show
that `I'm a new D'Amato,' there's nothing new here. He's the same
old conservative D'Amato.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro's communications director, Stephen Gaskill, also seized
on news of the event, saying that it was ``not surprising that
D'Amato has a close relationship with Newt Gingrich, given the way
that both of them vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich's political spokesman, Michael Shields, ridiculed the
criticism, saying it came from ``liberal Democrats appealing to the
far left wing of their base by bashing a leading Republican.'' He
added, ``His opponents have not read any of the recent poll numbers
that show the speaker's approval ratings are much higher than they
used to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Shields said the speaker had offered to help D'Amato as a sign
of his regard for D'Amato, who is chairman of the Senate Banking
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The speaker and Senator D'Amato are good friends,'' he said.
``We want to make sure that we have a strong Senate and a strong
chairman of that committee. As we pass bills in the House, we want
to make sure we get them through the Senate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
