<HEADER>
A8500 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-USC-NOTES-LADN     08-17 0461
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QB THOMAS SAYS HE'LL STAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVINE _ By the end of Monday morning's practice, USC freshman
quarterback Jason Thomas was set to transfer.
</P>
<P>
   He told his father. He told USC coach Paul Hackett. He told his
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett told Thomas to take the afternoon practice off and meet
with his parents before making a decision.
</P>
<P>
   That meeting, along with an earlier individual meeting with
Hackett, prompted Thomas to decide he would stay at USC _ for now.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a time I wanted to transfer this morning,'' Thomas
said. ``This morning was the closest I ever came. I don't want to
say how close I was. It's rough. I told my father I was
transferring.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that kept me from transferring is I didn't want
to be a quitter.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas has been frustrated that he fell behind sophomore Mike
Van Raaphorst and freshman Carson Palmer so early in training camp.
</P>
<P>
   This was confirmed Monday when Hackett told Thomas during their
meeting that he was the No.3 quarterback. The player-coach meeting
actually helped settle down the highly touted freshman, who has
been hobbled by an ankle injury during training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I'm the No.3 quarterback because I didn't prepare
myself,'' Thomas said. ``I'm a couple pounds overweight. I paid the
price for it. After the (ankle) injury, I put on a lot of weight.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas said he entered camp weighing 232 pounds, and he would
ideally play at around 210.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett attributed Thomas' frustration to the ankle injury, the
result of scar tissue remaining from the fracture Thomas suffered
during his senior year at Dominguez.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is the injury. He can only practice once a day,''
Hackett said. ``It's hard for him. He's so competitive. This guy's
got four years to put up with me. They want to make an impact
immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas said he plans to redshirt this year, unless injuries
allow him to play. He said he refuses to switch positions, because
he said it would be like quitting.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson to linebacker: Junior David Gibson, who was battling
Grant Pearsall at safety, has been switched to starting weakside
linebacker. He'll replace freshman Darryl Knight, who was tentative
in Saturday's scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to put our best 11 guys on the field,'' Hackett
said. ``We did not move him with the idea he is a backup.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Pearsall injured his knee Monday morning but is
expected to be OK. It is not the same knee that Pearsall underwent
reconstructive surgery on last year. He did not practice Monday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   In another move, freshman defensive tackle Robby Wood has been
switched to offensive line.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-17-98 2317EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
