u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-ROYALS-NYT &LR;      08-17 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ROYALS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONE AND YANKEES BLITZ ROYALS, 7-1  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ David Cone is closer to his 50th birthday
than his high school graduation. Lines that didn't exist 10 years
ago cut across his face and neck when it's hot and he is straining
to get outs.
</P>
<P>
   But in his 35th summer, Cone is having perhaps the best season
of his career, and after he and the New York Yankees beat the
Kansas City Royals Monday night, 7-1, he is just two victories shy
of 20 _ which leaves Cone on the verge of accomplishing something
no one has in modern major-league history.
</P>
<P>
   Cone won 20 games for the Mets in 1988, the first and last time
Cone reached that mark. With two more victories, he would be the
first pitcher ever to go nine years between 20-victory seasons,
according to STATS, Inc. Jim Kaat, currently a Yankee broadcaster,
holds the existing record. Kaat went seven years between 20-victory
seasons: Kaat was 25-13 for the Minnesota Twins in 1966, and did
not win 20 again until he went 21-13 for the Chicago White Sox in
1974.
</P>
<P>
   Bernie Williams, Tim Raines and Tino Martinez each hit home runs
to support Cone, Martinez breaking open the game against the
Royals' Jose Rosado (6-9) with a three-run homer in the fifth
inning. The Yankees are 91-30, on a pace to win 121 games, and they
lead the American League East by 20 games, over Boston, the
Yankees' biggest lead since 1941.
</P>
<P>
   In the nine years since Cone last won 20 games, he has lived a
nomadic baseball existence, leaving the Mets for Kansas City, on to
Toronto and then the Yankees. He came to be familiar with aneurysms
and arthroscopic shoulder surgery as he struggled to stay healthy
through the 1996 and 1997 seasons. Now he is 18-4, the majors'
first 18-game winner this season, and a Cy Young Award candidate,
competing with Boston's Pedro Martinez and teammate David Wells.
</P>
<P>
   Mel Stottlemyre was the pitching coach for the Mets in 1988, and
he is Cone's pitching coach now. ``He's had the type of season
where you win 20 games,'' Stottlemyre said before Monday's game,
explaining how, early in the season, the Yankees scored lots of
runs for Cone when he wasn't pitching well, enabling him to win.
``Things always have to break right for someone to put up those big
numbers and win 20 games, no matter who it is. Right now, he's in a
good groove, and with the number of starts he has left, he should
get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitching in his hometown Monday night and in the hot and humid
conditions he has come to love, Cone struggled with his control
early in the game, his fastball riding high and command of his
split-fingered fastball eluding him. A walk and a double in the
first inning and the Royals had runners at second and third and one
out.
</P>
<P>
   But Cone bore down, sweat glistening on the sides of his face
and in the hollow below his Adam's apple. Chewing gum nervously, he
stopped his jaw when he looked in for a sign, and then attacked.
David Palmer struck out on a fastball that singed the edge of the
strike zone and Terry Pendleton grounded out.
</P>
<P>
   With the Yankees holding a narrow lead in the third, Cone walked
two and allowed a hit to fill the bases, and again he pitched out
of trouble. In the first seven innings, the Royals were 1 for 6
with runners in scoring position, stranding eight runners as the
Yankees' offense finally steamrolled them.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees were vulnerable to left-handed pitching for most of
June and into July, when Williams was out with a knee injury. But
Williams has come back and Derek Jeter has matured as a hitter and
now the switch-hitting Davis can be the designated hitter against
left-handers, and now the Yankees' attack is quite potent against
left-handers.
</P>
<P>
   Through games of Saturday, in fact, the Yankees' lineup included
the American League's top four batting averages against lefties:
Jorge Posada (.370), Jeter (.368), Scott Brosius (.363) and
Williams (.359).
</P>
<P>
   Those numbers improved against Rosado Monday night. Leading off
the second inning, Williams _ who closed Sunday's victory against
the Rangers at Yankee Stadium with an upper deck home run _ crushed
a fastball some 421 feet to center field, onto the grassy knoll
beyond the fence.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Girardi singled in the fifth and Jeter walked, bringing
Davis to the plate with two outs. Rosado had struck out Davis with
fastballs in his first two at-bats _ Davis, like most older
players, sometimes cannot catch up to a high fastball _ and Rosada
started Davis with a high fastball in the fifth, missing high.
</P>
<P>
   Rosado then made the mistake of throwing the ball low; Davis
ripped a single to left-center, Girardi rounding third and scoring
the Yankees' second run. Williams followed that with an RBI single
before Martinez launched his three-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
