<DOCNO> NYT19980817.0493 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-17 23:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8504 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-RDP-1STLD-WRI     08-17 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-RDP-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-1,300(3TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON, IN ADDRESS TO NATION, ACKNOWLEDGES RELATIONSHIP WITH
LEWINSKY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs 8th thru 12th grafs for new material concerning Clinton's
speech and testimony.)  (Also see: CLINTON-PSYCHE, CLINTON-PROCESS, CLINTON-HILLARY,
CLINTON-FRIENDS, CLINTON-GORE, CLINTON-SCENE, CLINTON-LEGAL,
CLINTON-MEDIA, CLINTON-ASSESS, CLINTON-REACT.) 
(ART ADV: Two photos have been sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual puorchases by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(sw) 
 By JAMES BENNET   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hemmed in by prosecutors and reaching for political
forgiveness, President Clinton testified for more than four hours
at the White House on Monday before admitting in an extraordinary
address to the nation hat he had carried on a relationship with a
former White House intern that he said was ``not appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   In his address, Clinton did not directly acknowledge a sexual
affair with the intern, Monica Lewinsky, after seven months of
emphatic denials. But he said, ``I did have a relationship with Ms.
Lewinsky that was not appropriate. In fact it was wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he had misled his wife, but added: ``It is private, it
is nobody's business but ours. Even presidents have private
lives.''
</P>
<P>
   The details of Clinton's testimony were not immediately
disclosed. But his lawyer, David Kendall, issued a brief statement
describing Clinton's liaison with Ms. Lewinsky as ``inappropriate
contact.'' It also appeared that Clinton declined to give detailed
answers about some aspects of the relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made the painful admission that he had inappropriate
contact with Ms. Lewinsky,'' Kendall said. ``As to a very few
highly intrusive questions with respect to the specifics of this
contact, in order to preserve personal privacy and institutional
dignity, he gave candid, but not detailed answers.''
</P>
<P>
   In testifying and then speaking to the public, Clinton tried the
riskiest high-wire act of his career, trying to balance legal and
political burdens. Two days short of his 52nd birthday, he sought
to protect his presidency and elude legal jeopardy by acknowledging
an intimate relationship in the White House with a subordinate less
than half his age.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had been working on the brief public speech for several
days, his advisers said, operating on the belief that Americans
were not interested in the details of his relationship with Ms.
Lewinsky but did want him to own up to having made mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   While the public focus on Monday was on sex as the airwaves
filled with chatter about the president, little was learned about
the less titillating but legally more threatening question of
whether Clinton tried to obstruct justice by possibly covering up
the relationship. He has denied that accusation, which associates
of Kenneth Starr, the Whitewater independent counsel, has said is
at the center of the inquiry by the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I told the grand jury today,'' Clinton said in his address
on Monday night, ``and I say to you now that at no time did I ask
anyone to lie, to hide or destroy evidence, or to take any other
unlawful action.'' He concluded his public speech by saying, ``It
is past time to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   The president seemed defiant toward Starr, and his grand jury
session was described as very contentious.
</P>
<P>
   He told the grand jurors that he did not obstruct justice, and
said that his relationship with Ms. Lewinsky did not constitute sex
under the definition used in the sexual misconduct case filed by
Paula Jones, according to a lawyer familiar with his testimony. As
a result, he argued, he did not commit perjury in denying an
affair.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's prosecutors informed Clinton that they might subpoena
him again if he did not answer their questions, and his lawyers
responded that they might fight such a subpoena. Beginning at 12:59
p.m., Clinton met with prosecutors in the Map Room on the ground
floor of the White House. His testimony was videotaped and
transmitted by live closed-circuit television to a grand jury at
the federal courthouse, just blocks away.
</P>
<P>
   While his lawyers were also in the room, Clinton sat alone in a
gilt chair before a table by a bank of windows, facing off against
a cadre of prosecutors who, his associates say, he believes is bent
on destroying him.
</P>
<P>
   Starr is investigating whether the president lied under oath in
denying an affair with Ms. Lewinsky last January in his deposition
during the Paula Jones sexual misconduct suit. Beyond the nature of
Clinton's relationship with Ms. Lewinsky, Starr has been
investigating whether Clinton tried to obstruct justice and suborn
perjury.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton took several breaks from his testimony on Monday to
confer with his lawyers in the doctor's office next door to the Map
Room. At about 3:30, he took a break that lasted roughly an hour,
one Clinton ally said.
</P>
<P>
   The furor over the Lewinsky accusations has consumed seven
months of Clinton's presidency, his aides have acknowledged.
Clinton viewed his own place in history as riding in part on his
performance Monday and its impact on public opinion, one of his
friends said.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republican congressional leaders have said that an
acknowledgment by Clinton that he had not told the truth about his
relationship with Ms. Lewinsky might blunt the threat of
impeachment proceedings on Capitol Hill. Erskine Bowles, the White
House chief of staff, called Democrats on the Hill this evening to
rally support for the president.
</P>
<P>
   But even if Clinton heads off such hearings, it is far from
clear whether he will put his second term back on track, or put to
rest smirking speculation about his private life and inflamed
doubts, reflected in public polls, about his truthfulness. More
fundamentally, it was uncertain whether the presidency itself has
been diminished by a tawdry spectacle that on Monday drew so much
attention that one television camera monitored the scene from the
top of the Washington Monument.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   With a grave expression and a brief wave, Starr left the White
House through the Diplomatic Entrance at 6:40 on Monday evening.
Moments later, Kendall stepped through the same door and made brief
remarks by the rain-slicked White House drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hopeful that the president's testimony will finally
bring closure'' to the four-year inquiry into the Clintons'
Whitewater real estate investment, he said, adding that it had
culminated ``in an investigation of the president's private life.''
</P>
<P>
   White House aides picked up on Kendall's call for closure,
declaring that the president's statement on Monday would satisfy
any public interest in the long-running Lewinsky drama, and any
sense of aggravation with Clinton for his role.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people are not pounding on the door for details,
they're pounding on the door for closure,'' one senior
administration official said. ``He doesn't owe them details, he
owes them an explanation.''
</P>
<P>
   The official compared Clinton's remarks Monday night to his
acknowledgment on national television in January 1992 of ``causing
pain'' in his marriage. Clinton, then campaigning in New Hampshire
for the Democratic nomination, had been accused of an affair with
Gennifer Flowers, a singer in Little Rock, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   On a sweltering, rainy Washington day, White House officials
abandoned almost any pretense of the business-as-usual approach
they have taken during the head-snapping swerves and reversals of
the Lewinsky investigation.
</P>
<P>
   At the senior staff meeting on Monday morning, Bowles reminded
the staff of the importance of sticking together. According to Mike
McCurry, the press secretary, Bowles quoted his own father, saying
``it's easy to be there for someone when they're up, but it's the
good ones who are there when you're down.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a rare admission by the White House that the president's
spirits had sagged. One friend said that the president avoided
focusing until Sunday on the implications of his testimony. ``It
hit him hardest on Sunday,'' the friend said. ``This was a very
very difficult weekend for him. Nothing is more important to him
than his place in history. He is worried that this investigation
will eclipse everything else.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's wife, Hillary Rodham Clinton and his daughter,
Chelsea, remained at the White House on Monday, and were believed
to have met with him after he testified.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Some of the president's own advisers expressed relief on Monday
that he was finally telling his side of the story. Some, however,
also feel misled by him, since he denied an affair to them as well.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton worked out on Monday morning in the White House
gymnasium, then spent about two hours preparing with his lawyers in
the White House residence. At noon, he broke for a briefing on
domestic and national security matters. Advisers described him as
engaged and interested during his ten-minute foreign policy
discussion, asking Sandy Berger, the national security adviser, how
the Russian ruble was trading.
</P>
<P>
   The White House released a photo of that meeting, the only
public glimpse of the president before Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Then, at about 12:30, Starr's blue-gray Crown Victoria sedan
swept up the White House drive, and he and his team of prosecutors
headed for the Map Room. The room, on the ground floor, is named
for its wall map of Europe still stuck with the colored pins that
Franklin D. Roosevelt used to mark the progress of World War II.
Clinton used the room to hold ``coffees'' for large donors to the
Democrats during the 1996 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In his deposition on Jan. 17 in the Jones lawsuit, the president
acknowledged a mere acquaintance with Ms. Lewinsky, whom he met in
1995 when she was a 21-year-old unpaid intern. Clinton said that he
could not even recall ever being alone with her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never had sexual relations with Monica Lewinsky,''
Clinton said. ``I've never had an affair with her.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky had sworn in an affidavit that she did not have a
sexual relationship with him.
</P>
<P>
   Unknown to Clinton, an associate of Ms. Lewinsky, Linda Tripp,
had secretly tape-recorded numerous conversations in which her
friend described an affair with Clinton. Mrs. Tripp provided those
tapes to prosecutors, and also met with Mrs. Jones' lawyers before
they interviewed the president.
</P>
<P>
   Securing permission from Attorney General Janet Reno to expand
his investigation, Starr pounced, suspecting that Clinton had lied
in his deposition and then tried to cover up his relationship by
securing a job for Ms. Lewinsky, among other means.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton repeated in public his denial of any affair with Ms.
Lewinsky, issuing it in strong terms after giving a tepid response
to the accusations when they first surfaced.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not have sexual relations with that woman, Miss
Lewinsky,'' he said on Jan. 26, shaking his head and jabbing the
air with one finger. ``I never told anybody to lie, not a single
time _ never.''
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton fell publicly silent about the nature of his
relationship with Ms. Lewinsky, Starr's investigation ground on. He
called more than 70 witnesses before the grand jury here, amassing
circumstantial evidence of an affair. Finally, after issuing a
subpoena for Clinton's testimony, he secured an agreement with Ms.
Lewinsky to testify in exchange for immunity. She acknowledged
under oath that she had had sex with Clinton, but denied he asked
her to lie.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky also turned over a blue dress to prosecutors, which
they are having tested to determine if it carried residue of a
sexual encounter with the president. The test results were not
disclosed, deeply worrying the president's advisers as he prepared
to testify.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton agreed to testify in exchange for Starr withdrawing the
subpoena.
</P>
<P>
   Advisers to the president were buoyed on Monday by public
opinion polls that continued to show Clinton with approval ratings
above 65 percent. By contrast, when President Ronald Reagan
acknowledged making mistakes in the arms-for-hostages swap known as
Iran-Contra, his popularity had fallen to his lowest level of
support in four years.
</P>
<P>
   One White House adviser noted that a CBS News poll, 24 percent
of people surveyed said that Clinton lying bothered them most,
while 16 percent said that they were most bothered by the media
coverage of the Lewinsky investigation. ``You guys are getting a
good second,'' he said. ``If we keep it going right, you may pass
us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
