<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-RUSSIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: LETTING THE RUBLE SLIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, Aug. 18:
</P>
<P>
   Devaluation and default were steps the Russian government wanted
to avoid for fear they would unleash political unrest and anger
foreign lenders. But on Monday the Kremlin took those steps because
the alternative _ the collapse of the banks and eventually the
economy _ seemed worse.
</P>
<P>
   Given the developing banking crisis and the loss of confidence
in international markets, the Kremlin had little choice. It had
become clear that not even the International Monetary Fund bailout
announced last month would be enough to keep the Russian government
afloat.
</P>
<P>
   The decision was forced when Russian banks, which have borrowed
large amounts of dollars, began to be pressed for repayment by
lenders last week. The banks tried to buy dollars from the
government, threatening to deplete its small reserves of foreign
currency. Last week the government blocked those dollar purchases.
Now it has blocked the debt repayments.
</P>
<P>
   The moves delay for 90 days the foreign currency debt repayments
owed by Russian banks and other private borrowers. That is aimed at
providing time for those borrowers to restructure their loans,
which many will have difficulty paying simply because of the
decline in the value of the ruble. The government said it would be
allowed to fall by up to a third. It is not clear how far the
currency will actually drop.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Russia promises that later this week it will
restructure its own ruble-denominated debt, on which it has been
paying extraordinarily high interest rates. It is expected to force
lenders to agree to accept lower interest rates and delayed
payments.
</P>
<P>
   Given the declining price of oil, a major Russian export, and
the government's failure to collect taxes, a devaluation has been
economically logical for some time. But Western governments were
reluctant to press for devaluation, because they feared the popular
reaction in Russia, where the availability of imported items,
particularly food, clothing and cars, has been a benefit of
economic reform.
</P>
<P>
   Russians do not anger easily and are likely to live with higher
prices as long as the government seems to be leading the country
toward greater financial stability. But the steps taken Monday will
no doubt deepen public cynicism about the country's political
leaders and could make it more difficult for reform candidates in
the next parliamentary and presidential elections. Their prospects
would be even less promising if the economy collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   Finding a way for the Russian economy to recover will not be
easy. But it is in no one's interest to see the government
disintegrate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
