<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-CLINTON-COLORADO-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        COLORADO LAWMAKERS SPLIT ON CLINTON CONFESSION
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Elliot Zaret  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Aug. 17 -- As President Clinton finished his speech
Monday night, Rep. Scott McInnis watched his wife Lori stand up,
shrug, and walk into the kitchen of their home.
</P>
<P>
   ``She just didn't believe him,'' said the Pueblo Republican.
``He doesn't have it in his gut just to apologize. He's always
gotta add a 'but' to it or an 'and' to it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Colorado Gov. Roy Romer, who chairs the Democratic National
Committee, applauded the speech, saying it was ``a forthright
statement and I respect him for saying it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard a very strong apology,'' said Romer. ``It was a frank
statement of confession... I think it will help get this all off
the table.''
</P>
<P>
   Colorado lawmakers split on everything from whether Clinton
actually apologized to the potential impact of the speech.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Wayne Allard, R-Colo., didn't find the speech to be enough.
``He expressed sorrow -- he did that,'' said Allard. ``He expressed
regret. But I didn't hear the word 'apologize.'''
</P>
<P>
   McInnis said he especially disagreed with Clinton's assertion
that his affair is his private business.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (ITAL)is(END ITAL) our business,'' said McInnis. ``More
secrets and more information has been exchanged through sex
throughout all time. The strongest tool for information and for
blackmail has been sex. What if it was a Chinese spy he was with?''
</P>
<P>
   Others said the speech was enough, and that the country should
move on to more important issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people deserve the truth and this is a positive
step in the right direction,'' said Sen. Ben Nighthorse Campbell,
R-Colo. ``I cannot and will not condone the President's behavior,
but enough is enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Diana DeGette, D-Denver, agreed: ``I am disappointed that
he did not acknowledge this earlier, but I have hope that this
matter now comes to a conclusion, so we can turn our attention to
the critical issues facing the country.''
</P>
<P>
   State lawmakers also disagreed on another important issue: how
Clinton's confession affects the possibility of an impeachment
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since he didn't answer all the questions, I think there's
another chapter yet to be played out,'' said Allard. ``I don't
think anyone in Congress relishes the idea of an impeachment
hearing. But I think they'll be looking for the facts.''
</P>
<P>
   But Romer said impeachment hearings would only help the
Democrats: ``If somebody tries to make a strategy of impeachment
after this confession, it will hurt them politically,'' he said.
``It will help the Democrats win back the House.''
</P>
</TEXT>
