<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-LEWINSKY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ADMITS RELATIONSHIP WITH LEWINSKY AFTER GRAND JURY
TESTIMONY 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Complete writethru; adds Clinton address, details, quotes)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Abandoning months of denial, President Clinton
admitted Monday night that he had an inappropriate relationship
with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky and said he misled
his family and the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton delivered his somber, nationally televised admission
less than four hours after completing sworn testimony before a
federal grand jury that is looking into allegations that the
president carried on an 18-month sexual relationship with the young
college graduate and coaxed her to lie about the affair.
</P>
<P>
   In a bid to quell a scandal that has undercut his presidency and
raised the specter of impeachment by the Republican-led Congress,
Clinton abandoned his long-standing denial of the relationship 11
days after Lewinsky detailed the sexual relationship for the same
grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, seated in the historic Map Room at the White House and
looking squarely into the television camera, insisted that he had
not lied about his relationship with Lewinsky in response to
questions posed to him on Jan. 17 by lawyers pressing Paula Jones'
$700,000 civil sexual harassment against him.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton added: ``While my answers were legally accurate, I
did not volunteer information. Indeed, I did have a relationship
with Ms. Lewinsky that was not appropriate. In fact, it was
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Without going into details about the relationship, Clinton
called it ``a critical lapse in judgment and a personal failure on
my part for which I am solely and completely responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   The president said his public denials left ``a false
impression,'' adding: ``I misled people, including even my wife.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's personal lawyer, David Kendall, told reporters that
Clinton ``made the painful admission that he had inappropriate
contact with Ms. Lewinsky'' during his testimony to the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall said that in response to ``a very few highly intrusive
questions with respect to the specifics of this contact,'' Clinton
offered ``candid but not detailed answers'' in order to ``preserve
personal privacy and institutional dignity.''
</P>
<P>
   Special prosecutor Kenneth Starr's team is assessing whether to
recall Clinton for additional testimony, according to lawyers
involved in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton insisted, as he has since the allegations broke on Jan.
21, that he had not urged ``anyone to lie, to hide or destroy
evidence or to take any other unlawful action.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he had denied the relationship for seven months to
avoid ``the embarrassment of my own conduct'' as well seeking to
protect his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now this matter is between me, the two people I love most _ my
wife and our daughter _ and our God,'' Clinton said. ``I must put
it right, and I am prepared to do whatever it takes to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nobody's business but ours,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton used his six-minute address to criticize Starr's wide
ranging investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has gone on too long, cost too much and hurt too many
innocent people,'' he said. ``It is time to stop the pursuit of
personal destruction and the prying into private lives and get on
with our national life.''
</P>
<P>
   Kendall said that Clinton answered Starr's questions for more
than four hours during the five-hour, 25-minute session in the Map
Room.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hopeful that the president's testimony will finally
bring closure to the independent counsel's more than four year and
over $40 million investigation, which has culminated in an
investigation of the president's private life,'' added Kendall, a
trusted Yale Law School classmate of the president and first lady
Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Aides said Clinton chose to deliver his nationally televised
explanation from the Map Room, a formal sitting room adorned with
antiques and dominated by a World War II-era map showing allied
troops closing in on the Nazi capital of Berlin in April 1945.
President Franklin D. Roosevelt and British Prime Minister Winston
Churchill charted allied strategy there at the outset of the
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's secret testimony was relayed by closed-circuit
television to a 23-member federal grand jury seated in a courtroom
at the federal courthouse a dozen blocks away from the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky, 25, initially denied a sexual relationship with
Clinton in her sworn deposition in the Jones' sexual harassment
lawsuit. That lawsuit was later dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   But Lewinsky reversed course after winning immunity from
prosecution from Starr to tell the grand jury on Aug. 6 that she
and Clinton carried on a sexual relationship while she worked at
the White House, according to lawyers familiar with her testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had repeatedly denied a sexual relationship with
Lewinsky, who went to work at the White House in June 1995 as an
unpaid intern. Clinton emphatically reiterated his denial in an
appearance at the White House on Jan. 26 with Mrs. Clinton by his
side.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not have sexual relations with that woman, Miss
Lewinsky,'' Clinton declared, waving his index finger for emphasis.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons, accompanied by Chelsea, a student at Stanford
University, planned to leave for a two-week vacation on Martha's
Vineyard, Mass., on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton became the first American president to testify before a
grand jury investigating his conduct just two days before his 52nd
birthday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's testimony was a crucial milestone in White House
efforts to quell a seven-month scandal that has obscured the
president's domestic agenda and hampered his efforts to bolster
Democrats' chances for retaking control of the House in the
mid-term congressional elections.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's aides say the special prosecutor hopes to present a
report to Congress within three to five weeks on the results of his
four year inquiry into the Clintons' failed 1978 investment in the
Whitewater land scheme in Arkansas, their firing of White House
travel office personnel, the alleged abuse of FBI background
reports on prominent Republicans and the Lewinsky affair.
</P>
<P>
   Starr may recall Lewinsky for a second appearance before the
grand jury before his inquiry ends. Starr's spokesman, Charles
Bakaly, said that prosecutors are near the end of their inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to complete the investigation as quickly as
possible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   By law, Starr must report his findings to the House Judiciary
Committee, which then weighs whether an impeachment inquiry is
warranted. Republican lawmakers in the House are divided, with some
conservatives insisting that the House undertake a full inquiry
into Starr's findings before reaching a decision on recommending
impeachment to the full House.
</P>
<P>
   But Senate Judiciary Committee Chairman Orrin Hatch, R-Utah,
reiterated at a news conference in Des Moines, Iowa, on Monday that
he did not believe impeachment proceedings are warranted if Clinton
told the truth before the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally hope it works out well for the president,'' Hatch
said. Truthful testimony is ``the one thing that he can do that
might not only save his presidency but allow him to finish the
presidency through the year 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   White House Press Secretary Mike McCurry said that Clinton hoped
that his candor and apology would help douse a scandal that dogged
his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has been shadowed throughout his national political
career by allegations of marital infidelity. With his presidential
fortunes in jeopardy in the New Hampshire presidential primary,
Clinton denied a ``12 year'' affair with Gennifer Flowers during a
high stakes interview on CBS News' ``60 Minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton admitted the relationship with Flowers in his Jan. 17,
1998, deposition in the Jones' suit.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also denied Jones' allegations that he summoned her to a
Little Rock, Ark., hotel room in May 1991 _ five months before
launching his presidential campaign _ and solicited oral sex.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has also denied Kathleen Willey's allegations that he
forced himself on her and fondled her during an encounter in the
Oval Office in November, 1993.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
