<SLUG> BC-CONCERT-INVEST-FRAUD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO CHARGED WITH BILKING INVESTORS IN PHONY CONCERTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., N.C., Fla.)  (nk) 
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A licensed stock broker and another man were charged
in indictments unsealed Monday with bilking investors out of more
than $150,000 by pretending to promote concerts featuring the
Artist Formerly Known as Prince.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors are calling the men Con Artists.
</P>
<P>
   ``The defendants contacted potential investors and solicited
money to finance concerts for the Artist,'' said Manhattan District
Attorney Robert Morgenthau. ``Rather than invest the money they
received in concert promotions, the defendants took the money for
their own use. Furthermore, the defendants had no connection
whatsoever to the Artist, and had no authority to sell any
promotional interests in his concerts.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffery Brewer, 46, who worked for Millennium Securities Corp.
in Manhattan as a broker and lives in Princeton, N.J., was charged
with grand larceny, conducting a scheme to defraud and securities
fraud, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer surrendered to the authorities Monday; his bail was set
at $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Moore, 28, of Raleigh, N.C., who allegedly posed as the
promoter of the concerts, was charged with grand larceny and
conducting a scheme to defraud, Morgenthau said. He is not yet in
custody; a warrant was issued Monday for his arrest.
</P>
<P>
   The most important charge, grand larceny, is punishable by up to
15 years in state prison.
</P>
<P>
   The scheme was carried out last summer, prosecutors said, and
involved at least four victims, none of whom were from New York.
</P>
<P>
   The largest loss was suffered by a Florida man, Harold Wexelman,
who was one of Brewer's stock clients and who gave the men more
than $50,000, according to the indictment.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors uncovered the unusual scheme of selling stakes in
nonexistent concerts as part of a broader investigation into the
securities industry, Morgenthau said. When they realized that the
men were passing themselves off as representatives of the former
Prince, they called the performer's agent and his lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Artist doesn't run his business like that,'' said Carolyn
Pelling, the assistant district attorney prosecuting the case. ``He
doesn't take individual investments, and he certainly doesn't need
small-time investors to put any money up front in order for him to
have concerts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
