<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-17 23:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8528 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COX-CLINTON-MAIN-2ndL     08-17 1941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-CLINTON-MAIN-2ndLEDE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON ADMITS AFFAIR WITH LEWINSKY, ASKS NATION TO RESPECT HIS
PRIVACY
 &HT;    EDS: Adds 3rd graf to recast issue of an apology 
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton told an anxious nation Monday
that he had a ''relationship that was not appropriate'' with former
White House intern Monica Lewinsky, directly contradicting the
blanket denial he issued to the American people seven months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Reversing an extraordinary campaign of deception, denial and
evasion in a desperate attempt to salvage his presidency, Clinton
moved to try to repair a serious breach of public trust, in a
televised address to the country he hoped would clear the slate on
charges that have dogged his administration.
</P>
<P>
   In brief comments that were at least as combative as they were
contrite, however, Clinton never explicitly apologized to the
country for months of deception. On the contrary, he lashed out
against independent counsel Kenneth Starr and what the president
cast as a broader assault on the privacy of public figures, boldly
asserting at one point that his personal affairs were ''nobody's
business,'' even if they took place in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ''I did have a relationship with Ms. Lewinsky that was not
appropriate _ in fact, it was wrong,'' said Clinton, who appeared
weary and emotionally spent after more than five hours of White
House interrogation by Starr earlier in the day. ''I misled people,
including even my wife,'' he said, his voice quivering slightly.
``I deeply regret that.''
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton assumed the blame for his relationship with
Lewinsky _ ``It constituted a critical lapse in judgment and a
personal failure on my part, for which I am solely and completely
responsible'' _ he also said it was time for the country to ``get
on with our national life.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton stopped short of asking for national forgiveness,
however, pointedly asserting his right to a personal life that
includes personal mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now this matter is between me, the two people I love most _ my
wife and our daughter _ and our God,'' Clinton said. ''I must put
it right. And I am prepared to do whatever it takes to do so.
Nothing is more important to me personally. But it is private. And
I intend to reclaim my family life for my family.''
</P>
<P>
   Going to dramatic lengths to distance what he regards as a
private matter from affairs of state, Clinton fired off a
determined counter-volley to his critics, saying the question of
his relationship with Lewinsky is a family concern, not a national
issue.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's nobody's business but ours,'' Clinton asserted. ''Even
presidents have private lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Staring straight into the camera, and wearing a dark suit, white
shirt shirt and conservative blue necktie, Clinton stood by his
earlier claims that he did not urge Lewinsky, or anyone else, to
lie about allegations that he and Lewinsky had a White House
affair.
</P>
<P>
   ''At no time did I ask anyone to lie, to hide or destroy
evidence, or to take any other unlawfuyl actions,'' said Clinton,
urging the country to put the issue behind it. He added: ''This has
gone on too long, cost too much and hurt to many innocent people.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's personal attorney, David Kendall, said the president
conceded in his testimony that he had ``inappropriate contact with
Ms. Lewinsky.'' But, Kendall said, Clinton did not respond to some
questions touching on intimate details of their relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made the painful admission that he had inappropriate
contact with Ms. Lewinsky,'' Kendall told the Associated Press.
``As to a very few highly intrusive questions, with respect to the
specifics of this contact, in order to preserve personal privacy
and institutional dignity, he gave candid, but not detailed,
answers.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton postponed until Tuesday afternoon his departure, with
First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton and their daughter Chelsea, to
Martha's Vineyard, Mass., for a long-scheduled vacation.
</P>
<P>
   He was expected to spend much of the morning Tuesday on the
telephone making personal pleas for support from key political
figures, and trying to mend fences with senior White House aides,
many of whom have spent months defending him before a skeptical
public.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's comments, telegraphed late last week in a series of
carefully orchestrated White House leaks, marked the theatrical
climax _ but not the end _ to a moral and political drama that has
traumatized the administration and agonized the nation since
January.
</P>
<P>
   Starr is expected to deliver an exhaustive report of his
investigation within weeks to Congress, which must then assess
whether the evidence justifies impeachment proceedings, formal
censure, or neither.
</P>
<P>
   As independent counsel, Starr presumably has reserved the right
to ask follow-up questions of Clinton, though it could not be
determined Monday whether he planned to do so.
</P>
<P>
   In early political reaction, Democrats were predictably quiet on
the matter, though some Republicans ventured that Clinton would pay
a political price of some sort for months of deceit.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever Congress decides, Clinton, who has been dogged by a
series of scandals involving issues as diverse as his draft record,
White House travel operations and the use of the Lincoln Bedroom as
a perk for political backers, faces a daunting challenge: trying to
restore his credibility to the point that he may govern the country
for the two and a half years remaining in his badly tarnished term.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to begin that process, Clinton addressed the nation from
the historic Map Room, a formal parlor in the White House residence
that President Roosevelt used for top secret briefings during World
War II.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also used the Map Room for his testimony, part of a
public relations effort to distinguish between his private affairs
and his official business, most of which is conducted away from the
residence in the White House West Wing.
</P>
<P>
   The First Lady and Chelsea were at the White House on Monday,
having met for some two hours late Sunday night with civil rights
activist the Rev. Jesse Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson told reporters he was called to the White House at
Chelsea's request and that, after meeting with her and the First
Lady, the three of them met with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that Bill has a sense of embarrassment,'' Jackson told
the Associated Press. ``Hillary, as the wife, there's a sense of
humiliation. Hillary is dedicated to her marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's testimony began at 12:59 p.m. and lasted until 6:25
p.m. It was fed live to the federal grand jury that has been
reviewing evidence since January in Starr's inquiry into
allegations that Clinton conducted an affair with Lewinsky then
later urged her to lie about it under oath.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's comments directly contradicted the public position he
has held since January 21, when the Washington Post newspaper first
reported that Starr was investigating allegations that Clinton had
an affair with Lewinsky then later urged her to lie about it under
oath.
</P>
<P>
   ''I did not have sexual relations with that woman, Miss
Lewinsky,'' Clinton declared in televised remarks from the White
House less than a week after the allegations first surfaced. ''I
never told anybody to lie, not a single time. Never. These
allegations are false, and I need to go back to work for the
American people.''
</P>
<P>
   That same month, in a deposition in Paula Jones' sexual
harassment suit against him, later dismissed, Clinton also said,
this time under oath, ''I have never had sexual relations with
Monica Lewinsky. I've never had an affair with her.''
</P>
<P>
   In testimony several weeks ago, Lewinsky reportedly detailed a
White House affair she said lasted more than a year. She reportedly
testified that she and Clinton discussed various cover-up schemes,
though he never explicitly urged her to lie.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky also reportedly turned over to Starr a dress she claims
contains physical evidence of a sexual encounter with the
president.
</P>
<P>
   Starr has also questioned dozens of Clinton aides and members of
the White House Secret Service detail in an effort to corroborate
Lewinsky's testimony.
</P>
<P>
   While her version of events contradicts Clinton's public
statements, the president's lead personal attorney, David Kendall,
said Clinton set the record straight during Monday's testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ''He testified truthfully,'' Kendall told reporters at the White
House shortly after Starr's questioning ended. Without detailing
Clinton's testimony, Kendall took a parting shot at Starr,
continuing a central theme in months of White House efforts to
undermine the president's critics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hopeful that the president's testimony will finally
bring closure to the independent counsel's more than four-year and
over $40 million investigation, which has culminated in an
investigation of the president's private life,'' said Kendall,
again drawing a distinction between Clinton's performance on the
job and his handling of personal affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Starr waved quickly without comment to reporters as he exited
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   It was clear, though, that Clinton's dramatic day of atonement
did not bring an end to a scandal that has already stained his
legacy and wrenched the nation.
</P>
<P>
   In a year in which the United States and Iraq drew close to war,
India and Pakistan flirted with nuclear Armageddon, ethnic
bloodshed reignited in the troubled Balkans, people power toppled a
U.S.-backed dictator in Indonesia and the global economy was
threatened by financial turmoil in Tokyo and Moscow, Clinton has
been distracted by months of complex efforts to avoid a day of
reckoning on the Lewinsky matter.
</P>
<P>
   There is no reliable estimate as to how much time and effort the
president and his staff have devoted to the issue. By Clinton's own
claims, however, and those of his attorneys, the distraction has
been extensive; there seems to be little doubt it's been
disruptive.
</P>
<P>
   Monday began, for instance, with Clinton's Chief of Staff
Erskine Bowles meeting with two dozen senior White House officials
and trying to buck up their spirits for what promised to be a long
and painful day.
</P>
<P>
   ''He said, 'It's easy to be there for someone when they're up,
but it's the good ones who are there when you're down,''' White
House spokesman Michael McCurry told reporters gathered in a packed
briefing room early Monday. ''I thought the analogy was a very good
one.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's own mood, McCurry acknowledged, was grim.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wouldn't say he's exactly looking forward to it,'' McCurry
said as Clinton prepared to be interrogated, later adding, ''He
looks forward to getting this matter behind him.''
</P>
<P>
   For all of the drama that Monday brought, and all the intrigue
it finally laid to rest, Clinton's testimony and public statements
have not ended the Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Starr is likely to present Congress with an exhaustive report,
sometime next month, of his investigation, an event certain to
prompt a new round of media attention to the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Then, based on Starr's findings, Congress would have to decide
whether to begin impeachment proceedings _ a process that would
involve lengthy hearings that could drag on well into next year _
or vote to censure the president for his activities or simply
ignore the issue entirely.
</P>
<P>
   There is also the matter of how the scandal will play in the
upcoming election season. All 435 seats in Congress, one-third of
the 100-member Senate and dozens of key gubernatorial and mayoral
slots, are up for grabs in November.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
