<SLUG> BC-BOMBECK-GRAVE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bombeck to have 'a piece of Phoenix' at gravesite
 &HT;    By Brandon Peterson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ For the past two years, only a potted plant
marked the grave where Dayton native and internationally-read humor
columnist Erma Bombeck is buried at Woodland Cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   But soon the plant will be replaced by a massive rock that was
brought in from near Bombeck's former home in Arizona to adorn her
final resting place.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, a 29,000-pound rock measuring 6 feet wide and
standing 5 feet 3 inches tall was delivered to the cemetery on a
flatbed semi truck.
</P>
<P>
   The stone was lugged off the property of one of Bombeck's
neighbors on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, Bill Bombeck, said he ``wanted a piece of Phoenix''
at his wife's grave to commemorate the 25 years they spent together
in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The rock is the largest marker in the cemetery, according to
Teresa Moyer, director of public relations for the cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will definitely add fascination to the cemetery,'' Moyer
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bombeck died of complications following a kidney transplant in
1996. Shortly after her death, Bill Bombeck decided to have his
wife buried in Woodland Cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   Woodland Cemetery is the oldest non-profit cemetery in the Miami
(Ohio) Valley, according to Moyer. The cemetery is the final
resting place of numerous Dayton natives. James M. Cox, former
governor of Ohio and publisher of the Dayton Daily News, the Wright
brothers, Paul Laurence Dunbar and Charles Kettering, are among
those buried at the 157-year-old cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   Moyer said the next step is to have someone determine what type
of stone the marker is and more importantly _ how to place the rock
on the gravesite.
</P>
<P>
   Cemetery officials are trying to figure out how to preserve a
Magnolia tree that is situated near Bombeck's grave where the rock
is to be placed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some site constraints, and we are looking into
various options on how to place the rock without damaging the
tree,'' said Mary Rogero, architect with Rogero-Buckman architects
who is handling the project. Rogero said she wasn't sure when the
excavation would begin.
</P>
<P>
   Bombeck began writing columns for the Journal Herald in 1965.
She also worked for the Kettering-Oakwood Times. Bombeck, who was
known for her witty but wise columns that poked fun at family life
began her humor column as a suburban housewife.
</P>
<P>
   Brandon Peterson writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
