u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BENGALS18-COX     08-17 0541
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BENGALS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Despite defeat, quarterback question may be answered for Bengals
 &HT;    By Chick Ludwig
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ Bengals head coach Bruce Coslet has said it plenty
of times: The quarterback competition will be settled on the field.
</P>
<P>
   If that's the case, then Neil O'Donnell is the clear-cut leader
in his race against teammate Jeff Blake for the starting role Sept.
6.
</P>
<P>
   Forget the Bengals' 30-27 preseason defeat at the hands of the
Indianapolis Colts on Monday at Cinergy Field.
</P>
<P>
   The big story was O'Donnell grabbing the quarterback job by the
lapels and pulling it toward him, while Blake played giveaway. Many
spectators booed Blake and the defense off the field at halftime
with the Colts ahead 23-14. O'Donnell started and had the Bengals
up, 14-10, when he left at 11:52 of the second. He completed all
five passes for 58 yards, with a 7-yard TD to Darnay Scott.
</P>
<P>
   Blake played the final 9:30 of the second quarter, going 0 for 7
passing with an interception and no first downs in four series.
</P>
<P>
   He bounced back in the third quarter, guiding the Bengals on a
nine-play, 82-yard opening drive that Eric Bieniemy finished with a
5-yard run.
</P>
<P>
   Blake looked much smoother after halftime, setting up the TD
with passes of 29 yards to tight end Marco Battaglia and 15 yards
to David Dunn.
</P>
<P>
   But his night ended with more boos _ a false-start penalty on
left guard Rod Jones on fourth-and-1 near midfield that forced the
Bengals to punt.
</P>
<P>
   Blake may have even lost the backup job to Paul Justin, who
fired a 39-yard TD pass to rookie Damon Gibson with 3:18 to go.
</P>
<P>
   Colts rookie quarterback Peyton Manning completed 5 of 11 passes
for 112 yards and a 12-yard TD to Marvin Harrison.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison's TD came five plays after cornerback Jeff Burris
picked off Blake at the Colts' 41.
</P>
<P>
   Indianapolis opened the game with an 11-play, 71-yard scoring
drive that culminated with Marshall Faulk's 1-yard plunge on a
delayed call by officials. As the Bengals' celebrated what they
thought was a goal-line stand, the referees waited until they were
sure, then thrust their arms skyward.
</P>
<P>
   Tremain Mack exploded 60 yards with the ensuing kickoff to the
Colts' 37 and Corey Dillon took over from there. He carried five
times for 33 yards on runs of 6, 21, 4 and a pair of 1-yarders to
tie the score at 7.
</P>
<P>
   Manning, who fired a 25-yard pass to Torrance Small on the first
drive, launched a 39 yarder to Harrison at the Bengals' 28 on the
Colts' second drive.
</P>
<P>
   Bengals' top draft pick Takeo Spikes sacked Manning for an
8-yard loss and the Colts' settled for Mike Vanderjagt's 49-yard
field goal.
</P>
<P>
   After Scott's TD catch _ set up by O'Donnell's 31-yard pass to
Dillon _ the Colts took control, reeling off 13 straight points.
</P>
<P>
   Mack added a 59-yard kickoff return to his 60 yarder and rookie
Artrell Hawkins had a 37-yard kickoff return. A pair of Bengals'
rookies _ linebacker Adrian Ross and nose tackle Glen Steele _
joined Spikes with sacks.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Steve Tovar suffered a neck injury in the fourth
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Chick Ludwig writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
