<SLUG> BC-NY-SCAFFOLD-COLLAPSE-415&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOUR WEEKS AFTER SCAFFOLDING COLLAPSE, STREET TO REOPEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By TERRY PRISTIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ To the relief of the business owners who were among
the hardest hit by the July 21 scaffolding collapse at the Conde
Nast building, the plywood gates that have sealed off 43rd Street
for several weeks were dismantled Monday, and the street itself was
scheduled to reopen Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   For the Roundabout Theater, that means that its hit musical,
``Cabaret,'' can resume performances at the Kit Kat Klub on
Thursday after missing 35 performances and losing more than $1.5
million in ticket sales, artistic director Todd Haimes said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is truly unprecedented,'' Haimes said. ``It is truly an
act of God. You wait 20 years to have a hit like this and then _
literally _ the sky falls in.''
</P>
<P>
   For Steve Chang, the owner of Rio de Janeiro, a new
all-you-can-eat barbecue restaurant, the reopening of 43rd Street
means he can begin hiring and training people to replace the 40
waiters who left because he could no longer pay them. If he can
hire enough employees _ and get the gas turned on _ he, too, can be
up and running by Thursday, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But at the Woodstock Hotel, where an elderly woman was killed
when the construction scaffold buckled, sending debris flying
through the roof, there was no hopeful news for the 274 mostly
elderly residents who were forced to relocate elsewhere on the West
Side.
</P>
<P>
   Structural engineers were breaking into the walls of the hotel
Monday to determine whether any of the support columns were
damaged, and were expected to file a report with the city Tuesday,
said Buildings Commissioner Gaston Silva.
</P>
<P>
   ``The building is going to need work,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It was not known Monday when the hotel would be ready for
occupancy. The only other business on the block that is not being
allowed to reopen is a parking garage, which was also damaged by
falling debris.
</P>
<P>
   One restaurant, Manhattan Chili Company, has been operating a
takeout and delivery service, using a second entrance in the office
building at 1500 Broadway. The manager, Ken Kessler, plans to
reopen the restaurant on Thursday, but he said he would not be
surprised if many potential customers avoided 43rd Street in the
wake of the scaffolding collapse. ``For how long I don't know,'' he
said. ``People have short memories for some things.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A building crew finished removing the last part of the damaged
scaffolding late Saturday, and the most dangerous part of the
operation was completed last week, when an elevator cab was
extricated from the 24th floor, said Richard Kielar, a senior vice
president of Tishman Realty and Construction, the construction
manager.
</P>
<P>
   Construction work on parts of the building not affected by the
accident resumed on Aug. 10, Kielar said, adding that the building
was expected to be finished by next spring.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, as workers were cleaning up debris at the
construction site, city sanitation workers removed six huge trash
bins full of spoiled food from several restaurants on the block,
said Sunny Mindel, a spokeswoman for the Mayor's Office of
Emergency Management.
</P>
<P>
   Chang, the owner of Rio de Janeiro, said that he was first
allowed to return to his restaurant about 10 days ago, and then was
allowed to return again Sunday night. ``The bad smell was swirling
around,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He estimated that the restaurant lost $750,000 by being closed.
</P>
<P>
   The 2-year-old Casablanca Hotel, a 48-room boutique hotel with a
Moroccan theme, is also expected to reopen on Thursday, said
manager Brian Dass.
</P>
<P>
   Estimating that the hotel had lost about $200,000 in business,
he said that he was even more concerned about the damage to future
bookings, given that people plan their trips far in advance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have an e-mail from someone asking if we would be open by
April 1999,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
