<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-WOMEN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL WOMEN SUPPORTERS STILL STAND BEHIND CLINTON? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JEAN BUCHANAN AND MATTHEW SCHOFIELD  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star   ( Kansas City, Mo. ) _ For better. For
worse.
<TEXT>
<P>
   For seven months, many American women have stuck with President
Clinton. He may have broken his vows to his wife, they said, but he
was faithful to causes important to them.
</P>
<P>
   And at least some said they did not care what Clinton told a
grand jury Monday. They like his policies; they want the
investigation to be over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little embarrassed, sure,'' Kansas resident Elizabeth
Appelbaum said about the allegations about Clinton. ``But he's not
my husband, and he's not my preacher either, and I wish he hadn't
done it, but I really don't care very deeply about his sex life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I care very much about what issues he's pushing and what
issues he's not pushing.''
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen, of course, whether the loyalty will last.
But for years, and through many allegations, women have been core
supporters of Clinton. They voted for him in 1996 by a 55-37
margin.
</P>
<P>
   Many women like Clinton because of his appointments. He gave the
nation its highest-ranking woman government official ever:
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright. He named the first woman
attorney general: Janet Reno. He has supported family leave, a
higher minimum wage, abortion rights _ all issues many women
consider important.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, in fact, one Kansas City woman had had enough of the
investigation. Ernestine Davis, a retired Kansas City
schoolteacher, turned off her television and radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``We elected a president, not a pope,'' she said. ``And I look
at how people are working, and how the government has made attempts
to be for people, rather than for the elite....I think this has
been one big effort to get Clinton because he's been too fair to
minorities.''
</P>
<P>
   Some longtime backers of the president are troubled, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``I support Clinton's policies, what he's done,'' said Judith L.
Zillner, an investment planner with Berthel Fisher &AMP; Co. ``But I'm
uneasy with his personal conduct. His conduct diminishes the office
of the presidency, and people need to believe in something. They
need to believe in their president and their country.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people were still sorting out their feelings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most women...are most interested in how good a job he's
doing,'' said Jackson County Prosecutor Claire McCaskill, a
Democratic candidate for state auditor in Missouri. ``But we all
want to admire him as a man, as well _ and this makes it very hard
to admire the man. This is just embarrassing. It's embarrassing to
him, to the office, to his family, to my party and to women, who've
supported him so strongly.''
</P>
<P>
   Other people, however, knew exactly how they felt, including
those who have never backed Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Kay Culp, the former head of Missouri Right to Life, said
her lack of faith in him has been justified by the current scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``What angers me is that Gennifer Flowers' whole story came out
before he was elected,'' she said. ``We had the warning signs on
this behavior, and we ignored them. And because we ignored those
signs, we elected a president who has torn down the image of the
presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   A recurring theme among Clinton's women supporters, however, is
that his sex life is not the business of anyone but Clinton and his
wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a witch hunt by (independent counsel Kenneth)
Starr and the Republicans, and a waste of taxpayer money,'' said
Kathy Reed, president of the Kansas City Federation of Teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Reed has been a Clinton supporter from the beginning. She likes
his beliefs and actions on education.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Bill Clinton has been able to do for this country far
outweighs any problems he might have in his personal life,'' she
said. ``And make no mistake, this is his personal life.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharon Lockhart of Leawood, Kansas coordinator for the National
Organization for Women, said women don't applaud extramarital
affairs, but most recognize that they happen.
</P>
<P>
   She said she does not defend him on the issue, but ``most
people, we want to mind our own business. We don't want to know
about their sex lives, and we don't want them to know about our sex
lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyer Micheline Burger of Lenexa, who is chairwoman of the
Democratic Party in Johnson County and practices family law in
Olathe, agreed. She thinks Clinton's private life is the business
of his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's taken seriously the issues that women feel
strongly about, that families feel strongly about,'' Burger said.
``Protecting children, protecting the elderly, protecting the
Social Security trust fund...those things are important to me and
to women in general.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue being investigated is sex, said Mary O'Halloran,
co-host of ``Talk Back'' radio station.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not sexual harassment,'' she said. ``This is not a
crime, and I won't stop supporting this president until I see
evidence that his actions were criminal.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Halloran said she would be surprised to see a decrease in
Clinton's popularity among women because ``he is the strongest
advocate for women ever to sit in the White House, without a
doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   But, she added, ``Whether his support among women will hold if
the news continues to splatter this story across the front page for
another six months, I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   And there is dismay about the mess.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every living person is full of contradictions, I know that,''
said Zillner, the investment planner. ``But he is the president,
and he's supposed to work hard to be above these things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
